<HEADLINE>
ATTENDANTS UNION WAITING FOR BETTER OFFER FROM AMWEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With a strike showdown looming in 15 days, America West Airlines
and its flight attendants are still at odds over how much the
company can boost wages and stay competitive.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendants union says the Tempe carrier is offering
too little in its proposal to raise starting pay from $14.28 per
hour to $16.13, and the top wage from $24.41 to $34.59.
</P>
<P>
   Another big sticking point is per-diem pay during layovers.
</P>
<P>
   America West says it's a fair offer for the 2,400 flight
attendants, based on its position as the country's ninth-largest
airline with a revenue disadvantage of 23 percent, compared with
the six largest U.S. carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The union's goal, according to Bill McGlashen, president of the
Association of Flight Attendants Council 66, is to get wages as
close as possible to the industry average for the top 10 airlines:
$15.11 per hour for starting flight attendants and $39.50 for those
with more than 12 years of experience.
</P>
<P>
   What will it take to settle the dispute, short of a strike that
would disrupt Arizona's spring travel season and cost America West
millions of dollars in lost revenue?
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the flight attendants union say their demands do not
threaten America West's viability but reward the flight attendants
for their loyalty during tough economic times earlier this decade
and allow them to share in the company's current prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good contract causes a little pain on both sides,''
McGlashen said. ``The flight attendants feel there is no pain in
this contract for the company.''
</P>
<P>
   America West says its offer improves total compensation nearly
16 percent the first year and just shy of 45 percent after five
years. The carrier is taking its offer straight to the flight
attendants with letters to them and a Web site that explains how
much each worker's pay would increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``As much as we want to reach an agreement, we will not
compromise the viability of the company to do so,'' America West
Chairman William Franke said in a letter to flight attendants.
</P>
<P>
   The AFA is saying that the company needs to increase its offer
by $16.5 million, but it has not disclosed its proposed pay scale.
</P>
<P>
   With a strike deadline of 10 p.m. March 19, and last-minute
negotiations expected to start as early as next weekend, the union
is holding out, anticipating that the company has not yet made its
best offer.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to higher salaries, the AFA is seeking better
per-diem pay and compensation for attendants' extra time, when
flights run longer than scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   America West pays flight attendants on overnight trips $2 per
hour from when they check out after their last flight to when they
check in the next morning, according to Greg Garger, vice president
of labor relations. They are not paid during layovers.
</P>
<P>
   The industry standard is for flight crews to be paid from the
time they check in at their base city to when they check out,
McGlashen said.
</P>
<P>
   That is how America West's pilots are paid. They receive
per-diem of $1.80 per hour.
</P>
<P>
   America West is offering the flight attendants $1.30 per hour,
increasing to $1.50 after 2{ years and $1.75 at the end of the
five-year contract. The current per-diem system is worth about 89
cents per hour.
</P>
<P>
   Per-diem pay is a fundamental issue for flight attendants, and
they want their rate to be on par with the company's pilots,
McGlashen said, adding that the flight crews all stay in the same
hotels and generally eat at the same restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   America West says its offer would initially increase per-diem by
$1,066 annually, or 46 percent for a flight attendant working 80
credit hours per month.
</P>
<P>
   To compensate for the increased per diem, the company wants
flight attendants to give up a proposed provision that would pay
them for all of their time when a flight runs longer than
scheduled. America West wants to pay only for the extra time if it
exceeds 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   It may not sound like much, but the extra time adds up and can
amount to a loss of up to 3 percent of a flight attendant's annual
salary, McGlashen said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the ledger, the company is offering a
maximum of five weeks of vacation (up from three weeks), increased
flexibility in scheduling and a provision allowing flight
attendants to save up more sick leave.
</P>
<P>
   Is it enough to satisfy the union, which has been seeking an
initial contract for the flight attendants for four years?
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Buttrick, an airline analyst for PaineWebber in New York,
said he senses that the economic differences can be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But from an emotional standpoint there's so much pent-up
frustration and anger, and that pent-up frustration is going to
need to find an appropriate vent,'' he said, hinting that a strike
may be inevitable. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815, or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
