<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
 12-HNS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Everyone's a contender for Big 12 men's tournament title
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By TERRY BLOUNT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KANSAS CITY _ It would be fair to say that the first two years of
the Big 12 men's basketball tournament lacked a little drama. It
was Kansas and the other 11 teams, each of which had slim hopes of
knocking off the Jayhawks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the kids felt we were selling them a bill of goods the
past two years by telling them we could go win this tournament,''
Oklahoma coach Kelvin Sampson said. ``There's no question things
have changed. It's up for grabs now, and I think it is going to be
more fun for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas (18-11 overall and 13-3 in league play) enters the
tournament as the regular-season champion and the top seed, but the
Longhorns are not an overwhelming favorite the way Kansas was the
last two years at Kemper Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the tournament is wide-open and everybody knows it,''
Texas coach Rick Barnes said. ``A very fine line separates the top
from bottom, and we saw that in games last week.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas A&AMP;M defeated Oklahoma, Texas Tech upended Nebraska and
Iowa State surprised Kansas in games leading up to the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have a great team in our league, but we have a lot of
real good ones,'' Oklahoma State coach Eddie Sutton said. ``There
are more quality teams in the field than I've seen in the past. We
have more teams capable of winning the championship than ever
before.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven teams enter the tournament with at least 18 victories and
nine teams have winning records for the season. But the Big 12 does
not have a team ranked in the top 20. Missouri is the only ranked
team at No. 24 after its victory over Texas at Austin on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our league has been unfairly criticized,'' Texas Tech
coach James Dickey said. ``I still think we deserve to have five
teams in the (NCAA) Tournament. The only difference is we didn't
have a bell cow this year like we did with Kansas the last two
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Kansas is 19-9 and 11-5 this season and enters the tournament as
the No. 3 seed. It is a year that most teams would be proud of, but
it isn't up to the Jayhawks' normal top-10 standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``People just expect Kansas to beat up on everybody,'' Colorado
coach Ricardo Patton said. ``But they have some youth they are
depending on right now. That's the transition period they are going
through. They have some young guys who are going to be great
players in this league, like (Eric) Chenowith, (Jeff) Boschee and
(Kenny) Gregory.''
</P>
<P>
   Chenowith, a 7-foot center, and Gregory, a 6-5 guard, are
sophomores. Boschee, a 6-1 point guard, was voted the Big 12
Freshman of the Year. But this season was an adjustment for a
Kansas program that lost two All-Americans in Raef LaFrentz and
Paul Pierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the (Big 12 tournament) championship game last year, we led
Kansas at halftime,'' Sampson said. ``Then Paul changed in a phone
booth and took over the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there are no Paul Pierces in this tournament, and
certainly no Raef LaFrentz. There are a lot of good players in the
league, but the talent is more spread out. Texas has three good
ones (Chris Mihm, Gabe Muoneke and Kris Clack), but everybody has
one or two.''
</P>
<P>
   The Longhorns trio is why Sutton still believes Texas should be
considered the favorite to win the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas has some go-to guys down low that really make a big
difference,'' Sutton said. ``If Texas has a game where they are not
shooting well outside, they can concentrate on getting the ball
down to the low post. That's a luxury we don't have.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas will play Friday at noon against the winner of the Iowa
State-Colorado game today. Oklahoma State (19-9, 10-6) needs a win
over Baylor today to play Oklahoma at 2:20 p.m. Friday.
</P>
<P>
   OSU and Nebraska (18-11, 10-6) are believed to be the two teams
that need to win some games this week to be assured of an at-large
spot in the NCAA Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did something last week I've never done before,'' Sutton
said. ``I called a member of the (NCAA selection) committee, who
happens to be an old friend. I told him, if it comes down to an
at-large bid, I hoped he would consider our loss at Kansas. That
was a tough loss on a very tough call.''
</P>
<P>
   OSU lost 67-66 in overtime when Adrian Peterson was called for a
controversial foul on a last-second shot attempt by Ryan Robertson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we won that game, we would have been seeded here and
probably already be in the (NCAA) tournament,'' Sutton said.
``Seven of our losses have come against teams that likely will be
in the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   And what did the committee member, a person Sutton would not
name, say to Sutton?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very surprised,'' Sutton said. ``He told me he saw the
game, and he would be surprised if every member of the committee
didn't see it. It shows how seriously they take this
responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   The four bye teams in the Big 12 tournament _ Texas, Missouri,
Kansas and OU _ probably have a spot in the NCAA field regardless
of how they do in the Big 12 tournament. The other eight teams in
the conference will have to win four games in four days to claim an
automatic bid in the NCAA field.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a very difficult task,'' Sutton said of the four wins
in four days. ``I didn't realize earlier that only one team has
ever done that. Auburn did it one year in the SEC.''
</P>
<P>
   But all the Big 12 coaches believe the chances of that happening
this year in the Big 12 tournament are much better than they were
the first two years of the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are 11 teams that believe they can win this
tournament,'' Missouri coach Norm Stewart said. ``I don't know who
I would pick, but I have lot confidence in our team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
