u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      03-04 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rockets' meeting addresses means to communicate
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By MICHAEL MURPHY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
After two weeks of game after game after game, the weary Rockets
finally get a break in their schedule. Or at least as close to a
break as you get in the NBA this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Clippers, the bunch that always seems to be
circled in red on every team's schedule, come to Compaq Center
tonight, mired in another of those slumps they always seem doomed
to endure. The Clippers have lost all 13 games they have played,
and there's no end in sight.
</P>
<P>
   Or is there?
</P>
<P>
   The way the locals have been playing, you have to wonder if the
Clippers aren't the ones who have broken out the red markers and
circled tonight's game as their chance to finally break through.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they must be champing at the bit to play the Rockets,
who were blown out by the struggling San Antonio Spurs 99-82 on
Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rocket Mario Elie came to town with the Spurs and bombed
the Rockets for 15 first-half points, then sat out the second half
with a strained groin.
</P>
<P>
   That injury report was updated to a strained grin because even
the notoriously grumpy Elie had to be elated after whacking his
former team. That win helped the Spurs end not only a two-game
slide, but also end all the talk _ temporarily, at least _ about
San Antonio's struggles.
</P>
<P>
   Now that talk has shifted down Interstate 10 to Houston. And
tonight, the Rockets will face a team that is desperate for a win,
which could lead to a highly competitive game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're more desperate than we are?'' said Charles Barkley in
mock exasperation. ``It couldn't get any lower for us if we lost to
those guys. That would be as low as it can go. We have to win
(tonight). But we can't really concern ourselves with the Clippers.
We have to get ourselves together. I'm excited that we're getting a
little bit better every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that process started when coach Rudy Tomjanovich and the
team met before Wednesday's practice to address the problems the
Rockets have experienced, and all agreed it was a productive
session.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we had a good talk about being a team and
communicating as a unit and feeling free to do it the right way in
the locker room _ about where we're at,'' Tomjanovich said.
``Because we have so many new guys that we have different ideas on
certain things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some things are just lack of knowledge. Other things are
different ideas and philosophies, but we have to be on the same
page, no matter what that is. We got some good work done, I think.
I feel that we did.''
</P>
<P>
   As does Hakeem Olajuwon, who is adjusting his game to
accommodate Scottie Pippen. For Olajuwon, accommodation means
communication, which is why Wednesday's meeting was so vital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Communication is always important,'' he said. ``It doesn't
matter (how many new players are on the team). Even though you have
been together for so long, you still have to communicate and
reinforce it every time to become second nature, without thinking
about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why this meeting today was very important because
everybody raises their concerns and how to solve the problem. We
recognized what the problem was, and now we are solving it. Now we
plan to move forward from now on.''
</P>
<P>
   And Olajuwon appreciates that Tomjanovich and the coaches sought
input from the players rather than attempting to dictate how things
would go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important because it is a team problem _
everybody is involved,'' Olajuwon said. ``Everybody is concerned,
so everybody has input to solve the problem, and that's the best
way, I think, to communicate for the players and the coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippen, who has appeared frustrated at times by the Rockets'
fitful play, thought one of the most important issues raised in the
meeting was that the players will be more aggressive in holding
each other accountable for the lack of effort they exhibited in
Tuesday's loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one in this locker room has the right to point any fingers
at anybody,'' Pippen said. ``We have to look at ourselves first and
realize that we're not giving a wholehearted effort. It's something
that we're not doing. (It can be corrected by) telling someone or
correcting someone in some way. That could even help. But we have
to provide more energy out on the court, and I think we all realize
that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, the players adjourned to the court, where
they had a spirited practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we had a good practice today,'' Barkley said. ``We had a
lot of energy left over from last night. A lot of energy left over
from last night.''
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully some of that energy will go into tonight's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just look at the fact that we still have plenty of time for
recovery from the huge disappointments that we encounter,''
Olajuwon said. ``The best thing now is just to regroup and make
positive strides.''
</P>
</TEXT>
