</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-UH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Gervin's attitude cause for optimism at Houston
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DALE ROBERTSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIRMINGHAM, Ala. _ The start was dreadful but the subsequent
spirited rally gave reason for hope. Then, mere seconds into the
second half Wednesday, Gee Gervin lofted a perfect alley-oop pass
to a soaring William Stringfellow, who had cut hard to the hoop.
</P>
<P>
   As should be the result of such a textbook play, there was
nothing but fresh air between String and the twine below him. That
gimmie jam would have cut UNC Charlotte's lead to three points,
down from 13 early in the game. That no-brainer jam might have
provided the impetus for a Cougars upset of a fairly decent NCAA
Tournament-bound team, thus giving Clyde Drexler something tangible
as he hits the recruiting trail in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, Stringfellow somehow bricked the dunk and, inside of five
minutes later, the 49ers had blown out to a 15-point lead. The end
for UH was nigh. The big Fellow, utterly deflated by his
all-but-impossible gaffe, fouled out with more than 11 minutes to
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see the look on (Stringfellow's) face,'' Drexler
said. ``It took all the wind out of his sails.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gervin, dragging around on a throbbing heel, was to be
finished himself soon thereafter.
</P>
<P>
   Gee whiz. Conference USA's regular-season assists leader never
registered a single one against the Niners, and he scored only 13
points to boot, seven off his C-USA leading average. His final
moments of an otherwise glorious UH inaugural season would be spent
on the bench with one shoe missing and his face hidden under a
towel.
</P>
<P>
   He stayed covered up so long we began to worry about him
suffocating. Gervin even changed seats once without ever removing
his shroud.
</P>
<P>
   Back for his senior season
</P>
<P>
   But his disconsolate countenance should have filled the Cougars'
hearts with joy. If you think this 75-51 first-round facial
courtesy of UNC Charlotte's defensive web was an unmitigated
disaster for the Cougars, think again. Rather, like Gee, it was a
blessing in disguise.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go out like this,'' Gervin said, ``would be a disgrace. I'm
looking forward to next year, to coming back to the tournament and
having a strong showing.''
</P>
<P>
   So he will ignore the NBA's siren's song and, to make amends,
stay at UH for his senior season?
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely,'' Gervin said.
</P>
<P>
   Ahh
</P>
<P>
   Rumors, you see, had begun circulating that Gee was
contemplating leaving for pro ball. That would not have been a nice
thing for a long-humbled program that's suddenly just one elite
recruiting class away from a return to national prominence, to high
hopes and legitimate aspirations for a place in the rankings sun
and March Madness participation.
</P>
<P>
   Although Drexler, the talent magnet, is off to a nice start in
procuring the kind of lads needed to play with, and beat, the big
ones, it's his intention to build around Gervin, a player he has
come to greatly admire.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's much better than I thought he was,'' Clyde said. ``He had
a fabulous year. I felt bad for him today, that he didn't get to
use the tournament to show people what he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Niners' own first-year head coach, Bobby Lutz, drew up
another smart game plan for stopping Gervin _ he always does _ but
it proved to be overkill. Gee was a step slow from the get-go and
would have had a difficult time beating a lone defender, never mind
the two or three coming at him from all points on the compass.
</P>
<P>
   Respect from an opponent
</P>
<P>
   It was a measure of the respect Lutz has for Gervin that he put
his best athlete, the 6-7, 205-pound Galen Young, on Gee, a
relative wisp at 6-2, 165, and sent plenty of help Young's way,
too. With Gervin hogtied, turned every which way but loose, UH
produced its worst offensive effort of the season by far.
</P>
<P>
   Where does Gervin go from here, if not to the bank and Benz
dealer? First to rest _ and probably to the doctor for an MRI on
his foot _ then straight to the weight room. Although he knows he
can't get any larger, he can get stronger. He has to, what with the
way people keep banging on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can gain some weight, musclewise,'' he said. ``But only so
much. I mean, my father was 6-8, 180.''
</P>
<P>
   And his mother, Joyce, is maybe 5-3. But Gee is an Ice cube off
the old block as far as his hoops instincts are concerned. He's a
scorer like George, despite being vertically challenged relative to
Pop's height. Drexler sees him having a bright future in the NBA,
where the illegal defense rule will give him considerably more
wiggle room.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see anybody like Young on him, either,'' Clyde said.
``That would be like me covering him.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the buzz that Gervin was eyeballing the NBA, Drexler
denied knowledge of same but responded in a tactful manner, saying
father would know best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell him anything his dad can't,'' Drexler said.
``That would be their decision. I wouldn't try to advise him,
unless he asked me to.''
</P>
<P>
   A moot point now, it appears. A bad day would get no worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
