</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN--Astros-Everett-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Playing time puts Astros' Everett in the swing
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By JOSEPH DUARTE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
KISSIMMEE, Fla. _ Astros hitting instructor Tom McCraw, who has
been in the business a quarter-century, has a theory: With enough
playing time and a little attention, most players will have their
coming-out-party within three or four years.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett was right on time.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in his three-plus major-league seasons, in
his first season with the Astros, Everett finally learned what it
was like to play. Not just an occasional start or pinch-hit
assignment, but to really play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's been the problem my whole career I never played every
day,'' said Everett, the Astros' starting center fielder heading
into the season. ``Everybody wanted to say I couldn't do this,
couldn't do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett's playing time has seen a sharp increase over the past
three seasons, as has his average.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, he started 36 games and batted .240. He started 101
games in his last season with the New York Mets in 1997, hitting
.248 with 14 home runs and 57 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   With the Astros last year, Everett started 113 times, setting
career highs for at-bats (467), runs (72), hits (138), doubles
(34), triples (four), homers (15) and RBIs (76).
</P>
<P>
   ``If a young offensive player is talented and is getting his
at-bats, he doesn't blossom until his third or fourth year. That's
when you see it come together,'' McCraw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of young players come up and down (from the minor
leagues to the majors). I think you can take all of Carl's pieces
of years, put them together, and he was in his fourth year when he
blossomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is if you get a guy, for any number of reasons,
who doesn't get his chance to play and develop in that third year,
he's going from a prospect to a suspect (in some people's eyes).
Nobody takes into consideration that he hasn't been playing,
getting 300 at-bats. He's in the big leagues getting 100 or 200
at-bats, playing part time, spare here, spare there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before finalizing the deal to acquire Everett last winter, the
Astros consulted with McCraw, who worked with the 27-year-old
outfielder briefly while McCraw was in New York. By the time McCraw
left for Houston, Everett had started to develop as a productive
hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told us Carl was ready to come into his own,'' manager
Larry Dierker said. ``He really thought Carl was ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon joining the Astros, Everett became part of a center-field
platoon with rookie Richard Hidalgo. By the end of May, Hidalgo was
sidelined with a separated shoulder and Everett had assumed the
starting role on a full-time basis.
</P>
<P>
   He became comfortable with his surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   From June 2 to July 31, Everett owned the steadiest bat in the
Astros' lineup, hitting .318 during one 25-game stretch with seven
homers and 39 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   His batting averaged topped out at .351 on June 10, when he was
near the top among NL hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Everett said his breakthrough season was all about getting
enough opportunities to step to the plate. His 467 at-bats last
season were 275 more than he got in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the case with anyone,'' Everett said. ``You take any
player and sit him out for 10 days and then ask him to do what he
normally does, and it's not going to happen. No player in baseball
can sit out 10 days and come back and be themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   The drop in Everett's performance came during the final two
months, when Hidalgo's return necessitated a return to the platoon.
Everett's average dipped 25 points to .296.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first year he had a chance to play through some
slumps,'' Dierker said. ``I think he went a long way toward proving
those hot streaks were something that if you left him out there, it
would come back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think last year was a fluke. I think he'll have a good
year again this year.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the Astros would like Everett to work on is his
running. He was thrown out 12 times in 26 stolen-base attempts, a
factor Everett attributes to getting bad jumps.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went when I shouldn't and didn't go when I should have,''
Everett said. ``I've never had that much trouble (in the past)
stealing bases.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett will be counted on to carry an extra load in 1999
following the loss of left fielder Moises Alou, who had knee
surgery Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Everett will play center while Hidalgo moves to left. Dierker
has plans to try using Everett second in the batting order, though
he could hit where he did last year _ sixth or seventh _ or maybe
even fifth.
</P>
<P>
   As for pressure, Everett doesn't believe he has to duplicate
Alou's 38 homers and 124 RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never think about pressure because it's a game you can only
do what you're able to do,'' Everett said. ``If there is any
pressure, it's pressure you put on yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
