u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS &LR;      03-04 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
West Coast events take toll on Doral
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MIAMI _ The PGA Tour has come east finally, wondering how in the
world the monthlong swing through Florida is going to live up to
the first two months on the West Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Most likely, it can't.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't individual moments like David Duval's 59 at the Bob
Hope Chrysler Classic or the debut of the World Golf Championships
at last week's match-play tournament that made the West Coast swing
such a hard act to follow (although they didn't hurt). It was the
whole, grand picture. Tiger Woods and Duval played six tournaments
in the eight weeks. Woods won once, Duval twice. Other winners
included big names like Payne Stewart and Ernie Els. Television
ratings soared at most events.
</P>
<P>
   But for every rise, there has to be a fall. While the top 64
players were at the Match Play Championship last week, the Tucson
Open had an obviously weakened field.
</P>
<P>
   And now, the Florida swing begins at the Doral-Ryder Open,
traditionally one of the Tour's strongest tournaments that signals
the beginning of the countdown to the Masters in early April.
</P>
<P>
   This year, however, it's not quite as formidable as in the past.
Only one of the top seven players in the Official World Golf
Rankings (Els) is playing and only one of the top seven
money-winners so far this year (John Huston) is in the field.
</P>
<P>
   No Woods. No Duval. No Jeff Maggert, who is No. 1 on the money
list after his win at La Costa. No Davis Love III, Mark O'Meara,
Phil Mickelson or Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Doral is bereft of quality, name-brand players. Among
those in the field are Els, Greg Norman, John Daly, Steve
Elkington, Nick Price, Jesper Parnevik and Vijay Singh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doral is kind of like Pebble Beach,'' said Elkington after his
pro-am round Wednesday. ``It's always going to get a lot of the top
players, no matter when it comes up on the schedule. It's a good
place to come to.''
</P>
<P>
   As Tour commissioner Tim Finchem said, there's nothing wrong
with the picture when looking at the field in the first week after
the match-play event.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of PGA Tour events would kill for this field,'' Finchem
said. However, he added that Doral may be getting by this year
somewhat on its reputation.
</P>
<P>
   It would be easy to say that Doral is feeling the effects of
post-major bailout. Not that the match-play tournament is a major
championship. But it was required attendance for the top 64 players
in the world because it was the first WGC event and had a $5
million purse. Most of those players also tuned up by playing in
Los Angeles the week before.
</P>
<P>
   Anytime there's a big tournament, the unlucky event the
following week suffers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doral is in the same position that we have been in during past
years,'' said Eric Fredricksen, executive director of the Houston
Golf Association, which runs the Shell Houston Open. ``When you
follow a major tournament, it has an impact on your field. Guys
usually play quite a bit leading up to a major tournament, then
take some time off.''
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame the top players for doing so? The biggest money
and the biggest prestige is what they play for.
</P>
<P>
   But Doral this year upped its purse to $3 million. Only six
tournaments this year will have bigger prize money and five of
those are invitational events.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Doral will represent the first full PGA Tour event
for Norman this year.
</P>
<P>
   Norman had shoulder surgery in April and didn't return to
competition until November. He has played a few competitive rounds,
such as The Presidents Cup, and he advanced to the second round of
the match-play last week.
</P>
<P>
   But this will be the first time he has teed it up in a four-day
Tour event since the Masters.
</P>
<P>
   ``My doctor doesn't want me playing more than two tournaments a
month,'' Norman said.
</P>
<P>
   Norman added that he has no reason to believe his game will not
return to the status it was before the injury, although if it
doesn't, he won't push any panic buttons.
</P>
<P>
   Norman has won Doral three times in the '90s, including 1990
when he shot 62 in the final round and won in a playoff. It would
surprise no one if he contended again this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to say Greg's the favorite this week,'' said Els.
``He plays this course great.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, at least, he used to. Doral underwent a facelift before the
1997 tournament and the remake was met with some discontent by Tour
players. That, combined with the West Coast boom, has made this
week a little less electric than usual.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
