<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 00:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7159 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--CLIPPERS-HNS &LR;      03-04 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--CLIPPERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Clippers threaten to sink to new depths
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By BILL SULLIVAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
DALLAS _ It's late in the third quarter in a one-third full Reunion
Arena, and Chris Ford wants to try something a little different. To
do so, the Los Angeles Clippers coach is standing in front of the
media table, shouting for the attention of guard Charles Smith, who
is dribbling the ball just outside the 3-point arc at the other end
of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run the play, Charles!'' Ford calls out, his tones audible in
a relatively quiet building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Run the play!''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Smith finds room for interpretation in this request. In
a heartbeat, the second-year guard from New Mexico _ seeing his
first action of the season and therefore relatively blameless for
the team's wretched start _ squares up and hoists a 3-pointer.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Smith, it finds the bottom of the net by way of
the cylinder. As the teams head back the other way, Ford's
expression is equal parts exasperation and relief.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nice shot, Charles,'' the coach says, smiling thinly.
</P>
<P>
   Such is life in Clipperville, which despite any proximity to
Disneyland remains The Unhappiest Place on the NBA Earth. As the
latest incarnation of Team Lotto rolls into town to take on the
Rockets tonight, a place in history once again beckons the
woebegone Buffalo-San Diego-Los Angeles franchise, which seems to
find dark days and low comedy wherever it may roam.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's 112-99 loss to the Mavericks made it a baker's
dozen to open this strange, abbreviated season. At 0-13, Los
Angeles' ``other'' team finds itself just three losses short of its
own worst-ever start and only four from tying the 1988-89 Miami
Heat for the most fruitless beginning in NBA history.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a season marked by tired legs, artless play and dubious
achievements, the Clippers continue to carve out their special
niche. Now, with each stop along the road, they find opponents more
and more determined to make sure the league's only winless team
remains that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't want to be the one,'' the Mavericks' A.C. Green said
after his 19 points and 12 rebounds helped assure the streak would
live another night. ``You have a team that's on the brink of
disaster. You don't want to be the team they're going to beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The pleasure of being First Clipped remains to be had, with the
Rockets next on the list of potential victims. Lose by a little,
lose by a lot, the Clippers have found a way to get it done each
and every time out, and the end might not be in sight.
</P>
<P>
   For the better part (and we use the term loosely) of the decade,
the Mavericks have been even more inept than the Clippers, winning
40 fewer games since the 1989-90 season and leaving the visitors a
little room to dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing disparaging,'' Ford said, ``but you think you have a
shot coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   The next one might be a while in coming. After tonight, the
Clippers go to San Antonio before facing the cross-town rival
Lakers in back-to-back games next week.
</P>
<P>
   If the trend continues, that first game against Shaq, Worm, Kurt
and Kobe could be for No. 16, tying the club record. The second
could enable the Clippers to match the Heat's league mark.
</P>
<P>
   That would set up a March 11 date with infamy as the Sacramento
Kings call _ a game perhaps not everyone circled when the revised
schedule was released.
</P>
<P>
   If the Clippers were bent on ending the suspense Tuesday night,
it wasn't immediately evident. Dallas scored 38 first-quarter
points _ a season best _ to open a 14-point lead. After seeing that
advantage shrink to 53-48 at the break, the Mavericks opened the
second half with a 7-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of things, Smith's shot selection by no means was
the most curious. In the third quarter, the Clippers insisted on
taking the ball inside on 7-6 Dallas center Shawn Bradley, who
blocked five attempts in the period and nine in the game while
barely so much as shuffling his feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Bradley) just stood there with that hand out, and for some
reason we continued to challenge him,'' Ford said. ``For what
reason, I have no idea.''
</P>
<P>
   When it was done, the coach (who wasn't hired until Jan. 13
because owner Donald Sterling didn't want to spend the money during
the lockout) was promising lineup changes.
</P>
<P>
   Starters Lamond Murray and Eric Piatkowski had lost minutes to
Smith and rookie free agent Tyrone Nesby, and Ford said the latter
two would get more playing time in the near future. Forward Brian
Skinner, the first-round pick from Baylor, is back after missing
the first 11 games following arthroscopic knee surgery and is
expected to be more of a factor, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``The energy the young guys are providing _ that's what I
want,'' Ford said. ``I've tried every way I can to get it across.
If they don't realize it by now, the younger guys will play.''
</P>
<P>
   But unraveling the mystery of the most intriguing of those young
players will have to wait. Michael Olowokandi, the 7-foot center
and first pick in the draft, was averaging 9.7 points and 7.8
rebounds before spraining an ankle against the Lakers on Feb. 26
and going on the injured list.
</P>
<P>
   So the bad times continue for a franchise all too accustomed to
insult and injury, not to mention being on the short end of the
score. Incredibly enough, the run is the ninth losing streak of 12
or more games in franchise history, and the Braves/Clippers have
proved remarkably adept at spreading joy wherever they go.
</P>
<P>
   Lest LA fans (those who care, at least) feel too put upon, they
can take heart in the knowledge the club previously turned the
trick in Buffalo and San Diego. Folks just down the coast once were
treated to a 19-game skid before their heroes won the final game of
that 1981-82 season.
</P>
<P>
   The crowning accomplishment, though, might have been the 1986-87
club featuring Benoit Benjamin, underachievement's poster boy. In
one particularly gruesome stretch, those Clippers lost 12 in a row,
won once, then dropped the next 16. As if to underscore this was
not the product of dumb luck and bad officiating, they ran the
table at season's end, losing their last 14 to finish 12-70.
</P>
<P>
   Now, old misery seeks new company. The future might prove less
dreary, but the present isn't crying out for a new pair of
Ray-Bans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing's going to be easy,'' Ford said. ``No one's going to
give us a gift.''
</P>
<P>
   No one has.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean they haven't been happy to see the
Clippers coming.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0006EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
