<HEADER>
A7162 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-RICE-HNS &LR;      03-04 0722
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-RICE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rice, New Mexico vie in WAC quarterfinal
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By NEAL FARMER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
LAS VEGAS _ The Rice Owls have one goal in this glitter capital of
the world: to look postseason sexy.
</P>
<P>
   So far, so good.
</P>
<P>
   The Owls shot 52 percent from the floor in beating an inspired
San Jose State team 64-61 in the first round of the Qwest Western
Athletic Conference tournament on Tuesday. The only blemish: Rice
missed nine of its last 15 free throws to throw the game into
question.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shot the ball pretty well, just not at the free-throw
line,'' said Owls coach Willis Wilson. ``The free throws at the end
just made that part of our game look glaring. But I thought we
played well.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice plays 25th-ranked New Mexico at 8 tonight in the WAC
quarterfinals at the Thomas &AMP; Mack Center. The question now,
barring a tournament championship, is whether the 18-9 Owls look
good enough for the National Invitation Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have put ourselves in position to merit a lot of
consideration for the postseason,'' Wilson said. ``But first things
first. We have to try to beat New Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson believes the Owls can be tough when they dictate the
tempo. It doesn't have to be turtle-like, just methodical enough
for the Owls to put up high-percentage shots every time down the
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing good basketball right now. Against San Jose
State, our defense was a little off, and I attribute that to the
Spartans' style of play,'' Wilson said. ``We feel like with each
passing game, the challenges get better. And we have risen to those
challenges. We're looking forward to going out there and playing a
quality basketball team like New Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said his biggest qualm about facing the Lobos is their
desire to run wild.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are very good in the open floor,'' he said. ``They shoot
well from the outside and present a lot of problems. We'll have to
force them to build a half-court offense and not allow they to run
off and build a big lead.''
</P>
<P>
   UNM center Kenny Thomas, an NBA prospect, could be less than 100
percent. Thomas and teammate Damion Walker collided in practice on
Monday, and Thomas swallowed two pieces of teeth after the bump.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny and Damion were just battling hard under the boards,''
said Lobos coach Dave Bliss. ``Things like that just happen.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rice-New Mexico winner will meet the survivor of today's
late quarterfinal between SMU and Moutain Division champion UNLV,
the tournament's host. The Mustangs got this far by edging Texas-El
Paso 65-64 on Tuesday on Renaldo Bratton's layup with one second
left, the result of a length-of-the-court drive.
</P>
<P>
   In today's first quarterfinal, Fresno State will take on a hot
Tulsa team. The Bulldogs on Tuesday overcame a trip straight from
Hawaii, where they closed the regular season, to Las Vegas, ripping
Colorado State 80-59.
</P>
<P>
   Fresno State coach Jerry Tarkanian said he wasn't sure if his
team would be around after the first half.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were dealt a tough hand,'' Tarkanian said. ``We had the
right to be tired and flat. If we didn't come out and play well, we
wouldn't even have needed to bring a change of underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   Utah, projected unanimously as the tournament's winner, takes on
Brigham Young in today's second game. The Utes have tied a school
record with 19 consecutive wins and are coming off a 77-47 rout of
New Mexico in their regular-season finale. The eighth-ranked Utes
are in the NCAA Tournament; it's just a question of how high the
defending national runners-up will be seeded.
</P>
<P>
   BYU was a surprise 90-74 first-round winner over TCU. The Horned
Frogs, who were on the NCAA bubble, probably played their way into
the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   TCU coach Billy Tubbs, who was less than pleased with the
officiating, said his staff charts how many calls each referee
gives each team and that referee Scott Thornley made 15 calls
against TCU and two against BYU. But despite his anger, Tubbs
denied speculation that TCU would either go to the NCAAs or nowhere
for the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard it was on the Internet (that TCU did not want to go to
the NIT),'' Tubbs said. ``I don't know where that came from. It
didn't come from our basketball office. If they want us, we'll
definitely go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
