<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-MAPLELEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT MAPLE LEAFS, 5-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Years from now the New Jersey Devils will be the
answer to a trivia question as the team that beat the Maple Leafs
for the first time in Toronto's new home, the modern Air Canada
Center, which replaced historic Maple Leaf Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils not only became the first visitors in four games at
the new arena to beat the league's most productive team, but also
did it in style, scoring five unanswered goals after falling behind
by two for a 5-2 triumph over the Maple Leafs on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We kept our composure after we went down by two goals and took
a couple penalties,'' said Scott Stevens, the Devils' captain, who
took one of the penalties in the second period while the Devils
were trailing on two goals by Sergei Berezin.
</P>
<P>
   After goals by Scott Niedermayer and Bob Carpenter tied the
score at 2-2, Jason Arnott scored twice and Patrik Elias added an
empty-net goal to help the Devils improve the league's best road
record to 20-8-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of character on this team,'' said Arnott, who
has five goals in the last three games to give him 18 for the
season. ``We knew we had to come back and we did.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory pushed the Devils (34-20-8) into a tie for first in
the Eastern Conference with Ottawa at 76 points and extended their
Atlantic Division lead over idle Philadelphia to 3 points. Toronto
is 34-22-5.
</P>
<P>
   An instigating penalty against the Devils' Lyle Odelein for
fighting Tie Domi for the second time in the game proved costly as
Berezin capitalized on the man advantage to give the Maple Leafs a
2-0 lead 9 minutes 29 seconds into the period. It was an easy task
for Berezin as he had plenty of time for two attempts from Martin
Brodeur's right doorstep.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the last bright moment in the game for the Maple
Leafs, who lost for the first time in their new home after
victories over Montreal and Florida and a tie with Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Niedermayer started the Devils' comeback with 3:21 left in the
second period with his eighth goal of the season, and Carpenter
tied it with 25 seconds left on the clock to send the teams
deadlocked into the third period. That set the stage for Arnott's
line.
</P>
<P>
   Arnott broke the tie with a blistering shot from near the
right-wing boards just 51 seconds into the last period and extended
the lead with his second goal of the night with another blistering
shot, this time from the left point at 11:35. Elias iced the
victory with his empty-netter with 44 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody keeps telling me to shoot the puck, and that's what
I'm trying to do,'' Arnott said of his recent success. ``Our line
is playing well and we're communicating well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
