<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NJ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT HELPS TORRICELLI RAISE $2.1 MILLION 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ On a day when millions tuned in to see Monica
Lewinsky on television and thousands turned out to see Hillary
Rodham Clinton in New York City, President Clinton stayed quietly
out of the limelight, flying to New Jersey to help raise campaign
money for Sen. Robert Torricelli.
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton arrived here late on Wednesday afternoon, his wife
was across the Hudson River in Manhattan, receiving the kind of
media attention usually reserved for the president himself.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton is considering running for Senate in New York next
year, and her two-day visit to the city has attracted a horde of
reporters from across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Later, as the president was flying back to Washington aboard Air
Force One on Wednesday evening, ABC was broadcasting Barbara
Walters's two-hour interview with Ms. Lewinsky, whose book,
``Monica's Story'' is to go on sale on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Aides to the president said he did not watch the ABC interview
and would have no comment on Ms. Lewinsky's remarks.
</P>
<P>
   The $1,000-per-person fund-raiser for Torricelli, who is not up
for re-election until 2002, drew 1,500 people to the New Jersey
Performing Arts Center here.
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli's aides said the event, which took in $2.15 million,
was the most successful fund-raiser in history for an individual
member of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   During his speech on Wednesday night, Clinton did not refer to
his wife's potential Senate candidacy. But Torricelli did, taking
credit for having started the drumbeat several weeks ago when he
mused off-camera before a Sunday talk show that Mrs. Clinton was
thinking about moving to New York to run for the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies and gentlemen,'' Torricelli told the audience, ``I am
the man who created and is managing the Hillary Rodham Clinton
campaign for the United States Senate.''
</P>
<P>
   The event opened with appearances by several prominent New
Jersey natives. Kevin Spacey, the actor, was the master of
ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   The singer Cissy Houston, whose daughter is the pop star Whitney
Houston, sang the national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   And the singer Gloria Gaynor performed two of her biggest hits
for the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to the podium, Clinton said he had been singing
along with Ms. Gaynor backstage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to decide whether it was more appropriate for me
to sing `I Will Survive,''' he said, drawing wild applause from the
audience. But he said he preferred ``Never Can Say Goodbye.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's speech touched on his major goals for the year:
securing the Social Security and Medicare systems, increasing
federal spending on schools and expanding the rights of managed
care patients.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
