<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SALMON BACK ON HIS (INJURED) FEET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ Yes, Tim Salmon says, he's tired of talking about
his left foot. But at least he's saying good things about it.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon was limited to DH duty nearly all of last season because
of a torn ligament in the foot. He had surgery immediately after
the season to sever the ligament completely. He also had a
procedure on his right foot, and couldn't begin running until
January.
</P>
<P>
   But Salmon is running now _ and jumping, and sliding without
pain. He's playing right field again and says it's like he never
left.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I went back to the outfield, I was worried about my
skills,'' Salmon said. ``But when I went out there, it was like I
never missed a day. It was like last year never happened. I was
doing all the same things I normally do.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said he did not rush his rehab during the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a good boy about it,'' he said. ``It was my career. The
last thing I wanted to do was set myself back. I even held back
playing golf, and I usually play a lot during the off-season.''
</P>
<P>
   Last season was tough for Salmon and he admits he felt like an
outsider.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you can't do what you're supposed to be doing, you feel
like you're letting the team down,'' he said. ``I was fortunate to
be able to DH. If I was in the other league, I would have been done
for the year.''
</P>
<P>
   In his six full seasons, Salmon has hit .297 and averaged 30
homers and 98 RBIs (including strike-shortened 1994 and '95), yet
he's never made an All-Star team. Salmon, traditionally a slow
starter, took extra hitting during the spring last year in an
effort to get off to a fast start. He'll do the same this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I got off to a good start in the first two weeks
(before injuring the foot),'' he said. ``I feel like it made a
difference. Whether it translates into an All-Star appearance, I
don't know. As I get older, it means a little bit more to me. But
it's not the reason I'm doing the extra things. I want to be
productive so this team can be a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina update: Shortstop Gary DiSarcina, out with a broken
bone in his left forearm, was X-rayed again Wednesday and was told
the bone is healing properly. He was fitted for a new hard cast,
which was the same size as the previous one that went from his hand
to biceps muscle.
</P>
<P>
   He had hoped the cast size would be reduced, which would enable
him to increase the amount of work he could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready for a short cast yet because it still hurts,''
DiSarcina said. ``I have no problem being cautious like that... I
may be hard-headed when it comes to certain things, but when it
comes to serious pain, I'm the first to bow out. The last thing you
want to happen is to re-break the bone. I guarantee I won't be
playing opening day if I have pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Deals and steals: The Angels agreed to terms on one-year deals
with pitcher Jason Dickson, infielder Justin Baughman and catcher
Bret Hemphill. The club still has eight players unsigned but has
until March 10 to renew their contracts.... The Angels will begin
selling individual game tickets on Saturday from 9 a.m.-5:30 p.m.
at the main box office at Edison Field. Tickets also will be
available at TicketMaster Ticket Centers.... The Angels begin
Cactus League play Friday at Tempe Diablo Stadium against the
Oakland A's. Every game except those on Sunday and March 28
(preempted by Lakers games) will be broadcast on KLAC beginning at
12:05 (PST).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
