<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: AFTER INDY COUNSELS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs 7th graf for clarification)  By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Back in the Bush administration, press reports
revealed the corrupt use of U.S. government grain guarantees to
help Saddam Hussein build his war machine before he surprised us by
invading Kuwait. When the Justice Department shyly turned away, the
need arose for independent counsel to explore ``Iraqgate.''
</P>
<P>
   No way, said George Bush, already burned by a special
prosecution of Iran-contra. His attorney general instead used a
patsy prosecutor until the Independent Counsel Act lapsed.
</P>
<P>
   During that '92 campaign, I called candidate Bill Clinton to ask
if he favored renewing the Independent Counsel Act to handle such
high-level corruption, and in this space reported his unequivocal
answer: ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, I reminded President Clinton of his promise and
asked if he would sign the bill languishing in Congress. He
replied: ``I certainly intend to sign the law just like I always
said I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus publicly encouraged, the Senate Democratic leader, George
Mitchell, put the five-year renewal forward and the majority
leader, Bob Dole, brought it to the floor for passage. Clinton
signed it in June 1994. (For some reason, he has not returned a
call of mine since.)
</P>
<P>
   The act expires in June, and _ thanks to the unpopularity of Ken
Starr _ the idea of an unconflicted investigation of wrongdoing in
high places has become the loneliest legislative orphan in America.
Critics holler: Costs too much! Takes too long! Criminalizes
political mistakes and mere personal flings!
</P>
<P>
   Not since that catastrophic day in 1915 when the Lake Michigan
cruise ship Eastland capsized as it left its dock on the Chicago
River, drowning 800 passengers, partly because so many rushed to
the same side, has there been such a disaster threatened by a crowd
surging to one side.
</P>
<P>
   Not really a disaster; the Republic will survive when denizens
of the White House can rely on a political crony in the attorney
general's chair to shut down investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Renoism is already with us. The illegal financing of the 1996
election by Asian bankers buying influence was the recent case that
most cried out for aggressively independent probing. But Reno
defied the FBI director and punished a too-honest prosecutor who
had dared to recommend that the investigation be entrusted to those
not previously involved in malfeasant befuddlement.
</P>
<P>
   Because that internal Clinton Justice cover-up worked despite
the clear mandate of the act, even a man as steeped in Watergate as
Sen. Fred Thompson has thrown up his hands and joined the crowd
stampeding to the railing.
</P>
<P>
   What can be placed in the indy counsel's stead to prevent the
appointment to high Justice posts of dishonest cronies (like
Webster Hubbell), or to stop the present see-no-evil attitude
toward corruption by the politically grateful?
</P>
<P>
   1. Build some oversight into the way an attorney general selects
outside, ``special'' _ though not independent _ counsels. An
advisory board of judges appointed by all three branches could
provide the names of outsiders capable of giving ethical cover to
an administration under public pressure to show no conflict of
interest.
</P>
<P>
   2. Put more subpoena-power bite and professional investigators
into Judiciary committees to act as a whip on the backs of lax
Justice investigators. Such full-time ``oversighters'' would work
best when one House of Congress is of a party different from the
president's.
</P>
<P>
   3. Make the chief of Justice's now-laughable Office of Public
Integrity confirmable by the Senate. Sweep out time-servers
blocking reform.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these thoughts will be transmitted to Justice soon by
Reps. Gekas, Hutchinson and Graham of the House Administrative Law
subcommittee in an effort to get Reno to spell out its alternative
to the Independent Counsel Act.
</P>
<P>
   With no independent counsel, Congress must turn to serious
oversight _ pressing prosecutors to do their anti-corruption job.
The media should reduce their self-flagellation as well as their
dependence on prosecutorial leaks, and invest more in original
investigative stories.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, what will rebuild pressure on the powerful to obey
the law, stick to the truth and adhere to ethical standards? Only
the renascence of public outrage.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
