<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: AN INTERVIEW PAINFUL BUT FASCINATING TO WATCH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (With LEWINSKY-INTERVIEW)   (sw) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The promotions that ran for days showed Monica Lewinsky wiping a
tear from her eye, as if in a parody (or a promise) of the
inevitable: Barbara Walters always gets her subjects to cry. The
weeping Monica image came near the end of Wednesday night's
two-hour extravaganza, but the teasers were misleading in their
traumatic tone.
</P>
<P>
   The choice of Ms. Walters as interviewer was guaranteed to
provide maximum sympathy and questions about feelings. Allowed to
shape her own image this way, Ms. Lewinsky created yet another
persona. She was not the hysterical rejected woman taped by Linda
Tripp, or the composed mature woman of her videotaped deposition.
Here she displayed all her lingering girlish delusions in an
interview that was surprisingly painful and fascinating to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The interview may have been a ``20/20'' news special, but it was
packaged and promoted with all the skill, though slighlty less
glitz, than the typical Walters pre-Oscar interview. There were
fewer family photos than usual, though there was a home video of a
chubby, adolescent Monica singing.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, Ms. Lewinsky softened her image. With her hair sleekly
back off her face, (conveniently matching the fresh-faced photo on
her book jacket) she literally looked less bubble-headed. Seated on
a sofa, she was viewed from a slenderizing angle.
</P>
<P>
   And though she got around to the sobbing, wrenching moments (``I
felt like a piece of trash,'' she said of her reaction to the
president's admission that their affair was wrong), through much of
the interview she was smiling, trying almost too hard to be
engaging and accepting. At times her words made her seem like a
lovelorn adolescent clinging to what she called a ``crush,''
giggling when she said of the president, ``He's a good kisser.''
</P>
<P>
   After all this, what can Monica Lewinsky add to the picture of a
presidential crisis? She might have helped answer a lingering
question: Who is the woman who provoked it? But the interview's
only hint in that direction came in its affirmation of how ordinary
the affair was. In Ms. Lewinsky's account, the president comes
across as a common lying cad, who said, ``I can't wait until I can
hold you again,'' then broke his promise about bringing her back to
work near him at the White House. That's bad news for those who
think the president should be a heroic role model, but it's a
realistic image for this non-heroic age.
</P>
<P>
   If Ms. Lewinsky had chosen a different interviewer, she might
have had to spin in a different direction. Oprah would have tried
to inspire her to change her life; Roseanne would have encouraged
her to dish the sexy details in the name of girl power. Ms. Walters
is the master of asking a tough question then letting the subject
off the hook without a tough follow-up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did you tell Linda Tripp about this dress?'' she asks
about the infamous DNA-stained blue dress from the Gap.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it was funny,'' Ms. Lewinsky answers.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walters then plays a tape of Ms. Tripp suggesting the dress
is evidence; Ms. Lewinsky smiles and shrugs.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Walters also knows how to let the famous reveal
themselves accidentally; that's why her interviews can be
illuminating in spite of her questions. On her daytime show ``The
View,'' she displayed a gift: a scarf Ms. Lewinsky had knitted and
handed to her in, of all things, a Gap bag. Ms. Lewinsky may be
acquiring a constellation of images; let's be grateful that Saint
Monica is not among them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
