<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROBINSON TO MISS GAMES FOR FUNERAL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS   
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kings coach Larry Robinson will leave the team
today for several days to attend the funeral of his mother, who
died late Tuesday in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   In Robinson's absence, assistant coaches Rick Green and Jay
Leach will run the team. Robinson is expected to miss home games
tonight and Saturday against Nashville and Calgary, and is expected
to rejoin the Kings on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Isobel Robinson was 78.
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin out: The Mighty Ducks were without center Steve Rucchin,
their third-leading scorer with 22 goals and 56 points. According
to the team, Rucchin was sidelined with ``sinus problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin suffered a broken nose nearly two weeks ago in a game at
Calgary. Over the weekend, he took a shot to the head from San
Jose's Bryan Marchment, but Rucchin said he was not hit in the
nose. According to Rucchin, a combination of flu and the broken
nose was the reason he didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said, `His nose was basically
crushed in Calgary. I'm sure there's a combination of things going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Peaking Ducks: February was the best month in Ducks history, and
a big part of the reason was Teemu Selanne, who had 25 points and
was the NHL's Player of the Month.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks posted a 10-3 record in February, besting their 7-3-4
record in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of Selanne, Hartsburg said: ``He's a unique guy. He loves to be
around the guys and he loves playing. That combination is hard to
find. Teemu makes the most out of every day, and I'm sure not every
day is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya added: ``He's real good when things aren't going
well. He never gets down. He always has something to be happy
about, like getting a new car.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne had at least one point in each of the Ducks' 13 games in
February, collecting a total of 12 goals and 13 assists. He scored
the 300th goal of his career Saturday against San Jose, reaching
that milestone in 464 games, the sixth-fastest in NHL history. Only
Wayne Gretzky, Mario Lemieux, Brett Hull, Mike Bossy and Jari Kurri
scored 300 goals in fewer games.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: The Ducks entered the game with an 8-2-4 record
against Pacific Division teams, compared with the Kings' 3-13
mark.... The Kings re-assigned center Eric Belanger to Springfield
of the AHL. Belanger, one of the Kings' top prospects, had been
assigned to the Long Beach Ice Dogs last week, for whom he appeared
in one game.... Winger Vladimir Tsyplakov, sidelined two weeks with
a knee injury, has been skating with a brace.... Kings center Yanic
Perreault, who has six goals in the last 52 games he's appeared in,
was a healthy scratch. Perreault was benched for the entire third
period of Sunday's 1-0 loss in Dallas. Winger Sandy Moger also was
a healthy scratch, and defenseman Philippe Boucher missed the game
because of a bout with the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
