<SLUG> BC-MONICA-GALLERY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY INTERVIEW VIEWERS DISPLAY NO SYMPATHY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
In the end, no one felt any sympathy for Monica Lewinsky.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The seven people who gathered at The Arizona Republic's offices
to watch ABC's Barbara Walters inter view the former White House
intern left completely revolted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone in the nation wanted to give her the benefit of a
doubt,'' said Gwen Moreno of Phoenix. ``I thought I would feel some
sympathy for her or something after watching this. But I am totally
disgusted with her. She has no remorse.''
</P>
<P>
   In the East Coast, viewers might have been talking about a
potential political career. In California, the topic could have
been a place for her in Hollywood. But in Arizona, in a ninth-floor
conference room, people felt stunned by Lewinsky's glowing face and
joyful smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at her. Her face is beam ing. She is so happy to be in
the na tion's spotlight,'' noted Jane Reddin, an attorney with
Lewis &AMP; Roca in Phoenix. ``Her words are not matching her face. We
see this a lot with witnesses. They say one thing, `I feel bad.'
But their face says something else. That's what's hap pening with
Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   Why so happy? Why so proud? People in this room kept looking for
the answer.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Murray, a Scottsdale sex therapist, thought it was
``euphoric recall.'' While she can't diagnose Lewinsky, Murray says
many people with sexual addictions often become elated reliving
illicit affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like she's going into euphoric recall,'' explained
Murray. ``She is so happy to be reliving the moments with the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Others had more simple answers.
</P>
<P>
   Toni Morales believed Lewinsky was beaming because she was still
in love with President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is still madly in love with him. She's not in reality. If
she was my daughter, I would slap her,'' said Morales, a Phoenix
hairdresser.
</P>
<P>
   No so, argued Sam Rogers, who works for the Environmental Protec
tion Agency and attended the im peachment trial on the first day.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a profit involved here. This has been all very
well-orches trated,'' Rogers said. ``She knows it.''
</P>
<P>
   I had expected to come away feeling sorry for Lewinsky. After
all, she was just a 22-year-old in tern. But as I watched, the
distaste grew. It wasn't until the end, when I was hit with this
realization, that I felt some sympathy:
</P>
<P>
   No matter what Lewinsky does with her life, she will be always
be known as the White House intern who had an affair with the presi
dent.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton, however, will be re membered as president of the
United States. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
