<SLUG> BC-WIND-BRIDGE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITICAL COMMUTER BRIDGE DAMAGED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GEORGE FOSTER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Imagine a plugged funnel.
</P>
<P>
   With the storm-damaged Evergreen Point Bridge closed at least
until Friday, more than 120,000 cars, trucks and buses that flow
across the Lake Washington floating span each day will instead have
to flow somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   Brace for gridlock on some of the worst-congested highways and
bridges in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn yesterday morning, high winds and waves shattered
mechanical parts that control the bridge's west drawspan. The state
immediately closed down the 1.4-mile bridge, one of the longest of
its type in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bad thing is the damn thing broke; the good thing is that
we have spare parts,'' said Jerry Weigel, the state's chief bridge
and structures engineer.
</P>
<P>
   That's not much of a silver lining for drivers. Department of
Transportation television monitors Wednesday night showed tightly
packed lines of cars threading slowly through Seattle as commuters
who usually rely on state Route 520 detoured to Interstate 90.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the normal traffic load of 120,000 to 150,000 vehicles a
day from the Evergreen Point Bridge to the Interstate 90 bridge and
roads at either end of Lake Washington is expected to make
Thursday's commute especially long and tedious.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the rain continues, the whole area will experience a form
of gridlock,'' predicted Department of Transportation spokesman
Bill Southern. ``Start off early or figure out a way to car pool,
telecommute, or maybe take the day off. Think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Or take the bus.
</P>
<P>
   Metro Transit will add coaches to routes that normally use Route
520, shifting them to I-90 for the commute across the lake. The
longer drive will add time, but don't yell at the bus driver. Blame
the weather.
</P>
<P>
   State transportation personnel check the bridge whenever there
are sustained winds of 45 mph or higher. Wednesday, the gusts were
recorded at higher than 60 mph, and inspectors noticed the center
drawspan was moving around a more than usual when the lake is
rough.
</P>
<P>
   After consulting with maintenance engineer Tom Lentz, they
opened the drawspans at about 5:50 a.m. and found that two of the
vertical rollers and one of the horizontal rollers that keep the
movable west span in line had been damaged by waves. Also, 2-inch
bolts that keep them in place had been stripped of their threads,
Lentz said. A large support beam that holds one of the vertical
guide rollers was damaged and also may need to be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to stormy weather, the location of the damage
complicates the work. The damaged vertical rollers are in a small
space under the span, Lentz said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the center lock system that holds the two movable
spans together was broken while the span was being unlocked and
waves several feet high washed over the bridge sections.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation couldn't estimate the cost of
the repairs Wednesday. New parts could cost less than $100,000,
Lentz said, adding that the major cost would be in labor _ crews
working around the clock on 12-hour shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things,'' he added, ``is that we haven't found
structural damage.''
</P>
<P>
   That means the hollow concrete pontoons are sound.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the damage was the worst since the Jan. 20, 1993,
Inaugural Day storm, when waves whipped by winds of up to 80 mph
bashed the floating bridge, severing anchor cables and cracking the
pontoons, Southern said.
</P>
<P>
   More cracking, mainly on the bottom of the pontoons, was noticed
after a Dec. 12, 1995, storm.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact that no structural damage or leaks were found
Wednesday, the damage is further evidence that the 36-year-old
bridge is aging while traffic over it is steadily increasing.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little like a senior citizen slipping on the back
steps and spraining an ankle,'' Secretary of Transportation Sid
Morrison said. ``It's just another reminder that this bridge is
approaching 40 years of age and exists in a strenuous
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   While state inspectors were checking the bridge Wednesday for
damage, a Trans-Lake Study Committee met on the Eastside to
consider ways of reducing traffic congestion to and from the
Eastside.
</P>
<P>
   Among the options are an additional floating bridge north of the
Evergreen Point Bridge, ferry service, and adding high-occupancy
vehicle lanes to the existing bridge.
</P>
<P>
   A briefing paper presented to the state Transportation
Commission a year ago put the cost of bringing the bridge up to
100-year storm design standards at $150 million. That would
involved replacing the anchor cable system and pontoons for
carrying the same four lanes of traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a new six-lane bridge, including HOV lanes, has been
estimated at about $800 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the cost of preserving the present bridge over the next
20 years would be $26 million, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
   The state already has begun the preservation work, sealing
pontoon cracks and spending $5 million on new cables. In addition,
Weigel said, new high-strength cables will connect all the pontoons
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an old bridge that needs a whole lot of work to bring it
up to standards,'' said state Rep. Karen Schmidt, a Bainbridge
Island Republican who shares the chairmanship of the House
Transportation Committee with Rep. Ruth Fisher, D-Tacoma.
</P>
<P>
   A new one, added Fisher, would be ``one of those high-cost
projects that we cannot find the money for.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
