<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOL-NURSES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RULING ON NURSES FOR DISABLED COULD COST L.A. SCHOOLS $18 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY SHARLINE CHIANG  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles school officials said the district
will be hit hard financially by a U.S. Supreme Court ruling
ordering public schools nationwide to provide disabled students
with nurses during school hours.
</P>
<P>
   An initial estimate put the Los Angeles Unified School
District's cost at $18 million for as many as 300 students who
could request the new service to attend school.
</P>
<P>
   The 7-2 ruling stemmed from a case involving a quadriplegic Iowa
teen-ager, whose family requested a nurse for the boy so he could
attend regular school.
</P>
<P>
   L.A. school officials complained the ruling is excessive and
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Either the law has got to be altered, or someone is going to
have to find additional funding or else local school districts are
going to go bankrupt,'' said school board member David Tokofsky.
``Since we're a big district, we can cover these costs easier.
We'll just have less available for other programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The school district's $18 million a year estimate is based on
the district's enrolling 200 to 300 students covered by the ruling
and nurses costing more than $60,000 per student, according to
Bonnie Garcia, attorney for the district's special education reform
program known as the Chanda Smith Decree.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, who has been following the Iowa case for about five
years, said since the law mandates full-time nurses, districts will
not risk ``cutting corners'' by hiring attendants.
</P>
<P>
   Placing certain handicapped students on campus could increase
liability to the school and place pupils at a safety risk, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have concerns that if they are so fragile that they require
a nurse and not an attendant, then that is a medically fragile kid.
All things assumed, we'd rather have them at home,'' Garcia said.
``That's a quality of care issue. That's a risk issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Upon first glance, local advocates for the disabled rejoiced the
ruling Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cost impact to something like this ... but society
has to decide what it wants to fund for its most vulnerable
citizens,'' said Nancy Graves, director of consumer services in the
Ventura County office of the Tri-County Regional Center, which
provides services to developmentally disabled people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0100EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0022 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7186 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-ARENA-AZR     03-04 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ARENA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARENA PLAN WOULD IM PROVE COYOTES SEATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KENT SOMERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - America West Arena officials are finalizing a plan to
renovate the north end of the arena and use collapsible seat risers
in an effort to alleviate the problem with obstructed-view seats
for hockey.
</P>
<P>
   One option in the plan calls for 1,000 to 1,300 new seats to be
installed through the construction of the US West Pavilion on the
east side of the arena, a project that has been delayed because of
the NBA lockout.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Machen, the arena's president and general manager, said the
two projects could solve the seating problems for hockey, a major
reason the Coyotes are pursuing a new arena as part of the Los
Arcos redevelopment project in south Scottsdale.
</P>
<P>
   However, a Coyotes official said Wednesday the team remains
committed to putting an arena on the Los Arcos site.
</P>
<P>
   About 4,200 seats in the north end of America West Arena provide
fans a view of only one goal. Machen said he doesn't have a final
figure of how many seats would be fixed under the proposal, which
should be made public in the next two weeks. Obstructed-view seats
in upper balcony of the north end probably will not be improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing is definitely going to bring into play a tremendous
number of seats,'' he said. ``We're not going to bring 100 percent
of them in, but we can get their (the Coyotes') numbers way, way up
there with these two projects.''
</P>
<P>
   Machen declined to discuss the cost of the proposed renovation,
or how it would be financed. Sources close to the situation have
told ``The Republic'' that the cost will be around $10 million.
</P>
<P>
   But the limited-view seats are just one problem Coyotes
officials have with the arena. They maintain their lease at the
arena, which expires after the 2000-01 season, limits how much
money they can make through luxury boxes and advertising.
</P>
<P>
   That's as big a sticking point for the Coyotes as the seating
problem and probably a harder one to fix. Jerry Colangelo, Suns
president and chief executive officer whose organization operates
the building, said last week there isn't anything he can do about
the Coyotes' lease problems.
</P>
<P>
   He has said the Coyotes have a sweetheart deal at America West
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Arena revenue is essential to success in the NHL, which has
little revenue sharing, said Coyotes President Shawn Hunter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is wrong here,'' Hunter said. ``The facts are there are
revenue challenges on a couple of fronts. Those challenges get to
be very painful as we progress and the cost of doing business
rises.''
</P>
<P>
   Hunter declined comment on the renovation plans because he
didn't know specifics of the proposal, but he reiterated that the
Coyotes are focused on making the Los Arcos project work.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing we said we wouldn't do was pit two cities
against each other or buildings against each other,'' he said.
``That's why the organization chose to pursue Los Arcos; it
represented the potential for long-term success and, most
importantly, keeping the franchise in Arizona long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Coyotes, arena management and the city of
Phoenix, which owns the arena, began pursuing the option of
renovating the building.
</P>
<P>
   A Detroit architecture firm presented a $20 million renovation
plan that would have shut the arena down for at least two summers.
</P>
<P>
   Arena management rejected that proposal and began to work on one
of its own. The Coyotes, meanwhile, focused their efforts on a new
arena.
</P>
<P>
   Machen said architects, engineers and a seating company have
developed the latest plan.
</P>
<P>
   The new plan will involve some demolition work in the north end,
and Machen hopes the renovation will take only a summer to
complete.
</P>
<P>
   He would like to see construction begin in 2000, which would
give the arena's spring and summer tenants, the Rattlers of the
Arena League and the Mercury of the WNBA, time to adjust their
schedules.
</P>
<P>
   The goal, Machen said, is to keep those teams in the arena
because moving them to other facilities in the Valley would cause
problems with marketing and confusion among season ticket holders.
</P>
<P>
   Machen also plans to consult with construction experts to
determine if it's feasible to do the renovation over a summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
