<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-BROWN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TACKLE, TACKLE, WHO HAS TACKLE?  
 FREE AGENT BROWN SIGNS WITH CLEVELAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE Schoenfeld  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - By now, offensive tackle Lomas Brown's agents
have stopped negotiating with the Cardinals and realize that he is
a member of the Cleveland Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Or have they?
</P>
<P>
   Even after Brown announced on Wednesday he was leaving the
Cardinals to sign a three-year, $10.75 million deal with the
expansion Browns, his agent, Lamont Smith, still was talking to
Cardinals officials, according to team executives and sources close
to Brown.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Cardinals officials said that Brown's agent told them
several times Tuesday and Wednesday that Brown had reached
agreement with the Cardinals, who were offering a two-year, $6.5
million contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 12:40 p.m. (Tuesday), Lamont called me on his cell phone to
say we had a deal,'' said Rod Graves, Cardinals assistant to the
president who was the chief negotiator. ``He was consistent
yesterday and today that we had a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown's decision leaves the team with a huge hole at left
offensive tackle. Second-year pro Anthony Clement likely is the
favorite to get the job. But Bob Ferguson, team vice
president-player personnel, said the team also will address the
position with a ``high'' pick in the April draft. The Cardinals,
who no longer are interested in tackle Wayne Gandy, have two
first-round picks _ Nos. 8 and 21 overall.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said Smith acted independently of him and that the agent
knew he had chosen the Browns over the Cardinals as early as Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brown acknowledged that he was unaware what the
Cardinals' final offer was Wednesday because he had stopped talking
to Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Things got so bizarre, that while Brown was giving a news
conference at his Chandler home to announce he had picked
Cleveland, Cardinals officials were trying to reach him by phone.
He signed the deal on TV in front a friend and business adviser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamont Smith represented to us he had the authority to make a
deal,'' Graves said. `` He was adamant that he had the authority to
pull the trigger.''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said there was a ``big misunderstanding in the line of
communication,'' and that as a result, he is considering firing his
agents, Smith and Peter Schaffer, who were unavailable for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They might not be my agents much longer,'' Brown said.
``You're dealing with a person's integrity. When I tell someone I'm
going to a place, I keep my word. They were the ones who said I'm
not going (to Cleveland).''
</P>
<P>
   Brown said he never second-guessed his decision Monday night to
pick the Browns over the Cardinals, who increased their offer
$500,000 on Tuesday. The increase matched a Browns deal that was
worth $6.75 million the first two years. In fact, the Cardinals'
offer was worth $750,000 more than the Browns' deal next season.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said his decision didn't come down to money. ``I left
money on the table by signing with Cleveland,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The 14-year pro wanted to be closer to his three daughters, who
live in Detroit with Brown's wife, Delores. The couple are
separated.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the Cardinals blew it nearly two weeks ago when they
couldn't close the deal. He said a deal seemed imminent but that
the team went five days without negotiating, so he decided to visit
Cleveland, where the Browns enticed him by offering perks such as
being the first player introduced at their preseason opener. They
also tried to entice him by telling him they might hire his Detroit
parking firm for stadium parking in Cleveland and talked to him
about a job with the team when he career ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that's a joke,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   All along, the Cardinals insisted they wouldn't sign Brown, who
will be 36 next season, to a three-year deal. Brown said he
understood their reasoning, but that he was bothered by comments
from Cardinals Vice President Bill Bidwill Jr. to quarterback Jake
Plummer that he ``wouldn't mortgage his future for a 36-year-old
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidwill Jr. denies saying that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (Plummer) we had a lot of factors,'' Bidwill Jr. said.
``I think I said I didn't think he's going to be playing when he's
40 years old. It wasn't denigrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Ferguson said he knows losing Brown is an unpopular move, but
that free agency is only four weeks old and that there still are
other ways to build a team, including free agency and the draft.
The Cardinals' next target in free agency is re-signing linebacker
Jamir Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago at this time, people were saying, `Oh, man, what
are (they) doing?' '' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals then made the blockbuster trade with San Diego
that brought them two first-round picks, a second and two players,
and also acquired running back Adrian Murrell from the New York
Jets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Players who have been here the last year and a half know what
we're all about,'' Ferguson said. ``We're not the same team.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
