<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-HOMETOWN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
90210 SET YAWNS AT NEW BOOK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Daily News Staff Writer Beth Barrett contributed to this
report.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ To hear it from the kids at her alma mater,
Beverly Hills High School, and her fellow Brentwood residents, the
Monica Lewinsky saga is so (italics) passe (end italics).
</P>
<P>
   It's so tired.
</P>
<P>
   It's so ... 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be really interesting, but now it's really
annoying,'' Danny Karotin, a 14-year-old freshman at the school,
said Wednesday. ``We're kind of tired of it, actually.''
</P>
<P>
   For many, the prospect of buying Lewinsky's tell-all book,
``Monica's Story'' when it is released today, let alone watching
her televised interview Wednesday was just, well _ borrrring.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got really old,'' said 10th-grader Natalie Housepian, 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are disrespecting the president now,'' she added. ``I
kind of disrespect Monica just as much. She had no business doing
that with the president in the first place. It's kind of
degrading.''
</P>
<P>
   Most students said they weren't going to bother tuning in to the
interview. Housepian said she might, ``if I don't have too much
homework.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky's former attorney, William Ginsberg, said he's also
gotten on with his life, and suggests the rest of the country do
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a terrible way to spend our time and our money,''
the Los Angeles resident said. ``This is not what America is made
of, or what it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Her story is not that interesting. We all need to move on,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   That's exactly what folks want to do in Brentwood, the tony L.A.
neighborhood where Lewinsky's father and stepmother live, and which
was the scene of many a media stakeout during the height of the
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Dutton, who has owned his namesake bookstore there for 15
years, ordered only 30 copies of the former White House intern's
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not anticipating a flood of interest,'' he said.
``Ordinarily I would've had a waiting list. With other books of
this nature we've had a lot more interest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of these things that will have a very short shelf
life,'' Dutton said. ``I think she's a perfectly lovely young lady.
But I don't think she particularly has something to say to me.''
</P>
<P>
   At a cafe in front of Dutton's Brentwood Books, 16-year-old Gina
Merchant was flipping through a copy of Jane magazine and pondering
the affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's our business. It's been blown out of
proportion,'' she said. ``There's more important things to be
concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   ``But some people fall into that trap _ it's something cool to
talk about because it's sex,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever.''
</P>
<P>
   A 16-year-old Beverly Hills High sophomore named Monica (no, she
wouldn't give her last name, and yes, she's gotten plenty of
ribbing in the past year) questioned Lewinsky's motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care. Nobody should care,'' she said. ``She just
wanted to write a book.''
</P>
<P>
   Vagabond Books, on San Vicente Boulevard in Brentwood, can't be
bothered to carry the publication.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh! I forgot to order them,'' owner Craig Graham said in mock
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a literary book store,'' insisted his wife, Patti. When
asked about a copy of the Starr Report on the front counter, she
replied, ``Somebody donated that to our shop. You can have it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said Lewinsky stopped by the store at Christmastime, glanced
at art books and left without buying anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't wear a beret, so we didn't know who she was,'' she
joked. ``I feel sorry for her. Everybody was ragging on her.''
</P>
<P>
   But don't look for Lewinsky at a book signing there anytime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody around here cares,'' Craig Graham said. ``This area is
pretty sick of that stuff. People are fed up. They just wish it
would blow over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0109EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7194 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-WESTPHAL-A     03-04 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-WESTPHAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WESTPHAL'S WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   Coach stands by hands-off approach 
 (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ As a player, he could go right.
</P>
<P>
   Go left.
</P>
<P>
   Go his own way.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Westphal hasn't changed much. He's older. He limps on a
right leg that has begun to show the corrosive toll of 12 years in
backcourts for the Boston Celtics, Suns, Seattle SuperSonics and
New York Knicks. There's some gray in the hair. Lines circle his
eyes and run across his temples.
</P>
<P>
   Time has left some inevitable marks. Westphal, 48, can't beat
the years. But their passage is the only defense that has ever been
able to stop him long enough to leave an enduring label. The
ambidextrous player of the late 1970s and early 1980s is today's
many-sided coach with a range of philosophies that sometimes sound
contradictory and are always intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   For a while, his ideas worked in Phoenix. Today, he is working
to apply them in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Between the two stops, some pragmatic lessons about politics and
people marked his career just as surely as that limp. The Suns
fired him suddenly in 1996. On the day his firing was announced in
a stunned room at America West Arena, he wasn't there. But his
Phoenix jersey was.
</P>
<P>
   The old Westphal number, 44, hung in honor high above the seats
at America West Arena. There aren't many who have had their number
retired and been fired by the same franchise. It's a unique double
from a unique personality. Go right. Go left. Westphal has his own
way.
</P>
<P>
   He looked back on his coaching experience with the Suns the
other day while sitting in an office above the SuperSonics practice
court. He spoke mostly in generalities.
</P>
<P>
   There always has been an air of mystery about the firing despite
a .685 winning percentage and his subsequent absence from the
league for more than two years. A palace revolt? A locker room
``coup d'eta''t? An exile imposed by a campaign of whispered
condemnation from former Suns' colleagues?
</P>
<P>
   Westphal won't point fingers. Disappointed? Without a doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it ill will,'' said Westphal, who faces the
Suns for the first time since his firing tonight at Seattle's Key
Arena. ``But there was certainly some disappointment attached with
personal relationships that I had. That's probably inevitable in
this business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of great memories. Most of my career was in
Phoenix. Most of it was positive. There are the fans, people and
players in the organizations and the city in general. I had great
years there.''
</P>
<P>
   If there's rancor, he doesn't express it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no advantage in that,'' said Westphal, a friend and
fan of conservative talk-show host Rush Limbaugh who used to
register at hotels under names from songs written by counterculture
icon Bob Dylan. ``I understand the questions. People would love to
have all the dirty laundry out there. Heck, I like to read that
stuff, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't think it's good for anybody personally. And I
don't think it's good for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   For Westphal, it's always the game, first and foremost. He
thought about it while traveling up and down Route 66 with musician
John Stewart about a year ago. Stewart was searching for a
different America, which is a place that has always included one
kind of basketball or another for about a century.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal has played it on every level. More significant, he's
coached it on every level. He created and coached the program at
the Valley's Southwestern Baptist Bible College in 1985. He coached
Grand Canyon College to an NAIA title in 1988. There was time on
the Suns bench as an assistant to Cotton Fitzsimmons. Then, there
are the three-plus season as the Suns coach, before he was fired.
But the firing didn't change his enthusiasm for what happens
between the baselines. He worked as a volunteer assistant for
Chaparral High School, where his son Michael played.
</P>
<P>
   Big-time is a matter of perception and bright lights, he said.
The game itself is what endures.
</P>
<P>
   The problems, the separation point between him and the Suns,
came with his unyielding adherence to a belief in how the game
should be played. Westphal believes it belongs to the players. They
dictate style and strategy. It's not imposed from above by a coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys go out of their way to prove how tough they are,''
Westphal said about perceptions that he was too lax. ``I can't do
that. For instance, there was always the perception that I didn't
coach enough defense. It's always been my belief that, if you win,
you played enough defense. I've always believed that the game is
played on both ends of the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``But people don't want to hear that. They want you to go in
with a whip and chair and make a statement to these overpaid
athletes. I think there's a feeling out there that's the only kind
of real coaching there is. You know, beat them into shape.''
</P>
<P>
   As a Suns guard, it was Westphal's player-first philosophy that
eventually forced the Suns to trade him in 1981 to Seattle for
Dennis Johnson. Westphal wasn't comfortable with the strict,
carefully orchestrated style of then-Coach John MacLeod.
</P>
<P>
   As the Suns coach, it probably led to Westphal's firing. The
charismatic Charles Barkley, independent and profane, was the
breaking point just a couple years after he became the first Suns
player to ever be elected the NBA's Most Valuable Player. From top
to bottom, Suns management began to grumble about his escapades and
a Barkley-dominated offense that had grown stale.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably true, although I didn't think so at the
time,'' Westphal said. ``I think there were different opinions on
Charles. My feeling was that Charles was always who we expected him
to be. We knew there were going to be some negatives. We knew there
were going to be some positives. He came as advertised. My feeling
was, and is today: Why hold it against him for being who he is?
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I can look Charles in the eye and he knows that I never
changed on him. I'm not sure everybody else can say that.''
</P>
<P>
   A player in the Barkley-ruled dressing room of that time was
Danny Ainge, now the Suns coach. He shared some of his teammates'
opinions that Barkley had been allowed to run amok.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a player, I was at times critical of the way he handled
Charles, although I was never as critical as say A.C. Green,'' said
Ainge, who believes the Suns of 1993-94 and 1994-95 were the NBA's
best despite their playoff elimination by Houston in each season.
``There were times when I thought he could be more firm. But, now
as a coach, I can see that Paul got more out of Charles than
anybody ever has.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing that Paul Westphal did prevented us from winning a
championship ring. It was fate, or injuries, or whatever. My three
years under Paul was the most fun I've ever had playing basketball.
I liked every part of it. And I respect him a great deal. He's a
man of integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing tension in the Suns locker room was said to be factor in
Westphal's firing. There was talk of a team spinning out of
control, whispers of a plot led by Kevin Johnson and Green.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal says there were problems with KJ. But he also said the
two spoke with each other last summer for the first time since he
was fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship is OK,'' he said. ``It is now.''
</P>
<P>
   He also talked about prevalent speculation of a rift between
Barkley and KJ.
</P>
<P>
   ``There probably was,'' he said. ``It's hard to get to the
bottom of those kind of things. To what extent it affected the play
of the team, to what extent it affected my firing, I can't say.
It's hard to say I would have done anything different, although I
question it all the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is that everybody has to look in the mirror. I know
I can. I don't know who else can. I'm not going to run around
trying to figure out who's lying and who's telling the truth. I
take people at face value. I've heard a lot of things. I don't know
who to believe.''
</P>
<P>
   But he does know how to move on. In his own way. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
