<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-CASSTEVENS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EASY, UNIT, DON'T HURT A FUTURE LEADER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID CASSTEVENS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - University of Arizona baseball Coach Jerry Stitt
gathered his team in the visitors clubhouse at Tucson Electric
Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big game today, men,'' the skipper said. He checked his lineup
card. ``Smith, you're leading off.''
</P>
<P>
   Heads turned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smith? Where's SMITH?! Anybody seen Smith?''
</P>
<P>
   Smith was on the team bus, hiding, palms pressed together in an
attitude of prayer.
</P>
<P>
   OK, that didn't happen. Arizona doesn't have a player named
Smith. The Wildcats leadoff hitter is a fresh-faced youth named
Andy Juday, and even though Andy was apprehensive about facing
Randy Johnson _ who in his right mind wouldn't be? _ there was no
way the kid was going to chicken out and miss this experience.
</P>
<P>
   Three hours before the Big Unit ambled to the mound in his
pinstriped pants, looking even taller than his measured height of 6
feet 10, Andy sat in his Psychology of Sports class on the UA
campus.
</P>
<P>
   His mind was elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   He was thinking. Imagining.
</P>
<P>
   Daydreaming as he has for a week about the moment when his name
would be announced over the stadium speakers and he would take a
deep breath to steel himself and head toward the plate, all eyes on
him, bat in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Excited? Oh, yeah,'' Juday said before the game. He was
beaming.
</P>
<P>
   The 21-year-old second baseman didn't feel like a condemned man,
but rather like a realist whom fate had blessed with a rare and
magical opportunity. As he put it, ``I'll never face Randy Johnson
again the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   What did he expect?
</P>
<P>
   ``I dunno.'' Juday's shrug said he was prepared to accept
whatever happened. ``He may strike me out on three pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson wasn't thinking strikeouts as he pawed the mound and
turned his baleful gaze toward the plate, the ball hidden in his
black glove. The $50 million pitcher for the Diamondbacks wanted to
concentrate on his location, his rhythm, his timing. The velocity
of his whistling fastball gradually will increase during spring
training. Wednesday, he worked only two innings, delivering 31
pitches.
</P>
<P>
   The morning of the exhibition game, UA right fielder Shelley
Duncan received a surprise telephone call from Mark McGwire. The
Wildcats cleanup hitter is the son of Dave Duncan, St. Louis
Cardinals pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire wished Duncan good luck and offered a scouting report.
``He said Randy throws 100 mph and doesn't know where it's going,''
Duncan said, and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   Fear is Johnson's ally, but the big left-hander performed his
art with care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get worried (about hitting a batter) if the guy up there is
making millions, let alone if you're a kid trying to get a college
education,'' Johnson said. The opening day pitcher for the
Diamondbacks thought about our leaders of tomorrow. ``The guy might
become the president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure whether Johnson thinks his accidentally beaning a
future U.S. president could have repercussions. Who knows? Someday,
President Juday or Duncan might order the IRS to audit him.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson fared better than he did the last time he pitched
against the Wildcats. In 1985, Arizona tagged him for six runs and
13 hits. Johnson played for Southern Cal.
</P>
<P>
   The playful notion that this rematch, after 14 years, would
serve as a measure of revenge amused him.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks tried to assist the collegians. Tommy Jones,
director of minor league operations, delivered a box of wooden bats
to the Wildcats with the promise that the half-dozen new sticks had
``nothing but hits in 'em.'' But the lumber malfunctioned.
</P>
<P>
   His heart beating with excitement, Juday willed himself to stay
calm. With his parents watching _ and the crowd calling out
``C'mon, Andy!'' _ he struck out _ on five pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan fanned, too. So did two other teammates, unable to resist
offerings that Johnson indicated were ``up here'' _ shoulder high.
Two others grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Diamondbacks catcher Damian Miller studied the UA hitters as
they came and went.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking into their eyes, they didn't seem scared,'' Miller
said. ``Maybe awe is a better way to describe it.''
</P>
<P>
   Awe is a good word. Imagine stepping into the batter's box and
locking eyes with the most intimidating pitcher in baseball. Even
from a distance of 60 feet, 6 inches, Randy Johnson atop a mound
appears bigger than life.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looked like the Eiffel Tower,'' marveled Keoni DeRenne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 5-7.'' &QL; 
David Casstevens can be reached at 602-444-8635 or at
david.casstevens(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
