<HEADLINE>
START OF GAMES STIRS NEW PASSION  
 SEVERAL STORY LINES WORTH WATCHING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Now ``this'' is Fantasy Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Affordable games. Approachable players. And the perfect
opportunity to see superstars in the making.
</P>
<P>
   Six teams begin Cactus League competition today. The
Diamondbacks meet Colorado at Tucson's Hi Corbett Field, Oakland
visits Milwaukee at Maryvale Baseball Park, and Seattle and San
Diego square off at Peoria Stadium. The rest of the league starts
play Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see certain things in the bullpen during workouts,''
Brewers pitching coach Bill Campbell said. ``But there's nothing
like getting under the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Last spring's fans had the chance to see the talents unfold of
baseball's top rookies: Chicago Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood and Oakland
Athletics outfielder Ben Grieve. They got a firsthand look at the
charisma and skill of Cubs slugger Sammy Sosa, who went on to hit
66 home runs and help bring back fans to the game.
</P>
<P>
   They got a peek at the San Diego Padres, who would win a
franchise-record 98 games and advance to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``My son got Tony Gwynn's autograph here (last year),'' said Ken
Ferrell of Mission Viejo, Calif., who was watching batting practice
at Peoria Stadium on Wednesday. ``It would have been hard to do
that during the season. It meant a lot because of the season they
had.''
</P>
<P>
   What does the 1999 Cactus League season have in store? Here are
some story lines to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   The development of Oakland third baseman Eric Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Many have tagged him as the front-runner for American League
Rookie of the Year. The A's would love to have back-to-back
winners.
</P>
<P>
   The sheer talent of Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   The first baseman, who joined the California Angels in the
off-season, is an ironman. He played in all but one game last
season despite a variety of ailments. Imagine what he can do when
he's healthy.
</P>
<P>
   The ability of Jose Mesa.
</P>
<P>
   For the Seattle Mariners to succeed, they need Mesa to become
the premier closer he was during his stay with Cleveland. Watching
the Mariners during late innings in recent years demanded heart
medication. Mesa should give some clues this spring to what he has.
</P>
<P>
   The future of the Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   The popular thinking is that Chicago didn't do enough in the
off-season to return to the postseason. The Cubs believe they can
return with what got them there in the first place, and that the
team just needs tweaking.
</P>
<P>
   The performance of Frank Thomas with almost no protection in the
lineup.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision by the White Sox to go young and cheap (Albert
Belle and Robin Ventura are history), will Thomas be able to
rebound from a mediocre year? The odds don't look good.
</P>
<P>
   The fortunes of the Colorado Rockies with Jim Leyland as
manager.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are counting on Leyland to inspire a veteran team that many
believe underachieved the past few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Even though right-hander Darryl Kile's 13-17 record was a bit
misleading, the Rockies will need more from him to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Is there another San Diego among the 10 teams?
</P>
<P>
   We're talking about the Padres from 1998, who went on to a
successful postseason. This season's team isn't nearly as deep, and
few are predicting that San Diego will win the West.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, most of the teams predicted to win their divisions this
season come from the Grapefruit League. Only Anaheim seems to be
getting some respect.
</P>
<P>
   The nine remaining Cactus League teams call that fantasy, not
reality. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
