<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARIZONA-USC-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UA HOPING TO MAKE LAST IMPRESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE SHAPPELL  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ They've got the atlas out and are examining it closely.
</P>
<P>
   Where will the Arizona Wildcats be sent? Boston or Charlotte,
N.C., in the East Regional? Orlando or Indianapolis in the South?
Milwaukee or New Orleans in the Midwest?
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats are concerned about where they are going in more
ways than one after two convincing losses in the Bay area last
week.
</P>
<P>
   They tumbled from seventh to 13th in this week's standings.
</P>
<P>
   Seventh in the country? They'll likely be no better than fourth
or fifth in a region in the NCAA Tournament when pairings are
announced Sunday. They have an Ratings Percentage Index _ 18th _
consistent with a No. 5 seed. They're convinced they'll be shipped
out of the West, where Pac-10 champ Stanford is expected to be
assigned.
</P>
<P>
   The good news for the Wildcats (20-6, 11-5 Pac-10) is that
they're assured of their 15th straight NCAA Tournament berth.
</P>
<P>
   The bad news is that if they continue to defend as they did at
California and Stanford, their tournament stay will be a short one.
</P>
<P>
   The Wildcats wrap up the regular season at home at 6:30 tonight
against Southern California (14-11, 6-10) and at 1:30 p.m. Saturday
against No. 12 UCLA (21-7, 11-5). Those are opportunities to
correct deficiencies exposed last week and perhaps improve their
tournament seeding.
</P>
<P>
   Neither game, however, is a gimme. The Trojans won at Stanford
and played tight games at California and UCLA. USC was the only
Pac-10 team to beat the Wildcats last season. USC also controlled
most of the game against Arizona in Los Angeles on Jan. 4 before
the Wildcats pulled it out, 87-76.
</P>
<P>
   ``They probably feel that's one we stole from them,'' UA Coach
Lute Olson said.
</P>
<P>
   And the Bruins need no introduction. They're the only Pac-10
team with a winning record over Arizona, including an 82-75 romp in
this year's conference opener that was much worse than the score
indicates. UCLA led by more than 20 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   So, were the Wildcats seriously overrated, and what is their
problem?
</P>
<P>
   More than likely, their ranking was a product of their
reputation. Arizona has been in the Top 10 in 30 of the past 34
polling periods, and in the Top 25 for 197 straight.
</P>
<P>
   Relying on five freshmen, three of them starters, Arizona showed
its age last week. While the youngsters now have had an entire
season to learn what college basketball is about, they still don't
know everything, particularly defensive effort, according to Olson.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had been the only opponent to shoot at least 50 percent
against Arizona until Cal and Stanford did it last week.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive lapses on the wings, where freshmen Richard Jefferson
and Ruben Douglas play, and at power forward, where freshman
Michael Wright saw only six minutes because of foul trouble at
Stanford, were the greatest contributing factors.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona had lost four games by a combined 15 points before last
week. It then lost by 13 and 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do something about what happened,'' center A.J.
Bramlett said. ``We had so many mental breakdowns defensively.
Stanford had guys open because of non-rotations by us, or guys not
fighting through screens.
</P>
<P>
   `We can't have those kinds of mistakes now. The good thing is
they're all fixable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
