<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-04 0867
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGES WEARING HARD HAT TO WORK AT WASHINGTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ In January, just days after Rick Neuheisel was nailed
for those against-the-NCAA-rules Sunday visits to Husky football
recruits, the new coach joined athletic director Barbara Hedges at
a Husky basketball game at Hec Ed Pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel was easy enough to spot. Red-cheeked, blond-haired,
Neuheisel did not have a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he sat on the step, right on the floor next to Hedges.
</P>
<P>
   Not for one moment did any good Husky fan at Hec Ed that night
miss the obvious comparison. I mean, did anyone ever see ex-Husky
coach Jim Lambright ever sit so obediently at Hedges' feet?
</P>
<P>
   Neuheisel, whose embarrassing rules violations in his first
weeks on the job made him the talk of Montlake _ and Colorado,
where he has been all but vilified _ looked exactly like a puppy in
trouble with the master.
</P>
<P>
   The funny thing is, no matter how much embarrassment Neuheisel's
inaugural faux pas brought to the University of Washington, the
master said she did not spend a minute quietly cursing her newest
and very expensive hire.
</P>
<P>
   For Hedges, there are no such moments of soul-shaking doubt,
which might come as a surprise to the core group of football
diehards convinced Hedges has not demonstrated enough commitment to
that most important cornerstone program.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling was that I was very sorry that it happened,''
Hedges said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It set us back a little. He has to prove himself a little
more. Not to me, because I know he's a fine coach, but to the
public.''
</P>
<P>
   No one is doubting that the bold about-face Hedges performed in
firing Lambright and luring golden boy Neuheisel to Montlake will
be a grand piece of her legacy _ providing Neuheisel succeeds the
way Hedges vows he will.
</P>
<P>
   Hedges knows this all too well because, even as she can be found
handing out boxed lunches to members of the sporting media in the
way she might have once fed peanut butter sandwiches to her two
sons, this is one shrewd businesswoman.
</P>
<P>
   ``The success of football will define me to an extent. It is
such a very large part of the program, that's the nature of
football,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But about that bigger picture Hedges has her vision trained on _
like the $80 million building fund that is renovating or adding
five major sports facilities at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Six years after she first began deliberating ways to upgrade
Washington's desperate facilities, the renovation of Hec Ed is set
to begin. After Saturday's Pac-10 finale between the Husky men and
Washington State, Hec Ed will undergo a $61 million upgrade, making
it the centerpiece of Hedges' Campaign for the Student Athlete
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Washington also is getting a new indoor practice facility and
crew house in addition to its new soccer, baseball and softball
fields.
</P>
<P>
   And, while some Husky football diehards might have wanted Husky
Stadium and the football program to get top billing for upgrades,
Hedges' commitment to the school's 22 other intercollegiate sports
is proved in this equitable building campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Already, under Hedges, Washington has gone from No. 47 among all
Division I schools to No. 8 last year for overall sports
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   By 2000, Washington will be the envy of Pac-10 counterparts from
Eugene to Tucson _ which is exactly the point of all this
fundraising and barn raising.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the key people around Hedges in this facilities campaign
say there are certain ingredients Hedges has brought to the job.
Vision is one. So is a background in fundraising.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she can choose people very well who can work from
disparate points of view and build a consensus,'' said Seafirst
executive Tom Powers, head of the capital campaign fundraising
group. ``She is very persistent.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think she deserves more credit ... although I don't know if
she'd want it,'' University booster Ron Crockett said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Crockett, like Powers, has watched Hedges since her arrival at
Washington in 1991, and both men say Hedges' competitiveness and
strength have served her well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, there were people talking about how could she head
up the athletic department when she never coached a linebacker,''
Powers said, rolling his eyes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in becoming only the second woman to head up a Division
I athletic department when she came on board, Hedges said she has
grown used to that sort of mindset _ not that it bothers her.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she never coached a linebacker, ``but I have known a lot
of linebackers,'' Hedges said in a comedic comeback she has no
doubt used in lectures and speeches.
</P>
<P>
   She also has known football coaches _ ones that suit her and
Washington, ones that don't. In January, Hedges made a blockbuster
move with that very football program people have suggested she
might mess up.
</P>
<P>
   While Neuheisel will no doubt be the most high-profile hire
Hedges ever makes, the hire is still just a part of the bigger
picture _ a picture that appears to be putting Hedges well on her
way toward a bold legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
