<SLUG> BC-BKC-ASU-UCLA-ADV-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE SETTLING ON SOLID GROUND  
 GUARD HAS OVER COME SHAKY START AT ASU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Asked whether he considers this a breakthrough
year for him, Eddie House thought for a moment.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The question was meant to elicit an answer on his emergence as
a dynamic source of offense for Arizona State, as one of the
quickest guards in the Pac-10, if not the nation, as a player who
has a lot of upside, as NBA folks like to say.
</P>
<P>
   As he has all season, House chose a different direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think so,'' he said. ``It's kind of put my name out there in
a positive manner. Before, if my name was in the paper, it would be
over something that wasn't too positive, some things I'm not too
proud of. This year was kind of a way of getting back on the right
track.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he made the Pac-10 all-freshman team and was generally
productive his first two years, House had jumped the tracks more
than once. His mouth contributed to the outrageous total of 16
technical fouls by players last year. He scuffled with a teammate,
Bobby Lazor, during a game, and with an opponent, Arizona's A.J.
Bramlett, in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1997, House was arrested for allegedly helping
then-teammate Reggie Hester steal a portable CD player from a dorm
room. Although House later was cleared, the incident was the final
straw preceding the forced resignation of Coach Bill Frieder.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, House, described by all who know him as a smart
kid, was admittedly lax in the classroom. And underscoring all of
this was an attitude characterized mainly by unflattering
adjectives _ sullen, aloof, arrogant. One person involved with the
program called House ``a good kid trying to act bad.''
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything first-year Coach Rob Evans and his staff
can't stand, it's a bad actor. Which is why House's introductory
meeting with assistant coach Tony Benford began with Benford saying
something like, ``So, Eddie, how come everyone thinks you're an
(expletive)?''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, nice meeting you, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard he had some problems the previous year, and everybody
we talked to said he had an attitude problem,'' Benford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that as a staff, we were willing to give him the
benefit of the doubt. But if he didn't want to accept the rules the
coaches have in place, we'd be willing to call any school in the
country if he wanted to transfer.''
</P>
<P>
   Replied House, ``This is where I signed, and this is where I
want to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the meeting still jostled House. Soon, much of his family
was descending on Tempe from northern California to find out what
the heck was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``His relatives took offense,'' Evans said. ``And that's OK.
They have a right to defend Eddie and voice their opinions.''
</P>
<P>
   House owns up to some of the misdeeds, but said his personality
was misread. He said mistrust of ``some people'' was reflected in
his demeanor.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were some things I shouldn't have done, but as far as
the attitude and the type of person I am and the image, it was a
big misunderstanding,'' he said. ``Once people formed those views,
it was like a snowball effect.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the message that Evans and the coaches were
sending was received loud and clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to melt that snowball,'' said House, who is the
favorite player of Benford's young son, Tony Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been a joy for me to coach,'' Evans said. ``I haven't had
to challenge him off the floor. He calls me when he's going to be a
little bit late, or if there's something I need to know. He takes
care of his business. On the floor, if he's not working as hard as
I think he should be working and I tell him, I guarantee you he
goes to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Only once has House strayed, early on, and it proved to be a
defining moment. He skipped a summer school class and was sentenced
to Evans' infamous ``5 at 5,'' which is five miles at 5 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were saying, `He won't show up, he won't show up,' ''
Benford said. ``And Eddie was there at 4:30 in the morning, and he
ran as hard as anybody. From that day forward we said, `This kid
wants to be here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Born in Berkeley, Calif., near the University of California
campus, House grew up in Union City. He was a big Cal fan but was
shunned by then-head coach Todd Bozeman. That hurt, he said, and
ever since, ``I take it personally every time I play them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even ASU was a reluctant suitor until Frieder showed up for a
game and House scored 45 points. He started 22 games as a freshman
and averaged 12.6 points, playing both guard positions. He played
mostly off-guard last season under Don Newman and again scored in
double-figures, even though he was the fourth scoring option behind
Jeremy Veal, Mike Batiste and Lazor.
</P>
<P>
   This season, with Veal gone and Evans recognizing a scalding
offensive player when he sees one, the 6-foot-1 House has
flourished. Despite starting the season with a broken jaw wired
shut, he is second in the Pac-10 in scoring (19.5) going into
tonight's game against UCLA. He also averages more than three
assists and nearly five rebounds a game, and is third in the Pac-10
in steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can beat you off the dribble, he can beat you off the
catch,'' said Evans, who hopes to land House a tryout for a U.S.
amateur team this summer.
</P>
<P>
   House has worked hard on his all-around game, stepping up his
defense and his rebounding. The pros question his size, not his
skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love the way, off the dribble, he can get his defender
off-balance and get him to back up,'' said Dick Van Arsdale, the
Suns vice-president of player personnel. ``He's as good at that as
anyone I've seen in college ball. . . .The bottom line is, I think
he's a very good player.''
</P>
<P>
   And he can only get better next season when he's the veteran of
a young but potentially very talented team. With this season not
yet over, House sometimes has to harness his enthusiasm about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be a joy to watch,'' he said, choosing a word
rarely heard from him before. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
