<HEADLINE>
18-YEAR-OLD AUSSIE UPSETS 2ND SEED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. - Lleyton Hewitt turned 18 a week ago
Wednesday, and it already appears he may become the next Australian
superstar.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, he proved once again how good he is, beating second
seed Patrick Rafter in straight sets to advance to the
quarterfinals of the Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic at the
Canadian Pacific Scottsdale Princess resort.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, the No. 5 player in the world, played tough in the first
set, losing, 7-6, on a 7-5 in a tiebreaker. In the second set,
however, Hewitt cruised to a 6-1 win.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Andre Agassi, the third seed, struggled to a
three-set victory in his first-round match, saying he was playing
not to lose rather than to win.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night was a different story when he buried Mariano
Zabaleta of Argentina, 6-2, 6-0, in a match that lasted only 50
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt won his first ATP Tour title when he was 16 years, 10
months old in Adelaide, Australia, his hometown. He was ranked
550th at the time. Along the way, he beat both Agassi and Jason
Stoltenberg, who met in last year's Franklin Templeton final. He
currently is ranked 91st.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous meeting with Rafter on Jan. 12 in Sydney, Hewitt
also won in straight sets, 7-6 (7-1), 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   After Wednesday's victory, Hewitt was jubilant.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels fantastic to beat him again,'' he said. ``It proved
it wasn't a fluke the first time. And it was great to beat him in
straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It also feels good to have won away from Australia. This is my
first big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt is 9-3 this year and has been to the quarterfinals in
three of four tournaments. He won only 10 matches last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm starting to get a little confidence,'' he said. ``My
ranking hasn't been good enough to get into many big tournaments.
This is much better than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know more about the ATP, how to handle myself. You have
be tough against the big guys. You have to play your game.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt will play his quarterfinal match Friday against Jerome
Golmard of France.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter was complimentary after his loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Hewitt) plays a good game and doesn't make too many
mistakes,'' he said. ``I needed to take more chances, and I
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Rafter said a lack of work has hurt his game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't played many matches,'' Rafter said. ``This year I
won't be playing as many tournaments as last year. I want to enjoy
myself, and if I work hard, it will come.''
</P>
<P>
   If history is an indication, Agassi is in good shape to win this
tournament. When he has advanced beyond the second round, he has
won the title all three times _ 1993, '94 and '98.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi has lost the fewest games in this tournament since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was better tonight,'' he said. ``Different players play
different ways. Yesterday (Tuesday) it was a lefty. It was harder
to size up his shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day is a new one. I was really hitting the ball. I'm
satisfied with everything I did tonight. Well, I can serve
better.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi will play Cedric Pioline of France in Friday's
quarterfinals. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
