<HEADLINE>
EX-NAU STAR TEAMS UP FOR WIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Defending doubles champions  &UR; Cyril Suk and  &UR; Michael Tebbutt, who
are unseeded this year in the Franklin Templeton Tennis Classic,
won their first-round match Wednesday with a 2-6, 6-4, 6-2 victory
over  &UR; Pablo Albano and  &UR; Daniel
 &UR; Orsanic.
</P>
<P>
   Tebbutt, 28 and an Australian, was an All-America tennis player
at Northern Arizona University in 1992-93 before he turned pro. He
has won a total of almost $1 million in his pro career. &QL; 
French advance &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sixth-seeded  &UR; Cedric Pioline and  &UR; Jerome Golmard, both of
France, were the first to advance to the singles quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   Pioline, playing in Scottsdale for the first time, easily beat
 &UR; Andrew Ilie, 6-1, 6-2, and Golmard, who was trailing 3-5 in the
first set, advanced when qualifier  &UR; Nicolas Lapentti of Ecuador
retired with an ankle sprain. &QL; 
Rafter sinking &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Patrick Rafter's fortunes seem to be sinking in competition
with fellow Australians.
</P>
<P>
   Rafter, ranked fifth in the world and the second seed in this
tournament, won seven straight matches against his countrymen from
the beginning of 1997 through May of that year.
</P>
<P>
   But from June '97 through Wednesday's matches, when he was
eliminated by Australian  &UR; Lleyton Hewitt, he is 4-6. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
