<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOISO'S FEET NO LONGER ARCH ENEMY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All the advice, all medical technology and
advanced treatments available at UCLA, and what freshman forward
Jerome Moiso really needed was a dabble of over-the-counter
ointment to help his tender feet.
</P>
<P>
   Before Saturday's game against Washington, a friend introduced
Moiso to the magic of heat-generating sports cream. It immediately
eased the pain from tendinitis in his arches. Moiso felt good for
the first time in weeks and played like it _ 11 points and six
rebounds in 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ointment warmed my feet, so I didn't feel any pain,''
Moiso said. ``Saturday was the first time I tried it, and it worked
pretty well. It was almost like I felt a month ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Moiso's confidence is as tender as his feet. The tendinitis
flared in early February and disrupted his rhythm. That caused him
to miss shots, which hurt his confidence, and the spiral continued.
He was 1 of 12 at Stanford before missing two games (Cal, USC). He
played a few minutes against Syracuse and Washington State, then he
met the ointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``My friend said I'd feel no pain,'' Moiso said. ``Now, I use it
for every practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The more he practices, the better he plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``His timing and rhythm are back,'' coach Steve Lavin said.
``He's in the offensive flow, and with that he's getting confident
and aggressive. But (without injured center Dan Gadzuric), we can't
pin it all on his shoulders. We have to do it collectively.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior commitment: Moiso, a native of Guadeloupe who was educated
in France, said he probably won't play for the French national team
in the European championships this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``They start practice in mid-May, and I have school until
mid-June,'' he said. ``I'd like to play, but the team will have
been practicing hard and to come in late would not be right.''
</P>
<P>
   Firepower: Arizona State has the best trio of scorers in the
Pac-10, with guard Eddie House and forwards Mike Batiste and Bobby
Lazor combining for 54 points per game. Lazor and House probably
will make the all-conference team (to be announced this weekend).
</P>
<P>
   ``They have three players who are all capable of getting 30,''
Lavin said. ``If they have one of those nights, it'll be tough on
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Tiny does it: Gadzuric grabbed 14 rebounds in 18 minutes in the
first Arizona State game, but the Bruins were most effective
without him on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   In Batiste and Lazor, the Sun Devils have two 6-8 forwards but
no center, and they pose a difficult matchup for opposing big men.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the first game, our smaller lineup (was more effective),''
Lavin said. ``It was similar to Oregon and the Taiwan national
team. All year, we've had a difficult time with small teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
