<SLUG> BC-BKC-PITT-NAU-HOWLAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAU'S HOW LAND ACCEPTS POSI TION WITH PITTS BURGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Northern Arizona men's basketball Coach Ben Howland
has accepted the head coaching position at the University of
Pittsburgh, sources close to both schools confirmed late Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Howland would not comment Wednesday night. He was traveling to
Ogden, Utah, today with his team for the Big Sky Conference
Tournament. He interviewed with Pittsburgh earlier this week and
was the only candidate for the job.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers likely won't introduce Howland as their next coach
until at least Monday. Sources in Pittsburgh said they wanted to
wait until NAU's season was over to give Howland a chance to get
the Lumberjacks in the NCAA Tournament for the second consecutive
year. The winner of this weekend's Big Sky Conference Tournament
earns an automatic bid to the NCAAs.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt lost to Rutgers, 64-51, in the first round of the Big East
Tournament on Wednesday night in Coach Ralph Willard's last game.
Willard went 63-82 in five seasons at Pitt. This season Pitt was
14-16 overall and 5-13 in the Big East for an 11th-place finish. He
had one winning season in his five there.
</P>
<P>
   Howland, 40, is going to a job that pays him nearly four times
the the $110,000 package he earns at NAU. His name first surfaced
at Pitt a week ago when Panthers Athletic Director Steve Pederson
went to Flagstaff to interview him. Howland was recommended by
several high-profile coaches, including Utah's Rick Majerus, a
close friend of Howland. Last Sunday, Howland then flew to
Pittsburgh to meet with school officials and tour the campus. But
he wasn't offered the job until Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   NAU Athletic Director Steve Holton said there was nothing to
announce but acknowledged that the university is in the preliminary
stages of a search for a new coach.
</P>
<P>
   Expected to head that list is former NAU and current Hawaii
assistant Jamie Dixon, who has already inquired about the job. But
Holton said it's too early to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not far enough along to narrow the list down to four or
five guys yet, but he is definitely somebody we're considering,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Holton said Howland's success should help in the search for a
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are going to see this program has the ability
to be successful and compete not only in the Big Sky, but also at
the national level.'' he said. ``Ben has brought in a talented
group of young players, and a new coach could step right in and not
have to rebuild.''
</P>
<P>
   Howland took over a perennial Big Sky cellar dweller and has led
NAU to a 75-57 record in five seasons. He led the Lumberjacks to
regular-season conference titles in 1997 and 1998 and the NCAA
Tournament in '98. This year's Lumberjacks are 20-7 and finished
second in the Big Sky. They will play at 7 p.m. Friday against a
team to be determined tonight. &QL; 
Correspondent Rory Faust contributed to this report. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0121EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
