<SLUG> BC-BKC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP USC RECRUIT HAS SURGERY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   USC's top basketball recruit, Nate Hair of Capistrano Valley
High, underwent arthroscopic knee surgery Wednesday in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The surgery was performed at USC University Hospital by Dr.
Thomas Vangsness. Hair damaged the meniscus in his knee during
Capistrano Valley's playoff opener against Yucaipa two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   USC officials did not know how long Hair would be sidelined, but
the shooting guard's injury is not considered serious.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a career-threatening surgery,'' Capistrano Valley
coach Brian Mulligan said. ``It's a meniscus problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to the meniscus usually require four to eight weeks of
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine honored: Sophomore center Brian Scalabrine was named
the Pacific-10 Conference's Newcomer of the Year on Wednesday.
Scalabrine leads USC in points (14.9), rebounds (6.5) and
field-goal percentage (53 percent). He is also second in assists
(2.4) and third in blocks (0.8).
</P>
<P>
   ``Brian came in and outplayed every big guy we had,'' USC coach
Henry Bibby said. ``If you looked at who graded highest at every
practice since October, the two best players have been Brian and
Jeff Trepagnier.''
</P>
<P>
   Also named to the team were guards Josh Steinthal of Oregon
State, Alex Scales and Darius Wright of Oregon and Jan-Michael
Thomas of Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   Scalabrine is the second USC player to win the award in the last
three seasons. Rodrick Rhodes won in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   As for Scalabrine, he is expected to play tonight against
Arizona after recovering from food poisoning.
</P>
<P>
   In defense of the defense: Although some USC players said the
Trojans are just now fully grasping all aspects of the team's
defensive schemes, Bibby said he doesn't believe the defensive
plays have been too complex this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense is not complicated,'' Bibby said. ``There's just
too many new faces. It's a matter of buying into and accepting what
you want them to do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the field? USC may be unsure of its chances of making the
National Invitation Tournament, but one mock field already includes
the Trojans. Of course, that's before this week's games. USC would
greatly improve its chances of making the tournament with a win
against Arizona in the McKale Center, where the Wildcats are 12-0
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get a win there would be great,'' Bibby said. ``What are
the odds of us going in there and winning? If you're a gambler, it
doesn't look good. But how many people thought we would win at
Stanford?''
</P>
</TEXT>
