<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROCKIES-LEYLAND-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYLAND PHILOSOPHY TRANSCENDS TIME  
 `I WANT TO BEAT THE OTHER TEAM' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. _ The term ``old school'' is tossed around often
these days. It's used to describe just about anyone who gets dirty
while doing his job.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's not warranted. In Jim Leyland's case, it's the
best possible description for someone who could have managed in any
era. Step into the office of the Colorado Rockies' new skipper and
it's like walking back 30 or 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   He charges through his cigarette, not caring that each one he
pulls out of the soft pack is crumpled and bent. Next to his
ashtray, a clubhouse attendant makes sure he has a fresh cup of
decaffeinated coffee.
</P>
<P>
   On this particular morning, he downs three cups in a 20-minute
period before his wife calls and he answers with his western
Pennsylvania accent, ``How yous doin'?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not into this to pick up a paycheck,'' Leyland said. ``I
feel no different now than when I played for $400 a month; I want
to beat the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   Hardly anyone doubts Leyland's sincerity when he talks of not
caring about the money. The reality, however, is that Leyland has
risen to the top of his profession. In turn, he has become the
highest-paid manager in the game, earning about $2 million per year
from Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most players, over the course of their careers, have talked
very favorably of him,'' said Diamondbacks shortstop Jay Bell, who
played eight seasons for Leyland in Pittsburgh. ``His reputation is
to be somebody who allows his players to play. He gives all the
credit when his team wins and takes all the blame when they lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``He relates so well to everyone he comes across. On a daily
basis, he probably has 40 different relationships. It's amazing how
Jim and Buck (Showalter) are so closely related. They have
different personalities, but if you go below the surface to their
baseball minds, they are almost identical.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rockies made hardly any changes with their roster over the
winter, believing the club they assembled last season (one that was
predicted by many to win the National League West) was not far from
being able to wedge its way into the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, other than the additions of pitcher Brian Bohanon and
superb utility player Lenny Harris, the Rockies look almost
identical to the club that finished 77-85 and 21 games behind NL
West champion San Diego under Don Baylor, who managed Colorado
during its first six seasons.
</P>
<P>
   While Baylor was made a bit of a scapegoat for the Rockies'
floundering season in 1998, Colorado owner Jerry McMorris stepped
in after the season and made Leyland his top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he allowed Leyland to assume more control of the
club than Baylor ever enjoyed. Leyland's first order of business
when the Rockies opened their spring camp two weeks ago was to
submit his list of no-nonsense personal rules:
</P>
<P>
   1. Make sure you are always on time.
</P>
<P>
   2. Bust your butt whenever you are on the field.
</P>
<P>
   That's it. No more, no less.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells you what he wants and he keeps it simple,'' Colorado
center fielder Darryl Hamilton said. ``He trusts you. He knows by
this time, we should know what's right from wrong. He's definitely
old school. Like every good manager, he puts his pride aside.''
</P>
<P>
   This will be Leyland's 14th season of guiding a club: eleven
with Pittsburgh and two with Florida. He has taken four different
clubs to the postseason, finally winning it all with the Marlins in
1997. He also managed a depleted and torn-apart Florida club to 108
losses last season. Yet surprisingly, he took great pride in his
job last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very humbling experience,'' Leyland said from his
cramped office at Hi Corbett Field. ``But last year was one of the
best groups of players I've ever had. Don't get me wrong, I didn't
feel good about losing 108 games, but we took a good core of kids
who will wind up being fine big-league players.''
</P>
<P>
   Like players, Leyland thrives on the competition. Though he
never made it as a major league player, the burning desire to
compete has never escaped him. It was the overriding reason he left
Pittsburgh (his home) after yet another losing season in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Friends in the game were in Leyland's ear, reminding him how
competing in Pittsburgh (at least at that time) was nowhere in the
Pirates immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   ``The easiest thing I could have done was to stay in
Pittsburgh,'' he said. ``I was stale in Pittsburgh after 11 years.
They used to ask me, `You want a chance to win, don't you?' I'm no
different than anybody else. I want to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
