<HEADER>
A7214 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      03-04 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS STRIKES LOCO NOTE OVER M'S PITCHING STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
 BBA-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ At 6-foot-5, Stan Williams is a little closer to
the sun than most. In Seattle, that makes no difference, because
the Mariners play inside. Even when they move outside, local clouds
are denser than Kingdome concrete.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, however, extra altitude is apparently a liability.
</P>
<P>
   As the pitching coach approached his charges on the practice
field Wednesday morning, he boomed out, ``Hello, my beauties!'' to
one of the more beleaguered staffs in the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicion that the man's cerebrum has been sun-dried was
confirmed when he offered up this observation about the presumptive
closer this season, newcomer Jose Mesa:
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifty saves for him is not out of the question.''
</P>
<P>
   There you have it _ proof of the deleterious consequences of the
sun. Stay away from here, Puget Sounders. As every cowboy or miner
in every Western movie has always warned, the desert makes you
loco.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there is a possibility Williams is right about Mesa,
who saved 46 games for Cleveland in 1995. If that proves true,
Williams will become the next mayor of Seattle, a guest on
Letterman and Leno and cover boy for Magicians Monthly magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Stan, my man, regarding Seattle pitching forecasts, skepticism
runs deep.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, manager Lou Piniella was convinced his relief corps
was better than the critics claimed. Turned out the most expensive
bullpen in baseball ($8.9 million in '98 salaries) was even more
costly, finishing next to last in the team relief standings that
measure saves and wins against blowns saves and losses. And then it
lost to free agency Mike Timlin, whose seasonal second half
bordered on the superlative.
</P>
<P>
   So now Williams is asking us to believe that the Mariners have
found more than Timlin's equivalent, for about half Timlin's cost.
Williams might have an easier time this morning selling irrigation
systems in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like his makeup, his workmanlike attitude and self-control,
and he's easy to talk to,'' Williams insisted, sincerity burning
from his eyes into the inquisitor's. ``Mesa looks outstanding.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams is equally buoyant about the other spot that is
critical to Mariner pitching fortunes, the No. 3 starter. In his
first full season a year ago, Ken Cloude had one of the poorer
efforts by a major league pitcher, going 8-10 with a 6.37 ERA.
Baseball Weekly calculated that Cloude's on-base percentage and
slugging percentage added together was the highest in baseball for
a starter with more than 75 innings.
</P>
<P>
   No team can be a contender without consistent quality innings
from the third man in the rotation, particularly on a staff that
failed to replace No. 1 starter Randy Johnson. The fourth and fifth
spots are a crapshoot, here as well as with many other teams.
</P>
<P>
   So if Cloude, 24, doesn't deliver behind Jeff Fassero and Jamie
Moyer, the new ballpark will quickly become the world's second-most
expensive tomb, behind the pyramids of Egypt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've ironed out his principal problem, and Ken is
going to be fine,'' Williams said. ``He had an outstanding game at
the end of last season, after we made the adjustment. He's going to
be the Kenny Cloude we were looking for.''
</P>
<P>
   Cloude's mechanical trouble stemmed from a habit of holding the
glove near his face before releasing the ball. It caused him to
limit his arm extension, and thus short-arm the pitch. Williams
gave Piniella credit for spotting the flaw.
</P>
<P>
   With the glove now coming to rest at his waist before delivery,
``it allows me a full arc with my arm,'' Cloude said. ``I'm
pitching much more relaxed and effortlessly. It's made a
significant change in locating the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether fans buy Williams' optimism about the two pivot points
on the Mariner staff is secondary to whether the pitchers buy it.
Right now, the sale is made.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike his predecessor, Piniella's Bible-study pal, Nardi
Contreras, Williams has his players' full attention and respect.
Since this is his first spring camp under Piniella (Williams came
on when Contreras was fired 11 games into last season), he has made
a point of introducing his old-school, yet upbeat style to
youngsters and vets.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more like a father, and he's pretty calm and subtle,''
said Billy Swift. ``And he's been there,'' referring to Williams'
14-year major league pitching career that ended in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   The skeptical view is that since Williams is the fourth pitching
coach in seven years under Piniella, he's merely the next
scapegoat-in-waiting.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest counterpoint Williams, 62, offers is his deep
friendship with Piniella, 55, that was helpful in bringing them a
World Series ring with the Cincinnati Reds in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Lou almost since he was a baby. We've been friends
a long time. We have a good rapport,'' he said. ``Lou can be very
tough. He wants to win so badly, that's why I like him so much.
He's also big-hearted, an emotional guy. Sometimes things come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I try to let it slide and discuss things after he quiets
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Any success Williams has in keeping Piniella from hijacking the
soul out of a young pitcher in the event of a walk will be a signal
accomplishment, almost as heady as restoring the No. 3 starter or
the bullpen closer.
</P>
<P>
   If Williams can't get any of those things done, well, he's
already desert loco, so the season shouldn't bother him.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0124EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
