<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON SATISFIED WITH 1ST SPRING OUTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON _ This was big. The table full of microphones indicated
so. The crowd of reporters, waiting to devour every morsel of
information, was another sign.
</P>
<P>
   On  &UR; Randy Johnson's grand scale, however, his first pitching
assignment for the Diamondbacks on Wednesday against the University
of Arizona was tame by comparison.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was exciting to be out there, but not nearly as exciting as
it will be in LA for the opener (on April 5 against the Dodgers and
right-hander  &UR; Kevin
 &UR; Brown) or the first time I pitch at Bank One Ballpark (likely April
15 against the Dodgers),'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander pitched the first two innings of the
Diamondbacks' 10-2 victory over the Wildcats at Tucson Electric
Park. He didn't give up a hit and struck out four of the six men he
faced. His pitch speed averaged 93 mph and topped at 95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just working on my location, mechanics and trying to get a
feel for my breaking ball, but it usually doesn't come until late
spring,'' Johnson said. ``I want to show improvement, but I don't
base what kind of year I'm going to have on what I do in the
spring.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Damian Miller enjoyed his first opportunity to catch Johnson in
game conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching him on TV, you would think he would be hard to catch,
but he's really not,'' said Miller, who never faced Johnson when
both were in the American League or last season after Johnson was
traded to Houston on July 31. ``Once he finds his release point,
it's right there. He shook me off a few times, but I'm sure we'll
get used to each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bulldog out there. Once he gets going, it's `Here it
is, boys, see if you can hit it.' There ain't no messing around.''
</P>
<P>
   It was mentioned to Manager  &UR; Buck Showalter that Johnson
occasionally grunts when he throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I heard that grunt one too many times,'' Showalter said,
referring to the times when Johnson, then with Seattle, squared off
against his New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's next scheduled start is Sunday against the Chicago
White Sox at Tucson Electric Park. After throwing 31 pitches
Wednesday, he likely will throw closer to 50 on Sunday. If Johnson
needs more work after leaving the game, he will throw on the side. &QL; 
Womack Mfg. Co. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New acquisition  &UR; Tony Womack was the designated hitter Wednesday
and struck out in his first plate appearance, but later showed why
the Diamondbacks wanted him.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth inning, he led off and reached base on a bunt
single, stole second, went to third on single by  &UR; Edwin Diaz and
scored on a double-play grounder by  &UR; Dante Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Showalter said Womack will not play in today's Cactus League
opener against the Colorado Rockies, but will remain at Tucson
Electric Park to work on fundamentals related to his switch from
second base to right field. &QL; 
Robinson services &QL; 
Funeral services for Diamondbacks minor league pitcher  &UR; Ken
Robinson, who was killed early Sunday in a Tucson auto accident,
will be Friday in Jacksonville, Fla. The family has requested that
in lieu of flowers, contributions be made to an education fund for
Robinson's 1-year-old son, &UR; Chase. Address is Nations Bank Florida,
14288 Beach Boulevard, Jacksonville, FL 32250-1546. The account
number is 0030-6265-0521. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
