<HEADER>
A7217 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPOR     03-04 1510
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-MOTORSPORTS-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODINE SPEAKS, AND THE SECRET IS OUT ABOUT TMS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bodine said the secret words without prompting Tuesday
afternoon at Texas Motor Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of those moments where you're glad you had your tape
recorder rolling, inconspicuously under a notepad, just to make
sure you had heard what you had written down, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this track right now definitely has the potential for
side-by-side racing,'' Bodine said into the tape recorder, above
the din of a screaming NASCAR Winston Cup engine. ``That's what
race fans want to see and that's what we want to do as drivers,
because that's how we pass people. We get beside 'em.''
</P>
<P>
   And race 'em, side-by-side.
</P>
<P>
   Other than, ``Turn 1 isn't leaking any more, guys,'' no nicer
words have been spoken lately about the racetrack in far north Fort
Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In 24 days, TMS is scheduled to play host to its third annual
Winston Cup race. During Tuesday's media intrusion into Cup testing
at the 1.5-mile quad-oval, we learned that Bodine unofficially had
blown the doors off the track-qualifying record a day earlier.
Bodine also felt comfortable enough with the revised layout to
state that he and his Winston Cup brethren will be able to race
door handle-to-door handle on Palm Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Recall that after the water seepage problems experienced in
turns 1 and 4 during Cup qualifying last year, and continued
complaints about the track's ``one-groove'' geometry, developer
Bruton Smith and general manager Eddie Gossage had the track ripped
up, reconfigured and repaved. The $3 million redesign eliminated
the controversial 8-degree ``dual-banking'' from the turns, leaving
the track with true 24-degree banked corners.
</P>
<P>
   And the promise of two grooves.
</P>
<P>
   Rising series star Jeremy Mayfield set the Winston Cup
qualifying record last year with a hot lap in 29.047
seconds/185.906 mph in the No. 12 Mobil 1 Ford Taurus. On Monday,
Bodine unofficially toured the track in 28.72 seconds, or 188.022
mph. Bodine's lap is a whopping 2.116 mph faster than Mayfield's,
but, because it was recorded during a test, the numbers remain
unofficial.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bodine said the lap was run under qualifying-type
conditions. Assuming that Bodine's No. 60 Power Team Chevrolet
Monte Carlo also would have passed NASCAR tech inspection, and the
numbers are even close to legit, speeds should take a significant
jump at the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of the ``new'' TMS is not the only factor in play
here. NASCAR also has ditched the controversial ``5-and-5''
aerodynamics package, giving the three car manufacturers taller
rear spoilers and lower front air dams to help increase stability
everywhere, but especially through the corners.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's one groove here that's really fast,'' said
Bodine, who spent Tuesday refining a race-day setup. ``When we get
here and get racing, the groove will move up, and I think you'll
have two grooves out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Two grooves. Side-by-side racing. Passing for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Bodine has spoken. And it's all down on tape.
</P>
<P>
   LAJOIE TESTS WINSTON CUP CAR
</P>
<P>
   Randy LaJoie admittedly misses the perks accompanying the title
of NASCAR Busch Grand National champion, a cache not limited to a
steady supply of six packs courtesy of the series title sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie simply loves the drive-hard, party-hearty BGN lifestyle _
one that he parlayed into series championships in 1996 and 1997.
LaJoie failed in his bid for a third consecutive title in 1998,
when he ran into a couple of upstarts named Dale Earnhardt Jr. and
Matt Kenseth.
</P>
<P>
   But an off-season change of teams and a victory in the season
opener at Daytona International Speedway on Feb. 13 have allowed
LaJoie to re-invent himself as the series points leader after two
of 32 events. He will take a 10-point lead over Kenseth into the
Sam's Town 300 on Saturday at Las Vegas Motor Speedway, secure that
team owner James Finch and Phoenix Racing are committed to chasing
the 1999 BGN championship.
</P>
<P>
   Then what was LaJoie doing at Texas Motor Speedway this week,
testing a Winston Cup car? A Ford Taurus, yet? And hanging out with
road racer Boris Said?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm coaching,'' said LaJoie, moments after stepping out of an
unpainted version of the No. 14 Federated Auto Parts Ford. ``I'm
here kind of as a coach and mentor to shake the cars down and help
the team.''
</P>
<P>
   The team is co-owned by Cup regular Ernie Irvan and associate
Mark Simo, who are attempting to execute the transition of Said
from NASCAR's Craftsman Truck Series to Winston Cup as quickly as
possible. Irvan-Simo have plotted an eight-race Cup schedule for
Said, beginning with the Primestar 500 in Fort Worth on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   The schedule includes the Winston Cup road races at Sonoma,
Calif., and Watkins Glen, N.Y., where Said is expected to qualify
well and excel. Running the six ovals, however, will hinge upon
Said's progress at turning left in a 750-horsepower Cup car.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be perfectly honest, I don't have the experience to be out
here racing Cup,'' said Said, who racked up a second-place finish
in the inaugural NASCAR Truck race at TMS in June 1997. ``We need
some experience, and he's \RLaJoie\S the best guy we could have
got.''
</P>
<P>
   LaJoie said he has not committed to run for Irvan-Simo, mainly
because he does not want to jeopardize his BGN relationship _ and
an expanded research and development role _ with Chevrolet. But the
prospect of testing and racing Cup cars, and transferring that
knowledge to his BGN program, intrigues LaJoie.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our ultimate goal is the championship,'' LaJoie said. ``I've
won 'em. I know how to win 'em. I want to get back to being
competitive, that's the biggest thing.''
INSIDE THE NUMBERS
LaJoie-ful seasons A comparison of Randy LaJoie's NASCAR Busch
Grand National Series championship seasons: Year Starts Poles Wins
Top-5s Top-10s Winnings 1996 26 2 5 11 20 $532,823 1997 30 2 5 15
21 $1,105,201
QUICK HITS THEY GOT TICKETS
</P>
<P>
   The ticket office at Texas Motor Speedway has 150 season tickets
available for sale, courtesy of fans who failed to meet the payment
renewal deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Prices range from $235 to $345, which is approximately half of
what some scalpers on various Web sites are asking for tickets just
to the combined NASCAR Busch Grand National and Winston Cup weekend
March 27-28. All the season seats are in the frontstretch
grandstand, and will cover the six major races scheduled at TMS
this year.
</P>
<P>
   For more information or to purchase a season package, call (817)
215-8500.
FORMULA ONE RETURNS
</P>
<P>
   Mika Hakkinen of Finland apparently has grown to like his
lifestyle as reigning Formula One World Driving Champion over the
past four months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am hungry like no tomorrow. I tell you, I really want to
win,'' said Hakkinen, who begins defense of his title at the
Australian Grand Prix on Sunday. Speedvision is scheduled to carry
the race live at 8:30 p.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Hakkinen, who won eight of 16 races last year for West
McLaren/Mercedes, again is teamed with David Coulthard of Scotland.
They are expected to battle Ferrari's Michael Schumacher, a
two-time world champion from Germany, and Eddie Irvine of Ireland
for F1 supremacy.
NEWMAN/HAAS SWAPS TIRES
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone/Firestone struck a major blow in the Championship
Auto Racing Teams ``tire wars'' earlier this week, when Newman/Haas
Racing announced it was ending its association with Goodyear after
16 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Drivers Michael Andretti and Christian Fittipaldi will run their
Swift/Ford V-8s on Firestone Firehawks beginning with the CART
FedEx Championship Series opener on March 21 at Homestead, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Andretti scored his series-leading 37th career victory on
Goodyears at Homestead last year. But it was Goodyear's only
victory in 19 CART races.
FIRST FOR MOPAR
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kinser became the first Sprint Car driver to win a Pennzoil
World of Outlaw ``A'' main event with Mopar power at Manzanita
Speedway in Phoenix, Ariz., on Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives from Chrysler's parts division announced a
multiyear sponsorship agreement with car owner Karl Kinser, Mark's
father, at the end of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Kinser finished ahead of cousin and 15-time WoO champion
Steve Kinser in the third race of 1999. Danny Lasoski is leading
the points standings after three consecutive top-five finishes.
GALLES LANDS SPONSOR
</P>
<P>
   Car owner Rick Galles' gamble of running the Pep Boys Indy
Racing League season opener without a major sponsor has paid off.
Galles' revived team, featuring two-time points runner-up Davey
Hamilton, has signed Big Daddy's BBQ as primary sponsor for their G
Force/Aurora for the remaining 10 IRL races.
LAST WORDS
</P>
<P>
   ``If you've been to New York, you know it's not going to happen
in Manhattan _ unless they're going to take Central Park out of the
way. I don't think they're going to do that for a racetrack.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeff Gordon on locating a proposed NASCAR track on Long Island
nn
</P>
