<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BUCKHORNCREE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREDGING UP MEMORIES  
 BUCKHORN CREEK MAY BE DRY NOW, BUT TRACES REMAIN OF A GOLDEN ERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even with extremely dry conditions, trips into the desert at
this time of year still are beautiful. Few grasses are growing, but
other vegetation is green and pretty.
</P>
<P>
   But beware. Temperatures already are above average. If history
is any indication, we could have temperatures in the high 90s by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   And unless you're a hardy soul, hot days aren't much fun for
outback travel. Even with an air-conditioned vehicle, there are the
perils of overheating or a breakdown that would leave you to your
own devices in unforgiving heat.
</P>
<P>
   But now, traveling is wonderful _ on warm, spring-like days with
cloudless skies.
</P>
<P>
   That leads us to a trip that doesn't require a four-wheel-drive
vehicle, but does require one with high clearance. And there will
be some driving in sand, so don't take this trip lightly.
</P>
<P>
   The scenery is great, there's a chance to hike in a lovely
riparian area between two steep hills and you can see the remnants
of a strange gold-mining operation _ one that is something like
panning for gold in a huge way.
</P>
<P>
   The trip begins in Wickenburg, northwest of Phoenix on U.S. 60,
simply because it's easier to find this route than by starting at
the other end.
</P>
<P>
   Before you reach downtown Wickenburg, turn right on El Recreo
Road, which leads to Constellation Road. This unpaved but decent
road heads toward the ruins of the famous Constellation Mine, but
you don't go that far.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 miles in, you'll see a junction to the right. A sign
points to Owl Springs Ranch. Turn right, and you'll be heading onto
a road that will head down to Buckhorn Creek, which is dry. You'll
drive along and through Buckhorn. This is where the most adventure
lies. Finally, you'll hit Castle Creek and take a right.
</P>
<P>
   This is most difficult part of the trip. There's plenty of sand,
and the road is rough. When you leave the creek, you'll take a
short jog to the left on Morristown Road and turn right on Castle
Hot Springs Road, which will take you past the famous former resort
called Castle Hot Springs Ranch and back to State Route 74 near
Lake Pleasant.
</P>
<P>
   You have to look for it, but gazing high into the hills, you'll
get a chance to see the buildings at Owl Springs Ranch. The ranch
is in a spectacular setting on a desert mountain. The view from
there must be fantastic.
</P>
<P>
   But the fun doesn't start until dropping down into Buckhorn
Creek. The roads all are rough from now on.
</P>
<P>
   Down the creek a short distance, you'll encounter a small
concrete structure along the road on the right. Turn into the
driveway there for a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   The old ranch house that was built against a hillside is gone,
but things remain that are even more interesting.
</P>
<P>
   This is Buckhorn Springs, and you'll quickly encounter a couple
of water troughs kept full by the springs. The troughs are fed by
gravity from pools higher above through plastic pipe. The pipe must
have some small leaks because the larger trough burbles with air
that is released with the water.
</P>
<P>
   Follow the pipe up along the mostly dry stream created by the
springs. The scenery is terrific _ rock cliffs, trees, plants and
ultimately pools of water. It's an easy walk along the stream bed.
The pipe is buried in one pool. The springs are higher above.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great place to stop for lunch (and carry out your
trash).
</P>
<P>
   Now travel farther down the road, and suddenly you'll encounter
a huge piece of machinery in the middle of the dry streambed among
vegetation that has grown up around it.
</P>
<P>
   It appears to be a huge pontoon boat sitting on the rocks and
sand. In a way, it is. But this was a working boat, a gold dredge.
Though they're gone now, the boat appeared to have had a diesel
engine and large pump. Two 20- to 30-foot steel pipes rise above
the dredge.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently this is how it worked: The stream was dammed when it
was flowing, creating a small lake to float the dredge. The steel
pipes were rammed into the bed to keep the dredge stable.
</P>
<P>
   Gold particles would settle out in the lake and could be dredged
from the bottom. The pump also could spray a strong stream of water
on the shoreline, bringing more gold-bearing sediment into the
lake.
</P>
<P>
   It seems impossible that the dredge could have been brought to
this site in one piece. It must have been constructed on site. It's
impressive to see.
</P>
<P>
   A short distance downstream, a side road to the right reveals a
metal scow tangled among the trees. At one time the scow, a
ponderous thing, had a hand winch with cable that was attached to
the dredge and shoreline. It allowed travel between the two sites.
</P>
<P>
   Farther up this side road, one can see remnants of more recent
gold-mining operations.
</P>
<P>
   The whole thing was fascinating.
</P>
<P>
   There is another abandoned ranch on the way out, but it is
posted with no trespassing signs.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's always a pleasure to drive past Castle Hot
Springs Ranch with it's well-kept lawn and buildings.
</P>
<P>
   This was an interesting adventure for a warm March day. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
