u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI &LR;      03-04 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECOVERY FROM ELBOW SURGERY REKINDLES BUNHNER'S FIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PEORIA, Ariz. _ People everywhere revived an old romance on
Sept. 8, 1998, when Mark McGwire lined a baseball into history and
a Cupid's arrow through the hearts of wayward fans.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Buhner fell in love all over again, too. Only he didn't know
it at the time, and his reasons had nothing to do with a
record-breaking home run in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Sept. 8 was frightening for the Mariners' resident
tough guy. That was the day Buhner learned the problem with his
right elbow was much more serious than he had first been told. He
would need reconstruction of the elbow, requiring his second, and
most serious, surgery that year.
</P>
<P>
   The news, so ominous at first, turned out to be wonderful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing _ it definitely rekindled my love for the
game and re-fueled my desire and fire, there's no doubt about it,''
Buhner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through a time when I needed a second wind. I know
it might sound bad, but there were a lot of things that were kind
of on my mind that I needed to get away from. This injury enabled
me to step back, really take a look at it and realize how much I
loved the game, how much I missed it. It was a wake-up call.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner, who will play designated hitter in a morning ``B'' game
Thursday but appears healthy enough to play in the outfield, was
emotionally spent by the end of last season. Out for 59 games with
a knee injury, he agonized through the M's lost season, finding
himself wishing he could do more _ not only on the field, but
everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a tendency to get caught up in a lot of different
things, trying to be a leader, trying to do this or do that,''
Buhner said. ``Now I realize that basically I have no control over
those things. The only thing I can control is what I do on the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   He embraced the new challenge, aiming to return to the field as
quickly as possible. But nobody expected him to be where he is now.
If Buhner navigates carefully through this month of exhibition
games, he has a solid chance to open the season in right field on
April 5.
</P>
<P>
   The first several days of exhibition games, Buhner will play
designated hitter and pinch-hit, with an off-day or two mixed in.
He will start in left field on March 10, then gradually increase
his innings and at-bats and play consecutive games in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners would like to see Buhner play at least a half-dozen
full games in the outfield by the end of camp, and if everything
goes well, said trainer Rick Griffin, some of those games should be
in right.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to astound those who have gone through ``Tommy
John'' surgery, which normally takes at least nine to 12 months of
recovery time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been amazed at what Jay's doing at 5{ months,'' said M's
left-hander Butch Henry, who missed nearly 18 months after his
surgery in August 1995. ``He's a year and a half ahead of where I
was at that stage.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of the reason for Buhner's progress is his trust and
confidence in the Mariner medical staff. Players routinely go out
of town for such surgeries, but Buhner had his performed by team
doctor Larry Pedegana. A year-round resident of the Northwest,
Buhner checked in every two weeks with Pedegana and worked out
daily at the Kingdome with Griffin. He allowed himself a week off
at Christmas, and only four other off days all winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``If all patients were like that,'' Pedegana said, ``it would
make surgery a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   How dutiful a patient was Buhner? He took his medical team on
vacation. Buhner and Griffin, who are best friends, have a cabin in
Montana, and they brought along Pedegana on a fly-fishing trip in
October.
</P>
<P>
   It was there Buhner made the first breakthrough in his recovery.
At first, Buhner said he would cast left-handed, but one day he
tried it with his right. Casting the fly rod, which is similar to
throwing a dart, Buhner realized he didn't hurt at all. He wasn't
even sore the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there for a week,'' Griffin said, ``and when we came
back he had full range of motion.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner has known Pedegana and Griffin his whole Mariner career.
He said it was comforting this winter to know he could call them at
any time and get not only attention, but a straight answer. Instead
of hedging against a full recovery, Buhner said, Pedegana assured
him he could make a full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Once he heard that, Buhner said, all that remained was the work.
It was something he could thrive on, especially when he heard this
from Griffin: No matter how hard it was for you to get to the major
leagues, the hardest thing you will ever do is recover from this
injury.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing I told him is don't doubt yourself or doubt
that you can come back,'' Griffin said.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner has had only minor setbacks. In December, he needed a
removal of scar tissue that was clamping down on his ulnar nerve
and causing him to lose feeling in two fingers. He had to stop
throwing on the second day of camp because of elbow soreness, but
by the end of the day he was throwing pain-free again.
</P>
<P>
   There are bound to be more rough days. Henry said you have to
respect the injury, but you will never recover without testing your
limits
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk a fine line between getting healthy again and
re-injuring it,'' Henry said, ``because you've got to push it to
its boundaries because that's the only way to make it stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   Examples abound, and one stands out for Buhner. Anaheim
infielder Randy Velarde, a teammate of Buhner's in the Yankees'
minor-league system, played in only one game in 1997 after the
surgery, then had setbacks when he tried to return last spring and
again in May. Velarde didn't come back for good until August _ like
Henry, nearly 18 months later.
</P>
<P>
   As great as he feels right now, Buhner knows Velarde felt the
same way this time last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randy Velarde is probably one of the best physical specimens
you've ever seen, and if it can happen to him, it shows you
something,'' Buhner said. ``You get out there and you start to feel
good, and even when you don't you still push it, because you're a
gamer and you want to be out there. It's a rude reminder that
you've got to be smart, and even when you feel good, you've got to
limit how hard you go.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Buhner has positioned himself for a remarkable
comeback, but the arm he calls his pride and joy isn't back just
yet. The only thing that has returned for sure is his love for the
game.
</P>
<P>
   MARINER NOTES: Outfielder Butch Huskey was the Mariners'
happiest camper Wednesday, when his new No. 42 jerseys were
delivered to the clubhouse. Huskey had been issued No. 36 after
coming to Seattle in a trade from the New York Mets, but he had
worn 42 his whole career to honor Jackie Robinson. ``It's just a
number, but it's significant to me,'' said Huskey, who feared he
wouldn't be allowed to wear the number, which was retired by
baseball in 1997. ``I didn't want to make a big deal about it, but
there was no reason I couldn't get it if I was grandfathered into
it.'' ... The lineup for Thursday's ``A'' game against the San
Diego Padres: RF Ichiro Suzuki, SS Alex Rodriguez, CF Ken Griffey
Jr., 1B David Segui, LF Huskey, 3B Russ Davis, C Tom Lampkin, 2B
Carlos Guillen and P Jeff Fassero. The game can be heard on KNWX
radio 770 at 12:05 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
