<SLUG> BC-BBA-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-RANGERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATER, ALLIGATORS; RANGERS NEED A BONAFIDE ACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Doug Melvin can't deny it. Neither can
Johnny Oates. But for the record, Tom Vida rejects the notion about
the Rangers being ace-less in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom Vida''?
</P>
<P>
   A former high school coach in Ohio, Vida is the supervisor of
grounds at the Rangers' vast spring training complex, and has
helped maintain the best-kept baseball fields in Florida for 13
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep an eye on that lake over there,'' Vida advised yesterday.
``Then tell me what you see.''
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long until a 12-foot alligator crawled up on the
lake bank for a sunning session, no more than 70 yards from the
ticket windows at Charlotte County Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   While small alligators have frequently homesteaded the three
lakes surrounding the main ballpark, this 12-footer is by far the
largest Vida has spotted on the grounds in 13 years.
</P>
<P>
   Such jaws haven't been seen around here since the last Will
Clark clubhouse tirade against the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' said Vida, ``we now officially lead the league in
alligator.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson told the Rangers no, then so did Roger Clemens.
But from the surrounding swamps, ``Ace the Alligator'' has arrived,
and joined up with the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ace'' also has a traveling companion. ``Tail-Gunner'' is a
7-footer, large by normal ballpark lake standards, and he/she is
never far behind the big thing.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has to be asking himself how come No. 1 pitchers aren't
finding the Rangers this attractive.
</P>
<P>
   But the general manager flashed plenty of teeth _ no, not quite
``Ace'' size _ when he smiled and said, ``I don't think that search
is ever over. The Yankees win 125 ballgames, have a staff leader
like \RDavid\S Wells and are still trying to upgrade by trading him
for Clemens. If the Yankees didn't think they had enough pitching,
who does?''
</P>
<P>
   Good point.
</P>
<P>
   The names to remember between now and July are obvious. Kenny
Rogers in Oakland. Curt Schilling in Philadelphia. Brad Radke in
Minnesota. Kevin Appier in Kansas City (if healthy). Alex Fernandez
in Florida (if healthy). Denny Neagle in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   When those teams start falling out of the race (for a couple,
that will be the end of April), one or more of these pitchers
figure to come available. The Rangers, of course, figure to be very
interested. None of them is Johnson or Clemens, except Schilling is
close. But all are appealing to any club wanting to upgrade its
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Here in early March, the Rangers' brass gives proper lip service
to its current rotation members, faking surprise that anyone would
think additional help is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Reality, of course, says Schilling could be this staff's new
alligator, or ``Ace,'' and any of the others would make the
rotation better.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Hicks' hip pocket is sitting on go. A pitching trade will
happen at some point this spring, or, more likely, by July. But the
rub comes with what the Rangers are willing to give up.
</P>
<P>
   Once Ruben Mateo's name hit print as the key to the
almost-Clemens trade with Toronto, other clubs will now demand this
young, gold-plated outfield prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``I doubt we'd give Ruben up for anyone other than Clemens,''
Melvin said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   But if the Phillies are going to deal Schilling, then they would
certainly be asking for Mateo in the package _ and stay tuned on
what happens if Melvin is faced with that brain-squeezer. Actually,
such a thought already makes Melvin nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Tom \RHicks\S when we were talking about Clemens that I
had a knot in my stomach,'' he said. ``I couldn't explain if the
knot was caused by the excitement of possibly landing Clemens, or
the worry of giving up Mateo. Either way, it wasn't going to be a
deal where I gleefully walked to the microphones and announced it
to the media.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how much Melvin thinks of Mateo, slated for Triple-A duty
with Oklahoma this season, and in center field in Arlington in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the ever-present nightmare of having once traded a
young Sammy Sosa still dogging the organization, there is a
long-standing theory in baseball that even Melvin doesn't dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   That theory says never trade a hot pitching prospect, but always
consider dealing a positional prospect if you are receiving a top
pitcher in return. Such was the case with Mateo-Clemens. Such would
be the case with Mateo-Schilling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Positional guys will come back to haunt you, too,'' said
Melvin, ``but they are also usually easier to evaluate than young
pitchers. And when that young pitcher goes somewhere else and
becomes like an ace, it stings the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   In time, the Rangers will again try to pounce on a rotation
acquisition for this season. Meanwhile, they sit, wait and try to
stay out of the way of the only proven ace they currently have in
camp. Meaning ``Ace the Alligator.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
