<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-FREEHOUSE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE HOUSE HOPES TO CHARM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART WILSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jockey Chris McCarron was always impressed with Free House's
ability and tenacity when he raced against the 5-year-old gray son
of Smokester.
</P>
<P>
   Now that McCarron is the regular rider of one of the favorites
in Saturday's $1 million Santa Anita Handicap, he understands why
he respected the 1997 Santa Anita Derby champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can see why he's got so much talent,'' McCarron said. ``He's
a very grandly built horse. He's got a very muscular frame, and
he's got one of the smoothest strides of any horse I've ever
ridden. He's very efficient, there's no wasted action.
Consequently, fatigue becomes less of a factor.''
</P>
<P>
   That muscular frame and smooth, efficient stride have helped
Free House, a California-bred, win 8 of 20 lifetime starts for
earnings of nearly $2.5 million. Included among the eight victories
was a four-length romp in last summer's Grade I Pacific Classic at
Del Mar, when he ran away and hid from horses the likes of
Gentlemen and Puerto Madero.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, Puerto Madero, who may be favored when the horses go
postward for the 62nd Big 'Cap at approximately 2:40 p.m., is a
much tougher horse now than in August. But so is Free House,
according to his connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's more mature,'' trainer Paco Gonzalez said. ``He's 5 years
old now. He's at the best age for a horse. His attitude is
different. He's more like a man now.''
</P>
<P>
   Free House comes into Saturday's race off a neck victory over
defending Big 'Cap champion Malek in the Grade II San Antonio
Handicap. The two hooked up head-and-head virtually the entire way,
spitting out turtle-like fractions of :24.17, :48.56 and 1:12.7 for
the 1 1/8 miles on the main track.
</P>
<P>
   Malek may skip this race, however, in favor of the Dubai World
Cup on March 28. With a little early speed, Free House could find
himself on the lead again trying to hold off Silver Charm, Puerto
Madero and Event of the Year in the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   Can Free House take this Grade I field gate to wire?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm gonna leave it up to Chris,'' Gonzalez said. ``If he feels
comfortable being on the lead, that's fine. He knows the horse
pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Said McCarron: ``And I'm going to leave it up to the horse. If
he breaks cleanly. I'm going to let him run out of there and see
where he is and how aggressive he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key with him is to just allow him to settle into stride,
make him happy. If he's content and happy in the early running of
the race, he's going to give you everything he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   Free House and Silver Charm, who have developed a rivalry dating
back to their battles as 3-year-olds, will be hooking up for the
eighth time. Silver Charm has won five of the seven matchups,
including the past four.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm's affable trainer, Bob Baffert, used to joke that
the two horses knew each other. Free House's owner, Trudy
McCaffery, laughs when the statement is relayed to her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they do know each other,'' she said. ``I said to
somebody the other day, I think it's really impressive that Silver
Charm and Free House are still, at 5 years old, rivaling each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez does not enjoy the rivalry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just enjoy my horse,'' the Arcadia resident said. ``Every
time he runs, it's a special race for me no matter who is in the
race.''
</P>
<P>
   So as McCarron prepares to climb aboard Free House for the sixth
time, dating back to a seven-length victory in last summer's Grade
II Bel Air Handicap at Hollywood Park, Gonzalez marvels at the
strength of this year's Big 'Cap field and is thankful his horse is
100 percent fit.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffery said Free House is more confident, more focused than
when he finished second in the Preakness Stakes and third in the
Kentucky Derby and Belmont as a three-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to Chris after (Free House's) work on Monday (six
furlongs in a bullet 1:11 3/5), and to quote him it sent shivers up
his spine,'' McCaffery said. ``I don't think the horse could be
doing any better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
