<SLUG> BC-BBA-SULLIVAN-COLUMN-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX AREN'T READY TO THROW IN TOWEL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ The Boston Red Sox have declined to offer
unconditional surrender.
</P>
<P>
   The hated New York Yankees have Roger Clemens, and Mo Vaughn has
left town. But the Red Sox are bravely going on with the season
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't have to go out there, but we have to because
we're getting paid,'' said Red Sox second baseman Jeff Frye, taking
the realistic approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also know that to cancel the season would also deny
their painfully loyal fans another summer of pathos at Fenway Park.
They wouldn't be able to sit in the shadow of the Green Monster,
sip their suds, eat their Fenway Franks and lament blunders past:
the loss of Babe Ruth, the betrayal of Carlton Fisk and now the
departure of Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was the Red Sox's leader and best hitter, an All-Star
first baseman and community activist who was allowed to get away as
a free agent. He follows the well-trodden paths of Fred Lynn, Wade
Boggs, Fisk, Clemens and Red Sox icons whose relationship with the
mother ship ended in bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the fanatical faithful remain behind and prepare to
chalk up another season without a World Series championship, an
unhappy famine that is entering its 81st season.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox do get to play host to the All-Star Game at Fenway
in July, but that might only serve to reopen old wounds should
Clemens be standing on the mound in a Yankees uniform and Vaughn at
first base wearing the dreadful Angels digs.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the Red Sox clubhouse is there the smallest bud of hope.
This is the team that had the second-best record in the American
League last season and there is a belief that the Yankees are at
least slightly less than invincible.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no reason why they can't be beat,'' first baseman/DH
Mike Stanley said. ``Last year was a pretty magical season for
them. Everything fell into place. You never know what could happen
in the course of a year. Guys get injured, have a bad year. You
don't win anything until you go out on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The bravado might be a little more realistic had the Red Sox
re-signed Vaughn. Instead, they settled for Jose Offerman, a
defensive liability without power, but who has shown a knack for
both getting on base and stealing a few. He had a .403 on-base
percentage for the Royals last season along with 45 stolen bases
and 102 runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   So, the Red Sox gave him $26 million over four years, hoping
he'll offset the loss of Vaughn's 40 home runs and 115 runs batted
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to compare me and him,'' said Offerman, who
might have a hard time convincing Red Sox fans of that. ``We are
two different players. There are things that he can do that are
hard for me. My job is to get on base.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox historically are a power-based team, but producing
again will difficult to do without Vaughn. Instead, they'll have to
rely on a pitching staff that had the second-best earned-run
average in the American League last season.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez is one of the best pitchers in baseball, Tom
Gordon proved to be a success as a closer, and Tim Wakefield (17-8)
and Bret Saberhagen (15-8) help give the Red Sox a strong rotation.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also have Nomar Garciaparra, one of the best
shortstops in the league. But he also shoulders the burden of being
the Red Sox's new team leader in the absence of Vaughn, a
responsibility he would prefer to decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo is over there,'' Garciaparra said. ``He's worried about
getting the Angels to the World Series. We're doing the same thing.
He's got a job to do and so do I.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox's pitching makes them a wild-card threat, but any
success they have this year will be accompanied with the cry, ``If
only we had Mo!'' The season draws nigh and nobody does pathos like
a Red Sox fan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
