<SLUG> BC-FBC-SEAHAWKS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QB SEARCH CONTINUES AS FREROTTE PASSES ON HAWKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CLARE FARNSWORTH  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRKLAND, Wash. _ The Seahawks were stymied in their attempts to
sign a veteran quarterback for the second time when Gus Frerotte
signed a contract with the Detroit Lions Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Frerotte, who visited the Seahawks last week, was given a
three-year, $3 million deal by the Lions to be the backup to
Charlie Batch.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks also were interested in Doug Pederson, but the
former backup with the Green Bay Packers signed a three-year, $4.9
million deal two weeks ago to be the starter in Philadelphia,
scrapping a scheduled visit to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently working against the Seahawks is the presence of a
young incumbent, 26-year-old Jon Kitna, and a rumor circulating
among agents and front-office executives from other teams that the
Seahawks will use their first-round pick to select a quarterback in
April's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're a gambler, the upside situation is clearly
Seattle,'' one agent said. ``But the unknown element is whether the
Seahawks will draft a quarterback in the first round. A lot of
people think that will happen, and even more are saying that will
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   So new Seahawks coach and general manager Mike Holmgren, who had
coached Pederson in Green Bay, continues to look for a young
veteran to challenge Kitna for the starting job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a list of players we are either talking to or we're
going to bring in here,'' Holmgren said. ``Gus was one. Doug
Pederson was one. We'll probably continue to do that until we find
someone and the fit is right.''
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks also had Chris Miller and Stoney Case in for visits
last week. Case signed with the Indianapolis Colts Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The pool of available talent is becoming more stagnant because
10 quarterbacks already have been removed from contention. Two have
re-signed with their old teams: Casey Weldon (Redskins) and Wade
Wilson (Raiders). Two others have been traded: Brad Johnson (to the
Redskins by the Vikings) and Ty Detmer (to the Browns by the
49ers). Six more have signed with new teams: Frerotte, Pederson,
Case, Rich Gannon (Raiders), Kerry Collins (Giants) and Trent Green
(Rams).
</P>
<P>
   What remains is an assortment of quarterbacks who are either too
old (Steve DeBerg, Warren Moon, Dave Krieg, Frank Reich and Steve
Bono); too inexperienced (Shane Matthews, Doug Nussmeier, Steve
Stenstrom, Scott Zolak and Steve Walsh); too similar (Heath Shuler,
Danny Kanell, Donald Hollas and Todd Philcox); or too expensive, in
that they are restricted free agents and would cost the team
signing them a draft choice (Bobby Hoying, Tony Banks, Jay Fiedler
and Steve Matthews) or make too much money (Jeff George).
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawks are not alone in this. The San Diego Chargers,
Baltimore Ravens, Tampa Bay Buccaneers, Pittsburgh Steelers and
Chicago Bears also are seriously searching for quarterbacks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
