<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVERICKS-BRADLEY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON DEFENSE ALONE, MAVERICKS' SHAWN BRADLEY AT HEIGHT OF POWERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DWAIN PRICE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ The proof came Tuesday night, as it has in a number of
games this season, that Shawn Bradley can be a force in the NBA.
</P>
<P>
   And he has no need to score a lot of points to make that point.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley had an NBA-season-high nine blocked shots to spark the
victory against the Los Angeles Clippers. And now, Mavericks fans
can no longer laugh about Bradley awkwardly trying to become a
dominant offensive threat. Instead, Bradley sets a tone on defense
with his shot-blocking and rebounding skills, and that has
transformed him into a threat opponents have to account for.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been several games this year where Shawn Bradley
was the best player we had out on the floor,'' Mavericks coach Don
Nelson said. ``In fact, I don't think he's had a bad game yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's new role _ where his offense is de-emphasized _ has
helped him become more comfortable on the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more confident, whether it's because of this role or
maturity or whatever,'' Bradley said. ``I just feel that way. But
it's a combination of things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nelson figured the only way he was going to get maximum
production out of Bradley was to diminish his role as a scorer.
That plan was put into action before this year, and Bradley has
responded with his most productive all-around season to date.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley averages six points, 6.3 rebounds and 3.94 blocks while
playing an average of just 23.8 minutes per game. He is shooting a
team-high 50.8 percent from the field, and has blocked four or more
shots in 10 games this season.
</P>
<P>
   He is averaging the most blocks per game of his career while
playing the fewest minutes of his career. And Bradley and the
Mavericks take a four-game home winning streak into tonight's 7:30
game at Reunion Arena against the San Antonio Spurs.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's teammates are benefiting from his defensive dominance.
They now can gamble and overplay the passing lanes, knowing that
the 7-foot-6 center is back in the middle ready to clean up their
mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect him to be that force, and he's been doing it
defensively,'' forward Michael Finley said. ``Guys have been beaten
off the dribble and Shawn's been there blocking shots and just
making their shots even harder.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he can do that on a night-in and night-out basis, it
makes us good defensively. And when he scores offensively, it's
just an extra added bonus.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley said opposing players ``just kept trying him and trying
him and Bradley keeps blocking their shots.'' That was very
apparent Tuesday night against the Los Angeles Clippers, when
Bradley blocked nine shots, tied for tops in a single game in the
NBA this season.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, who said he might retire when his contract expires
after the 2000-2001 season, has a bad reputation around the NBA of
repeated complaints to referees during the games about perceived
blown calls. As part of his maturation process, those complaints
have decreased considerably this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't change the coaches decision, or what the coach's
philosophy is,'' Mavericks forward A.C. Green said. ``And he can't
change the referees, whatever their impressions of Shawn Bradley is
throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``But he can control his effort, he can control the way he goes
out and plays the game, and that's really the most important thing
right now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going out and kicking behind every night _ that's his
attitude.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
