<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-LEBRETON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR TCU WOMEN BASKETBALL'S TEAM, STEPSISTER DAYS ARE GONE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Once upon a time, there was a hapless stepsister
upon whose head had been placed a loathsome curse.
</P>
<P>
   The curse was so bad, the stepsister once lost to Texas by a
score of 96-33.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody came to watch the stepsister. Few even cared.
</P>
<P>
   The curse was so vile, the hapless stepsister once lost 64 of 67
basketball games. It lost to Rice _ Rice! _ by 51 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point,'' said an innocent voice who was there,
``that we were asking ourselves, `Why are we even in practice?' We
knew people were going to kick our butts.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it came to pass that a brave prince arrived.
</P>
<P>
   He challenged the curse. He ignored the past. He showed TCU
women's basketball, long the university's spurned stepsister, that
it could, indeed, go to the palace ball. OK _ maybe the NIT ball.
</P>
<P>
   Cry no more, Cinderella. Even after a 74-62 loss to New Mexico
yesterday in the second round of the Western Athletic Conference
tournament, the Frogs were able to walk away smiling and proud.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one on this team likes to lose today,'' guard Jill Sutton
said. ``But I know that all the players are going to walk away from
this feeling good. Yesterday was the best any of us have felt in a
long time. It was a big step.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Monday's first round, no TCU women's basketball team had
won a game in its conference tournament. Until this season, no
NCAA-member TCU women's basketball team had ever had a winning
record.
</P>
<P>
   Until yesterday, no coach of a TCU women's basketball team could
actually wish aloud for a postseason tournament invitation without
drawing a room-wide smirk.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are extremely deserving to play after this,'' said Mike
Petersen, whose princely coaching has brought TCU from the 2-25
cinders to a relative 16-12 throne.
</P>
<P>
   It was three seasons ago that the university stood on the damp
end of that 2-25 plank. Under coach Shell Robinson, the Frogs had
been a carefree bunch destined to also record seasons of 5-22 and
1-26.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coach didn't know how to use our players,'' said senior
Ginger Usher of Keller, the lone player remaining from the Robinson
years. ``We would go into games and never have a thought about
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   TCU had a choice. It could go on losing to Rice, 93-42, and
getting hammered by the likes of Southwest Texas and
Missouri-Kansas City. Or it could do it right.
</P>
<P>
   Petersen, a successful coach at New Mexico State, was brought in
at twice the salary that the previous head coach was making.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing we had to do was change the attitude,''
Petersen said. ``One of the hardest things to do is to teach
players to expect to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Usher remembers the earliest message being one of ``be good or
be gone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the boss, though,'' she said. ``He made it clear to us
what he expected of us.''
</P>
<P>
   The Frogs found Petersen to be a relentless stickler for
preparation. His scouting reports began to take on an eerie
thoroughness. He stressed knowing how to move your feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has the best basketball knowledge of any coach I've ever
been around,'' Usher said. ``And, somehow, he got it all pulled
together.''
</P>
<P>
   They won't be playing in the WAC tourney semifinals tomorrow.
The Frogs played the higher-seeded Lobos off their feet in the
first 17 minutes yesterday, only to run out of gas and fresh legs
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   In the locker room when it was all over, Petersen brought tears
to some eyes by telling them that they've been a special team.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my 11th team,'' he told a visitor later, ``and it's by
far not the most wins (16) I've ever had. But as I told them, it's
one of my most favorite teams ever. They've been a special group.
They've done things the people here have never done before.''
</P>
<P>
   Petersen knew the risks of coming to TCU, where the program
averaged less than seven wins for an entire decade. But the kids he
recruited knew the risks and accepted the challenge as well.
</P>
<P>
   They are players like the talented sophomore twins, Jill and Amy
Sutton. Players like Karen Clayton from Southlake Carroll, and
Duncan, Okla., freshman Tricia Payne.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told each of them, `They were 3-52 at TCU. That's not my
fault. If you come, we'll win,' '' Petersen said. ``Every one of
them bought into it _ bought into the chance to do something that's
never been done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every one of those kids could have gone elsewhere. The twins
could have gone to Oklahoma. Clayton was recruited by Oklahoma
State, Colorado and Florida. They could have gone to a school that
would've sounded better.''
</P>
<P>
   The curse over, Mike Petersen waits for a princely phone call
from the NIT.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, this sounds pretty good,'' he said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
