<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WHITT-COLUMN-CLIPPERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS SO BAD THEY COULD BE GOOD FOR NBA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Move over, Mark McGwire, make room for the Los Angeles
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Just as McGwire's pursuit with Sammy Sosa on the home run record
handcuffed fans to baseball last summer, the Clippers are preparing
for a magical run toward imperfection that should likewise
captivate basketball.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer: ``Did McGwire go deep again?''
</P>
<P>
   This spring: ``Did the Clips get beat again?''
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's 13-point loss to the Mavericks, the Clippers are
0-13, steaming toward the 0-17 NBA record for disgustingly
interesting starts held by the expansion Miami Heat in 1988-89.
LA's ugly stepsisters next play at Houston and at San Antonio
before a home-and-home with the Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, 0-17 should be a reality. McGwire hit 70, could
the Clippers lose 50?
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing is going to be easy for us,'' Clippers coach Chris
Ford said. ``No one wants to be the team to give us a gift. I'm
sure the embarrassment of losing to us is the topic of every team's
pregame discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   The next game in which the Clippers will be less than a 10-point
underdog will come March 19 at Toronto, at which point they could
be a headline-grabbing 0-22.
</P>
<P>
   How bad are these Clippers? They've lost just once by less than
four points and already have home losses to Chicago, Dallas, Golden
State and Vancouver. Trailing the Mavericks 34-16 in the second
quarter, Ford trotted out a lineup of James Robinson, Sherman
Douglas, Tyrone Nesby, Brian Skinner and Rodney Rogers.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Duke would wipe the floor with them and they'd
be favored by only a bucket against the Washington Generals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they're struggling,'' Mavericks guard Michael
Finley said. ``Whoever loses to them will be the first story on
``SportsCenter''.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall of Fame center-turned-Clippers TV commentator Bill Walton
thinks long and hard when asked how bad LA is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hmmm,'' Walton said scratching his red head. ``The effort is
there, but to say the talent isn't would be a severe
understatement.''
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than a management whose litany of first-round
draft choices reads like a who's who of lottery busts: Benoit
Benjamin, Reggie Williams, Joe Wolf, Ken Norman, Danny Manning,
Hersey Hawkins, Danny Ferry, Bo Kimble, Loy Vaught, LeRon Ellis,
Randy Woods, Elmore Spencer, Terry Dehere, Lamond Murray, Greg
Minor, Antonio McDyess, Lorenzen Wright, Maurice Taylor, Michael
Olowokandi and Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Donald T. Sterling, the captain of this Clippers' sinking
ship, refused to hire a head coach during the lockout in order to
save money. When the lockout ended, they had no coach, and No. 1
overall pick Michael Olowokandi was playing in Europe. Just last
season, when they bolted to a 1-12 start, the Clippers traded
blossoming star and fan favorite Brent Barry for Ike Austin, then
let the franchise center get away in free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really tough,'' Murray said. ``You want to see a light at
the end of the tunnel. But right now it looks pretty dark.''
</P>
<P>
   For morbid curiosity, the Clippers are great for the NBA. The
Mavericks, in fact, should hoist a banner to the top of Reunion
Arena in appreciation. Without the Clippers, Dallas would be the
butt of NBA jokes.
</P>
<P>
   LA's first-round flops and front-office follies make fans forget
that the Clippers have actually gone to the playoffs twice this
decade and won four postseason games. The Mavericks, meanwhile,
haven't seen May in eight seasons and last won a playoff game in
1988. In fact, if the '90s were a season, the Mavericks (186-486)
would trail the Clippers (243-426) by 58 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the Clippers who will flirt with the worst season in
NBA history as far as winning percentage. To eclipse the .109
established by the 9-73 Sixers in 1972-73, LA will have to go 5-45
(.100).
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Clippers are gaining momentum, and fans are
starting to take notice of their improbable run at an unbreakable
record. The magic number for imperfection is 37 and counting.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
