<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS RUN OUT OF GAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Maybe the physical toll from the night
before, when they had to battle tooth and nail with the Phoenix
Coyotes, had taken too much out of them. Maybe it was the fatigue
of playing their third game in five days. Maybe it was the result
of taking penalties at the wrong time and not converting their
power plays. Perhaps the Carolina Hurricanes just played better.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Bruins looked battle weary
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night and the result was a 2-1 loss at the Greensboro
Coliseum before a sparse crowd of 7,507.
</P>
<P>
   The arena was the temperature of a meat locker and Boston's
scoring touch was about as cold as the Bruins suffered their first
defeat in six games (4-1-1).
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances we had weren't solid chances,'' said coach Pat
Burns. ``We missed the net a lot. We fought hard but we came up
short. We've got to put it aside and go onto the next one.''
</P>
<P>
   The only saving grace was that the Florida Panthers, Boston's
closest contender for the eighth and final playoff berth in the
Eastern Conference, blew a 5-0 lead and lost to Colorado, 7-5.
</P>
<P>
   The rule of thumb when playing on the second of back-to-back
nights is get the lead early. That way you can conserve some energy
for when the legs start to give out late in the third period and
the weariness sets in.
</P>
<P>
   However, that objective didn't come to fruition as Boston fell
behind and wound up using most of its energy in the late going to
kill off penalties (three in the third period, six total).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed with our start once again,'' said goalie
Byron Dafoe, who kept the Bruins in it, finishing with 23 saves.
``We were outshot, 9-1, in the first 10 minutes. They only got one
goal out of it but maybe we get four shots and it's a 0-0 game.
Instead, we're down, 1-0. They're another team that's good at
holding a lead. They definitely took advantage of the fact that we
played (Tuesday) night. They're a very fast skating team and they
came out flying and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The first period was a scramble with both clubs trying to get
their offense on track. The Hurricanes took a 1-0 lead at 7:46 on a
goal by former Bruins defenseman Glen Wesley. Sami Kapanen left a
drop pass at the right point for Martin Gelinas. Gelinas fired a
shot from the right circle that Dafoe stopped but the rebound
bounced to Wesley in the left circle and he buried it into the top
of the net for his fifth goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had a golden opportunity to tie it when they had a
two-man advantage for more than a minute. With Gelinas off for
holding and Kent Manderville joining him in the box 55 seconds
later, Boston had a five-on-three for 1:05. The Bruins managed two
shots but couldn't get anything past goalie Arturs Irbe.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the period, the Bruins pulled even on a goal by Anson
Carter, his 11th of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Carter got the puck as a result of a major hit by Ken Belanger.
Carter skated in alone on Irbe and beat the netminder with a
forehander inside the left post at 18:38.
</P>
<P>
   The Hurricanes took the lead for good early in the second period
on a goal by Gelinas. Center Keith Primeau got the puck behind the
Boston net and fed a centering pass to Gelinas in front at 3:05. It
was Gelinas' 11th goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had to kill off two Carolina power plays in the
middle period, both of which yielded quality scoring chances. One
came at 12:48 when Primeau had a point-blank chance on Dafoe. A few
minutes later, with Don Sweeney in the box, Dafoe again faced a
point-blank blast, this time off the stick of Ron Francis, who took
a centering pass from Jeff O'Neill, but Dafoe stood tall.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins had a hard time breaking into the Carolina zone and
even when they did, not much happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes they're a pretty stingy team to play against,'' said
center Jason Allison. ``Maybe we got outbattled a little. It's
something that can't happen. Guys are working hard, don't get me
wrong. It wasn't from lack of effort. They didn't give us very much
and we didn't earn very much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
