u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKW-HOLYCROSS-NAVY-BO     03-04 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-HOLYCROSS-NAVY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLY CROSS WOMEN GAIN NCAA BERTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WORCESTER _ The crowd of 3,152 set a Patriot League
championship-game record. In numbers, in decibels, in frenzy. They
love their Crusaders in the cozy Hart Center, and think nothing of
painting themselves purple, or dashing to and fro in purple capes,
or screaming in a purple fury. All they expect in return is a Holy
Cross win.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just what the fans got Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night as the No. 1
seed Crusaders downed No. 3 Navy, 72-58, to win their sixth Patriot
League tournament in seven years and another automatic bid to the
NCAA women's basketball tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``The longer I'm in this thing, the sweeter it gets,'' said Holy
Cross coach Bill Gibbons, coaching in his ninth league final and
winning his sixth. ``I always dreamed about this type of
atmosphere. I think the first couple, only my family knew we were
in a championship game.''
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't as easy as tying on a purple kerchief or even
dredging up a purple boa. For starters, Amy O'Brien, whose 22.6
scoring average ranks eighth in the country, was held to a single
field goal in the first half by the only league team to beat the
Crusaders this season (81-74 Jan. 17).
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never sweat so much,'' said O'Brien, a senior and
two-time Patriot League player of the year playing her last game in
Hart. ``I couldn't hold on to the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   After managing an 11-point halftime lead despite their star's
butterfingers, the Crusaders (21-7) saw their lead whittled to
43-39 with 12:41 left in the game. But then Holy Cross kicked into
gear for its best offense of the night, exploding on a 21-11 run
that put away the Midshipmen (17-11).
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien, breaking free of double- and triple-teams in the second
half, finished as the game's leading scorer with 25 points, while
5-foot-6-inch dynamo guard Anna Kinne, who kept the Crusaders in
the game early on, had 15 on her way to being named the
tournament's most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Midshipmen crawled back into the game, a technical
foul early in the first half turned the tide in favor of Holy
Cross. With the score tied, 12-12, with 12:29 left in the half,
Navy center Laurie Coffey, an all-Patriot League first-teamer,
protested too vigorously after picking up a quick second foul and
was slapped with her third via a T.
</P>
<P>
   Kinne made both free throws, giving the Crusaders the lead for
good at 14-12. Coffey stayed on the bench for the rest of the half,
and she soon was joined in foul trouble by forward Erica Hayes,
also a first-team all-leaguer. With Navy coach Joe Sanchez forced
to play four guards at times, the Midshipmen could never get back
in their game. Midway through the half, Navy went on a 6 1/2-minute
scoreless drought. By then, the Crusaders were up by 11, thanks
mostly to the shooting of Kinne, who was 3 for 7 behind the arc in
the half. Holy Cross led, 34-23, at the break.
</P>
<P>
   In all, the Crusaders earned 27 of their points from behind the
arc. ``Those nine 3-pointers, we didn't count on those,'' said
Sanchez. ``We worried a little too much inside.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
