<SLUG> BC-BKC-BIG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROVIDENCE GETS THE BOOT 
</HEADLINE>
 EAST-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ No. 10 seed Georgetown, looking to avenge a 2-point
loss in its regular-season finale at Providence College, advanced
to the quarterfinals of the Big East tournament in Madison Square
Garden with a 68-66 victory over the seventh-seeded Friars
Wednesday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   Ruben Boumtje-Boumtje led the Hoyas (15-14) by scoring 14 of his
team-high 18 points in the second half. He gave Georgetown the lead
for good when he hit the front end of a one-and-one with 15.2
seconds to go. Erron Maxey led Providence (16-13) with 18 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very gratifying for a lot of reasons, because we really
needed this victory,'' said Georgetown coach Craig Esherick, whose
team will face No. 2 seed Miami in the quarterfinals. ``I'm so
proud of the way our team fought their way back.'' The Hoyas
trailed, 49-39, in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The game was marred by controversy when, unbeknownst to
officials, Trez Kilpatrick threw a punch at Providence's Jamel
Thomas with 12:17 to go. Kilpatrick was hit with a technical, but
was allowed to remain in the game and came back to score a key
basket that gave Georgetown a 64-62 lead with 3:56 to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``The official who saw the play deemed it to be a forearm in the
player's back and assessed a deadball technical,'' said lead
official Jim Burr. ``At no time did anyone mention to us that a
punch had been thrown or did we think about the possibility of a
punch being thrown.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Thomas: ``I'm not going to complain about the
(officiating). They called it, and you have to respect that and
deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had a chance to make it all moot, but was unable to
squeeze off a final shot. With 12.4 seconds left, John Linehan
dribbled across midcourt and got the ball to Thomas with six
seconds remaining. However, Thomas (17 points) committed a critical
turnover (his fourth of the game) when he was trapped in the lane
and lost the handle as he attempted to dish it to Maxey.
</P>
<P>
   Villanova 73, West Virginia 61 _ John Celestand rallied the No.
5 seed Wildcats from a 29-24 halftime deficit by scoring 21 of his
game-high 26 points in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   Celestand connected on 7 of 15 field goals, including 5 of 10
from 3-point range, while Howard Brown chipped in 16 points to help
Villanova (21-9) earn a berth in the quarterfinals against
fourth-seeded Syracuse.
</P>
<P>
   Brown scored on a putback that tied it, 57-57, and Celestand
followed with a layup that gave Villanova the lead for good, 59-57,
with 3:15 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall 79, Notre Dame 69 _ No. 9 seed Seton Hall got
double-figure scoring from three starters, including 18 points
apiece from Duane Jordan and Rimas Kaukenas, to secure a matchup
against top seed Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   The Fighting Irish suffered their fourth straight first-round
loss despite getting 28 points and 15 rebounds from freshman Troy
Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers 64, Pittsburgh 51 _ Geoff Billet, Rob Hodgson, and
Alvydas Tenys each scored 11 points apiece to lead the No. 6
Scarlet Knights to a quarterfinal matchup against No. 3 seed St.
John's. It was the final game for Pitt coach Ralph Willard, who
earlier in the season announced he was stepping down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
