<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ATLANTIC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORDHAM OUSTED 
</HEADLINE>
 10-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ For three years they had been the Atlantic 10
tournament's equivalent of a pitcher batting against Greg Maddux.
Since joining the league in 1996, Fordham has been an easy out, a
virtual afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   This year was supposed to be different. Fordham entered
Wednesday's first-round contest against Virginia Tech having won a
school-record five regular-season A-10 games and as a No. 5 seed,
were considered a sleeper.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday, the Rams discovered nothing has changed as
regards the tournament. Its 74-63 loss to the Hokies wasn't even
compelling: Virginia Tech (12-15) jumped to a 33-24 halftime lead,
increased it to as many as 15 in the second half, then withstood a
mild Fordham rally late.
</P>
<P>
   Fordham finished its season at 12-15, its best mark since the
1993-94 season.
</P>
<P>
   Rolan Roberts had 19 points to lead a balanced attack for
Virginia Tech, which shot 57 percent from the floor in the second
half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an easy game to analyze. Their defense overpowered our
offense and we just didn't play any defense,'' said Fordham's Nick
Macarchuk, the A-10 coach of the year. ``They just overpowered us
and outplayed us in every facet of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Dayton 70, St. Bonaventure 69 _ Dayton center Mark Ashman had a
team-high 16 points and sank a 5-foot baseline jump shot with 1:08
left to give the Flyers an overtime victory over the Bonnies.
</P>
<P>
   St. Bonaventure (14-15) had several chances to tie it or take
the lead after Ashman's shot, but missed 3 of 4 free throws. The
Bonnies had possession with 16.7 seconds left but guard J.R.
Bremmer missed a shot just before the buzzer.
</P>
<P>
   La Salle 81, St. Joseph's 54 _ The Explorers won their first
tournament game since joining the A-10 three years ago with a
surprisingly easy romp over the Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Carr scored 14 of his game-high 21 points in the first
half as La Salle (13-14), which needed two overtimes to beat St.
Joseph's (12-18) Jan. 23, jumped to a 48-26 halftime lead, then
coasted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0157EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
