<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 01:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7245 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN     03-04 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEBERT STOPS KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Kings were a desperate team heading into Wednesday
night's game at the Pond. The Mighty Ducks were merely a team that
wants to continued to play like a desperate team even though their
playoff chances look better and better each day.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Kings played desperately, knowing full well that
their playoff hopes get slimmer with every loss. But Guy Hebert and
the Ducks were able to hold off the Kings 2-1 before 17,174 at the
Pond.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks certainly couldn't have planned it, but they played
their version of rope-a-dope. Anaheim landed two punches early
(goals by Matt Cullen and Teemu Selanne) and then spent the rest of
the night avoiding the Kings' counterattack.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks had to kill off a Kings power play in the final two
minutes and did so; Tomas Sandstrom forced the Kings to take a
penalty of their own after goalie Stephane Fiset had been pulled to
give Los Angeles a two-man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles outshot Anaheim 34-14 but the Kings lost their
fourth consecutive game to Hebert and the Ducks this season. Hebert
has allowed only three goals in the four games.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' victory moved them three games over the .500 mark
(28-25-9) for the first time since they were 8-5-4 on Nov. 8, 1997.
It also moved them within five points of fourth-place Phoenix in
the Western Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   The defeat dropped the 10th-place Kings seven points back of
eighth-place San Jose with only 20 games left in the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings spent most of the first period in the Ducks' zone,
easily killed two penalties, held Paul Kariya and Selanne without a
shot and outshot Anaheim, 13-3. But Los Angeles still left the ice
trailing 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sandstrom, who scored twice in the Ducks' win over the Kings on
Feb. 15, put a centering pass on the stick of Cullen. The Anaheim
center, who had beaten Donald Audette to the net, chipped the puck
past Fiset at 8:21 for his seventh goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came on Anaheim's second shot of the game. The Ducks
wouldn't get another for 10 minutes, but they retained the lead
thanks to Hebert and some help from the post.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings players twice raised their sticks believing they had
tied the game. Hebert got just enough of Luc Robitaille's one-timer
from the right circle to keep it out of the net on a Kings' power
play, and Glen Murray's shot from the slot bounced off the right
post with 4{ minutes left in the first.
</P>
<P>
   The second period had to be nearly as frustrating. Once again
the Kings outshot the Ducks (13-9) and outchanced them, but Anaheim
still led 2-1 after 40 minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' No.1-ranked power play unit converted its third
chance of the game when Selanne turned a harmless looking play into
a goal.
</P>
<P>
   After the Ducks won a battle in neutral zone, the winger darted
around Sean O'Donnell, passed off to Travis Green and then stuffed
Green's return pass past Fiset at 8:21 on Anaheim's fourth shot of
the power play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks managed just two shots at even strength in the period.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's 35th goal and 80th point of the season extended his
goal-scoring and point-scoring streaks to seven and 14. Meanwhile,
the Kings were huffing and puffing as they attempted to break the
spell that Hebert has held over them this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie, who came into the game with .067 goals
against average and .978 save percentage in three games against the
Kings, stopped Robitaille, Sean Pronger and Rob Blake before Blake
finally beat Hebert low on the glove side from the right circle to
make it 2-1 at 13:32.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's third goal in four games was the Kings first in 131
minutes, 7 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Kings failed to help themselves on the power play.
Los Angeles, which is ranked 25th in the league, couldn't convert
any of its four opportunities in the first two periods.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
