<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-WRITETHRU-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A TOUGH DAY FOR ROBINSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Kings coach Larry Robinson will leave the team
today to attend the funeral of his mother, who died late Tuesday in
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a long day,'' Robinson said following the Kings' 2-1
loss Wednesday night to the Mighty Ducks at the Pond. ``I got a
call early on this morning that one of my horses had a heart attack
and died on the farm (in Florida). A half hour later, I found out
my mother had died. I guess things can always get worse.''
</P>
<P>
   The cause of death for Robinson's 78-year-old mother, Isobel,
was not disclosed. A wake is tentatively scheduled for Friday near
Ottawa, with the funeral planned for Saturday. Robinson probably
will rejoin the Kings on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson is expected to miss home games tonight and Saturday
against Nashville and Calgary, respectively. Assistant coaches Jay
Leach and Rick Green will be in charge in Robinson's absence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jay will take over my job behind the bench, and between him
and Greeny, they'll work out the game plans and lineups,'' Robinson
said. ``I'll leave that up to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin out: The Ducks were without center Steve Rucchin, their
third-leading scorer with 22 goals and 56 points. According to the
team, Rucchin was sidelined with ``sinus problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Rucchin suffered a broken nose nearly two weeks ago in a game at
Calgary. Over the weekend, he took a shot to the head from San
Jose's Bryan Marchment, but Rucchin said he was not hit in the
nose. According to Rucchin, a combination of flu and the broken
nose was the reason he didn't play.
</P>
<P>
   Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg said: `His nose was basically
crushed in Calgary. I'm sure there's a combination of things going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   Peaking Ducks: February was the best month in Ducks history and
a big reason was Teemu Selanne, who had 25 points and was the NHL's
player of the month.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks posted a 10-3 record in February, besting their 7-3-4
record in March 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Of Selanne, Hartsburg said: ``He's a unique guy. He loves to be
around the guys and he loves playing. That combination is hard to
find. Teemu makes the most out of every day and I'm sure not every
day is the best.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Kariya added: ``He's real good when things aren't going
well. He never gets down. He always has something to be happy
about, like getting a new car.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne had at least one point in each of the Ducks' 13 games in
February, collecting a total of 12 goals and 13 assists. Selanne
has scored at least one goal in his last seven games and has at
least one point in 14 straight games.
</P>
<P>
   He scored the 300th goal of his career Saturday against San
Jose, reaching that milestone in 464 games, the sixth-fastest in
NHL history. Only Wayne Gretzky, Mario Lemieux, Brett Hull, Mike
Bossy and Jari Kurri scored 300 goals in fewer games.
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Ducks defenseman Pascal Trepanier was struck by the
puck in the first period and left the game with a bruised left
leg.... Kariya recorded his 200th career assist on Selanne's
second-period goal.... The Ducks are 9-2-4 against Pacific Division
teams, and the Kings are 3-14 mark.... The Kings reassigned center
Eric Belanger to Springfield of the AHL. Belanger, one of the
Kings' top prospects, had been assigned last week to the Long Beach
Ice Dogs, for whom he appeared in one game.... Winger Vladimir
Tsyplakov, sidelined two weeks with a knee injury, has been skating
with a brace.... Kings center Yanic Perreault, who has six goals in
the last 52 games he's appeared in, was a healthy scratch.
Perreault was benched for the entire third period of Sunday's 1-0
loss in Dallas. Winger Sandy Moger also was a healthy scratch, and
defenseman Philippe Boucher missed the game because of a bout with
the flu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
