<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-CYCLING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERFECT TIME FOR CYCLING IN MOUNTAINS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LANGTON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The visitor's view of Southern California includes
warm summers, palm trees swaying lazily in the breeze and a
Starbucks on every corner serving up iced lattes.
</P>
<P>
   Some chemical in the smog must block out their memories of the
San Fernando Valley's 100-plus degree days, ever-present brush-fire
potential and crowded freeways.
</P>
<P>
   But those of us who live here year-round know that the winter
and spring months are actually the best time of the year. Who says
the Southland only has one season?
</P>
<P>
   Late winter and early spring promise the explosion of
wildflowers, without the brain-melting heat. You're missing a
wonderful treat if you're not getting out to see the hillsides from
February through April.
</P>
<P>
   ``This really is the best time of year to ride in the Santa
Monica Mountains,'' said Michael Thomas of Michael's Bicycles in
Newbury Park. ``The native plants, such as the California poppy and
lupine, are in full bloom, and the rains make the stream crossings
interesting ... just a little extra excitement. It may be a little
nippy when you first start riding, but in 10 or 15 minutes, it's
perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't use winter as an excuse not to go riding. Peak daytime
temperatures can range in the high 60s and low 70s. A few wispy
clouds can help create a dramatic sunset of fiery red and orange
strokes.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there's the occasional rain shower, but it rarely lasts
long, and the mountain-biking trails usually dry up after a day or
two. Besides, they've turned our dull, brown hillsides into greener
pastures.
</P>
<P>
   Too many times I hear riding buddies beg off on an invitation to
an early-morning ride. Too bad. The air is crisp and clean, and the
trails are firm and full of traction. But take a few simple
precautions.
</P>
<P>
   For cycling, dressing ``in layers'' is essential. High-tech
garments made from breathable and moisture-wicking materials for
the upper body keep the rider warm without becoming a one-person
sauna.
</P>
<P>
   Lycra spandex leg tights come in a variety of thicknesses. One
tip: Go a little lighter rather than heavier. While it may seem
cold at the start of the ride, it only takes a few hundred yards to
get the heart and blood pumping. You'll be amazed at how quickly
you warm up.
</P>
<P>
   Bike shops and recreation outfitter carry a wide variety of warm
and comfortable clothing for daytime jaunts or night rides. The
gear should be similar to that of cross-country skiing; avoid baggy
clothing if at all possible.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget polypropylene socks, gloves and maybe a lightweight
headband with ear flaps to keep the chill out.
</P>
<P>
   If you're venturing into canyons near sea level early in the
morning, you might want to consider insulated gloves and a light
mask to cover the nose and lips. Usually the air temperature is not
enough to cause a problem, but windchill (don't forget, you're on a
bicycle traveling at speed) can cool extremities quickly.
</P>
<P>
   If your fingers become numb, it can hamper braking control. If
your toes become numb, it's just no fun. And trying to converse
during a chance encounter with the mountain biker of your dreams
can be difficult with frozen lips.
</P>
<P>
   Another benefit to winter cycling is that you'll be that much
more fit come summer _ just in time to start taking off all those
layers. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 0244EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
