<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7279 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-L     03-04 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS DEFEAT KINGS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Kings were a desperate team heading into Wednesday
night's game at the Pond. The Mighty Ducks merely continue to play
like a desperate team even though their playoff chances look better
each day.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings played desperately, knowing their playoff chances grow
slimmer with every loss. But Guy Hebert and the Ducks were able to
hold off the Kings 2-1 before 17,174 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play very smart or very desperate,'' said Anaheim
coach Craig Hartsburg. ``The most desperate team usually wins, but
we were lucky to have great goaltending.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks certainly couldn't have planned it, but they played
their version of rope-a-dope. Anaheim landed two punches early
(goals by Matt Cullen and Teemu Selanne) and then spent the rest of
the night avoiding the Kings' counter punches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We outplayed them, no doubt about it,'' said Kings coach Larry
Robinson. ``We deserved a lot better, but the biggest difference
was Hebert, he was stopping everything. He won that game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' defeat was a mere footnote to a sad day for Robinson,
who was informed that one of his horses had died of a heart attack,
then a short time later he received the news his mother had died.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had better days,'' said the Kings coach.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who played passively much of the night, had to kill
off a Kings power play in the final two minutes and did so when
Tomas Sandstrom forced Donald Audette to take a penalty after
goalie Stephane Fiset had been pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles outshot Anaheim 34-14, but the Kings lost their
fourth consecutive game to Hebert and the Ducks this season. Hebert
has allowed only three goals in the four games and defenseman Rob
Blake said it really didn't matter how his team played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether we played a good game or a bad game, it's the same
result,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' victory moved them three games over the .500 mark
(28-25-9) for the first time since Nov. 8, 1997. It also moved them
within five points of fourth-place Phoenix in the Western
Conference playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks knew the result could have been much different.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the game we were talking and said it was great we won,
but let's be honest, we didn't play very good,'' said Selanne. ``We
can't play like this very often. We aren't the Dallas Stars, we
have to play well every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those games you try to forget and be better the
next time.''
</P>
<P>
   The defeat dropped the 10th-place Kings seven points back of
eighth-place San Jose with only 20 games left in the season. Los
Angeles (23-34-5) has already lost one more game than it did all
last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings spent most of the first period in the Ducks zone,
easily killing two penalties, holding Paul Kariya and Selanne
without a shot and outshooting Anaheim, 13-3. But Los Angeles still
left the ice trailing 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   Sandstrom put a centering pass on the stick of Cullen and the
Anaheim center, who had beaten Audette to the net, chipped the puck
past Fiset at 8:21 for his seventh goal of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The goal came on Anaheim's second shot of the game. The Ducks
wouldn't get another for 10 minutes, but they retained the lead
thanks to Hebert and some help from the post.
</P>
<P>
   Kings players twice raised their sticks believing they had tied
the game. But Hebert got just enough of Luc Robitaille's power-play
one-timer from the right circle and Glen Murray's shot from the
slot bounced off the right post with 4{ minutes left in the period.
</P>
<P>
   The second period was nearly as frustrating. Once again the
Kings outshot the Ducks 13-6, but Anaheim still led 2-1 after 40
minutes of play.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks' No.1 ranked power play unit converted its third
chance of the game when Selanne turned a harmless looking play into
a goal.
</P>
<P>
   After the Ducks won a battle in neutral zone, the winger darted
around Sean O'Donnell, passed off to Travis Green and then stuffed
Green's return pass past Fiset at 8:21.
</P>
<P>
   ``The difference was we couldn't score on the power play (0 for
5) and they need only one or two chances,'' said Robinson. ``We
haven't been giving up many goals, but we have to start get guys to
put the puck in the net.''
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's 35th goal and 80th point of the season extended his
goal-scoring and point-scoring streaks to seven and 14. Meanwhile,
the Kings were huffing and puffing as they attempted to break the
spell that Hebert has held over them this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim goalie, who came into the game with .067 goals
against average and .978 save percentage in three games against the
Kings, stopped Robitaille, Sean Pronger and Rob Blake before Blake
finally beat Hebert low on the glove side from the right circle to
make it 2-1 at 13:32.
</P>
<P>
   Blake's third goal in four games was the Kings first in 131
minutes, 7 seconds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
