<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   DISPATCHES FROM DREAMSVILLE: Growing up in small-town Chicago
</P>
<P>
   (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share, via Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray,
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
</P>
<P>
   By Lois Oller Nasados
</P>
<P>
   Special to Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   Not all Dreamsvilles are located in small towns. Mine, in the
late 1940s, existed on Chicago's Far Northwest Side near what is
now O'Hare International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   It may be hard for youngsters of the '90s to imagine, but it was
a gentler time when children roamed freely through their
neighborhoods, and it took, if not a village, at least a whole
neighborhood to raise a child.
</P>
<P>
   This was never more appreciated than when we, the under-12
crowd, all gathered to play hide-and-seek.
</P>
<P>
   Favorite hiding places included the open space under the porches
of the old farmhouses that still survived amid the post-World War
II brick bungalows now lining the city's streets.
</P>
<P>
   In the yards of some houses ancient stands of lilac bushes,
twice the height of the average father, guarded back fences from
prying eyes, while overgrown honeysuckle vines hid the trellises
that supported them.
</P>
<P>
   Their fragrance would envelop us as securely as the branches
that hid us. The trunk of a giant maple tree could easily conceal a
child or two crouching behind it.
</P>
<P>
   I don't remember ever being shooed away by a neighbor concerned
about a flower bed or a trampled lawn.
</P>
<P>
   I do remember being so snug and cozy in my fragrant nest that I
didn't want to leave, ignoring the rules of the game that required
me to sneak back to ``goal'' before ``It'' found me.
</P>
<P>
   Other children hid behind my grandpa's white picket fence or on
his big front porch. Hiding as far as possible from your own house
was an unspoken rule.
</P>
<P>
   Friends who have grown up in small towns or in the country often
offer sympathy that I was a child of the city. They're apt to smile
and shake their heads in disbelief when I tell them about the giant
maples, the ancient lilacs and the white picket fences that were a
part of my Chicago childhood.
</P>
<P>
   But we weren't so different.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday mornings we'd get up early, hoping to be first in
line at the neighborhood movie theater.
</P>
<P>
   We'd worry all week long if our current serial hero would
survive the horrors that the villain had planned for him.
</P>
<P>
   We'd laugh at the cartoon that seemed so magical in those days
when not everyone had a TV and the Cartoon Channel was
unimaginable.
</P>
<P>
   Of course all the boys wanted to be as brave as Roy and Gene,
and all the girls wanted to be as beautiful as Dale.
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar?
</P>
<P>
   If we were able to study all the Dreamsvilles _ east, west,
north and south _ we would find many unique features of each, but
we might also find that we have more in common than we ever
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Lois Oller Nasados is a writer who makes her living as a
bookkeeper in Longview, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915. A photo of the writer is optional. If your
article is used, you will receive $25.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
