<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 09:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7374 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-CO     03-04 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLEINBERG-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: ... and that brings us to Pete Rose
 &HT;    (For release Sunday, March 7, 1999. Moving on commentary and
sports wires.)
 &HT;    By Howard Kleinberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The people who run baseball, and those who report it, long ago
established a litany of hypocrisy that was further evidenced last
week by the election of Orlando Cepeda to baseball's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is not about Mr. Cepeda. I felt all along that
this man they called ``the baby bull'' deserved his place in the
Hall of Fame, earning it on the playing fields.
</P>
<P>
   If it is not about Cepeda, then it is about Pete Rose.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose made a mistake. Despite being one of the greatest
baseball players of all time, he is not in the Hall of Fame, not
even at its doorstep. Rose's impropriety was that he cheated on his
taxes and bet on baseball games, allegedly some involving the team
he was managing at the time.
</P>
<P>
   For this, Rose received a lifetime ban from baseball -- as well
as jail time.
</P>
<P>
   Switch back to Cepeda. He also made a mistake. His great career
ended, he returned to his native Puerto Rico and sold marijuana to
kids. He also did jail time, 10 months in the slammer.
</P>
<P>
   And when he got out, not even the Little League in Puerto Rico
would allow him to coach youngsters.
</P>
<P>
   But that was two decades ago and smarter heads have prevailed.
While Cepeda may not have been a model person then, he's done his
time and he's been rehabilitated. So, after years of being spurned
by the moralists who cover baseball games for the nation's media,
he's been permitted into the Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   Good for Cepeda. But what about Rose?
</P>
<P>
   Is cheating on your taxes and betting on games a crime more
heinous than selling marijuana to children? I don't think so.
</P>
<P>
   The baseball writers, who have the responsibility for electing
former players into the Hall of Fame, are hiding behind some
regulation that says a player cannot be elected if he is under
suspension from Major League Baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Rose has attempted to be reinstated but the baseball
commissioner's office has rebuffed him. So the baseball writers
stick to their narrow bylaws. With any guts, they could change
their bylaws and tell the baseball commissioner's office what it
can do with its lifetime ban of Rose.
</P>
<P>
   One might ask why Cepeda did not also get a lifetime ban, but I
won't because I think a lifetime ban is absurd, leaves no room for
rehabilitation or re-examination. Cepeda today is not the marijuana
advocate he once was; he is, in fact, a man who speaks to youth
groups about the pitfalls of the drug culture.
</P>
<P>
   How many decades is it that baseball fans have argued against
the lifetime ban imposed on the great Shoeless Joe Jackson for
whatever role he might have played in the infamous 1919 Chicago
Black Sox scandal? (How could someone who batted .375 and committed
no errors in the 1919 World Series be part of a plot to
intentionally lose?)
</P>
<P>
   Baseball has an amazing elasticity _ when it wants to. It can
keep a Rose away from his deserved honor for decades but can allow
a franchise to pick itself up and steal away in the middle of the
night, as it did the franchises in Brooklyn and Manhattan four
decades ago.
</P>
<P>
   Rose, who suffers from a bombastic personality that I am certain
works against him, feels he has served out his penalty, as did
Cepeda. So do I.
</P>
<P>
   It is inconceivable that baseball and the baseball writers can
continue this constraint against Rose indefinitely. If anything,
the Cepeda experience and subsequent election to the Hall of Fame
should open their eyes to their own hypocrisy.
</P>
<P>
   (Howard Kleinberg, a former editor of the Miami News, is a
columnist for Cox Newspapers. His e-mail address is
hkmiami(at)aol.com.)
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
