<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPECIALS-BUDGET-NYTSF </SLUG>
  
 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No. 2525 - March 4, 1999   NEWS AND FEATURE
SUMMARY -- No. 2525 -- March 4, 1999 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. THE LONELY SUPERPOWER The unipolar moment has passed. Even
old allies stubbornly resist American demands, while many other
nations view U.S. policy and ideals as openly hostile to their own.
Washington is blind to the fact that it no longer enjoys the
dominance it had at the end of the Cold War. It must relearn the
game of international politics as a major power, not a superpower,
and make compromises. U.S. policymaking should reflect rational
calculations of power rather than a wish list of arrogant,
unilateralist demands. By Samuel P. Huntington. Foreign Affairs
magazine. 1,800 words. 2. IN INDIA, CHILDHOOD IS FOR SALE Sonia is
12 and blind; not surprisingly, she has never played with
footballs, but from the age of six she was forced to stitch them,
eight hours a day, seven days a week. At the end of each day, she
had not earned enough to buy even a loaf of bread for her family.
Still, Sonia was one of the lucky ones. Kailash Satyarthi, who has
been fighting child labour for the last two decades, raided the
factory - media in tow - where Sonia and many other children
worked. Sonia was finally given back her childhood. The crusade
Kailash has launched against child servitude in South Asia has seen
him coping with as many disheartening defeats as victories. By Soma
Wadhwa. Changemakers.net Journal. 2,000 words. 3. FEELINGS vs.
BRAINPOWER The mythical hero of Silicon Valley is the nerd - a
brain trapped inside a geeky-looking body. Research now suggests
otherwise : the way to get ahead in the age of the knowledge worker
is not through raw brainpower but by harnessing your emotions.
Interview with Daniel Goleman, author of the 1995 blockbuster
``Emotional Intelligence.'' By Jeff Greenwald. Wired magazine.
1,500 words. (Q&AMP;A format.)
_______________________________________________________________ 4.
INTIMATE ENGINEERING When Diane Kelly describes her unusual field
of study, her listeners, especially the men, tend to squirm. That's
because she spends her days doing experiments on the penises of
mammals from rats to armadillos. She is, to her knowledge, the
first and only scientist to study the biomechanics of the male
organ - in other words, the principles of engineering and physics
that enable the penis to do what it's supposed to do. By Mary
Roach. From Discover magazine. 1,000 words + photos. 
____________________________________________________________________
_____ 5. EUROPE, BEYOND THE BUREAUCRATS A lot has changed, in
everyday life, everyday attitudes, everyday assumptions and
expectations since Europe was only a geographical world. By Flora
Lewis. 800 words.
________________________________________________________ 6. STUDIES
FIND SIMPLER TREATMENT CUTS HIV INFECTIONS
</P>
<P>
   IN NEWBORNS Roughly 1,600 children become infected by HIV, the
virus that causes AIDS, each day (or about 600,000 a year.) Ninety
per cent of these children live in developing nations, most
contracting the infection from their mothers during pregnancy,
delivery or while breast-feeding. Treatment available in developed
nations can cut the risk of infection by about two-thirds, but it
is too expensive and complex to be provided in most developing
nations. Now a far shorter, simpler and less expensive treatment
protocol may have been found which could cut mother-to-child
transmission of HIV by one-third to one-half. By Michael McCarthy.
The Lancet News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
FROM MEDICAL TRIBUNE NEWS SERVICE : A. FIGHTING MENSTRUAL MIGRAINE
Special strategies can help women avoid menstrual migraines or
substantially lessen the severity of these headaches. 500 words. B.
DETECTING SKIN CANCER Underscoring the need for people at risk for
skin cancer to have regular checkups, researchers report that
doctors are more likely than patients to detect melanoma in its
earliest stages. 500 words. C. YOGURT MAY BRING DOWN BLOOD
CHOLESTEROL Many people eat yoghurt for its bone-fortifying
calcium, but new research suggests that it may be good for the
heart as well. 500 words. D. STRUCTURAL CHANGES IN HAIR COULD
SIGNAL BREAST CANCER Hair-sample tests could one day be used to
screen women for breast cancer. 500 words. 8. NEW THERAPY HELPING
SMOKERS QUIT A new approach combining an anti-depressant,
nicotine-replacement and counseling is sharply increasing the
chance of success of people who are trying to give up smoking. By
Holcomb B. Noble. New York Times Science Times. 1,500 words +
photo. Please fax to Paris 33.1.47.42.80.44 or 33.1.47.42.18.81 I
am interested in story no. ______ from summary 2525 Name :
____________________________ Publication :
_________________________ Country : ___________________ Fax :
___________________ Tel : ______________ email
