</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE CHOLERA LESSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; FOUR COLOR SLIDES ARE AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (1,000 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By CATHERINE DOLD &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Microbiologist Rita Colwell was at first excoriated by the
scientific world for her ideas about the behavior of the bacterium
that causes cholera. But research has borne out her notion that the
bacterium can lie dormant in the environment and then erupt.
Previously, scientists thought that a human host was necessary. Now
Colwell is focusing on helping to prevent major outbreaks of
cholera in poor communities with contaminated drinking water by
using a filter fashioned of sari cloth. Catherine Dold is a
free-lance writer who lives in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-CURBING-CHOLERA-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FIRE IN THE FLESH &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; ONE COLOR ILLUSTRATION IS AVAILABLE FREE &QL; 
 &UR; (900 words) &QL; 
 &UR; By ROBERT A. NORMAN &LR;  &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Norman, a dermatologist, was called in by a medical
colleague to help solve a medical mystery. The top layer of skin of
the 28-year-old patient was peeling off her entire body. Her body
was a blanket of red. She looked as if she had been badly burned in
a fire. Norman had seen the rare affliction twice before, though
never such a severe case. It was toxic epidermal necrolysis, or
TEN, an extreme allergic reaction to a drug that is fatal in 30
percent of cases. In this fascinating feature, Norman explains how
he treated the case.
</P>
<P>
   slugged: BC-LOSING-FLESH-NYTSF. Sent to category codes ``a''
general news and ``l'' lifestyle news.
</P>
<P>
   Thank you.
</P>
<P>
   _ The New York Times Syndicate.
