<P>
   Microbiologist Rita Colwell was at first excoriated by the
scientific world for her ideas about the behavior of the bacterium
that causes cholera. But research has borne out her notion that the
bacterium can lie dormant in the environment and then erupt.
Previously, scientists thought that a human host was necessary. Now
Colwell is focusing on helping to prevent major outbreaks of
cholera in poor communities with contaminated drinking water by
using a filter fashioned of sari cloth. Catherine Dold is a
free-lance writer who lives in Boulder, Colo.
</P>
