<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASSAU-CORRUPTION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COUNTY DEMOCRATIC CHIEF GUILTY IN BANKRUPTCY FRAUD 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By JOHN T. McQUISTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAUPPAUGE, N.Y. _ Stephen J. Sabbeth, the chairman of the Nassau
County Democratic Party, was found guilty Wednesday of bankruptcy
fraud, throwing his already splintered party into further disarray
as it immediately began to talk about his departure.
</P>
<P>
   While party members, on hearing word of his conviction, publicly
expressed sympathy for Sabbeth and his family, they said privately
that it was time for him to step down as party chairman even though
the charges against him were not related to the party itself.
</P>
<P>
   The calls for his departure came quickly after a federal jury
convicted Sabbeth of bank fraud as well as perjury and money
laundering in connection with a scheme to conceal $750,000 from his
bank creditors when his lumber business failed a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbeth was accused by the government of hiding the money in a
secret brokerage account under his wife's maiden name and under a
fake Social Security number. Although Sabbeth denied all the
charges, the jurors said on leaving U.S. District Court here this
afternoon that the evidence against him ``was overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   Sabbeth repeatedly denied the charges against him, asserting
that he had nothing to hide, that any money he put into the account
was rightfully his and that his broker had filled in the wrong
Social Security number.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbeth said the account was opened in his wife's name because
she wanted a separate account. He said that the banks to which he
owed money had been informed about the account and had records of
all the checks deposited to the account.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Denis R. Hurley of Federal District Court said that
Sabbeth, 51, of Old Brookville, could remain free on $50,000 bail.
He faces 70 to 87 months in prison under federal sentencing
guidelines, according to Seth Marvin, the chief prosecutor in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   Sabbeth's wife, Carole, 54, is also awaiting sentencing. Mrs.
Sabbeth pleaded guilty in December to two counts of perjury as part
of a plea agreement. She had initially asserted that she alone had
opened the account in her maiden name, Carole Fiore; that her
husband did not know about it, and that she did not know the
stockbroker who handled the account.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
