<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7453 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DRINKING-AGES05-COX     03-04 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRINKING-AGES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chihuahua governor pushes ban on boozing by U.S. youth
 &HT;    By Dave Harmon
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CIUDAD JUAREZ, Chihuahua _ Crossing the Rio Grande to carouse in
Mexico has been a rite of passage for border teen-agers for
generations. The governor of Chihuahua wants to clamp down on
Juarez's party-all-night image by adopting the U.S. drinking age _
but only for Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Patricio Martinez, governor of this northern Mexico state, has
proposed keeping the legal minimum drinking age for Mexicans at 18
but raising it to 21 for U.S. residents. Other Mexican states would
not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso, meanwhile, will try to deter underage drinkers by
posting police officers at the four international bridges to look
for intoxicated youths as they return from Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The main target of Martinez's proposal is the Juarez club
district, where bars that offer unlimited drinks for an $8 or $9
cover charge draw flocks of high school and college students from
El Paso, Las Cruces and other nearby cities in Texas and New
Mexico. Students say fliers advertising ``drink and drown''
specials in Juarez clubs circulate in El Paso high schools and on
the campus of New Mexico State University in Las Cruces.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge problem,'' said Del Chavez, administrator of the
El Paso Mothers Against Drunk Driving chapter. ``If someone's got
the money to buy, they will sell it to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's administration wants to target bar owners rather than
the drinkers. Instead of a new state law, the governor's office
wants to use the state's control over liquor licenses to force the
clubs to comply. Businesses that serve alcohol would have to check
patrons' identification, and those who serve to underage Americans
could be slapped with fines or forced to close, said Aurelio Licon,
the governor's representative in Juarez.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's office has already used this method to cut back the
hours of the clubs, which until recently stayed open until 5 or 6
a.m. to bring in after-hours crowds from the United States. They
must now close at 2 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   Licon said the dual drinking age would be the first of its kind
in Mexico. The governor's office is still studying how to implement
the policy but wants to start it as soon as possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although young Americans spend a lot of money in Juarez, Licon
said: ``We don't want that type of spending; we don't want that
kind of tourism. We want family tourism.''
</P>
<P>
   At one popular Juarez club last week, the doorman watched
students from El Paso and New Mexico filter in on a slow Thursday
night. He said the new governor _ who reclaimed the governorship
for the ruling party last fall and immediately announced a
crackdown on various social ills _ is just pulling a publicity
stunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't enforce it,'' said the man, who refused to give his
name because he feared the government would retaliate against his
club. ``Only the congress can change the law. It's a lot of noise
on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Dangers
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, New Mexico State student Philip Muller, who had made the
45-minute drive from Las Cruces to Juarez with about 40 fraternity
brothers, most of them underage, said he first came to the Juarez
bars when he was 14. No one asked his age, he said, ``and I've been
coming ever since.''
</P>
<P>
   Muller, now 21, said that when he was an El Paso high school
student, Juarez bar owners would pay students $1 for every 20
friends they brought in. He said he and his friends passed out
homemade fliers in the school halls. He said he still sees similar
fliers on his college campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father used to do this when he was 16,'' he said. ``I guess
that's why we come here, so we can all have a good time and not get
arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   But getting arrested isn't the only danger. Roger Maier,
spokesman for the U.S. Customs Service in El Paso, said Customs
agents who work the bridges sometimes have to assist people who
need medical attention after getting beaten up or stabbed _ usually
during alcohol-fed altercations.
</P>
<P>
   That worries El Paso Mayor Carlos Ramirez, who supports the
Chihuahua governor's plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a problem with the idea that some bar and club owners
across the river consider getting our young people drunk economic
development,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez said he and Martinez discussed their common problem in
Austin six weeks ago when they met during Gov. George W. Bush's
inaugural celebration.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican governor was tired of the fighting, drunken driving
and general disorder that spilled from the clubs. The El Paso mayor
was worried about the safety of his city's young people and other
residents who might cross paths with an inebriated young driver.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said he was pleasantly surprised at Martinez's bold
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bar owners and the disco owners are not going to like it,
and I applaud his stance,'' Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who became El Paso's mayor in June, said the city will
send police officers, and perhaps some volunteers, to the four
international bridges next week as spring break begins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be looking for kids who are obviously underage
and very drunk,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those who are under 21 and come over the bridge intoxicated will
have their parents called to pick them up and may face a fine,
Ramirez said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
