<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7457 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RTP-GOODNIGHT05-COX     03-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-GOODNIGHT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAS chief guiding company to become a solutions vendor
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARY, N.C. _ Jim Goodnight, SAS Institute Inc.'s president, is
rich but not flashy.
</P>
<P>
   His fortune is estimated at $3 billion, ranking him as the
wealthiest North Carolinian. But he drives a 1996 Buick Roadmaster,
spacious enough for his lanky 6-foot-5-inch frame. Hanging from his
key chain is one of those electronic-sensoring tags that rings up
discounted groceries at Harris Teeter.
</P>
<P>
   Trained as a computer programmer at North Carolina State
University, the son of a Wilmington, N.C., hardware store owner
co-founded SAS in 1976. Intensely private and publicity-shy to the
point of seeming disinterested, even bored, Goodnight, 56, recently
lifted the veil surrounding himself and the nation's largest
privately held software manufacturer, based in Cary, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with staff writer Chris Burritt, Goodnight talks
about SAS' future, the Microsoft challenge, his purchase of Midway
Airlines and making money.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You have been described as a visionary. What will SAS'
business look like in the year 2005?
</P>
<P>
   A: Our goal over the next few years is to turn into more of a
solutions vendor, one that solves business problems that our
customers have. We have for so many years been more of a toolmaker,
making tools that customers can use to put solutions together
themselves to solve problems. That aspect of SAS will always be
there, but we are moving more now into what I like to call the
knowledge ware, not just the software but the knowledge that goes
with it, to help install product, get it up and running to help
solve problems.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You talk as though you are becoming a consultant to business,
more than a software maker.
</P>
<P>
   A: We will still make software, but it will be more specifically
tailored to specific solutions and requirements of our users. By
2005, Microsoft will have probably put all other software
manufacturers out of business. That is their main objective, their
main goal.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Including you?
</P>
<P>
   A: Certainly they have targeted us. They are going after our
multidimensional database business. They have changed their
product, and, guess what, they are giving it away free as part of
their SQL Server (a database product). It is a typical tactic ...
something that other people are charging for, give it away for
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On the U.S. Justice Department's lawsuit against Microsoft,
what side do you come down on?
</P>
<P>
   A: I would have to come down on Justice's. They are now giving
away a product that we are charging for. ... They have done this
over the years. ... The list is a mile long of these kinds of
activities that Microsoft has done. They have used their enormous
revenues that they've gained from their operating systems, have put
out of business spreadsheet makers and word processing people, now
they are moving up the food chain to the (Web) browser area.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Where are you on the food chain, how high up?
</P>
<P>
   A: We are reasonably high up, but we are climbing fast
(laughing) trying to get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Q: On another topic, did you ever consider going public to raise
funds for SAS' expansion?
</P>
<P>
   A: We would not go public to raise funds. We have funds.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why have you remained a privately held company?
</P>
<P>
   A: The head of one of the biggest banking concerns in New York
said to me at dinner one night, ``Jim, if you don't need the money,
don't go public.'' I agreed with him. It is an enormous pain. There
are quarterly demands about whether or not you make profits each
quarter, or whether it was more than it was in the quarter a year
ago. I don't care about stuff like that. Our focus is on a year
out, two years out, trying to deliver solutions for our customers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When Midway Airlines was faltering at Raleigh-Durham
International Airport, you bought control of it in 1997. Why?
</P>
<P>
   A: John Sall (another of SAS' founders) and I bought controlling
interest in it. It was on the block, and we were looking at the
potential of losing that airline to another group who planned to
take the planes and move them somewhere else. We felt like we
needed it as part of our business and for the Triangle area. Before
Midway, this was an American hub, and we certainly got used to the
convenience of not having to fly through Atlanta any time we went
out of the South.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why is it that the software business is so profitable for
companies such as yours?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you finish your research and development, you stamp it
out. It's not as though you have to build an assembly plant. The
biggest expense is people.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
