<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7458 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RTP-SAS05-COX     03-04 1387
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RTP-SAS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Software firm's perks help cut employee stress
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARY, N.C. _ The fitness staff at SAS Institute Inc., the big
software maker, was torn over hardware.
</P>
<P>
   Should they buy more exercise bikes or rowing machines?
</P>
<P>
   They opted for a half-dozen rowing machines, concluding that
SAS' computer programmers who spend hours at keyboards would
benefit from the backward motion of rowing. By contrast, leaning
over the handlebars of a bike replicates hunching over a computer.
</P>
<P>
   Such seemingly small decisions are a big deal at SAS, where many
of the 2,700 employees in Cary, N.C., work as programmers of
statistical software. With sales this year forecast to reach $1
billion, the nation's largest privately held software producer
sells to thousands of businesses, universities and government
agencies worldwide _ including Atlanta giants Coca-Cola, Delta Air
Lines, BellSouth, Home Depot and Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   In a setting of such rapid growth and highly technical work, SAS
seems a natural breeding ground for the type of mind-numbing,
productivity-sapping stress that infects much of corporate America.
But SAS officials have discovered that many of the perks the
company uses to recruit and retain hard-to-find programmers have
proved helpful in reducing employee stress.
</P>
<P>
   People are clamoring to work at SAS. It has more than 21,000 job
applications on file. Yearly turnover hovers around 4 percent,
compared with a software industry average of 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, publications including Working Mother, Fortune,
Business Week and Mother Jones have ranked the company as one of
the nation's best places to work.
</P>
<P>
   SAS is building an indoor swimming pool on its bucolic corporate
campus, adding yet another fitness option that includes yoga,
massage, aerobics, basketball, weight training, golf and tennis
lessons, and Tai Chi, a form of martial arts designed to reduce
stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to give people the chance to pop off the top of the
steam kettle,'' said David Russo, SAS' vice president of human
resources. ``This type of work is intellectually intense. It causes
a fatigue that is hard to rest up from.''
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, workplace stress is linked to computers. An
estimated 20 million Americans work in occupations where computers
are a primary tool. More than 40 percent of households have
computers.
</P>
<P>
   As computer usage has soared, so has the incidence of repetitive
stress injury, a broad category of ailments of the back, neck,
arms, wrists and hands. SAS isn't immune to such problems.
</P>
<P>
   Every week, an estimated 20 employees visit the company's
4-year-old ergonomics lab, equipped with an assortment of
odd-looking chairs, keyboards and mice intended to prevent
stress-related injuries. Stress also contributes to a host of
emotional problems, including depression, anxiety and anger.
</P>
<P>
   SAS offers at least a partial cure for this worsening ill of
corporate America. The company's broad array of amenities seeks to
relieve stress related not only to computers but also to everyday
life.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, SAS has been so inwardly focused for so many years that
it has something of a mysterious image. That's especially true
among people who have never ventured past the gatehouse entrance
onto the company's campus, tucked on 200 wooded acres on I-40
between Raleigh and Research Triangle Park.
</P>
<P>
   A ``23 mph'' sign just inside the entrance suggests that things
here are a bit different. The campus is dotted by futuristic
sculptures, which seem to pop up overnight at the whim of SAS
President Jim Goodnight and his wife, Ann.
</P>
<P>
   Closer to reality are SAS managers such as Stuart and Suzy
Nisbet. Both are 34, a year older than the average age of company
employees. One of their biggest challenges is balancing work and
home, and SAS helps them do that.
</P>
<P>
   The company's flexible, 35-hour workweek allows the Nisbets to
trade off duties, such as getting their two daughters ready for
school.
</P>
<P>
   Starting as infants, both attended SAS' on-campus Montessori
school, reasonably priced at $250 a month per child.
</P>
<P>
   Nicole, 6, now attends elementary school. But her sister,
3-year-old Rachel, frequently eats with her parents in the
company-subsidized cafeteria, the Pennies Cafe, where pianist
Brenda Bruce taps out the themes from ``The Phantom of the Opera''
and ``Barney'' on a baby grand.
</P>
<P>
   The Nisbets exercise at the fitness center several days a week.
If they or their children are sick, they visit the on-campus family
practice medical clinic, which is free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The loyalty that people build up over things like that goes
beyond words,'' said Stuart Nisbet, a graphics software manager.
</P>
<P>
   Nisbet lives with his wife and daughters in Prestonwood and
belongs to the Cary subdivision's 54-hole private golf club. Both
are owned by Goodnight, who gives discounts to SAS employees who
buy homes in the subdivision and join the club. Cary Academy, a
private high school started by Goodnight and his wife, Ann,
provides tuition breaks to the children of SAS employees.
</P>
<P>
   Once or twice a month, Nisbet receives phone calls from rival
software companies, offering him jobs in Silicon Valley paying as
much as 40 percent more than he makes at SAS. So far, he has
resisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``In terms of quality of life and lifestyle,'' Nisbet said,
``there is nothing I've seen that compares with what we have
here.''
</P>
<P>
   SAS has evolved into a sort of stress-busting laboratory in the
nearly two decades since co-founders Goodnight and John Sall
attached an indoor racquetball court to their first building.
</P>
<P>
   At North Carolina State University in nearby Raleigh, Goodnight
earned a doctorate in statistics, and he fell in love with
programming. That spurred him and three partners to develop the
software that led in 1976 to the creation of SAS, which stands for
Statistical Analysis System.
</P>
<P>
   A primary job of SAS' software is referred to as ``data
warehousing and data mining.'' It sorts huge volumes of information
_ from grocery purchases to U.S. Census data to credit card
transactions _ and organizes it in ways that customers, such as
Coca-Cola or Home Depot, can interpret to drum up new business or
forecast sales.
</P>
<P>
   As the company has grown, Goodnight has insisted that some of
the oldest perks remain. Break rooms contain free soft drinks,
juices, coffee and tea. They're stocked with fresh fruit on Monday,
M&AMP;Ms on Wednesday, and doughnuts and pastries on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight employs an artist in residence, Holly Brewster Jones,
whose abstract watercolors are scattered among SAS' 20 buildings.
Inside several of the buildings are fountains and atriums decorated
by trees and flowers.
</P>
<P>
   In choosing the architectural footprint for SAS' newest office
buildings, Goodnight insisted on putting patios between every two
floors. They're intended as meeting places for staff, reminding him
of the friendliness among employees when SAS consisted only of
Building A, a two-story rectangle of brown bricks and dark glass.
</P>
<P>
   Employees consume 22 tons of M&AMP;Ms (peanut and plain) a year,
hinting at the scope of SAS' package of amenities. Human resources
chief Russo said the company gladly invests in perks because it
contributes to a stable, well-trained work force.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, if turnover were a problem, SAS would spend big
sums on training, Russo said. The cost per employee could reach 2
1/2 times SAS' average salary of $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight dismisses the suggestion that SAS avoids paying top
wages under the guise of tax benefits to employees. ``We don't pay
less,'' he said. ``We are in the middle of Research Triangle
salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   He is just now considering a plan to provide SAS workers with
stock options, a highly lucrative perk for employees of many
publicly traded technology companies. Granting options would allow
SAS to sell shares to the public but not enough to strip Goodnight
of control.
</P>
<P>
   For 22 consecutive years, the company has contributed to a
profit-sharing plan for employees and doled out discretionary
bonuses. In some cases, that year-end perk pads employees' pay by
20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think long and hard before they go somewhere else,''
Goodnight said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
