</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCNEELY-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Critics want to force Bush to define his terms
 &HT;    By Don McNeely
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Monday morning, teachers rallied in front of the
Capitol to protest teacher pay in Texas, which ranks 38th among the
states.
</P>
<P>
   That afternoon, Interfaith organizations from throughout the
state baked in the sun on the Capitol steps, trying to persuade top
state officials to spend more money on schools that serve students
from poor families.
</P>
<P>
   Other organizations are urging legislators _ and Gov. George W.
Bush _ to take action to qualify more than 1 million uninsured
Texas kids for federally subsidized health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, Democrats in the Texas Senate asked for a rare
interruption of the Senate's proceedings for a brief Democratic
Caucus meeting. The result: a slight delay in approving Gov. Bush's
three most recent nominees for University of Texas board of
regents. But Senate business was held up just long enough to make a
point.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Royce West (D-Dallas), an African-American, noted in a
floor speech that the governor failed to nominate an
AfricanAmerican to fill any of the board positions. That is despite
the fact that Texas is rapidly reaching the point where a majority
of its citizens are members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   While all the senators except West voted for the governor's
nominees, some of their speeches aimed to put Bush on notice that
words alone are not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Taken collectively, the groups in front of the Capitol and the
Democratic legislators are putting a spotlight on Gov. Bush's claim
to be a ``compassionate conservative.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people inside and outside Texas expect Bush's continuing
exploration of the presidency to end in a decision to run. And that
makes his attitudes on Texas issues, such as how much to spend for
schools, teachers and health insurance for kids, a matter for
national attention.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush has made reaching out to Hispanics and
African-Americans a major part of his political journey and
education his No. 1 priority, West questioned why Bush can't make
room for one African-American among the nine members charting UT's
course.
</P>
<P>
   The 140-day biennial session, already a third over, will be a
laboratory for measuring the governor's attitudes on some critical
areas, measuring his compassion against his conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   Running for president in 1992, Bill Clinton took on some
powerful groups within the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton advocated free trade before the United Auto Workers
union. Before the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People, Clinton criticized what he said were racist remarks
by an African-American rap singer.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Begala, a Texan who just left as a top adviser to President
Clinton, says he's watching to see if Bush will take on some of the
more conservative elements in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge to the 'compassionate conservative' will be to
put some meaning behind the label,'' Begala said.
</P>
<P>
   At his meeting with Texas reporters Tuesday, Bush tried to do
that: ``It's conservative to cut taxes,'' Bush said, while it's
compassionate ``to make sure that every child (who needs it) gets
extra help.''
</P>
<P>
   Karen Hughes, his spokeswoman, called Bush a conservative who
wears a smile rather than a frown, who says what he's for rather
than what he's against.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has advocated shifting more of the burden for paying for
public schools from local school districts to the state. He has
called for more attention to teaching children to read. He wants to
stop social promotions when students' work is not up to par.
</P>
<P>
   But how much Bush is willing to advocate spending, or allow to
be spent, on those and other programs will increasingly receive
attention not just from teacher organizations and other groups, but
from national news reporters and political pundits. And from other
presidential candidates and voters.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's short-term effort is to prove to Republican primary
voters he's conservative enough to justify the GOP nomination, the
depth of his compassion may decide how many additional votes he can
attract in the general election from Democrats and independents, as
well as from moderate and liberal Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
