   BOOKS
</P>
<P>
   SKUBE-ON-BOOKS _ One brave scholar, David Stoll, an
anthropologist at Middlebury College, deserves a prize, not the
Nobel perhaps but something on the order of the Purple Heart.
``Rigoberta Menchu and the Story of All Poor Guatemalans''
demythologizes a Mayan woman whose presence elicits tears on
campuses and a book that has been translated into 12
languages.(Skube, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) FOR SUNDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-REVIEW-PRETTYGIRL _ Review of ``The Diary of Vaslav
Nijinsky.'' (Brock, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BOOK-NOTES _ Pat Conroy is the winner of the first award
honoring Stanley Lindberg, editor of the Georgia review. The former
Atlanta author also picks up a Grand Master award at
Birmingham-Southern on March 13. Allan Gurganus now prefers writing
novellas to lengthy tomes about Confederate widows. Ben Affleck and
Matt Damon set to produce movie version of book about Georgia war
hero Damon Gause. (O'Briant, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) ETA: 6
p.m. skedded to run3/4
</P>
<P>
   MOVIE NEWS/REVIEWS
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-TEENS _ Remember when the scariest thing about '90s
teenagers was the music they listened to and the body parts they
pierced? Suddenly, Marilyn Manson and nipple rings seem downright
quaint. What we really have to fear now is teens' all-consuming
power at the movie box office. It's quickly turning anyone over 21
into human Betamaxes: Movies simply don't fit them anymore. Like so
many successful movie genres, the teen flicks all may seem somewhat
familiar. They also might seem somewhat foreign to anyone over 21.
So, herewith a simple guide to the movies taking over your
multiplex. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). WITH COLOR
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 7
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-LOCK _ People are calling ``Lock, Stock &AMP; 2 Smoking
Barrels'' a British version of Quentin Tarantino. But
writer-director Guy Ritchie and two of his stars - Jason Flemyng
and Jason Statham - are too busy touring the States to worry about
labels. They're also learning big, unwieldy words out of
dictionaries. And they're insisting that, despite prevailing
gossip, Madonna is not Guy's new girlfriend. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: EMBARGOED UNTIL SUNDAY, MARCH 7
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ANALYZE _ Review of ``Analyze This,'' a comedy about a
psychiatrist (Billy Crystal), whose No. 1 patient is an insecure
mob boss (Robert De Niro.) Grade: B. (StMurray, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-ANALYZETHIS _ Review of ``Analyze This.'' Robert De Niro
is a New York Mob boss suffering an anxiety attack; Billy Crystal
is his therapist. (Garcia, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-GENERAL _ Review of ``The General,'' an Irish crime drama
shot in black and white and directed by John Boorman. Cast includes
Brendan Gleeson, Adrian Dunbar, Jon Voight, Brenda Fricker and
Eamonn Owens. Grade: A-. (Ringel, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-THEGENERAL _ Review of ``The General.'' Director John
Boorman (``Deliverance'') offers this black-and-white, fact-based
tale of a Dublin mastermind thief who likes to make the cops look
foolish. (Macor, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-CRUEL _ Review of ``Cruel Intentions.'' Another mean teen
movie. Ryan Phillippe and Sarah Michelle Gellar play bickering
step-siblings who, together, quietly control much of the social
lives of the students in an affluent NY prep school. They make a
bet over whether he can bed a fellow student who is a virgin.
(Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MOVIES-MINIREVIEWS _ Mini reviews of all currently playing
movies. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   REVIEW-MYNAMEISJOE _ Review of ``My Name Is Joe.'' Mullan won
the best actor award at Cannes, playing a recovering alcoholic in
this film from Ken Loach (``Land and Freedom''). (Garcia, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
