</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COX NEWS SERVICE FEATURES BUDGET
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   These feature stories are moving today to clients of the New
York Times News Service. Stories are for release Friday, March 5,
1999, unless otherwise embargoed.
</P>
<P>
   So specialty editors won't have to look at every day's budget,
Cox's features budgets have daily themes according tothis schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Monday for Tuesday: Technology
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday for Wednesday: Automotive
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday for Thursday: Food, CD reviews, video reviews
</P>
<P>
   TODAY: Movie reviews, travel, books and fashion
</P>
<P>
   Friday for Saturday: Religion, science &AMP; health, and home &AMP;
garden
</P>
<P>
   In addition, separate budgets move daily with spot news, sports,
business and commentary.
</P>
<P>
   Stories are moving in the category they're listed under. Stories
moving to duplicate categories are marked. An ETA is given if a
story will move after 8 p.m. Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   If you have questions or need a resend, please call CoxNet, the
Cox News Service, at 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   SAVE TIME: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available for
purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   MONICA-RATINGS _ How many people tuned in to Barbara Walter's
interview with Monica Lewinsky, local and national overnight
ratings. (Kloer, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the lifestyle (l) and general news (a)
categories.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-MONICA _ LONDON _ Former White House intern Monica
Lewinsky comes to Britsh television live on Thursday. And we'll be
watching. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Moving in the lifestyle (l) and international (i)
categories.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-BIRTHDAY _ People, the ``mother of all human interest
magazines,'' turns 25 years old Friday (March 5). It's the magazine
that most shrewdly anticipated and capitalized on our national
obsession with celebrity. People was a punchline in ``The Big
Chill,'' when it served as an emblem for empty fluff (''It's just
good investigative journalism'' deadpanned Jeff Goldblum, who
played a People reporter), but, in fact, has expertly gauged what
we want to read about. With 33 million readers and spinoffs such as
InStyle and Teen People going strong, and ongoing expansion into
television and cyberspace, the franchise looks durable. A look at
the People phenomenon. (Emerson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ANNIE-REVIEW _ NEW YORK _ Review of ``Annie Get Your Gun'' with
Bernadette Peters. (Hulbert, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
