<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7487 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET     03-04 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, March 4, 1999      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, please call Tim Spence at
202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   UGANDA-ADAMS (San Francisco) _ Linda Adams of Alamo, Calif.,
tells how she escaped the nightmare massacre in Uganda this week in
which Rwandan renegades kidnapped her and 31 others who were there
to find the rare mountain gorillas in the mountains. The rebels
marched 14 of them into the hills and hacked eight of them to
death. By MICHAEL DOUGAN.
</P>
<P>
   READING-TESTS (San Francisco) _ While students across the
country are showing gains in reading, California schoolchildren
rank near the bottom on a state-by-state report card. The 1998
National Assessment of Educational Progress shows that 52 percent
of California's fourth-graders can't read at the most basic level.
By JULIAN GUTHRIE.
</P>
<P>
   HIV-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ When the pain got unbearable,
Steve Iacovino sought the help of a University of California at San
Francisco surgeon. But he declined to operate. Later Iacovino found
another doctor and underwent shoulder replacement surgery. Now, he
is suing the UCSF surgeon and the university, charging that they
turned him down because he is HIV positive. By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SF-SPENDING (San Francisco) _ The days of the city hall spending
spree here may be over. San Francisco's top financial wizards say
that if the level of government service remains constant and the
revenue stream slows, San Francisco will face a $26 million deficit
in two years. By RACHEL GORDON.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE (Albany, N.Y.) _ Revered, reviled, renewed, tatooed and
debunked. As if that weren't enough, now Barbie turns 40 on
Tuesday. Don't expect a midlife crisis. Crow's-feet don't sell.
Maybe a career change. It's Barbie's favorite catharsis! She's had
75, from surgeon to ambassador to rock star. Actually, ole Babs is
probably closer to 56 (Remember, she was a teenage model when she
debuted in March 1959 for $3.) By KATE GURNETTA. (For Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   BARBIE-DEMON (Albany, N.Y.) _ I love my girls. And they love
Barbie. This isn't easy for me to admit; I'm no fan of the woman.
Fate forces me to accept that Barbie shares our home with us. By
AMY BIANCOLLIA. (For Sunday.)
</P>
<P>
   KIDS'-MUSEUM (Pittsfield, Mass.) _ The Berkshire Museum, home to
fine art and sculptures and hermit crabs and snakes, is now
exhibiting childhood memories. It is a hands-on trip through years
past where today's children can start making their own fond
remembrances, and where adults can relive theirs. By MARK McGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   With: KIDS'-MUSEUM-QUIZ.
</P>
<P>
   SUNDANCE-QUEST (Albany, N.Y.) _ Call it the RV ride from hell. A
fledgling filmmaker and a pair of move-buff friends from New York
braved blizzards and mechanical problems on a trek to crash the
Sundance Film Festival in Colorado in January. But their
problematic journey in a 1982 Winnebago may be the stuff of a
documentary. By STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   LEVI-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ A former Levi Strauss &AMP; Co.
manager claims in a lawsuit she was fired for cooperating in an
investigation of two supervisors who promoted women with whom they
were allegedly having affairs. Patricia Ogden accuses the company
of retaliation, age and sex discrimination, sexual harassment and
breach of contract. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ Monica Lewinsky now says she
wants to make a ``contribution to society.'' Contribution? She
already made it. She filled the great conversational void for a
full year, fed the voracious media maw, created new networks,
empowered pundits, contributed to the growth of the Internet and
helped grind the Republican Party into the dust. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   SALTER-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ You may love e-mail. Your
friends and associates may love it. Corporate, academic and
governing America obviously love it and run on it. But I don't like
it. I am quite happy with the two methods of communication I grew
up with: letters and phone calls. By STEPHANIE SALTER.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ We live in a big, complex society
where about a million Americans a year have problems so severe that
they're forced into bankruptcy. And, if they happen to have your
name, their problems can become your problems, too. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
