<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSEANNE BARELY GOES SKIN DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This week's National Enquirer seemed full of promise. Roseanne
is guest editor. That's thrilling, of course. And the cover story
really set my pulse pounding: stars' beauty secrets.
</P>
<P>
   I've been collecting choice celebrity beauty secrets for years.
Here's one of my favorites, from the Enquirer, circa 1986: Morgan
Fairchild uses mayonnaise as a hair conditioner. She rinses with
lukewarm water, because hot water curdles the eggs. And she always
uses real mayonnaise, not sandwich spread, which makes hair sticky
and hard to manage.
</P>
<P>
   Here's another: Once a week Doris Day coats her entire body with
Vaseline, dons flannel pajamas and then goes to bed, presumably
alone. She claims the Vaseline routine keeps her skin soft. This
one is from ``Doris Day: Her Own Story,'' published in the late
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   These secrets, fascinating though they may be, are dated. So
when I saw the Enquirer cover story I welcomed the opportunity to
add to my collection. The subject seemed seemed a perfect target
for Roseanne's angry, feminist brand of humor.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago Roseanne was guest editor of a special women's
issue of the New Yorker. With all due respect to that distinguished
weekly, editing the Enquirer seems more Roseanne's metier. In her
editor's notes she writes that while she's had her differences with
the Enquirer over the years, she's always been a faithful reader.
</P>
<P>
   Roseanne promises ``The wildest edition ever _ I'm in charge!''
But the results are disappointing. The high point may be a
first-pastry account by a Twinkie that claims it was nibbled by
Calista Flockhart (`` . . . she nipped a few crumbs from my end and
put me down . . . I'm the luckiest Twinkie alive!'')
</P>
<P>
   The stars' beauty secrets story doesn't reflect a shred of
Roseanne's attitude. It's an adoring look at 20 celebrities
Roseanne apparently is trying to flatter into appearing on her talk
show. I searched the text for tips in the Vaseline vein, but in
every case, the ``secret'' of the star's beauty is being born
gorgeous.
</P>
<P>
   Gwyneth Paltrow has ``luminous . . . flawless'' skin. Cindy
Crawford is ``a natural beauty.'' Thandie Newton ``could wear a
sack and still look stunning.'' Cameron Diaz describes herself as,
``a cheeseurger junkie, a salty greasy girl. . . . I give every
French fry a fair chance.'' Eat up, Cameron. In just a few years
you'll be smearing that grease on your outside, a la Doris Day.
</P>
<P>
   Roseanne's Enquirer issue had only a couple of collectible
secrets. 1) Jaclyn Smith uses a different cream rinse on her hair
every day. 2) Kim Basinger washes her hair with Evian water. I was
hoping for something more, perhaps involving some of the popular
new condiments, balsamic vinegar, maybe, or Inner Beauty hot sauce,
although I realize that in Hollywood only outer beauty matters.
</P>
<P>
   It's possible celebrity beauty secrets are all but obsolete in
an age when the rich and famous rely on plastic surgery to maintain
their looks. Roseanne herself has no beauty secrets. She lays it
all out in a two-page photo essay in which she looks back at her
``amazing 10-year transformation'' from 230-pound TV star to
160-pound TV star. The diets. The breast reduction. The tummy tuck.
The face-lift. The eyelid-lift. Most recently, the Fobi gastric
bypass operation, a radical procedure that drastically reduces the
amount of food a person can eat. Roseanne's transformation is
illustrated with photographs of herself from the Enquirer, some of
them extremely unflattering. No wonder she can't be funny about
stars' beauty secrets. In her business, a woman's looks are no
joke. They're the only thing that matters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a columnist with The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1308EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
