<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-MONICA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA, UNABASHED, SHOWS STAR POTENTIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A largely unsympathetic nation waited for Monica Lewinsky to
portray herself as a victim _ of the president, of Linda Tripp, of
the media, of Ken Starr. We waited and waited, but in a two-hour
episode of ABC's ``20/20'' Wednesday night, the 25-year-old refused
to play the fragile descendent of Marilyn Monroe. Despite a few
teary moments, and one or two embarrassed blushes, she presented
herself as a strong, articulate, self-aware, sexual, and completely
unashamed adult. She has compared herself to Princess Diana in the
British press recently, but for America she chose to position
herself a bit more toward the Madonna end of the spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   And so ``That Woman'' did not attempt to be like Marlo Thomas's
``That Girl.'' She came off more like the racy Fox network
nighttime soap characters played by Shannen Doherty and
Tiffani-Amber Thiessen, actresses whom joking journalists have cast
as Monica Lewinsky in a hypothetical movie. With her newly tamed
hair, her clear and animated eyes, and her sparkling teeth, she
rarely pretended to be suffering during her extended ``20/20''
moment of revelation. At points, her enthusiasm even crossed the
line from poised and honest to exhibitionistic. ``Yes!!'' she said,
laughing, when Barbara Walters calls her a passionate woman.
``Yes!!'' she said, laughing, when Walters asks if she worried
about being caught in flagrante in the Oval Office. Phone sex?
``It's fun,'' she said, laughing. ``He's a good kisser,'' she said,
laughing. If Lewinsky has thought much about the Americans who view
her as a Devil in a Blue Dress, she didn't play to that audience.
And with comments like, ``I don't have the feelings of self-worth
that a woman should have,'' and talk of her psychotropic drug
perscription, she second-guessed those who might try to label her
as painfully deluded or depressed.
</P>
<P>
   Seemingly born to thrive in a tell-all culture, Lewinsky made
Barbara Walters's job extremely easy. Walters had only to lob her
expected questions, inserting motherly comments like, ``That was
probably very painful,'' and Lewinsky eagerly shared everything
from intimate sexual details to suicidal thoughts. And that is most
likely how Lewinsky wanted it. Yes, Lewinsky was a fantastic
``get'' for Walters, but Walters was no small get for Lewinsky, who
benefited from Walters's humanizing touch and her unwillingness to
be openly adversarial. Walters was the best possible chaperone into
America's living rooms, just as Oprah Winfrey once provided entree
for an image-battered Michael Jackson. If there was a hint of the
cheap odor of ``The Jerry Springer Show'' in Lewinsky's first TV
interview (``Women Who Fooled Around with the President and Liked
It''), the flowery perfume of Walters managed to smell a little
stronger.
</P>
<P>
   But only a little stronger. The massively promoted event _ which
ABC scheduled on the last night of the sweeps period _ presented an
embarrassment of rich commentary on ``the way we live now,'' as
Anthony Trollope put it. It was the quintessential moment of
1990s-style American self-reinvention, with Lewinsky trying to lift
the curtain for herself on a second act. I kept thinking of Martin
Scorsese's ``King of Comedy,'' which seemed sharply satirical back
in 1983. In the America of that comedy, fame, and infamy were so
inextricably joined at the hip that a desperate kidnapper easily
reinvented himself as a beloved talk-show host. In 1999, Scorsese's
movie is very old news indeed. Courtroom television has turned into
the equivalent of ``Star Search,'' with shady folks like Joey
Buttafuoco and John Wayne Bobbitt and all the performers in ``The
O.J. Show'' emerging as the big ``gets'' on newsmagazines and the
lead characters in made-for-TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky is the latest in that family of peculiar icons. With
her comfort on camera, could she become a TV celebrity? With her
penchant for self-revelation, could she host a talk show? With her
relentless bubbliness, could she replace Mary Hart on
``Entertainment Tonight''? With her budding legal mind, could she
become a commentator on CNN, MSNBC, etc.? Sure, in this day and
age, and with her self-possession, she probably could _ but let's
hope she doesn't. Let's hope that, once the newsmagazines move onto
other stories of sex and betrayal, and once her book falls off the
best-seller lists, Monica Lewinsky takes her millions of dollars
and goes in search of a (itals)very private(unitals) life. We owe
her _ and ourselves _ as much.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1309EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7564 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      03-04 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEOPLE: 25 YEARS OF CELEBRITIES IN SOFT FOCUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As its founding editor Richard Stolley once noted, everything
about the debut People magazine cover was wrong. The subject,
actress Mia Farrow, wasn't looking into the camera and her new
movie, ``The Great Gatsby,'' hadn't even hit the theaters yet.
Meanwhile, in 1974, the mere idea that ``august Time Inc.'' would
launch a celebrity glossy was ``something of a scandal,'' recalls
media analyst Tom Rosenstiel.
</P>
<P>
   This week, as it celebrates a quarter-century of stargazing with
a 336-page issue and a two-hour ``Dateline NBC'' special, People
can be forgiven for musing wondrously over what it has wrought. Not
only is the magazine _ with a 3.64 million circulation and annual
ad revenues of nearly two-thirds of a billion dollars _ a stunning
success. As Barbara Walters's mega-hyped interview with Monica
Lewinsky proves, it has also helped transform the media universe.
</P>
<P>
   People's role as the crossover act that brought celebrity
journalism from the shadowy scandal sheets to the mainstream media
is evident in everything from ABC's Monica-mania to the
glitz-conscious New Yorker under Tina Brown, from Newsweek cover
stories on Don Imus and Nicole Kidman to the gossipy Life pages of
USA Today.
</P>
<P>
   People ``made celebrity journalism more respectable and it also
proved that it could be done elegantly and be enormously
successful,'' says Rosenstiel, vice chairman of the Committee of
Concerned Journalists.
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as People celebrates 25 years of exceeding expectations
with its brand of literate celebrity journalism, some wonder
whether it is a primary culprit for the voyeurism now preoccupying
the media.
</P>
<P>
   The special 25th-anniversary edition of People skillfully
follows the magazine's formula of ``extraordinary people doing
ordinary things and ordinary people doing extraordinary things.''
The issue updates the fleetingly famous such as Patty Hearst,
Lorena Bobbitt, and Rodney King. It cheers ``profiles in courage''
like the HIV-infected Magic Johnson and James Brady, Ronald
Reagan's press secretary who was seriously wounded in the 1981
assassination attempt.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, it features such ordinary ``angels'' as a
20-year-old boy who donated a kidney to his ailing grandmother and
the Congressional Budget Office assistant who dove into the icy
Potomac River to save a victim of a 1982 plane crash. And then
there are the surpassing celebrities, the ``25 Legends of the past
25 years'' who range from Oprah Winfrey to Princess Diana. (The
late princess is the classic People star, having appeared on the
cover a mind-boggling 50 times. She graced three of the magazine's
top 10 best-selling covers.)
</P>
<P>
   No one suggests that People magazine is responsible for Princess
Di's incredible popularity or for creating America's obsession with
celebrity. But to some extent, its rise dovetails with ``a longer
trend of moving the personal into public view,'' says Joshua
Gamson, an associate professor of sociology at Yale. The obsession
with ``celebrity we've always had to a certain degree,'' says
cultural critic Steven Stark. But what's new is ``an obsession with
the personal as political.''
</P>
<P>
   People managing editor Carol Wallace explains her magazine's
appeal more simply: ``I think it's like a best friend to people. I
think there's a bond there. They like to identify with people who
come into their home on the TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The key to People's success, however, is not simply a focus on
celebrity. It is the canny way in which the magazine straddles the
conflicting reader emotions of envy and admiration provoked by
tales of the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to celebrities has always been ambivalent and the
presentation of celebrities has always been ambivalent. . . .
They're just like you and me and they're different from you and
me,'' says Gamson, author of ``Claims to Fame: Celebrity in
Contemporary America.'' ``People is a great purveyor and marketer
of that ambivalence. That's their brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   In its choice of subject matter, People varies the mix.
Sometimes it portrays stars as ``different from you and me'' _ as
evidenced by its cover stories on the ``25 Most Intriguing People
of the Year'' or its ``40 Most Fascinating Stars of '98.'' Yet,
just as often, it will humanize the travails of celebrities,
publishing a story on the personal problems of model Kate Moss,
Michael J. Fox's battle with Parkinson's disease, and Peggy
Fleming's struggle with breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Even as People evinces a tabloid interest in the lives of the
lustrous, however, it displays none of the tabloid culture's
icon-smashing nastiness. ``The celebrity media have two functions _
to envy the famous and to destroy the famous,'' says Stark.
``People has never been into the second.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't write stories that necessarily rock the boat,''
says Mediaweek senior editor Lisa Granatstein. ``It's a nice family
magazine. Everybody can read it and everybody can feel good.'' Even
the recent Chelsea Clinton cover story that sparked White House
charges that People was invading the first daughter's privacy
proved to be a friendly, quasi-puff piece.
</P>
<P>
   Although the magazine earns widespread kudos for what Stark
calls a ``kinder, gentler'' breed of celebrity news, it also
ignites a debate over whether it is culpable for a broader dumbing
down of American journalism.
</P>
<P>
   ``What People did is they really identified the genre and put it
out there,'' says Fran Shea, the president of the 10-year-old E!
Entertainment Television, which derived inspiration from the
magazine. ``People identified that audiences take celebrity
information very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   A study done by the Committee of Concerned Journalists revealed
that from 1977 to 1997 _ even as People was moving toward a greater
percentage of news or trend covers _ Time and Newsweek doubled the
number of cover stories they published with ``celebrities, a sexy
man or woman or an image story about sex.''
</P>
<P>
   The news magazines and People are ``meeting in the middle,''
says Rosenstiel. People gave ``respectability to a kind of
journalism that is running amok. Unwittingly, they gave a good name
to a less significant kind of journalism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real mixed,'' says Gamson of People's journalistic
legacy. ``I don't think the focus on individual personalities and
individual stories as a culture-wide phenomenon is a great thing.
(But) the making of personal lives to be publicly relevant, that's
not all bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Media critic and Brill's Content founder Steve Brill believes
People's ``editorial standards are right'' and absolves the
magazine of blame for making it ``possible and palatable'' for less
skilled imitators to follow its lead. ``It always worries me,''
Richard Stolley once noted, ``that we get blamed for something we
clearly can't control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
