<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDCARE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PRESCHOOL, MULTIPLES THRIVE ON `YOU'RE DIFFERENT PEOPLE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA F. MELTZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Whether it's the first glass of orange juice at breakfast or the
sleep-tight kiss at night, being first is paramount in the lives of
5-year-old fraternal twins Ziv Arzt and Ezra Porter. Time to get
dressed? ``Put my clothes out first!'' Mom's gonna read a book?
``My book first!'' Time to go to preschool? ``Do my seat belt
first!''
</P>
<P>
   When cries of ``Me first!'' surfaced 18 months ago, parents
Eliza Arzt and Meredith Porter tried to be fair by hooking seat
belts simultaneously and rotating who did what first. But as the
litany grew, it got too hard to keep track. Now Arzt and Porter
have systems _ Ezra is first to get in the car, Ziv is first to get
out _ but they also tell their sons, ``You're two different people
and we can't be absolutely even every time. You two figure this out
and let us know.''
</P>
<P>
   The message, ``You're two different people,'' is one parents of
multiples need to send beginning at birth, but it takes on new
significance in the preschool years when all children struggle with
individuality. For multiples who function as a unit, especially
identicals, it can be particularly difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Haigney, director of the Barat Montessori Preschool in
Cochituate, Mass., has seen the process unfold. She describes
identical twin girls who, at the age of 3, were happy to be
mistaken for each other, indeed, encouraged it. At 4, though, she
says, ``They got angry to be called by the wrong name.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeing themselves as distinct usually begins at about age 3 and
can take years to complete. Arzt says her sons know who is who and
don't always have to be together, but, she adds, ``There are ways
in which they see the results of what they do as one big thing,
rather than the result of individual efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me first!'' is one of the early signs of individuation; all
parents with more than one child suffer through it. But with
siblings of different ages, a fight can peter out because the older
one gets bored or the younger one knows she's outmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Not so with multiples.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their desires are equally matched and they are at the same
stage of development, so the skills they bring a situation are also
basically equal. That makes competition more intense,'' says
psychologist and twin researcher Nancy L. Segal.
</P>
<P>
   The most valued commodity for any preschooler is mom or dad's
attention. With two, three, or four like-minded children in one
family, that ratchets up the competition. In the Arzt-Porter home,
even with two parents and an older sister, there are days when Mom
feels like a prize. ``It's not enough if I take one downstairs in
the morning and my husband the other,'' she says. ``They both want
me, and they both want to be first.'' (The twins, by the way, have
different last names not to individualize them but so that Eliza
wouldn't be the only Arzt in the family.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Parents can't eliminate the need to compete but we can minimize
it by giving each child consistent time alone with each parent,
preferably daily, says British pediatrician Elizabeth Bryan, a
specialist in multiple-birth children. However, she says, don't
feel like your time alone has to be an ``event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have this tendency to want to make up for lost time, so we
overstimulate,'' says Bryan. ``Sometimes it's better not to do
anything. Sometimes what a multiple needs most is to do what he
wants peacefully, without interruption. Having you available to him
without competing for your attention is special enough.''
</P>
<P>
   From birth, most multiples, especially identicals, function as a
social unit and tune out the rest of the world. ``That makes them
more socially advanced than single children because they have
experience in making a relationship work,'' says Patricia Maxwell
Malmstrom, president of Twin Services, a nonprofit resource agency
in Berkeley, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   It also gives them hardly any experience in being alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time a twin sits quietly to paint or do a puzzle, she's
either wondering where her co-twin is or the co-twin distracts
her,'' says Bryan. As a result, multiples tend to have a short
attention span. Quiet time with a parent can help with this, too,
especially in the preschool years, she says. Bryan is founder of
the Multiple Birth Foundation in London and author of ``Twins,
Triplets and More'' (St. Martin's Press).
</P>
<P>
   The less experience they have being apart, the harder it can be
for them in the preschool years when some separation is expected.
``Send a singleton to preschool and he's got to separate from Mom.
Send twins, and they have to separate from Mom and each other.
That's expecting a lot,'' says Segal, who is a professor at
California State University at Fullerton. Her new book, ``Entwined
Lives: Twins and What They Tell Us about Human Behavior'' (Dutton),
is due out later this month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Segal and other researchers recommend keeping multiples together
in preschool, with two exceptions. Many twins develop their own
language, called ``twin speak.'' That's a problem only if they use
it to exclude peers. If that happens, and/or if preschool multiples
also won't play at all with other children, Segal suggests some
degree of separation, perhaps different classrooms for part of the
morning. Otherwise, she says, let the children initiate separation,
even if it takes months, even if all they do is sit on opposite
sides of an art table.
</P>
<P>
   At the Barat Montessori School, the policy is to expose twins to
choices. ``Eventually, even identical twins who were stuck like
glue will choose different things to do,'' says Haigney. Fraternal
multiples, whose interests are more likely to differ, usually have
an easier time, but both identicals and fraternals typically want
to keep tabs on each other. ``A child might leave an activity and
walk across the room to where her twin is playing, not to talk to
her, just to see her,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   What's perhaps most hurtful in the preschool years is when one
twin is very social and the other isn't. ``Parents typically see
this as awful and unfair and they panic, insisting the twins go as
a unit on playdates,'' says Malmstrom. She tells parents to see it
instead as an opportunity for the less social child to have time
alone to do things he likes or time with you. Her rule of thumb:
``Give each child what he needs when he needs it. Your acceptance
and calmness around them not always being together is what will
make it OK.'' This is especially true with boy-girl pairs where the
girl is more socially advanced than the boy, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it comes to discipline, multiples may stick together.
``I've seen situations where a preschool-age twin insists on
sharing punishment even though she wasn't naughty,'' says Segal.
She prefers not to punish two children when only one deserves it,
but she admits it can be hard to prevent a child from sharing in a
consequence if he insists. Bryan says the worst punishment parents
can inflict on multiples is to simply ignore the naughty one and
lavish positive attention on the other(s).
</P>
<P>
   Your time alone with each child can pay off in this arena, too.
``Young children only respond to discipline when there's a tight
bond to the person administering it,'' says Bryan. ``If the closer
bond is to the twin who is egging you on rather than to the parent,
there will be times when they gang up to show off to each other,
and you'll be at a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   Arzt calls that ``twin escalation:'' ``One minute everything is
calm, the next there's wild laughter and everything is being taken
apart. I can be at my wit's end in a matter of minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   If both parents are home, one grabs each child to physically
separate and calm him down. If not, Arzt has learned there are
times when togetherness works in her favor. Once a week there's
candy morning, which is earned, among other things, by being in bed
on time. It's a joint reward: For each to get it, both have to
behave.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
TIPS FOR PARENTS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --It's easier for multiples to see themselves as separate if
parents make a habit of splitting them up for some activities _ mom
takes two to the grocery, dad takes one for a haircut.
</P>
<P>
   --One way to get time alone with each child is to create breaks
in the routine. Instead of a shared bath, mom gives one a bath
while dad reads to the other and vice versa. Or pick a day once a
week or once a month when they take turns not going to preschool
and stay home with you instead.
</P>
<P>
   --In the preschool and toddler years, if they fight over sides
of your lap, lie on the floor. Then there's no lap.
</P>
<P>
   --Researchers encourage schools not to have blanket policies
about separating multiples but to judge each case individually.
</P>
<P>
   --With preschool or elementary school conferences, have separate
meetings for each child. If there are issues to discuss surrounding
their twinship, schedule a third meeting.
</P>
<P>
   --A preschool twin who maliciously scribbles on a co-twin's
paper or ruins something the other is working on may be frustrated
from too much sharing. Try simple adjustments: Does each twin have
a designated place to sleep? Toys and clothes that belong only to
him as well as a place to keep them?
</P>
<P>
   --Whenever possible, make sure your twins or triplets are
hearing this message: ``There's room in our family for both/all of
you to do what you want and succeed at it.''
</P>
<P>
   --Look for neutral ways to rotate who's first: There's an odd
number of letters in one's name, an even number in the other, so
one goes first on odd-numbered days, the other on even days.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Barbara F. Meltz's first book, ``Put Yourself in Their Shoes:
Understanding How Your Children See the World'' (Dell), is now
available in bookstores. She welcomes letters and comments and can
be reached via e-mail at meltz(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
