<HEADLINE>
COMING TO A TV NEAR YOU: `THE MONICA SHOW' 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Toward the end of the interview of the century,
Barbara Walters asked Monica Lewinsky where she would go from here.
Besides straight to the bank, of course.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to make a contribution to society, a good
contribution, I think,'' Monica said in her charming,
self-deprecating way. ``I'd like to find the right person, have a
meaningful relationship and have kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Contribution to society? She already made it. She filled the
great conversational void for a full year, fed the voracious media
maw, created new networks, empowered pundits, contributed to the
growth of the Internet and helped grind the Republican Party into
the dust.
</P>
<P>
   She has been The Topic for more than a year, outperforming even
O.J. Simpson. Lord knows what the next Topic is. The millennium
just won't cut it.
</P>
<P>
   I purposely am not reporting many of Monica's priceless quotes
from the interview. I don't want to help promote her book, the
forthcoming ``Monica's Story,'' billed by the leader of her army of
publicists as ``the essential document for closure.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorry. The essential tool for closure was the power button on
the television remote, and most Americans probably hit the closure
button at 11 o'clock Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   OK, one more quote. The funniest one was when Barbara asked
Monica why the president had an affair with her. Monica said,
``Sometimes you just need a piece of ... normalcy.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, she said it with the pause, and ``normalcy'' was the last
word I expected would follow.
</P>
<P>
   I don't have to tell you all the great questions and answers in
the two-hour interview, which featured a lot of $400,000, 30-second
commercials for Advil.
</P>
<P>
   If you didn't watch the interview, you don't want to know what
was said.
</P>
<P>
   If you're a normal American, you watched the interview, sucked
up everything that was said and analyzed the semiotics of Monica's
new and very serious hairdo _ flattened with the gel from hell.
</P>
<P>
   She did great.
</P>
<P>
   Not to have watched the interview seems almost un-American, like
not owning a TV in the first place. People who didn't watch it
probably own Volvos and claim they only listen to NPR. Or else they
have standards.
</P>
<P>
   Help, I'm a cog in the Monica publicity machine. I actually
wrote down everything she said and most of what Barbara asked. It
was the perfect match of interviewer and interviewee. Barbara and
Monica melded deliciously like Jell-O and Cool Whip on a hot
summer's day.
</P>
<P>
   Monica told of how the president seemed to indicate he would
marry her, and asked what he would do (pardon the quote) ``when I'm
75 and have to pee 25 times a day.''
</P>
<P>
   She told of how the president felt her pain and how tears came
to his eyes when he broke up with her on D-Day, for ``Dump Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica said she didn't have sex with the president. She had oral
sex, and winningly called it ``messin' around.''
</P>
<P>
   She said it was exciting to be messin' around with the president
while he was talking on the phone to a congressman.
</P>
<P>
   I can't help myself. I'm promoting the book, the essential
document of closure that could make this young woman a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   My bet is that the book will go over slightly better than the
O.J. exercise video, and Monica will have to get a job.
</P>
<P>
   The only real job she ever had was at the Pentagon in public
affairs, perfectly enough. She's gone as far as she can in public
affairs, as far as is humanly possible, in fact. She has to move
on.
</P>
<P>
   When you're only 25 years old and you're a one-name person, the
most famous name on the planet, there's only one place to go. You
have to get your own talk show.
</P>
<P>
   Monica has all the moves. She's personable, articulate, humorous
and has a winning smile. She nods sympathetically. She can tug
heartstrings. She's well-spoken and sincere. She's adorable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she was naive to think that Clinton loved her for her mind
and soul, but she's grown. She doesn't love him anymore.
</P>
<P>
   After the interview, she's no longer a stalker, a victim, a
vixen and certainly not a bimbo. She is still Monica, but that
could be as in ``On the next Monica ...''
</P>
<P>
   Watching Monica with Barbara Walters was like watching the old
film clip of young Bill Clinton shaking hands with President John
F. Kennedy at that White House conference of dorky student leaders.
</P>
<P>
   It was like seeing royalty and a future successor.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Monica can't replace Barbara, but I hear Oprah is giving
up her time slot to ascend to the Earth goddess Gaia.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
