<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT'S IN A NAME: MAYBE TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ ``The first call I got,'' Kathy Rosenbaum was
telling me, ``was about a year and a half ago. Somebody called
looking for Jeff Rosenbaum for some equipment he'd ordered. So, I
said, `Oh, baseball equipment?' My husband is heavily into baseball
in this area. And they said, `No, restaurant equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   That made no sense to Kathy Rosenbaum. Her husband, Jeff, is a
certified public accountant. You have the wrong guy, she told the
caller. Jeffrey M. Rosenbaum of the Albany suburb of Schodack has
nothing to do with the restaurant business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I started getting more calls for Jeff _ baking ovens he
had ordered. They were calls from New York City. I told them they
had the wrong person. They said, `Fine.' Then they started getting
more insistent when they called several weeks later. I would say,
`How did you get our number?' And they would say they called
directory assistance. And we're the only ones listed under Jeffrey
Rosenbaum ... Then they started getting belligerent.''
</P>
<P>
   There were nastier messages on the Rosenbaums' answering
machine. Pay up, the callers would say. Your check bounced, and
we're going to the cops. Kathy would call back and say the caller
had the wrong Jeff Rosenbaum. The callers would threaten her
husband with jail.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Kathy Rosenbaum went to the New York State Police. She
and her husband hired a lawyer to communicate with these furious
creditors. Ultimately, they learned that there was another Jeff
Rosenbaum among the one million or so residents of the Albany metro
area _ a Jeffrey D. Rosenbaum and not Jeffrey M. Rosenbaum, the CPA
_ and that Jeffrey D. Rosenbaum was in the restaurant supply
business.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a horror show, Kathy Rosenbaum said. All these
calls, all these threats from creditors her husband doesn't know
and doesn't owe, probably 150 of them.
</P>
<P>
   I got some idea last week what it must have been like for
Jeffrey M. Rosenbaum and his wife, Kathy, when I mentioned Jeffrey
D. Rosenbaum in a column. Ed Novak, who operates a pizzeria, had
sworn out a criminal complaint against him for allegedly writing a
bad check. After taking some abuse from a court clerk _ and aware
that Jeffrey D. Rosenbaum's wife is an assistant Albany County
district attorney _ Novak began to fear that he might not get
justice in the village court of suburban Ravena, population 3,500,
where nobody ever seems to be paying attention to what the little
local dukes and duchesses are doing.
</P>
<P>
   Once that column ran, my phone rang right off the hook. Person
after person, company after company. They all were complaining that
Jeffrey D. Rosenbaum had stiffed them, had written them bad checks.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know if any of that is true. But I do know that Jeffrey
D. Rosenbaum has a serious history of such problems in other parts
of New York. He has done jail time. He has at least one bankruptcy.
He has had problems holding on to a driver's license. I tried to
talk to him about all this, but his phone is unlisted. Clearly,
this is a guy with problems.
</P>
<P>
   I feel bad for people with problems. But I feel worse for people
like Jeffrey M. Rosenbaum, the CPA from Schodack, and his wife,
Kathy, who also ended up with problems, and through no fault of
their own. They and their three kids have been subjected for 18
months now to harassing phone calls and angry threats of arrest.
</P>
<P>
   This sort of thing is grim but not uncommon. There are,
according to an Internet search I conducted, 52 Daniel Lynches
living among New York state's 18 million residents. One time, when
I bought a house on Long Island, I had to sign an affidavit stating
that I wasn't four of them.
</P>
<P>
   The point is simply this: We live in a big, complex society
where about a million Americans a year have problems so severe that
they're forced into bankruptcy. And, if they have the wrong name,
their problems can become your problems, too.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
