<SLUG> BC-SALTER-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
E-NOUGH E-MAIL! 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEPHANIE SALTER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Everyone tells me I am being troglodytic and/or
selfish. But I really, really hate getting e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   This attitude probably speaks volumes about my creativity,
intestinal fortitude, intelligence and possibly childhood toilet
training; I don't care. E-mail is my idea of hell.
</P>
<P>
   I don't ``do'' e-mail at home, and I wish I didn't get it at
work.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was only recently that I found out that I have an
e-mail address at work. My Aunt Linda from Ohio called and said:
``Why don't you ever answer my e-mails?''
</P>
<P>
   Huh? Turned out I'd been getting e-mail messages from lots of
people for months. According to one of our computer helpers,
hundreds and hundreds of messages were causing ``our mail server to
get a little clogged up.''
</P>
<P>
   My ignorance was not the newspaper's fault. For two years I have
deliberately hidden from anything that looks like Internet access
training. A couple of times I hid in the women's room when
mandatory training sessions were held across the hall from my
office. Always, I managed to slip through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   You may love e-mail. Your friends and associates may love it.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate, academic and governing America obviously love it and
run on it. But I don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   Why is that such a crime? As I have explained to dozens of
e-mail-touting friends, family and bosses, I am quite happy with
the two methods of communication I grew up with: letters and phone
calls. They are all I need and definitely all I want.
</P>
<P>
   As for people's ability to communicate with me here at the
office, I am accessible via three wide, accommodating boulevards:
``snail mail,'' voicemail and fax. For 11 years, traffic along
these byways has kept me busy, busy, busy. In fact, as I have
written before, I have more communication than I can handle and am
notoriously inept at answering mail.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not proud of this. It's a flaw for sure _ or maybe a kind of
disability. But it's a deep flaw and not likely to soon disappear
without secretarial help.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't because I don't care, don't value suggestions to ``go
back to sportswriting'' or to the kitchen, to Russia or to ``your
father, Satan, where you belong.'' I just don't have time in a
five-day work week to do my job and compose a personal reply to all
the letters that demand one. Even the nice letters.
</P>
<P>
   What I can do is read all the letters, react in anger,
frustration, pity, compassion or happiness and _ once in awhile _
get an idea for another column. And I can file the letters for
posterity in a subject-appropriate folder.
</P>
<P>
   Why would I want to open another avenue of communication,
especially an avenue that tends to bring out the dump-and-run
artist in so many folks?
</P>
<P>
   Reams have been written about the nature of e-mail, how it
``frees'' people to just say whatever pops into their minds,
release it into cyberspace then go about their business with little
thought of the consequences. Unlike a letter, e-mail requires no
time to buy stamps, address envelopes or go to the post office, no
time for second thoughts, cooling off or reconsideration. Unlike a
phone call, e-mail does not require the intimate commitment of the
human voice.
</P>
<P>
   Despite my pleadings, my newspaper (understandably) won't make
an exception for me. So, if you want to, if you must, you can send
me e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   For your effort, you may rest assured that I will look at your
message _ sooner or later. But, please remember: I don't like
e-mail, I don't want e-mail and e-mail will always be the last
thing I get to.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Stephanie Salter is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner,
P.O. Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120. Her e-mail address is
salter &LR; examiner.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
