<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-PEYSER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CHIEF KNOWN AS A CRITIC OF PUBLIC SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JORDANA HART  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The new chairman of the state Board of Education
champions vouchers and charter schools, makes no secret of his
dismay with traditional public education, and sends his own child
to a suburban private school, Milton Academy.
</P>
<P>
   What is remarkable, observers said Wednesday, is that James A.
Peyser, who believes in privatization of almost every aspect of
government, will now be in charge of setting the agenda for one of
the state's largest bureaucracies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who espouses charter schools and choice like that is
basically saying they want to abandon public education,'' said Jack
Rennie, chairman of the Massachusetts Business Alliance, a group
advocating education reform. ``We basically have a fox in charge of
the chicken coup.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rennie and others at odds with Peyser's market-driven
philosophy Wednesday described Peyser himself as a reasonable,
low-key figure who they believe will work smoothly with the
nine-member board and the new education commissioner, David
Driscoll, a former math teacher who is well liked in the education
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they will do well together,'' said Senator Robert A.
Antonioni, a Leominster Democrat who is cochairman of the
Legislature's Education Committee. ``They are even-tempered
individuals who can have disagreements without fireworks.''
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Peyser said that while state
government clearly must play a role in education, more attention
must be paid to whether and how well programs help students
achieve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should not continue to fund and renew grants when there is
no evidence of such improvement,'' he said. ``There is too much
complacency in terms of assured revenue and assured survival, no
matter how poorly students perform.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the hard work of teachers and others, Peyser said,
parents and children are the ``customers'' of public education
``and not part of the system, and they need to be given options.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll, in an interview, said he has always found common
ground with Peyser, a board member from 1995 until resigning in
December to run for commissioner. Even if there are disagreements,
Driscoll said, ``I will implement what the majority votes, my
feelings aside.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of Peyser's politics, Antonioni and others noted that
it is ultimately the entire board, not Peyser alone, who will
juggle the tough issues facing the board, such as teacher testing
and what to do for schools that do not improve poor MCAS results.
</P>
<P>
   The board's reputation has suffered somewhat under the tough
hand of John Silber. Its often contentious public debates got more
attention than its decisions. As some see it, the board's job now
is to help the commissioner and Education Department get reforms
underway, not quibble over policy that was set long ago.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser's very passion for policy might get in the way, said one
critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we have a policy overload, and policy is a weak
instrument for bringing about change in the classroom,'' said Paul
Reville, chairman of the state Education Reform Review Commission
and a board member from 1991 to 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser's approach to being commissioner, Reville said, ``was to
say it was a policy job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My concern is, you have two people with very different
philosophies, and the politically expedient solution has been to
give them both a job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Peyser, 42, lives in Boston's Dorchester neighborhood with his
wife and two children, ages 2 and 6. He runs the Boston-based
Pioneer Institute for Public Policy Research, a think tank that
espouses limited government and a market-driven approach to all
aspects of public policy. Peyser said he would still run the
Pioneer Institute, in the role of chairman, a nonpaying job.
</P>
<P>
   Board member Abigail Thernstrom, an ardent Silber critic, said
Peyser is not a strident ideologue intent on smashing the education
bureacracy. He is more interested, she said, in easing the hand of
government in certain areas.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Peyser would rather see teachers choose their own
professional development programs than have the state pick them,
she said. ``He would say, `Let teachers themselves make education
reform work.' And I agree with him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
