<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRICE ISN'T TOO HIGH FOR THIS CHALLENGING SPORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some ideas not worth thinking.
</P>
<P>
   (1) Skiing is pricing itself out of business.
</P>
<P>
   This is a lament I hear at least 10 times per winter, often from
colleagues around the sweatshop in which I labor. Most recently, it
was voiced over the ``suggested retail'' for a pair of the latest
generation of shaped skis: $550.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ridiculous!'' thundered my fellow inked-stained wretch.
``Who's going to pay that kind of money for a pair of skis?''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is, no one. Or, let's amend that to read, no one
except the guy who has enough bucks to tear them up into shreds and
let the winter wind blow them away. Or the guy whom Darwin has
targeted as ``the fool and his money'' who will soon be parted?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, there is a world-wide overproduction of skis each
year, which in late summer get shipped in all their new-graphics
glory to the retail shops.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first powder has graced the first 4,000-foot summit,
those ski shops, fearful they will be stuck with their inventory,
begin marking them down in what becomes a ferocious price war.
</P>
<P>
   By post-Christmas, the prices get closer to the bone, and long
before midwinter Presidents' Day vacation, the ``end of season''
sales are in full flower.
</P>
<P>
   The really wise buyer waits until the following October when
such retailing giants as Ski Market sell last year's items at about
half that original $550 suggested retail price.
</P>
<P>
   Sooo, what about all of the other costs of skiing? Like Aspen's
$62 daily lift ticket price?
</P>
<P>
   Well, for starters, anyone who drives into Aspen (or Vail or
Deer Valley, etc.) and buys a retail-priced one-day lift ticket
fits into one of the two categories above and is crying out to get
rid of his cash.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, let's face facts: Anyone who goes to Aspen (or Vail or
Deer Valley) in the first place is not exactly counting pennies.
These are the high-priced spreads, and that means there is a
medium-priced and even a low-priced spread out there, which deliver
fine and fabulous skiing.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, from Lake Louise to Gunstock, there are extremely
lovely and affordable ski experiences all over this country. One
might even be forced to admit, the dizzying pace of life in the
sprawl-mall of Vail or overly-precious Aspen, can be a bit of a
downer for those seeking a pristine relationship with winter
outdoor beauty.
</P>
<P>
   For those Rocky Mountain fortresses of wealth to set the
psychological standard for what we might loosely term
``contemporary ski life'' is ridiculous. Fact is, with twining of
no-growth laws and beautiful-people syndrome, Aspen's average house
sells for close to $2 million, and a single-room sublet in the
basement of a Vail condo rents for $800 per month. Does that sound
like the real world?
</P>
<P>
   The point is the same now as it was when Henry Ford first
figured out that it didn't matter how many cars he could turn out
unless there was a middle class to buy them. As long as there are
mountains and people who want to slide down them, skiing and
boarding will be around.
</P>
<P>
   (2) The easier skiing gets, the more fun it is.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I plead guilty to having extolled the virtue of shaped
skis as they bloomed on the market in the last four years, but then
I'm an over-50 guy carrying, ahh, just a little extra baggage
around on football knees. To have some real performance skis that
made carving a turn that much easier, has been a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   But more generally, the trend to broad white-paved boulevards _
once the standard for that ubiquitous ``intermediate'' skier _ is
now, well, boring. So skiers and riders looking for more, headed to
the back country, the glades, the unbroken powder of the untouched
high country.
</P>
<P>
   If easier were better in a universal sense, then why not extend
the rule to golf? Let's do away with sand traps and water hazards.
Let's put electronic homing devices in the ball that correct bad
shots and send the ball straight to the green.
</P>
<P>
   Let's liberate the classic angler from all that fuss over the
right fly and the perfect presentation. Why not just a worm and a
hook to lure a hungry brown trout? Why not take the gutters off
bowling alleys so that the errant shot careens off the wall and
still nails the pins?
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, easy is not some ultimate goal, and skiing enjoyed
its greatest growth and enthusiasm nearly 40 years ago in an era of
hard, stiff hickory, soft leather, narrow twisting trails with
ungroomed crud.
</P>
<P>
   As Mt. Cranmore's Herbert Schneider points out, it used to take
at least six years to work one's way from novice, through the
layers of lessons, to the true intermediate who could, if the trail
weren't too steep, link some turns together in the wedlen look that
all skiers craved.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, skiing may be easier to learn now than it used to
be, but a real learning curve is still there, drawing the turned-on
neophyte back for ever more. ``Learn to ski in a day'' is a
marketing overstatement, and breaking out of the intermediate
plateau still takes real effort. Just when you think you have the
sport knocked, try trees and serious bumps, or maybe a few ice
drills.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
