</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKI-MARCH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WARMING TO THE SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   March.
</P>
<P>
   It's a month that totters between the giddy anticipation of
spring and a reveling in the snowiest time of the year.
</P>
<P>
   March is when the subsurface ice cap built up through months of
the freeze/thaw cycle begins to soften, when big dumps of natural
snow accumulate in the final blustery weeks of winter.
</P>
<P>
   March is when loyalties are torn between those first rounds of
golf, early cod and trout fishing, and the very best skiing of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get one of those really nice March weekends when it
feels like spring,'' says Mark Chasse, a part-time ski instructor
who lives on the Cape and commutes to New Hampshire on weekends,
``you have to really work to remind yourself that the skiing's
going to be great, too.''
</P>
<P>
   So, the age-old conundrum: How, in the best ski weeks of the
year, do ski areas keep the skiers from drying up long before the
snow melts?
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is perception,'' says Conrad Klefos, marketing vice
president at Jay Peak in Vermont's Northeast Kingdom. ``The problem
we've had this year is with the day market. People look out the
window and if they don't think the snow's really there, they choose
something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Particuarly after last season, which most people give the
highest marks, this winter has so far been a disappointment. There
have been some very fine days of skiing, but periods of snow
drought, warmer-than-usual weather, and rain in the snowbelt have
taken their toll. When the books are closed, few areas will be
boasting. For most, skier visits will be well off record numbers.
</P>
<P>
   And, yet, it is only March. At Jay, the largest single snowfall
and record crowd occurred in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year,'' says Klefos, ``we had a four-day dump late in
March that added up to 43 inches of snow.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in that month, Jay was packed the weekend of Good Friday
_ a day all Quebec residents get off. The long weekend, combined
with excellent snow conditions, brought 4,400 skiers to the
mountain. The average good ski day bings out about 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, anything like that could still happen,'' says Klefos,
noting that within three weeks of the big storm last year, a
``nuclear'' meltdown had occurred, all the snow was gone, and the
mountain closed.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the effort to draw skiers focuses on price packaging
aimed at making the planning of a ski vacaiton attractive enough
for skiers to take a chance on the conditions. Jay, for example,
offers a March package that offers free skiing to skiers who pay
for an on-mountain weekend (or longer) rental. Since the area is
the most popular ski mountain among Montrealers, Jay reaps a bonus
when Canadians plan a four-day Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the underlying problem in March on a bad snow year
is compounded if skiers are unaware that the skiing is, in Klefos's
words, ``really pretty good. We may not have a lot of base in the
glades, and have to close some steep face chutes, but we've had
some good skiing this winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Jay, New England's greatest annual natural snow recipient with
more than 200 inches, is off by 61 inches so far this season, or 30
percent.
</P>
<P>
   At Maine's Sugarloaf, the snow has also been up and down, with
the good snowfall almost always interspersed with a warm, rainy
spell. But by mid-February the area was finally able to announce
the opening of the Snowfields, the area's standard for measuring
its optimum conditions, since it's the only above-timeline skiing
in the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the skiing finally gets good,'' says Leah Steven, a
spokesman for the area, ``we have to try to get the word out. It's
really word of mouth. We had great skiing during February vacation,
and the week after that a lot more people came up here to ski. You
could just tell, the word spread when skiers went home and talked
about their experience.''
</P>
<P>
   But experienced skiers know that, on average, March is the best
month to ski. ``If I had my choice,'' says Chasse, ``I wouldn't
even go skiing in New England until February. Then hit it really
hard until the meltdown in April. In March it's warmer but not mush
season yet. The light is better, you're in better shape, and the
crowds are getting smaller _ you can get good deals. No question
it's the month to ski.''
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of the March deals around the slopes, similar to
Jay's ``Ski Free'' slopeside vacations: Mad River in Vermont has a
$175 weekend ski-and-stay package ($75 midweek); Tenney cuts its
lift ticket to $32 weekends, $17 weekday; Mt. Snow offers a $61
midweek and $70 weekend package; Killington allows kids 12 and
under to ski free when parents buy a five-day lift ticket; Stowe
has a five-day ski-and-stay package at $69 per day, and the Blue
Hills offers half prices.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the areas are giving away the skiing, says one
manager in Vermont, ``but this is the time of year when it becomes
a real buyer's market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
