<HEADER>
A7585 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOICE-SURGEON-2TAKES-     03-04 1056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-SURGEON-2 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOCAL ADVOCATE 
</HEADLINE>
 TAKES-ART-BOS  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GLORIA NEGRI  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ On almost any clinic day, the voices of professional
singers can be heard scaling octaves in Dr. Steven Zeitels's
examining rooms at Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary. Some end up
having surgery; others voice therapy. While the singers provide the
music, it is Zeitels's cancer patients who provide the drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The man is touched by God,'' said 60-year-old Jesus Lopez of
Boston. Lopez was at the clinic for a postoperative checkup after
losing a major part of his larynx, or voice box, to vocal-cord
cancer. ``Because of him,'' said Lopez, a two-pack-a-day smoker for
37 years, ``I am still talking to you in my own voice and not
through a machine.''
</P>
<P>
   Under standard surgical procedure, Lopez might have required a
laryngectomy, the total removal of his voice box. With that, he
would have had to speak with the aid of a device. Zeitels found a
less drastic way to remove his cancer. Since his surgery, Lopez
breathes partially through a tube in his trachea, or windpipe. Yet,
he exults in the fact that he can still talk with his own voice and
might someday breathe on his own.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Zeitels is highly regarded worldwide for his skill and
the pioneering surgical procedures he designs and performs, often
with instruments he invents. He has been saving voices and lives of
throat cancer patients for 10 years. The goal, as Zeitels sees it,
is to do ``minimally invasive surgery'' not only to heal patients
but to preserve their quality of life. ``The key,'' he said, ``is
not organ preservation, per se, but function preservation.''
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, Zeitels will remove the cancer through the
patient's mouth by using an endoscope, or tube in the throat,
instead of cutting externally and causing disfigurement. Zeitels's
dedication to his patients has brought them to his office from all
walks of life, not only the professional singers, but lawyers,
broadcasters, teachers, and others who damage their voices through
overuse or improper use.
</P>
<P>
   He is so committed to the belief that people should have the
full use of their voices, he treated a street folk singer who had
no medical insurance in exchange for a tape of a rare rock album.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His colleagues say that some of the procedures Zeitels has
developed have made them take a second look at what they're doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of Steve's presentations have really altered how we
should think about disorders of the voice,'' said Dr. Gerald B.
Healy, chief of otolaryngology at Children's Hospital. The two met
when Zeitels was a resident there. ``I see him as a major
contributor to the field. I have been going over to watch some of
his new operating techniques and, I believe, he's developed some
that can be applied to pediatrics,'' Healy said.
</P>
<P>
   Healy said Zeitels's ``phenomenal knowledge of medical history''
of his specialty has enabled him to improve on earlier procedures
with new instrumentation.
</P>
<P>
   The Eye and Ear Infirmary has such faith in Zeitels's work that
it has just created a Division of Laryngology and made him its
director. He works closely with the infirmary's Voice and Speech
Laboratory and is associate professor in the Department of Otology
and Laryngology of Harvard Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitels said his work would not be as successful as it is
``without the staff in the lab, people like Bob Hillman,'' its
director. ``We're a team effort here,'' he says. Zeitels sends
almost all of his patients to the lab for speech therapy, whether
they have had surgery or not. Next to the accolades of his
patients, Zeitels said he is particularly proud of being recognized
last year by the American Laryngological Association with its
Casselberry Award for his new procedure in treating vocal cord
paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   While challenges seem to invigorate him, so does a heavy daily
hospital schedule. On a recent ``light'' day, he operated on a
cancer patient, a rock singer, and a new-age inspirational
vocalist. That was just before leaving to lecture at a voice
conference in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's a fixer,'' said folk singer Livingston Taylor, whom
Zeitels treated for vocal cord hemorrhaging. ``He's a guy who is
clear and bold in his desire to find ways of helping people
continue living the type of life they want to live.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, since Zeitels removed abnormal blood vessels from Taylor's
vocal cords (or vocal folds), and after Taylor went to a voice
management expert, the singer is doing fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's great story is not what he does for a couple of
overpaid prima donnas,'' Taylor said. ``It's fine to rescue
Livingston Taylor's career, but it's miraculous to rescue Betty
Doe's ability to speak to her grandchildren. Steve has this
incredible ability to jump in and really work to save people's
speech. He is just ferocious about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeitels proved that, in surgeries he performed on three men with
throat cancer who faced the possibility of a laryngectomy, but
which Zeitels avoided by using a procedure that didn't cause them
any significant loss of function.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The men, like many other patients at the clinic, were eager to
talk to a visitor about how Zeitels had saved their voices.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Gregory, a Boston political consultant, said his throat
cancer resulted from ``smoking too much'' during his 57 years. His
wife, lawyer Mary K. Ames, told of their fear that he might require
a laryngectomy. Ames said she searched the Internet and medical
journals and spoke to other doctors looking for ``the kinds of care
that work and save function'' and the surgeon who could provide
that kind of care.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name that kept popping up was Steven Zeitels,'' Ames said.
``We found that Dr. Zeitels is concerned with the total person and
respects the patient's intelligence and fears. His is not
conservative, conventional medicine,'' Ames said, ``but the
brilliant discoveries never are.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of doing a laryngectomy on Gregory, Zeitels removed his
tumor through his mouth by laser. That was followed by radiation
therapy at Massachusetts General Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QC;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1323EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7589 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VOICE-SURGEON-2DTAKE-     03-04 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VOICE-SURGEON-2DTAKE-ART-BOS </SLUG>
  
 BOSTON: ... General Hospital.  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Paul Glassett, 43, a hospital security officer from South
Weymouth, wants so much for others to know of Zeitels's work that
he invited a visitor to watch his third surgery.
</P>
<P>
   A nonsmoker, Glassett said he worked as a highway toll collector
for 10 years until stricken with persistent hoarseness and
laryngitis a year ago. It was diagnosed as vocal-cord cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In July, in an endoscopic procedure, Zeitels used a laser to
remove cancerous tissue from Glassett's right vocal cord. In
October, because vocal muscle was also removed, Zeitels built up
the cord with fat removed from Glassett's armpit. In a third
surgery, Zeitels made an incision in Glassett's neck and implanted
two synthetic wedges to move the vocal cords together so they could
vibrate and produce speech.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with Glassett under local anesthesia, Zeitels was able to
adjust the pitch of his patient's voice by having him talk, just
like a musician tuning a violin.
</P>
<P>
   James Walton, 65, whose Chelsea firm is doing the vacuum
drilling on the Big Dig, said he got throat cancer ``from 35 years
of smoking cigars. I didn't inhale,'' he said, ``but the juices and
smoke caused my problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeitels removed the cancer from the base of Walton's tongue by
using a procedure he designed nine years ago. ``Instead of using
the standard technique, which splits the jawbone,'' Zeitels said
``it involved making an incision in the front of the neck which
does not violate the oral cavity. As a result, Mr. Walton had no
neurological deficit, swallowing problems, or voice change. Nor did
he need a tracheotomy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy's a miracle worker,'' Walton said. Though many of his
patients feel the same about him, Zeitels is slightly uneasy with
the description. ``It isn't faith healing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Caroyln Wood, 53, came from Kansas City., Mo., to see
if Zeitels could wake her from ``the nightmare'' she has lived for
three years. ``I had wrist surgery in Kansas City,'' Wood said
hoarsely, ``and when the anesthesiologist intubated me, he tore my
trachea.''
</P>
<P>
   She came to Boston where, she said, a surgeon at Mass. General
repaired her trachea. ``For about six months, I had to live with a
tube inserted in my throat that went up through my vocal cords. But
it scarred them, making a big hole where the two come together.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' Wood said, ``Dr. Zeitels removed some fat from my
shoulder, pulverized it, sucked it up with a syringe, and injected
it into my right vocal cord to fill in the hole. But,'' she said,
``another procedure is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of Zeitels's medical mentors recalled that signs of his
commitment were already evident when he was studying at the Boston
University School of Medicine. ``Steve had total career commitment
and is driven, happily so,'' said Dr. M. Stuart Strong, Zeitels's
BU adviser. ``Golf would be a very bad game for Steve because it
takes too long.''
</P>
<P>
   At BU, Zeitels was enrolled in its six-year medical program and
got his medical degree in 1982. ``Those students were the cream of
the crop,'' Strong said. ``Steve was among the few at the top of
them, always brilliant, full of questions and great with patients
who were scared.''
</P>
<P>
   After BU, Zeitels was a fellow in Strong's department there and,
after training at Boston hospitals, Zeitels worked with Strong
again at the Veterans Administration Medical Center in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitels chuckles at his description as, ``happily driven.''
``There are still many unsolved questions,'' he said, ``and I have
a great curiosity regarding human voice production. The spectrum of
human voice is like a fingerprint and people who can't communicate
are often very unhappy. To regain someone's voice is gratifying
both to the patient and the doctor.''
</P>
<P>
   He was, he conceded, so fully occupied with his work that it has
made it impossible to pursue hobbies or sports. He is unmarried,
but there is a woman in his life. Right now, he is writing a
history book about laryngology and preparing an atlas on surgical
procedures from some 25,000 slides, showing the instruments in
place.
</P>
<P>
   He will continue, he said, to look for better ways to operate
and better instruments to use. Just recently, he got a US
government patent for a universal modular glottiscope he invented,
a form of laryngoscope, that is inserted into a patient's throat
during surgery. He said it will not only give ``wider exposure'' to
the surgeon, but be more comfortable for the patient.
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in New Rochelle, N.Y., Zeitels said he always wanted
to be a doctor. ``My older brother, now a plastic surgeon,
convinced me do to surgery because I was always good with my
hands.'' Before retiring, his mother taught school in the Bronx and
his father was an orthodontist.
</P>
<P>
   Zeitels said the passion he had for crafting items out of
leather as a child helped him develop ambidexterity and precision
that have enhanced his surgery. ``Steve's hands are so steady,''
observed Dr. Tuan Nghiem, an anesthesiologist who works in surgery
with him. ``It's amazing to watch him removing lesions the size of
a sesame seed with long instruments.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, to promote the study of laryngology, Zeitels
started a Harvard Medical School fellowship at the infirmary; now
there is competition among young doctors to be chosen for it.
``There aren't that many people in the country practicing
laryngology with the same perfection as Dr. Zeitels,'' said Dr.
Rosemary Desloge, the current fellow. But, it is Zeitels's
patients, like Jesus Lopez and South Boston's Wacko Hurley, who pay
him the most touching tributes.
</P>
<P>
   Hurley, who organizes the St. Patrick's Day parade, said he lost
his voice after being treated elsewhere for a blocked carotid
artery and that ``Dr. Zeitels got it back for me. I love the guy,''
Hurley said. ``He's a shining star in medicine. I want him on a
float in the parade, but he told me he's too busy to attend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
