<HEADLINE>
LEAKS APLENTY PRECEDED LEWINSKY INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not since presidential attorney David Kendall denounced
independent counsel Kenneth Starr for feeding damaging information
to the media has the Monica Lewinsky scandal been so awash in
leaks.
</P>
<P>
   In the days leading to the Lewinsky interview with ABC's Barbara
Walters, excerpts of that taped conversation began showing up in
news accounts like salacious bits of the Starr report. Even as ABC
officials cried foul, it's possible that the steady drip of tidbits
could boost ratings.
</P>
<P>
   The first breach occurred last Thursday when Washington Post
media critic Howard Kurtz, citing ``a source who was present during
the (Feb. 20) interview,'' reported that Lewinsky apologizes to the
country in her chat with Walters. Much more disturbing, from ABC's
perspective, was the (N.Y.) Daily News's scoop on Tuesday when it
obtained an ``unedited audio tape'' of part of the interview and
reported that Lewinsky apologizes to Hillary and Chelsea Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We see this as two separate situations,'' said an ABC
spokeswoman, Eileen Murphy. ``We are convinced the Howard Kurtz
leak came from somewhere else than ABC.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's wise for me to characterize my source in
any way other than to say that the information seems to be right on
target,'' Kurtz responded.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Daily News was more of a concern to us because that was
someone who stole our property,'' added Murphy. ``If we find out
with certainty where it came from, we are considering legal
action.'' Daily News senior managing editor Arthur Browne said the
tape was delivered anonymously to the Daily News and ``we have no
idea who gave it to us,'' adding that the paper was careful not to
infringe on ABC's copyright.
</P>
<P>
   The Daily News and Post leaks were not ``something we devised
strategically,'' insisted Murphy, who had heard the speculation
that the leaks were part of an ABC plan to build ratings. In recent
days, the network had been busy parceling out pieces of the
interview, starting with a Walters telephone press conference Feb.
22 and including the airing of a clip on Wednesday's ``Good Morning
America'' program.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in the supersonic world of Monicagate, the Walters
interview was already becoming old news by the time it aired.
Wednesday's big revelation was that in her upcoming book,
``Monica's Story,'' Lewinsky is harshly critical of her treatment
by Starr and his deputies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
