<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPY IN MANANA'S EMBRACE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a week in Mexico, I've decided the world is divided into
two kinds of people: those who feel they must control their
environment and those who don't. I've known some Mexicans who fit
into the first category. I'm still searching for a US tourist who
fits into the second.
</P>
<P>
   There was a good reason our family vacationed for the second
year at Costa Azul, a small ``adventure'' resort in a small town an
hour's drive from Puerto Vallarta. We wanted to have others take
care of us, including the grandchildren. After all, we assumed sole
responsibility for getting ourselves to the open-air dining area on
the beach when we craved a fruit smoothie. If we chose to do more
than watch the waves crash on our deserted stretch of ocean where
the undertow was too powerful for swimming, we had to decide
whether to take a dip in the pool or walk all the way to a
sheltered cove at the end of the beach.
</P>
<P>
   So it seemed only fair that if we wanted the adventures that
came with our package _ a kayak trip to an island off Rincon, a
horseback ride though the jungle above the resort, a 3-mile hike to
a hidden waterfall at Yelapa, a sail to a snorkeling spot called
Los Arcos, or a visit to an alligator farm in San Blas _ the people
in charge should make all the arrangements, including
transportation, food, and guides.
</P>
<P>
   They did, too. Only this being Mexico, they did it their way.
</P>
<P>
   For example, on the way to Rincon, the kayak trailer blew a
tire. Feeling lucky the trailer didn't flip, taking our van with
it, we agreed that one guide would seek a replacement for the tire
while the rest of us went on with the other guide to Rincon. There
we rented a small boat to take us to the bird sanctuary in the
middle of the bay.
</P>
<P>
   The boat owner assured us he'd be with us in ``un momentito.''
Back at Costa Azul, ``un momento'' translated into half an hour and
a ``momentito'' generally meant half that. We efficiency-possessed
Americanos fidgeted like crazy, tormented by our own helplessness.
It was unbearable to stand around for 40 minutes watching a man
just offshore bail out a boat full of water with a small tin can.
</P>
<P>
   Within a day of arrival, we'd faced every American's nightmare:
a situation in which there was nothing to do but let go and relax.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, we set off for Yelapa, a small beach town
accessible only by boat. After a snack, we headed inland, stepping
over boulders, wading through rivers, avoiding the piles of manure
left behind by the burros and horses that transported
``nonadventure'' tourists to the waterfall. A group of us stopped
at a lovely secluded rock pool for a swim. The more daring climbed
a rift in an extremely steep cliff to reach the waterfall itself.
</P>
<P>
   I was summoning my courage to go behind the thundering curtain
of water when my daughter Julie shouted, ``Mom, Dad's been stung.''
The last time Jack was bitten, a hornet entered his mouth on a
chicken leg and he ended up in the hospital, gasping for breath.
This time Jack disturbed a nest of hornets and was bitten four
times before scrambling back down the cliff. Luckily, an American
had packed antihistamines for just such an event so that Jack
suffered no serious consequences.
</P>
<P>
   By week's end, the horse one daughter was to have ridden threw a
shoe. The boat for the sailing trip was damaged, adding three hours
to an already long trip. Though the surfers were thrilled, the huge
waves meant no more kayak trips. Nothing started on time. Meals
took forever to arrive. Stray dogs wandered in and out of the
eating area. On Friday night, a garlanded burro arrived with the
mariachi band and pooped right in the middle of the dining area
with a great flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans protested. ``You can call me an ugly American,
but I won't get onto this boat unless every member of my family has
a life preserver!'' Some commiserated with one another. ``OK, what
went wrong on your trip?'' Most adapted. ``Have another cup of
coffee. We won't be leaving for a while.'' Actually, our family
thrived.
</P>
<P>
   We kayaked in the pool. We walked nowhere special and always
found something extraordinary. We built sand castles. We chased
crabs and observed iguanas. We watched the sun set. We kidded
around. We whiled away untold, blissful, nonproductive,
nonpurposeful hours.
</P>
<P>
   No efficiency. No stress. No expectations. No pressure. No
appointments. No disappointments. No schedules. No lists. No
errands. No phone calls. No news. No anxiety. No headaches. No
insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   Best of all. No complaints.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To find out more about Costa Azul in San Francisco, Nayarit,
Mexico, call 800-365-7613.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Linda Weltner's Web site is www.shore.net/weltner)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
