<HEADLINE>
BRACKETS WILL SILENCE SQUEAKY FLOORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I misplaced an article you had about elminating squeaky
floors. It showed a picture of an aluminum brace that is inserted
under the floor against a joist. Where can I find them?
</P>
<P>
   FRED Z., Dover, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try the Improvements catalog, 800-642-2112. The bracket is
called Squeak Relief, item number 105064, four for $14.99,
including screws. The bracket is inserted on a joist where it meets
the floor above, and screws are driven into the joist and the
floor, keeping it from moving; when the floor does not move, it
will not squeak.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. How can I get a print of The Wall Street Journal off a white
leather chair? I bought a leather cleaner that didn't work. Neither
did vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   KIM MURRAY, Sudbury, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Try Spray and Wash, which takes newspaper print off Formica.
Try it in an obscure area to make sure it does not affect the
leather adversely. Because leather is leather, you have to be extra
careful cleaning and caring for it.
</P>
<P>
   Or, try Apple Leather Care by Apple Polishers, Box 43, Stow, MA
01775; telephone 978-897-6569 or 800-322-6569. Their products
include Garde, which keeps suede, Nubuck, leather, and fabrics
water repellent and stain resistant; Creme Polish, which brings
dull, cracked leather back to life; and Leather Cleaner, an
aggressive cleaner designed to safely clean finished leather.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do those ultrasound machines I see widely advertised actually
scare mice away? Are they any good?
</P>
<P>
   PLAGUED BY RODENTS
</P>
<P>
   A. Here is what the authors of ``Common-Sense Pest Control''
say: There are no studies indicating that ultrasound devices are
effective at significantly reducing or eliminating rats or other
rodents from an area. There are reports showing that certain types
are helpful when used in combination with other methods, but this
still does not mean they will eliminate an infestation.
</P>
<P>
   If you see one mouse, you probably have 20. The standard
treatment is to use D-Con, but keep it away from pets, kids, and
other critters. And if you have a cat, do not use D-Con, because
mice killed by D-Con and eaten by kitty could kill the cat, too.
</P>
<P>
   Or, use the tried-and-true method of traps. Any kind of trap is
effective, but the snap traps are still probably the best. Place
them in the basement, behind the stove, and where you think the
mice are running. They usually run along a wall, so traps set near
a wall are most effective.
</P>
<P>
   Another deterrent is a little harder. Close all openings in the
foundation and anywhere else you may find them; remember, mice can
go through a hole the size of a dime, and they are also good
climbers. Fill holes and big cracks in the foundation with mortar,
and stuff other holes with Stuffit, a nonrusting brass or copper
``steel'' wool. You can buy Stuffit by calling Creative Expressions
at 316-788-6290.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have an old poured floor, of the type in which liquid vinyl
is poured on the floor, allowed to set, then embedded with colorful
chips. It is all brown and ugly. How can I remove it?
</P>
<P>
   GINGER WINSLOW, Hingham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Scrape the floor with brute force, although adding a litle
heat might make it easier to scrape. Use a hair dryer, not a
hot-air gun; the latter is much too hot to use indoors. You can
rent a power scraper, which will hasten the chore, from a rental
store. But it is still hard work. Poured floors were developed in
the 1970s, but never really caught on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a blockage in my sewer line in the basement; the
dishwasher backed up through the cleanout in the basement pipeline.
How can I unblock it?
</P>
<P>
   CAROLYN, Winchester, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You might be able to loosen the debris by inserting a snake
into the line through the cleanout; then send a lot of water down
the line to float the debris further down, hoping that the blockage
will continue to break up. The ony other recourse is to call good
old Roto-Rooter, which claims to be able to cut through any
blockage.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My rubber roof was installed three years ago. One of the
seams has lifted and is leaking, enough so that water runs through
a light fixture. How can I fix it? I have called the roofer without
success.
</P>
<P>
   ROB JOHN, Beverly, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. While a roof is usually warranted by the roofer for only a
year, I think he is still responsible, or should be, to fix the
leak. I suggest you cover the leak with a tarp, but don't touch the
seam; the tarp will at least prevent most water from coming in.
Have your lawyer write a nice letter to the roofer; and the roofer
should get the message. If that fails, have another roofer fix the
leak, if you can find one willing to do someone else's work.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(The Handyman chats on line about house matters Thursdays, 1-2 p.m.
To participate, point your Internet browser to www.boston.com and
use the keyword: Chat.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
