A7608 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KIDS'-MUSEUM-HNS &LR;      03-04 0843
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KIDS'-MUSEUM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERKSHIRE MUSEUM'S TOY EXHIBIT IS A FOUNTAIN OF YOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: With KIDS-MUSEUM-QUIZ)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. _ There is an antidote to the velvet-roped,
don't-touch, guard-scowling, no-talking, no-running, no-singing,
no-dancing, no-throwing, no-laughing, no-fun museum experience.
</P>
<P>
   No fooling. In fact, there is a museum where kids are welcome,
yelling is allowed, throwing is encouraged and scurrying feet
across hardwood floors is accepted. And those are the parents.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkshire Museum, home to fine art and sculptures and hermit
crabs and snakes, is now exhibiting childhood memories. It is a
hands-on trip down years past where today's kids can start making
their own fond remembrances. And adults can relive theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is wild. I am in my glory,'' said Joanna Navone, 35, of
West Springfield, Mass. ``I brought my kids to play here, and I'm
having more fun.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a sound of perpetual squealing and motion, except for
the adults who plop in chairs in front of a television (with a
covering to make it look like a monstrous old Philco set) that
plays loops of classic toy commercials.
</P>
<P>
   The toys themselves, well, you've heard of them before. If there
were a toy hall of fame, they would be the Ruths and DiMaggios and
Aarons: The Duncan Yo-Yo. Frisbee. Hot Wheels. Colorforms. Barbie.
G.I. Joe. Erector set. Lego. Lincoln logs. Silly Putty. Slinky.
Magic ``8'' Ball. Play-Doh. View-Master. Flexible Flyer (the sled).
Radio Flyer (the red steel wagon). Matchbox cars. Pez. The
Easy-Bake Oven. And more.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Easy-Bake Oven in turquoise is the '60s dream kitchen,''
sighed Sharon Wolf, 41, of Saddle River, N.J., as she looked at
just such a model. ``They made a yellow one, but it had to be
turquoise.''
</P>
<P>
   The 4,500-square-foot exhibit, which runs through May 30 (before
going on a nationwide tour), not only displays the toys of the
1930s to 1960s that remain in production, but also the even more
nostalgic advertising that went with them.
</P>
<P>
   You'll be shocked at just how stupid the ``Slinky'' theme song
is. Then again, you will also be singing it the whole way home.
</P>
<P>
   There are no Cabbage Patch dolls, or Teletubbies, or Beanie
Babies. To make the cut for this exhibit, the toys had to remain
popular through at least several generations.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are toys that have become icons in today's society,''
said Amy G. Burger, the museum's assistant director of marketing.
``They have stood the test of time. We played with them. Our
parents played with them. Our kids played with them. Our kids' kids
will probably play with them.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost as striking as seeing some of these toys again are the
stories behind them. For example, two of the most resilient toys on
the market were created as a result of World War II _ and by
accident.
</P>
<P>
   In 1943, Richard James was an engineer in the Cramp Shipyard in
Philadelphia, charged with the responsibility of creating a
mechanism for measuring horsepower on a battleship. One day he
dropped an inner spring to the apparatus he was working on. The
spring hopped across the floor.
</P>
<P>
   What a wonderful, wonderful toy. For wonderful girls and boys.
</P>
<P>
   The Slinky was born. Although James left his family in 1960 to
join a cult in Bolivia (not mentioned in the exhibit), Slinky
remains in production today (forget the plastic ones; stick to
metal), with alternative uses ranging from gutter protectors to
pigeon repellers to makeshift antennas popular among the troops
during the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Around the same time the Slinky was invented, James Wright was
working in a New Haven, Conn., lab for the General Electric Co.,
trying to find a synthetic substitute for rubber, since America's
supply to the vital component in the Far East was cut off by the
Japanese. He mixed boric acid with silicone oil, with lousy
results.
</P>
<P>
   But the stuff did bounce high. And it could clean typewriter
keys, remove lint, strengthen wrists during exercise and serve as
makeshift earplugs. For some reason, it could also lift print off a
newspaper. It was putty. It was silly. And Silly Putty remains with
us long after the war ended.
</P>
<P>
   Although some toys can be played in the solitude of a child's
room, many were made to be shared (one-person Wiffle Ball is pretty
boring). And many toys like Erector sets required dexterity and
thought _ developmental motion _ rather than merely steady eyes
glued to a computer screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It brought me back, good memories of childhood,'' said Joe
Testa, 47, of Dalton, Mass., ``when there was more imagination,
more interaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Toys that required you to run and laugh and squeal, and no
velvet ropes were required. No fooling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (``Kid Stuff: Great Toys from Our Childhood'' runs through May
30 at the Berkshire Museum, 39 South Street, Pittsfield, MA 01201.
Admission is $6 for adults, $5 for seniors, $4 for children 3-18
and children under 3 are free. For information call 413-443-7171.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
