<SLUG> BC-KIDS'-MUSEUM-QUIZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEST YOUR TOY KNOWLEDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSFIELD, Mass. _ You know the toys and games of your youth.
You remember them better than what you had for breakfast. But let's
see how much you know about the background of your childhood
playthings. Take this test from the Berkshire Museum.
</P>
<P>
   1. This game was originally rejected in 1934 because it had ``52
fundamental errors.''
</P>
<P>
   2. This product initially crashed in the 1950s under the cosmic
name ``Pluto Platters,'' but soared when the original unofficial
nickname of its unmarketed 1920s predecessor was restored.
</P>
<P>
   3. Architect John Lloyd Wright, the son of famed architect Frank
Lloyd Wright, came up with the idea for this toy based on his
father's 1916 design of Tokyo's Imperial Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   4. The name of this toy comes from ``leg godt,'' Danish for
``play well.''
</P>
<P>
   5. Johnny Gruelle came up with the concept for this toy in 1906,
after his daughter found an old, tattered doll in her grandmother's
attic.
</P>
<P>
   6. This toy actually was first used as a weapon centuries ago in
the Philippines; its name means ``come back'' in Tagalog, a native
language.
</P>
<P>
   7. Safety concerns prompted changes in 1964 in this toy that
initially required the use of fruit and/or vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   8. In 1958, this product cost Ohio Art $25,000 to license, five
times the existing record, even though they originally rejected it.
</P>
<P>
   9. Joshua L. Cowen invented this toy as an ``animated
advertisement'' that went around in a storefront window. The toy
was given his middle name.
</P>
<P>
   10. This toy was originally used as a nontoxic compound for
cleaning wallpaper.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ANSWERS: 1. Monopoly 2. Frisbee 3. Lincoln Logs 4. Lego 5.
Raggedy Ann 6. Yo-Yo 7. Mr. Potato Head 8. Etch A Sketch 9. Lionel
trains 10. Play-Doh.
</P>
</TEXT>
