<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-DRUG </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. DRUG WAR SHOULD FOCUS MORE ON DEMAND  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARED IN THE MARCH 4 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
 WAR-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Critics of the annual certification of Mexico as a
partner in fighting illegal drugs are right to decry the
presidential decree as a ``sham'' and a ``whitewash'' by the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   It is. And it's a shame a federal law makes us do it every year.
</P>
<P>
   More shameful, however, is our own tepid acknowledgement of the
real problem in battling illegal drug use. With a seemingly
insatiable appetite for poison, Americans are the greatest enemy in
this national fight.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing _ not a mirror held to our stoned faces, not the
burden of hypocrisy _ stops the words and deeds that annually
jeopardize the mutually beneficial relationship between the nation
and our dear neighbors to the south.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had my way,'' U.S. Rep. E. Clay Shaw Jr., R-Fla., said
this week as decertification legislation was introduced, ``I'd stop
every truck coming across the border and unload it.''
</P>
<P>
   Now isn't that a terrific way to promote trade and goodwill
between the two countries?
</P>
<P>
   Shaw believes the United States should take unilateral action
against Mexico and impose stiffer sanctions against one of our
strongest economic and political allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``These weapons of mass destruction (drugs) are killing
Americans,'' Shaw said, offering up his argument to treat Mexico as
we treat Iraq. ``These weapons of mass destruction are contributing
to growing crime in America.''
</P>
<P>
   But these ``weapons'' are harmless unless put to use by millions
of Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico can be blamed for making it too easy for drug traffickers
to do business in the United States. About 60 percent of the
cocaine and half the methamphetamine and marijuana that is smuggled
into the United States comes across the 2,000-mile U.S-Mexico
border.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican government lacks the resources and at times the
unimpugned leadership to fight well-armed, well-endowed drug
cartels. Clinton administration officials acknowledged last week
that corruption in Mexico seems to be at an all-time high.
</P>
<P>
   But Mexico cannot be blamed for drug habits in the United
States. Americans snort, pop, smoke and shoot about $50 billion
worth of illegal drugs every year.
</P>
<P>
   It makes little sense to impose economic sanctions against a
struggling neighbor whose healthy future is vital to the interests
of the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico is cooperating with us in the battle for our lives,''
President Clinton said in announcing his decision to renew
certification. ``(President Ernesto Zedillo) cannot win this battle
alone. And neither can we.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the nation has tried to prevent dope from reaching
our borders. Emphasis on reducing demand only now is getting some
of the attention it deserves in our national plans. The White House
Office of Drug Policy is directing more money in its $17.1 billion
budget for prevention and treatment. A major ad campaign is the
most visible sign of the goal to reduce demand.
</P>
<P>
   But the emphasis on interdiction continues.
</P>
<P>
   Mexico has a new $400 million battle plan to fight drug
traffickers by land, air and sea. It won't be effective without a
strong plan in the United States that targets the hearts, heads and
bloodstreams of millions of Americans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
