<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7611 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      03-04 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONICA'S MESSAGE WINS OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Turns out the Beltway babblers underestimated her, and
so did the rest of us. After 15 months of constant media coverage,
thousands of pages of depositions, X-rated diaries, taped telephone
conversations and a strategically unlaundered blue dress, we
figured the only meaningful revelation to emerge from the Monica
Lewinsky saga had to do with the significance of dry cleaning.
</P>
<P>
   But, no.
</P>
<P>
   What Monica Lewinsky has demonstrated most clearly is the
complete insignificance of capital punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Just look at what happened Wednesday in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day the ABC television network scheduled Barbara
Walters' two-hour interview with Monica, Arizona scheduled the
execution of murderer Walter LaGrand.
</P>
<P>
   The killing of LaGrand was to follow the execution last week of
his half brother, Karl, the two of them convicted of the 1982
murder of bank manager Kenneth Hartsock and attempted murder of
teller Dawn Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   The brothers were born in Bavaria to a German mother and
separate U.S. Army fathers. Over the past month or so, German
officials ranging from its ambassador to its chancellor have asked
Arizona officials to cancel or at least postpone the executions.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Dee Hull turned them down, saying Tuesday, ``In the
interest of justice and with the victims in mind, I have decided to
allow this execution to go forward as scheduled.'' &QL; 
GIRL TALKING, MAN DYING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LaGrand died an ugly suffocating death in the state gas chamber
about the same time Monica told Barbara on TV that Bill Clinton is
``a very sensual man who has a lot of sensual feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the two events _ the man dying or the girl talking _ which do
you figure was more eagerly anticipated by the general public?
</P>
<P>
   Which was more interesting?
</P>
<P>
   Which are they talking about now around the water cooler?
</P>
<P>
   For this I believe we must say, ``Thank you, Monica.''
</P>
<P>
   We live in a place and at a time in which croaking a guy isn't
nearly as interesting as watching a 25-year-old former intern
declare, ``From the beginning there was a very intense sexual
attraction (between her and Clinton), and I don't necessarily think
a sexual attraction is a bad thing. I didn't feel that way _ and I
still don't.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Walter LaGrand told a state clemency board, ``No
one, me, Karl, anyone, has the right to take another life and that
includes the state of Arizona and the United States of America.''
</P>
<P>
   He's wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The state has the right to kill a murderer if it wants to. In
fact, Arizona started killing criminals back in 1873, and didn't
stop until the 1960s, when the U.S. Supreme Court stopped us. We
started up again in 1992 with the execution of murderer Donald
Harding.
</P>
<P>
   Since then we've executed 15 guys, more or less. I'm guessing
there's not a person in the state who knows exactly how many, or
anyone (besides victim families) who could name them. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BESTSELLER IN THE MAKING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But we know all about Ms. Lewinsky, and want to know even more,
which is why the book about her, ``Monica's Story,'' is about to
hit the bestseller list.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of execution is to send society a message about
justice, accountability, revenge. And, now that we've executed a
bunch of bad guys, the message seems pretty clear:
</P>
<P>
   Killing doesn't mean much.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that's not exactly what we had hoped to get across
to the punks on the street.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrand's lawyers were able to delay his scheduled afternoon
execution. But not for long.
</P>
<P>
   He died Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Even the most stringent supporters of the death penalty must be
upset with that development.
</P>
<P>
   They have no problem with execution. But killing Walter before
he had a chance to watch Barbara's interview with Monica, that was
cruel and unusual. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
