<HEADER>
A7619 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEBANON-HASHISH-$ADV2     03-04 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEBANON-HASHISH-$ADV20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HEZBOLLAH MOVES IN TO COMPENSATE WHERE DRUG CROPS ONCE MADE
FARMERS RICH
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add that begins at 775 words.
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Ali Salwan.
 &HT;    For Use Sat., March 6 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAI, Lebanon _ The farmers in the fertile Bekaa Valley
longingly recall the good ol' days, when lush fields of hashish and
opium provided for BMWs, chic leather jackets and schooling for
their children at prestigious American universities.
</P>
<P>
   That came to an end in the early 1990s. With pressure and help
from the United States, Lebanese army tractors plowed up the crops
and soldiers enforced tough anti-drug laws.
</P>
<P>
   In a report released this week(CQ), the U.S. State Department
praised the near-total elimination of drug crops in the Bekaa
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   But, the victory for America's war on drugs is also a public
relations triumph for the anti-American Hezbollah, which has come
to the aid of farmers while international bureaucracies struggle to
provide alternatives for drug farmers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah is the answer,'' says Mohammad Shammas, a
48-year-old farmer who used to grow hashish and now raises
chickens. Sitting in a house that is large but rundown, he ticks
off the benefits of Hezbollah: ``They pay money. They build
schools. They do everything.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Hezbollah is not the only group trying to help the
farmers. But, the centerpiece effort, by the United Nations, has
had only mixed results. A U.S. program shows potential, but is
still new, and the Lebanese government has done little. Meanwhile,
Hezbollah, has been able to play Robin Hood against the perceived
injustices of the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``One could argue that (the drug) program ended the empire of
hashish,'' said Nizar Hamzeh, an expert on Hezbollah at the
American University in Beirut. ``(But) the consequence was
basically boosting the image of Hezbollah . . . These people are
really depending on Hezbollah aid.''
</P>
<P>
   The chaos of the 16-year Lebanese civil war, ending in 1991,
allowed farmers in this large plain near the Syrian border to
openly cultivate drugs for export to Europe and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations estimates that as many as 65,000 farms were
involved. Farmers say hashish is no more dangerous than alcohol,
and they deny responsibility for what was done with the opium. They
claim they were promised help by their government.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they were going to pay us something for what we
lost, but they didn't,'' says farmer Ali Salwan, 64, who has sold a
car, carpets and appliances since he gave up hashish farming. He
says he now grows wheat at barely 15 percent the price of cannabis.
</P>
<P>
   The Bekaa is now one of the poorest areas of Lebanon. Houses are
sparsely-furnished and dilapidated. The poverty is not at the level
of some African or Latin American nations, but drinking water is in
short supply, youth are moving to the crowded cities and per capita
income is around $1,700 a year.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Hezbollah, the Iranian-backed ``Party of
God,'' has been strong in the region and has used it to base
training camps for guerrillas fighting Israel's 17-year-occupation
of southern Lebanon. At night, Hezbollah recruits can be seen
goose-stepping along the narrow country roads.
</P>
<P>
   Hezbollah became infamous in the 1980s, when it was blamed for a
series of kidnappings. The U.S. government considers it a terrorist
organization. In the last two weeks, it has displayed its
battlefield skill by killing seven Israelis, including a brigadier
general.
</P>
<P>
   But, it is also a political party in the Lebanese parliament and
a social network that builds schools and hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The party subsidizes poor families with $200 to $500 a month and
gives money for tractors, fertilizers and even irrigation systems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hezbollah is against drugs and our (Muslim) religion is
against drugs,'' says Hezbollah Sheikh Nabil Kaouk. ``(But)
supporting people in the Bekaa comes from our belief in helping the
poor.''
</P>
<P>
   The primary need for the valley is water. Most legal crops need
more water than hashish. The farmers also need loans, healthcare,
access to markets and expertise for crops they may not have grown
before.
</P>
<P>
   The State Department narcotics report said the UN's program to
address those needs has spent its money ``inefficiently,'' and UN
officials acknowledge they have not raised half the $50 million
needed for the valley.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the U.S. Agency for International Development, or
USAID, began a five-year project aimed at helping rural communities
throughout Lebanon. The Bekaa portion has spent about $2.2 million
in 74 villages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are a number of issues with availability of
water, marketing of new crops, viability of new crops,'' said
Lebanon USAID mission director James Stephenson. ``This takes time.
There is no quick fix. (But) I would be optimistic that those
problems can be solved.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional trim follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The USAID program is new, but it uses contributions from the
farmers themselves and expertise from the American University in
Beirut. Providing skills and markets, it could promise a better
future than Hezbollah's subsidy approach.
</P>
<P>
   That, ultimately, might be fine with Hezbollah. Analyst Hamzeh
said the Bekaa work stretches the party's budget. Sheikh Kaouk
acknowledges, ``financially, we are limited. There are other places
we need to spend.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
