<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARBIE: ALL DOLLED UP EVEN AT 40 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATE GURNETT  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Barbie. Revered, reviled, renewed, tatooed and
debunked.
</P>
<P>
   As if that weren't enough, now she turns 40. On March 9. Don't
expect a midlife crisis. Crow's-feet don't sell.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe a career change. It's Barbie's favorite catharsis! She's
had 75, from surgeon to ambassador to rock star.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, ole Babs is probably closer to 56 (Remember, she was a
teen-age model when she debuted in March 1959 for $3.)
</P>
<P>
   So today, in her tiny arched feet and her favorite color (pink),
Barbie can smile without a care while those around her reflect on
her life. Her tens of thousands of collectors include celebrities
such as Demi Moore, Roseanne and Danielle Steele. As a child,
singer Ru-Paul collected Barbies and cut off their breasts. Drag
queens say Barbie makes the perfect model: broad shoulders, narrow
hips and ample bosom.
</P>
<P>
   For such fans, the Mattel Inc. doll's got it all over other
American icons, argues M.G. Lord, author of ``Forever Barbie: The
Unauthorized Biography of a Real Doll'' (William Morrow and Co.
Inc., 1994).
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Elvis or Marilyn or even Madonna, Barbie will never
bloat. Or wrinkle, rot or overdose.
</P>
<P>
   Lord, who cross-dressed her own Ken doll as a girl, admits to
having a Midge complex (those feelings of inferiority that stem
from hanging out with Barbie's second-fiddle friend). In pursuit of
the truth about this plastic doll that still rings up $2 billion in
annual sales, Lord uncovered some little-known Barbie data. Such
as: Our very own Babs is based on a German hooker doll called the
Bild Lilli, a postwar gag gift for men sold in tobacco shops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether more or less naked, Lilli is always discreet,''
proclaimed one brochure promoting Lilli's wardrobe.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's first outfits (she began with 22) were sewn by Japanese
housewives. The doll was manufactured in Tokyo; manufacturers here
said it couldn't be done. Included was a girdle. (Maybe it doubled
as a sports bra?)
</P>
<P>
   Barbie's official name is Barbie Millicent Roberts from Willows,
Wis., though her creator Ruth Handler lived in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   She's a Pisces, sensitive and moody. That might explain all the
wardrobe changes.
</P>
<P>
   Early marketing studies found mothers complaining that Barbie
was too suggestive. Girls, however, liked the doll.
</P>
<P>
   Handler fought against the desires of male executives to have a
bulge added to the Ken doll's groin. She won. Handler blocked
efforts to have Barbie wed _ or breed. And no vacuuming. Barbie
doesn't do ``rough housework.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, Mattel introduced Living Barbie, whose jointed ankles
permitted her to walk flat-footed. A year later, the model was
discontinued.
</P>
<P>
   In 1971, Barbie's eyes, which had been cast down and to one side
on a gaze common in early paintings of pornographic nudes, were
changed. Malibu Barbie looked straight ahead.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984, when Mattel faced financial ruin, the company was saved
by junk bond king Michael Milken and others who invested $231
million _ based on Barbie's profitable track record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the new astronaut Barbie ditched her puffy 1965
spacesuit for a hot pink miniskirt, a clear plastic helmet, a sleek
pink bodysuit and silver space lingerie. And then, there was the
new ``realistic'' Barbie who debuted with smaller measurements last
year.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Mattel fought slumping sales with Butterfly Art
Barbie, who sports a butterfly tattoo on her stomach.
</P>
<P>
   But what of Barbie's ``real'' family? Handler was a stenographer
at Paramount Pictures before she and her husband Elliot, a
furniture designer and art student, created the Barbie doll.
Elliot, who used Plexiglas, lucite and plastic in his furniture,
transferred the technology to the doll.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ruth Handler named the Barbie and Ken dolls after her
children, Barbie and Ken.
</P>
<P>
   No, Ken didn't model himself after the doll. (Although his
sister stuck pretty close to the Barbie doctrine, he told Lord.)
</P>
<P>
   If Ken Handler had his way, Barbie and Ken would parrot his
lifestyle: Train as ethnobotanists, study the curative values of
the South American rain forests, ``tan themselves in the sweat of
the equatorial jungle sun and give themselves to people that
desperately need to learn from them.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did the real Ken encourage his children play with the Barbie
doll. ``This bimba ... never has a serious thought,'' he told Lord.
``And she has a figure no young lady could ever achieve without a
severe anorexic leaning or surgery.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
