<P>
   &UR; FOR FRIDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Friday, March 5:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR (Camp Lejeune, N.C.) _ A court martial acquits
Capt. Richard Ashby, accused of manslaughter in the deaths of 20
skiers in Italy. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BLACKMUN (Washington) _ Former Justice Harry Balckmun, who
wrote the majority opinion in the 1973 landmark abortion case, Roe
vs. Wade, has died at 90. By Linda Greenhouse. (4800 words)
</P>
<P>
   Eds, we will also file a shorter version of about 2400 words.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIEF (Washington) _ The House stalls an emergency
Central American relief bill on the eve of President Clinton's trip
to the region, as both House and Senate committees seek to cut
coveted administration anti-poverty programs to pay for Hurricane
Mitch aid and stay within budget caps. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-EDUC (Washington) _ The Senate votes on education
issues. By Lizette Alvare.
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-REACT (Washington) _ Reaction to last night's Monica
Lewinsky interview.
</P>
<P>
   (See also the review of her book, listed below under
ENTERTAINMENT.)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-APPOINT (Washington) _ The Clinton administration names
an Ohio State law professor, Peter Swire, to new post coordinating
privacy policies across federal government. By Joel Brinkley. (500
words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SCIENCE &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LA-QUAKE (Undated) _ Using information once jealously
guarded by oil and gas companies, scientists have identified a
major new fault under downtown Los Angeles. Called the Puente Hills
blind thrust, the fault, which is active, lies hidden in the
basement of the metropolitan area and is capable of producing a
devastating earthquake. Scientists have inferred the existence of
such faults under the city for many years but this is the first
solid proof that one actually exists. By Sandra Blakeslee. (1100
words)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-IMMORTAL-CELLS (Undated) _ A gene that confers
fountain-of-youth properties on human cells grown in laboratory
glassware has now been tested in mice to see if its absence will
cause the opposite effect, that of premature aging. The answer is
yes, in part. The findings, reported Friday in the journal Cell,
sustains but does not yet fulfill the hope that manipulations of
the gene will provide treatments for cancer, heart disease and
other maladies of aging human tissues. By Nicholas Wade (1400
words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SHRINKING-ICESHEET (Undated) _ The southern half of the
Greenland ice sheet, the second largest expanse of land-bound ice
on earth after Antarctica, has shrunk substantially in the last
five years, scientists have found in airborne surveys using new and
more precise techniques. The finding is important because
mainstream scientists predict that global warming, now under way,
will partially melt the planet's ice sheets, causing sea level to
rise and perhaps disrupting ocean currents that modulate the
earth's climate by distributing heat around the globe. By William
K. Stevens. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BALLOONISTS (Undated) _ Two British hot-air balloonists,
still bidding to circle the world non-stop, have broken the
distance record. By Malcolm W. Browne. (800 words)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.S. (Dateline to kum) _ Developments on U.S. policy in
Kosovo. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   And
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO (Pristina) _ Developments in the troubled Yugoslav
province. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-VIOLENCE (Belfast) _ As the formal peace process moves
