<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7636 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS07-COX     03-04 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    As academia embraces lies of `larger truth,' true scholar
prevails
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Rigoberta Menchu and the Story of All Poor Guatemalans. By
David Stoll. Westview Press. $27. 400 pages.
</P>
<P>
   If you enrolled at the University of Maine in the fall of 1996,
there was one book you could be certain you would read. The book
was ``I, Rigoberta Menchu,'' by the winner of the 1992 Nobel Peace
Prize.
</P>
<P>
   The memoir of a Mayan woman who claims to have seen family
members tortured and burned alive during Guatemala's civil war,
``I, Rigoberta Menchu'' was chosen as the ``class book'' for the
Class of 2000. If you wanted to graduate, you read it. And you
would read it in more places than just the University of Maine. On
campuses in this country and others, it is required reading.
</P>
<P>
   If the Nobel Peace Prize is the secular equivalent of
canonization, Menchu has been sainted by the academy as well. Her
testimonio was the authentic voice of indigenous peoples in the New
World and of women everywhere, a young girl denied an education,
sent into the coffee fields to work from sunup to sundown,
traumatized by the death of her brother and her father at the hands
of the Guatemalan army. It has become a cornerstone of the
multicultural curriculum, so much so that it is read in courses
where you might least expect it _ English, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Now it turns out that her book is not entirely true _ is, in
fact, false in significant respects. The academic left, tremulous
in its reverence for the author, has egg on its face yet again. But
so, too, does the Nobel Prize Committee, along with journalists who
never thought to question Menchu's story. In the wake of so much
farce, one brave scholar, David Stoll, an anthropologist at
Middlebury College, deserves a prize of his own, not the Nobel
perhaps but something on the order of the Purple Heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rigoberta Menchu and the Story of All Poor Guatemalans''
demythologizes a Mayan woman whose presence elicits tears on
campuses and a book that has been translated into 12 languages. The
author herself claims that some 15,000 scholarly papers _ assiduous
as biblical commentaries _ have been written on her book since its
publication in 1982.
</P>
<P>
   Stoll realizes he has committed heresy, but he is not without
sympathy for Menchu. When he first heard her story, he was disposed
to believe it like anyone else. But during the 1980s, while he was
interviewing victims of Guatemala's political violence, he stumbled
upon first one fact and then another that didn't fit. Menchu, he
learned, was not an uneducated peasant's daughter, but a girl who
had been sent to a Catholic boarding school. She picked no coffee
and her father was not cheated out of his land by rich ladinos
(Guatemalans of European descent). He lost it in a dispute with his
Mayan in-laws.
</P>
<P>
   No one is so romantic as the hero-worshipping academic, and no
one quicker to hiss when the daydream is punctured. ``Whether her
book is true or not, I don't care,'' Marjorie Agosin, head of the
Spanish department at Wellesley College, told the Chronicle of
Higher Education. For the true believers, it represents that
all-purpose ``larger truth,'' malleable as putty in constructing
multicultural illusions. It's the same hear-nothing, know-nothing
response that followed revelations of Tawana Brawley's
fabrications. Patricia Williams of the Harvard Law School said it
mattered little that Tawana's story of rape was without factual
basis. It was true in a symbolic sense. (The rights and reputation
of the accused apparently didn't matter either.)
</P>
<P>
   In Menchu's case, there was enough truth that fabrication ought
not have been necessary. Only a little more than a week ago, a
United Nations commission concluded that the CIA had given money
and training to the Guatemalan military, and had abetted ``acts of
genocide'' against Mayans during the country's civil war.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions this, least of all Stoll. Menchu's father was
in fact burned alive, her brother was executed by the army and her
mother did ``disappear.'' But none of it happened as she describes;
some of it happened quite differently. The fire in which her father
died, during a takeover of the Spanish embassy in 1980, was sparked
by the guerrillas' Molotov cocktails. When violence is cyclical,
Stoll argues, identifying victims and victimizers cannot be done
with the moral certitude that graduate students and assistant
professors on distant campuses would like to believe.
</P>
<P>
   But they believe anyway. It is a psychological need, and books
such as Menchu's, Stoll writes, ``will be exalted because they tell
academics what they want to hear. ... The simplistic images of
innocence, oppression and defiance can be used to construct
mythologies of purity for academic factions claiming moral
authority on the grounds that they identify with the oppressed.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, inevitably, that authority collapses, like a sinkhole.
If books such as Menchu's are going to be required reading, then
Stoll's is more necessary still _ as a corrective to an
intellectual bankruptcy that is not merely accepted but embraced.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: mskube(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
