<HEADER>
A7640 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-NOTES04-COX     03-04 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-NOTES04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conroy first to win Stanley Lindberg award
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For more than two decades, Stanley Lindberg has been
an unsung hero on Georgia's literary scene. As editor of the
Georgia Review, he transformed the magazine into an award-winning
publication. In 1985, he organized the successful Roots of Georgia
conference, bringing together all of the state's top writers, from
James Dickey to Erskine Caldwell. And in 1996, he brought Toni
Morrison and other Nobel laureates to Atlanta as part of the
Cultural Olympiad.
</P>
<P>
   All of this he did with little fanfare or self-promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Now Lindberg is scheduled to be honored alongside another
Georgia writer who is not so unsung. On April 24, Pat Conroy will
receive the first Stanley W. Lindberg Award in ceremonies at the
Georgia Center for Continuing Education beginning at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Novelist Terry Kay, who will deliver the opening remarks,
praised Lindberg as ``one of the most important figures in the
history of letters in the South. We felt it was proper to honor him
by establishing a career-achievement award in his name.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stanley W. Lindberg Award will be given every two years to a
person who has contributed substantially to the literary culture of
Georgia through a lifetime body of work. The event is co-sponsored
by the Georgia Center for the Book, a statewide program that
celebrates books, reading and literacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a totally unexpected and humbling experience to be
honored in this fashion _ and somewhat unusual, I understand, for
one to enjoy such homage while still alive to blush,'' says
Lindberg, who has been editor of the Georgia Review since 1977. ``I
am, of course, deeply grateful to those who have defined and
established this worthy prize, and I salute Pat Conroy as its
distinguished first recipient.''
</P>
<P>
   Conroy is best known for his rich, lyrical style and for the
series of highly successful movies made from his books, but the
author of ``The Great Santini'' and ``Beach Music'' was also
extremely influential in establishing a writing community in
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Pat moved to Atlanta in 1973, there were fewer than 10
people in Georgia being published by major houses,'' Kay says.
``Within three years, a number of people were being published.
Pat's influence, either directly or indirectly, played a role in
all that.''
</P>
<P>
   Tickets to the black-tie event in Athens are $40 each. The
reservations deadline is April 12. Checks should be made payable to
the University of Georgia and mailed to the Stanley W. Lindberg
Award at the Georgia Center for Continuing Education, University of
Georgia, Athens, GA 30602-3603, along with the name and address of
the person who will be attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Lindberg award, Conroy is scheduled to
receive the Grand Master Award at the Writing Today conference
March 12-13 at Birmingham-Southern College. Previous winners
include Dickey, Caldwell, Ray Bradbury and Edward Albee.
</P>
<P>
   Gurganus at work on novellas
</P>
<P>
   If Allan Gurganus had listened to his readers, he would have
written a half-dozen sequels to his best-selling tome, ``Oldest
Living Confederate Widow Tells All.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 51-year-old writer went in a different direction.
His latest book, ``Plays Well With Others'' (Random House, $14
paperback), depicts the gay art scene in New York in the 1980s. The
book sold well, he says, but reviews were mixed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always some initial resistance when you present a book
that's unlike your other books,'' says Gurganus, who will be here
next week to sign books. ``Some people were bothered that I would
write a comic novel about something as dark as the pandemic.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurganus, a North Carolina native who moved back from New York
to the Chapel Hill area recently, has been working on a book of
five novellas, ``Fables for Adults,'' which will be published next
spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Peter Taylor defined a novella as a work of fiction you can
pick up after dinner and finish before bedtime. It's a perfect
length for the way people read now and the way we live now. I love
that length. You can have all of the intensity of the novel yet
leave out the secondary characters who walk on for comic relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurganus will be at Borders Books and Music in Atlanta (3637
Peachtree Road N.E., 404-237-0707) at 7 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
