<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7641 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-PRETTYGIRL07-CO     03-04 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-PRETTYGIRL07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nijinsky: Portrait of the artist as a madman
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Nijinsky myth has come down to us as a titillating mixture
of sex and madness. We have the photographs of the great Russian
dancer _ the faun in the fig leaf, the slave prancing ecstatically
in yards of gold lame. And we have the diary, which he wrote in
1917-1918 as he leapt full throttle into schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky'' _ widely believed to be the
only first-person, on-the-spot account of a major artist's collapse
into psychosis _ is a harrowing book. Losing one's mind is not
romantic. But, oh, how we like to think it is.
</P>
<P>
   Look a little deeper into van Gogh's swirling rosettes, Sylvia
Plath's self-lacerating verse or Nijinsky's confessions and you
won't see much to commend the process of going crazy. It is a sad,
sordid business, made worse by the fact that we, the witnesses,
tend to recoil in horror. But isn't it ourselves that we grieve
for?
</P>
<P>
   No one knew that better than Nijinsky's wife, Romola. When she
first published her husband's diary, in 1936, it was a heavily
edited, self-serving version that tried to put a benign spin on
Nijinsky's homosexuality, among other things. It did the trick.
Though Nijinsky was to live under lock and key until he was 60, the
diary had imbued him with an aura of early autumn.
</P>
<P>
   ``He became a symbol for that part of us that, in fantasy, takes
off for the high hills, as opposed to the part that stays home,''
Joan Acocella writes in the introduction to this newly restored
version, freshly translated by Kyril FitzLyon. ``Nijinsky had
always been famous for his jump. As witnesses describe it, he would
rise and then pause in the air before coming down. Now, it seemed,
he had declined to come down.''
</P>
<P>
   Acocella _ the dance critic for The New Yorker, who has written
a biography of choreographer Mark Morris and co-authored a textbook
on abnormal psychology _ goes about her scholarship with authority
and passion. In her insightful essay and annotations, she makes a
case for Nijinsky's genius, rather than relegating him to the file
of psychological oddity or cult personality. She restores the
integrity of his text _ and brings him to the attention of a new
generation of readers. I only wish someone had remembered to
include an index.
</P>
<P>
   Those looking for a lurid memoir may be disappointed by this
``unexpurgated'' diary. Though Nijinsky lived openly with Ballet
Russes director Sergei Diaghilev _ and was a star dancer of that
international ensemble _ he was by his own account a lover of
women. His marriage to Romola de Pulszky in 1913 was a slap in the
face to Diaghilev. As their relationship crumbled, so did
Nijinsky's health.
</P>
<P>
   Like any portrait of a madman, this is a strange little book, at
times reading like surrealistic fiction by Kafka or Borges. ``I
will build a bridge between Europe and America that will not cost
much,'' Nijinsky writes. ``I already know the method for building
this bridge, because God has told me.''
</P>
<P>
   The memoir often finds Nijinsky raging against his enemies and
worshipping his heroes. He has adopted the all-embracing empathy of
Tolstoy and believes that man is losing his sense of ``feeling.''
He is obsessed with his bodily functions and tries to give up
eating meat. He not only believes in his kinship with God, but that
he is God. He even
</P>
<P>
   signs one of the volumes ``God Nijinsky.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyone fascinated by the fragmentation of the human psyche
should read this book. But be forewarned: It can be painful.
Waiting for Nijinsky's wife and mother-in-law to take him to the
asylum is like waiting for a ride to the charnel house. ``I heard
the voice of my little Kyra,'' Nijinsky writes of his 3-year-old
daughter in the final pages. ``She loves me, because she wept when
I told her I was going away forever.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky: Unexpurgated Edition. Translated
from Russian by Kyril FitzLyon. Edited by Joan Acocella. Farrar,
Straus &AMP; Giroux. $30. 312 pages.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: It ends in tears.
</P>
<P>
   Wendell Brock writes about the arts and culture for The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
