<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7643 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-CRUEL05-COX     03-04 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-CRUEL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Calculated cruelty meets hopped-up high school hormones
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Advance word had described ``Cruel Intentions'' as being a high
school version of ``Dangerous Liaisons,'' and it seems that, for
once, a movie lives up to its billing. Or down to it, depending on
your perspective, which probably directly relates to how many years
have elapsed since your last prom invite.
</P>
<P>
   The two movies do share the same basic plot outline _ a couple
of desultorily rich people manipulate the romantic lives of
everyone around them, purely for their own amusement and without a
whit of concern about who may get hurt in the process. But, whereas
the 1988 Oscar-winning ``Liaisons,'' with Glenn Close and John
Malkovich, slowly and skillfully seduced viewers to fall into its
web of intrigue, ``Cruel Intentions'' comes on with all the finesse
of a horny kid with only an hour to score before Mom and Dad get
home from the mall.
</P>
<P>
   Thus does Sebastian (Ryan Phillippe) snap nude photos of his
shrink's daughter and post them on the Internet. And rub his body
all over his stepsister and fellow teenager, Kathryn (Sarah
Michelle Gellar), frequently and friskily enough to make Jerry
Falwell forget all about that little Tinky Winky problem.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, meanwhile, Kathryn engages in long,
open-mouthed kissing with the virginal Cecile (Selma Blair), who
apparently needs lessons in how it's done. And Kathryn also offers
to sleep with Sebastian if only he manages to deflower the even
more virginal Annette (Reese Witherspoon).
</P>
<P>
   All this during summer break from their elite private school,
and all within the first 30 minutes of a movie that might better
have been titled, ``I Know Who You Did Last Summer.'' And all this
practically guaranteed to make ``Cruel Intentions'' a runaway hit
with the teen audience at which it is so obviously aimed.
</P>
<P>
   After all, the key components are in place: to wit, the adult
characters who are barely there, either literally (Kathryn and
Sebastian's parents are vacationing somewhere, leaving the
teenagers to their own devices and impossibly stylish clothes in a
massive Fifth Avenue mansion) or figuratively (indeed, Christine
Baranski, as Cecile's ``image is everything'' mother, and Louise
Fletcher, as Sebastian's ditzy aunt, ought to smack their agents _
hard).
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention the stars of white-hot teen-oriented movies and
TV shows: Phillippe was in ``I Know What You Did Last Summer,''
while Gellar is TV's ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.'' And finally, the
fantasy world where people under the age of 18 spend as much time
drinking expensive champagne as they do summoning limousines and
ordering the servants around.
</P>
<P>
   Criticizing ``Cruel Intentions'' for being unrealistic, even
sexually irresponsible, would be about as pointless as a
well-meaning adult trying to convince a teenager that he or she is
really not in love for the first time. Adults probably just don't
get it in either case, although the broad laughter that greeted
some of ``Cruel Intentions' '' most emotionally charged moments at
a recent screening suggests that for some grown-ups, anyway, the
movie might prove to be amusingly entertaining viewing _ even
downright campy fun.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest of us, we'll just have to accept that young
viewers could accept that a loathsome Lothario (and occasional
over-actor) like Sebastian could be suddenly redeemed by the love
of a good virgin like Annette, or that a stiletto-heeled, oversexed
vixen (and occasional over-actress) like Kathryn might actually
show up at school often enough to be elected senior class
president.
</P>
<P>
   More likely, though, the appeal of this movie will have less to
do with the story line and more with young viewers' getting to see
people very nearly their age dress up and do the sort of risque
things they almost never get to do.
</P>
<P>
   Not unless Mom and Dad linger a little too long at the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Sarah Michelle Gellar, Ryan Phillippe, Selma Blair,
Reese Witherspoon and Joshua Jackson. Written and directed by Roger
Kumble. Rated R for sexual situations, profanity and alcohol and
drug use. 1 hour, 37 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``Dangerous Liaisons'' hits high school _ and Larry
Flynt writes the Cliffs Notes.
</P>
<P>
   Jill Vejnoska writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
