<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLASS-COLUMN07-cox     03-04 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN07-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: FEDS SEEK TO PART THE DIGITAL WATERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Mar. 7.
 &HT;    Moving in commentary (k) and business (f) queues.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON When our family goes off on vacation, we leave the
house keys with the neighbors, just in case something goes awry.
</P>
<P>
   For people who communicate on the Internet, encryption programs
are the ``house keys'' to security in the Information Age. These
programs scramble data into unreadable globs, insuring privacy.
</P>
<P>
   Encryption strength is measured in bits: the more bits, the
harder it is to crack the code. It's best to use a Web browser with
128-bit technology. Without such an industrial-strength browser,
neither my online bank nor my online broker will let me access my
files.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, the administration limited U.S. firms seeking to
communicate with their foreign suppliers or customers to low-power
40-bit encryption programs, so the government could break the code.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, federal agencies raised the ceiling to 56 bits.
Government flacks issued press releases lauding their masters for
having taken such a gracious step. Attorney General Janet Reno
pleaded with business leaders to recognize that terrorists and
criminals also use the e-mails and must be watched.
</P>
<P>
   But they told her that they needed still more security to do
business overseas. So the feds said if you want to use something
stronger than 56 bits, then you'll have to incorporate ``key
recovery'' features into your encryption programs.
</P>
<P>
   That's the cyberspace equivalent of leaving the family house
keys behind -- with the feds as the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   If the White House has its way, these ``keys'' will be stored in
massive central databases that cops can access under a court order.
It's really no different, Reno says, than the wiretap laws now on
the books that help the FBI catch spies and drug dealers.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the government argues, 56-bit keys should suffice. They
offer only one chance in 72,057,594,037,927,936 of breaking a code.
If each of these quadrillion-plus numbers were to be checked at a
rate of one per second, it would take 9 billion years to work
through the entire code set.
</P>
<P>
   In January, RSA Data Security, a software firm, offered $10,000
to the first group that could break its 56-bit encryption program.
It took a couple of hackers only 22 hours to get the job done.
</P>
<P>
   So in February, RSA set up shop in Australia to market 128-bit
programs. Nobody notified Janet Reno about the loss of U.S. jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Not that it would faze her. The attorney general hopes Congress
will pass a law that, in effect, orders anyone who does business
with the government to deposit a set of digital ``house keys.'' It
would be only a matter of time before such rules rippled through
the whole business world.
</P>
<P>
   FBI Director Louis Freeh points out that if Ramzi Yousef --
convicted of the 1993 World Trade Center bombing -- had used strong
encryption in his computer files, then his other murderous plans
might never have been known. If we can't decode it, Freeh argues,
then you shouldn't be using it.
</P>
<P>
   But the flow of cyberspace can't be turned off. And Freeh is no
Moses: he can't part the digital waters. In the long run, any
attempt to impose ``key recovery'' won't work. In the short run,
however, such efforts could cause an unholy mess by stifling
commerce and retarding the Internet's growth.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
