<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7646 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-LOCK07-COX     03-04 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-LOCK07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Director riding high _ lock, stock and barrels
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLNATA _ Some people making the rounds on a long publicity tour
cut the boredom by playing cards. Or reading. Or listening to
music.
</P>
<P>
   These lads are learning big, unwieldy words. Like ``apostasy,''
``sanguine'' and ``proselytize,'' exactly the sort of words you
won't hear in their movie ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been wondering where to use (expletive) `serendipity,'
'' says writer-director Guy Ritchie, relaxing recently at a Atlanta
pub with two of his cast members, Jason Statham and Jason Flemyng.
``We looked it up in the dictionary. Every city we go to, we win
points for who uses the longest words. And if you're in Chicago and
it begins with C, you get double points.''
</P>
<P>
   Only 30, but considered the Next Big Thing, Ritchie watched his
debut feature become the biggest-grossing British film of 1998.
(Last Monday it also nabbed a best British film nomination in
England's version of the Oscars.) ``It did $20 million, which for
the UK is a huge hit,'' he says. His movie was a crowd-pleaser at
Sundance, and he signed with a big Hollywood agency, ICM. Then
there's the Madonna thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only know her in a professional sense,'' Ritchie, 30, says
of the singer, with whom gossip columns linked him. You can tell
he's had plenty of practice saying that. (The official story: She
met him to discuss putting the soundtrack on her Maverick label.)
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie's action-comedy, opening in Atlanta on Friday, tells the
knotty story of four London East End friends (including the two
Jasons) who stake all their money on a poker game, blow it and have
to come up with half a million dollars _ or lose bits of their
anatomy piece by piece to the gangster they owe. It's been
described as a British take on Quentin Tarantino, but the movie's
tone owes as much to the helter-skelter styles of Danny Boyle
(``Trainspotting'') and Richard Lester (``Help!'').
</P>
<P>
   A comic hybrid
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand why people want to _ `compartmentalize'; that's
one of our new words,'' the director says with a grin. ``I can
understand why people want to compartmentalize it.'' (Two points
for Ritchie.) He has his own reference point for the movie: ``This
has more in common with an Ealing comedy than it does with
Tarantino,'' he says, referring to the series of dry British
comedies of the '40s and '50s, such as ``The Lavender Hill Mob''
and ``Kind Hearts and Coronets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying, incidentally, that it's completely free of the
influence of Tarantino,'' he adds. ``You just can't be anymore.''
One big difference, though: ``My movie's not taking itself too
seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, except when it comes to the matter of casting. Some of the
movie's tough guys seem authentically tough, because they are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted credibility,'' says Ritchie, who struggled for two
years to get the film funded because would-be backers wanted a
star. ``I wanted to use people who came from that world and
understood it.'' His example of the wrong way to cast a film is
``The Krays,'' which starred the pop-star Kemp brothers as the
notorious London gangsters.
</P>
<P>
   For ``Lock, Stock,'' Ritchie hired several nonprofessionals for
the cast, including Statham, 31, who spent five years selling stuff
on the streets. ``I told Guy about my shaky past and con men on the
street,'' the first-time actor says. ``He liked the fact that I had
a great understanding of the dialogue he'd written.''
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing you get with Jay (Statham) is a credibility that
might be lacking,'' says his co-star Flemyng, 32, a professional
whose acting resume ranges from Bernardo Bertolucci's ``Stealing
Beauty'' to last year's monster-movie bomb ``Deep Rising.''
``Luckily, I'm born and bred in south London. I didn't go through
the public school, Merchant-Ivory system, so I know what I'm
talking about as well. But having Jay there gives you, osmotically,
an authenticity.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Osmotically.'' (Two points for Flemyng.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a gamble, really,'' Statham says about playing the
role. ``Guy didn't know whether I'd (mess) my pants in front of the
camera.'' Meanwhile, some people behind the scenes advised the
director against casting him. ``They said I'd be the catastrophe of
the bloody film. But not to my face.''
</P>
<P>
   Vicious verisimilitude
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of faces, Ritchie himself has his own brand of street
cred: A moon-shaped scar that swoops from the left corner of his
mouth up to his ear lobe. ``When I was about 20, I got into a knife
fight,'' he says. ``Big, isn't it? It makes it look like I know
what I'm writing about.''
</P>
<P>
   His next film will also star the Jasons, along with others of
the ``Lock, Stock'' cast, in new roles. And the actors hope the
next flick will be as fun as making this one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like being in a pub,'' Statham says. ``We stood around
playing cards, telling jokes. There were hardly any serious
moments, apart from when the cameras were running.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole team was young and sort of thrilled by what they
were doing,'' Flemyng says. ``It was a break for everyone, so there
was a great feeling of sort of excitement all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Statham laughs: ``And a lot of testosterone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels''
</P>
<P>
   Starring Nick Moran, Jason Flemyng and Jason Statham. Directed
by Guy Ritchie. Rated R for language and violence. 1 hour, 46
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
