<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7647 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-TEENS07-COX     03-04 1683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-TEENS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A teen takeover at the box office is undeniable, with a flood of
flicks targeting a `younger, hipper, smarter,' generation of movie
lovers
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The most frightening things about '90s teenagers _ at least as
far as many adults were concerned _ used to be the music they
listened to and the body parts they pierced. Times have changed.
Suddenly, Marilyn Manson and nipple rings seem downright quaint
compared with the scary way teens have taken over Hollywood's box
office. It's a trend that's quickly turning anyone over 21 into
human Betamaxes: Movies simply don't fit them anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the evidence: Beginning in mid-January, two teen
movies,``Varsity Blues'' and ``She's All That,'' alternated as No.
1 and 2 at the box office for three consecutive weeks, vanquishing
such ``geezer'' flicks as Robin Williams' ``Patch Adams'' and John
Travolta's ``A Civil Action.''
</P>
<P>
   That was only the beginning of the onslaught. ``Cruel
Intentions,'' which opened Friday, had such teen buzz that a TV
series pilot is already in development. The throes-of-puberty
remake of ``Dangerous Liaisons'' is but one of nearly a dozen
``teen'' movies being released before Memorial Day (``teen'' being
loosely defined as being about or for high schoolers).
</P>
<P>
   ``Our audience is getting younger, hipper, smarter and more
interested in movies,'' Walt Disney Studios Chairman Joe Roth said.
``So we're aiming for this new generation of kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Theories abound about why this is happening now, ranging from
the population explosion of baby boomers' kids (at 60 million, it's
a group three times the size of Generation X) to the need for quick
entertainment fixes among this Internet-savvy, video-weaned group.
Then there's the ascendancy of such teen-oriented TV shows as
``Dawson's Creek'' (the star of ``Varsity Blues'' is Dawson
himself, James Van Der Beek), ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' (Sarah
Michelle Gellar, a.k.a. ``Buffy,'' stars in ``Cruel Intentions'')
and ``Party of Five.''
</P>
<P>
   But let's not forget about ``Titanic.'' Clearly, many
moviemakers looked at its record 15 straight weeks at No. 1 and
$600 million in earnings, largely due to teenage girls going back
for second, third and fourth viewings, and decided to jump on board
before they completely missed the boat.
</P>
<P>
   The teen movie trend, however, may actually have begun well
before Leonardo DiCaprio went eyeball-to-eyeball with that iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people credit `Titanic' as (being) the thing that
really opened people's eyes, but I think it was really `Clueless'
that started it,'' Isabel Walcott, founder and president of the
teen-attuned SmartGirl Internette Inc., said recently of the 1995
movie about a rich, socially savvy high schooler. ``That was such a
hit with teen girls, I think it opened people's eyes to the fact
that if they could get teenage girls especially to come to a movie,
they could make a killing.''
</P>
<P>
   But sixty killings?! Reportedly, that's how many high
school-themed films may be coming to a theater near you this year.
</P>
<P>
   Just this month alone brings ``Go,'' starring ``Dawson's Creek''
cutie Katie Holmes in a series of misadventures in Los Angeles'
underground scene. ``Scream'' star Drew Barrymore plays an adult
nerd who goes back to high school in ``Never Been Kissed,'' and
Julia Stiles (late of the TV miniseries ``The '60s'') stars in ``10
Things I Hate About You,'' a high school-based version of
Shakespeare's ``The Taming of the Shrew.'' Coming in October, ``O''
is a teenage version of another Shakespeare classic, ``Othello.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, it's ``Dawson'' cast member Michelle Williams' turn in
``Dick,'' about a pair of teenage girls (Kirsten Dunst co-stars)
lost during a tour of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Further down the pike, ``Killing Mrs. Tingle,'' again stars
Holmes in a high school story from Kevin ``Scream'' Williamson, and
on Dec. 10, expect to see ``Party of Five's'' Neve Campbell back in
``Scream 3.''
</P>
<P>
   Like so many successful movie genres, the films all may seem
somewhat familiar, even exactly alike in some cases. They also
might seem somewhat foreign to anyone over 21. So, herewith a
simple guide to the movies taking over your multiplex:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The names
</P>
<P>
   They come in threes: Besides Sarah Michelle Gellar, there's
Rachael Leigh Cook (``She's All That'') and the ubiquitous Jennifer
Love Hewitt (``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,'' ``Party of
Five''). Acceptable exceptions to this rule: Neve and Drew
(Campbell and Barrymore, of the ``Scream'' movies and the upcoming
``Never Been Kissed,'' respectively.) Or they come shortened into
cool nicknames: Usually, they are based on the character of the
actor's hit TV show. Gellar, for instance, is often referred to as
``Buffy'' (``Hey, there's Buffy!'' one teen nudged another at a
recent Atlanta showing of a movie where Gellar has a cameo.) Joshua
Jackson (``Urban Legend,'' ``Cruel Intentions'') is known as
``Pacey,'' because that's who he plays on ``Dawson's Creek.''
Acceptable exception: Hewitt, who likes to be known as _ who can
blame her? _ ``Love.'' Unacceptable exceptions: ``Mom'' or ``Dad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The hit TV shows
</P>
<P>
   The smaller the network's actual audience, the better (Hint:
Stay away from anything with nightly news broadcasts). WB may only
have several million, almost uniformly teenage viewers, but make a
movie with a ``Dawson'' or a ``Buffy'' star in it and they're there
at least once. (Lovett School senior Spencer Hux didn't like
``Varsity Blues,'' but he saw it anyway. Twice.) Acceptable
exception: Having a hit show on Fox (home of teen-themers ``Party
of Five'' and ``That '70s Show''). It's older and more successful
but still acceptably news- and viewer-lite.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The importance of staying in school
</P>
<P>
   High school, that is. ``I Know What You Did Last Summer'' did
way better than its sequel, ``I Still Know What You Did Last
Summer,'' where the characters had finally hit college. Need more
proof? Gellar played a virtual senior citizen (21) in last month's
``Simply Irresistible,'' and it bombed. Van Der Beek played a
senior in ``Varsity Blues,'' and it hit No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The right look
</P>
<P>
   When a teen star appears to have lost interest halfway through
the hair grooming process (or just like a foreign exchange student
20 years ago), it's exactly right. For girls, this means a zigzaggy
part down the middle of their straight, straight hair. For guys,
this means dying their artfully tousled hair pltinum, but only on
the top, so plenty of black shows through. Unacceptable exception:
Van Der Beek reversed the process in ``Varsity Blues,'' dying his
platinum hair black. The result was nearly as sloppy as his
Texas-by-way-of-Connecticut ``drawl.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The right wheels
</P>
<P>
   Teens in movies drive Jeeps. Or they don't drive at all.
Acceptable exception: Borrowing someone else's Jeep and driving it.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The friends
</P>
<P>
   The teenage pop star: Grammy winner Brandy played the hippest
(and therefore the unlikeliest) roommate for Hewitt's mopey, serial
murderer stalkee of a character in ``I Still Know What You Did Last
Summer.'' And the high school in ``She's All That'' apparently had
no teachers but did have a complete radio studio, so Grammy nominee
Usher could play the role of just your typical student-DJ.
Acceptable exception: Rapper-actor Will Smith (``Men in Black'') is
30 and the top-ranked celebrity on SmartGirl's latest Internet
survey of mostly teen users.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The racial mix
</P>
<P>
   It's arguably the most welcome aspect of the teen movie glut.
Nearly all the casts are integrated, and no one seems to feel the
need to explain why black and white kids are hanging out together,
even living together. In ``I Still Know What You Did Last Summer,''
Brandy was Hewitt's friend and onscreen equal (if truth be told,
she was more than her equal, showing more smarts and acting chops)
and has already signed on for the sequel's sequel. Usher was
probably the best-known teen in ``The Faculty,'' and ``She's All
That'' showed groups of white and black kids partying and going to
the beach together. Unacceptable exception: ``Scream 2'' integrated
its cast with African-American actress Jada Pinkett Smith, then
promptly killed her off. Of course, minutes later, they also killed
off Gellar.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The adults
</P>
<P>
   Uh, what adults? Grown-ups not only don't matter in these
movies, they almost don't exist. Most of the parents in ``Scream''
are either horribly murdered or off on extended business trips.
``Varsity Blues'' does have several significant adult roles, the
mean football coach and the nice teacher by day/sexy stripper by
night. Guess which one doesn't come to a horrible end? Acceptable
exception: Drew Barrymore in the upcoming ``Never Been Kissed'' is
an adult working as a newspaper copy editor who realizes the error
of her ways and goes back to being a high schooler. Unacceptable
exception: ``The Faculty'' was set in a high school, but all the
juicy roles (i.e., the aliens masquerading as teachers) went to
adults. It didn't exactly burn up the box office.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The in jokes and sly references to other teen stars
</P>
<P>
   ``Sly'' meaning you never explain them and ``in'' meaning no
adult without a serious WB habit actually gets them. Otherwise,
it's just not funny when Gellar appears fleetingly _ unbilled and
without uttering a single word _ in a high school cafeteria scene
in ``She's All That.'' Nor when Joshua Jackson's character starts
his car in ``Urban Legend'' and grimaces when the radio blares out
part of the Top 40 song that also serves as the opening theme of
his TV show, ``Dawson's Creek.'' Acceptable exception: The
``Friends'' jokes in ``Scream,'' because Courteney Cox stars in
both. Unacceptable exception: The Chelsea Clinton reference in
``She's All That.'' Not because she's not a teen star of sorts, but
because adults in the audience would actually know who she is.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
