<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7648 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ANALYZE05-COX     03-04 0626
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ANALYZE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Analyze This' as gangster angst
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the lead-pipe world of gangster Paul Vitti (Robert De Niro),
the deepest kind of communication goes something like this: ``Did
you talk to that guy about the thing?'' More comfortable expressing
his feelings with a bullet, Paul is not a natural candidate for
psychotherapy. But in ``Analyze This,'' the shiny-suited mobster
winds up in the bland suburban office of Ben Sobol (Billy Crystal),
a nebbishy psychiatrist whose clients run toward long-marrieds
bored with their sex lives.
</P>
<P>
   Planning for a meeting of New York's rival mob families, Paul
has had trouble sleeping. And breathing. He'd rather think it's
heart trouble than his doctor's diagnosis: a sissy-sounding ``panic
attack.'' That's what leads him to demand some quality shrink time
with Ben. Or else. Of course, the good doctor has to face the moral
quandary of helping Paul become ``a happy, well-adjusted
gangster.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ben's on his way to Miami to marry Laura (Lisa
Kudrow), a TV newscaster. The last thing she expects is having to
share Ben with the needy and demanding Paul as both big days
approach: the wedding and the mob family meeting. (Kudrow's small
role verges on two-dimensional nag, but she can make the stalest
material seem fresh.)
</P>
<P>
   Harold Ramis (``Groundhog Day'') directs with a sleek
professionalism exemplified by the honey-toned camera work of
Stuart Dryburgh (``Portrait of a Lady''). It's all easy on the eye
and pleasant enough. But it won't surprise you. You get mob jokes,
therapy jokes and parodies of scenes from ``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   The script, by Ramis and three others, is a farce with a
structure reminiscent of ``La Cage aux Folles.'' Here, mob life
replaces gay identity as the closeted danger that threatens to
derail a wedding. In ``La Cage,'' news reporters added heat to the
situation; here we get undercover agents keeping Paul and then Ben
under surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   And like ``La Cage'' (the American remake, not the nuttier
French original), ``Analyze This'' never really reaches the
breathless giddiness you want from a farce. That may be because of
the subject matter. The movie has lots of gunfire and falling
bodies. It never quite reconciles its bullets and its belly laughs.
It wants to be a gangster comedy, but a nice gangster comedy.
</P>
<P>
   The movie also can't figure out whether it's making fun of
psychiatry or endorsing it. In a climactic scene, Paul uncovers a
suppressed memory of his father's death. Sure, it gives De Niro
something meaty to play, but it seems like a weird digression in
the middle of the comedy.
</P>
<P>
   What keeps the movie clicking is Crystal and De Niro's
consummate interplay, the comic collision of Crystal's righteous
indignation against the brick wall of De Niro's tough-guy sarcasm.
They're what makes the picture work. Paul's disgust on learning
what an Oedipal complex means is terrific, not because the material
is fresh (it's decades old), but because De Niro sells the scene.
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, ``Analyze This'' lets him prove he can pull off
comedy, even if he isn't any threat to Robin Williams. Or, for that
matter, Crystal.
</P>
<P>
   As for Crystal, maybe this is his official way of apologizing
for ``My Giant.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Robert De Niro, Billy Crystal and Lisa Kudrow. Rated R
for language, a scene of sexuality and some violence. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 46 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An agreeable farce propelled mainly by its two
consummately professional leads.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
