NYT-03-04-99 1427EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0171 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7649 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-GENERAL05-COX     03-04 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-GENERAL05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `General' is grudging Irish salute
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel Gillespie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's been 12 years since the glory days of ``Hope and Glory,''
the movie that earned John Boorman the Oscar nominations for best
picture, director and original screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman is back in fine form _ and finer fettle _ with ``The
General,'' a cocksure character study of celebrated Irish criminal
Martin Cahill. It copped Boorman the best-director prize at Cannes.
</P>
<P>
   The movie begins with Cahill's death in 1994. He's gunned down
by an assailant in front of his home. This is a bit suspicious,
because Cahill's neighborhood usually was crawling with cops. (He
was under 24-hour police surveillance.)
</P>
<P>
   Further, the news of the death of The General _ his nickname _
draws cheers at the nearby precinct, with congratulations extended
to the Javert-like inspector (Jon Voight) who had dogged him for
years. One senses that the cops didn't exactly pull the trigger but
that their hands were near the gun assumed to have been wielded by
the Irish Republican Army.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the film is essentially a flashback, beginning with
his childhood as an irrepressible petty thief (played by Eamonn
Owens of ``The Butcher Boy'') pinching rolls for his starving
family _ plus a prized pack of ciggies for his ma.
</P>
<P>
   As an adult, Cahill (Brendan Gleeson) becomes a folk hero of
sorts in Dublin, known for his roguish ways and daring robberies.
Cahill will steal anything that catches his fancy, from a gold
record to a Vermeer painting. But, as Boorman never lets us forget,
he mostly steals out of good old-fashioned greed.
</P>
<P>
   On the surface, he's a teddy bear of a man, the sort of
good-ol-boy bloke you'd want to raise a few with at the pub. But
Cahill was more complicated than that. He was a natural contrarian,
with no respect for the police, the church, the politicians or even
the much-feared IRA. When he and his gang knock over a jewelry
store considered so impregnable that the IRA won't tackle it,
Cahill refuses the terrorist organization's demand that he share
the loot, thus making a particularly deadly enemy.
</P>
<P>
   But that's who this man is: an equal-opportunity
anti-authoritarian. For him, the IRA isn't any different from the
cops. And that cheeky individualism is what ultimately does him in.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman is clearly enthralled by Cahill. That's the director's
gold record _ given him by the record industry for boosting the
sales of ``Dueling Banjos'' with his movie ``Deliverance'' _ that
Cahill makes off with (it happened in real life). But Boorman and
his star refuse to romanticize this gangster-rebel. Gleeson, with
his stocky build and soccer-thug eyes, plays Cahill with a
disarming child-man spark. He's a true eccentric. For instance, his
close-knit extended family consists of children with both his wife
(Maria Doyle Kennedy) and her younger sister (Angeline Ball).
</P>
<P>
   Yet underneath the hearty geniality lies a vicious streak that
erupts with chilling intensity. A gang member who he believes has
crossed him ends up crucified on a pool table (but it's also Cahill
who then rushes him to a hospital). He's like an overgrown, lovable
puppy who can suddenly turn on you.
</P>
<P>
   Boorman has shot the film in sparkling black and white, harking
back to his early days in the mid-1960s when he did such kicky
flicks as ``Catch Me if You Can'' and the cult classic ``Point
Blank.'' He clearly knows he has a terrific tale, and he has a
terrific time telling it. It's like being joined by a pal over a
few beers who starts out with, ``Wait'll you hear what this guy did
next.''
</P>
<P>
   But again, under the games and goofs, Boorman is examining a
complex inevitability. Men like Cahill typically end up worn down
by the constant harassment they've invited from the authorities.
More typically still, they end up with a bullet in their head.
</P>
<P>
   The point, one guesses, is that a life like this is better
witnessed than lived. No wonder ``The General'' leaves an
aftertaste that's rollicking but also oddly poignant.
</P>
<P>
   ``The General''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   Starring Brendan Gleeson. Directed by John Boorman. Rated R for
language and violence. 3 hours, 3 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: An entertaining true-life tale of an Irish master
thief who was both lovable rogue and ugly thug.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gillespie writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
