A7679 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NURSING-HOMES05-COX     03-04 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESSIONAL PANELS OKAY NURSING HOME PROTECTION
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two congressional panels approved bills Thursday
that would prevent nursing homes from discharging Medicaid patients
if the homes drop out of the Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Medicaid patients in a nursing home can't be forced to leave
because the home made a voluntary decision to withdraw from the
Medicaid program,'' said Sen. Bob Graham, D-Fla., the bill's Senate
sponsor, moments after it breezed through the Senate Finance
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Less than an hour later, a House Commerce subcommittee passed a
similar bill sponsored by Rep. Michael Bilirakis, R-Fla., chairman
of the health and environment subcommittee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nursing home residents and their families will not have to
live with the fear of eviction,'' Bilirakis said. ``Enactment of
this legislation will remove that threat.''
</P>
<P>
   To become law, the House and Senate would have to be approve
identical versions of the bill and the president would have to sign
it.
</P>
<P>
   The bills approved Thursday would cover instances in which a
nursing home that formerly accepted Medicaid patients decided to
drop out of the program. Medicaid patients already in the home
would be allowed to remain, and their costs would continue to be
paid by the program.
</P>
<P>
   People who enter non-Medicaid homes as private patients would
have to be given written notice that if they became Medicaid
patients they would no longer be allowed to remain in the home.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla., said he planned to offer an amendment
when the bill reaches the full Commerce Committee that would exempt
homes from the new rules in states that cut their Medicaid payment
rates in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``No new nursing homes are going to be built for Medicaid
patients'' if the bills become law, Coburn said.
</P>
<P>
   The bills grew out of a situation last year in which Vencor
Inc., one of the nation's largest nursing homes, attempted to evict
Medicaid patients in Florida and Indiana after it homes decided to
drop out of the program. The company reversed its efforts after
complaints were raised publicly. The company and the industry have
endorsed the Graham and Bilirakis bills.
</P>
<P>
   In another action Thursday, the Senate Finance Committee voted
18-2 to extend the limits on Medicaid and Medicare benefits for
disabled people who return to work.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which has 62 co-sponsors, would allow states to lift
the income eligibility cap for disabled Medicaid beneficiaries who
return to work. Currently the cap is 250 percent of the poverty
level. States would be allowed to set their own threshold above
that amount.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the bill would extend Medicare coverage for
disabled workers who return to work from the current three years to
10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, however, the two committee votes against the bill
were from Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., and Senate
Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla. There opposition could delay
consideration of the bill by the full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
