<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7690 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BARBIE-DEMON-$ADV07-H     03-04 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BARBIE-DEMON-$ADV07-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONGING FOR THE INVASION OF THE BARBIE SNATCHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 7)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By AMY BIANCOLLI  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ I love my two girls. And they love Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't easy for me to admit; I'm no fan of the woman. Fate
forces me to accept that Barbie shares our home with us, that our
lives are filled with Barbie dolls and Barbie-related
paraphernalia: Barbie vehicles (a car; a bike), Barbie combs and
brushes, Barbie shoes (which, for the record, stay on Barbie feet
12.8 seconds before dislodging and becoming lost), Barbie socks and
Barbie microdresses, all of them pink.
</P>
<P>
   Add to these the numerous items emblazoned with Barbie's
doe-eyed visage _ pajamas, barrettes, puzzles, tea sets, coloring
books, jewelry _ and the end sum is a lot of plastic femininity.
</P>
<P>
   It was not always so. When my 5-year-old, Madeleine, was born, I
vowed that Barbie dolls would never Darken Our Door. Madeleine
would never play with one; I would never buy her one; Barbie's
pole-vault legs and petroleum bouffant would never come between us.
Barbie, I believed, provides an unrealistic model of feminine
beauty: She's a negative influence on the psyches of young girls,
damaging their body images and emphasizing artifice over
accomplishment. No bubble-headed Barbie for my baby girl. No way.
</P>
<P>
   Then somebody gave her one. The occasion was her second birthday
party, and the giver _ a ringleted, sweetly poised 2 1/2-year-old _
was Madeleine's best friend. My first impulse was to scream ``DEMON
BARBIE!!! AGGGGGHHH!!!!'' and propel the doll over the heads of
several guests into a burning fire. But etiquette demanded
otherwise. So I smiled at the 2 1/2-year-old and thanked her mother
(a friend of mine), all the while devising a secret post-party
Barbie-disposal plan.
</P>
<P>
   First, I would wait until Madeleine had set aside the dreaded
Barbie. I would stash it in some remote corner of the house, out of
sight and out of reach. Eventually, maybe after a week, maybe after
a month, she would forget about it. And as soon as she forgot about
it, I would throw it out. Poof. End of Barbie.
</P>
<P>
   Except she never forgot about it. The Barbie-disposal plan never
had a chance. No sooner had I stuffed Barbie into some dank recess,
Madeleine asked to play with her. After which Mother was faced with
a harsh dilemma: Lie to a 2-year-old? (``Barbie's lost, honey.'')
Be brutally honest? (``Barbie's an evil contortion of the human
body, and I forbid you to play with her.'') Or act like millions of
mothers since the dawn of bendable playthings, and cave in?
</P>
<P>
   The answer: Cave in.
</P>
<P>
   When my daughter Jeanne was born, and all heck broke loose. One
of the hard-and-fast rules of parenting is that Child No. 2 does
not play with baby toys. Child No. 2 plays with whatever mess Child
No. 1 has left on the living room floor. When the mess consists of
serrated edges and objects fit for lodging in windpipes, Mom clears
it away before baby gets there. But when the mess consists of
Barbie dolls, none of which (despite their other negative aspects)
has ever boasted a serrated edge, Mom leaves it alone and wanders
off to extract crayons from the kitchen drain instead. It's a
matter of prioritizing.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is a complicated way of saying that I was, by then,
too exhausted to object. Barbie was a Fact. And once she became a
Fact, I relaxed my defenses. I bought Barbie sleepwear, necklaces,
tchotchkes. Eventually I bought a doll myself: an African-American
model, which I outfitted with a big pink Barbie mountain bike and
bundled up for Madeleine's fifth birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Because the girls had always been fans of so-called ``boy''
stuff, their interest in the frillier realm of doll collecting
seemed like a fair balance. Barbie was bland, Barbie was
unrealistic, Barbie was bizarre but she was no more bland,
unrealistic or bizarre than Barney, another iconic oddball I've
come to terms with. Her feet may be deformed (how high are those
heels, anyway?) and her eyelashes thick with mascara, but at least
she doesn't have a show on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   The body-image problem still bugs me, however. I've talked to
the girls repeatedly about the inherent weirdness of Barbie's
figure _ ``Real women don't look like that,'' I say, whereupon they
give me a look that's best translated as: Duh.
</P>
<P>
   They knew that already. But it's my job, as their mother, to
state the obvious: To tell them that they're beautiful the way they
are, that it's good to be strong and healthy and solid, that no one
on God's green Earth has legs that start at their earlobes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
