<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 14:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-WATER-BOS &LR;      03-04 1511
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-WATER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATER-RICH CANADA WARY OF THIRSTY US 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: Budgeted photo is unavailable.)  
 (i and a coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTREAL _ Canada holds a fifth of the world's fresh water
supply, but doesn't want to share a drop, at least not for now. And
especially not with its increasingly thirsty neighbor to the south.
</P>
<P>
   Motivated as much by raw nationalism as environmentalism, and
with an eye toward one day becoming the OPEC of H(2)O, Canada is
seeking to ban bulk sales of water to foreigners _ the first
``water-rich'' nation to attempt to block the flow of a resource
that some specialists predict will become the most valuable
commodity of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   With little fanfare and less public debate, Parliament last
month voted unanimously for a moratorium on bulk exports of water,
cloaking its action in Queen and flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is as Canadian as hockey, as the Mounties, as the
beaver,'' said Bill Blaikie, a member of Parliament from Manitoba.
</P>
<P>
   Said International Trade Minister Sergio Marchi: ``Canadians
feel extremely passionate about water.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, it seemed a curious move for a country whose economy
depends heavily on extracting and exporting fabulous quantities of
non-renewable resources, from gold to natural gas. No one one seems
to worry too much about reserves of Canadian oil or iron ore, but
water gets the blood pumping.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't drink oil,'' explained Foreign Minister Lloyd
Axworthy.
</P>
<P>
   Canada's water, of course, is a resource that each hour
replenishes itself by the billions of gallons. Every day, the St.
Lawrence River alone disgorges into the Atlantic the equivalent of
10.1 million railroad tanker car loads of fresh water.
</P>
<P>
   The vote by Parliament, although scarcely noticed outside
Ottawa, may turn out to have been the starting gun in a new global
scramble for resources.
</P>
<P>
   As the millenium approaches, the world's thirst for water is
growing at a stunning rate, with global demand doubling every 21
years. By the year 2025, the World Bank predicts, more than 3
billion people in 52 countries will suffer from chronic shortages
in water for drinking or sanitation.
</P>
<P>
   Even rich countries may be forced to reduce consumption
drastically _ especially agricultural use _ or search outside their
boundaries for sources of the life-giving liquid.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Canada's extraordinary wealth of water, many
observers say the new moratorium is just a temporary stopgap,
giving Ottawa and the provinces time to devise a coherent water
policy _ and pricing strategy _ before opening the resource to the
highest bidders. They say Canada is less interested in keeping
water permanently away from bulk buyers than devising a plan to
circumvent the North American Free Trade Agreement and ensure that
Canadian companies _ not avaricious Americans _ profit most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canada is a future OPEC of water,'' said Terence Corcoran,
business editor of the National Post, a Toronto-based daily
newspaper known for sober-minded financial coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Canada may even be moving on US water: a Canadian company has
quietly won the first North American license to ship bulk
quantities of drinking water to China _ from a pristine lake in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Global Water Corporation of Vancouver, British Columbia, in
a precedent-setting deal that attracted surprisingly little
attention, plans to siphon 18.2 billion gallons a year from Blue
Lake near Sitka, Alaska, for shipment to bottling plants in China,
one of the countries most threatened by looming shortages.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1998 report to shareholders, Global Water noted that
``consumption of water products is growing at a rate faster than
any beverage product.''
</P>
<P>
   Among environmentalists and economists, there is widespread
agreement that water shortages will become commonplace in the
coming decades, and that countries that control fresh water will be
kings of the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``By 2010, Canada will be exporting large quantities of fresh
water to the US, and more by tanker to parched nations all over the
globe,'' Corcoran wrote in a recent article. ``The issue will not
be whether to export, but how much money the federal government and
the provinces will be able to extract from the shipments.''
</P>
<P>
   A study by the World Bank recently forecast that the planet's
rapidly expanding population will drain lakes and mighty rivers,
causing calamitous shortages of water for irrigation, drinking, and
sanitation. Water is being pumped at dangerous rates from exhausted
underground aquifiers throughout Asia, Africa, the Middle East, and
even parts of the United States, such as southern California and
several Midwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Competition for dwindling shares of the resource is already
intense, and could become ferocious. Stated the World Bank: ``Wars
of the next century will be over water.''
</P>
<P>
   Canada's water moratorium, which has yet to be tested under free
trade treaties like NAFTA, is aimed straight at the United States,
where several businesses are quietly hatching plans to siphon off
shiploads of water from Canadian lakes for delivery to dusty
agricultural lands in the southwest.
</P>
<P>
   That prospect has plainly spooked Canada. Politicians there vow
to protect the resource as nationalists thump up anti-American
sentiment by suggesting that their nation's pristine lakes and
rivers are about to be sucked dry by greedy US agribusiness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing freaks out Canadians like the idea of American
supertankers coming in and taking off our water,'' said Maude
Barlow, head of the Council of Canadians, a nationalist lobbying
group that believes free trade treaties have left Canada vulnerable
to economic rape by its powerful neighbor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Water is our lifeblood,'' said Barlow, who favors a flat ban
on bulk water exports, except for humanitarian shipments. ``Once
the tap is open, no one can turn it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa is urging the 10 provinces, which share control of water
with the federal government, to help devise forceful strategies for
better guarding the nation's hoard.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the hullabaloo over water comes at a time of year
when Canadians from Niagara Falls to the high Arctic are hip deep
in the stuff, in the form of snow. Canada posseses the simple
compound of hydrogen and oxygen in more staggering abundance than
any other nation. Scientists estimate that 20 percent of the
earth's entire bounty of fresh water lies untouched in this country
of only 30 million people. Much of Canada remains virgin
wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   A bit less than half of Canada's fresh water is renewable and,
at least theoretically, accessible from rivers, lakes, and
underground flows. The rest is so-called ``fossil water,'' locked
in glaciers and the permanent ice shield that covers the far north.
</P>
<P>
   On a per capita basis, Canada boasts 11 times as much renewable
fresh water as the United States: about 28.7 million gallons for
every woman, man, and child, compared to 2.6 million gallons per
American, according to UN figures.
</P>
<P>
   Citizens of the two countries are by far the world's most
prolifigate users of water, consuming 100 gallons per day per
person (Canada's average is slightly lower) _ most of it flushed
down the toilet or bath drain. The average person drinks only about
2 quarts per day.
</P>
<P>
   American/Canadian household consumption is nearly three times
higher than the European average, and 25 times greater than
personal consumption in the Third World.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in rich and poor countries alike, water quaffed from
drinking glass or drawn into the bath is but a drop compared to the
stupefying amounts lavished on crops.
</P>
<P>
   ``Irrigation is far and away the biggest consumer of water
worldwide, accounting for about 80 percent of use,'' said Sandra
Postel, director of the Global Water Policy Project, a research
group based in Amherst, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   For the United States, the most obvious new source is Canada,
which uses only the tiniest fraction of its available water to
slake its thirst, water its crops and turn the turbines of its
mammoth hydroelectric dams.
</P>
<P>
   Among the companies clamoring for access to the water wealth of
the northern neighbor is Sun Belt Water Inc. of Santa Barbara,
which during the mid-1990s sought the right to ship tanker loads of
water from British Columbia to California. British Columbia killed
the deal and imposed a provincewide ban on bulk water exports. Sun
Belt is now seeking compensation of $220 million from Canada,
claiming the ban violates NAFTA, the free trade pact signed by the
United States, Canada, and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Trade specialists say that if Canada permits even a single
shipload of water to be exported, water will automatically become a
``tradeable commodity'' under NAFTA. That means US companies would
legally have the same rights as Canadian firms to exploit and
export the resource.
</P>
<P>
   ``Canadian water would come under as much pressure as Canadian
culture is already under from the American juggernaut,'' warned
Barlow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1454EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
