<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX     03-04 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Potential adversaries agree: We can afford cleaner air
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ In their respective environments, Texans,
politicians and political activists each can be cited for emissions
of ``toxic overstatement'' _ sometimes referred to as ``bovine
biomass.''
</P>
<P>
   But, no bull. This is big.
</P>
<P>
   It's particularly big since the politicians we are about to cite
are Texas Republicans and the activists are Texas
environmentalists.
</P>
<P>
   This week Waco's state Sen. David Sibley, and by assent Gov.
George W. Bush, said they would link electric deregulation with a
major cleanup of electric utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley, the power center of electric deregulation, said Monday
he would amend his deregulation bill to include what would be a
barely noticeable increase in utility bills _ less than a dollar a
month for most residential customers _ to pay for utilities to add
pollution devices that cut emissions of nitrogen oxides by up to 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   That pollutant is a key factor in the visible ozone that turns
skies from blue to milky. This initiative would achieve with one
fell swoop a long-delayed environmental gain.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Carman, the clean-air program director of the Lone Star
Sierra Club, calls Sibley's proposal ``a major leap forward.''
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, he wouldn't mind being able to say he'd be the
``environmental president'' his father pledged to be (for ``bovine
biomass,'' see above). Sibley, a close ally, would appear to have
handed George W. a certifiably environment-friendly initiative to
tout on the campaign trail.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental activists who a decade ago simply might have
thrown themselves on the railroad tracks before a
Republican-sponsored electric deregulation bill this time decided
to try and get what they could in the face of the inevitable. Not
for the first time, they've found in Sibley a listener and a doer.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with poll numbers showing most Texans would support paying
a little more for cleaner air, they came forth with a plea to
incorporate into electric deregulation a cleanup plan for too-dirty
grandfathered electric plants _ those in place before and not
subject to the Texas Clean Air Act of 1971.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates rubbed their eyes this week when they realized
that Sibley's $1.4 billion initiative not only would pay for new
controls at grandfathered plants but at all utilities in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Smith of the public-interest advocacy group Public Citizen
calls this investment a Texas-sized bargain. It would achieve ozone
reduction at a third of what it would cost to make a comparable
reduction in automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   It can be done
</P>
<P>
   Skepticism is well in order over what might derive to the common
man from electric deregulation. Indeed, it may offer little more
than confusion to many. But if in fact it is inevitable, with
federal deregulation coming down the track, a clean-air initiative
is a most wise and savvy seizing of the day for environmentalists.
And they have a conservative Republican to thank for the daylight.
</P>
<P>
   Public Citizen's Smith sees this as a landmark move that could
make other steps to clean up pollution politically palatable.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has been frozen in indecision about what to do about
cleaning up old power plants, with the specter of their retirement
seemingly looming.
</P>
<P>
   Sibley's proposal, said Smith, might enable lawmakers to look
further at dealing with other air pollution issues rather than
waiting for the sooty, suffocating end of time.
</P>
<P>
   Smith sees hope that Texans, and Texas politicians, if fully
informed about the pollution coming from power plants and the costs
of cleanup, could ``go the whole enchilada, the whole deal'' _ to
curb emissions of visible particulates and deadly metals like
mercury that get spread with the breeze from coal-fired generators.
</P>
<P>
   That would be big.
</P>
<P>
   John young is the opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald
in Waco, Texas. E-mail: jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
