<HEADER>
A7705 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUNDANCE-QUEST-HNS &LR;      03-04 0912
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUNDANCE-QUEST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLEDGLING FILMMAKERS TRAVEL TO HELL AND BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ John Holser knows about hell.
</P>
<P>
   There is one.
</P>
<P>
   It's a town halfway across Wyoming, goes by the name of Rawlins
and is cold. A woman named Mirinda works in a truck stop there.
</P>
<P>
   You want Mirinda fixing your ailing Winnebago about as much as
you want Marilyn Manson reading bedtime stories to your children.
</P>
<P>
   John Holser didn't have a choice. The 38-year-old filmmaker from
Averill Park, N.Y., and a pair of movie-buff friends _ Mike Camoin,
33, and Robin Nagengast, 31 _ were already a few days behind
schedule. It was late January, and they still had to get to Park
City, Utah, in time for the Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   The Winnebago _ a 27-foot Brave, built in 1982 _ had wheezed
into an exhausted collapse a few miles outside of Rawlins and
required a tow to the second repair shop. Earlier, back in Laramie,
they came down a steep mountain pass, in a nighttime blizzard, with
an ailing alternator. To keep the RPMs up, Holser, who was driving,
put the RV in neutral, goosed the engine with his right foot and
stepped gently on the brake with his left. He had to keep the
engine roaring, because if the revs dropped, the already-weak
headlamps would further dim and the windshield wipers would sweep
across their arc even more slowly.
</P>
<P>
   A garage in Laramie had temporarily fixed the alternator. It
lasted halfway across the state, almost until Rawlins.
</P>
<P>
   In Rawlins, Mirinda rendered her verdict: bad injectors and an
alternator beyond revivification. This was after, back about
mid-Kansas, they'd already had to replace an engine belt and the
fuel filters. Now they were only one state away from Sundance, and
the celebrated film festival was going on without them.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Holser and crew had been invited. They were going to
crash Sundance.
</P>
<P>
   Holser directs films and corporate videos. He's currently
working on a documentary titled ``Lights, Camera &AMP; Credit Cards,''
about the making of seven independent films, and he runs a Web site
about independent films. Nagengast also makes movies, as does
Camoin. Camoin's documentary ``Inside the Blue Line: Leadley's
Legacy,'' is about a woodsman in the Adirondack Mountains. It was
accepted by the annual Cornell Environmental Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   But Sundance turned down Camoin's movie. Twice. Which was at
least part of the impetus for their whole cross-country expedition.
</P>
<P>
   The plan: Convert the RV into a mini screening room, complete
with theater seats and a 27-inch TV. ``It was jammin', like a
totally cool fort on wheels,'' says Holser. They named the
Winnebago Dances on Wheels and called it a ``mobile film venue''
the movie-theater version of a bookmobile.
</P>
<P>
   They would drive to Utah over two days. Park on the main street
of Park City. Hand out fliers advertising that they'd be showing 20
films, mostly shorts, none of which were accepted by Sundance. Pour
coffee and hot chocolate. Impress people, get noticed.
</P>
<P>
   The actuality: They decided to take a southerly route to avoid
snowstorms. The first blizzard hit in Delanson, N.Y. Then a bunch
more storms. Then the fuel filters got stopped up. And the
alternator went. Twice.
</P>
<P>
   By the time they got to Park City, five days after having left
New York and three days late, the Winnebago was flatulent with
smoke and leaking diesel. Nix on the downtown-parking plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided we couldn't do it,'' Holser says. ``We go to Main
Street, where people are hanging out, standing on the sidewalk,
smoking cigarettes. We're leaking fuel. Someone tosses a cigarette,
and that's it. Boom. We'd blow up the whole town.''
</P>
<P>
   They decided to set up elsewhere. Driving into a parking lot
with a steep ramp _ a parking lot full of people they wanted to
impress _ the Winnebago got stuck. Front wheels on the incline,
trailer hitch in the road, rear wheels off the ground, back end
blocking a lane and a half of Sundance traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe 20 people came to their sole showing, in a hotel room.
Then Nagengast flew to Albany. Camoin stayed on awhile to see
films. And Holser left town, hoping to nurse the RV back home.
</P>
<P>
   Total time in Park City: one day.
</P>
<P>
   Holser headed south to avoid the weather.
</P>
<P>
   And hit, in Texas, a Texas-size storm that immobilized most of
the state, including a 55-mile-long traffic jam.
</P>
<P>
   And the Winnebago's transmission collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   A good mechanic fixed it. For $2,500. Included free: The news
that Mirinda and her Rawlins crew had put an engine belt on
backward, left a rag in the air filter and neglected to close the
valve that caused the fuel leakage.
</P>
<P>
   After the snow cleared and he got out of Texas, Holser drove
straight on home, Tulsa, Okla., to Albany in 21 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ten days in a broken-down RV, you really learn who you are,''
Holser says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole film industry is really a marketing industry. ...
It's about getting your film and yourself noticed,'' says Camoin.
``At least people were talking about us.''
</P>
<P>
   The trip wasn't a complete flop. They had a video camera going
at the worst moments. They can make a documentary about their
disastrous journey. The RV, now running happily, will roll out to
colleges in the Northeast, probably in the fall. And they'll even
think about returning to Sundance next January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just won't drive through Rawlins,'' Camoin says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1508EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
