u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UGANDA-ADAMS-HNS &LR;      03-04 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UGANDA-ADAMS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA WOMAN TELLS HOW SHE ESCAPED MASSACRE IN UGANDA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL DOUGAN  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Linda Adams went to Uganda in search of
gorillas. She found guerrillas, too.
</P>
<P>
   Adams, 52, a resident of Alamo, Calif., told how she escaped
from a band of Rwandan rebels who kidnapped her and 31 others
Monday in Uganda's Bwindi National Park. Fourteen of the captives
were marched into the mountains. Six were released and eight were
hacked to death with machetes.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the San Francisco Airport Wednesday, Adams said, ``I
wish all the hostages were free and alive. I grieve for those in
Oregon who lost their daughter, their father, their son.''
</P>
<P>
   She was referring to the deaths of Rob Haubner, 48, and his
wife, Susan Miller, 42, the only Americans among those murdered.
</P>
<P>
   Adams was taken prisoner during a five-day visit to see the
celebrated mountain gorillas in the nearby mountains. She said she
had spotted some gorillas on a grueling high-altitude hike the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   It was on that trek that Adams developed respiratory problems
and was unable to keep up with the younger members of her group.
</P>
<P>
   That, in turn, inspired her to declare that she could not
breathe when her captors tried to march her back into the mountains
the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The climb was strenuous and I was just not going to go with
them,'' said Adams. A tour leader told the rebel commander that
Adams suffered from asthma (which she doesn't). That tour leader,
in turn, could not see beyond three feet without her glasses, Adams
said.
</P>
<P>
   So the rebel leader told the two to return to the camp, where
other guerrillas were holding other tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, said Adams, she and her companion hid in the brush for
45 minutes or longer before entering the camp. By then, the rebels
had departed.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she didn't realize at first that an abduction was
taking place. When she emerged from her tent that morning, to be
greeted by ``four men with four guns,'' she assumed they were
gorilla poachers committing an armed robbery.
</P>
<P>
   The rifle-toting men asked for her money, she said, adding that
``if they wanted the money they could have the money.''
</P>
<P>
   When she asked them to return her airplane ticket and passport,
which they had taken from her tent, the rebels politely complied,
she said. That made her feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had been really nice to me, even though they captured us
at gunpoint,'' she recalled. ``I really felt there was some
compassion from their leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she was probably released because ``I would have been
a burden to them.'' What's more, ``I am a female with gray hair and
I think they had some respect for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Even then, she said, ``I don't know that I really realized I was
in danger. I was just not going to walk up the hill.''
</P>
<P>
   Only when she returned to the camp did those left behind tell
Adams that the men with guns were political rebels.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was informed that they had made demands,'' she said. ``It
took me by surprise. I thought maybe they were detaining us to keep
the Uganda police at bay for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams said she would have been killed had she not exhibited
breathing difficulties. ``I know I would not be here today if I
didn't do that, because I was the oldest and I was the slowest,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her experience there, Adams said she would be willing to
return to Uganda. ``It's not the Ugandans who did this to me,'' she
noted. ``The countryside was beautiful.'' On earlier trips she has
tracked polar bears and seals in the wintry far north and flown to
Australia and the Galapagos Islands on nature expeditions.
</P>
<P>
   She said she feared that terrorism in the area of the endangered
mountain gorillas will further threaten their survival. In fact,
she said that when she heard distant shots before emerging from her
tent and meeting the rebels, ``my first reaction was, `I hope no
one is shooting the gorillas.'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
