A7732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LOCK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-04 0821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOCK-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LOCK, STOCK AND TWO SMOKING BARRELS'': KEEPING THE THUGS IN
CONSTANT MOTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Guy Ritchie's brash, ebullient direction of his first feature,
``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels,'' makes it very obvious that
he honed his style making music videos and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   And for once that doesn't hurt. The punchy little flourishes
that load this English gangster film with attitude are perfectly
welcome, because there's no honest, substantial part of the movie
they can hurt.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie is skillful enough to make a fine feat of macho
gamesmanship out of the way four sets of East End crooks keep
outsmarting one another. And if that means having them all arm for
battle while the ``Zorba the Greek'' theme music heightens the
intensity of the moment, well, why not?
</P>
<P>
   Touches like that, along with flashy, random shifts of film
speed and a true rogues' gallery of striking if one-note
characters, do hold interest even if they have no real right to.
The commercial aspects also deflect attention from the fact that
this story has almost no center at all.
</P>
<P>
   The closest it comes to heroes are the four savvy young con men
whom the film introduces first. Ritchie brings on Eddie (Nick
Moran), Tom (Jason Flemying), Bacon (Jason Statham) and Soap
(Dexter Fletcher) as if they were the ``Trainspotting'' crew, but
the story soon begins to lose them in the shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   Thick accents, desaturated brownish color and 20-odd actors with
comparably important roles don't do much to alleviate this mild
confusion.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Eddie qualifies as the main character because Sting
plays his father, a bar owner named J.D., and because it's Eddie's
gaffe that gets the ball rolling. Eddie is a card shark, and
because his pals are tired of selling stolen merchandise on London
sidewalks and other dubious pursuits, they help him enter a secret
high-stakes game run by Hatchet Harry (P.H. Moriarity), a shrewd
old pornography merchant and crime boss.
</P>
<P>
   The dialogue sets the humorously hard-boiled tone, as when these
two first meet, and Eddie is introduced as J.D.'s son.
</P>
<P>
   ``You must be Harry,'' Eddie coolly remarks. ``Sorry, didn't
know your father.''
</P>
<P>
   And Harry answers: ``Never mind, son. You just might meet him if
you carry on like that.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a lot more manly posturing along those lines as the
story gets rolling. (The only women in the film are a card dealer,
a topless dancer and a person too easily mistaken for a pile of
throw pillows.) And things get downright dangerous after Eddie
finds himself heavily in debt to Harry and his henchman, Barry the
Baptist (Lenny McLean), who earned his nickname by drowning people.
</P>
<P>
   Harry and Barry are the film's closest approximation of senior
statesmen, and they also embody Ritchie's way of recruiting born
bruisers to add color to his story. The cast also includes a few
real ex-cons and the glowering English soccer star Vinnie Jones.
</P>
<P>
   The film is dedicated to McLean, the Cockney world heavyweight
bare knuckle champion, who was just embarking on an acting career
when he died last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Eddie et al. scramble to raise the money they owe Harry,
Harry hires his own team of bumbling thieves to procure the two
antique rifles that figure in the title.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile some stoned aristocratic slackers are raising a
healthy marijuana crop, and a separate gang of drug dealers is
operating right next door to the apartment of Eddie and friends
where it's easy to hear through walls. Enough? Not until the film
throws in a Samoan bar and yet another gang, with a leader whose
quaint Cockneyisms (``Chevy Chase'' for ``face'') add further to
the melee atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   With a big debt to ``The Usual Suspects'' and a ``Reservoir
Dogs,'' like the approach to population control, Ritchie revels in
the sheer knottiness of all this scheming. He makes it lively while
it lasts and empty when it's over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lock, Stock and Two Smoking Barrels'' is rated R (Under 17
requires accompanying parent or adult guardian). It includes one
extremely deadly shootout and other incidences of violence that are
more jokey. Sort of. One scene finds a drug dealer using an
upside-down underling as a target while he hits golf balls.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `LOCK, STOCK AND TWO SMOKING BARRELS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Guy Ritchie; director of photography,
Tim Maurice-Jones; edited by Niven Howie; music by David A. Hughes
and John Murphy; production designers, Iain Andrews and Eve
Mavrakis; produced by Matthew Vaughn; released by Gramercy
Pictures. Running time: 106 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Jason Flemyng (Tom), Dexter Fletcher (Soap), Nick Moran
(Eddie), Jason Statham (Bacon), Vinnie Jones (Big Chris), P.H.
Moriarty (Hatchet Harry), Lenny McLean (Barry the Baptist) and
Sting (J.D.).
</P>
