<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7743 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      03-04 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SIX WAYS TO SUNDAY': A HIT MAN MARRIED TO THE MOB, BUT NESTING
WITH MOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If black comedies came any blacker than ``Six Ways to Sunday,''
you'd need the candlepower of a government-surplus lighthouse to
see them.
</P>
<P>
   This rather grand little Guignol, built around incest, makes the
mother-son relationship in `Oedipus Rex'' look like just another
bad heir day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Ways to Sunday,'' set in the seedy precincts of
Youngstown, Ohio, is not for sensitive souls. It drips with bloody
murders, brutal beatings, schizoid behavior, police corruption,
suicide and unhealthy relationships, but it is filled with
character, well acted and directed with skill by Adam Bernstein,
who produced it and wrote the screenplay with Marc Gerald.
</P>
<P>
   And what's even better, for onlookers who survive till journey's
end, is a happy ending that in its own warped way speaks to the
myriad possibilities of love.
</P>
<P>
   Derived from the 1962 Charles Perry novel, ``Portrait of a Young
Man Drowning,'' about Jewish gangsters in Brooklyn, the film
centers on Harry Odum (Norman Reedus), a high school graduate who
flips burgers for a living and shares a shabby home with his
domineering mother, Kate (Deborah Harry, of Blondie), who still
bathes him, controls the light in his room, arranges his guilt
trips and is eager to warn him about young women. ``Girls today are
no good,'' she says. ``They're sluts.''
</P>
<P>
   Given that Kate is fond of negligees and sex lectures that are
as suggestive as they are cautionary, it is little wonder that the
repressed, conflicted Harry goes wild when he accompanies his pal
Arnie (Adrien Brody), a petty hoodlum, to a topless club to
administer a beating to the manager, who is in arrears on payment
to loan sharks.
</P>
<P>
   Harry's zestful attack is so effective that it brings him the
blessing of Arnie's supervisor, Abie (the Bug) Pinkwise (Peter
Appel), and eventually into the employ of the local Big, Louis
Varga (Jerry Adler).
</P>
<P>
   With the wealthy Varga as his benevolent employer and Abie as
his kindly mentor, Harry is soon a certified hit man, bringing in
money, buying a better home for dear old Mom and falling in love in
his sickly way with cute little Iris (Elina Lowensohn), Vargas'
lame servant.
</P>
<P>
   Out on the frayed fringes of Harry's life are Bill Bennett
(Isaac Hayes), a crooked police detective with a mean streak who
knows what drives Harry mad; Annibelle (Anna Thompson), the hooker
Harry pays to not have sex with him, and Madden (Holter Graham),
Harry's suave, handsome and assured alter ego.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later, Harry is going to have to make some choices
about Mom and Iris and Abie and Vargas.
</P>
<P>
   They're difficult choices, but as the old saying goes, love will
find a way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Six Ways to Sunday'' is rated R (Under 17 requires
accompanying parent or adult guardian). It involves violence and
incest.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `SIX WAYS TO SUNDAY'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Adam Bernstein; written by Bernstein and Marc
Gerald, based on the novel ``Portrait of a Young Man Drowning'' by
Charles Perry; director of photography, John Inwood; edited by Doug
Abel; music by Theodore Shapiro; production designer, Theresa
Mastropierro; produced by Bernstein, David Collins and Michael
Naughton; released by Stratosphere Entertainment. At Angelika Film
Center, Mercer and Houston Streets, Greenwich Village. Running
time: 97 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Norman Reedus (Harry Odum), Deborah Harry (Kate Odum),
Adrien Brody (Arnie Finklestein), Peter Appel (Abie [The Bug)
Pinkwise), Elina Lowensohn (Iris), Jerry Adler (Louis Varga), Isaac
Hayes (Bill Bennett), Holter Graham (Madden) and Anna Thompson
(Annibelle).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1529EST &QL; 
