<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following auto features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-HYUNDAI-NYT (Detroit) _ The Sonata sedan, redesigned
for the 1999 model year, embodies just how far the South Korean
auto company Hyundai has come. The Sonata has broken ranks with its
Asian counterparts by establishing a styling statement of its own.
Hyundai's California Design Center, which styled the Sonata, has
long turned out innovative and eye-catching concept cars. Some of
that style is now finally showing up in production vehicles. By
Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-SMART-FERRARI-NYT (Undated) _ Tired of your old workaday
Porsche Carrera or Acura NSX? Looking for something a little
sleeker with a little more oomph _ something sure to impress even
the most jaded valet parking attendant? Look no further than the
Ferrari 360 Modena, to be introduced on March 9 at the Geneva Motor
Show. The new model, which will go on sale in North America this
fall, replaces the F355 _ the last-generation ``entry level''
Ferrari. By Peter Passell.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-AZR (Phoenix) - Here comes another holdout, finally
admitting there is only one way to build a proper minivan. They've
all lined up _ Ford, GM, Nissan, eventually Toyota. And now, Honda.
All have come to the same conclusion that the front-wheel-drive,
sliding-door, triple-row-of-seats, tall, squared-off-backside
minivan invented 16 years ago by Chrysler was then and remains
today the best setup for a practical minivan. The Honda Odyssey for
'99 is smooth, roomy, powerful and sophisticated, and pretty much
shoulders its way to the head of the pack. By Bob Golfen.
</P>
