<SLUG> BC-STYLE-PROM07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    You'll look princess pretty in a drop-dead dress or sassy
separates
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ On your mark. Get set. Shop!
</P>
<P>
   Although the big dance is still weeks away, promgoers are
already on the hunt for the perfect outfit. And for the young lady
who wants to make a dazzling impression, a potpourri of styles are
available _ everything from seasonal strapless ball gowns to the
new evening separates. Full and billowy dresses are also popular
this year, as well as narrow and slim designs. For accessories,
butterflies have hit the big time and tiaras will crown many a
coif.
</P>
<P>
   To help with your shopping, we've highlighted some of the
hottest dresses for this year's prom season. Discover your style,
then go and have fun finding that dream dress.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Pretty and romantic: To show off your softer side, go for
ballerina-look dresses in tulle, organza or taffeta. Trims feature
embroidered flowers and butterflies, lace and a smattering of
sequins. Look for sun-washed pastels, including yellow, pink,
lavender. White is another top contender for these Cinderella-like
dresses.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sporty and sassy: You've seen the look on MTV and on the New
York runways: a sweater set paired with a long skirt for a casual
evening ensemble. A full tulle skirt is a must, in shades of
lavender, powder blue or baby pink. Pair these skirts with shiny
camisoles and cardigans. The great thing about these separates?
After the prom, you can always wear the sweaters with jeans or
khakis.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Go glam: If you prefer to shine with a subtle hint of
elegance, try gowns that are sleek and sophisticated, strapless,
halter-necked or with one shoulder styling. Other styles boast side
cutouts, trains and carved-out backs. Favorite colors are
turquoise, blue, black and silver.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Classic and chic: Snag the spotlight on that special night in
a long, shiny satin dress. Go for a strapless A-line accessorized
with a stole or a ball gown with a bustle. Think classics in black
or white. Or, for more color, go for periwinkle blue or pale pink.
</P>
<P>
   Marylin Johnson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
