A7779 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-PARKS-GEORGIA0     03-04 0596
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-PARKS-GEORGIA07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love outdoors? You can't beat Ga. state parks as natural resort
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Think of Georgia's 45 state parks as uncommonly fine
resorts for the common man. Five have lodges and most have cottages
or camping (and frequently both). Six parks have golf courses, 10
feature tennis courts and most have swimming pools, beaches or
lakes.
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, the state parks offer special programs
including nature crafts, snake shows, campfire sing-alongs, guided
hikes and birding. Canoes and motorized fishing boats are available
for rental at many sites year-round.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so none of the parks will be mistaken for the Cloister, but
where else can you experience such natural beauty and agreeable
accommodations for less than $100 a night?
</P>
<P>
   Lodging and restaurants are available at:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Amicalola Falls, Dawsonville ($79-$199; 706-265-8888).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  George T. Bagby, Fort Gaines ($42-$75; 912-768-2571).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Little Ocmulgee, McRae ($50-$75; 912-868-7474).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Red Top Mountain, Cartersville ($69-$109; 770-975-0055).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Unicoi, Helen ($69-$119; 706-878-2201).
</P>
<P>
   The lodges vary from 30 guest rooms at Little Ocmulgee to 100 at
Unicoi, and offer special features such as sleeping lofts and
suites with separate bedrooms and porches. Handicapped-accessible
and nonsmoking rooms are available. Pets not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Vogel State Park in Blairsville has the largest cottage
community with 36 units. Others have from two to 30. Cottages _
from $40 to $165 per night _ are one-, two- or three-bedroom and
all are fully equipped with stoves and refrigerators, cooking and
serving utensils, towels, bed linens and blankets. All have heat
and most have air conditioning. Many cottages have porches or decks
and wood-burning fireplaces or stoves (firewood is not provided).
Accessible cottages are available at many parks. Pets not allowed.
</P>
<P>
   Camping ranges from primitive back-country sites for about $3 to
full RV hookups from $10 to $18 a night.
</P>
<P>
   The state's first walk-in lodging is the Len Foote Hike Inn at
Amicalola Falls State Park. You must hike five miles to reach this
rustic lodge with 20 bunk-bed rooms. Rates are $55 per person,
double; $75 single. Breakfast and dinner are included.
</P>
<P>
   Golf courses can be found at Georgia Veterans Park, Cordele;
Gordonia-Altamaha, Reidsville; George T. Bagby, Fort Gaines; Hard
Labor Creek, Rutledge; Little Ocmulgee, McRae; Laura Walker,
Waycross; and Victoria Bryant Park, Royston. Fees vary, but you
can't beat unlimited play from $13 to $18 on weekdays. Rates are
somewhat higher on weekends and there are additional charges for
carts. Bagby's new, 18-hole course was recently named the nation's
sixth-best public golf course by Golf Digest.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight reservations must be made at least two days before
arrival but no more than 11 months in advance. During summer,
minimum stays may be required. To make reservations at any state
park or request a free brochure, call 770-389-7275 (in metro
Atlanta) or 1-800-864-7275.
</P>
<P>
   A $2 park pass is required for all vehicles. A $25 annual pass
can be purchased by calling 404-657-9851. The Georgia Parks Travel
Guide, which lists the parks and their facilities, is $6.95; call
404-656-6538. The information is also on the Web at
http://www.gastateparks.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
