<HEADER>
A7782 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHEAST-FAMILIES07-     03-04 1360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHEAST-FAMILIES07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eight great Southeastern destinations for families
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March, 7.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  Fontana Village, N.C.: A visit to the historic Fontana Village
Resort is like taking the whole family to summer camp. The rustic
and charming resort has three swimming pools (one indoors), a
riding stable, marina, crafts workshop, activities center with
equipment for archery, badminton, tennis, volleyball, shuffleboard
and horseshoes. Stay at the 94-room Fontana Inn or one of the 200
cottages. Built in the early 1940s by the Tennessee Valley
Authority to house construction workers building Fontana Dam, the
town was turned into a sprawling family resort after World War II.
Lodging rates highest in summer: inn $69 and $79; cottages $129 and
$159 (two bedrooms), $159-$189 (three bedrooms). Peppermill
Cafeteria serves hearty mountain country cuisine. Information:
1-800-849-2258 or http://www.fontanavillage.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hilton Head Island, S.C.: The shoe-shaped island's best
feature may be the 12 miles of beaches, but the beaches aren't the
only draw. Hilton Head has several stables that offer guided tours,
and some have special kids' packages and pony rides. Plus, there
are ample opportunities for golf, tennis and water sports. Families
also enjoy the popular dolphin cruises offered by several tour
operators. A good place to weigh all your options is at the Hilton
Head Island Chamber of Commerce Welcome Center on U.S. 278, on the
way into town. Accommodations run the gamut from motel rooms under
$100 to weeklong stays in beachside condos for $1,000 and up.
Hungry? For kids, we love Crazy Crab in Harbour Town and Crabby
Nick's on U.S. 278. Information: Hilton Head Chamber of Commerce,
1-800-523-3373 or http://www.hiltonheadisland.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New Orleans: Don't let the sleaze of Bourbon Street keep you
away from the Crescent City. The Big Easy is a great family
destination with the fabulous Aquarium of the Americas, the Audubon
Zoo, riverboat excursions on the mighty Mississippi and the
terrific Louisiana Children's Museum. Kids love visiting the French
Market, snarfing beignets and hot chocolate at Cafe du Monde,
watching street performers in Jackson Square, riding the St.
Charles streetcar and taking horse-drawn carriage rides through the
French Quarter. Expect to pay at least $100 (and potentially far
more) for a room. Le Richelieu, Hotel Provincial and Holiday Inn
Downtown-Superdome are reliable, moderately priced choices. Your
dining options are endless. For a taste of the food that made New
Orleans famous, splurge on Sunday jazz brunch at Court of Two
Sisters, and try the moderately priced Gumbo Shop on St. Peter
Street, just off Jackson Square, or Ralph and Kacoo's on Toulouse.
Information: 504-566-5011, New Orleans Metropolitan Convention and
Visitors Bureau; http://www.neworleanscvb.com or
http://www.neworleans.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Huntsville, Ala. Promise the kids the moon and take 'em to the
U.S. Space &AMP; Rocket Center in the Alabama city that produced the
rocket boosters that put men on the moon. Here you can see IMAX
shows about space, take a guided bus tour of NASA's Marshall Space
Flight Center and get a close look at the real Apollo 15 module
that hauled men to the moon. The rocket center spans the distance
between sci-fi space fantasy and sophisticated NASA reality, with
more than 60 interactive exhibits and 1,500 pieces of space
hardware. Downtown Huntsville has a variety of moderately priced
hotels close to the center, including the Radisson Suite Hotel,
several Holiday Inns, Hilton, Marriott and Ramada. Many offer
suites and family specials, with separate bedrooms for children and
parents, for $80 to $120 per night. The center's Galaxy Food Court
serves moderately priced hamburgers, grilled chicken sandwiches and
other American foods. Space Center information: 256-837-3400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Williamsburg, Va. American history steps out of the textbook
and onto the streets of Colonial Williamsburg, which looks very
much as it did when Thomas Jefferson, Patrick Henry, George
Washington and other patriots formed a new nation. In the restored
capital of Colonial Virginia, families become a part of a bustling
18th-century city filled with ``people of the past'' dressed in
period garb. Although family programs are offered during the summer
only, there's plenty to engage children throughout the year. A
visit is not complete without serving time in the public stocks. Be
sure to have at least one meal in a colonial tavern. Young ladies
play old-fashioned games, get lessons in manners and learn how to
serve tea during ``Felicity's Williamsburg _ An American Girls
Experience,'' a special package that includes accommodations, a
tavern dinner, the Felicity tour and tea, and Patriot's Passes
(1-800-501-0057). Information: 1-800-447-8679 or
http://www.colonial-williamsburg.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Chattanooga. Family Fun magazine ranks Chattanooga among its
10 Family Friendly Cities _ and we know why. The most obvious
reason is the Tennessee Aquarium and 3-D IMAX Theater, the hub of
the city's thriving riverfront. But that's not all: Just up the
street is the Children's Creative Discovery Museum. And smack in
the middle of the action is a great place to stay, the all-suite
Residence Inn by Marriott. Nearby are lots of fun restaurants like
T.G.I. Fridays, Electric Submarine Rock &AMP; Roll Cafe and Cheeburger,
Cheeburger. This summer, a huge, old-fashioned carousel will open
across the Tennessee River in Coolidge Park behind Frazier Avenue
(where you'll find a super toy store called The Big Much). The
Southern Belle Riverboat offers river excursions. Round out your
stay with visits to the Chattanooga Choo Choo (you can even spend
the night in a restored Pullman car) and close-by attractions
including Rock City, Ruby Falls and the Incline Railway. Another
bonus: free shuttles run daily from the Choo Choo to the aquarium.
Information: 1-800-322-3344 or http://www.chattanooga.net/cvb.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Jekyll Island (Ga.). Once upon a time, Jekyll Island was the
playground of the rich and famous. Now, you don't have to be either
to vacation on the historic island. Even in summer (high season),
it is possible for a family to find a place to stay on the beach
for less than $100 a night. And most restaurants are reasonably
priced and cater to families. In addition to 10 miles of beach,
you'll find Summer Waves Waterpark (open daily Memorial Day through
Labor Day), 63 holes of golf, tennis courts, miniature golf,
bicycle rentals (to explore 20 miles of paved trails), horseback
riding, fishing and sightseeing. Be sure to take a tour of the
island's National Historic Landmark District to learn about the
days when it was a ``millionaires' village.'' Tours leave 10 a.m.-3
p.m. daily from the Museum Visitors Center on Stable Road, where
free exhibits describe Jekyll's history. Information:
</P>
<P>
   1-800-841-6586 or http://www.jekyllisland.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  St. Augustine, Fla. If your kids think you're old, take them
to a place that'sreally ancient _ America's oldest, continuously
occupied European settlement, founded in 1565. Visit the Oldest
House, the Oldest Wooden Schoolhouse, the late 17th century Fort
Castillo de San Marcos and Ponce de Leon's Fountain of Youth. The
kids will also get a kick out of 3D World; Potter's Wax Museum,
where figures appear quite lifelike; and Ripley's Believe It or
Not! Museum, a collection of the world's oddities housed in
historic Castle Warden. Cruises on Matanzas Bay and horse-drawn
carriage rides are lots of fun, too. Older children will enjoy ``A
Ghostly Experience'' walking tours. Outside the historic district,
don't miss Alligator Farm, the Lighthouse and Museum and the
beaches of Anastasia Island. Plenty of good accommodations from
motels to historic inns (although some do not allow children).
Information: 1-800-653-2489 (ask for a free St. Johns County Travel
Planner) or http://www.oldcity.com.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
