<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0195 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 15:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7784 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHEAST-INNS07-COX     03-04 1804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHEAST-INNS07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Discover 10 great inns of the Southeast
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   So many inns, so little time. The region is dotted with
wonderful places to spend the night. This is just a sampling of
some of our favorites from recent travels. Some are country-cozy,
others are elegant. All are special in their own way.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Balsam Mountain Inn, Balsam, N.C. The best feature of this
comfortable 50-room inn, opened in 1908, may be the two-level
veranda from which one can rock, relax and gaze at surrounding
mountains. The inn's current incarnation dates to 1990, when
innkeeper Merrily Teasley began restoration of the neoclassical
Victorian structure perched on a hill above the Balsam Depot.
Inside are restored hardwood floors, beaded board walls, antique
wicker and Victorian trim. A double-sided fireplace in the spacious
lobby keeps the place cozy in winter. Rooms feature bent wood or
painted iron beds piled with down comforters (but no TVs or
phones), and some baths have antique claw-foot tubs. A full
breakfast is included; lunch and dinner are available. Information:
$90-$150. 1-800-224-9498 or
http://www1.aksi.net/(tilde)cmark/balsam.htm.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cedar Crest Inn, Asheville, N.C. Built in 1891 by the same
craftsmen who worked on the Biltmore Estate, the inn has beveled
glass and hand-carved oak mantels and trim similar to what is in
the nearby Vanderbilt mansion. The grand, yellow-painted Queen Anne
Victorian home _ listed on the National Register of Historic Places
_ sits high above Biltmore Avenue. The antiques-filled guest rooms
(each with its own character) and common areas are elegant but not
stuffy. Breakfast is served in the formal dining room, where, in
the evening, guests find cookies and hot or cold drinks (depending
on the season). Barbara and Jack McEwan are the hospitable hosts.
In addition to the 10 rooms in the main house, there is a guest
cottage and a bungalow. Downtown Asheville, with its shops and
galleries, is 1 1/2 miles north on Biltmore Avenue; the entrance to
Biltmore House is a quarter mile south. Information: $135-$200.
828-252-1389 or http://www.cedarcrestvictorianinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Richmont Inn, Townsend, Tenn. The Richmont's design echoes the
cantilevered barns of East Tennessee in which the second story
overhangs the first. But the rustic barn motif stays outside at the
casually elegant bed-and-breakfast with 10 guest rooms on three
floors, many featuring intimate balconies looking out at Rich
Mountain. Owners Jim and Susan Hind chose the barn design as a
tribute to their Tennessee roots. The historic theme continues in
the rooms, each decorated to honor an eminent mountain figure. The
Francis Asbury Room, for instance, is a tribute to a church circuit
rider who tirelessly spread the gospel in the Smoky Mountains in
the late 1700s and early 1800s. Motifs in other rooms include folk
art, botanical, log cabin and country parlor. In addition to the
gourmet breakfast, served in a dining area with floor-to-ceiling
windows with a mountain view, a stay at the inn includes
candlelight dessert for two every evening. Many of the guest rooms
have wood-burning fireplaces or spa tubs for two. Lounging robes
are provided, and romantic music is piped into the rooms until late
each night. Information: $95-$145. 423-448-6751 or
http://www.thesmokies
</P>
<P>
   .com/richmontinn.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Kendall Manor Inn, Eufaula, Ala. This elegant
bed-and-breakfast _ meticulously restored by Barbara Lubsen and her
husband, Tim _ is one of the crown jewels in a town that boasts
more than 700 architecturally significant structures dating to
1836. The National Register home two blocks from downtown is a
favorite stop on the annual Eufaula Pilgrimage (coming up April
9-11). Staying at Kendall Manor Inn is like stepping back a century
_ but with queen and king beds, telephones with dataports, heat and
air conditioning, indoor plumbing and a television (if you want one
brought to your room). Built by cotton magnate James Turner
Kendall, the home was completed in 1872. Architectural highlights
include the ruby-red Czechoslovakian glass sidelights for the
massive front door, Italian marble mantels and French gold-leaf
cornices and mirror frame in the front parlor. A carved walnut
staircase leads to the second floor. Topping it all is an
arch-windowed belvedere that provides vistas for miles.
Information: $89-$109. 334-687-8847.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mentone Inn, Mentone, Ala. ``Make yourself at home'' seems to
be the theme at this unpretentious inn on the Lookout Mountain
Parkway at the crossroads of the quaint little community of
Mentone. Frankly, it feels a little like visiting your grandmother
(that is, if she lived in a rustic house in the country). Rooms are
smallish but nicely decorated in country style, and some of the
baths have clawfoot tubs. There's a TV and stone fireplace in the
living room, where folks gather before turning in for the night.
The mountain-man breakfasts of eggs, grits, sausage, biscuit, OJ
and fresh fruit fortify guests for checking Mentone's craft and
antiques shops as well as nearby DeSoto Falls, DeSoto State Park,
Little River Canyon and Sequoyah Caverns. Information: Reopening
for the season in May. $70-$125. 256-634-4836.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Casablanca Inn, St. Augustine, Fla. This 1914 Mediterranean
revival home in the oldest city's historic district offers
panoramic views of Mantanzas Bay and traffic _ some of the
horse-and-carriage variety _ along Avenue Menendez. Guests take
breakfast on the porches that catch the breeze from the bay. Rooms
are decorated with antiques and some have Jacuzzis. All have
red-ribboned Casablanca bears sitting on the beds, ready for
snuggling. There are no TVs or phones in guest rooms in the main
house, but they are provided in the Coach House. Bicycles are
available at no cost to all guests. Legend has it that the house is
haunted by the spirit of a woman who signaled with a lantern to
warn rumrunners that the revenue boys were in town _ but that just
adds to the allure of the home that's listed on the National
Register of Historic Places. Special touches include a never-empty
plate of homemade cookies and a help-yourself fridge stocked with
soft drinks and beer. The inn is within walking distance of St.
Augustine's historic attractions and restaurants. Information:
$89-$199. 1-800-826-2626 or http://www.casablanca.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Gastonian, Savannah (Ga.). One of the grandest of Savannah's
grand dames is this 1868 charmer on a quiet residential street in
the nation's largest Historic Landmark District. Actually, the
17-room inn on East Gaston Street, two blocks from Forsyth Park, is
two Regency Italianate mansions connected by a green and tranquil
courtyard _ and there's an elevated deck with hot tub and a
carriage house in the rear. Sumptuously decorated and filled with
fine English antiques and a Waterford chandelier in the dining
room, the home is a showplace of elegance and good taste. Speaking
of good taste, breakfasts are gourmet Southern repasts, afternoon
tea is served with complimentary wines, and cordials await in the
parlor at night. Innkeeper Anne Landers, a former Atlantan who
bought the inn in October 1996, continues the tradition of
attention to details established in 1985 by Hugh and Roberta
Lineberger, who restored the two buildings. Rooms, all with working
fire-
</P>
<P>
   places, are appointed with Oriental carpets and antiques (some
are upper crust English in character, while others are pure
Americana), and most feature huge Jacuzzi tubs. Turndown service
includes sweets such as pecan pralines and floor mats beside the
bed. Information: $295-$350. 1-800-322-6603 or
http://www.gastonianinn.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  1884 Paxton House Inn,
</P>
<P>
   Thomasville. This blue and white Gothic Victorian beauty, with
its wraparound veranda and gazebo, is one of only two such homes in
the southwest Georgia town where presidents, royalty and the
wealthy have come to relax and socialize for more than a century.
Located in the Tockwotton Historic District, the inn has been
lovingly restored by Susie Sherrod and has received local and state
awards for preservation. The home features heart pine floors, a
circular staircase and a dozen fireplaces. Rooms are decorated with
antiques and Sherrod's remarkable collections of Messein porcelain,
dolls, Lladro figurines and clocks and handpainted Russian boxes _
amassed as she traveled abroad as an Army nurse. A full breakfast
is served in a light-filled sunroom with views of the backyard
gardens. In addition to four suites in the main house, there are
four rooms in the Garden Cottage and a suite in the poolhouse
(which has an indoor lap pool for use of all guests). All have
cable TV, phones, terrycloth robes, hair dryers and goosedown
pillows. The inn is an easy stroll from the restored historic
downtown, museums, restaurants and historic sites.
</P>
<P>
   Information: $85-$185. 912-226-5197 or http://www
</P>
<P>
   .1884paxtonhouseinn.com
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bluff View Inn, Chattanooga. Three historic houses make up the
Bluff View Inn: the late 19th-century Maclellan House, a restored
Tudor mansion on a bluff overlooking the Tennessee River; the 1927
Colonial-style C.G. Martin House; and the 1908 Victorian-style T.C.
Thompson House. They are all part of the Bluff View Arts District,
tucked away on a cul-de-sac, adjacent to the Hunter Museum and the
Houston Museum of Decorative Arts. The lodgings share the block
with the River Gallery, an outdoor sculpture garden, Rembrandt's
Coffee House, Tony's Pasta Shop &AMP; Trattoria and the Back Inn Cafe.
Our cozy third-floor room at the Maclellan was elegantly decorated
in soothing tones of mauve and green and furnished with a
queen-size sleigh bed, an antique secretary and sofa. Guests of all
three inns are served a three-course gourmet breakfast in the
Audubon Room at the Maclellan or continental fare at Rembrandt's.
Information: $100-$250. 423-265-5033.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Inn at Merridun, Union, S.C. Listed on the National Register
of Historic Places, this antebellum country inn with stately
Corinthian columns is tucked away on nine woodsy acres off a busy
highway. Innkeepers Peggy and Jim Waller are gourmet cooks whose
talents are apparent at the bounteous breakfasts, highlighted by
blueberry pancakes for ``dessert,'' and elegant candlelight dinners
at additional cost for overnight guests by reservation only. J.D.,
the yellow and white inn cat, is the purrsonable host with the
most. Each of the five distinctively decorated bedrooms has a
private bath, including Lucy's Garden Retreat with a jacuzzi tub.
Information: $79-$99. 864-427-7052.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
