<SLUG> BC-SEX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`RELAX ... IT'S ONLY SEX': THE NAMES ARE QUIRKY, AND THE SEX IS
MORE SO 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(rk) 
 By ANITA GATES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Not so long ago, in movieland, couples met cute. In ``Relax ...
It's Only Sex,'' they have sex cute. Two fashionable West Hollywood
gay men make love while discussing a future menu (something about
salmon and fresh parsley). Another gay man carries on an internal
(voice-over) monologue through much of the act about the
advisability of taking a particular health risk.
</P>
<P>
   The film's token straight couple ravage each other in the
kitchen so recklessly that nearby pots and pans rattle and clatter
to the floor. This is shortly after the woman, Tara (Jennifer
Tilly), tries to prove just how adorably frank she is by hitting
the man, Gus (Timothy Paul Perez), on the back and whining, ``But I
want your sperm!''
</P>
<P>
   Tara sets the tone for ``Relax ... It's Only Sex,'' an energetic
and often good-looking but completely unseductive film from P.J.
Castellaneta. In this comic drama about a group of California
friends, Tara gets the lines that are meant to be endearingly naive
(``AIDS is the biggest tragedy of the 20th century. Even Madonna
thinks so.'') or casually clever (``You know how lesbians are.
They're like Catholics or `Saturday Night Live.' They go on
forever, no matter how bad it gets'').
</P>
<P>
   Castellaneta, whose first film was ``Together Alone,'' a
two-character drama set on the morning after what may have been a
one-night stand, seems to be trying a little too hard to impress
here.
</P>
<P>
   Some characters and situations come off as too deliberately
quirky. Serena Scott Thomas, for instance, plays Megan, a very
femme British lesbian who has suddenly decided she's straight. Her
parents (Seymour Cassel and Susan Tyrell) are furious, because
they've become very active in an organization for the parents of
gay men and lesbians; Cassel's character even has a book coming out
on the subject. What are people going to say when they learn Megan
is dating men?
</P>
<P>
   One actor does stand out. When T.C. Carson appears, he
effortlessly takes over the screen. His character, a painter who
contends that HIV has nothing to do with AIDS, could have come off
as falsely quirky too, but Carson (who was the star of the film
``Livin' Large'') makes him absolutely believable and fascinating
to watch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Relax ... It's Only Sex'' has no shortage of events. The plot
includes an HIV diagnosis, a gay bashing, a
homosexual-to-heterosexual male rape, one character's affair with
her lover's cousin, a problem pregnancy and oh so much more. Even
the characters' names are a little complicated. I watched the
entire film thinking that one member of this circle of friends was
Harvey, but he turned out to be Javi (Eddie Garcia), and I was sure
that Megan was dating Jerry, but he turned out to be Jered (Billy
Wirth). The characters in ``Together Alone'' were named Brian and
Bryan, so maybe Castellaneta just enjoys nomenclature games.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `RELAX ...IT'S JUST SEX'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by P.J. Castellaneta; director of
photography, Lou Magdich; edited by Tom Seid; music by Lori Eschler
Frystak; production designer, Sharon Lynch; produced by Steven J.
Wolfe, Megan O'Neill and Harold Warren; released by Jour de Fete
Films. Running time: 106 minutes. This film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Mitchell Anderson (Vincey Sauris), T.C. Carson (Buzz
Wagner), Seymour Cassel (Emile Pillsbury), Chris Cleveland (Diego
Tellez), Eddie Garcia (Javi Rogero), Timothy Paul Perez (Gus
Rogero), Lori Petty (Robin Moon), Serena Scott Thomas (Megan
Pillsbury), Jennifer Tilly (Tara Ricotto), Gibbs Toldsdorf (Dwight
Bergman), Susan Tyrell (Alicia Pillsbury), Cynda Williams (Sarina
Classer), Paul Winfield (Auntie Miriam) and Billy Wirth (Jered
Bartoziak).  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
