<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOMINOES-TEXAS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BATTLEFIELD OF BONES: DOMINO TOURNAMENT BRINGS ACCLAIM TO TEXAS
TOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HALLETTSVILLE, Texas _ They're going to shake the bones in South
Texas this weekend. They'll be stirring and drawing, bidding and
slamming. There will be 200 people competing, and the Knights of
Columbus Hall will be the battleground.
</P>
<P>
   It is the Texas State Championship 42 Domino Tournament and it
is serious business. The rules are rigid: no talking, no touching,
no signals. No nelo, and if you bid in ``follow me,'' doubles are
not a suit of their own.
</P>
<P>
   If you don't know the meaning of all this, stay out of the line
of fire and just enjoy the kolaches, the sausages and the
hospitality of this German/Czech community.
</P>
<P>
   Hallettsville is as old as the state. John Hallet settled here
in 1833, built a log cabin on a league of land in the Austin
Colony, and then went to Goliad and died. His wife returned to the
cabin and a town sprang up around it.
</P>
<P>
   This area of South Texas, midway between San Antonio and
Houston, was populated in the late 19th century with immigrants
from Czechoslovakia and Germany. The heritage is evident from the
Kahanek &AMP; Renger Drug Store to Novosad's Meat Market.
</P>
<P>
   ``This community is very unique,'' said Frank Fishar, president
of the chamber of commerce. ``We have a lot of different events
throughout the year. The domino tournaments are big events. We also
have a four-day fiddlers festival, a polka and sausage festival and
two big church picnics.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a kolache festival, too. Last year, 800 dozen of the
pastries were consumed.
</P>
<P>
   But it is the domino tournaments that bring the most acclaim to
the town of 2,700. There is a straight domino championship in
January, and the 42 tournament in March.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call Hallettsville the domino capital of Texas,'' said
Bob Pesek, chairman of the straight tournament. ``This is a
community of German and Czech settlers, and dominoes have always
been a part of their pastime.''
</P>
<P>
   Straight dominoes is probably the more popular of the two games,
although it seems that most everyone in Hallettsville plays both.
</P>
<P>
   The straight tournament has had more than 390 players at one
time. The 42 competition topped out last year with 202 players.
Still, there is evidence that 42 is growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five years ago, we had 30 teams, last year, 101. It is growing
both because more people know about it and because 42 is gaining in
popularity,'' said Jim Foster, chairman of the 42 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The competition draws a lot of Texas A&AMP;M University students, he
said. ``They are learning the game at the Dixie Chicken in College
Station.''
</P>
<P>
   Fort Worth's Dennis Roberson can attest to 42's popularity. Last
year, Texas Tech University Press published his book ``Winning 42 _
Strategy and Lore of the National Game of Texas,'' and it is
already scheduled for a third printing.
</P>
<P>
   The game is taken from cards and is similar to hearts or spades,
a little like bridge. Players must bid on their hand, take tricks
and count points _ 42 in all.
</P>
<P>
   Roberson is a veteran of the Hallettsville tournament. He won't
attend this year because his wife, Charlene, delivered the couple's
daughter, Katy, on Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad is going to go without me this year,'' Roberson said.
``But the people down there are going to let me know who wins the
tournament, so I can get their name in the next printing of my
book.''
</P>
<P>
   Roberson also intends to include a new chapter that will discuss
Texas celebrities and their experiences with 42. He sent out
questionnaires and has had responses from singers Robert Earl Keen
and B.J. Thomas, writer Bud Shrake
</P>
<P>
   and TV journalist Bill Moyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale Evans' parents played 42,'' Roberson said. ``I also heard
back from (Texas first lady) Laura Bush. She said she and her
grandmother played all the time while she was growing up in
Midland, and that Laura and George W. played quite a bit until the
twins were born.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hallettsville, there isn't a tavern without a domino table.
The old slate tables, where marks are kept in chalk on the black
surface, are gone, replaced by Formica.
</P>
<P>
   There are domino clubs in the community. ``We have 22 people in
ours,'' Foster said. ``Twenty who play and two will cook. It's been
going on for 28 years, and I can promise you the food will be good
and so will the fellowship.''
</P>
<P>
   Every town around here has domino clubs. There are satellite
tournaments in places such as Wharton, Yoakum, Shiner, Ganado and
Victoria. To come to Hallettsville and win represents the ultimate
in bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   There isn't much money involved. The winner in Saturday's
tournament only gets $75 and a trophy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to remember it is still just a game,'' said Foster.
``We want to keep it fun and in the spirit of friendly
competition.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
