<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BLACKMUN-OBIT (Washington) _ Former Supreme Court Justice Harry
Blackmun, the author of the landmark 1973 decision legalizing the
right to abortion, dies of complications following hip-replacement
surgery. He was 90. By STEVE LASH.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKMUN-ROE-WADE (Undated) _ A look at the legacy of former
Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun's Roe vs. Wade decision, to
some a gift from Blackmun that keeps on giving, to others a dark
day that has plunged the country into a titanic 25 year-plus
political struggle. By KIM COBB.
</P>
<P>
   FAD-DIETS (Washington) _ Fad diets and bad nutrition advice are
spurring consumers to cut healthy foods such as bread and cereals
from their daily consumption, according to a new Gallup
Organization survey. By ERIC ROSENBERG.
</P>
<P>
   GOP-GORE (Washington) _ Republican Chairman Jim Nicholson calls
Vice President Al Gore a ``reckless environmental extremist'' for
his support of the 1997 Kyoto treaty to cut industrial gas
emissions. Nicholson charges that the agreement, which the
administration has signed but not sent to the Senate, would trigger
U.S. job losses and boost energy costs. By DAN FREEDMAN.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-PRISONERS-ABUSE (Washington) _ A report from Amnesty
International USA says many women inmates in America's prisons and
jails are ``routinely'' raped and otherwise abused by male guards
and are denied proper medical care by prison doctors. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   DISASTER-AID (Washington) _ The Clinton administration's effort
to provide aid for hurricane-stricken Central America hits
Republican roadblocks as the president prepares for a four-day trip
to Nicaragua, Honduras, El Salvador and Guatemala. An aid bill was
blocked by House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, R-Texas, an action the
White House says is partisan meddling. By JOHN C. HENRY.
</P>
<P>
   DELAY-ACCUSATIONS (Washington) _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay,
R-Texas, denies inconsistencies between his deposition in a legal
dispute with a former business partner and sworn statements on his
federal financial disclosure statements. He also directly responds
to rumors that he fathered a child out of wedlock. By GREG
McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   KID-CARE (Austin, Texas) _ A Texas Senate health panel
unanimously approves a compromise bill providing health coverage
for hundreds of thousands of uninsured children. The bill provides
full coverage for children up to 10 years whose families earn up to
$34,600 a year. Older children would qualify for coverage if their
families earn $25,900 or less. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   ORGANS-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ Legislation filed by state Sen.
Mario Gallegos would set aside organs harvested in Texas for
Texans, rather than making them available nationally. With other
states doing the same thing, Gallegos says the message is ``keep
your hands off our organs.'' By JULIE MASON.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-VOUCHERS (Austin, Texas) _ Texas Senate Education
Chairman Teel Bivins unveils legislation to create a pilot voucher
program for schools, one of the legislative session's more
controversial issues. By CLAY ROBISON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINE-COMPETITION (Washington) _ A bill designed to spur
airline competition by allowing more landings and takeoffs at
airports in Washington, D.C., Chicago and New York City is unveiled
by a bipartisan group of House lawmakers. Similar legislation is
pending in the Senate. By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN. Story will also
be filed in the WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'') category.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Now that more than 900 women have
filed job discrimination claims against Merrill Lynch under a
class-action settlement, it is finally Wall Street's turn to pay a
price for workplace gender bias. President Clinton, Congress and
the AFL-CIO are also moving to get working women a better deal and
fatter paychecks in a new phase of the drive against
discrimination. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Kissimmee, Fla.) _ They are not the starters, and
they are not the closer. But the middle men _ the relievers who
come in to hold down the fort during the middle innings _ are every
bit as important to the Houston Astros' chances in the NL Central
race. A look at two of the Astros' top middle men, Jay Powell and
Doug Henry. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   BKN-ROCKETS (Houston) _ Walking away from two disappointing
losses, the Houston Rockets will try to vent their frustrations on
the hapless _ and winless _ Los Angeles Clippers tonight. By
MICHAEL MURPHY.
</P>
<P>
   BKC-RICE (Las Vegas) _ The Rice University Owls try to keep
their season alive as they take on nationally ranked New Mexico in
a quarterfinal game at the WAC postseason basketball tournament. By
NEAL FARMER.
</P>
