<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYZE-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ANALYZE THIS': MOBSTER WITH PANIC ATTACKS MEETS THERAPIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By JANET MASLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' (say that second word with feeling!) has a
funny title, an even funnier premise and inspired odd-couple
casting that's enough to prompt laughter just on the basis of the
two-shots in its ad campaign. Think of it as an offer you can't
refuse.
</P>
<P>
   With the utmost affection, Harold Ramis' new comedy summons the
hallmarks of a mob movie and just the man to send them up: Robert
De Niro, in the hilarious role of a don experiencing fits of
self-doubt. Without betraying the genre that has handed him such
choice opportunities, De Niro gives a performance that amounts to
one long wink at the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   And the funniest thing he does here is to play the role of Paul
Vitti (other characters in the movie react to this name exactly as
if it were John Gotti) nearly straight. Vitti doesn't lighten up,
not even when he ought to. ``Would you stop talking? I'm trying to
(italics)do(end italics) this here!'' says Vitti to his girlfriend
when the two of them are in bed.
</P>
<P>
   One day, while yelling ``Who killed Dominick?'' and trying to
beat a confession out of a gangland enemy, Vitti finds himself
unable to strike a decent blow. He himself has been hit by a crisis
of confidence and walloped hard.
</P>
<P>
   And since the inability to inflict harm is a serious liability
in his line of work, Vitti needs help in a hurry. Sure, the first
doctor to tell Vitti that he's had a panic attack gets roughed up;
Vitti doesn't welcome that diagnosis. But the second medical man,
Dr. Ben Sobel (Billy Crystal), gets the patient from hell on a
24-hour basis.
</P>
<P>
   These days every good new film idea has a roommate, so the HBO
series ``The Sopranos'' also revolves around the notion of a
mobster in need of psychological help. Happily, the world of pop
culture is big enough for two versions of this premise, especially
when both are such fun.
</P>
<P>
   As he demonstrated in ``Groundhog Day,'' Ramis knows how to
handle a high-concept story with unusual cleverness, and he does it
again here. It helps to no end that De Niro and Crystal, despite
their obvious differences, are perfectly in tune.
</P>
<P>
   As written by Peter Tolan, Ramis and Kenneth Lonergan, ``Analyze
This'' works best when it concentrates on the culture clash between
the two of them. Its subplots (one about mob infighting, one about
the psychiatrist's imminent wedding) are weaker, but why care?
</P>
<P>
   The two stars meet often and crazily enough to keep the movie on
track, especially after Vitti decides that his peace of mind
depends entirely on the doctor. ``The load?'' he exclaims after
their first little talk. ``Gone! Where is it? Don't know! You're
good, Doc. I'm gonna be getting in touch with (italics)you.''(end
italics)
</P>
<P>
   Of course there are gags here based on Vitti's way of demanding
the doctor's company in the wee hours of the night, or causing
trouble whenever the doctor starts to get married. (Lisa Kudrow
does her best with the routine role of his exasperated fiancee.)
</P>
<P>
   And there are frequent opportunities for sight gags, as when
Vitti expresses his gratitude to the doctor with the gift of a
huge, ornate lawn fountain. ``Call the Vatican,'' the doctor says
drily. ``See if anything is missing.''
</P>
<P>
   Wicked as the stars and the one-liners can be, ``Analyze This''
does drift away from its strong suit at times. Crystal is much
better as a beleaguered doctor than he is at impersonating a
gangster, which the last and iffiest part of the screenplay makes
him do. De Niro boohoos comically when talking about Vitti's
childhood until the film starts taking an early trauma seriously
and pushing for a therapeutic breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, he happens to be in the midst of a shootout when
his emotional catharsis kicks in. And the scared doctor is at his
side, begging him to ``turn this nice grief into murderous rage!''
</P>
<P>
   Contributing nicely to the mock-mob ambiance are Joe Viterelli
as Jelly, the faithful Vitti sidekick in charge of borrowing the
doctor whenever it's least convenient, and Chazz Palminteri as an
even more dapper Don than the one De Niro plays. (The costumes are
often funny in their own right.)
</P>
<P>
   From its clotheshorse crime bosses to its shootout filmed in
slow motion and accompanied by opera, ``Analyze This'' knows just
where to aim.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes mild violence, brief sexual
references and profanity used in familiar gangland fashion.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `ANALYZE THIS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Harold Ramis; written by Peter Tolan, Ramis and
Kenneth Lonergan, based on a story by Lonergan and Tolan; director
of photography, Stuart Dryburgh; edited by Christopher Tellefsen;
music by Howard Shore; production designer, Wynn Thomas; produced
by Paula Weinstein and Jane Rosenthal; released by Warner Brothers.
Running time: 110 minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Robert De Niro (Paul Vitti), Billy Crystal (Ben Sobel),
Lisa Kudrow (Laura MacNamara), Joe Viterelli (Jelly) and Chazz
Palminteri (Primo Sindone). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
