<HEADLINE>
A FORMER LEVI STRAUSS MANAGER SUES THE FIRM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A former Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. manager claims in a
lawsuit that she was fired for cooperating in an investigation of
two supervisors who promoted women with whom they were allegedly
having affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In the suit filed Wednesday in San Francisco Superior Court, 44-
year-old Patricia Ogden, a 12-year veteran of the company, accuses
it of retaliation, age and sex discrimination, sexual harassment
and breach of contract following her termination in October last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Levi Strauss) has the public image of being a progressive
company. That public perception is not consistent with what I've
seen,'' said Ogden's lawyer, Philip Kay of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   According to Kay, Ogden, the former merchandise manager of men's
shirts for Levi's Dockers division, was supervised by two men _
Vincent Tavani, marketing director of the company's Dockers' brand
and James Capon, president of Dockers.
</P>
<P>
   The two men, according to the suit, were sexually involved with
two lower ranking employees. ``Two senior executives were having an
affair with these two women. The two women were getting advances in
the company they weren't entitled to receive,'' Kay said.
</P>
<P>
   Kay contends his client was fired for taking part in an
investigation of the alleged relationships that was prompted by
another employee, a male merchandising manager.
</P>
<P>
   Tavani, reached at his home, said he had not seen the suit or
talked to anyone in the company about it. ``This is all new,'' he
said, refusing further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Capon could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss spokesman Dan Chew said he could not comment
because the company had not yet been served with the lawsuit. ``We
wouldn't comment on any employee issues out of respect of both
privacy of current employees as well as previous ones,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says that in August 1997 the company fired the male
merchandising manager after he complained about one of the alleged
relationships. In November 1997, according to the suit, Levi
Strauss initiated an investigation into the man's claims, which was
handled by an outside counsel.
</P>
<P>
   The suit says Ogden objected to the promotions made by Tavani in
December 1997. Specifically, she objected to the promotions of the
woman Tavani was allegedly involved with as well as the woman with
whom Capon was rumored to be having an affair.
</P>
<P>
   The next month, Ogden claims, she received the first written
criticism of her performance from Tavani. When Ogden sought help
from a Levi Strauss attorney, she was told about the investigation
and relayed what she knew on the assurance she would not be subject
to retaliation, the suit states.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation of Tavani, according to the complaint,
resulted in that supervisor apologizing to his subordinate
managers, including Ogden. In August 1998, Tavani was promoted to
marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden said she was fired in October 1998 after a negative
mid-year review and after she refused to make changes in a product
line suggested by a designer. Ogden claims Tavani was having an
affair with the designer as well. The suit claims two other
employees _ one who cooperated with the initial complaint and
another who agreed with Ogden about the design change _ were fired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pure retaliation,'' Kay said. ``The message this has
sent is that anytime anyone cooperates in an investigation based on
someone above them, they will be subject to losing their job.''
</P>
<P>
   Kay argues his client had a strong reputation in a Levi division
that has been performing well: ``Odgen was a superstar there. There
was no reason to get rid of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Levi Strauss blamed its 13 percent sales drop on
poor sales of its classic five-pocket jeans but described its 1998
Dockers sales as ``record breaking.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1605EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
