<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7803 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX     03-04 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZBOOKS-REVIEWS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SOBERING LOOK AT GLOBAL GRAYING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA McUSIC 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Feeling old lately? You're not alone.
</P>
<P>
   A huge percentage of the Earth's population is heading for
senior status, in numbers never before seen. And as the world
continues to gray, the ranks of younger generations are thinning.
</P>
<P>
   Witness the birth rate, which is dropping drastically. The
fertility rate in developed countries is down to 1.6 children per
woman, 25 percent beneath the rate necessary to maintain current
population levels.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the two trends, and you've got one heck of a global
economic mess, economist Peter G. Peterson says. And the collision
date of those two global generational whirlwinds is coming up fast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that global aging will become the transcendent
political and economic issue of the twenty-first century,''
Peterson writes. ``I will argue that _ like it or not, and there's
every reason to believe we won't like it _ renegotiating the
established social contract in response to global aging will soon
dominate and daunt the public policy agendas of all the developed
countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson makes a compelling case in ``Gray Dawn: How the Coming
Age Wave Will Transform America _ and the World'' (Times Books, 280
pages, $23.00).
</P>
<P>
   This isn't Peterson's first sounding of alarm on the coming
geriatric generation.
</P>
<P>
   He began writing about the United States' Social Security system
in 1982, eventually leading to ``Will America Grow Up Before It
Grows Old?'' in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   That book focused on the aging population of the United States.
Now, Peterson
</P>
<P>
   takes a global view.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are startling:
</P>
<P>
   _ Before the Industrial Revolution, less than 3 percent of the
world's population was 65 or older. Today, 14 percent are senior
citizens. By 2030, that number will soar to 25 percent of the
population.
</P>
<P>
   _ Today, the ratio of working taxpayers to nonworking pensioners
is 3-1 in the developed world. By 2030, under the current
retirement system, that ratio will fall to 1.5-1, even lower in
Germany and Italy.
</P>
<P>
   _ While the number of seniors ages 65 to 84 is projected to
triple within 50 years, the number of those over age 84 is expected
to grow sixfold. These ``old old'' will require twice as much
hospital care per person and more than 20 times as much nursing
home care as their younger senior counterparts in the United States
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson says the United States will fare better than some
countries, such as Italy and Japan, in the next few decades. But by
2030, the benefits of Social Security, Medicare, Medicaid and
federal and military pensions will exceed total revenues in this
country, according to a commission report that Peterson and others
prepared for Congress in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would leave zero tax revenue for any other purpose _ not
even for interest payments, nor for national defense, nor for
education, nor for child health, nor for the federal payroll,''
Peterson writes. ```Not a penny available for anything else.'''
</P>
<P>
   Peterson outlines a somber but thoughtful view that appears to
be amply supported with analyses from distinguished sources.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rarely have so many official multilateral bodies _ such as the
International Monetary Fund, the World Bank, and the Organization
for Economic Cooperation and Development _ agreed with such
unanimity on the dimensions of a problem,'' he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Yet little is being done to address this economic iceberg,
Peterson writes. He provides interesting overviews of how the
problem is surfacing in Japan, Italy, Latin America and Asia, as
well as America. Few politicians are facing the challenge, and
those who try are often voted out in the next election, he writes.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson offers several suggestions for addressing the
generational problem. Among them are a major global aging summit of
world leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have been willing to convene summits of this type to
discuss global `warming,''' he writes. ``Why not global `aging,'
which will hit us sooner and surer?''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, an Agency on Global Aging should be established to
share information, guidelines and initiatives, Peterson suggests.
</P>
<P>
   Other ideas include extending the work life of employees by
raising retirement ages so benefits don't kick in until later;
increasing immigration to the developed countries; encouraging
larger families with government benefits toward more children; and
applying benefits only to seniors who need financial help, not to
those with other incomes and savings.
</P>
<P>
   Peterson's book also looks at some of the lucrative markets to
be developed based on this demographic shift. Peterson provides
thoughtful ideas on a fascinating trend.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
