</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRUEL-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`CRUEL INTENTIONS': BACK TO THEIR OLD TRICKS, BUT A WHOLE LOT
YOUNGER 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Production notes are at end of review)  
 (af)  
 By STEPHEN HOLDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something faintly ridiculous in the spectacle of Sarah
Michelle Gellar and Ryan Phillippe portraying upscale Manhattan
teen-age versions of the manipulative sexual predators in Choderlos
de Laclos' 18th-century novel, ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses.''
</P>
<P>
   Watching these fresh-faced actors go through the motions of
seducing and betraying their classmates at a fancy Manhattan
private school is rather like watching child actors playing
gangsters in Alan Parker's Prohibition-era movie ``Bugsy Malone.''
</P>
<P>
   You have the queasy sense that the whole thing is just an
elaborate stunt, and in this case an exploitative one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions,'' written and directed by Roger Kumble, is
the fourth and by far the weakest film adaptation of Laclos'
epistolary novel. It is the second, following Roger Vadim's
European jet-set version (with Jeanne Moreau and Gerard Philipe as
a promiscuous married couple) to update it.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Vadim adaptation (in 1960) had its ridiculous
moments, it at least had a couple of world-class sex symbols
pulling the strings.
</P>
<P>
   Making a teen-age soap opera out of a novel about jaded
sybarites corrupting younger people and comparing notes robs the
story of moral resonance. Ruining reputations, in any case, isn't
what it used to be, at least not in late-20th-century Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   And because ``Cruel Intentions'' is set in the age of the cell
phone and e-mail, you're continually aware of the contortions the
screenplay goes through to justify its characters' besieging one
another with handwritten notes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gellar and Phillippe are Kathryn and her step-brother,
Sebastian, a pair of spoiled preppy brats who live in a palatial
Manhattan apartment without noticeable parental supervision. The
two, who have been eyeing each other lustfully since their parents
met, have slept with everybody except each other.
</P>
<P>
   One afternoon, Kathryn summons Sebastian and enlists him in a
vindictive kiss-and-tell scheme to seduce her ex-boyfriend's chaste
new girlfriend, Cecile (Selma Blair), and ruin her reputation.
</P>
<P>
   The two also make a diabolical wager. If Sebastian can seduce
Annette (Reese Witherspoon), the proudly chaste daughter of their
school's new headmaster, Kathryn will finally give herself to
Sebastian no holds barred. But if Sebastian fails, he must hand
over his most prized possession, a 1956 Jaguar.
</P>
<P>
   Cecile turns out to be a piece of cake, but Annette presents a
major challenge. Having written an article for Seventeen magazine
urging girls to save themselves for marriage, she has a lot to lose
if Sebastian's campaign succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   If ``Cruel Intentions'' is all about teen-age sex, it isn't
especially sexy. Ms. Gellar's Kathryn is a snide, potty-mouthed
brat who always seems to be in a minor snit. Her coldly snippy
performance is enough to make you long for the young Tuesday Weld,
who lent her overprivileged teen-age wild girls an undercurrent of
destructive recklessness that made psychological sense.
</P>
<P>
   Phillippe's hushed, carefully elocuted speeches in ``Cruel
Intentions'' seem modeled after John Malkovich's mannered line
readings of Valmont in ``Dangerous Liaisons.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Hampton's screenplay for that mostly wonderful movie
is also the obvious blueprint for Kumble's screenplay, which
self-consciously translates the dialogue into an arch,
profanity-laced modern teen-age argot. This version also throws in
half-baked subplots involving bisexuality and interracial sex.
</P>
<P>
   The movie's tone veers uncertainly between comedy and soap
opera. The opening scene, in which Swoosie Kurtz, as Sebastian's
psychiatrist, discovers to her horror that he seduced and abandoned
her daughter, is played for farce. After that the movie loses its
grin. The soberer it gets, the more forced and false it feels.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cruel Intentions is rated R (Under 17 requires accompanying
parent or adult guardian). It includes profanity and sexual
situations.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   `CRUEL INTENTIONS'
</P>
<P>
   Written and directed by Roger Kumble; suggested by the novel
``Les Liaisons Dangereuses'' by Choderlos de Laclos; director of
photography, Theo Van de Sande; edited by Jeff Freeman; music by
Edward Shearmur; production designer, Jon Gary Steele; produced by
Neal H. Moritz; released by Columbia Pictures. Running time: 97
minutes. This film is rated R.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Ryan Phillippe (Sebastian Valmont), Sarah Michelle Gellar
(Kathryn Merteuil), Reese Witherspoon (Annette Hargrove), Selma
Blair (Cecile Caldwell), Louise Fletcher (Helen Rosemond), Joshua
Jackson (Blaine Tuttle), Eric Mabius (Greg McConnell), Sean Patrick
Thomas (Ronald Clifford), Swoosie Kurtz (Dr. Greenbaum) and
Christine Baranski (Bunny Caldwell).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
