<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HIV-LAWSUIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIV PATIENT SUES DOCTOR WHO ADVISED AGAINST SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ELIZABETH FERNANDEZ  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When the pain in his shoulders became
unbearable, Steve Iacovino sought the help of a surgeon at the
University of California at San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   But after the surgeon declined to operate, Iacovino said he was
so devastated that he wanted to throw himself off the roof of the
hospital parking garage.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he found another doctor and, a few months later,
successfully underwent shoulder replacement surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in a trial under way before San Francisco Superior Court
Judge A. James Robertson II, Iacovino is suing the orthopedic
surgeon and the University of California alleging he was
discriminated against because he has the AIDS virus, or HIV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begged him to do the surgery ... I saw no end to the pain,''
said Iacovino, 47, a former technician at the San Francisco Fine
Arts Museum who now lives in Honolulu. ``I figured if UC wasn't
going to operate on me no one would because they were the leading
AIDS experts. I thought my life was being written off.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Lucey, the lawyer representing the now-retired surgeon,
Dr. Franklin Hoaglund, denied that the doctor discriminated against
Iacovino when he suggested a more conservative approach of physical
therapy instead of surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every doctor has to be free to make medical judgments and
recommend treatment without fear of being sued simply because
another doctor disagrees with them,'' Lucey told the court
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Iacovino was diagnosed with irreversible bone
degeneration called avascular necrosis. Referred by his primary
physician to the university's orthopedics department, Iacovino was
taking heavy doses of morphine to combat the pain. He had tried
physical therapy, he said, but could not tolerate it.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1997, he met with Hoaglund and again the following
month.
</P>
<P>
   Iacovino said that because of the risk of infection from his
weakened immune system, the doctor advised against surgery. ``I
told him I was willing to take any risk, I did not want to live my
life on morphine,'' Iacovino said.
</P>
<P>
   Iacovino's lawyer, Gary Cloutier, said the refusal to operate
indicated that the surgeon ``didn't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucey, however, told the jury Wednesday that while Hoaglund has
treated HIV-positive patients, shoulder replacement surgery was
rarely done because of the serious risk of infection.
</P>
<P>
   Lucey said Iacovino also had medical complications other than
HIV and chronic shoulder pain, including herpes, headaches and
severe asthma.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dr. Hoaglund was sued for recommending a conservative course
of treatment,'' Lucey said. ``The plaintiff wanted the surgery and
he wanted it now ... you do not dictate to the doctor what
treatment should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Four months after Hoaglund declined to operate, Iacovino had the
surgery performed in Honolulu on his right shoulder. A second
operation was later performed on his left shoulder. Iacovino said
he is nearly off morphine and is again able to do most of the
activities he could not handle before the surgery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
