<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-IN-BRIEF-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW AND NOTEWORTHY MOVIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is a selective listing by critics of The New York Times of
new or noteworthy movies currently playing in theaters. Running
times and ratings of films are in parentheses.
</P>
<P>
   `AFFLICTION,' starring Nick Nolte, James Coburn, Willem Dafoe,
Sissy Spacek and Mary Beth Hurt. Directed by Paul Schrader (R, 114
minutes). Nolte is devastating in the performance of his career, as
Wade Whitehouse, a New Hampshire loner fighting a losing battle
with demons from his past. Foremost among them: Coburn,
terrifyingly authentic as the drunken, abusive father who long ago
cowed his sons into submission. As directed by Schrader, this pure,
unfettered adaptation of Russell Banks' novel starts on a
deceptively ordinary note, then escalates into inexorable fury.
Every little detail matters. Ms. Spacek and Ms. Hurt expertly play
the women who trigger Wade's crisis (Janet Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `BLAST FROM THE PAST,' starring Brendan Fraser, Christopher
Walken, Alicia Silverstone and Sissy Spacek. Directed by Hugh
Wilson (PG-13, 105 minutes). More amusingly than might be expected,
this comedy tells the story of one very nuclear family that has
been hiding in a fallout shelter since 1962 and emerges into a '90s
world of grunge and attitude. In fact, it's funnier underground,
with Fraser as the strapping son of a cheerfully mad scientist
(Walken) and sherry-sipping housewife (Ms. Spacek), 1962 style.
Once he comes above ground and meets a hard-boiled Ms. Silverstone,
it's clear that Fraser is once again a film's true ingenu, doing
the wide-eyed hunk thing that has become his specialty. He does it
a lot better in ``Gods and Monsters,'' but this comedy is still
lighthearted fun (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `CENTRAL STATION,' starring Fernanda Montenegro. Directed by
Walter Salles (R, 115 minutes). In this quiet, luminous Brazilian
gem, a joyless woman crosses paths with an orphaned boy. There's
plenty of room for sentimentality here, but the wonder of Salles'
film is all in the telling. As these characters develop a fractious
bond, then embark on a road trip that takes them vividly to
Brazil's hinterlands in search of the boy's father, Salles brings
great tenderness and surprise to the events that punctuate their
journey. Ms. Montenegro's tough bravura performance was one of last
year's very best (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `EIGHT MILLIMETER,'' starring Nicolas Cage, Joaquin Phoenix,
James Gandolfini and Catherine Keener. Directed by Joel Schumacher
(R, 120 minutes). This thriller delves into the perverse underworld
of the pornography business, shocking audiences with the
realization that sex and violence can be so dull. Cage, seriously
miscast, plays a private detective and devoted family man who is
suddenly, to his horror, drawn into the realm of porn. Naturally,
this is where the film wanted to be even when its opening scenes
were stuck in suburban Pennsylvania. But the story's parade of New
York and Hollywood sleazeballs fails to deliver either engaging
drama or heartfelt kinks. Phoenix is scene-stealingly good in a
sidekick's role (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `JAWBREAKER,' starring Rose McGowan, Julie Benz, Rebecca
Gayheart and Judy Greer. Directed by Darren Stein (R, 85 minutes).
More nasty schoolgirls, and this time they're meant to be as hard
as the candy of the title. Intending more of a spoof than he
delivers, Stein introduces spike-heeled teen-age queens who
accidentally kill one of their own. Bummer! They spend the rest of
the story tarting up the class nerd so that she'll keep their
secret. This slender story is accompanied by lots of references to
other, better films in this genre, from ``Grease'' to ``Heathers,''
in a movie that (despite flashy directorial touches) doesn't show
much personality of its own. Special bonus: Marilyn Manson without
makeup is the guy in the bar (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MESSAGE IN A BOTTLE,' starring Kevin Costner, Robin Wright Penn
and Paul Newman. Directed by Luis Mandoki (PG-13, 110 minutes).
Nicholas Sparks' best-selling novel, about a lonely, sensitive man
who sends a message out to sea and the lonely, beautiful woman who
finds it, is now a long and soggy film. Kevin Costner crosses the
line from teasingly laconic to stodgy and seems as likely to have
written ``Bleak House'' as the love letter in question. Robin
Wright Penn makes an appealing heroine, but there's not much room
for real emotion in a film with the tenor of a commercial for
hazelnut-flavored coffee. As the hero's crusty old father, Newman
steals what's left of the show (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `MY FAVORITE MARTIAN,' starring Christopher Lloyd, Jeff Daniels
and Ray Walston. Directed by Donald Petrie (PG, 88 minutes).
Pixilated pixels and other up-to-the-minute moviemaking magic
manage the neat feat of turning the big-screen, resurrected ``My
Favorite Martian'' into an amiable family entertainment. In this
updated version of the 1960s CBS sitcom, Jeff Daniels as Tim O'Hara
(now a television newsman rather than a newspaper reporter) and
Christopher Lloyd as the visitor from another planet take over the
roles played by Bill Bixby and Ray Walston. In one of the happy and
logical little jokes that lend a disarming charm to the comedy,
Walston turns up once again in a welcome guise as government
bloodhounds set out to capture the Martian. But a good deal of the
fun in this tale is provided by Zoot, his high-spirited polymorphic
space suit (Lawrence Van Gelder).
</P>
<P>
   `OCTOBER SKY,' starring Jake Gyllenhaal and Chris Cooper.
Directed by Joe Johnston (PG, 100 minutes). By far the most moving
scenes here are home movie snippets, circa 1957, that show the real
people on whom the film's characters are based. Otherwise, despite
being closely based on a best-selling memoir (``Rocket Boys'') by
the NASA engineer Homer H. Hickam Jr., this earnest, nostalgic film
has a way of seeming too good to be true. The film's simplicity is
appealing, as is Gyllenhaal in the central role of a boy in a West
Virginia coal mining town who becomes obsessed with rocketry. But
the story, filled with father-son conflict and down-in-the-ground
versus up-in-the-sky contrasts, often follows a familiar trajectory
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   `PAYBACK,' starring Mel Gibson and Gregg Henry. Directed by
Brian Helgeland (R, 110 minutes). In this inept, excessively
sadistic film-noir spoof adapted from the same Richard Stark novel
(``The Hunter'') that inspired the 1967 genre classic ``Point
Blank,'' Gibson is a thief named Porter who retaliates with a
vengeance after an attempt on his life. Determined to recover
$70,000 that was stolen from him by a double-crossing partner in
crime, he works his way up the pecking order of a crime syndicate,
brutally dispatching all who stand in his way. The hard-boiled
dialogue is ludicrous, the storytelling clunky, the acting fair to
awful, the gore ankle deep. Credit the star with being able to keep
a straight face through this loathsome mess (Stephen Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   `RUSHMORE,' starring Jason Schwartzman, Bill Murray and Olivia
Williams. Directed by Wes Anderson (R, 93 minutes). A dryly
hilarious portrait of the mogul as a young man, with Schwartzman a
real find as its perfectly horrid little hero, Max Fischer. Max's
prep school, Rushmore Academy, does have a faculty, but none of the
grown-ups have anything like Max's natural authority. Murray is
sneakily fine as the steel tycoon and Rushmore benefactor who
happens to be on Max's own wavelength as they vie for the same
beautiful teacher. A particular treat for its skewed, outrageously
funny memories of a cutthroat boyhood (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `SHAKESPEARE IN LOVE,' starring Joseph Fiennes and Gwyneth
Paltrow. Directed by John Madden (R, 113 minutes). A witty, sexy
and merrily literate delight, with an exhilaratingly clever premise
that only gets better as the film unfolds. The screenplay,
originating as Marc Norman's brainstorm and turned by Tom Stoppard
into razor-sharp dialogue reminiscent of his ``Rosencrantz and
Guildenstern Are Dead,'' dares to imagine whatever it likes about
the link between Shakespeare's artistic passions and his mad
yearning for a certain aristocratic beauty. Meanwhile this
tirelessly inventive comedy envisions an Elizabethan theater
fraught with the same backbiting and conniving we enjoy today and
has great fun presenting the creation of ``Romeo and Juliet,''
glitches and all. Fiennes and Ms. Paltrow make a fine, tempestuous
duo, and she gives the first great, fully realized starring
performance of her career (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `TANGO,' starring Miguel Angel Sola. Written and directed by
Carlos Saura. Cinematography by Vittorio Storaro (PG-13, 100
minutes). A thrilling display of tango heat and virtuosity. And
it's no slight to the actors who play lovers to say that the
dancing here is steamier than any kiss. In his most electrifying
dance film Saura offers transfixingly beautiful glimpses of the
dance and the great range of emotions it can conjure. Storaro's
dazzlingly fluid cinematography captures all the nuances this
material demands. Everyone in the film is utterly consumed by tango
fever; audiences will be, too (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `THE THIN RED LINE,' starring Jim Caviezel, Ben Chaplin, Nick
Nolte and Sean Penn. Directed by Terrence Malick (R, 166 minutes).
From the first frame of this huge, drifting war epic loosely
derived from James Jones' Guadalcanal novel, it's viscerally clear
that Malick is back. The exquisite, oddly detached visual style
that made ``Badlands'' and ``Days of Heaven'' the most beautiful
films of the 1970s is instantly apparent here, even if the
narrative vagueness and brooding voice-overs are also familiar. The
film sprawls, gets lost and occasionally delivers visual poetry,
the kind that could have been greatly helped by tighter editing.
Bottom line: No one who admired Malick's early work should miss
this. But those expecting anything simple will not find it here
(Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `20 DATES,' starring Myles Berkowitz. Directed by Berkowitz (R,
88 minutes). The filmmaker's gimmick is to make a film about
dating. His goal: To go out with 20 different women, get them on
camera by any means necessary and promise to fall in love with one
before the experiment is over. Berkowitz, pesty and proud of it,
has absorbed enough of Jerry Seinfeld and Garry Shandling to create
a diffident, nit-picking, sitcom-ready persona. But whenever his
film establishes a playful mood, it's liable to do something to
make you squirm. Crassness and mock candor aren't all that funny
(unless they're coming from Albert Brooks, whose ``Real Life''
paved the way for this). And discovering that cheese makes
Berkowitz constipated, or that one of his dates disappoints him by
not looking enough like Jessica Rabbit, is more than you need to
know (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   `200 CIGARETTES,' starring Paul Rudd, Kate Hudson, Ben Affleck,
Janeane Garofalo and Courtney Love, Directed by Risa Bramon Garcia
(R, 102 minutes). This contrived but cheery party movie marks the
feature directing debut of a well-known casting director. And in
making her film, Ms. Garcia does what she does best: cast. A group
of bright young players is brought together for a largely plotless
New Year's Eve, rambling around a colorfully evoked East Village,
circa 1981. Essentially just a set of interwoven skits, this comedy
still makes good use of the actors noted above, along with Casey
Affleck as a nice-guy punk, Dave Chappelle as a cabbie full of
advice and Martha Plimpton as a hopeless hostess. Ms. Hudson, who
is Goldie Hawn's daughter and has her mother's grin and giggle,
makes an adorable debut despite spending part of the movie with dog
excrement on her coat (Maslin).
</P>
<P>
   Film Series:
</P>
<P>
   `THE BILLY ROSE TRIBUTE TO EDWARD G. ROBINSON.' At 30, he made
his film debut, playing an old man in ``The Bright Shawl'' in 1923.
He didn't make another film for six years. But before his career
ended, he performed in some 80 films across five decades in roles
that ranged from ruthless gangster to man of science to introverted
accountant. His name was Edward G. Robinson (1893-1973). He spoke
eight languages, amassed a famous collection of French
Impressionist and Post-Impressionist art and denounced racism and
fascism. Now he is the subject of a retrospective of 27 features,
plus live-action shorts and animated films, at the Museum of Modern
Art. ``Robinson's type of stardom, unlike that of the romantic
leading man, enabled him to create complex, memorable personalities
in later supporting as well as principal roles,'' says Mary Lea
Bandy, the chief curator of the museum's Department of Film and
Video and an organizer of the retrospective. Among this weekend's
attractions, at 5 p.m. Sunday, is Fritz Lang's ``Scarlet Street''
(1946), with Robinson as an unhappily married company cashier whose
passion for a scheming young woman enmeshes him in embezzlement and
murder. Continuing through April 12 at the museum, the series, a
collaboration between the museum and the Billy Rose Foundation, is
free with museum admission: $9.50 for adults, $6.50 for students
and those 65 or older; free for members and visitors under 16
accompanied by an adult. Pay what you wish on Fridays from 4:30 to
8:30 p.m. Screening information: (212) 708-9400 (Van Gelder).
</P>
</TEXT>
