<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE GREAT WHITE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The foundering of ``Titanic,'' which said this week
that it will close at the end of March, has left the Lunt-Fontanne
Theater, one of Broadway's prime locales for big-budget musicals,
suddenly up for grabs.
</P>
<P>
   One seriously discussed option is that ``Beauty and the Beast,''
at the Palace Theater, would be transferred to the Lunt-Fontanne to
make way for Disney's new musical project, ``Aida,'' which is
aiming for a Broadway opening in spring 2000. Disney executives had
no comment on the possible deal, although officials for Nederlander
Organization, which owns both the Lunt-Fontanne and the Palace,
confirmed that talks were under way.
</P>
<P>
   But the Nederlanders are also considering booking a fall musical
rather than leaving their theater dark for an entire year, said
Nick Scandalios, the organization's executive vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Among the musicals mentioned to be looking for a home in the
fall, although not necessarily at the Lunt-Fontanne, are a planned
revival of ``The Music Man'' and a current tour of ``Evita,'' as
well as several new works. ``Music Man'' is being produced by
Dodger Theatricals, which also produced ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   Scandalios cautioned that any speculation was premature. The
first step for the Lunt-Fontanne, after ``Titanic,'' will be a
lengthy dismantling of the show's equipment, including its huge
mechanized set. That process, plus cleanup and repairs, is expected
to take several months.
</P>
<P>
   Dancing on the Rules
</P>
<P>
   The news that ``Rollin' on the T.O.B.A.'' will be moving to the
Kit Kat Klub, on West 43rd Street in Manhattan, promises to set off
another hot debate over the Tony Awards' famously flexible
eligibility standards.
</P>
<P>
   The producers of ``T.O.B.A.,'' a well-reviewed look at the songs
and experiences from the heyday of black vaudeville, have already
written to the Tony Administration Committee seeking a special
dispensation for the show. Their argument is that because the Kit
Kat Klub, formerly the Henry Miller Theater, was the initial home
of the production of ``Cabaret'' that was deemed eligible by the
committee last year, so should ``T.O.B.A.'' be considered eligible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't understand how you can say during one year that a show
in a theater is eligible, and the next year another show isn't,''
said Ashton Springer, the show's producer.
</P>
<P>
   But Keith Sherman, a Tony spokesman, said the decision on
``Cabaret'' dealt only with that production, and that the Kit Kat
Klub itself was not an eligible theater. The club's owners are also
seeking permanent eligibility, though that decision, even if
approved, would not be in effect until next year.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the committee's 24 members said that in winning
eligibility, ``Cabaret'' had several advantages over ``T.O.B.A.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Cabaret'' was a production of Roundabout Theater Company, an
established Broadway producer and a proprietor of Stage Right, at
the Criterion Center, a Tony-eligible theater; ``T.O.B.A.'' has
independent, lesser-known producers. ``Cabaret'' also had the
advantage of having been produced, to good reviews, in London, and
of starring Natasha Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Sherman said the Tony administrators would consider the request
soon. ``Every year there are a few situations that the rules don't
address,'' he said. ``That's why we meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Springer said he was simply pleased by the turn of events for
``T.O.B.A.,'' which began last fall at the Billie Holiday Theater
in Brooklyn before transferring to the 47th Street Theater. ``I
never in a trillion years was thinking about it going on to
Broadway,'' Springer said. ``We would have been happy to get
nominated for an Obie.''
</P>
<P>
   Not About Hair
</P>
<P>
   Finbar Lynch says one of the acute dangers of acting is boredom
_ not only for audiences but for actors. ``If you're just churning
out the same thing night after night,'' Lynch said, ``you're going
to go nuts.''
</P>
<P>
   He knows of what he speaks. An actor since he was 18, Lynch, now
36, has enjoyed long runs in several shows at the Royal Shakespeare
Company in London. Currently he's earning strong reviews as Jim
Allison, the book-smart convict in Tennessee Williams' prison
melodrama, ``Not About Nightingales,'' at the Circle in the Square
Theater, after a run last summer at the Alley Theater in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The actor said he had experimented with his role since the
summer. But not all his efforts have been rousing successes. During
previews for ``Nightingales,'' Lynch tried out a new wig for his
character. ``I thought it might be a good idea to have a bit of
hair,'' he said. ``It was sort of public-school boy look.''
</P>
<P>
   But he decided that ``it was ridiculous,'' he said. ``I felt I
was in a different play, `Arcadia,' or something. I wouldn't have
lasted 10 seconds in prison with that hair.''
</P>
<P>
   Lynch has also changed his name since his last appearance in New
York, in 1996, during a tour of ``A Midsummer's Night Dream.'' At
that point he was going by his nickname, Barry. That, too, had
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to get fan letters for an actor named Barry Lynch who
was on `Star Trek,''' he said. ``And when I was in England, I used
to get letters for a diet doctor named Barry Lynch with checks
inside.'' He added, ``I did not cash them.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernard? Is That You?
</P>
<P>
   It was an unexpected Broadway debut. On Tuesday night, midway
through Act II of ``Death of a Salesman,'' the actor Richard
Thompson, who plays Bernard, was felled by food poisoning and
missed an entrance. After several moments of watching the actors ad
lib onstage (``Bernard? Bernard, where are you?''), the stage
manager stopped the show and brought up the house lights.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, on came Steve Cell, Thompson's understudy,
who had been on call in a basement green room. His first scene was
with the show's star, Brian Dennehy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just looked at him and said, `Be with the guy,''' Cell said.
</P>
<P>
   Cell received a special ovation during the curtain call.
Thompson, who went to the hospital on Tuesday night, returned to
the show for the Wednesday matinee.
</P>
</TEXT>
