<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATALOG SELLERS THRIVE ON LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As video sales on the Internet rise, it's good to see old-line
purveyors _ those with paper catalogs in the two-to-three-pound
range _ holding their own, not only between covers but on the Web
as well.
</P>
<P>
   To be respectable in video mail order these days, one needs at
least 40,000 titles. Movies Unlimited, a large Philadelphia
distributor, packs that many in a fat catalog that can now be found
on the Internet at www.mostmovies.com.
</P>
<P>
   Like other sites, this one has specific strengths. Built over 20
years, the collection at one time or another has gotten into every
nook and cranny of a genre or career, at least as it exists on
video. Search John Wayne, for example, and you come up with more
than 200 entries from feature films to television commercials.
</P>
<P>
   Another virtue of the large older mail order operation is that
over the years it has accumulated a wide assortment of titles that
are no longer in distribution and probably never will be again. If
you've been told a film isn't available, perhaps Movies Unlimited
has a copy available.
</P>
<P>
   For example, ``Absolute Beginners'' (1985), a look at the London
fashion world of 1958 (with a soundtrack by David Bowie and
others), is $35.99, which is a representative price for these
few-of-a-kind videos. That's $35.99 used, it should be added. Many
of the cassettes were in rental circulation years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The company says that tapes are in very good shape unless
otherwise stated. Prices vary according to a title's past
popularity, present rarity and condition. ``The American Friend''
(1977), Wim Weders' highly regarded film noir starring Dennis
Hopper and Bruno Ganz, is $53.99 used, another typical price.
</P>
<P>
   But choice obviously recommends a catalog or Web inventory.
Perhaps the most unusual selection belongs to Facets International,
a Chicago distributor. Last week Facets issued its very large
(10-by-15-inch, 625-page) paper catalog. Jump into it at random,
and there is Victor Sjostrom's ``Secret of the Monastery'' (1919),
and Henry Jaglom's ``Babyfever'' (1995) and Jack Arnold's
``Tarantula'' (1955).
</P>
<P>
   The catalog can also be found at the Facets site,
www.facets.org, where this week the noted selections include
Mitchell Leisen's 1934 comedy ``Death Takes a Holiday'' and George
Romero's second film, ``There's Always Vanilla'' (1971).
</P>
<P>
   The catalog is edited by Milos Stehlik, Facets' video director.
``The Internet has helped people become aware of these films,'' he
said. ``That leads to sophisticated specialized collecting.''
</P>
<P>
   Another hopeful sign for a broader selection, he said, is
increased activity by smaller independent distributors like Fox
Lorber, First Run, Kino, Water Bearer and Home Vision. All are
putting out more high-grade independent and foreign films, like
Abbas Kiarostami's acclaimed ``Taste of Cherry,'' an Iranian film
about a man's search for someone to go to the cemetery and bury him
after he has committed suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Home Vision is to release the movie next month. It was shown at
the New York Film Festival in 1997 and made a brief theater
appearance. ``People are looking to video for these kinds of
films,'' Stehlik said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Slam
</P>
<P>
   It's fitting that the verbal competitions called slams _
head-to-head clashes of rap, performance art and stand-up comedy _
have their own movie to do for this rhythmically charged, fervently
incantatory street poetry what ``Saturday Night Fever'' did for
disco in the 70s.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Joshua (Saul Williams, left) makes a charismatic young black
inner city hero. Around the housing project known as Dodge City,
Ray's mild-mannered intelligence makes him something of a mythic
being, but that doesn't keep him out of prison for possession of
marijuana.
</P>
<P>
   Behind bars he writes poetry, develops his delivery to
mesmerizing effect and meets a young woman (Sonja Sohn), a slammer
herself, who teaches a writing class. Later on the outside she
invites Ray on stage, where he ``kills'' (slamese for knocks them
dead).
</P>
<P>
   This may be rose-colored, but ``what `Slam' possesses,'' Stephen
Holden wrote in The New York Times, ``is a real passion, and that
is in short supply in movies these days.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Trimark. $79.99. 100 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: March 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   What Dreams May Come &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How about this for movie pathos? Two children die in a car
accident, leaving the mother in a suicidal depression. The father
rallies the mother, but he gets killed in an accident so she
commits suicide anyway.
</P>
<P>
   And now everything points to a big rendezvous in the hereafter.
Annie (Annabella Sciora), a painter in life, has landed in
purgatory for taking her own life. Chris (Robin Williams, all
crinkly and misty-moisty) is upstairs in a golden kingdom bathed in
glorious light, a sort of hallucinatory extension of the physical
world he left behind when he was still a talented pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, Chris goes below to look for Annie (with Max von Sydow
as a grim guide called The Tracker). That they get their reunion is
fair enough, but in the process too much about these people and
their children is crammed into too little space, and all the
weeping and hugging can't make up for a ``fatal lack of texture and
psychological nuance'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Polygram. $106.99. 114 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: March 9. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ever After: A Cinderella Story
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later she had to happen: a Cinderella who makes it on
guts and drive and not on just foot size and a boost from her fairy
godmother. This Cinderella (Drew Barrymore) rises from her humble
station to become a princess in 16th-century France.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of being saved by the prince (Dougray Scott), this
Cinderella turns the tables, saving her wimpy consort from a band
of outlaws in the forest. A princess with very progressive ideas,
she gets her in-laws to pay for a university with a library for all
the people.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the charmed couple have wed, she has schooled the
prince in the harsh political realities from which his privileged
life has shielded him. The problem is that as refreshing as this
is, the movie ``never makes up its mind whether it's a spoof, a
soap opera or a feminist pep talk'' (Holden). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Fox. $19.98. 122 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   These days many video stores, especially the chains, are
stocking more copies of new releases, which means the supply of
hits is less likely to run out over the weekend _ or so the theory
goes. In any event, here are some current best renters you may have
a better chance of finding when you want them. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THERE'S SOMETHING ABOUT MARY. A young man (Ben Stiller) still
smitten with the girl he asked to the prom years ago (Cameron Diaz)
tracks her down in Florida, where matters turn outrageous. 1998.
Fox. $108.97. 118 minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   MULAN. In the Disney animated film, a young woman dresses like a
man and takes the place of her ailing father when he can't serve in
the army. But in the ranks and in life, the men she meets are
generally buffoons. 1998. $26.99. 88 minutes. Closed captioned. G.
</P>
<P>
   ANTZ. A worker ant called Z (the voice of Woody Allen) is called
on to take up arms and rescue his breed from their enemies. ``Why
don't we just try to influence their political process with
campaign contributions?'' he wonders. 1998. Dreamworks. $26.99. 83
minutes. Closed captioned. PG.
</P>
<P>
   ROUNDERS. Off hours in smoky rooms a clean-cut law student bets
his tuition in big-stakes poker games with a Russian gambling
kingpin and other high rollers. 1998. Miramax. $107.37. 120
minutes. Closed captioned. R.
</P>
<P>
   LETHAL WEAPON 4. With all its familiar pieces in place _
including the usual benighted jokes about homosexuality and other
sensitive topics _ the old action series blasts along on the same
jokey camaraderie between the detectives Riggs (Mel Gibson) and
Murtaugh (Danny Glover). 1998. Warner. $107.37. 127 minutes. Closed
captioned. R.
</P>
