<P>
   MARINE-AVIATOR (Camp Lejeune, N.C.) _ A court martial acquits
Capt. Richard Ashby, accused of manslaughter in the deaths of 20
skiers in Italy. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   with
</P>
<P>
   MARINE-REACT (Rome) _ Italians reacted with shock and outrage to
the acquittal. Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, who was giving a
speech in Boston, said he was ``baffled'' by the verdict and would
bring up the perceived injustice on Friday at a meeting with
President Clinton. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-BLACKMUN (Washington) _ Former Justice Harry Balckmun, who
wrote the majority opinion in the 1973 landmark abortion case, Roe
vs. Wade, has died at 90. By Linda Greenhouse.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-RELIEF (Washington) _ The House stalls an emergency
Central American relief bill on the eve of President Clinton's trip
to the region, as both House and Senate committees seek to cut
coveted administration anti-poverty programs to pay for Hurricane
Mitch aid and stay within budget caps. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washinton) _ A financial overhaul bill
proposed by Senate Banking Chairman Phil Gramm, R-Texas, split the
committee along partisan lines today. It faces a presidential veto
because President Clinton believes the bill, which would remove the
Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms and
insurance companies, fails to protect consumers and would hurt
community lending laws. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
