<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7848 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SF-SPENDING-HNS &LR;      03-04 0490
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY OFFICIALS SAY SAN FRANCISCO SURPLUS SHRINKING FAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RACHEL GORDON  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The city budget faces a $57 million deficit in
three years if the rate of spending remains the same and revenue
slows, San Francisco's senior financial wizards say.
</P>
<P>
   That would represent a stark turnaround in City Hall's recent
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate was released Wednesday in a joint report by
Controller Ed Harrington, Board of Supervisors Budget Analyst
Harvey Rose and Matthew Hymel, the mayor's budget director.
</P>
<P>
   They were quick to point out that budget projections are based
on today's understanding of the city's budget picture, taking into
account everything from inflation to pay raises for public
employees.
</P>
<P>
   However, Harrington and Hymel said they were optimistic that the
tax base would continue to grow, averting deficits that were
routine just a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The projection, they said, should be used as nothing more than a
signal that close vigilance over the budget is warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Finance Committee should use a lot of caution in
their budget considerations this year,'' Rose said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The days of living high on the hog are over,'' said Leland
Yee, chairman of the Board of Supervisors' Finance Committee. ``Now
we have to start tackling the structural problems of the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed that there would be no automatic midyear bailouts when
departments run out of money and that workers' compensation claims
would be monitored. Some 6,000 of San Francisco's 27,000 city
employees file for workers' compensation each year, accounting for
one of the city's most nagging and costly budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're going to continue this lifestyle, we are going to be
in deficit mode,'' Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's last fiscal year ended in June with a $145
million surplus _ the largest this decade. But a combination of
runaway workers' compensation costs, unanticipated overtime,
higher-than-expected expenses to run the two public hospitals and a
bailout for the municipal transit system have been eating into the
money pot.
</P>
<P>
   Add to that the 1,800 new employees in the four years since
Mayor Willie Brown has been in office and a steady stream of pay
raises, and balancing the almost $4 billion budget becomes more
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Harrington said that by the start of the next fiscal year, on
July 1, the surplus will shrink to $1.5 million. He said even that
is a comfortable cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``In summary, the city is in good shape,'' Harrington said.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, when the economy was flat, deficits were
routinely $100 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   By law, San Francisco must start each new fiscal year with a
balanced budget, so any deficits must be erased by service cuts,
dismissals or increases in taxes and fees, prospects that make
politicians flinch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
