<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7849 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT &LR;      03-04 1157
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS WEEK'S TV HIGHLIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Talk about your hardy perennials. After nearly 100 years ``The
Scarlet Pimpernel'' remains a tingling adventure yarn. A string of
novels and stories by Baroness Emmuska Orczy that began in 1900
have spawned at least seven movies, countless spoofs and several
stage adaptations, including the current Broadway musical.
</P>
<P>
   Betting that there's still some swash in the old boy's buckle,
A&AMP;E is offering three new ``Pimpernel'' films. Judging by the first
of these, to be seen on Sunday night, the bet has paid delightful
dividends.
</P>
<P>
   It's 1793, and the French are revolting. Things are getting out
of hand; those who toppled the king are proving to be tyrants
themselves. Heads are rolling. Literally.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one ray of hope: a small, mysterious band has been
rescuing some innocent prisoners from the clutches of Robespierre's
henchmen and spiriting them to safety in England. The band's
fearless leader (OK, (italics)you(end italics) try telling this
story without cliches) is known by his nom de guerre, the Scarlet
Pimpernel. Who is he?
</P>
<P>
   He is Sir Percy Blakeney, a foppish Englishman, the witty life
of any party, whose dalliances _ fencing, hunting, racing his yacht
_ are the perfect cover for his secret identity. This playboy is
the original Batman, the proto-Green Hornet.
</P>
<P>
   And the current adapters, led by the director Patrick Lau and
the writer Richard Carpenter, retell his tale with tongue firmly in
cheek, toying merrily with this costume-draped fable without ever
letting it descend into camp.
</P>
<P>
   Two of this romp's strongest assets are Richard E. Grant as
Percy and Martin Shaw as his evil nemesis, Chauvelin, once the
lover of Lady Blakeney, nee Marguerite Sainte-Just, back in the
days when she was a Parisian music-hall chanteuse.
</P>
<P>
   Now Chauvelin is a dogged pursuer of those deemed enemies of the
French Revolution, with the Pimpernel at the top of his list.
</P>
<P>
   When the two first meet at a London party for the Prince of
Wales, Percy is deep into his silly-weakling act, which has even
fooled Marguerite (Elizabeth McGovern). Challenged to a duel, he
parries with bons mots, saying he won't fight because ``it's bad
for the digestion, and it ruins one's clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the two-hour film _ a satisfying resolution that
still leaves room for adventures to come _ the two antagonists are
snorting fire at each other. Their performances honor the memory of
Leslie Howard and Raymond Massey, who played these roles in 1934,
while adding just the right dash of 1990s irony.
</P>
<P>
   As the third member of the story's central triangle, however,
Ms. McGovern looks as if she isn't having any fun. As the story
progresses, Marguerite must radically change her opinion of her
husband as she understands his true courage and must display a
barrelful of courage herself.
</P>
<P>
   But even while declaiming lines like ``Love is stronger than
hate,'' Ms. McGovern seems ever passive and a bit dazed. (You may
be a bit dazed, too, if you try too hard to follow the convoluted
plot, filled with intrigues and betrayals. Don't sweat the small
stuff.)
</P>
<P>
   Ms. McGovern is an American playing a Frenchwoman. But as
everybody does in this film (a co-production with the BBC) she
speaks with a British accent. It would have helped the American
viewer if there were some aural clues to keep the fictional French
and Brits sorted out.
</P>
<P>
   But if the ear is a bit confused, the eye is well served. The
French Republic, as recreated in the Czech Republic, is a dark and
smoky but endlessly fascinating place. Many scenes are packed with
details, like the children playing with their imaginary, improvised
guillotine on a Paris street.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the supporting cast members are worth attention,
among them Ron Donachie as Percy's French friend Mazzarini, a
forger who can duplicate paintings and documents. ``I haven't an
original brush stroke in my body,'' he proclaims proudly.
</P>
<P>
   There may be no more originality in this film than in one of
Mazzarini's masterpieces. But this is no forgery. It's genuine
silly fun. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEASONS OF LOVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CBS, Sunday and Tuesday night at 9 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 2 in New York) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The story (italics)about(end italics) the novel ``The Earth
Abideth'' may be more fascinating than anything (italics)in(end
italics) it. The plot, beginning in the 1860s, spans 50 years in
the life of an Ohio farm family. It was written in 1938 but not
published until 1986, when the author, George Dell, was 85.
</P>
<P>
   Now, alas, the story has been slapped with a one-size-fits-all
title, ``Seasons of Love,'' and turned into a generic mini-series
that's as distinctive as a can of store-brand no-frills green peas.
</P>
<P>
   When first seen, Thomas Linthorne (Peter Strauss) is a traveling
seed salesman. He will spend the rest of his life reaping what he
sows. The moment he sees Kate (Rachel Ward), he knows he's found
his life's companion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I ain't lookin' for a workhorse,'' he says. ``Don't you worry
about me workin','' she replies. They talk like that to each other
for four hours, while they endure trials, tribulations and
children. Then they die.
</P>
<P>
   Strauss and Ms. Ward, mini-series mainstays, conserve their
acting energy over the long haul, letting a brave smile or mopey
pout define the husband and wife. This is more like reciting than
acting. At one pivotal moment Thomas explains, ``My heart is
broken.''
</P>
<P>
   The supporting cast includes Rip Torn, who looks uncomfortable,
and Hume Cronyn, who proves that it is possible to create a
three-dimensional three-minute character. Three cheers.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Thomas says, ``There don't seem to be no rhyme or
reason how things turned out,'' you'll have to agree. Unless you
have a heart of iron, you'll be moved by the story's conclusion.
But unless you have a constitution of steel, you won't get that
far. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SCARLET PIMPERNEL  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;E, Sunday night at 9 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   First of a three-part film series written by Richard Carpenter
and based on the books by Baroness Emmuska Orczy. Patrick Lau and
Edward Bennett, directors; Julian Murphy, producer; music composed
by Michal Pavlicek and performed by the Prague Philharmonics,
conducted by Mario and Adam Klemens; choreography by Bruno Tonioli;
Simon Kossoff and John Hooper, directors of photography.
</P>
<P>
   An A&AMP;E/BBC co-production in association with London Films. Tony
Virgo (BBC); Johan Eliasch, Morgan Mason and Hannah Rothschild
(London Films), executive producers. Dela Fine, executive producer
for A&AMP;E Network. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Richard E. Grant (Sir Percy Blakeney), Elizabeth McGovern
(Lady Marguerite Blakeney), Martin Shaw (Chauvelin), Anthony Green
(Sir Andrew Foulkes), Ronan Vibert (Robespierre), Christopher
Fairbank (Fumier), Gerard Murphy (Planchet), Ron Donachie
(Mazzarini), Beth Goddard (Suzanne De Tourney), Milton Johns
(Fisher) and Jonathan Coy (the Prince of Wales). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
