<HEADER>
A7852 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-FREDERICKSBURG-T     03-04 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-FREDERICKSBURG-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROLL OUT THE ... RACK OF LAMB AND OTHER SOPHISTICATED DELIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's not all kuchen and kitsch in Fredericksburg anymore.
</P>
<P>
   A serious tourist trade also means some serious restaurants.
Although we love brats and beer, it's terrific to have the option
of something a little less, well, Germanic. Here are some newish
offerings in the heart of the Hill Country.
</P>
<P>
   Lincoln St.: Start out the evening in this meandering
wine-cheese-olive emporium. Order a plate of cheese for two of
manchego, white Cheddar, bel paese or fontina, take a pick of your
favorite plonk and sit down to watch a collection of locals from
cattlemen to lawyers wander in to say howdy. It's very civilized
without being pretentious.
</P>
<P>
   111 S. Lincoln St., (830) 997-8463. Open 10 a.m.-9 p.m.
Tuesday-Thursday; 10 a.m.-11 p.m. Friday-Saturday; 1-9 p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Navajo Grill: This very modern restaurant is tucked in among the
gift shops on Fredericksburg's main drag. Desert tones on the tiled
floors take diners far away from cuckoo clocks and Hummels.
</P>
<P>
   The Banderas pork chop ($17.95) is a mountainous double-cut chop
served with roasted-garlic mashed potatoes and grilled vegetables.
(We had been tipped to the restaurant's wonderful fried spinach _
spinach deep-fried until it is just an ethereal mouthful _ and the
waiter nicely made the substitution.) Just as heavenly is the Black
Angus rib-eye ($20.95) served with creole garlic cream potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   As we were leaving, we complimented the chef through the serving
window from the kitchen. The pork, we said, was fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, thanks,'' he replied, ``the trick is to turn it on its
side with the bone touching the grill for the last few minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   A terrific meal and a cooking tip to go.
</P>
<P>
   209 E. Main St., (830) 990-8289. Open 11:30 a.m.-2 p.m.
Tuesday-Saturday; 6-9 p.m. Tuesday-Thursday; 6-10 p.m.
Friday-Saturday. Reservations recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Cuisine: Marie-Claire Quittelier is a bundle of energy.
She made her name in Fredericksburg with the eponymous
MarieCuisine, a tiny house where she served breakfast and lunch,
the occasional dinner (locals knew to call to find out if dinner
was on), taught cooking classes and catered special events.
</P>
<P>
   Lunches tend to be on the light side. Our favorites here include
a tomato soup with madeira (customers call in advance to find out
if it's the day's soup) and the chocolate mousse, a
too-often-forgotten classic.
</P>
<P>
   As high season approaches, Marie-Claire is readying a bistro on
Main Street that will handle the breakfast and lunch trade. The
original Marie Cuisine will then serve only dinner.
</P>
<P>
   202 E. Schubert, (830) 990-0498, call for hours. The Bistro in
the Courtyard of the Nimitz Birthplace (249 E. Main St.) will open
in March to serve breakfast and lunch.
</P>
<P>
   The Nest: John and Monica Wilkinson took a round-about route to
the Hill Country. Originally from San Antonio, they moved to Aspen,
where John was chef at the Ritz-Carlton Hotel. Now back in Texas,
they're doing a bang-up job with The Nest.
</P>
<P>
   The aptly named restaurant is a cozy little refitted house with
service Fort Worth could aspire to. The menu is a mix of native
ingredients with classic treatments. A velvety fillet of beef is
paired with bordelaise sauce for $21. A rack of to-die-for lamb is
served with a stone-ground mustard demi-glace and turnip mashed
potatoes (they do love their potatoes in Fredericksburg) for $23.
On the lighter (and less expensive side of the menu) are pasta with
tomato sauce, kalamata olives, capers and asiago cheese for $9, and
a roasted half-chicken with portobello mushroom sauce for $15.
</P>
<P>
   607 S. Washington, (830) 990-8383. Open 5-9 p.m. Thursday and
Sunday-Monday; 5-10 p.m. Friday-Saturday. Reservations recommended.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
