<HEADER>
A7853 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-JENNIFERGREY-TEX     03-04 1096
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-JENNIFERGREY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`DIRTY DANCING' STAR GOT A NOSE JOB TO BOOST HER CAREER _ BUT IT
BACKFIRED
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by GREY-COSMETIC SURGERY and GREY-FLAWED FACES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two things used to be off-limits in a Jennifer Grey interview.
</P>
<P>
   Her nose job and her love life.
</P>
<P>
   Now both are fair game.
</P>
<P>
   In ``It's like, you know,'' the promising midseason comedy
premiering March 24 on ABC, Jennifer Grey portrays Jennifer Grey, a
struggling actress who unwittingly created her own anonymity with a
less-than-flattering nose job.
</P>
<P>
   The running gag of the series, created by former ``Seinfeld''
writer and producer Peter Mehlman, is that Grey's appearance has
been so joltingly modified that even the most passionate ``Dirty
Dancing'' followers aren't sure it's her. Jennifer Grey has to
convince people she's actually Jennifer Grey.
</P>
<P>
   If the actress is still pained by this unfortunate career fluke,
she's not letting on. What's certain is that she has received so
much flak about her nose, from stunned casting directors passing
her over to moviegoers squinting to recognize her, that mocking her
own misfortune couldn't damage a career defined by theatrical flops
and featherweight made-for-TV movies.
</P>
<P>
   For Grey, 39, this might be her last-ditch effort for stardom.
She admits now that she panicked when scripts didn't come her way
after the 1987 sleeper hit ``Dirty Dancing'' grossed more than $300
million worldwide and made a sensual star of co-lead Patrick
Swayze.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the scapegoat was the nose.
</P>
<P>
   On hiatus from the film ``Wind'' in 1992, she returned with the
new look, stunning her co-workers, none of whom thought she needed
it. Her old pudgy nose (which had gotten her the ``Dirty Dancing''
lead, after all) was now slimmer, leaner, sleeker, longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was strictly so I could get jobs,'' Grey says. ``The intent
was to look exactly the same. Just photographed a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, cosmetic surgery is like white noise _ omnipresent
and virtually unnoticed. Not getting some kind of facial or body
lift is more the exception in a business that's fueled by the
exterior.
</P>
<P>
   But few have gone through the public ridicule experienced by
Grey, whose shapely almond eyes complemented her wider nose in
pre-surgery days. Now it simply looks like something is missing
from her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go under the knife, you're taking an enormous risk,''
says Ted Harbert, a former chairman of ABC Entertainment and a
co-executive producer of ``It's like, you know.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early episodes of ``It's like, you know,'' which will air
at 7:30 p.m. CST Wednesdays, Grey's revelations represent some of
the funnier threads weaving through this series, a kind of ``L.A.
Story'' wheeled around a sitcom formula. It focuses on a New York
writer's (Chris Eigeman as Arthur) cynical pretenses about Los
Angeles. Like, you know, how the city comes to a halt during
highway car chases.
</P>
<P>
   Grey is the neighbor of Arthur's friend (Robbie, played by
Steven Eckholdt), and she bounces in and out, sharing anecdotes
about horrible auditions and clashes with fans who think she's
Jennifer Grey but aren't sure. (In one scene, she's ecstatic when
someone actually recognizes her.)
</P>
<P>
   Just as revealing is her other continuing story line _ that men
seem to become famous after she dates them.
</P>
<P>
   Grey has rarely wanted for romantic attention (another sign that
The Nose wasn't much of a hindrance). She was engaged to Johnny
Depp for nine months in 1990 and has been romantically linked to
Tom Cruise, Liam Neeson and Matthew Broderick. (Post-surgery dates
included former Clinton staffer George Stephanopoulos.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I just have very good taste in men,'' Grey explains.
``Honestly, guys becoming famous after they date me is a joke in my
life. So I thought, let's make this someone who can't get ahead
herself but everyone she kisses or dates or goes out with, even a
little, gets what she wants. So it's a lot of, `what, him, too?'''
</P>
<P>
   Grey tells Mehlman so much about her life that she has to
preface chats with ``but this can't be in the show'' just so he'll
know what's for the art and what's a private conversation. And in
an interview, sharing only goes so far; Grey won't talk about how
her show-biz family feels about her change in face or a role
basically poking fun at her life. She's the granddaughter of
comedian Mickey Katz; her mother is former Broadway actress Jo
Silver, her father is Broadway star Joel Grey.
</P>
<P>
   She spent most of her childhood shuttling between Manhattan and
LA, all the while dreaming of being an actress, a profession
forbidden by her father until she was old enough to leave home. He
felt she needed more maturity to deal with the hardships of acting,
and now she gets his drift.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, there's the way she felt after learning that the
``Dirty Dancing'' role was won because she wasn't considered ``an
obvious beauty.'' This feeling of inadequacy was renewed during the
movie's 10-year anniversary when producer Linda Gottlieb told
``Entertainment Tonight'' that she saw Grey in the same vein as
Barbra Streisand in ``The Way We Were,'' another fantasy in which
the average girl gets the gorgeous guy.
</P>
<P>
   Now Grey talks about her experiences in a Zen-like way, speaking
of things like destiny, and saying that without having had things
happen ``exactly'' as they did, she would have never gotten the
lessons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have never figured out who I was without celebrity,''
she says. Nor would she have been handed a gift many famous people
crave.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got to be in the world with normal people again after that
was taken away by being recognizable,'' Grey says. ``I had to
completely rebuild who I thought I was without anyone's input. And
I think that's the most valuable thing in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's another oddity. If ``It's like, you know'' becomes a hit,
Grey could lose what she gained, falling back into the unrealistic
world her series character mocks.
</P>
<P>
   Grey is Zen-like again. ``I'll deal with what comes,'' she says.
``And even if (the series) doesn't work, I'll deal with that also.
There is no way of anticipating or controlling any of it. We're all
so powerless. We can only do the best we can. The results are out
of our hands.''
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
