<HEADLINE>
THE COSMETIC SURGERY HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TV-JENNIFER GREY) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jennifer Grey isn't the only star who has cut off her nose to
spite her face _ or reshaped some other part of the anatomy. Here
are our nominations for the Cosmetic Surgery Hall of Fame. (Kudos
to the Plastic People Page,
www.geocities.com/Hollywood/7990/plastic.html).
</P>
<P>
   MICHAEL JACKSON: Having seen his face on TV since he first
upstaged his brothers at age 10, Jackson must've become bored. How
else to explain the way the attractive young African-American on
the cover of 1979's Off the Wall evolved into the angular, oddly
pigmented eccentric who's really off the wall?
</P>
<P>
   ROSEANNE: According to the Plastic People Page, Roseanne has had
work on both face and body. If only there were cosmetic surgery
that could alter unpleasantly caustic personalities.
</P>
<P>
   CHER: On their TV show, Sonny Bono constantly ribbed his
then-wife about her big nose. So she changed it _ and just about
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   DEMI MOORE: Moore has claimed that she hasn't had her breasts
done. Rent ``Blame It on Rio'' and ``Striptease,'' then you decide.
On second thought, rent ``About Last Night'' ... and ``A Few Good
Men''; the first two movies are too high a price to pay for
curiosity about someone's body.
</P>
<P>
   PHYLLIS DILLER: Unlike some other stars, Diller has been open
about her surgery, but it's a little pointless, like restoring one
of those Gremlin cars from the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
