<HEADLINE>
FLAWED FACES WE ADMIRE
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanies TV-JENNIFER GREY) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probable that every star in Hollywood over the age of 30 _
and many under _ has had some sort of cosmetic surgery. But a few
wear their most prominent flaws as badges of honor. We salute them,
because flawed beauty is more interesting than perfect beauty.
</P>
<P>
   BARBRA STREISAND: Streisand's strikingly large nose _ not to
mention her too-wide lips _ wonderfully offsets her huge, warm blue
eyes, making her the poster child for not messing too much with
your face.
</P>
<P>
   DUSTIN HOFFMAN: Because of his honker, Hoffman has played
oddball character roles much more often than he has played romantic
leads. Not coincidentally, he has also become one of Hollywood's
most interesting actors.
</P>
<P>
   ELLEN BARKIN: We're not sure how to put this delicately, so we
won't: Barkin looks like she's been hit in the face with a frying
pan. But her attitude can be so unbelievable sexy _ watch her back
Al Pacino against a door in ``Sea of Love'' _ that we're infatuated
with her, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   CLINT EASTWOOD: With every new movie, Clint's face looks more
and more like the rugged landscapes of his spaghetti westerns, but
he has taken advantage of the crags in his aging tough-guy roles.
</P>
<P>
   CAMRYN MANHEIM: The Emmy-winning star of TV's ``The Practice''
has proved that you don't have to be slim to be beautiful.
</P>
<P>
   _ Robert Philpot
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
