</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLYAKITE-TEX </SLUG>
 
IT'S SPRING, AND THAT MEANS IT'S TIME TO CATCH THE WIND (For use by
NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MARK LOWRY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kite-flying season is almost here. As far as you're concerned.
</P>
<P>
   For some _ namely members of the American Kitefliers Association
and its Dallas-Fort Worth chapter, Jewels of the Sky, or JOTS _
it's always the right time for flying kites.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you need is a steady wind with no turbulence, preferably
12 to 15 miles per hour,'' says Larry Whitacre, JOTS vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, but most people wouldn't be willing to endure Mother
Nature's other elements _ precipitation and cold weather, for
example _ in order to get that thrill of getting a kite off the
ground and keeping it afloat.
</P>
<P>
   Well, even JOTS folk don't fly in the driving rain, but they do
have the patience to wait it out. Or, they turn to one of the
newest trends in kite flying: indoor kites.
</P>
<P>
   Flying kites indoors is not ideal, though, considering that they
are ultralight and can only fly a few score feet overhead, with the
operator's walking movements rather than the wind as the
centrifugal force.
</P>
<P>
   For those of us on a more basic kite-flying level, spring is an
ideal time of the year to fly a kite.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the AKA and the Kite Trade Association International
are heading an effort to officially designate April as National
Kite Month. Trial events _ including community flies, education and
youth involvement _ will premiere this year, with a bigger,
millennial push for nationwide awareness in April 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Kite flying is a great family activity, but if you attend JOTS
functions _ which happen each weekend and rotate between parks in
Fort Worth, Richardson and Lewisville _ it's the older kids, the
30-plus-somethings, you'll see constantly constructing, comparing
notes, measuring the wind. You know, having ``fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Nixie, former JOTS president, has been fascinated with
kites most of her life. ``It's playing with the wind,'' she says.
``You're playing with something you can't see. I like everything
having to do with nature, storms and all that.''
</P>
<P>
   When the big kids play, kite flying becomes a sport that
requires as many safety rules as a full-contact sport. Kite
etiquette _ knowing how much distance to give between oneself and
other fliers, watching out for grounded kite lines _ is mandatory.
After all, some of these kites can cost hundreds of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   This is where education comes in. Nixie often holds workshops
and teaches in the schools about kiting safety and how to construct
a basic kite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We usually start with a sled kite, made from an 11-by-17-inch
sheet of copier paper, a paper streamer tail and rods of plastic
drinking straws,'' she says. ``It's a tiger-face design, so I have
them draw on eyes, mouth and the tiger stripes.''
</P>
<P>
   These kites are usually given about 60 feet of line, plenty to
keep a youngster amused.
</P>
<P>
   ``For children, they learn the wonder of nature by flying
kites,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about kite-flying events, or anything
pertaining to kites, call Jewels of the Sky at (972) 423-3630. Or
look at the AKA's Web site, www.aka.kite.org.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The Kite Stuff: What puts the wind beneath their wings? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are many types of kites and materials used to make them.
And kite-making technology continues to grow, with new, lighter
materials and methods being introduced on a regular basis.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is not any one type of kite that is preferred by
professional fliers, there is a new fad going on with buggies _
small, three-wheeled carts on which the operator sits and is pulled
by a large, sturdy, multi-lined kite. This obviously takes a high
wind velocity, 20 miles per hour or more.
</P>
<P>
   Another kite of interest is the Indian fighting kite. A small,
diamond-shaped kite, it is swift and ferocious. This kite
originated on the Indian subcontinent, where the operators lace
their strings with broken glass and try to cut the opponents' kites
out of the sky. In America, this practice is a little less vicious
and has stricter regulations. But the main object _ to make the
other guy's kite crash _ is still the same.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Let's go buy a kite
</P>
<P>
   Currently, there are no specialty kite shops in the Metroplex.
If you want something more than the typical kite found at Wal-Mart
or Kmart, you'll have to order from catalogs, most of which are
available on the Internet. Be prepared to fork over a little more
money than expected.
</P>
<P>
   A few sites include:
</P>
<P>
   Into the Wind: One of the leading companies for research and
kite development, the online store offers windsocks, kites and
other flying toys from all over the world: www.intothewind.com.
</P>
<P>
   BFK: The world's largest online kite store has anything and
everything you'll need to know: www.kitestore.com/kite/index
</P>
<P>
   Air-Fun: Great site with calendars, links, updates on new
products and much more: www.air-fun.com
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
