<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 16:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7858 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOP-GORE-HNS &LR;      03-04 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP CHAIRMAN TAKES AIM AT GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican Party Chairman Jim Nicholson fired an
early salvo Thursday in the 2000 presidential campaign, calling the
Democratic frontrunner, Vice President Al Gore, a ``reckless
environmental extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson cited Gore's support for an international treaty to
control so-called ``greenhouse'' gas emissions, which many
scientists say is a prime cause of gradual global warming.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide efforts to control such emissions will lead to high
energy costs and unemployment in the United States ``while giving
key advantages to nations such as China,'' Nicholson told
reporters. Administration support of emission reductions ``will
surely cause middle-class families to shiver in the winter time.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the treaty negotiated in Kyoto, Japan, in December 1997,
the world's leading industrial nations agreed to cut industrial
emissions from the burning of coal, oil, wood and natural gas.
</P>
<P>
   The pact obligates the United States over the next 10 to 15
years to cut such emissions by about 7 percent from its 1990 level.
Critics of the treaty, many of them representing key U.S.
industries, say it is not as harsh on developing Third-World
countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America, and would give them a
competitive advantage in global markets.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration signed the accord late last year but
won't forward it to the GOP-controlled Senate for ratification
until it wins concessions from other countries that would enable
U.S. industries to hold down the cost of compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the administration's leading spokesman on environmental
issues, praised the treaty last year, saying it ``underscores our
determination to achieve a truly global solution to this global
challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson charged Thursday that Gore likes ``to pose as kind of
a boring but essentially sober policy wonk. He's nothing of the
sort. He's a reckless environmental extremist.''
</P>
<P>
   In attacking Gore, the GOP chairman offered a preview of the
Republican strategy against the presumptive Democratic candidate.
Republican contenders Patrick Buchanan, Steve Forbes and Lamar
Alexander have taken shots at the vice president on a variety of
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, spokesman for Gore, dismissed Nicholson's attack
as the cry of a ``party without ideas, devoid of message and
lacking vision. They focus on past and we look to future.''
</P>
<P>
   Lehane said that six years of Democratic control of the White
House ``have proven you can balance the environment and the
economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholson said Gore also is vulnerable for his defense of
President Clinton throughout the impeachment effort.
</P>
<P>
   Gore ``is probably the only politician in America who has not
criticized President Clinton for being dishonest with the American
people,'' Nicholson said. ``I think that's going to hurt him in the
election in 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Republicans might pay a price for pushing
impeachment when polls showed most Americans wanted Clinton to
remain in office, Nicholson replied, ``Republicans stood up for
principles and not polls and did what they thought was the right
thing to do. This election will be determined by the issues and the
agenda and the vision and the values we communicate to the American
people about their future.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are focusing on lower taxes, saving Social Security,
beefing up the military and greater local control of education
dollars flowing out of Washington, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1646EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
