<SLUG> BC-FILM-FESTIVAL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEATTLE LOOKS AT IRISH FILMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the '90s, Ireland has experienced its biggest boom ever in
domestic film production. Just last week, actor Aidan Quinn called
it an ``explosion'' and the ``prying off of the cement lid of
oppression in Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of the higher-profile films of this ``explosion'' _ such as
John Boorman's ``The General'' and Neil Jordan's ``The Butcher
Boy'' _ have, of course, been internationally financed and
distributed. But most of its smaller-budget, independent films have
never reached these shores.
</P>
<P>
   So an Irish Film Festival seems a particularly good idea at this
time. And Seattle is lucky to have ``Irish Reels: The Second Annual
Irish Film and Video Festival,'' which kicks off Friday night in
the luxurious confines of General Cinema's new Pacific Place
Cinema. It continues through Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The festivities begin at 6 p.m. with a reception, followed by a
15-minute short, ``Freesia of Eden,'' at 6:45 p.m., and the
90-minute opening-night feature, ``2x4,'' directed by and starring
Jimmy Smallhorne, at 7:15 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Described as a ``raw, visceral portrait of the Irish immigrant
experience,'' ``2x4'' follows a crew of Irishmen who work on
construction sites in Manhattan by day and party into the night at
their Bronx pub hangout ``facing conflicts with each other and with
New York itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The festival continues Saturday with a showing of ``Best of the
Northern Ireland Film Commission Shorts, Part 1,'' at 3 p.m.;
``Southpaw,'' a feature documentary about a poor Irish boy who
becomes an Olympic boxer, at 6 p.m.; and ``Ailsa,'' a new film by
Paddy Breathnach, the director of ``I Went Down,'' at 7:45.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the offerings will be a selection of Irish shorts at
3 p.m.; ``Just in Time,'' a 52-minute domestic drama directed by
John Carney and Tom Collins, at 6 p.m.; and ``The Bogwoman,'' an
84-minute tragicomedy about three women living in the Derry Bogside
in the '60s, at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the festival moves to 911 Media Arts Center (117 Yale
Ave. N.) for ``Best of Northern Ireland Film Commission Shorts,
Part 2,'' at 7 p.m.; and ``Irish Cinema: Ourselves Alone,'' a
52-minute documentary about ``the past 100 years of filmmaking in
Ireland,'' at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, also at 911 Media Arts Center, the festival
concludes with ``My Great Grandmother Was a Boxer,'' a 50-minute
video documentary about a woman's look into her family's past, at 7
p.m.; and ``The Three Brothers,'' a 51-minute video documentary
about the making of ``This Is My Father,'' a film by Quinn and his
two brothers that premiered at the last Seattle International Film
Festival. It shows at 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   A closing-night party sponsored by Guinness will follow the
final screening. Ticket prices are $7 ($5 for 911 members) for each
evening screening; $5 ($3) for matinees; $10 ($8) for opening
night; and $40 ($35) for a series pass.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
