</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R&AMP;D-TAX-CREDIT-$ADV06-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY FIRMS LOBBY FOR PERMANENT EXTENSION OF R&AMP;D TAX CREDIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, March 6)   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hi-tech company officials are lobbying hard for a
permanent extension of the research and development tax credit,
hopeful that the budget surplus and talk of tax cuts in Congress
will boost its chances this year.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit, which is usually renewed for one year, provides
up to a 20 percent credit for R&AMP;D investments that are beyond what
corporations have traditionally spent. The tax credit pays
primarily for wages of researchers.
</P>
<P>
   The credit, due to expire June 30, has been renewed temporarily
since 1981. Technology companies say they need the permanent
extension so they can plan long-term projects. Supporters say such
an extension would create and sustain high-skill jobs for American
workers, increase domestic exports and fuel a strong U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Graves, director of tax policy for the American
Electronics Association, which represents 3,000 high-tech firms,
said the extension is the top tax priority this year for the
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need an incentive in the tax code to help our businesses do
the research they need to do,'' Graves said.
</P>
<P>
   Technology companies use the tax credit for research on a wide
range of projects such as a new drug, a faster disk drive or a
system to make the Internet run faster.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Sample, chairman of the R&AMP;D Credit Coalition, which
represents more than 50 trade associations and 1,000 companies
working to make the tax credit permanent, said that ``for many
companies, it provides an additional source of funds to do extra
research they wouldn't otherwise be able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Sample said research projects often last up to 10 years and that
companies need to budget for them years in advance.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 50 technology companies _ including aerospace,
telephone, biotech, software and pharmaceutical firms _ are
boosting their lobbying effort on Capitol Hill, he said. He added
that he is optimistic that the credit may become permanent or at
least extended for a longer period this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think that with the surplus and the general upbeat economic
forecast there is a greater chance that Congress would be willing
to extend it for a longer period,'' said Sample, a senior tax
director at Microsoft Corp. in Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has been reluctant to approve a long-term extension of
the credit largely because it costs the federal government about $2
billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Reps. Jennifer Dunn of Washington and Jerry Weller of
Illinois, both members of the tax-writing Ways and Means Committee,
have drafted a broad five-year $340 billion tax cut bill that
includes a permanent extension of the R&AMP;D tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Reps. Nancy Johnson, R-Conn., and Bob Matsui,
D-Calif., also Ways and Means panel members, introduced a narrower
measure that also would extend the credit permanently.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Orrin G. Hatch, R-Utah, and Max Baucus, D-Mont.,
have drafted a bipartisan counterpart to the Johnson-Matsui bill,
also calling for permanent extension. The Hatch-Baucus bill has at
least 24 co-sponsors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
