<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0233 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-TANGO-SPI &LR;      03-04 0536
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TANGO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TANGO OFFERS GREAT MOMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's always been a terrific chemistry between the tango and
the movies. Even before film could talk, one of its signature
sequences was Rudolph Valentino tangoing his way into immortality
as the hero of 1921's ``The Four Horsemen of the Apocalypse.''
</P>
<P>
   Think of Al Pacino and Gabrielle Anwar in ``Scent of a Woman.''
Think of Jack Lemmon and Joe E. Brown in ``Some Like It Hot.''
Catherine Deneuve and Linh Dan Pham in ``Indochine.'' Is there any
ballroom dance quite so sensuous, so visually seductive?
</P>
<P>
   The new Spanish-Argentine dance movie, ``Tango,'' is crammed
full of great tango moments: in fact, it's the movies' greatest
celebration of tango since Raul Julia's ``Tango Bar'' (a 1988 movie
memorable for its vintage clips of everyone from Fred Astaire to
Fred Flintsone doing the tango).
</P>
<P>
   With its best foreign film Oscar nomination and
behind-the-camera dream-team _ Spain's master director Carlos
Saura, Italy's legendary cinematographer Vittorio Storaro and
Argentine-born Hollywood composer Lalo Schrifin _ it's also likely
to be the tango movie to beat for a good long time.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, the film is a tango version of Bob Fosse's ``All That
Jazz,'' the story of a Buenos Aires director (Miguel Angel Sola) in
the midst of making ``the ultimate film about tango,'' which he
hopes will both evoke the great Argentine tango films of the '40s
and surpass them.
</P>
<P>
   We follow him as he casts and rehearses his dancers, works with
his choreographers and art directors and haggles with his
financiers _ all while struggling with the personal handicap of a
broken leg from a recent auto accident and the emotional
devastation of having just been left by his tango-dancer wife
(Cecilia Narova).
</P>
<P>
   And we get inside his creative process as tries to work out his
complex artistic concepts for the film, and inside his sexual
fantasies as he falls in love with one of his beautiful young
ingenue dancers (Mia Maestro), who just happens to be the live-in
lover of the film's chief financial backer: a particularly violent
gangster.
</P>
<P>
   The director sees everything in terms of tango. It's his way of
looking at the world and his vehicle for expressing love, hate,
passion, melancholy, the agony of the aging process. So everything
that happens to him both internally and externally is an excuse for
the screen to break into stylized fury of dance.
</P>
<P>
   At times, it seems a bit too much of a good thing. In the
show-within-a-show's epic finale, a tango-version of Argentina's
recent sad political past _ complete with government executions and
mass graves _ I found myself sympathizing with the director's
backers who beg him to cut the scene because ``it's too much.''
</P>
<P>
   But this is a small caveat. ``Tango'' has zip, color,
captivating music, striking camera work, mesmerizing dancers. It's
a grand opera of tango: a film that tries to sum up the human
condition in terms of history's sexiest, most passionate dance. It
can't possibly succeed in such an ambitious undertaking, but it's a
movie that's still very hard to resist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1705EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7893 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR &LR;      03-04 0627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-INTERNET-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB SITE FOR FINDING AND SHIPPING WINE IS PLANNED 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM HAMMETT   
 WINETODAY.COM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA ROSA, Calif. _ A San Francisco company with powerful
financial backing and support from the biggest foe of direct wine
shipping plans this year to unveil a multibillion-dollar national
wine-locator system and wine-shipping Internet site.
</P>
<P>
   Naxon Corp. is working in cooperation with the Wine and Spirits
Wholesalers Association and is backed by the investment group that
helped fund AOL, Netscape and Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some winery organizations expressed skepticism that Naxon
could overcome the logistical and regulatory obstacles that
hindered similar projects in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Naxon Corp. officials said the system would allow consumers to
locate and purchase wines online and have the wines delivered
legally to their homes or a local retailer. No name has been set
for the Internet site, nor a date when it will go live, company
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the system, wine orders would be filled using an
established network of wholesalers and retailers through Virtual
Distribution Inc., a Naxon-owned company that is already licensed
in 37 states.
</P>
<P>
   Naxon got support for the service from one of the strongest
opponents of direct wine sales _ the national wholesalers
association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our primary role in partnering with Naxon is to provide the
inventory database of brands available from wholesalers,'' said
David Dickerson, vice president of public affairs for WSWA, the
national wholesalers' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Dickerson said that Naxon approached WSWA for its support at a
time when WSWA was trying to come up with its own locator service
for consumers. ``They recognized first off that there has to be a
commitment to provide legal fulfillment to shipping wines, to make
sure that only adults can buy the wine, and that they have to
fulfill tax obligations with the states,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   WSWA has long opposed direct sales of wine via the Internet or
toll-free telephone numbers, squaring off against some wineries and
winery organizations that want to change laws in states to permit
direct sales. Currently a handful of states allow some form of
direct sales, but in the last two years Georgia, Florida and
Kentucky have made direct shipment of wine a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Some winery organizations are taking a cautious stance toward
the new venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We applaud efforts to improve wine access for adult wine
lovers,'' said Jeremy Benson, executive director of Free the
Grapes!, a coalition of wineries, retailers and consumers that
wants to ensure consumer access to fine wine. Benson said his
organization was concerned that ``the same hurdles that currently
block consumer access to direct shipping in many states, and the
harsh restrictions wineries encounter in conducting interstate
trade, may hinder the development of Naxon's concept.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems, Benson pointed out, was that most states
require brand and label registration before a wine can be sold.
Those costs _ up to $500 per label _ and the time involved _ up to
90 days _ may be impractical for one-time shipments, he said.
Benson also noted hurdles involving varying franchise laws and laws
in states where the government is both wholesaler and retailer.
</P>
<P>
   A backer of the project is the venture capital firm Kleiner
Perkins Caufield &AMP; Byers, which financed companies like AOL,
Compaq, Netscape, drugstore.com and realtor.com.
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Hammett writes for Winetoday.com, a daily Internet wine
publication published by the New York Times Co. and The Press
Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif. The Web address is
http://www.winetoday.com. This story was distributed by The N.Y.
Times News Service.))
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
