<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-ROCK-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOUTHERN ROCK VETERANS BAND TOGETHER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ala., Fla.)   By TERRY PACE   
 NYT Regional Newspapers   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MUSCLE SHOALS, Ala. _ Two decades after the musical explosion
known as Southern rock, four prime movers and shakers of that
free-spirited, '70s-centered cultural phenomenon are back on the
road and back in the studio.
</P>
<P>
   Billed the Southern Rock All-Stars, the band's lineup features
representatives of such hard-driving Southern-rock acts as
Blackfoot, Molly Hatchet and the Rossington Band. Twenty-five years
ago, those bands along with such kindred spirits as Lynyrd Skynyrd
and the Allman Brothers brewed their own rambunctious,
guitar-seasoned brand of blues, boogie and heavy metal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those days were great, but this time it's for us,'' said
All-Stars vocalist, lead and slide guitarist Dave Hlubek, one of
the founding members of Molly Hatchet. ``Back then, I wasn't
prepared for the success at all _ I had no idea what kind of a
rocket ride it would be. This time we're doing it for fun, and it's
never felt better.''
</P>
<P>
   The other members of the All-Stars are Jakson Spires, Blackfoot
founder on drums and vocals; Jay Johnson, a veteran of Rossington
Band on lead guitar and vocals, and Pete Geddes, an alumnus of the
Lester Chambers Group and Buster Cherry Band on bass and vocals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we're doing this because we got tired of buying
everybody else yachts and speedboats every year,'' said Spires.
``We didn't know just how well we were doing in those days until we
saw how our managers lived. We've decided that we want one now.''
</P>
<P>
   The All-Stars'new album, ``Crazy Again,'' was co-produced by
Johnson with Spires at his home studio in Muscle Shoals.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the leading Southern-rock bands originated in
Jacksonville, Fla., bands like Blackfoot and Skynyrd recorded some
of their earliest and most memorable tracks in Muscle Shoals.
</P>
<P>
   ``
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we needed to be here if we wanted to rekindle some of
that old magic,'' Geddes said.
</P>
<P>
   In between trips to Muscle Shoals for work on ``Crazy Again,''
the All-Stars have performed 60 gigs over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a whole new crowd out there,'' Hlubek said. ``It's a
hodgepodge of people of all ages and from all kinds of backgrounds.
We've got people saying things like, `You've got to come out and
see this guy Jakson Spires _ he was the greatest when I was growing
up.' Then those people are bringing in their kids. It's great to
see the music carried on like that.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cuts from ``Crazy Again,'' the All-Stars'
colorful concert repertoire includes such Southern-rock anthems as
Blackfoot's ``Wishing Well,'' Molly Hatchet's ``Flirtin' with
Disaster'' (written by Hlubek), Marshall Tucker's ``Can't You
See?'' and Skynyrd's ``Sweet Home Alabama.''
</P>
<P>
   The band even delves into the deep blues of ``Stormy Monday''
and roars through Rolling Stones territory with ``Jumpin' Jack
Flash.''
</P>
<P>
   The band began in the early '90s as the Dixie All-Stars
``Everybody thought we were a basketball team or some barbershop
band or something,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   The group then endured a number of personnel changes, losing
members to ``everything from road burnout to suicide,'' before the
arrival of Geddes. ``He was the spoke that was missing,'' Hlubek
said, ``and now the wheel's turning.''
</P>
<P>
   The group works without lawyers, managers or agents, setting
their own standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've done the record this way, too,'' Spires said. ``Pete
plays his part his way. Dave plays his guitar the way he plays it.
Jay and I may be called the producers, but we're saying to these
guys, `Come in here and play like you play not like I want to hear
you play.' ''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, fellow band members Hlubek and Geddes feel
secure being produced by trusted colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Your fellow performer can get the best performance out of
you,'' Hlubek said. ``There's not some straw boss around telling us
what to do. Why do we want some guy coming in here producing our
record who can't play an E chord? In the end, whatever it is, it is
and we had a good time doing it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Terry Pace writes for the TimesDaily in Florence, Ala.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
