<HEADLINE>
EFFECTIVE MUCKRAKING ON TIBET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   After the financial flop of both ``Kundun'' and ``Seven Years in
Tibet'' in late 1997, one Hollywood trade paper predicted it
``would be a long time before an American filmmaker made a
contemporary movie about Tibet again.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, barely a year later, here is ``Windhorse,'' another (albeit
smaller budget) U.S. film that sets its story against the brutal
Chinese subjugation of Tibet. It's an effective piece of muckraking
too, and perhaps somewhat more authentic, since part of it was
actually filmed in Tibet on the sly.
</P>
<P>
   The film opens in a village in the country's remote western
mountains in 1979, as a game played by three children _ Dorjee, his
sister Dolkar and their girl cousin Pema _ is interrupted by the
sound of a gun shot: their grandfather has just been casually
executed by a Chinese government death squad.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to 18 years later, and the three have moved to Lhasa, grown
up and developed quite different lifestyles: Dorjee is an aimless
slacker, Dolkar is the city's hottest cabaret singer and Pema is a
Buddhist nun and dedicated follower of the exiled Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the film deals with the way their scattered lives
come together again when Dolkar is given a lucrative television and
recording contract but is expected to sing songs praising Chairman
Mao and Pema is arrested after a spontaneous anti-Chinese
demonstration in the marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   Directed, produced and co-written by Paul Wagner (who won an
Oscar for his documentary short, ``the Stone Carvers'') and shot
mostly in Nepal with a cast of Tibetan refugees, the film has
little of the epic sweep of its more expensive predecessors in the
Tibet-under-heel genre.
</P>
<P>
   And, like them, it's pretty much of a propaganda piece. We get
no hint, for instance, of China's motivation for being so nasty:
its long-standing fear of Tibet, which has historically been much
more militant than its ``Lost Horizon'' image might indicate, and
once even conquered and ruled China.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Windhorse'' is an effective piece of propaganda. Wagner
gets believable and heart-felt ensemble performances from his cast
of unknowns, his camera paints a devastating portrait of a
spiritually starved nation on its knees, and he has no trouble
convincing us that the Chinese occupation is barbaric and
intolerable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
