<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISPERSING TREASURES FOR A GOOD CAUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By WENDY MOONAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Giuseppe Rossi of Turin, Italy, was famous for his
connoisseurship, but he will be remembered for his generosity.
</P>
<P>
   Next week Sotheby's in London is selling Rossi's collection,
approximately 1,400 spectacular lots of 18th-century furniture,
Meissen porcelain, Italian silver and Chinese ceramics, with the
proceeds of the sale promised to a school of conservation and
restoration of the decorative arts, the Scuola per Artigiani
Restauratori d'Arte, in Turin.
</P>
<P>
   The collection, amassed between 1945 and 1979, is expected to
bring about $15 million, said Mario Tavella, Sotheby's furniture
specialist in London.
</P>
<P>
   Rossi was born in 1914 into a family of craftsmen; his father
and maternal grandfather were cabinetmakers in Turin, the capital
of the Piedmont region, in northwestern Italy.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy, he was serious about his studies, but when the
Depression hit in 1929 he had to join the family's shop.
Eventually, he got back to his studies and graduated in 1937.
</P>
<P>
   He worked in the paper business until the war, when he was
drafted into the army. In 1944, he opened the Rossi Art Gallery,
selling antiques and decorative paintings, and quietly became a
connoisseur and very successful businessman. He traveled all over
the world to buy pieces for his gallery and private collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't a glamorous person,'' Tavella said, ``but he was
well known internationally.''
</P>
<P>
   The sale of the estate of Rossi, who died 10 years ago, runs
from March 10 through March 12 and includes more than 700 pieces of
French and Italian furniture. In collecting Italian antiques for
himself, Rossi concentrated on examples from the Piedmont, Venice
and Genoa, particularly ones with lacquer, veneer and inlays of
ivory or precious woods like tulipwood, rosewood and ebony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Piedmontese furniture has always been very desirable because
it's quite rare,'' Tavella said. ``A lot of Italian furniture is
regarded as provincial but not Piedmontese. It is seen as
international in taste and appeal.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most interesting Piedmontese pieces in the sale is a
bureau Mazarin, a writing desk, circa 1725. It is made of ebony and
rosewood. It has eight square tapering legs, three drawers on each
side and a cupboard and drawer above the kneehole space. It is
intricately inlaid with ivory scenes depicting foliage and human
figures.
</P>
<P>
   The piece is attributed to Luigi Prinotto, an accomplished Turin
cabinetmaker known for ivory inlays. There is a similar piece by
him in the Royal Palace's museum in Turin.
</P>
<P>
   In the desk at Sotheby's, the inlays depict hunting scenes and
banquets. Various cartouches show hounds roaring to get started on
the hunt. In one, they jump on their master in excitement; in
another, they circle a huntsman signaling with his horn. The
banquet scenes are alfresco: huge tables laden with foods that have
been laid out for the guests under a shade tree.
</P>
<P>
   The estimate is $193,000 to $290,000. ``It's very rich in taste
and very grand, almost flashy,'' Tavella said, ``but this is the
region the royal family came from.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deco Ironwork
</P>
<P>
   Imagine the mother of all decorative arts fairs. Italy, Russia,
Poland, the Netherlands, Austria, Britain, Spain, Czechoslovakia,
Japan, Denmark, Sweden and France _ in fact, every important
country except the United States _ participate. Set virtually in
the shadow of the Eiffel Tower, the fair lasts six months and
attracts 16 million visitors.
</P>
<P>
   This was the famous 1925 Paris ``Exposition Internationale des
Arts Decoratifs et Industriels Modernes,'' which gave Art Deco its
name. The fair included fashion (think Paul Poiret); furniture
(Jean-Michel Frank); silver (Jean Puiforcat); decoration (Sue and
Mare, Jacques-Emile Ruhlmann); even architecture (Le Corbusier).
</P>
<P>
   It's taken more than 70 years, but now Americans are beginning
to appreciate the incomparable designers who emerged in France in
the early 1920s and changed the direction of design history.
Several of them are represented in auctions of 20th-century
decorative works of art next week.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Sotheby's sale on March 12 includes pieces by Edgar
Brandt, a relatively underappreciated craftsman whose artistry and
close interactions with his contemporaries are explored by the
historian Joan Kahr in ``Edgar Brandt: Master of Art Deco
Ironwork,'' to be published by Abrams next month.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt (1880-1960) was a metalwork artist and entrepreneur who
started out making iron costume jewelry in 1900. He moved on to
larger-scale pieces like fireplace equipment and door knockers.
</P>
<P>
   Before long, he was making elaborate stairway railings festooned
with pine cone and needle motifs for private houses in Paris. He
was soon recognized as a master craftsman, with plenty of private
and commercial commissions for doors, gates, screens and monuments.
</P>
<P>
   He was 34 when he was drafted in World War I. Seeing the
conditions in the trenches, he suggested that the infantry needed a
maneuverable lightweight mortar. The French Army told him to make
one, and he spent two years developing it.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he returned to his ironwork atelier, where he
designed and manufactured fire screens, furniture, light fixtures
and doors for houses, banks and French government buildings. He was
commissioned to create glass domes and iron banisters for the ocean
liner Paris and the elaborate balconies and grand staircase for the
department store Au Bon Marche.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's is selling a pair of gilded Brandt gates, circa 1925.
Here the ironwork motif looks more like fiddlehead ferns. The
estimate is $60,000 to $90,000.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's also has a Brandt marble dining table, circa 1925,
with wrought-iron legs that curl up like ribbon candy. Here the
motifs are grapes and vine leaves. The estimate is $40,000 to
$60,000. A matching marble console with a mirror carries the
estimate of $30,000 to $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Brandt collaborated with talented peers, like the glassmakers
Rene Lalique and Antonin Daum. His work remained in demand until
the 1930s, when he began spending most of his time developing
armaments for the French government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to two sets of gates by Brandt, the Sotheby's sale
has an Armand Albert Rateau pedestal; two Gilbert Poillerat
wrought-iron doors, and an Albert Cheuret bronze and alabaster
chandelier.
</P>
<P>
   The Christie's sale of 20th-century decorative arts on March 18
includes a Brandt console; two fire screens and some lamps, as well
as a console designed by Cheuret; a set of Puiforcat silverware, a
Rene Prou console and a black lacquer screen, circa 1922, by Eileen
Gray.
</P>
<P>
   It's time to rediscover the second iron age, circa 1925.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
