<HEADER>
A7934 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-CRUEL-SPI &LR;      03-04 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-CRUEL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PREP-SCHOOL SEX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   What's happening at high school? Movies are depicting high
school kids as terminally abusive, mean-minded, irresponsible
creeps.
</P>
<P>
   In ``She's All That,'' an unpopular art student is first
humiliated and then transformed into a swan by the most popular
boy; in ``Jawbreakers,'' a group of girls are status-seeking sexual
teases and killers; and in ``The Craft,'' witchcraft is the tool
used for revenge.
</P>
<P>
   So it comes as no surprise that someone would come up with the
idea to turn the 1782 novel ``Les Liaisons Dangereuses,'' which has
already been filmed three times, into prep-school scandal and
sexual intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, writer and director Roger Kumble adapts his
teenage tantalizer more from Stephen Frears' successful film
``Dangerous Liaisons'' than from Laclos' classic book. As a result,
he doesn't bring much new to the party and his movie must rely on
eye candy of lavish, tony Manhattan locales rather than substance.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, it's impossible to care about any of these
characters. Wealthy Kathryn (Sarah Michelle Gellar) and her idle,
cruel stepbrother, Sebastian (Ryan Phillippe), make sport of
manipulating, seducing and abandoning conquests. The pair are bored
and spoiled.
</P>
<P>
   After Kathryn gets dumped by beau Court Reynolds for the
unformed, innocent Cecile Caldwell (Selma Blair), Kathryn plots
revenge: She coerces Sebastian to seduce Cecile and take away the
one thing Court cares about _ Cecile's chastity. She promises him
that which he most desires if he succeeds: to sleep with her.
</P>
<P>
   But a virginal newcomer catches Sebastian's eye. Annette
Hargrove (Reese Witherspoon) has just arrived at the school. She's
a pillar of virtue. And she sees through all of Sebastian's plays
and poses. The young man finds his cynicism crumbling and soon, the
pawn holds the power and Sebastian finds he's in love for the first
time _ much to Kathryn's fury.
</P>
<P>
   The idea to use three budding stars _ Witherspoon, Phillippe and
Gellar (from TV's ``Buffy, the Vampire Slayer'') _ might have
looked good on paper, but none has an ounce of conviction or
gravity onscreen.
</P>
<P>
   The only one who brings a whit of freshness to her role is
Blair, whose Cecile is a bumbling harebrain. The other paper-thin,
wooden performances feel like something from the high school annual
play rather than a big-budget movie.
</P>
<P>
   Though the film continually tries to be racy and attempts to
crack some taboos _ Kathryn teaches Cecile to kiss, the hint of
incest looms large, and there's even a racial subplot _ nothing
feels even tinged with threat, menace or conviction. The movie is
as boring as the characters, and by the time Sebastian performs a
final, redemptive act, the preview audience was laughing out loud
at the silliness of the whole mess.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1720EST &QL; 
