<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0241 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7941 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-INNOCENCE-SPI &LR;      03-04 0314
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-INNOCENCE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYFUL, MOVING STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Iranian director Mohsen Makhmalbaf has argued ``the European
cinema offers sex and violence, the Indian cinema sells dreams and
the Iranian cinema tries to sell poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Makhmalbaf ingeniously meshes pure cinematic visual imagery with
delicate, poetic stories. His 1996 film ``A Moment of Innocence''
is certainly no exception. But it's more personal and less
objective that his 1995 success, ``Gabbeh.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to recapture my youth with a camera,'' says the
director and, indeed, the film chronicles a chance meeting between
an ex-policeman, who was stabbed some 20 years earlier in a
political act against the Shah's regime by Makhmalbaf, then a
17-year-old militant.
</P>
<P>
   The cop now wants to become an actor and asks the
internationally known director to put him in a film. Makhmalbaf
suggests they cinematically reconstruct this dramatic event instead
and the pair set out to cast the film with replicas of themselves
as young men, and to find the girl who was an instrumental witness
to the stabbing, and who became an icon of lost love for the now
40-year-old policeman.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Moment of Innocence'' slowly fits together like the pieces
of a puzzle, telling a playful, moving story of love and youthful
idealism. It weaves its characters _ old and young _ together in an
innovative way and proves that history doesn't necessarily need to
repeat itself to heal old wounds. In fact, the biggest hope in
excising old scars may be to change the course of history entirely.
In this case, through the medium of film.
</P>
<P>
   Though Makhmalbaf's movie is small in scope and often feels
improvised and rough, its ability to gaze back in time through more
mature eyes gives it an emotional and poignant resonance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1725EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0242 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-NIGHT-COURT-2TAKES     03-04 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NIGHT-COURT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIGHT COURT JOINS THE THEATER THAT IS NEW YORK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   JANNY SCOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The hour was closing in on midnight. A detachment of
ruddy-faced German tourists emerged from the metal detectors in the
Criminal Courts building in lower Manhattan, took a sharp left and
headed down the empty marble corridor toward the city's least
likely international attraction, night court.
</P>
<P>
   Tentatively, they filed into Room 130. They entered like
spelunkers, wide-eyed and hushed amid the cavernous courtroom's
disconcerting fluorescence. Wrestling off ski jackets, they settled
into several rows of dark wooden benches, looking eager, alert and
utterly out of place.
</P>
<P>
   The court stenographer squinted at them, then shrugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like they came off a tour bus or something,'' she
muttered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm telling you, this is in the tour books,'' said Judge Ruth
Pickholz, who was presiding that night. ``They should have been
here the night of the escape.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan makes its name on superlatives, so maybe it should
come as no surprise that in the only borough with 24-hour-a-day,
seven-day-a-week arraignments. The 5:30 p.m. to 1 a.m. shift at
arraignment court at 100 Centre Street near Chinatown is both a
tourist attraction and an occasional cheap date.
</P>
<P>
   This is, after all, post-O.J. Simpson America. Who is not
interested in sidebar conferences and orders to show cause? With
criminal lawyers serving as hosts of television talk shows and
Judge Judy becoming a celebrity, courtrooms are becoming a
daytime-television cliche. Night court, meanwhile, is the real
thing.
</P>
<P>
   Like much in Manhattan, night court is real-life theater. It is
the criminal-justice equivalent of a ringside seat at
emergency-room admissions. It is mostly pantomime, robbed of its
dialogue by bad acoustics, but it offers the curious visitor a hard
look at a sad slice of New York life.
</P>
<P>
   Hour after hour, the door to the holding pens behind the
courtroom bangs open and shut. Men and women with smudged faces and
sleep-flattened hair slouch before the judge. Charges are barked
out: heroin possession, fare-beating, possession of stolen
property. Lawyers argue in shorthand; the judge sets bail.
</P>
<P>
   Once in a while, something startling breaks the rhythm. Denied
bail, a defendant dares the court officers to force him to return
to the pens. Or as had happened in Judge Pickholz's courtroom
earlier that week, a man leaps the rail and tries to bolt, only to
be caught in the corridor and charged with escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I consider arraignments the E.R. of the court system,'' said
Judge Pickholz, a former lawyer with the New York Legal Aid Society
and former corruption prosecutor for the city. ``We triage. Some
cases need a Band-Aid. Some of them need major surgery.''
</P>
<P>
   Every day, hundreds of people are arrested in Manhattan. Under
state law, the city has 24 hours to get them arraigned before a
judge, who will hear arguments from a prosecutor and usually a
court-appointed defense lawyer on, among other things, how high to
set bail.
</P>
<P>
   Time was, people used to languish in jail for days, unarraigned.
Then in 1990, the Legal Aid Society went to the state Supreme Court
and argued that the city was violating a law requiring arraignment
``without delay.'' In April of that year, a judge agreed and set
the limit at 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the arrest-to-arraignment time is usually less than
that. But a visitor to night court may be struck by the tension
between the pressure to deal quickly with the flow of ``bodies,''
in law-enforcement parlance, and the countervailing impulse to
treat the ``bodies'' as something more.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone finds the balance satisfactory.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system believes in processing our clients, kind of like
cans of tuna fish,'' said Stephen P. Pokart, a Legal Aid lawyer who
has worked in night court often since 1980. ``They don't recognize
them as humans. They are species as paperwork, species as
statistic, the species defendant.''
</P>
<P>
   Standing on the western rim of Chinatown, the vast Criminal
Courts building is an awesome place. ``Where law ends there tyranny
begins,'' reads the inscription on one wall. Homeless men can be
seen bedding down along the sidewalk, while litter swirls in windy
eddies near the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   Room 130 is the bigger of the two arraignment courtrooms, a room
so archetypal that Barbra Streisand replicated it for her 1987
movie ``Nuts.'' The cracks in the benches appear in places to have
been spackled with now petrified chewing gum; even tourists look
pallid under the 11 overhead lights.
</P>
<P>
   A low rail divides the room _ public on one end, lawyers and
accused on the other. There is an interview booth for lawyers and
clients, reminiscent of a confessional. Up near the ceiling, there
are eight tall, rectangular windows, their Venetian blinds in
varying degrees of disarray.
</P>
<P>
   Judge John Walsh, a former police inspector who oversees
arraignments throughout the city, recalls watching from the bench
some years ago as a pigeon flew into the courtroom through an open
window, circled the room as if according to long habit, then came
blithely to rest in an indoor nest.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see what's on that screen?'' he asked a visitor one
afternoon, pointing out a mysterious constellation of small white
globs on an out-of-use video monitor that had come to rest on top
of the interview booth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spitballs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The cast of characters at night court is shifting yet somehow
constant. Criminal- and civil-court judges are assigned in rotating
five-night shifts. The lawyers cycle in and out, too. Only the
court officers are regulars, a tight-knit group with a shared
social life outside of court.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for the accused, they have a certain superficial sameness. If
they look as if they slept in their clothes, they did. They appear
weary and bedraggled; some are sick. Told to keep their coats with
them, many stand before the judge in down jackets, as though
expecting snow.
</P>
<P>
   Some stare at their feet, hands behind their backs. Some list to
one side, looking warily at the judge. Some chortle in disbelief at
the prosecutor's account. Some are mentally ill; many are indigent.
Some are in withdrawal; a few are diabetics in danger of insulin
shock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great deal of trouble getting credibility with our
clients, for all sorts of socio-economic and other reasons,'' said
Pokart, 58, who joined the Legal Aid Society, a nonprofit agency
that provides representation for indigent defendants, after
graduating from Harvard Law School, then getting a degree in
theater directing and running soldier shows in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clients often ask us, `Are you a paid lawyer?''' he said.
``You can make a joke and say, `No, I do this for the fun of it.'
So they smile, maybe. But they think of us as not paid lawyers
because they're not paying us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So, we're not `paid lawyers,''' he continued. ``Generally
we're white and they're not. We're well dressed and they're not.
We're educated and they're not. We're out of jail and they're in
there.''
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, he said, many of them have been badly represented
by incompetent lawyers before. He added, ``So there is a great deal
of mistrust.''
</P>
<P>
   Each arraignment tends to follow a pattern. A defendant is
brought into the courtroom through the door leading to the holding
cells and is deposited on one of several wooden benches. There he
is left to wait with maybe a dozen other men and women, their backs
to the public, until a court officer calls his case.
</P>
<P>
   Cases are announced in a loud, barely intelligible rush of
terminology. The defendant takes his place next to his lawyer, whom
he met minutes earlier in an interview booth adjoining the pens.
The prosecutor asks that bail be at a certain level; the defense
wants it lower.
</P>
<P>
   If the defendant's mother is in the courtroom, she is pointed
out _ an indication that the accused might be counted on to come
back to court. The defense lawyer might talk about the client's
job, if he has one, or his medical condition, if he has one, and
how he will suffer if held in jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our job is to help them as lawyers,'' said Pokart, who once
tossed a client's glass eye to a judge while making the case that
the client could not keep it clean in jail. ``If they're locked up
at arraignment, helping them as a lawyer means to get them out of
jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the judge's turn.
</P>
<P>
   He or she skims a sheaf of papers: a one-page complaint; the
defendant's rap sheet; a brief report on where he lives, how long
he has lived there, whether he works, where he works, and a bail
recommendation from the private agency that the city uses to
prepare such reports and recommend bail.
</P>
<P>
   The judge then has a minute or two to set bail. Maybe three.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not decisive, they had better become decisive very
quickly,'' said Walsh, who retired as a police officer, was sworn
in as a judge and hit night court all in the same week. ``You have
to make decisions and there's no second call, no let-me-think or
what-do-you-think? You're the one.''
</P>
<P>
   What is more, the decisions are hard and the judge has little
information to go on. ``I've never had something bad happen,''
Judge Pickholz said. ``That's every judge's nightmare. That's the
one thing you don't want to be responsible for _ having somebody
get hurt because of something you've done.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The pressure lifts briefly when the court breaks for dinner
around 9 p.m. It is a segregated ritual: Judges gravitate to
Forlini's, a nearby Italian restaurant, defense lawyers to
Chinatown, court officers to their desks. When they return, many
are fighting exhaustion.
</P>
<P>
   Other tasks punctuate the night. Some defendants, charged with
misdemeanors, plead guilty and must be sentenced. Sometimes orders
of protection and search warrants need to be signed. Often, there
are defendants with drug problems that jail will not help and who
have no other place to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get yourself some help,'' Judge Pickholz told a
woman, who was 41 but looked 60, limping toward the bench to be
arraigned on yet another misdemeanor drug charge. ``Do you know
that? Because you're going to end up in jail or dead on the
street.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman nodded blankly. A tourist dozing in the second row
snapped awake. It was well past midnight. The defense lawyer and
the prosecutor huddled with the judge. ``She's a lost soul,'' the
judge said quietly. ``If you want to help get her into a program,
I'm not going to keep her in jail.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the woman had a record, the prosecutor agreed to reduce
the charge from a misdemeanor to a lesser category called a
violation. That way, the woman could plead guilty and not be
charged with violating her probation. Maybe she would even get
help.
</P>
<P>
   The judge thanked him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a place for DA's like you,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   He answered, ``I hope they send me there soon.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
