<P>
   TURNER-CABLE _ NEW YORK _ Time Warner Vice Chairman Ted Turner
addresses the opening of a major cable TV industry convention in
New York, sponsored by the Cable Advertising Bureau. (Haddad,
Atlanta Jurnal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   COKE-PROXY _ ATANTA _ Coca-Cola Co. releases its proxy statement
late this afternoon, and it will show the 1997 compensation for its
top executives. (Unger, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NCR-PROXY _ NCR Corp's final proxy was mailed to investors this
week, and it will reveal CEO Lars Nyberg's bonus for the year. It
probably will top $500,000. (Bischoff, Dayton Daily News). 8.
</P>
<P>
   DELL-IBM _ Dell Computer Corp. and IBM announced a $16 billion,
multi-year agreement Thursday that would allow Dell to use IBM's
advanced technology in Dell's high-end products for large customers
and, potentially, to IBM's next generation of microprocessors.
While it's an endorsement of IBM's technical prowess, analysts
suggested that this deal may foreshadow an agreement in which Dell
takes over the manufacturing of IBM's PCs, a business that has been
</P>
<P>
   a drag on IBM's earnings in recent years. (Mahoney, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   AOL-VIRGINIA _ Following up on a Washington Post story that
explains how Virginia won the $550 million AOL data center that,
for a time, Georgia officials were certain would locate in Cobb
County. The Virginia Assembly passed a bill written specifically to
benefit AOL, saving it $18 million in taxes. (Thurston, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   MENS-WAREHOUSE _ Men's Wearhouse acquires K&AMP;G Men's Center and
combines it with its SuitMax stores. K&AMP;G operates 33 men's apparel
superstores in 16 states. Men's Warehouse will merge its 20 SuitMax
stores into K&AMP;G's operations. (Bond, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   RTP-GOODNIGHT _ CARY, N.C. _ Jim Goodnight, SAS Institute Inc.'s
president, is rich but not flashy. His fortune is estimated at $3
billion, ranking him as the wealthiest North Carolinian. But he
drives a 1996 Buick Roadmaster, spacious enough for his lanky 6'5''
frame. Intensely private and publicity-shy to the point of seeming
disinterested, even bored, Goodnight, 56, recently lifted the veil
surrounding himself and the nation's largest privately held
software manufacturer, based in Cary, N.C. (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   w/RTP-SAS _ CARY, N.C. _ The fitness staff at SAS Institute
Inc., the big software maker, was torn over hardware. Should they
