<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0251 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7957 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-SCHOOLS05-co     03-04 0719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-SCHOOLS05-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    BILL WOULD PROTECT CHILDREN AGAINT INTERNET PORNOGRAPHY
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington category
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The virtual version of Solace House, a therapeutic
center in Leawood, Kan., that serves grieving children and their
families after loved ones have been lost, appeared on the Internet
one day in December. Within hours, its creators found to their
dismay that would-be visitors could all too easily be mistakenly
linked to several hardcore pornographic sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no black screen, no warning, no way to exit,
nothing,'' Janie Harris, executive director of Solace House, told
the Senate Commerce Committee Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Harris said she'd like to see enacted what she called a federal
''seat belt law'' to protect children against pornography. ''If it
were up to each community, we wouldn't have any seat belt law,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation under construction by the panel's chairman, Sen.
John McCain, R-Ariz., would provide what Harris wants. It would
impact some 26,000 U.S. schools and libraries that so far have been
awarded $1.7 billion in subsidies to hook up to the Internet. Under
his bill, to qualify for future funding, they would be required to
deploy blocking or filtering software on computers being used by
children.
</P>
<P>
   Said McCain: ``Parents have the right to feel safe that, when
they send their child to school, when they drop their child off at
the public library, someone is going to be looking out for their
children, protecting them. That's what this bill is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris, trembling visibly in the witness chair, told the panel
that pornographic images appeared if Internet users looking for the
Solace House site typed in ``www.solace.com'' instead of the
correct address: ``www.solacehouse.org.''
</P>
<P>
   Harris promptly launched a fight to shut down the offending
site, which was hosted in Canada. Within three weeks, the owner had
yanked the pornography and replaced it with an ``under
construction'' message.
</P>
<P>
   Although the courts have upheld child pornography laws, McCain's
bill has run into furious opposition from civil liberties groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``Federal filtering mandates would increase legal problems,
impose unjustified federal requirements on schools and libraries
and interfere with local efforts to deal more effectively with
Internet access issues,'' Elliot Mincberg, (cq), general counsel of
People for the American Way,'' told McCain.
</P>
<P>
   While sharing McCain's concerns that ``children's experience on
the Internet be safe, educational and rewarding,'' Candace Morgan,
a librarian from Fort Vancouver, Wash., said people in her
community oppose his filtering initiative.
</P>
<P>
   ``They support the approach of individual choice of
technological tools with parents making choices for their
children,'' she said. ``They do not want the library, or any other
governmental agency, to force one choice on all library users.''
</P>
<P>
   A shaken Harris thereupon turned to Morgan, who sat beside her
at the witness table, and said: ``A lot of kids don't have a parent
to guide them. That's our nightmare.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, McCain accused Morgan of not having read his bill,
a charge which she denied.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you decide not to use the (installed filtering) system,
then don't use it,'' he told her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under this legislation, you must install the technology but
you don't have to turn it on,'' Sen. John Rockefeller, D-W.Va.,
noted. That option could assist McCain's approach in the courts, if
his bill is enacted into law. A prior bid to censor Internet
content, while signed into law by President Clinton, was deemed
unconstitutional by the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   (optional trim follows)
</P>
<P>
   McCain told Morgan that when committee staffers had run the
librarian's name through several Internet search engines, they had
found two pornographic sites linked to ``Candace Morgan'' and five
sites to ``Candice Morgan.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was not happy to hear that.
</P>
<P>
   Said McCain, who will seek the Republican presidential
nomination next year: ``If (schools and libraries) don't want this
responsibility, the answer is simple: don't take the subsidy.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
