<HEADLINE>
MITSUBISHI BOOSTS BOTTOM LINE WITH SALE OF PLANT TO CANON  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The Mitsubishi Motors Corp. became the latest big
Japanese company to shrink its excess factory capacity Thursday,
announcing a deal to sell a plant that makes truck transmissions.
</P>
<P>
   The auto manufacturer said it would sell its Maruko plant in
Tokyo to Canon Inc. and the Mitsubishi Corporation by March 25 and
transfer the roughly 500 employees working there and their
equipment to its Kawasaki plant.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors said the sale would give it an extraordinary
profit of 25 billion yen, or about $205 million at current exchange
rates, which will help strengthen the company's weak bottom line in
the fiscal year that ends March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The company now projects that it will report a 1 billion yen, or
$8.2 million, loss on a consolidated basis in this fiscal year,
compared with a previous forecast of a 26 billion yen loss.
</P>
<P>
   Japan is home to 11 vehicle manufacturers, which are slugging it
out not only in a domestic industry that can produce between three
million and four million more cars than it can sell but also in an
industry suffering from a global overcapacity.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Nissan Diesel, the struggling truck-making affiliate
of the Nissan Motor Co., announced that it would close a production
line, and the Toyota Motor Corp. is pushing its affiliate, Kanto
Auto Works, to cut capacity by 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Mitsubishi Motors, burdened with $2 trillion yen in debt, is
Japan's fifth-largest auto maker.
</P>
<P>
   Katsuhiko Kawasoe, the president of Mitsubishi Motors, has said
repeatedly that he has been shopping bits and pieces of the company
around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1745EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
