<HEADER>
A7971 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ART-NOTES-NYT &LR;      03-04 0981
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL SQUABBLE OVER REAL ESTATE  
 SARA LEE'S ART COLLECTION  
 CONDENSED FUND  
 CHRISTIE'S BY A NOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CAROL VOGEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Although he is 91, retirement is not in the cards for
Leo Castelli. On April 17 Castelli, the art dealer, is to open a
new space at 59 East 79th Street, Manhattan, just two blocks from 4
East 77th Street, where he began in 1957. The inaugural exhibition
will be devoted to monotypes by Jasper Johns, one of Castelli's
longtime artists.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot is happening on the Upper East Side again,'' said
Barbara Castelli, Castelli's wife, who works with him. ``There are
a lot of other galleries in the neighborhood and hotels where
collectors from all over the world come to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   But where does this leave 420 West Broadway, the SoHo building
where the Castelli gallery has been since the 70s? The five-story
1890s building, just north of Spring Street, has played a major
role in contemporary art for 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Castelli has been fighting for two years with the building's
other owners: the art dealers Ileana Sonnabend and Charles Cowles,
the real estate investor Fritz deKnegt and the heirs of Wouter F.
Germans, who died in April and was deKnegt's partner.
</P>
<P>
   DeKnegt and Germans maintained that their 40 percent share of
the cooperative entitled them to lease the first and fourth floors.
They had tried to lease the ground floor to Esprit de Corps, the
San Francisco clothing company. But the three dealers, each of whom
occupies one of the three remaining floors, sued, contending that
the cooperative as a whole had a right to decide on the tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Now Esprit is suing deKnegt and the Germans estate, claiming
they misrepresented their authority to rent out the ground floor.
</P>
<P>
   The dealers have said that they would be willing to sell the
building, but that they did not want to see it transformed into a
shopping mall. Barrington, a Manhattan real estate developer, is
offering to buy the four upper floors, which it would turn into
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   Other developers have made approaches, but no deal has been
struck, said Howard B. Adler, a Manhattan lawyer representing Fritz
deKnegt and his business, F&AMP;W Management Co.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Castelli said that until the building was sold, the
Castelli Gallery there would remain open but only for a few hours a
day. Antonio Homem, director of the Sonnabend Gallery, said it was
planning to stay put until the fall, when it hoped to move to West
22d Street in Chelsea. Michael Sweney, director of the Cowles
Gallery, said Cowles had no plans to move before the fate of the
building was decided.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Sara Lee's plans to give away much of its prized art collection
to museums around the world _ which in addition to good public
relations also provides a nice tax deduction _ have doubled since
the original announcement in June. The corporation is now giving 52
works to 40 museums.
</P>
<P>
   One the latest recipients is the Museum of Fine Arts, Boston,
which has just received Rouault's ``Pierrot'' (1938), one of the
most important of the artist's clown paintings. It is the first
major Rouault to enter the museum's collection.
</P>
<P>
   The museums originally named were in cities where Sara Lee has a
corporate presence. But after deciding to amplify the program, it
has tried to match works to museums whose collections could benefit
from specific gifts.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is organizing a traveling exhibition of the 52 works
before they are scattered. ``Monet to Moore: The Millennium Gift of
Sara Lee Corporation,'' will open at the Singapore Art Museum on
April 1. It will travel to Australia, North Carolina, Oregon and
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Smarting from a decrease in donations for acquisition, the
Metropolitan Museum of Art is holding its first dinner to rebuild
its fund for that purpose, a $1,000-a-person gala at the museum on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our dinners have been to benefit our operating
expenses,'' said Philippe de Montebello, the Metropolitan's
director. ``This will replace our traditional spring gala and will
hopefully replenish the funds that have been cruelly depleted by
Reader's Digest.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the 1980s the Lila Acheson Wallace Fund has supported the
Met's operating and acquisitions budgets with dividends it received
on its stock in Reader's Digest Association. (Mrs. Wallace was a
founder, with her husband, of Reader's Digest.)
</P>
<P>
   These dividends were increased in some years, and as recently as
1997 $3.1 million went to the Met for acquisitions. But
shareholders' dividends have been reduced twice since then, and
that has slashed the Wallace Fund's annual contribution to the
museum to a mere $300,000 for acquiring art and objects.
</P>
<P>
   Emily K. Rafferty, the museum's senior vice president for
development and membership, said that this season the museum asked
its chairman's council, a group of about 60 donors who each give
the museum $40,000 a year, to add another $10,000 each specifically
for acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   With this appeal and the money raised from Monday's dinner, Ms.
Rafferty said, the museum hoped to raise about $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's and Christie's announced their 1998 worldwide auction
sales figures this week, and the two companies are nearly tied.
</P>
<P>
   For the second year Christie's has a tiny edge. Its auction
sales for 1998 totaled $1.96 billion, a 3 percent decline from 1997
when it was $2.01 billion. Sotheby's sales increased 5 percent, to
$1.93 billion, from $1.84 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Christie's became a private company this summer when Francois
Pinault, the French investor, purchased the auction house, so it is
no longer required to release its earnings figures. Sotheby's, a
public company trading on the New York Stock Exchange, must release
its earnings: they rose to $45 million, from $40.6 million in 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
