<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0261 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7974 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANADA-DRAWINGS-NYT &LR;      03-04 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-DRAWINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE MAGIC REALM OF DRAWINGS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Canada, France)   By JOHN RUSSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The secret life of a great art museum is often best
sought out in its department of drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who wants to experience the peculiar spell that
unfamiliar drawings can have upon us need only go to the Frick
Collection, where the current auxiliary exhibition focuses on
``French and English Drawings of the 18th and 19th Centuries From
the National Gallery of Canada.'' The exhibit runs through April
25.
</P>
<P>
   Right from the start, in the small room at street level that
serves both as an overflow and a teaser for shows of this kind,
there are drawings that, coming from no matter what source, would
hold our attention.
</P>
<P>
   The star attraction is the portrait by Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec
of his uncle Amedee de Tapie de Celeyran. This was done when
Toulouse-Lautrec was only 19, and it has precision, energy and
bounce in full measure. Uncle Amedee is pinned down like a rare
butterfly on a board.
</P>
<P>
   Not far from it is a large and tender drawing by Renoir of his
wife and her small son, Jean. Renoir was to go much further in the
final painting that resulted, but movie buffs will recognize the
future director of ``The Rules of the Game'' in the baby's head and
profile. Like ``Proud Maisie,'' the pencil portrait of an Edwardian
heartbreaker by Frederick Sandys that dates from 1902, these
drawings would make their mark anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But it is downstairs at the Frick, where we turn to the left for
English drawings and to the right for French ones, that the
character of the Ottawa collection really asserts itself. Among the
national galleries of the world, the one in Ottawa is relatively
young, though not as young (or so prepotent) as the one in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   It was founded in 1880, under impeccable imperial patronage.
(The head of it was the then governor general of Canada, whose
mother-in-law was Queen Victoria.) Its collection initially
consisted of works by Canadian artists who had been accepted as
members of the Royal Canadian Academy of the Arts.
</P>
<P>
   It took 31 years for the gallery to establish a department of
prints and drawings. Not until 1928 did the gallery hire a young
Englishwoman, Kathleen Fenwick, who had a passion for drawings. It
was to be a further 29 years before she had a substantial say in
what drawings should be bought.
</P>
<P>
   This might have been a recipe for stagnation. But in 1937 the
gallery appointed a British scholar and collector, Paul Oppe, to
work from London as its adviser for drawings. (The quality of
Oppe's own collection of British drawings and watercolors was such
that it was recently acquired from his family by the Tate Gallery
in London for a seven-figure sum in sterling.)
</P>
<P>
   During his 20 years as an adviser to Ottawa, Oppe did his very
best for Canada. The 341 drawings for which he was responsible
included the ``Two Men Standing'' in red chalks by Watteau that may
well be the most beautiful drawing in the French section of the
show.
</P>
<P>
   In his first year as an adviser, he gave a whole new spin to the
notion of English watercolors when he bought a masterpiece by
Samuel Palmer called ``Oak Trees, Lullingstone Park, 1828.'' This
was marvelously exact in its portrait of overhanging oak trees, and
Palmer contrasted them with a flood of egg-yellow light that gave a
new idea of abundant color as a presence in English landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Also in 1937, the gallery acquired a formidable Henry Fuseli
drawing of a young giantess seen from the back. Standing up
straight, with her arms stretched wide, she clearly had troubled
Fuseli's dreams. As so often in his work, he took the idea of a
very big young woman and passed her on to us with all her
monumentality intact.
</P>
<P>
   In the study of English townscape, Oppe got away from
traditional motifs when he acquired ``Chimney Sweepers, May Day''
by John Augustin Atkinson, dating from around 1814. Not much is
made of Atkinson in histories of English art, but there is a
magical freedom of color and light in this study of the London boy
chimney sweeps on May Day.
</P>
<P>
   Normally the lowest of the low on the labor market, on May Day
the sweeps wore brilliant blue-and-gold dress costumes and danced
in the streets, and were treated like gentlefolk by people who
normally shrank from their dirty hands.
</P>
<P>
   French drawings were held in honor in Ottawa as early as 1912,
when the gallery acquired the archetypal ``Young Mother Preparing
an Evening Meal'' by J.F. Millet, which is in the Frick show.
(France still ranks, after all, as one of Canada's two founder
nations.) The tradition has, if anything, been reinforced in recent
years. Drawings like ``The Raven'' by Odilon Redon, the sketch for
``The Barque of Dante'' by the then-young Eugene Delacroix, ``The
Black Arm'' by Courbet and the roundel portrait made in prison in
1795 by Jacques-Louis David are all important way stations in the
long history of French art.
</P>
<P>
   As for the ``Return of the Traveler'' by Jean-Baptiste Greuze,
it is one of the most powerful of Greuze's many investigations into
the melodrama of French family life. The mix of physical and
emotional distress could not be more vividly conveyed.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite extreme of size, weight and evident hard labor
is the drawing of the Piazzetta in Venice by Richard Parkes
Bonington. Delacroix, when young, loved and admired Bonington, and
the two friends both contribute a great deal to this show.
Delacroix's ``Crucifixion'' in pastel measures no more than 9
inches by 4, but it has a flamelike luminosity that makes its
impact even from far across the room.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bonington's Venetian drawing, it is as fresh and as
brilliant as if it had been done this afternoon instead of 175
years ago. All Venice is there: the light, the marine air, the
great monuments and the people, both native and foreign. It stands
out even in a show where much is irresistible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1747EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
