<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0262 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7976 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIDDLER-DANCE-REVIEW-     03-04 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIDDLER-DANCE-REVIEW-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIDDLERS GREEN': A FORMAL PASTORAL WORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul Taylor's recent dance works have tended to be
very funny or very nasty, sometimes both. His new and beautiful
``Fiddlers Green'' reminds us that the essential Paul Taylor is the
one who hears music and choreographs to it.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, that is what Taylor always does, and there is
nothing simple about the way he hears music. His plotless pieces
show him off as the most musical choreographer in modern dance. For
starters, one can name ``Aureole,'' ``Airs,'' ``Mercuric Tidings,''
``Arden Court'' and ``Esplanade.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fiddlers Green,'' given its New York premiere by the Paul
Taylor Dance Company on Wednesday night at City Center, is a
pastoral dance. The score consists of excerpts from ``John's Book
of Alleged Dances'' by the contemporary composer John Adams, whose
treatment of American folk motifs is obviously Taylor's
springboard.
</P>
<P>
   Like the 1962 ``Aureole,'' the new work is lyrical and
sprightly, haunting in its formal composition. ``Fiddlers Green''
is not the son of ``Aureole'' but perhaps the grand nephew of that
masterwork, which was long Taylor's signature piece.
</P>
<P>
   The dancers are again in white costumes, this time in Santo
Loquasto's Tom Sawyer overalls and shirts for the men and very
short dresses for the women. A male solo and a tender male-female
duet stand out in relief within the ensemble as they do in
``Aureole.''
</P>
<P>
   But Adams, not quite out of his post-Minimalist phase, is not
the Handel of ``Aureole.'' Taylor's great plotless pieces have been
set to music by 18th- and 19th-century composers.
</P>
<P>
   In Adams, he finds an American do-it-yourself inventiveness
similar to his own, and ``Fiddlers Green'' succeeds on a level of
immediacy. It does not have a soaring grandeur but its purity
recalls why ``Aureole'' was originally called Taylor's ``White
Ballet'' (a reference to the corps in white of ``Giselle'' and
other 19th-century ballets).
</P>
<P>
   The first of six sections opens with Patrick Corbin tapping his
foot as Jennifer Tipton's lighting renders the backdrop all green.
In this instant abstraction of small town America with its village
greens, Taylor and Ms. Tipton wittily recall a more bucolic time
when towns did not yet establish drug-free zones around their
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Kronos Quartet, which commissioned the score, is heard on a
recording. The strings, especially the violin playing, make up the
avant-garde fiddling. Adams also used a prepared piano (objects in
the piano strings to create rhythmic support). No wonder foot
tapping is the choreographic motif.
</P>
<P>
   The other dancers join Corbin as the happy-go-lucky hero. Their
movement is light, full of Taylorisms: curved arms in attitude
jumps, pelvis swivels, rotating shoulders and torso, rhythmic
shifts and fast skips with arms in flattened position, palms held
out.
</P>
<P>
   All sit and watch Richard Chen See, always his remarkable self
in a remarkably fast solo in which his elbows spin like juggling
pins when he is not walking like a chicken or pawing the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's attention is always to detail in movement, and the way
he offers a twist on other idioms, as well as on his own, sets the
tone in each segment. The third, danced by Lisa Viola, Kristi
Egtvedt, Silvia Nevjinsky, Andy LeBeau, Takehiro Ueyama and Maureen
Mansfield, begins with a wedge of hip-swaying dancers who look
dreamy and then communal as they form a cluster.
</P>
<P>
   This is the pastoral heart of the dance, very neat in its
symmetry of pairs, who are always on the move. The sweet violin
sounds give way to a thump for Ms. Viola's heel-clicking before the
cast forms a tighter circle and ends in a pose, arms curved.
</P>
<P>
   The major solo goes to Corbin, typically fast on his feet and
brilliant as a thigh-slapping hayseed. The choreography is a
difficult collage of unrelated steps, mainly jumps that change
shape in the air. Ueyama enters to copy Corbin, who chases him out
several times and never stops what is basically a continuous solo
that only looks like a duet.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Patrick and Rachel Berman are magnificent in a superb and
sensual duet. Patrick carries Ms. Berman before she slips to the
floor to recline like a latter-day Odalisque. The music, a slow
melody heard over little plunks, gives the beauty of the unfolding
choreography a complementary flow.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick is the protective, enraptured partner as he and Ms.
Berman explore a relationship: she puts her leg on his shoulder and
cartwheels, and both propel themselves on the floor in a half-lying
position. All is seamless.
</P>
<P>
   The finale has a punch line that doesn't quite work: Ueyama
chases Corbin, the town bully, offstage, and the piece ends with
Ueyama raising his fist in a power salute. But before that moment,
the full cast returns for a recapitulation of all the hip-slapping,
foot-tapping and heel-clicking. Not light, not dark, ``Fiddlers
Green'' is dancing to music.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Berest, Andrew Asnes, Ted Thomas, Michael Trusnovec,
Francie Huber and Caryn Heilman joined the other hard-working
dancers in ``Cloven Kingdom,'' which suffered from a glitch in the
lighting and sound system. The energy was there, but something was
missing in Taylor's reminder that under their elegant evening
dress, people can be positively beastly.
</P>
<P>
   Superlatives cannot suffice for the more recent ``Piazzolla
Caldera,'' a technical tour de force and essay on the tango. Taylor
captures the essence of that dance by filtering the music of Astor
Piazzolla and Jerzy Peterburshsky. Asnes' power was unmistakable;
Patrick and See, as a couple of drunks, gave the gymnastic
choreography their all. Ms. Huber was persuasive as the loner in
the crowd, and Corbin and Ms. Viola yanked and pulled with passion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
