<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MONICA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LESSONS IN LEWINSKY  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARS IN THE MARCH 5 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - `I felt dirty and I felt used,'' Monica Lewinsky told
an estimated 70 million television viewers Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   To which we reply: You are, and you were. So what's your point?
</P>
<P>
   Many Americans say they are sick and tired of the media's
obsession with President Clinton's sexual escapades and wish that
the country would focus on issues that matter - Social Security,
health care, foreign policy, education. But there's a disconnect
between what Americans say and what they do.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that 70 million Americans would tune into a two-hour
interview with a young woman of questionable intelligence and even
more questionable (non-existent?) morals indicates that Americans
aren't at all sick and tired of the topic.
</P>
<P>
   It may have been the most-watched news program ever broadcast by
a single network. Indeed, if Lewinsky's new book, written with
Andrew Morton of Princess Di fame, becomes a best seller, Americans
will have nobody but themselves to blame for the country's
obsession with the Monica Mess.
</P>
<P>
   None of which absolves Clinton of responsibility. This president
demonstrated appallingly bad judgment - not once, but many times.
And he lied about it. Not once, but many times.
</P>
<P>
   Including to a grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's accused of rape.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's wrongdoing will become his legacy. Saddest of all, it
does irreparable harm to the country he claims to love.
</P>
<P>
   After viewing ABC's Lewinsky special, some described Monica as
more vixen than victim. We agree. It's a distinction worth
remembering.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1749EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7980 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-PICASSO-EXHIBIT-N     03-04 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-PICASSO-EXHIBIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PICASSO`S CERAMICS: GENIUS ON HOLIDAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Exhibition notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By ROBERTA SMITH   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ You should have fun with the exhibition of Picasso's
ceramic work at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. Picasso certainly
seems to have enjoyed carving this particular notch in his cane of
art medium conquests. That he did so during one of the happiest
periods of his life may partly account for the unclouded lightness
of these charming figures, wittily decorated plates, casseroles,
pitchers, masks and glazed-tile paintings. Perhaps the second-class
status traditionally accorded ceramics had a soporific effect,
contributing to the air of genius on holiday, veering in and out of
focus, that permeates this show.
</P>
<P>
   The best pieces are utterly transparent. They reduce Picasso's
transforming genius to its most basic, accessible components;
present his favorite subjects in a medium that seems to fuse
painting, sculpture and drawing into a single, fluid process, and
reveal another side of his easy familiarity with different artistic
periods and styles. The less successful works parody those styles
to the brink of kitsch and confirm the careless bravado that
Picasso could almost always summon: Even on automatic pilot he
produced things that were at least Picassos and sometimes only
that. And they reiterate his reflexive obsession with the female
form. When is a vessel just a vessel? Almost never.
</P>
<P>
   By the late 1940s, Picasso was withdrawing from the pressures of
Paris and spending more and more time in the south of France,
enjoying a brief period of family life with his young mistress,
Francoise Gilot. In 1947 they had a son, Claude, and in 1949, a
daughter, Paloma. Also in 1947, Picasso began to work at Madoura,
the pottery factory of Georges and Suzanne Ramie in Vallauris, near
Antibes. Blessed with ground that yielded excellent clay, Vallauris
had been an important ceramics-producing center from Roman times to
the 1920s, when metal cooking vessels began to replace the
traditional earthenware. The Ramies extended the invitation to
Picasso partly in the hope that his presence would help revive the
town's depressed economy, which it did.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Picasso was spending his summers and more and more of his
winters in a villa above Vallauris, renting an old perfume factory
there as a sculpture studio and, for a decade, even producing
linoleum-cut posters for the town's small summer ceramics festival.
(They line the reading room in the Met exhibition and have the same
offhand liveliness as the ceramics.) His involvement with ceramics,
which was most intense during the late 1940s, eventually resulted
in more than 3,000 objects that form the only patch of terra
incognita remaining on the well-charted continent of his art.
</P>
<P>
   It is noteworthy that after his death, every art object in his
estate was photographed except the ceramic works, which he owned in
abundance. First exhibited around 1950, they were dismissed by
influential potters like Bernard Leach in England and viewed with
embarrassment by the art world.
</P>
<P>
   ``Picasso: Painter and Sculptor in Clay'' affords the first
in-depth look at Picasso's ceramics and avoids burdening them with
undue claims. It was seen last fall at the Royal Academy in London,
where it was organized by a curatorial team that included Claude
Picasso and Bernard Ruiz-Picasso, the artist's son and grandson;
Norman Rosenthal and Simonetta Fraquelli of the Royal Academy, and
Marilyn McCully, a London-based Picasso scholar.
</P>
<P>
   Showcased in the exhibition's opening gallery are works that
hint at the range of style, form and subject to come, as well as
some of the ups and downs. On view are a large pitcher painted with
robust flowers and a serpent in ultramarine and black; a tall,
curving vase that Picasso converted into a female torso by adding a
bright yellow bikini so crisply Minimal it might have been painted
by Alex Katz; a jolly mask that suggests some kind of high-class
touristware, and a bright green plate presenting a ceramic fish,
fork and lemon slice, a cliche worn thin by the Surrealists and
later thinner still by Robert Arneson.
</P>
<P>
   Also here is a bare-to-the-waist draped figure, a little Venus
de Milo with arms. And of course there is the artist himself, shown
in Attic-style black silhouette on a green and white pitcher,
painting and (on the other side) sculpturing from the nude model.
In one of the show's better moments of tossed-off brilliance, the
throat of the pitcher doubles as clerestory studio windows through
which birds and treetops are visible. Such depictive finesse
becomes overbearing later in the show, in a group of elliptical
platters and small bowls whose curves re-create that most macho of
Picasso motifs, the bullring, with almost cloying accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   The show has been beautifully installed by William Lieberman,
the chairman of 20th-century art at the Met and a veteran of many
Picasso shows. Happily, nearly everything can be seen in the round.
Unhappily, some interesting pieces were not lent to the New York
stop, including some early dabblings in ceramics dating from the
late 1920s, in which Picasso painted images onto vases made by Jean
van Dongen, the brother of the painter Kees van Dongen. Other works
were simply trimmed from the show, among them a singularly rugged
hybrid sculpture (1950-51) that consists of an earthenware vase
embedded in a larger, cruder pitcher made of cast plaster.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Picasso merely added glazed images and decorations to
traditional plates thrown on the wheel by the potters at Madoura.
Or he cleverly reshaped vases fresh off the potter's wheel, adding
a few dents, dots, dashes and wavy black lines to create a woman in
a billowing Fortuny-like gown, for example.
</P>
<P>
   But he also began designing zoomorphic pieces, made of
combinations of thrown forms that were often innovative departures
from ancient jugs and amphorae. These include the reclining kid
goat in the show's second gallery, and the man and woman mounted on
a bull and a horse. The extended necks of these vessels, with
curving arms attached, double as the human figures in these
ambitious works. The images of these animals are split and splayed
ingeniously onto tilted bullet-shaped volumes, one more round in
the continual contest between two- and three-dimensional forms that
began with the two-eyed profiles of ``Les Demoiselles d'Avignon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1751EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
