<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7981 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MET-PICASSO-EXHIBIT-2     03-04 0589
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MET-PICASSO-EXHIBIT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: Demoiselles d'Avignon.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   And naturally, Picasso began to rove through history, creating
amusing fragments that parody the black and red vases of Classical
Greece or depict arcadian fauns and flute players who began to
re-enter his art in the 1920s. Most convincing in this category are
the regal women inspired by Hellenic Tanagra figures, who are shown
draped in patterned robes.
</P>
<P>
   The rims of certain plates have wonderful details, even when
their central images fail to impress: decorative borders suggestive
of French peasant pottery, or colored confetti that seems lifted
from his own pointillist-flavored Cubist works of the late teens.
And of course there are images of Francoise: On one plate she's
depicted sentimentally as a doe-eyed beauty, on its neighbor in
crude childish scribbles of red and blue punctuated by a
sharp-pointed nose. Next to this, her face appears again, this time
carved into a mask with powerful volumes and startled eyes. After
1955, there are portraits of Jacqueline Roche, the saleswoman
Picasso met in the Remies' workshop, who became his companion and,
in 1961, his wife.
</P>
<P>
   While not overburdening Picasso's ceramics with claims of
greatness, the exhibition and its catalog, which includes essays by
Claude Picasso, Bernard Ruiz-Picasso and Ms. McCully, also stops
short of putting them in an appropriate historical context. But
that's fine for now. This show opens new territory. A land-rush of
research homesteaders will undoubtedly follow.
</P>
<P>
   One hopes that future scholars will reintegrate Picasso's
ceramics into his work as a whole and consider it in relation to
the work of his contemporaries in the fields of both art and craft.
Some of the ceramic pieces were cast in bronze, but only one
example is included here, the gracefully streamlined ``Centaur,''
from 1947-48, who carries a tiny water jug on his back.
</P>
<P>
   How do Picasso's efforts in clay compare with Matisse's sojourn
in the applied arts, which resulted in the chapel at nearby Vence?
And what was their effect on ceramic art? Despite Bernard Leach's
dismissal, a new book on 20th-century English craft by Tanya Harrod
states that in the early 1950s, a younger generation of English
potters found Picasso's ceramics liberating in their improvisatory
high-spiritedness, their modernity and their disdain of function,
qualities that provided alternatives to Leach's emphasis on Asian
ceramic traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Most interesting of all will be a consideration of their
relationship to the work from Picasso's last decade, when his
involvement with ceramics decreased and he turned to painting and
printmaking, often working in bouts of feverish productivity.
Lieberman has included two of Picasso's late paintings from the
Met's collection in the exhibition's final gallery, creating a
fascinating coda. Their blending colors and fluid forms could well
have been influenced by both the unpredictable melting of glazes in
the Madoura kilns and the abandon with which Picasso applied them.
It is interesting to think that these untroubled ceramic pieces,
intimating a pastoral idyll beneath an eternal Mediterranean sun,
might have helped set the stage for the desperate turmoil of the
late paintings, which often convey a portrait of the artist staring
death in the face and working against the clock.
</P>
<P>
   EXHIBITION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `PICASSO: PAINTER AND SCULPTOR IN CLAY'
</P>
<P>
   At the Metropolitan of Museum Art, Fifth Avenue at 82nd Street,
New York, through June 6.
</P>
</TEXT>
