<HEADLINE>
GONE _ BUT NOT FORGOTTEN _ AT R&AMP;B PIONEER AWARDS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``It's gotten to the point where every single day
something of value is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer and band leader Paul Westerberg, who made that comment
over the phone the other day, has a point, especially in a
transitory city like Los Angeles where a historical landmark is a
car wash that has stood on the same site for three years.
</P>
<P>
   In the music biz, revered artists of yesterday are routinely
discarded, shunted aside and forgotten, except by the collectors
and staunch fans who've stood by during the hard times.
</P>
<P>
   That's what was so touching about the recent Pioneer Awards
ceremony in which the Rhythm-and-Blues Foundation honored 10 soul
greats in an elaborate dinner the day after the Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   For some, like New Orleans r&AMP;b and jazz crooner Johnny Adams, it
was too late. Adams, who died last year, was represented by his
widow, Judy Adams, who insisted that unfair record contracts were
still in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny put out nine albums since 1984, and we haven't seen a
penny from any of them,'' she said. ``If he hadn't kept touring the
way he did, I don't know how we'd eat. This was slavery dressed up
in a suit.''
</P>
<P>
   The day of the Pioneer event, honorees including Joe Simon,
Mickey Baker, Brenda Holloway, Garnet Mimms and the Manhattans
gathered at a West Hollywood hotel to renew old friendships, meet
invited guests and give interviews.
</P>
<P>
   It was indeed heartwarming to see longtime fans who've turned
into friends approach artists such as Holloway to catch up on old
times. A British documentary crew shot the proceedings for a film
on the UK phenomenon known as Northern Soul, in which discos in
desolate places like Wigan and Blackpool turned obscure r&AMP;b singles
into a lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   The Pioneer Awards _ not the relatively hollow Grammys _ are the
industry's true best night each year, the latter more often than
not rewarding sales and marketing success over genuine musical
achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The performance segment of the r&AMP;b event should be televised
like the Grammys and the MTV Video Music Awards. In that way, the
pop audience might get a sense of what's being forgotten. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1756EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7989 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CENTRAL-ASIA-TEXTILES     03-04 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CENTRAL-ASIA-TEXTILES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM CENTRAL ASIA EXOTIC TEXTILES AS TROPHY CLOTHES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By GRACE GLUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The most appealing exotica produced in backwater
Central Asia during the 19th century _ as far from Paris as you
could get, fashionwise _ were the gorgeously colored and patterned
handmade silks known as ikat. Made by the complex ``resist''
method, which entails repeated binding and dying of the threads
before they are woven into fabric, ikat goes back to ancient times
and is known to many cultures throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Asian ikat revival that came and went in the last
century involved not only many intricate processes but _ talk about
multicultural! _ a rich mix of ethnic types who cooperated in
carrying them out: Tajiks, Uzbeks, Iranians and Jews, among others,
each a specialist in dying, weaving or another aspect of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Imbued, like their clientele, with the Central Asian passion for
textiles, they made ikats for sale as luxury goods and worked them
into presentation and ceremonial robes. In Bukhara and Samarkand,
along with smaller outposts in this desert-and-steppe segment of
the old silk route, your social status was judged by the number and
quality of ikats you wore and hung on your walls, and a bride's
dowry was nothing without them.
</P>
<P>
   Of the several fine Central Asian ikat collections in the West,
the most comprehensive is said to be that of Dr. Guido Goldman, a
political scientist and founding director of the Minda de Gunzberg
Center for European Studies at Harvard. Inspired by their parallels
with 20th-century abstract art, Goldman has been acquiring the
sumptuous silks for more than 20 years and refers to them as
textile paintings.
</P>
<P>
   From his holdings of more than 200 ikats (the word is derived
from mengikat, a Malay-Indonesian verb meaning to tie or to bind),
40 form the show at the Jewish Museum, ``Ikat: Splendid Silks of
Central Asia From the Guido Goldman Collection.''
</P>
<P>
   At first glance the exhibition, circulated by the American
Foundation for Textile Art Inc., is overwhelming, a dizzying blitz
of rug-bazaar color and pattern that to Western eyes might seem a
little over the top.
</P>
<P>
   Yet as noted in the handsome catalog written by two Central
Asian textile specialists, Katherine Fitz Gibbon and Andrew Hale,
the ikats clearly exemplify the conventions of Central Asian art:
``abstraction from nature, clear and defined color, vigorous line,
a love of pattern and, above all, a willingness to play around, to
try a new pattern with every warp.'' And pretty soon, in the
sensuous chromatic climate created by these objects, your guard
drops and your eye tunes up.
</P>
<P>
   Wall hangings, made of several same-patterned vertical fabric
lengths sewn together, predominate in the show. One of the most
striking is a rare, luxurious five-panel piece from Bukhara (in
Uzbekistan), dating to the first half of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating no less than eight colors (which meant eight dye
baths), it is a dazzling orchestration of highly stylized scorpion
motifs keyed in with lozenges of floral and jewelry designs. The
predominating reds are inflected by yellows, blues and greens, all
on an underlying white field.
</P>
<P>
   In another Bukharan wall hanging from the same period, rife with
warm reds and mustard yellows, the designer ``plays around'' by
mixing bunches of stylized pomegranates hanging from stalks with
the shapes of paired water jugs, like accidentally placed fruits,
to show his skill at sketching out a complex pattern on the bound
threads.
</P>
<P>
   Ikat designers didn't worry about such trifling Western concerns
as matching patterns or aligning them when panels were sewn
together. They assumed, in fact, that misalignment heightened the
visual buzz, and for the same reason they often used different
patterns in the same hanging.
</P>
<P>
   One mid-19th-century piece from Bukhara, for example, whose
central design is of pinched-in hexagonal medallions in red, black
and white, is surrounded by a ``frame'' of entirely different cat's
face motifs, smaller in scale but of similar colors. A deliberate
misalignment can clearly be seen in another Bukharan hanging from
the same period, a work whose involved design evokes the
intricacies of Central Asian architecture.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Predominantly colored in red, white and black, its forms are
part of a very large medallion whose full shape can barely be
perceived within the fabric length.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the ikats shown here are slightly more restrained. One
elegant hanging from the mid-19th century has a somber indigo
background, considered more appropriate for older women and funeral
clothes. It is figured with a dignified motif of white pendantlike
scrolls, inflected by long red free-form streaks. And there are
some simpler patterns much closer to Western abstraction.
</P>
<P>
   A single panel loom length, also from Bukhara but later in the
century, has a vertical animal skin motif, like a tiger's stripes,
in blue touched by red and bisected by a narrow white band down the
middle. It was probably influenced by a culture outside Central
Asia, maybe Russian or Far Eastern.
</P>
<P>
   More intricate but still close to Western design is an unusual
silk-velvet Bukharan hanging from the mid-19th century. Its dark
ground, timidly punctuated by small geometric solids in yellows,
reds and blues, is punched up by elongated diamonds and triangles,
outlined in tiny ziggurat steps, that seem to float in a linear
overlay.
</P>
<P>
   From Samarkand or the Fergana Valley, the area closest to China,
is another striking work whose regular, vertical arrangements of
combs between stylized branching steer horns, in arresting colors
on a pale ground, seem to have more in common with 20th-century
Western abstraction than mid-19th-century Central Asian esthetics.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be overlooked are the ikat robes whose distinctive,
stylized shapes counterpoint the many rectangular hangings in the
show. The chapan or khalat, a unisex outer coat of lightly padded
silk or cotton, was the everyday garment of Central Asia. Several
were usually worn on top of each other, conferring a uniform
chubbiness on the populace. Bukharan fops showing off their wealth
sometimes sported up to 10 robes at a time.
</P>
<P>
   But there were also robes made specifically for women. Young
ones wore the brightest colors and the biggest patterns; soberer
dress was assumed by middle-aged and older women. The most
luxurious women's garment was the munisak, worn by Muslim and
Jewish women during important rites of passage, and particularly
evident at their weddings and funerals.
</P>
<P>
   Like the boldly patterned late-19th-century silk-velvet examples
in the show, the garment had accentuated feminine lines with no
collar and flaring sides, although its silhouette was slimmer and
more elegant than other types of women's robes. Well-dressed
matrons of Bukhara and Samarkand would have laughed at staid
Western notions of coordinated colors and patterns; their idea of
high style was a riotous combo of bright calicos, chintzes and
ikats worn all together.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitably, coinciding with the collapse of the oasis kingdoms
by the end of the 19th century, commercial methods of production
began to invade the trade, and 20th-century dress modes crept in.
Handmade ikats became a thing of the past. Alas! This show can only
hint at what the Western world missed out on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
