<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CANYON-FIRE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND CANYON NEEDS FIRE EXPERIMENT  
 (ADV: THIS EDITORIAL APPEARS IN THE MARCH 5 ARIZONA REPUBLIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Imagine the unthinkable: A hot, roaring fire out of
control, jumping from treetop to treetop, destroying the old growth
Ponderosa pines that stand proud and tall in Grand Canyon National
Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody wants to think the unthinkable.
</P>
<P>
   But the harsh truth is that the forests at Grand Canyon are
disasters waiting to happen. More than a century of forest fire
suppression tactics have contributed to a situation ripe for a
repeat of the 1988 fire in Yellowstone National Park that burned
800,000 acres of forest.
</P>
<P>
   Across the canyon rim thick stands of sapling ponderosa pines
are common. There are thick layers of pine needle duff. Dead and
downed trees are everywhere. Factor in one of the driest winters in
a long time and the concern is palpable.
</P>
<P>
   Says an environmental assessment by the National Park Service,
``The potential for large, high-intensity, stand replacing fires in
the 21st century is very likely. The timely treatment of forest
duff and unnaturally dense stands of young trees is necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   To lessen the possibility of catastrophic fires and return the
forests to a healthier ecosystem, Grand Canyon officials want to
conduct a series of experiments on two, 80-acre sections _ one on
the South Rim and one on the North Rim.
</P>
<P>
   The experiments have the backing of Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt, who strongly rejects insinuations that the experiments
would be tantamount to the beginning of logging in the nation's
national parks. ``This experiment is an attempt to learn how to
return the forests to their natural, healthy state and eliminate
the danger of catastrophic forest fires,'' he says. ``That's all it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   One suggested model was pioneered by Wally Covington, a
professor of forest ecology at Northern Arizona University. His
view of the natural state of the forests in the Southwest more than
a century ago is a far cry from what we see today. To Covington,
there was large spacing between the tall Ponderosa pines. Tall
grasses grew on the forest's floors. Lightening would ignite the
grasses. These fires consumed the smaller trees and moved past the
fire-resistant bark of the old growth.
</P>
<P>
   We believe the experiments ought to go forward. Each site would
be divided into four, 20-arce experimental units. A different
technique will be used in each: 1) burn only; 2) minimal thinning
and then burning; 3) emulate presettlement forest structure
followed by burning; and 4) control, or no treatment.
</P>
<P>
   These are not a slippery slope to full-scale logging in our
national parks. The public wouldn't stand for such a thing. Rather,
they are designed to produce credible scientific information which
then can be used in the formulation of policy. If they lead to a
environmentally sensitive way to lessen the threat of a catastrophe
and restore forest ecosystems, what's wrong with that? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1757EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
