A7992 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAPIST-FIGHT-KAN &LR;      03-04 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAPIST-FIGHT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDGE SAYS ENOUGH IS ENOUGH IN CONVICTED RAPIST'S PAPERWORK
BLIZZARD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY RIZZO  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ After Patrick C. Lynn was convicted of
raping an Overland Park woman, he vowed in court to ``dedicate my
life to getting even.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his word, he has spent the past two years waging a legal
assault from his prison cell, firing off legal pleadings to
courthouses across eastern Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   The scope and tenacity of Lynn's legal efforts have prompted
unprecedented legal rulings against him.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the Johnson County judge who has borne the brunt of
much of Lynn's legal wrath issued an order prohibiting Lynn, 42,
from pursuing lawsuits against a dozen people associated with his
case.
</P>
<P>
   Administrative Judge Larry McClain said Lynn's lawsuits were an
effort to ``retaliate against virtually everyone who was involved
in the criminal process.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is now attempting to vent his predatory instincts through
the judicial system to attack those involved in his conviction,''
McClain wrote. ``The judicial system should not allow this to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   McClain ordered the court clerk to accept nothing further from
Lynn except notice that he will appeal Monday's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn already has filed 10 cases with the Kansas Court of Appeals
and the state Supreme Court, naming McClain in four of them.
</P>
<P>
   He also has filed eight actions in U.S. District Court in
Topeka, but a federal judge threw those cases out and ordered Lynn
to pay several hundred dollars in costs.
</P>
<P>
   Lynn began filing lawsuits shortly after he was sentenced to 88
years in prison in January 1997 in the attack on the Overland Park
woman. He did the same in South Carolina, where he was convicted of
rape and spent 15 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   In all, 30 persons were sued in seven lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   All, he contended, were involved in some type of conspiracy to
violate his rights or frame him for a crime he didn't commit.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of the Kansas attorney general's office, McClain
set temporary restrictions on how Lynn could proceed with his
lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami County judge was appointed to hear the case and issued a
permanent injunction requiring all of Lynn's claims to be reviewed
to see whether they had any merit before they could be filed.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas Court of Appeals is now considering Lynn's appeal of
that injunction as well as of his criminal conviction.
</P>
<P>
   McClain's ruling Monday was based on his review of lawsuits Lynn
has tried to file against the Overland Park woman, a woman he
dated, an Overland Park officer, the district attorney and seven
lawyers or their employees who had represented him.
</P>
<P>
   While calling Lynn's claims against his victim ``frankly
absurd,'' McClain had the strongest response to Lynn's attempt to
sue his former friend.
</P>
<P>
   He said it was best described ``as fantasized rambling of a
convicted rapist making a malicious attempt to embarrass and
humiliate an innocent witness and former friend.''
</P>
<P>
   As he did before his trial, Lynn fired the first two attorneys
appointed to represent him on the appeal, and he is trying to fire
Geary Gorup, the third attorney to represent him on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Gorup sought to have a mental examination for Lynn.
His motion notes the kinds of demands Lynn makes on his attorneys.
Besides the more than 1,100 pages of the official appeal record,
Lynn has produced more than 2,000 pages of ``pleadings, memorandums
and letters.''
</P>
<P>
   In his writings, Lynn has made 469 requests of Gorup and listed
``over 975 separate legal and factual issues and arguments (without
duplication).''
</P>
<P>
   Gorup said that of those approximately 1,450 ``separate issues,
arguments, requests or demands,'' he had found numerous instances
of factual contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Gorup suggested that a possible reason for Lynn's inconsistency
or his ``seeming self-destructive inability to accept the orders of
the court or the advice of counsel'' may be a sign of mental
incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   But the Court of Appeals denied the request.
</P>
<P>
   ``The appellant (Lynn) appears lucid and fully aware of the
judicial process, and this court finds no reason to interrupt the
course of his direct appeal for a hearing on this issue,'' Judge G.
Joseph Pierron wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The court also denied Lynn's request to fire Gorup.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
