<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Friday, March 5, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The ingredients for a storm system will come together across the
Middle West Friday. A jet stream disturbance, which was part of the
storm system that lashed the Pacific Northwest Tuesday night, will
merge Friday morning with another Pacific disturbance over the
northern Rockies. The merger will result in broken areas of snow
across parts of Nebraska, the Dakotas, Montana and Wyoming.
Moreover, the merger will provide additional energy for an
important surface low-pressure system to form over eastern
Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and a thunderstorms will burgeon Friday across parts of
the western Gulf States and lower Mississippi Valley as the
developing low works in tandem with a high pressure system over
North Carolina to draw increasingly moist air northward from the
Gulf of Mexico. If moisture mounts rapidly over the region, a few
thunderstorms with damaging winds are possible Friday afternoon and
evening.
</P>
<P>
   Steady rains will fall across the Ohio Valley north of the warm
front associated with the low, with rain changing to snow later as
colder air arrives once the low passes. Farther north, broken areas
of snow will develop over the southern Great Lakes, with
accumulations of 2 to 5 inches of snow possible by Saturday morning
across northern Illinois, southern Wisconsin and eastern Iowa.
Light snow will spread into western Pennsylvania and western New
York Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Pacific Northwest, recently battered by high
winds and heavy rains, will have a respite of tranquil weather.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Fried Electronics
</P>
<P>
   ``The upper-air system got fried by a lightning strike''
reported a forecaster at the National Weather Service in New York
City Wednesday evening. The forecaster was referring to the
electronic system that tracks weather balloons launched from Long
Island. The thunderstorm that zapped the electronics was one of a
bevy that invaded the Northeast states late Wednesday. Some
produced rain, while others produced snow. Winter thunderstorms
associated with a low pressure system indicate the low is rapidly
intensifying, a forecasting clue that can be gleaned without the
aid of a weather balloon.
</P>
</TEXT>
