<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KC-FURNITURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMFORTABLE WITH MARKET SHARE, SMALL FURNITURE STORES SITTING
PRETTY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GENE MEYER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Little guys almost always compete with big
guys in American business. But the story takes a different twist in
the world of furniture retailing.
</P>
<P>
   The little guys appear to be winning.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Orman has a theory. With his brother Dennis, Orman opened
Orman's Furniture on Metcalf Avenue in Stanley in southern Overland
Park ``back when we used to say we were just south of 151st and
plowed ground.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Kansas City and, I think, the whole country,'' Orman said,
``the stores that are doing best are family-owned businesses,
usually in a single location, that own their own real estate.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, to list just a few examples, he said,
``you've got Cousins, third generation, and Fuhr's, second
generation; there is us and Benchmark, two locations but first
generation, and they own their own land.''
</P>
<P>
   Owning property rather than leasing often is a big advantage for
furniture dealers, who need lots of room to showcase their wares.
</P>
<P>
   Those solidly established operations are thriving in comparison
with Levitz, which is sacrificing its area stores to a national
belt-tightening; Rhodes Furniture, whose slow sales nationally were
cited in corporate parent Helig-Meyers Co.'s latest earnings
report; and Greenstreet Interiors, whose out-of-state owners
recently closed the Country Club Plaza area store they had leased
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Benchmark, in contrast, appears to be thriving. Its owners, who
didn't return telephone calls for this article, have signed a pact
with one of the country's biggest furniture makers to build one of
the region's largest sales and distribution complexes in Olathe.
Going through a tunnel
</P>
<P>
   Similar stories abound in other cities, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``There appears to be consolidation under way throughout the
industry,'' said Bob Price, a divisional merchandising manager at
J.C. Penney Co. Inc.'s headquarters in Plano, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Penney, for instance, has yanked furniture out of some of
its stores. And in 36 communities, including Overland Park, it has
moved furniture departments out of sometimes-cramped
department-store space to freestanding home centers that are 40
percent larger.
</P>
<P>
   Rival Sears, Roebuck and Co. went a step further in January by
converting its former HomeLife division _ about 100 freestanding
stores and 30 more within existing Sears stores _ into a separate
HomeLife company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Furniture retailing is going through a bit of a tunnel right
now,'' said Dave Griesbaum, HomeLife's marketing director.
</P>
<P>
   What executives have a hard time predicting is what they will
find at the end of that tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   Statistics are hard to come by, but calculations based on sales
tax collections and similar revenue yardsticks generally indicate
that furniture sales last year rose 4 percent to 5 percent, or
about half as fast as home sales.
</P>
<P>
   No one knows how accurate those numbers are because sales
through catalogs and department stores, for example, often aren't
counted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is the notion that there may be many empty dining
rooms and other spaces where home sales have bloomed in beds of low
mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``There just aren't too many of us out there who are fortunate
enough to have threes or fives or tens of thousands of dollars left
over for furniture,'' said Greg Crowley, owner of Crowley Furniture
in Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   Because furniture is the third most costly purchase for many
families, after a home and a car, Crowley and many other retailers
offer deferred-financing plans.
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, many operators try to outhustle their bigger rivals.
Department store chains such as J.C. Penney typically offer at
least 90 days before payments begin. Crowley and other independents
sometimes try to beat that by extending the grace period to as much
as two years.
</P>
<P>
   Retailers offer these loans for the sake of flexibility and as a
marketing tactic, but they really don't push them, Crowley said.
That's because to get money now, retailers almost always must sell
the loans, at a discount, to a commercial finance company, which
will do the collecting when the grace period is up.
New competition
</P>
<P>
   Some lag time between home buying and furniture buying is
normal, industry veterans say. Many families make do with their
existing furniture until they've replenished some of their savings
or until they see what would fit best in the new space.
</P>
<P>
   There is another possibility. Sales may appear to be lagging
because customers may be buying from a new group of competitors,
said Christine Jobes. A former furniture chain executive, Jobes now
is an analyst at the National Retail Federation in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Stores such as Crate and Barrel, Pottery Barn, Restoration
Hardware and others that aren't traditionally considered furniture
stores are attracting two important groups of furniture buyers,
Jobes said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They aren't buying furniture so much as collecting things
they'd like for their lives,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Younger buyers, who are perhaps more affluent than before
because they are marrying and starting new homes later in life, are
buying more items in these lifestyle specialty stores because they
like the styles, Jobes said.
</P>
<P>
   Their baby boomer parents often show up there, too, to replace
what they had while they were growing up.
</P>
<P>
   It's tough to gauge how much business these lifestyle specialty
stores might be pulling from more conventional furniture retailers.
</P>
<P>
   Lifestyle specialty stores barely registered as a fast-growing
new market when the trade publication /{Furniture Today/} last
spring asked manufacturers which potential distribution channels
looked hottest for the foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Product specialty stores _ such as leather, mattress and baby
furniture outlets _ ranked similarly low on the previous survey two
years earlier, but they rank third on the latest list, just behind
struggling multicity chains such as Levitz.
</P>
<P>
   Further explosive growth seems likely for specialty stores
unless the economy tanks badly, said John Francis, a furniture
designer and owner of Unique Furniture Options in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   UFO, as the nearly 3-year-old store is informally called, is a
specialty store in both senses of the Furniture Today categories.
It does a primarily special-order business in high-end furniture
and fabrics. Customers are as apt to have checked out Restoration
Hardware, Pottery Barn or some other competing lifestyle store as a
conventional furniture store.
</P>
<P>
   But Francis said he thought a locally owned independent could
compete against the new specialty stores, too.
</P>
<P>
   Francis said that, as an independent, he could provide a level
of sophisticated customer service that corporately guided
competitors could only hope to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The secret is in listening, Francis said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be bold of us to presume we know what
customers want before they tell us,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1759EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
