r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN &LR;      03-04 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATWORK-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
12 RULES THAT SPELL SUCCESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE STAFFORD  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OVERLAND PARK, Kan. _ The notes for this column were scratched
on the back of a grocery receipt, the only paper scrap handy at a
recent breakfast. Sometimes, good tips come unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   I write about workplace issues for a living. That involves
attending a lot of seminars on management, labor relations,
training and teamwork. I've heard days upon days of ``expert''
advice about how to get hired, get along, get ahead, get rich.
</P>
<P>
   But it was at a recent high school academic honors breakfast
where I heard 12 rules that, if everybody followed them, could
pretty well make all the other success blather unnecessary. The
rules, penned by astronomer and author Carl Sagan, were shared by
Richard Siebs, principal of Blue Valley North High School.
</P>
<P>
   To paraphrase:
</P>
<P>
   1. Be a good ``baloney'' detector.
</P>
<P>
   2. Pick something difficult and learn it well.
</P>
<P>
   3. Don't be afraid to ask dumb questions.
</P>
<P>
   4. Engage in lifelong learning activities and discuss them with
others.
</P>
<P>
   5. Listen.
</P>
<P>
   6. Realize everyone makes mistakes. Be open to criticism and
tolerant of others' errors.
</P>
<P>
   7. Know the planet and take care of it.
</P>
<P>
   8. Don't spend too much time watching television.
</P>
<P>
   9. Learn about your own culture (read the great books, etc.) and
learn about other cultures. Value them all.
</P>
<P>
   10. Be active in the democratic process. (Yes, that means
politics.)
</P>
<P>
   11. Search for the truth.
</P>
<P>
   12. Be compassionate. Don't live solely for yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Siebs added a 13th rule, suggested by his wife:
</P>
<P>
   Find joy in what you do.
</P>
<P>
   Siebs was talking to straight-A students who know something
about commitment and success. He could have congratulated them and
sent them on to their first-hour classes. Instead he prodded them
to commit more.
</P>
<P>
   You might already have dismissed Sagan's ``rules'' as the kind
of inspirational drivel you'd see on a poster with a bird soaring
above the words. But ask yourself _ honestly _ how easy they are to
live by.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout our working lives, we're fed baloney and asked to
swallow it whole. Many of us stick to a comfort zone instead of
trying for a promotion, going back to school or switching careers.
</P>
<P>
   We sit mute in meetings, afraid to ask questions, or we're so
busy pontificating and formulating our own thoughts that we fail to
hear what others are saying. When we do hear something radically
new or different, we are suspicious, if not dismissive.
</P>
<P>
   We cover our backsides and hope blame hits another target, yet
we eagerly pounce on a victim when it wasn't our fault.
</P>
<P>
   We take the expedient way rather than the ecological one. We do
the couch potato act in front of sitcoms instead of reading a book.
We don't bother to vote because we don't know and don't care what's
going on.
</P>
<P>
   We spout our own truths. We look out for ourselves. And, surveys
say, many of us hate our jobs.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't have to be that way. Sagan, who searched the cosmos
for cosmic answers, knew that. He recognized the power of the
individual to search, to choose and to change. That's a profound
lesson, not just for students, but for us all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
