<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 18:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8000 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAM-MACKAY-0305-COX     03-04 0588
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-MACKAY-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ATTN COX EDs: Palm Beach Post Out.
 &HT;    CLINTON NAMES MACKAY LATIN AMERICAN ENVOY
 &HT;    EDs: With optional add that begins at 350 words.
 &HT;    By LARRY LIPMAN 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton Thursday tapped former Florida
Gov. Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay to be his new envoy to Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, 65, fills the post formerly held by Robert ``Mack''
McLarty, Clinton's first chief of staff, who left the
administration last year.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who had been in discussions with the administration for
several weeks, said he learned about the decision Thursday morning
when Clinton called and asked if he would take the job. He said he
expects to remain in the post through the remainder of Clinton's
term until January 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment, which carries a salary of about $125,000 a
year, does not require Senate confirmation. MacKay will plunge into
the job next week when he accompanies Clinton on a trip to Central
America to inspect hurricane damage in Nicaragua, Honduras, El
Salvador, and Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who spearheaded the Summit of the Americas in Miami in
1994 and served on the House Foreign Affairs Committee while he as
in Congress in the 1980s, said he has long been interested in Latin
America and appreciated its importance to Florida and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a very important role and one that will mean a
great deal to (Florida) and the country,'' MacKay said in a
telephone news conference. ``The future of this country, and
particularly (Florida), is very involved with what happens in Latin
America.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sunshine State is particularly sensitive to conditions in
Latin America, MacKay said, noting that adverse conditions there
can spur new waves of migration -- both legal and illegal -- to
Florida's shores. The state is also susceptible to drug trafficking
from Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Florida is on the frontline. We're really the gateway to Latin
America,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   MacKay, who does not speak Spanish, said learning the language
will be one of his first priorities.
</P>
<P>
   Other priorities will be learning the ropes of the new job --
which includes dealing with the U.S. State Department, National
Security Council, the drug czar's office and others.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   He'll also be looking for a place to live in the Washington,
D.C. area. MacKay will be based at the White House, but was unclear
late Thursday whether he would work in the West Wing -- where
McLarty worked -- or next door in the Old Executive Office
Building.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington Post story earlier this week speculated on whether
MacKay would have the same access to Clinton as McLarty. Although
personally not as close to Clinton as McLarty, a childhood friend
of the president, MacKay has had a close political relationship
with him. MacKay headed both of Clinton's presidential campaigns in
Florida, and the president stumped the state for MacKay during last
year's unsuccessful gubernatorial bid. MacKay said he was confident
he would have access to the president when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   One of his most difficult hurdles, MacKay said, will be in
convincing Latin American leaders of United States' interest in
lowering trade barriers in the wake of last year's failure to pass
so-called ``fast track'' trade authority.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hemispheric integration is in all of our interests,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
