<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLEASE! CAN WE END THIS LONG, NATIONAL PEEP SHOW? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED: Monica might have been bearable _ poor, sad little
dope.
</P>
<P>
   But not Walters. We just couldn't stomach Walters, so we passed
up the night's big attraction. In the two-week promotional blitz
that preceded the interview, we'd already seen more than enough.
</P>
<P>
   There in the teasers was Barbara _ mother confessor, grand
inquisitor _ fixing her subject with that wounded-doe stare and
asking, in a voice positively gooey with unctuousness, ``Monica,
are you still in luuuuv with Bill Clinton?''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, lordy, give us a break! Only a peep show like that one could
make Larry Flynt sound classy by comparison. There just is no
extreme of tastelessness to which television will not go to trump
the competition in the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   And there's still the book to look forward to _ on the shelves
any day, if it isn't already.
</P>
<P>
   Then there'll be the movie. Or, wait a minute _ we've had that
movie, haven't we!
</P>
<P>
   Next maybe the Monica pinup calendar.
</P>
<P>
   After that the life-size Monica inflatable toy.
</P>
<P>
   Then the inevitable anniversary pieces in the print media.
``Remembering Impeachment,'' the headlines will read. Year after
year after year.
</P>
<P>
   And meantime, the indefatigable Mr. Starr will plunge on boldly
where no man has gone before, with his fourth or fifth prosecution
of poor Webster Hubbell, and his 10th of Susan McDougal.
</P>
<P>
   Undeterred by misconduct proceedings against him, he will
convene yet another grand jury to examine the malfeasance and
slipshod work of previous grand juries.
</P>
<P>
   Time will have passed. A lot of it.
</P>
<P>
   Lucianne Goldberg will be circulating the manuscript of Jane Doe
No. 37.
</P>
<P>
   And Republican leaders in Congress will be sitting down with the
pundits on the Sunday morning talk shows to try to explain the
electorate's maddening indifference to moral instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't anybody, anybody, understand that the country's
tolerance for this stuff is exhausted? The public appetite for
garbage may be disheartening, but it is not insatiable.
</P>
<P>
   I hope the ratings show that only 35 households nationwide saw
that television abomination, and most of them tuned in only long
enough to see how Monica was wearing her hair and how much new
plastic surgery Barbara was sporting.
</P>
<P>
   And after that, they switched to whichever true-cops show
happened to be on.
</P>
<P>
   I hope the publisher takes a bath on the tell-all book (or
books), and Ken Starr stumbles off finally into the sunset, still
clutching a fistful of unserved subpoenas.
</P>
<P>
   I would wish for Linda Tripp a lifetime spent in a house of
rooms with mirrored walls.
</P>
<P>
   I hope those newspaper readers turned away by the prurience and
sensationalism of the press's coverage will one day forgive and
come back to us.
</P>
<P>
   And for myself and the rest of the journalist tribe, I pray
there'll be no temptation ever to write about this matter again.
Certainly there'll be no need to.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's over. It really is!
</P>
<P>
   Over. Over. Over.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1802EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
