<SLUG> BC-GORBACHEV-SPEECH-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA SMUG ABOUT ``WINNING'' COLD WAR, GORBACHEV SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WARRENSBURG, Mo. _ Mikhail Gorbachev doesn't like hearing
American politicians gloat about ``winning'' the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The boasting threatens to destroy the already fragile
relationship between the United States and his country, he said
Wednesday night at Central Missouri State University.
</P>
<P>
   ``The (Russian) government has been acting on the basis of an
inferiority complex...while America is acting on the basis of a
superiority complex, a winner's complex,'' the former Soviet Union
president said at a press conference before his speech. ``Frankly,
I don't think the American people hold that view, but the
politicians are saying, `We won the Cold War.' This is not a good
complex because it makes for too much arrogance. It makes for an
inability to work with other partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev, who won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1990, received a
gracious welcome from about 7,000 people gathered in the school's
gymnasium. He was brought in as keynote speaker for the
university's Excellence in Governance award ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   University President Ed Elliott won this year's award, which is
given by the students.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gorbachev stuck to a somewhat dry recounting of
how the former Soviet Union, now broken up into independent
nations, came to a better understanding with the United States and
opened up its economy and political system under his watch.
</P>
<P>
   But he also gave a glimpse of the problems in the Soviet Union
today, of the political disintegration, the financial struggles and
the inefficiency that make everyday life a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   And he warned against increasing Americanization of the world,
while also emphasizing that respect of the ``God-given'' diversity
of nations, cultures and ideologies will make the world more
peaceful and productive.
</P>
<P>
   Several Russian exchange students who are studying at William
Jewell College in Liberty made the hourlong trip to Warrensburg to
hear Gorbachev speak.
</P>
<P>
   Natalia Lavrshina, 21, a political science student from St.
Petersburg, Russia, said she had never seen Gorbachev in person.
</P>
<P>
   Gorbachev said young people in both countries will help improve
the relationship between the two former bitter enemies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe in the young people,'' he said. ``I represent the
older generations, and we carry the burden of our old experiences.
It is not easy for us to abandon old dogma and stereotypes....The
young people don't carry the burden of the legacy of the Cold War.
They will bring our world to a different place, a different
relationship between nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Lavrshina agreed, saying that Americans should get to know her
country better, and Russians should try to understand America.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans don't understand Russia. You have your government to
thank for that. They don't want you to understand,'' she said.
``People ask me what I think of America, and I say it's just like
Russia. The political machine is the same _ there are just some
different ideologies.''
</P>
<P>
   Luda Milashenko, 19, an international business student from
Moscow studying at William Jewell, said she was disappointed that
Gorbachev did not talk in depth about Russia's serious problems of
corruption and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't offer any solutions,'' she said. ``He was just
talking about the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But for Gorbachev, the improvement of relations between the two
superpowers in the 1980s holds the secret to bettering the current
relationship, which is challenged by serious economic inequality.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled talking to former President Ronald Reagan about how
average Americans and Russians got along while together, even as
the political leaders were mired in distrust.
</P>
<P>
   He said he told Reagan: ``If we cannot get along, the people
should kick us out. I am happy that President Reagan and I were
able to get along.''
</P>
<P>
   The audience applauded.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
