<SLUG> BC-NEAR-COLLISION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR TRAFFIC CONTROLLERS RECOUNT TENSE MOMENTS OF NEAR-COLLISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OLATHE, Kan. _ As anxious air traffic controllers looked on, two
blips on the radar screen slowly converged, until there was but
one.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve seconds later, as the radar beacon swept around again,
the dot disappeared from the screen.
</P>
<P>
   For about a minute Tuesday morning, the controllers, who had
been unable to make radio contact with two cargo planes heading
close to a collision high over Kansas, could only wonder if they
had just witnessed a midair disaster.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a helpless feeling, a very helpless feeling,'' said
Howard Blankenship, the facility representative for the National
Air Traffic Controllers Association, the union that represents the
controllers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The controllers basically watched these two airplanes come
together,'' he said. ``There was disbelief that something like that
could actually happen. What controllers are trained to do is keep
them apart.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to wait to see,'' said David Bennett, an air
traffic controller at the Kansas City Air Route Traffic Control
Center in Olathe.
</P>
<P>
   No tragedy occurred, but the airplanes came very close. How
close is still being investigated; estimates vary from 100 feet to
more than 2,000 feet.
</P>
<P>
   The National Transportation Safety Board is investigating the
incident, which involved a Federal Express McDonnell Douglas DC-10
traveling from Portland, Ore., to Memphis, Tenn., and a Kitty Hawk
International Lockheed L-1011 traveling from Los Angeles to
Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until we actually do our investigation, we can't really tell
you what happened,'' said Paul Schlamm, a safety board spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, we have a very safe air transport and aviation
system,'' he said. ``Sometimes there are problems, but we make
recommendations to try to avoid those problems in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   About 10:40 a.m. Tuesday, Bennett was notified that two aircraft
were leaving Denver Air Route Traffic Control Center's airspace and
entering the Kansas City center's airspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver did not have communication with them, so that meant
that they were not able to transfer communication to us,'' Bennett
said. ``They called and said: `Hey, these two are coming together.
It could get ugly.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, the planes were about 12 to 15 minutes apart.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Christopher, a Dallas spokesman for Kitty Hawk International
Inc., which is based in Detroit, said Kitty Hawk's aircraft was in
contact with the Denver center and had received instructions to
switch frequencies to talk with the Kansas City center. He said the
pilots attempted to do so but were unable to reach the Kansas City
center.
</P>
<P>
   Aircraft have entered a center's airspace without having contact
with air traffic controllers before. But it is not common, Bennett
said.
</P>
<P>
   It is also rare for two aircraft to lose radio contact in the
same area, let alone two aircraft flying at the same altitude on a
collision path, Blankenship said.
</P>
<P>
   Bennett said, ```There are procedures you do to get a hold of
them, and normally it works.''
</P>
<P>
   So controllers tried the various procedures, including using
alternative communication systems that companies subscribe to,
calling the companies directly to have them alert their planes and
using an emergency frequency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used every means that we had at the time and just were not
able to get ahold of them,'' Bennett said.
</P>
<P>
   When the planes got within three to four minutes of each other,
controllers started moving other planes away from the area so that
if one of the planes established contact, evasive maneuvers could
be taken.
</P>
<P>
   Soon the blips merged into one. Twelve seconds later, the blip
disappeared because the two radar reflections canceled each other
out. The blip didn't return for twelve more seconds. Then there
were two blips again.
</P>
<P>
   The planes' crews immediately contacted controllers wanting to
know why they had almost collided. Controllers explained their
inability to establish radio contact and told the crews to report
back once they landed.
</P>
<P>
   Sally Davenport, spokeswoman for Federal Express Corp. in
Memphis, said, ``We certainly are aware of the incident, but
because it is under investigation presently by the NTSB, we are not
able to provide any additional information or speculate to what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Christopher disputed reports that the aircraft came within 100
feet of each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they did come within 100 feet of each other, the pilots
still would not be able to talk,'' he said. ``The aircraft were
moving about 450 miles per hour, and they are huge airplanes.''
</P>
<P>
   He estimated the planes came within 1,300 to 2,600 feet of each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher said the planes ``weren't supposed to be that close
together, but when they got close together they saw each other and
took evasive action.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
