<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPUTER EFFECTS MAKE `DREAMS' SWEETER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROB LOWMAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Watching ``What Dreams May Come'' is an
uplifting experience. Not so much because the film's story, which
is a modern-day treatment of the Orpheus legend with a new-agey
twist, but because of its stunning special effects that augur some
wondrous cinematic times ahead.
</P>
<P>
   It's unfortunate that ``Dreams,'' which is being released on
video Tuesday, doesn't match its visual inventiveness. Written by
Ron Bass, who won an Oscar for ``Rain Man,'' ``Dreams'' follows
Chris (Robin Williams), a doctor, into the afterlife when he is
killed in a car crash while rushing home to his wife, Annie
(Annabella Sciorra).
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that, if you're deserving, the afterlife is pretty
much what you imagine it to be. In Chris' case, he finds himself in
a world that is much like his wife's paintings, slightly
impressionistic, colorful and romantic.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Chris maneuver through this fantastic artistic
landscape is eye-opening, as he squishes through daubs of paint and
then soars above it.
</P>
<P>
   He is helped by a guide, Albert (Cuba Gooding Jr.), who had been
Chris' mentor but takes on the guise of a younger version of
himself. Though in a form of heaven, all's not well with Chris. A
few years before he died, his two children were killed in an auto
accident, leaving his wife in a depression she had not recovered
from. Chris now wants to see his children but finds he can only see
them when the time is right. In the meantime, his wife _ unable to
face life without Chris, kills herself and is trapped in a
netherworld as a lost soul. When Chris finds out, he tries to
rescue her, traveling through hell with another guide (Max Von
Sydow).
</P>
<P>
   ``Dreams'' has its flaws _ particularly the pacing _ and the
Williams-Sciorra chemistry doesn't light any fires, though it does
seem sincere. At times, even the special-effect scenes are played
like they are there to wow you rather than being integrated with
the plot.
</P>
<P>
   The new-age feel to the questions of heaven and hell might be
off-putting to some, but ``Dreams'' should be commended for being
one of the first films to use the major advances in
computer-generated images (CGI) for something other than destroying
the world or building some dire futuristic universe. And even if
you have reservations about the story, it's provocative enough to
generate some discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Until you get your HDTV and DVD player, some of those special
effects are not going to match the film's big-screen visuals
(``Dreams'' comes out on DVD in May, by the way), but it still
offers enough of a taste to pique your interest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
DISNEY DOCUMENTARY: a few years ago, disney released the
documentary ``frank and Ollie'' about two of the studios' legendary
animators. Not only were Frank Thomas and Ollie Johnson co-workers
on such animated classics as ``Snow White and the Seven Drawfs,
``Pinocchio,'' ``Bambi,'' ``Peter Pan,'' Lady &AMP; the Tramp,
``Cinderella'' and ``The Jungle Book,'' the duo were also neighbors
for years.
</P>
<P>
   Set to be released on video Tuesday, the critically acclaimed
documentary uses film clips and interviews to tell the wonderful
story of these two men as well as tell the story of the Disney
animation empire, which they helped create.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Tuesday, Disney is running out another of its classic
animated films on video. This time it's `101 Dalmatians.'' The 1961
film will only be on store shelves for _ you guessed it _ 101 days.
sounds like a trick of Cruella de Vil. The digitally remastered,
restored video also includes a 90-second animated short featuring
Pluto called ``Street Cleaner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
