<P>
   CHURCHFIRES _ Whatever happened to all that church fire money?
The Rev. Henry Lyons was accused of depositing at least $60,000
into his personal checking account. A South Carolina pastor who
prayed with President Clinton over the fires was accused by his
congregation of misappropriating some of it. But a lot of the
money, indeed, rebuilt churches. Meanwhile, the National Task Force
on Church Fires says the number of church fires has steadily
declined the past two years. We check in with the task force, the
ADL and various other organizations that made the burning of black
churches a cause. A status report. (Manuel/Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN _ Gov. G.W. Bush heads to Dallas for a Friday
fundraiser for U.S. Rep. Jay Dickey of Arkansas, Bill Clinton's
hometown congressman. Also, the budding Bush presidential campaign
is hiring Maria Cino as its political director. Cino headed the
National Republican Congressional Committee in 1994 when the GOP
took control of the House for the first time in 40 years. (Herman,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   CARLOS-MUMMIES _ The Carlos Museum has completed raising the $2
million needed to purchase mummies for a new exhibit. It continues
to raise funds for support, conservation and other related costs,
and expects the mummies to arrive in May. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 7.
</P>
<P>
   GA-READING-SCORES _ The latest reading scores for Georgia point
to a widespread problem, not one limited to children with learning
disabilities or those in low-performing schools. A breakdown of the
National Assessment of Education Progress scores should show how
few students are reading at proficient and advanced levels in
Georgia. We talk to parents, students, teachers and reading
specialists about what's wrong with our reading instruction, and
how these weaknesses effect other aspects of a child's life --
self-control, interest in school, and aspirations for college and
career. Students and parents will come from a local after-school
Reading Challenge program. Experts will include professors at
Georgia State and David Denton of the Southern Regional Education
Board. (Cumming, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
