<HEADER>
A8022 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-FAMILY-1STLE     03-04 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FAMILY-1STLEDE-$ADV07 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CONGRESS MEMBERS STRUGGLE TO BALANCE DUTIES AND FAMILY
 &HT;    Eds: Corrects name to John Covey sted Thomas Coven in first two
grafs after trim advisory.
 &HT;    780&AMP;add. For release Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In order to be elected, members of Congress must
promise to tirelessly serve their districts. They also must
demonstrate their devotion to family.
</P>
<P>
   Living up to both can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job is becoming more demanding all the time,'' said Rep.
Chet Edwards, D-Texas, who recalls when Congress met only six
months a year, allowing lawmakers to spend a great deal of time
working in their home communities.
</P>
<P>
   Things have changed. The congressional schedule is longer and
more unpredictable, leaving lawmakers constantly running in and out
of airports. The long hours, the stress of political life and the
grueling travel schedule can strain families.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of politicians who glow in the limelight while
their children and families are dying in the shadows,'' said
Edwards. ``That is one mistake I will never make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is much too short to spend four or five days a week
regularly away from your children and spouse,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like many political families, Edwards and his wife, Lea Ann,
decided to raise their two children, John Thomas, 3, and Garrison,
1, in their home district. As a result, John Thomas made about 20
airplane trips before his first birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, the couple decided to move the family from Waco to the
national capital area _ an option often taken by senators, who
serve six years rather than two for House members.
</P>
<P>
   One reason behind the Edwards' decision is the House schedule,
which is already intense and may grow longer.
</P>
<P>
   Many members say the schedule is not ``family friendly,'' with
morning hearings, votes starting at midday and sometimes ending
long after a child's bedtime.
</P>
<P>
   Some still talk about the stressful year of 1995, when
Republican efforts to pass the party's ``family-friendly'' Contract
With America took an ironic toll on their personal life. At least
six 1994 freshmen ended up with broken marriages by 1996, and some
say the long hours and last-minute schedule changes played a big
part.
</P>
<P>
   Before deciding to resign from Congress, incoming Speaker Bob
Livingston proposed a five-day-a-week House schedule instead of the
current practice of conducting most business from Tuesday through
Thursday. The proposal, which members say is still under
consideration, would make it impossible for members to fly home to
work in their districts for half the week.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say the five-day schedule would make House service
more predictable and allow more weeks off during the year.
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Robert Wexler, D-Fla., said it would be a ``disaster''
for members with families in their districts.
</P>
<P>
   Wexler spent the first few months of his first term living in
Washington while his wife and three children lived in Boca Raton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't do it,'' he said. ``It was extremely hard. I
cannot tell you how many times at 2, 3, 4 in the night I was on the
phone with my wife because she was up with the baby. In the most
perfect of marriages, it creates strain.''
</P>
<P>
   Wexler moved his family to the capital area more than a year
ago. ``That's not so easy either,'' he said. The Wexlers left both
sets of grandparents and a network of community support in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cynthia McKinney, who is divorced, commutes to Decatur,
Ga., at least twice a week. Her 13-year-old son Coy lives in
Georgia and stays with McKinney's parents when she is in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said the choice of letting Coy grow up in Georgia
provides ``normalcy'' and a certain ``anonymity,'' while the
capital area is less than an ideal environment for raising
children.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, she said, ``everybody is the child of somebody
important. The sense of self-importance, I believe, gets blown way
out of proportion and you certainly don't want your children to get
infected with that disease.''
</P>
<P>
   But McKinney said living part-time away from her son is not
easy. About a month ago, she was reading some of her son's school
essays and realized her congressional schedule had a
``devastating'' impact on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that the job took his Mom away from him,'' she said.
``I felt terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said the essay prompted her to be even more dedicated
to incorporating her son's life into her schedule and to improve
communication between them.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to help his colleagues avoid such pitfalls, Rep. Jack
Kingston, R-Ga., recently wrote an article in The Hill, a weekly
political newspaper, titled ``15 Ways to Keep your Family, Sanity
and Inner Harmony.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingston advised lawmakers not to confuse their spouse with
their staff. ``Remember, your staff works for you _ your spouse
doesn't. You've already screwed up (your spouse's) life _ don't add
insult to injury.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Politicians are not alone in their growing concern about
balancing family life and work.
</P>
<P>
   John Covey and his brother Stephen have made millions of dollars
teaching people how to find such balance in their lives. Stephen
Covey is the author of ``The 7 Habits of Highly Effective People,''
which has sold more than 10 million copies worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   John Covey, who has developed and edited a new book about
``Highly Effective Families,'' gave a two-hour seminar at a
Democratic congressional retreat in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message hit them right in the bread basket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Covey told lawmakers to ``put the big rocks'' into their busy
schedules. The big rocks included one-on-one time with their spouse
and children and important family dates such as birthdays, planned
vacations and family traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Covey said politics has become more difficult in an age of
``information overload.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The political pressures are incredible,'' he said. ``The boss
is not only in the political arena, but you've got the media that
are just pushing'' and watching ``for any public or private
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a multiple stress for these people,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, who said he has taken a lot of Covey's advice to heart,
said that after 16 years in politics, he knows the world doesn't
revolve around his political career.
</P>
<P>
   ``The democracy will go on without Chet Edwards, but those
children only have one father,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
