<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8032 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-     03-04 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION FOR CLIFF NOTES  
 A JACKBOOT TO ART 
DIMMING STAR POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ Neither a borrower nor a lender be. ...
Whateverrrrrrr!
</P>
<P>
   Shakespeare has always enjoyed at least modest popularity in
Hollywood, with one movie studio or another taking a crack at his
plays in the form of faithful revivals or loose interpretations.
</P>
<P>
   But rarely has there been as big a rush as this year, when
audiences will get a chance to see works ranging from ``Titus
Andronicus,'' one of Shakespeare's least-known plays, to yet
another modernization of ``The Taming of the Shrew,'' this time
called ``Ten Things I Hate About You,'' set in a high school and
geared toward teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Six Shakespearean productions are scheduled to hit theaters
within the next year, three of them starring Julia Stiles and all
hoping to take advantage of the popularity of ``Shakespeare in
Love,'' a romantic fantasy that has little to do with the writer's
plays or life but has received 13 Academy Award nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Yet nearly everyone in Hollywood considers Shakespeare a box
office liability, at least if audiences get the impression they
will have to listen to long, opaque soliloquies in antiquated
English.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is how do we overcome it, because there is audience
resistance,'' said Mark Gill, president of the West Coast
operations of Miramax Films, the Disney unit that is distributing
three of the new Shakespeare movies. ``The more contemporary they
are, the better the chance they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Gil Junger, the director of ``Ten Things I Hate About You,''
said he had also been skeptical at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate reaction was, a teen-ager is just not going to be
interested,'' said Junger, until now a director for television,
including the episode in which Ellen DeGeneres declared she was a
lesbian on her sitcom, ``Ellen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just didn't want to do a Shakespeare movie because of the
commercial concerns,'' he said. ``But then I read the script and I
thought it was a great story. Then I said, `Of course, it's a great
story. It's Shakespeare.'''
</P>
<P>
   The film is scheduled to be released on March 31. In May, it
will be followed by ``A Midsummer Night's Dream,'' starring Calista
Flockhart, Kevin Kline and Michelle Pfeiffer. A version of
``Othello,'' also set in a high school and called ``O,'' again with
Ms. Stiles, is scheduled for an October release.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the year, there will be ``Titus Andronicus,'' directed
by Julie Taymor and starring Anthony Hopkins and Jessica Lange.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, early next year there will be a contemporary
version of ``Hamlet,'' set in New York, starring Ethan Hawke, Bill
Murray and Ms. Stiles. That will be followed by a new version of
``Love's Labour's Lost,'' with Kenneth Branagh, Alicia Silverstone
and Nathan Lane, set in the 1930s and made with music by Cole
Porter, George Gershwin and Jerome Kern.
</P>
<P>
   ``It all goes in cycles,'' Junger said. ``This may be over in a
year.''
</P>
<P>
   A Jackboot to Art
</P>
<P>
   Art, it is often said, transcends politics. ``The Harmonists''
is a cautionary tale about the risks of believing too much in that
old saw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Harmonists,'' which opens on March 12, is a German movie
about an extremely successful a cappella singing group in the 1930s
whose members, like many Germans of the day, believed that the
Nazis might break a few windows, and even a few laws, but that they
would not interfere with the popular arts.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which has been quite successful in Germany, examines
how wrong they were.
</P>
<P>
   The film is based on the true story of the Comedian Harmonists,
a popular singing group that was modeled on the American group the
Revellers. A play, ``Band in Berlin,'' scheduled to open in New
York on Sunday, is also based on the group's experience.
</P>
<P>
   The German group was formed in 1927 by Harry Frommermann, a
young man in love with music and eager to capture the upbeat
sassiness of the day. The group had six members, three Jewish. The
movie ends with the singers' forced dissolution in 1934, each one
shocked by the Nazis' belligerence, none yet aware of the extent of
their evil.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the movie has faced some criticism for not heavily
emphasizing the Holocaust, said Heino Ferch , the German actor who
plays Roman Cycowski, a Polish opera singer who was one of the
Jewish band members.
</P>
<P>
   Ferch, a former gymnast and acrobat, said the movie, while
ending on a note of foreboding, gives no direct hint of the
Holocaust. Some people, he said, had suggested the movie pulled its
punches in that respect.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, the film is stronger because it shows how people
only slowly woke up to the Nazis' real agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't necessary in a movie like this to go hard on the
Holocaust itself,'' Ferch said. ``It goes deeper in your heart, I
think, because you can see how these people reacted and their
denial. They were Jews, but they thought they were so popular, no
one would attack them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nazis began a crusade against what they considered Jewish
art or degenerate art, and banished or killed artists in many
fields.
</P>
<P>
   But the movie keeps its gaze tightly focused on the hopes,
dreams and personal lives of the Comedian Harmonists.
</P>
<P>
   In one striking scene, Ferch's character says he will marry his
girlfriend only if she converts to Judaism. She does, and the
wedding scene, shot in a synagogue in Prague, is a joyous occasion
filled with music and dancing, a stark counterpoint to the fate of
the group and millions of Jews across Europe.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Dimming Star Power
</P>
<P>
   S. Abraham Ravid, a business professor at Rutgers University and
New York University, has produced a fairly dense academic paper
whose conclusions are supported with entries like ``mean of
dependent variable,'' ``adjusted R-squared'' and ``F-statistic.''
</P>
<P>
   The paper might not be of much interest outside academia except
that it appears to disprove several cherished theories about what
makes a movie profitable.
</P>
<P>
   By examining a random sampling of nearly 200 movies, Ravid said
he found that lower-budget movies tended to be more profitable than
big-budget pictures, even though they often generated less revenue;
movies with unknowns or lesser-known actors tended to be more
profitable than star-driven films; there was no statistical
correlation between the strength of reviews and profitability, but
that there was a relationship between the mere number of reviews,
no matter how positive, and profitability, and the strongest
correlation for profitability was a movie's having a G or PG
rating.
</P>
<P>
   And, he added, sequels tended to be more profitable than the
average movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ravid, a lifelong film buff and a former radio journalist in
Israel, said the conclusions in his paper, ``Information,
Blockbusters and Stars: A Study of the Film Industry,'' which is
scheduled to appear in The Journal of Business later this year,
surprised him. He said that he had undertaken the study to
understand the business rationale of paying top dollar for
Hollywood stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to know why would you hire an expensive star right up
front for a movie,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The figures contradicted much of the Hollywood wisdom regarding
star power, he said. They also conflicted with some recent studies
that have purported to show that stars like Mel Gibson and Michelle
Pfeiffer have been the biggest profit generators.
</P>
<P>
   Among the reasons his study countered popular wisdom, he said,
was that he focused on the profitability of movies, not just their
box office revenues, and that, when looking at historical data on
older movies, he adjusted the revenues and profits for inflation,
so that direct comparisons could be made with current movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was actually very much rooting for the stars in my
analysis,'' Ravid said. ``Once I saw which way the results were
going, I tried several different definitions of a star and I was
wondering why it wasn't working out. But stars are not what they
seem to be. They often bring in higher revenues, but the
profitability is smaller.''
</P>
<P>
   Why would the studios persist in paying up to $20 million to get
a major star in a movie if such films rarely generate big returns?
</P>
<P>
   ``I can only speculate, but in an atmosphere of great
uncertainty, people try to play it safe,'' Ravid said. ``They can
say everyone else is doing it. That's my best interpretation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
