</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINE-COMPETITION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS INTRODUCE AIRLINE COMPETITION LEGISLATION. 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (EDs: FILED in ``f'' and ``w'' categories)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JENNIFER CORBETT DOOREN  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A bill aimed at boosting airline competition by
lifting federal limits on the number of hourly landings and
takeoffs at airports in Chicago and New York City was introduced in
the House Thursday by a bipartisan group of lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Bud Shuster, R-Pa., chairman of the House Transportation
Committee, said removing the limits would ``immediately increase
competition in the airline industry'' by allowing additional
flights at three of the nation's busiest airports. Shuster's
committee is scheduled to vote on the legislation next week.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to constituents' complaints about the cost of flying
to and from small and medium-sized cities and about the quality of
airline service, lawmakers have recently introduced several bills
dealing with both issues.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's measure, which is supported by more than 120 lawmakers
from both parties, would eliminate so-called slots at Chicago's
O'Hare and New York's Kennedy and LaGuardia airports by next March
1. An additional three flights a day would be added at Washington,
D.C.'s Ronald Reagan National Airport. The slot system, which
refers to the number of daily landings and takeoffs, was
implemented at the four airports in 1968 to reduce delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``All airlines, big and small, new or old, will now be able to
serve Chicago O'Hare, or New York's LaGuardia and Kennedy,'' said
Rep. William Lipinski, D-Ill., one of the bill's authors.
</P>
<P>
   Lipinski said he believes that eliminating the slots will make
airlines more willing to serve small- and medium-sized cities
without having to worry about using ``their precious few slots (at
the four big airports) on the most profitable routes.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear how many additional flights would be allowed at
O'Hare, Kennedy and LaGuardia airports. House Transportation
Committee staffers said the three airports have capacity to add
flights.
</P>
<P>
   At O'Hare 155 landings and takeoffs are currently allowed per
hour, 68 are allowed at LaGuardia and 60 at Reagan National. At
Kennedy Airport 88 hourly landings and takeoffs are allowed between
3 p.m. and 8 p.m. Under the House bill, the Federal Aviation
Administration would still set hourly limits based on the number of
flights air-traffic controllers can safely handle.
</P>
<P>
   A similar Senate bill, which was approved last month by the
Commerce Committee, would not eliminate the slot system but would
add 15 flights a day at O'Hare and 24 flights at Reagan National.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would add an unspecified number at Kennedy and
LaGuardia by giving the Department of Transportation greater
authority to grant exemptions to the slot rule. The DOT would also
be required to give exemptions to airlines operating 30- to 50-seat
regional jets that serve small- and medium-sized cities.
</P>
<P>
   The House bill would also require so-called hub airports, in
which a large carrier often controls a majority of gates, to
increase competition in order to receive additional federal funds.
Delta Airlines, for example, controls 80 percent of the market in
Atlanta while Northwest controls 79 percent of the gates in its hub
airports of Minneapolis and Detroit, according the House
Transportation Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Shuster's airline competition legislation would authorize more
funds for air traffic control facilities, airport security programs
and a general airport improvement program.
</P>
<P>
   Similar legislation was introduced in both houses last year. But
lawmakers representing districts near the slot-controlled airports
succeeded in killing it. Last month the new House Speaker, Dennis
Hastert, R-Ill., said he supports airline competition legislation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
