<HEADER>
A8052 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-REORG-475&AMP;A     03-04 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-REORG-475&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRADE GROUP PROPOSES BREAKING UP MICROSOFT, BUT NOT WINDOWS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The nation's largest software-industry trade group has warned
the government not to impose sanctions on Microsoft that could
``fracture'' the role of the company's Windows operating system as
an industry standard, if the government wins its antitrust suit
against the Microsoft Corp.
</P>
<P>
   But the report by the Software and Information Industry
Association, which was presented to the Justice Department two
weeks ago, does recommend that the government look seriously at
breaking up Microsoft as a cure for what the report regards as the
lack of competition in the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   The report was confidential, though there are now more than 100
copies in the hands of industry executives, consultants and
academics, all of whom signed nondisclosure agreements. The
existence of the report and that it suggested options to
restructure Microsoft was reported Thursday in The Wall Street
Journal.
</P>
<P>
   The group's paper suggests that the preferred restructuring
option, said an industry executive who had read the report, is a
break-up of Microsoft into three companies. The first of the trio
of stand-alone companies would get Microsoft's operating systems
business, including Windows, Windows CE and Windows NT.
</P>
<P>
   The second would get its software applications, which include
its Word, Excel and Powerpoint productivity programs. The third
would get the Internet media and commerce businesses, ranging from
its Slate online magazine to its Expedia travel site.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this kind of break-up was ``an attractive
alternative,'' the executive said, was that it would alter
Microsoft's current relations with the software industry.
</P>
<P>
   At present, companies that compete with Microsoft in the
applications business also badly need the cooperation of Microsoft
to share its operating system technology if their products are to
run smoothly on Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the break-up into separate businesses would also leave the
Windows operating system in the hands of one company. The report
states that ``antitrust remedies should not interfere with an
apparent consumer preference for an OS standard,'' according to
people who have read the report.
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, the 40-page report focuses on the balanced
assessment of various remedial options instead of advocacy. It is
intended mainly as a way of giving the Justice Department and 19
states suing Microsoft the industry's perspective on what steps
seem workable.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft, which is a member of the trade group, objected to the
recent report _ as it has to previous position papers by the group
that have said curbing Microsoft's power would result in a
healthier software industry. A Microsoft spokesman said the
``discussion paper'' was largely the work of its rivals within the
trade organization, including Sun Microsystems and the Netscape
Communications Corp., and did not represent the views of the
software industry overall.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The report begins with seven broad principles. These include
avoiding ``punitive remedies'' and ensuring that remedies result in
``equitable access to operating system information'' and ``minimize
unnecessary dislocations to equity markets, shareholders and
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   The report proceeds to assess 10 conduct remedies ranging from
prohibitions on bundling products and predatory pricing to
compulsory licensing of the Windows programming code. Finally, it
looks at the structural options.
</P>
<P>
   The group's conclusion, however, that it would be harmful to
allow several companies to compete with each other as Windows
suppliers does raise questions about two widely discussed remedies.
</P>
<P>
   The first such proposal is to break Microsoft into three to five
companies, each starting with the basic code for Windows and
Microsoft's other products. The proposed clone companies have
become known as the ``baby Bills,'' a reference to Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman.
</P>
<P>
   A similar recommendation, favored by advisers to the states,
calls for an auction of the Windows programming code and the
Windows brand name to three to five companies. The reasoning behind
the auction proposal is that the monopoly position of Windows _ and
its potential for the abuse of market power _ could be broken up
without breaking up Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   But one person who has read the report said it cautioned that
``deliberately fracturing'' the Windows standard could do more harm
than good by forcing consumers and software developers to grapple
with the confusion and cost of a handful of incompatible operating
systems.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
