<HEADER>
A8054 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-SWEEPS-BOS &LR;      03-04 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SWEEPS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY SWEEPS PUNCH MEETS ABC'S EXPECTATIONS _ AND MORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DON AUCOIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky's carefully orchestrated campaign to cash in on
her notoriety is off to a blockbuster beginning.
</P>
<P>
   An average audience of 48.5 million Americans were planted in
front of their TV sets on Wednesday night as President Clinton's
ex-paramour bared her soul to Barbara Walters on ABC's ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, ABC estimated that 74 million viewers tuned in for at
least part of the interview, which the network claimed makes it the
most-watched ``news program'' ever televised by a single network.
As a launching pad for her new book, ``Monica's Story,'' Lewinsky
could scarcely have hoped for better. That is, of course, if people
liked the person they saw on TV and want to learn more about her _
a thoroughly open question.
</P>
<P>
   There were certainly no symptoms of Monica fatigue in Boston,
where more than half of those watching TV from 9 to 11 p.m.
Wednesday were tuned to the interview. In fact, ratings were higher
in the Boston viewing area _ which extends north to Concord, N.H.,
and west to Amherst in western Massachusetts _ than in any other TV
market in the country except Philadelphia. Nationally, nearly half
the TV sets in use were tuned to the ABC interview.
</P>
<P>
   So why the continued interest in a story whose bathos-filled
details have been endlessly rehashed for more than a year? In the
view of TV historian Steven Stark, the interviewer was as much of a
draw as her subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Monica-meets-Barbara Walters. If it had been Monica and
Mike Wallace, or Monica and Diane Sawyer, it wouldn't have been as
big a deal,'' said Stark. ``Barbara Walters is the defining force
in television news of the past 50 years. . . . She can always be
counted on to ask the questions that are on everybody's minds at
home, but most journalists would never ask.''
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Daniloff, director of the Northeastern University
School of Journalism, agreed that Walters handled the interview
with her usual skill, but said that doesn't diminish the fact that
Lewinsky was using it to ``push her book.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She used the interview very well for her purposes,'' said
Daniloff. ``She has become very practiced; I assume that is a
result of the many interrogations she has been through. She
prepared a lot of her answers, until that time she broke down,
which was for me the most genuine and least rehearsed part of the
interview.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniloff said the ``invasion of privacy'' issues raised by the
interview made him queasy, but added: ``Clinton probably deserves
this. It's part of his punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   The other networks are feeling Clinton's pain: Thanks to
Lewinsky, ABC drew more than three times as many viewers on
Wednesday night as runner-up NBC did. The Lewinsky interview, which
aired as a two-hour ``20/20'' special on the last night of the
February ratings sweeps period, ranks as the second-highest program
of the 1998-99 television season, behind only the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The average audience of 48.5 million viewers for Lewinsky far
outpaced the audience for Bill and Hillary Clinton in their 1992
``60 Minutes'' confessional; that drew only 34 million viewers even
though it aired right after the Super Bowl. Among celebrity
interviews this decade, it appears that only Oprah Winfrey's 1993
conversation with Michael Jackson on ABC, with 62 million viewers,
has racked up higher ratings than Lewinsky/Walters did, according
to Nielsen Media Research.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, Lewinsky's ratings pale next to those of the
top-rated entertainment programs of all time. For instance, the
finale of ``M-A-S-H'' drew an average of 106 million viewers, the
``Cheers'' finale pulled in 80 million viewers, and the last
episode of ``Seinfeld'' was watched by 76 million.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when entertainment programs are factored in, the
Lewinsky interview does not even crack the top 100-rated programs
of television history.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not likely to trouble ABC or its affiliates as they
bask in the satisfaction of Lewinsky's lofty numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally, the interview got a 33.4 rating and a 48 audience
share. Such numbers are less and less common in an era when viewers
have dozens of cable channels to choose from on any given night.
Even when major news events occur, such as the O. J. Simpson
verdict or the death of Princess Diana, the audience is diffused
among many broadcast and cable channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rare that a network has a monopoly on an event,'' said
Stark, likening the Lewinsky interview to such network-exclusive
events as the Olympics or the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that the Lewinsky interview contained the
drama of either, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like any event, it probably didn't live up to the
expectations,'' said Stark. ``Monica Lewinsky's is not an earned
celebrity. . . . She's not terribly insightful. She really doesn't
have that much to say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
