<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0308 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 18:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CARS-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      03-04 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CARS-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NEW WAVE OF EUROPEANS IS SITTING TALL ON THE ROAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By WILLIAM DIEM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The sea change in the North American auto market in
favor of pickups, sport utilities and minivans is being reflected
in Europe, where vehicles are being designed with more spacious
interiors and higher seating. At major shows like the Geneva Motor
Show, which opens next week, it is clear that the European market
is moving from sedans and hatchbacks to a minivan-like shape known
as monospace. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   According to Georges Douin, vice president for product design at
Renault, traditional sedans and hatchbacks held 85 percent of the
European market in 1990 but fell to 70 percent in 1990. He expects
them to drop to 55 percent in 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most emblematic of the shift is Renault's Megane Scenic,
a compact five-seat minivan. It arrived in force in 1997, and
275,000 Scenics were sold last year _ more than the combined sales
of the Megane hatchback, sedan and convertible models. The Scenic
made Megane the No. 2 nameplate in Western Europe after
Volkswagen's Golf. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The compact minivan niche hardly existed in the region before
the Scenic. But last year, in the passenger car market of the 17
countries of Western Europe, the Scenic's compact minivan segment
grew to 3 percent. ``With all the product introductions, we expect
that by next year that segment will be 6 percent,'' said Colin
Couchman, an auto analyst at Standard &AMP; Poor's DRI in London. ``And
it could really take off. People talk about it being the new
hatchback. Hatchbacks didn't exist until late 1970s, and they
replaced the sedan as the basic car.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not far behind the Scenic in influence is the Mercedes-Benz
A-Class, a luxury monospace in a class by itself. DaimlerChrysler
says the A-Class competes for the same customers who consider
buying the Golf, a traditional hatchback. The A-Class sold nearly
120,000 vehicles in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lump the A-Class in a segment with the Scenic,'' said Andrew
Blair-Smith, an auto analyst with Commerzbank in Frankfurt,
Germany. ``Something between a people mover and a car. It's not the
same, but it's not a million miles away in terms of the flexibility
of interior space.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This year, two new compact minivans already have arrived: the
Mitsubishi Space Star, which is built in the Netherlands with
Volvo, and the droll-looking Fiat Multipla, with its two rows of
three seats. Sales start in April for the Opel/Vauxhall Zafira,
with its seven-seat option. By the end of the year, the Citroen
Picasso, a close copy of the Scenic, also will arrive. VW and Ford
are expected to introduce competitors later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The American contribution to monospace is DaimlerChrysler's PT
Cruiser, which arrives in Europe in summer 2000. When potential
customers were shown the car in Europe, the hot-rod panel van was
better received than in the United States, said Chris Theodore, a
former Chrysler vice president who is now with Ford Motor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The fascination with higher seating is strikingly evident in
another DaimlerChrysler car, the Smart. Some 20,000 Smarts were
sold in nine European countries in 1998, and DaimlerChrysler
expects to sell 100,000 this year.
</P>
<P>
   The miniature city car, which seats two, was designed for easy
parking. It is only 7 feet 4 inches long, but proportionally
speaking, it's a skyscraper at 4 feet 11 inches high. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In tests of high-speed maneuverability in 1997, the Smart tipped
over. The Mercedes A-Class, which also is relatively high for its
length, failed a similar test just weeks before, and Daimler did
not want to take any chances with small cars for which safety would
always be a question.
</P>
<P>
   Daimler halted delivery of the A-Class and delayed introduction
of the Smart six months, until October 1998. Engineers installed,
among other measures, electronic anti-skid devices that monitor the
wheels and selectively apply brakes.
</P>
<P>
   In North America, the sport utility craze reflects a Wild West
mentality, Peter Horberry, the chief designer at Volvo, said in an
interview at the Detroit auto show in January. ``It's a progression
from the covered wagon,'' he added. ``The driver sitting high up
there, all his horses in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   The European approach is gentler. BMW's new X5 sport activity
vehicle was designed in the United States but developed in Germany,
where engineers and designers insisted on carlike refinements. ``I
wanted it raw and strong, more out there, not too smooth and
politically correct,'' said Chris Chapman, its American designer. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Germans, however, insisted on changes. For example, Chapman
wanted the C-pillar, the sheet metal behind the rear door, painted
in body colors because that is a visual design cue of trucklike
sport utilities. But body color on the C-pillar would have diverged
from a design cue shared by all BMW sedans; they are designed and
painted so that the side windows appear to be one large opening.
The Germans won.
</P>
<P>
   The X5 is built in South Carolina, and North America is seen as
its primary market, but it will be sold in Europe as well. Europe's
compact minivans, however, are not scheduled to be exported to
North America nor are the Smart and A-Class.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Europeans remain famous for low-slung sports cars
like Ferrari and conservative luxury vehicles like the
Mercedes-Benz S-Class, but a shift _ even at the upper end of the
market _ seems evident. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renault is considered a European trend-setter. It introduced the
full-size minivan in Europe in 1983, about the same time Chrysler
introduced the Voyager in the United States. It introduced the
Twingo, a little monospace that now has competitors like the Ford
Ka. It invented the Scenic, and now it is trying to define the new
shape of luxury with the Avantime, a concept vehicle that will be
introduced to the public in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
   Renault calls its new shape the coupespace, a marriage of a
sporty coupe and a family minivan. The two-door vehicle with a
glass roof and four seats is expected to hit the showrooms in
spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is becoming less conventional,'' said Douin of
Renault. ``This shift away from classic cars will be to the
advantage of station wagons, four-by-fours and mid- and top-range
monospace designs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
