<HEADER>
A8072 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      03-04 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALL STREET'S TURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Now that 900 women have rushed forward to complain
officially about job discrimination at Merrill Lynch, gender bias
on Wall Street is no longer the dirty little secret of high
finance.
</P>
<P>
   The unexpectedly large number of women who filed their claims as
part of a class action lawsuit settlement against the huge
securities firm has shaken an elite, closed world. Tom Wolfe
sarcastically described that world in his best-selling ``Bonfire of
the Vanities'' as peopled with highly flawed ``masters of the
universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill Lynch is a brokerage giant, with 715 offices nationwide.
Since 1990, the percentage of female brokers it employs has
remained a pitiful 15 percent, highly suggestive of a silent quota
system.
</P>
<P>
   This lawsuit is going to cost Merrill Lynch a great deal of
money in compensatory payments. More importantly, it may finally
provoke substantive changes in the male culture that controls the
brokerage establishment.
</P>
<P>
   If you have ever watched a televised scene on the stock market
floor, you understand the problem. Virtually all the participants
are male. Yet investors are not exclusively male. Working women
with their own incomes increasingly play the market too. Money is
gender-free, and the brokers with whom it is entrusted should be
too.
</P>
<P>
   The revolution began brewing last year when a similar case was
settled involving job bias at Smith Barney (now Salomon Smith
Barney). It exposed for the first time Wall Street's ignorance of
the usefulness of employee diversity, which most major corporations
in other fields have long ago acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   Although women now account for roughly half of the securities
industry work force, few rise to the top jobs or earn the highest
incomes. The lawsuits indicate that this gender imbalance is not
the result of inferior female brainpower but systematic practices
that favor males with choice account assignments, higher salaries,
better management training opportunities and an old-boy network
that promotes its buddies.
</P>
<P>
   The thinking that produced this disparity centers on the
outdated stereotypical notion that men make great financial deals
while playing golf, but women would rather be home with their
babies than dealing with clients. Strangely, this attitude applies
to all women of all ages, whether they have babies or not.
</P>
<P>
   Women were told they didn't need salaries or client
opportunities equal to men's because they had husbands who could
support them _ and if they didn't have one, they should get one.
There was also the strong suggestion that money is a man's affair
and women simply can't add and subtract.
</P>
<P>
   The overdue assault on Wall Street elevates the struggle for
equal rights in the workplace to a new, higher level. We are truly
talking about the nuances of a sophisticated glass ceiling here,
not just equal pay on the assembly line. A successful broker can
earn $200,000 a year or more and bring in $2 million or more in
annual income to the firm.
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of elitist issue from which only a privileged,
highly specialized few can benefit and with which not all women may
be eager to make common cause. Yet it is just as elementary to
gender equality as a more basic crusade for equal pay for
equivalent work currently being waged nationally by President
Clinton, organized labor and women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   The president called attention to the new campaign in his State
of the Union address, asking for more enforcement teeth in the
current equal pay laws. He got a standing ovation from both
Democrats and Republicans, hinting that legislation that gets
serious about ending wage discrimination for work of comparable
character may actually pass Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Despite decades of progress, women still tend to be clumped in
lower-paying, female-dominated jobs and earn, on average, 74
percent of the wages paid to men. The AFL-CIO, which has mounted a
nationwide campaign to pass comparable-worth bills in 24 states,
released a study showing that the average working family loses more
than $4,000 a year to the gender wage gap.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court will soon weigh in on the subject of job
discrimination, deciding how far it is legally permissible to
financially punish guilty employers. The high bench heard arguments
this week on the standards for granting punitive damages _ which
are the most effective way to make the bad guys really take notice.
</P>
<P>
   Gender pay equity for jobs that are similar but not exactly
alike can be tricky and distorted by political influence on both
sides. But working women are here to stay. And they want their fair
share of the action. If male executives won't give it to them,
women will take it anyway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
