<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORGANS-TEXAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BILL WOULD GIVE IN-STATE PATIENTS FIRST SHOT AT RECOVERED
ORGANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JULIE MASON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Texas would join a growing number of states
flouting new federal guidelines for organ transplants under a bill
filed Thursday by state Sen. Mario Gallegos.
</P>
<P>
   With the backing of prominent Houston transplant surgeons and
groups involved in organ donations, Gallegos' bill stipulates that
organs recovered in Texas be offered to in-state patients first.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good system in Texas, we have worked hard to
increase organ donations,'' said Gallegos, D-Galena Park. ``If
Texas organs are spread around the country, many Texans may die
before other organs become available.''
</P>
<P>
   The federal government last year announced new transplant
regulations to take effect Oct. 1. The guidelines call for sharing
organs nationally, with the sickest patients receiving the highest
priority.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, organs are offered first to patients served by the
bank that collected the organ. If there is no match, organs are
shared regionally and then nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Medical advances have resulted in preserving organs longer and
flying them where needed most. However, several states now prohibit
sending organs out of state unless no in-state patient matches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem is not how to allocate this limited supply of
organs, but that we need more organs,'' said Dr. Patrick Wood,
director of the Texas Liver Center at Hermann Hospital in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Wood and Dr. Michael DeBakey, chancellor emeritus of Baylor
College of Medicine and a pioneer in heart and transplant surgery,
are supporting Gallegos' bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The shortage of viable donor organs makes it critical that
such tissues donated in Texas be offered to suitable candidates in
this state first,'' DeBakey said.
</P>
<P>
   Wood and others have said the new federal guidelines will force
patients to compete harder for the few, available organs. But
supporters of the guidelines claim the distribution process would
be more equitable, removing existing barriers for the neediest
recipients to obtain organs.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel Holtzman, president of Houston's LifeGift Organ Donation
Center, said his organization exported about 35 percent of the
organs it collected last year to areas outside Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Creech, a heart transplant recipient from Houston, added,
``The donation rate in Texas is much higher than the national
average, and it would not be appropriate to send those organs to
areas doing not enough to increase the supply of organs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other states that have taken steps to protect their organ
supplies from export are Louisiana, Oklahoma, South Carolina and
Wisconsin.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Kyle Janek, R-Houston, a physician, is filing a companion
bill to Gallegos' measure in the House. Decisions about Texas
transplants are better made by qualified medical professionals than
by ``politicians in Washington,'' Janek said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
