A8084 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-CONGRESS-HNS &LR;      03-04 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-CONGRESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS BLAST MEXICO, WHITE HOUSE OVER DRUG CERTIFICATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GARY MARTIN  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional critics on Thursday said President
Clinton's certification of Mexico as a cooperating ally in the war
on drugs is ``troubling,'' and they moved to overturn the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite a long and productive relationship with our ally to
the south _ Mexico _ the river of hard drugs is ending up on
America's streets and coming across the Mexican border,'' said Rep.
John L. Mica, R-Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is difficult for me to believe that this administration
would certify Mexico as fully cooperating. This is troubling,''
said Mica, chairman of the House Government Reform subcommittee on
drug policy.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Feb. 26 certified to Congress that Mexico is a fully
cooperating drug-fighting ally. Congress has 30 days from that date
to overturn the president's decision.
</P>
<P>
   A challenge to Mexico's certification is being mounted by
Democrats and Republicans in the House and Senate, although most
lawmakers agree that the effort is unlikely to overturn Clinton's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, House Speaker Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., has
instructed Mica and other Republican leaders in the House to move
forward with a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Reps. Spencer Bachus, R-Ala., and Clay Shaw, R-Fla.,
have introduced legislation that would strip Mexico of
certification. And Sens. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif., and Paul
Coverdell, R-Ga., have proposed a ban on business dealings with
foreign companies that serve as fronts for drug cartel smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Constantine, head of the Drug Enforcement Administration,
told Mica's subcommittee that drug kingpins in Mexico are
responsible for moving two-thirds of the cocaine consumed into the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   And although those narcotics kings are well known by the
authorities on both sides of the border, ``they have been able to
evade arrest and prosecution'' in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Corruption is pervasive in Mexican law enforcement ranks,
allowing drug cartels to grow stronger and branch out into
production and smuggling of methamphetamines and heroin,
Constantine said.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State Rand Beers said Mexico and the
United States admit that problems exist with drug-interdiction
efforts south of the border.
</P>
<P>
   But, Beers said, the president weighed the extent of Mexico's
efforts to combat illegal narcotics trafficking and the country's
attitude toward drug smuggling before certifying Mexico as a
partner in fighting illicit narcotics.
</P>
<P>
   Decertification, which could strip Mexico of U.S. aid, would
``jeopardize any cooperative efforts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The certification process, mandated by law, requires that the
United States decertify countries that do not cooperate with
American antidrug efforts. Decertified countries are often hit with
economic penalties such as loss of U.S. aid.
</P>
<P>
   Congress can overturn Clinton's decision by a majority vote in
both chambers within 30 days. But in the 13 years that the process
has been in effect, lawmakers have never reversed an administration
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 28 nations considered for certification this year, 26
were certified, including Colombia, which failed to make the list
in 1996 and 1997. Afghanistan and Burma were not certified, the
Clinton administration said, because the two nations produce more
than 90 percent of the world's supply of opium poppy.
</P>
<P>
   Mica said Mexico is responsible for the drugs and violence
``destroying young lives at a record level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Without question, no country in the world poses a more
immediate drug threat to the United States,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
