<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DELL-IBM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IBM, DELL ANNOUNCE PARTS DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In what is believed to be the biggest supply deal ever between
computer companies, IBM Corp. scored a major coup Thursday with the
announcement that Dell Computer Corp. will purchase up to $16
billion in IBM parts over the next seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will also cooperate on the development of new
computer technologies that will help Dell gain development
expertise and offer more advanced computers.
</P>
<P>
   Through the supply arrangement, Dell will get a reliable source
for state-of-the-art hard drives, flat panel screens , networking
equipment and advanced chips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it plays to the strength of each company,'' said Jim
Newmann, spokesman for IBM's technology group. ``We see this as a
mutually beneficial relationship that takes an existing
relationship to a new level.''
</P>
<P>
   Dell already uses IBM parts in its computers. Texas-based Dell
is the world leader in ``build-to-order'' machines purchased by
phone and over the Internet. Although Dell is one of the world's
largest computer companies, with $18.2 billion in revenues in the
past four quarters, the company is basically an assembler of parts
made by other firms, and develops little original technology on its
own.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Dell has aggressively moved into the high end of the
computer market, selling advanced servers for use by major
companies. Dell must compete with giants like Compaq Computer
Corp., which spent $4.6 billion in research and development in
1998, including the activities of the former Digital Equipment
Corp, which Compaq acquired last year for $9.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   IBM, on the other hand, is one of the world's leading developers
of advanced computer hardware. Among its latest developments are
chips that use copper circuitry instead of the traditional
aluminum, for faster, cooler performance. The company makes some of
the most advanced drives. Later this year, IBM will introduce a
drive for laptops measuring one inch square and capable of storing
340 megabytes of data. IBM also is a major manufacturer of
high-quality liquid crystal display panels.
</P>
<P>
   ``By more extensively pairing IBM's world-class technology with
our own, in systems brought to market through our efficient direct
business model, we intend to enhance Dell's competitiveness in the
global computer systems industry,'' said Mike Lambert, senior vice
president of Dell's enterprise systems group.
</P>
<P>
   The deal is not exclusive, so Dell will be free to shop for
parts from other suppliers. Dell spokesman Jerele Neeld said his
firm will continue to seek bids from major disk drive suppliers
such as Maxtor Corp. and Seagate Technology Inc. The company will
also keep buying from other suppliers of networking hardware, such
as 3Com Corp. and Cisco Systems Inc.
</P>
<P>
   And the deal will not affect Dell's long-term commitment to use
microprocessor chips from Intel Corp. IBM makes a line of
Intel-compatible chips. Nearly every other major computer company
now uses non-Intel processors in at least some of their computers.
But Dell remains firmly in the Intel camp.
</P>
<P>
   However, IBM technology group vice president Dave Ernsberger
said that Dell and IBM may work together on custom chips for use in
personal digital devices similar to 3Com's popular Palm Pilot. Dell
doesn't presently make such devices, but Ernsberger said that might
change as pocket-sized computers grow in popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Chu, an analyst with SG Cowen in Boston, said that Dell
is looking to secure early access to the latest hardware
technologies. He also noted that the deal gives Dell a highly
reliable supply of crucial parts, at a time when many Asian parts
makers are trying to bolster prices by cutting their output.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may seem like there's endless capacity out there,'' said
Chu, ``but being able to establish a high-level commitment on key
technologies...is tactically a smart thing to do.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM was up 4 1/4 to 171 on the New York Stock Exchange,
contributing to the overall rise in the stock market Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Dell stock closed up 15/16 at 81 7/8 on the Nasdaq stock
exchange.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1933EST &QL; 
