<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-EARNS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES REPORTS HIGHER EARNINGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joining the list of retailers that have beat Wall Street's
expectations, Staples Inc. said Thursday fourth-quarter profits
increased a whopping 45 percent to $101 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We continue to deliver industry-leading financial
performance,'' said Staples chairman and chief executive Thomas G.
Stemberg, commenting on company sales that rose 23 percent to $2.1
billion, and sales at stores open at least a year that jumped 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're cooking _ as usual,'' said PaineWebber analyst Aram
Rubinson. Of the three office-supply superstore chains, Office
Depot Inc., OfficeMax Inc., and Staples &UR;  &LR; is ``the best in its
class,'' Rubinson said.
</P>
<P>
   A strong economy and free spending by consumers during the
holiday shopping period made the fourth quarter a memorable one for
many retailers.
</P>
<P>
   But Staples once again outpaced the pack, showing signs of
strength in nearly all areas of its business, including its chain
of 913 superstores, its catalog sales, and its contract sales to
larger companies.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year that ended Jan. 30, sales rose 24 percent,
from $5.7 billion to $7.1 billion. Staples completed two
acquisitions during the year, but most of the sales increase came
from organic growth. Profits for the year grew 39 percent to $238
million.
</P>
<P>
   In other announcements, Staples said its board of directors has
authorized the Westborough, Mass. company to purchase up to $200
million worth of its common stock over the next year.
</P>
<P>
   Staples also announced that it has completed the $140 million
purchase of -Claricom Holdings Inc., a Milford, Conn. company that
provides telecommunications services and products to small and
mid-size businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Staples announced its plan to buy Claricom in December.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview on CNN, Stemberg said the company's on-line
retail operation, Staples.com, has gotten off to a good start since
its fall launch.
</P>
<P>
   The average order size from on-line purchasers is larger than
the average order size made from catalogs, Stemberg said.
</P>
<P>
   If there was any softness in Thursday's report, it was that
Staples' overseas operations have yet to perform as well as its US
counterparts.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, Staples bought the Quill Corp., the $600 million
marketer of office supplies directly to businesses. Plans call for
Quill to enter the European market within the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, shares of Staples rose 1/2 to close at 28 1/2.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 1935EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
