A8114 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RETAIL-SALES-BOS &LR;      03-04 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-SALES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETAILERS ENJOY A GOOD FEBRUARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A time for clearing out leftover winter merchandise for some
retailers, February was generally another good month as consumers
continued to spend freely at discount stores.
</P>
<P>
   And even some stores that posted mediocre results were singing a
happy tune: slow sales are a result of having nothing left to clear
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once again we're seeing the continuation of a trend as
consumers shift their dollars to discount chains'' and offprice
retailers such as TJX Cos., said Kurt Barnard, president of
Barnard's Retail Trend Report.
</P>
<P>
   Discounters such as Wal-Mart Stores Inc. and Kmart Corp. had
``superlative results'' in February, while many department stores
had sales gains only in ``the low single digits,'' Barnard said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, discounters seemed to take business away
from such department-store chains as Sears, Roebuck and Co. and
J.C. Penney Co.; both posted lackluster February sales.
</P>
<P>
   But as a result of strong housing sales, many retailers that
sell home furnishings and consumer electronics are faring well.
</P>
<P>
   Apparel chains including The Limited Inc., Gap Inc., and
AnnTaylor Stores Corp. also reported a good February.
</P>
<P>
   Observers such as Barnard focus on so-called same-store sales _
sales at stores open for at least one year; this, they claim, is
the best barometer of a retailer's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bloomberg News, which compiles a monthly index of same-store
sales based on results from a wide range of retailers, said
same-store sales were up a better-than-expected 7.6 percent in
February, compared with February of 1998. Sales have now exceeded
estimates for five months in a row, Bloomberg said.
</P>
<P>
   One locally based retailer that beat that average was TJX of
Framingham, Mass. The operator of such chains as T.J. Maxx and
Marshalls said same-store sales were up a whopping 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Ames Department Stores Inc., a regional discount chain based in
Rocky Hill, Conn., said February same-store sales were up 9.7
percent, thanks to strong sales of furniture, appliances, and home
entertainment merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   Some retailers argue that seemingly poor February numbers can be
a reflection of strength. If merchandise sells out at a full price
during the holidays, then there's little left over to promote as
part of February clearance sales.
</P>
<P>
   At Talbots Inc. in Hingham, Mass., February performance ``was
impacted by significantly less fall clearance merchandise versus
the previous year,'' said president and chief executive Arnold B.
Zetcher, explaining a 7.1-percent slump in February same-store
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Initial consumer response to the spring line of the chain's
classic women's apparel has been positive, he added.
</P>
<P>
   At J. Baker Inc., the Canton, Mass. company said ``significantly
less clearance merchandise'' at its flagship Casual Male Big &AMP; Tall
chain was partly responsible for a February same-store sales gain
of only 0.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Federated Department Stores Inc., which operates the Macy's
chain, said February same-store sales were up only 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Federated noted that a popular annual home sale has been
moved from February to January, skewing February results.
</P>
<P>
   When the two months are combined, sales were up 3.6 percent
compared with the same two months in 1998, Federated said.
</P>
<P>
   Designs Inc. of Needham, Mass. has been struggling of late. Its
stores rely heavily on clothing made by Levi Strauss &AMP; Co., which
has been in a slump.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Designs said same-store sales were up 8 percent for February
on a much smaller store base, 79 stores in February versus 113
stores for February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last year, the company has closed many underperforming
stores. With Levi's sales now showing signs of ticking upward, a
lean-and-mean Designs said it hopes 1999 will be a much better
year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
