<HEADER>
A8115 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDUCATION-VOUCHERS-HN     03-04 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATION-VOUCHERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
143,000 STUDENTS WOULD BE ELIGIBLE FOR VOUCHERS UNDER TEXAS BILL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Texas) 
 
By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ An estimated 143,000 public school students in
the state's six most populous counties would be eligible to receive
tax-backed vouchers to transfer to private schools under a bill
unveiled Thursday by the Senate Education Committee chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters predicted that only a small fraction of the eligible
students would actually take advantage of the five-year trial
program, which is backed by Gov. George W. Bush and Lt. Gov. Rick
Perry.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents, including most of the public education
establishment, warned it would hurt the public schools by draining
away much-needed tax dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents also said the bill would encourage parents to urge
their children to deliberately fail the Texas Assessment of
Academic Skills test to get a chance to go to private school.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation (Senate Bill 10), only low-income students
who weren't already enrolled in private schools and who failed the
most recent administration of the reading, writing or math TAAS
would be eligible for vouchers.
</P>
<P>
   That means the program would apply only to students in the
fourth grade or higher because the TAAS test is first administered
in the third grade.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Education Chairman Teel Bivins, R-Amarillo, admitted he
was trying to address one of the Legislature's most controversial
issues.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't know who was right but was trying to ``test
educational theories which are fiercely debated in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Bivins' bill _ which uses the term ``public education
scholarships'' instead of ``vouchers'' _ would require voucher
students to continue taking the TAAS tests in private schools and
require the state education commissioner to hold private schools
accountable for student performance.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Republicans Bush and Perry advocated a pilot voucher
program that would have been open to any low-income student from a
low-performing school or district in an urban areas.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins changed the plan to counter criticism that the proposal
would strip poor school districts of their best students. His bill
would apply only to low-performing, low-income students in any
school district in Bexar, Dallas, El Paso, Harris, Tarrant and
Travis counties.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins, using Texas Education Agency estimates, said that
143,000 students would be eligible. But Chuck McDonald, a spokesman
for Putting Children First, a pro-voucher group, said only 5
percent to 10 percent of eligible children have participated in
voucher programs in other states.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said the average voucher would be worth about $4,000 a
year, and private or parochial schools accepting vouchers would be
prohibited from charging any more than the voucher amount for
tuition.
</P>
<P>
   Students with special needs, such as special education students,
could receive more money.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said a student's voucher would be equal to 80 percent of
the total amount of state and local public school funding for that
student's education. The school district the student is leaving
would keep the remaining 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The senator disputed charges that the bill would drain money
from the public schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the student moved away or transferred, the entire amount
would be gone. Under my proposal, the public school ends up with
more money per student for the remaining students,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bivins said he had a ``reasonable chance'' of passing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just honing my persuasive skills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Boyle, a spokeswoman for the Coalition for Public
Schools, which includes the PTA and teachers' and school
administrators' groups fighting vouchers, said she believed
opponents had enough votes in the Senate to block the measure.
</P>
<P>
   But, she added, Perry and other supporters of the bill are
``working it very hard.'' Two voucher advocates helped guarantee a
$1.1 million loan that Perry used to finance the closing days of
his campaign last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Under Senate rules, one-third of the senators, or 11 members,
can block debate on any bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a mess. It's a bad idea. Texans can't afford to
experiment with a bad idea,'' Boyle said.
</P>
<P>
   But Jimmy Mansour, an Austin businessman and chairman of Putting
Children First, said that vouchers will work and that ``Texans will
see that choice and accountability are good for our schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Private and parochial schools accepting state vouchers would
have to be accredited or be in the process of seeking accreditation
from an organization recognized by the state education
commissioner.
</P>
<P>
   Private schools would be prohibited from accepting students on
the basis of race, ethnic background, religion, area of residence
or academic achievement. And schools couldn't consider athletic
ability in the admissions process.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be no cherry picking, as some people have referred
to it,'' Bivins said.
</P>
<P>
   A private school that had more voucher applicants than available
positions would have to give priority to students at risk of
dropping out of school and then fill any remaining positions by
lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Low-income students would be defined as those participating in
the free and reduced-price lunch program.
</P>
<P>
   The state education commissioner, under the bill, could suspend
a private school from the voucher program if he determined the
school was low performing _ based on TAAS scores, attendance and
dropout rates of voucher students.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Scripps Howard Texas Poll indicated that Texans are
about evenly divided on the pilot voucher proposal but that support
for the idea is slipping.
</P>
<P>
   The concept also is creating controversy in other states.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, Schools Chancellor Rudy Crew has threatened to
resign if Mayor Rudolph W. Guiliani pushes through an experimental
voucher program, The New York Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   At least two other voucher bills have been filed in the Texas
House, but Bivins' measure will get the most attention, at least
initially.
</P>
<P>
   One voucher advocate, who asked not to be named, said chances
were slim to none for getting a voucher bill out of the Texas House
Public Education Committee or getting one set for House floor
debate by the House Calendars Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Voucher proponents, however, could attempt to attach their bill
as an amendment during floor debate on another educational measure.
Such an attempt failed on a tie vote in the House two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
