u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBITUARY-MCKIBBEN-BOS     03-04 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MCKIBBEN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORDON C. MCKIBBEN, GLOBE EDITOR WHO RETOOLED BUSINESS COVERAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and f coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Gordon C. McKibben, the architect of The Boston Globe's
modern business coverage, died Wednesday at his home in Lexington
after a bout with cancer. He was 69.
</P>
<P>
   Hired as business editor of the newspaper in 1980, Mr. McKibben
remade the Globe's financial section. He expanded the staff,
boosted coverage, and pushed the paper to write about subjects like
computers and biotechnology that previously had been mostly
ignored.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the business section, he went to London as
European correspondent, then returned to Boston to take up the
ombudsman's post at the newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was one of the finest editors I ever knew and a superb
human being,'' said William O. Taylor, retired publisher of the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McKibben had a long and distinguished career in journalism
before he came to the Globe. He spent several years with the Wall
Street Journal in Los Angeles before moving to Business Week, his
employer for 17 years. At Business Week he covered everything from
the young Muhammad Ali to Canadian politics to the growing
technology industry along Route 128 in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   At the Globe, Mr. McKibben made his mark both professionally and
personally. Said John S. Driscoll, a former editor of the paper,
``Gordon had a special quality that was unmatched: the
professionalism of a veteran and the inquisitiveness and enthusiasm
of a cub reporter.''
</P>
<P>
   As a writer at the Globe, Mr. McKibben reported on the collapse
of the Soviet bloc. He also produced a series of stories on the
Arctic _ the kind of adventure he thrived on.
</P>
<P>
   And as the ombudsman _ the readers' representative inside the
Globe _ Mr. McKibben came into daily contact with a wide range of
readers. He used his biweekly column to explain to them the inner
workings of the newspaper's operations and, when he felt it
necessary, to offer hiw own opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McKibben didn't slow down in retirement. With Gillette's
cooperation, he produced a history of the company called ``The
Cutting Edge,'' which was published last year by Harvard Business
School Press. The book will be translated into Chinese and Thai
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McKibben was an active member of the Hancock United Church
of Christ in Lexington, a longtime member of the Lexington
Bicentennial Band flute section, and a volunteer in a Lexington
group that provided free rides for people who had to go to doctors'
appointments. An outdoorsman, he took his sons and brother in 1995
on a 100-mile hike around Mt. Rainier in Washington, retracing a
trip he had made when he was 15.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. McKibben earned his bachelor's degree at Stanford University
and a master's degree in political science from the University of
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   He leaves his wife, Peggy; two sons, William E. of Johnsburg,
N.Y., and Thomas G. of Freeport, Maine; two brothers, William T. of
Grinnell, Iowa, and Ernest C. Jr. of Redmond, Wash., a sister,
Helena Kirkwood of Whidby Island, Wash.; and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
