<HEADLINE>
HILLARY CLINTON URGES WOMEN TO SEEK CONTROL   OVER THEIR LIVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLUM LYNCH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Hillary Rodham Clinton, speaking Thursday at a
UN conference on women, discussed the suffering from sexual slavery
and domestic abuse, and urged women to take greater charge of their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton did not address the issue on the minds of many in
attendance: whether she will announce a run for the Senate seat in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the answer, it was clear that the hundreds of people in
the packed, mostly female, audience at UN headquarters had come to
offer their support. They greeted Clinton, who arrived about 30
minutes late, with cheers and a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why they are talking about her running for
Senate,'' quipped ABC correspondent Carole Simpson, who joined the
first lady at the commemoration of International Women's Day.
``Mrs. Clinton ought to be running for president.''
</P>
<P>
   In her speech, Clinton denounced Thai families for selling their
daughters to prostitution rings. And she railed against
Afghanistan's ruling Taliban for forbidding women to study,
practice medicine, or teach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is probably no more egregious and systematic trampling
of fundamental rights of women today than what is happening in
Afghanistan,'' she said. ``There are stories of women being flogged
with metal cables because a bit of their ankle is showing.''
</P>
<P>
   She also spoke of success stories.
</P>
<P>
   In Turkey, she said, a new law was passed banning spousal abuse.
Senegal recently outlawed the practice of female genital
mutilation. And she recounted a story of an Indian woman who fought
a legal system that deprived her of her husband's property upon his
death.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has her house and ... she has her dignity. And I'm told
she's even running for elective office in her community,'' she
added to laughter and applause.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the United Nations to the United States to places
throughout the world, more women are holding positions of power and
authority,'' Clinton said. ``We must strive ... to create the
conditions in which women have the right to make the choices in
their lives for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton applauded UN Secretary General Kofi Annan for announcing
a new UN policy to seize the salaries of ``deadbeat'' dads at the
UN who fail to pay child support or alimony. For years, the UN has
been criticized for shielding UN employees from foreign countries
who have abandoned their wives and children.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady did not discuss Barbara Walters' Wednesday
interview with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Following her speech, Clinton visited a Manhattan school and
attended a screening of an HBO documentary on women athletes. The
documentary, ``Dare to Compete: The Struggle of Women in Sports,''
begins with an interview with the first lady in which she says,
``Victory belongs to only those who dare to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   In her first visit to New York since she announced she was
giving ``careful thought'' to a Senate battle, Clinton teased a
group of supporters at a gathering at the Plaza Hotel Wednesday.
``I was told that there were some who thought I might have an
announcement to make,'' she said, pausing before adding, ``I
don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite her interest in New York politics, Clinton said Thursday
she is planning to travel to Egypt, Tunisia and Morocco to listen
to the ``voices'' of North African women.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many women around the world are finding their voice in new
ways,'' she said. ``We have to do all we can to make sure those
voices are amplified.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
