<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: Menem Race Approved
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge ruled that President Carlos Saul Menem could run
in the Justicialist Party presidential primary, expected to take
place in May, while he awaits a Supreme Court ruling on a
constitutional amendment that prohibits him from running for a
third consecutive term.
</P>
<P>
   ARGENTINA: Crime Crackdown
</P>
<P>
   President Carlos Saul Menem issued a decree widening the powers
of the federal police in Buenos Aires to crack down on the illegal
possession of firearms, prostitution and disorderly conduct.
Leaders of the Alianza opposition coalition, which runs the city's
government, said Menem was merely trying to embarrass them and
capitalize on crime as a political issue.
</P>
<P>
   PERU: Army Chief Dismissed
</P>
<P>
   The army discharged its chief of staff, Gen. Tomas Marky, a
month after he was arrested on allegations of stealing $1 million
in cash out of a case found at a clandestine airstrip run by
Colombian cocaine traffickers four years ago. The discharge came
only days after President Alberto Fujimori publicly defended Marky
as an honest officer.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA: Premier's Home Raided
</P>
<P>
   The premier of British Columbia, Glen Clark, ignored calls for
his resignation after a raid on his home by police investigating a
recently awarded license to run a charity gambling casino. Clark
insisted he had nothing to do with the license that went to a
neighbor who recently built an addition on the premier's house.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: 12 Cleared In Computer Case
</P>
<P>
   A federal judge acquitted a dozen former Mexico City officials
from President Ernesto Zedillo's governing party of charges they
conspired with IBM de Mexico executives to sell the city a $26
million law enforcement database system that failed to work. Three
IBM officials were acquitted in December.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: Tax Reform Approved
</P>
<P>
   Parliament approved a major tax reform welcomed by many small
businesses but opposed by several big corporations, which say they
face extra charges of several billion dollars because of the way
reserves will be taxed. The reform, still to be approved by the
upper house, cuts the lowest individual income tax rate to 19.9
percent from 23.9 percent and the top rate to 48.5 percent from 53
percent.
</P>
<P>
   AFRICA
</P>
<P>
   SOUTH AFRICA: Amnesty Rejected
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty applications from 27 leaders of the governing African
National Congress party were rejected by the Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. They had sought amnesty for collective
responsibility for acts by ANC members during the fight against
apartheid. But the commission can grant amnesty only for specific
acts and crimes.
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA: Prisoners To Be Freed
</P>
<P>
   The military government said it would release dozens of
political prisoners still in jail, accused of coup attempts against
the late dictator Gen. Sani Abacha. They include Lt. Gen. Donaldson
Oladipo Diya, who was Abacha's deputy until his arrest in December
1997.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: Missile Test Firing
</P>
<P>
   After going five years without test firing its missiles, the
Indian military will launch its Agni, an intermediate-range weapon,
within the next few days, according to several press reports. Its
range has been disclosed as 1,500 miles.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: Religious Quiz Halted
</P>
<P>
   After being accused of bigotry, the state government of Gujarat
has ordered its police intelligence agents to stop collecting
demographic information on religious minorities. Items on the
questionnaires asked about the number of guns owned by Christians
and Muslims and the ``tricks'' they used to convert people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
