<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8130 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRITAIN-MONICA-0305-C     03-04 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-MONICA-0305-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LEWINSKY WORKS CHARMS ON BRITISH TV
 &HT;    Moving in both the International and Lifestyle categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON Monica Lewinksy evolved from being a favorite source of
saucy pub jokes Thursday to being regarded as flesh and blood by
Britons long fascinated by the odd mess that has consumed their
American cousins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always thought the Monica jokes were the best,'' said
Len Armstrong, who watched Lewinsky's hour-long television
interview with friends and relatives in his home in Great Bookham.
``But, now that we've heard her, we've warmed a bit to her.''
</P>
<P>
   For an hour, the camera held a close shot of Lewinsky, smiling
and nodding energetically through the questions put gently to her
by dignified, gray-haired TV interviewer Jon Snow.
</P>
<P>
   Snow caused no tears, but he managed to prompt a few weighty
observations from the 25-year-old former White House intern.
``Married men are definite no-nos, never again,'' she said, summing
up the lessons of her tangled journey to celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   At the Armstrong house, the crowd was impressed. ``We thought
she was quite dignified,'' Armstrong said. ``We thought she might
go for the president, but she never did.
</P>
<P>
   ``What came across is her humanity, which had been ignored by
the press particularly the British press, which had demonized
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Channel 4 paid Lewinsky $660,000 for the interview, which was
taped last week in New York. The station ensured its investment
will pay off by selling the rebroadcast rights in more than 30
countries.
</P>
<P>
   The interview followed a documentary called ``The Half Monty,''
which traced the bittersweet careers of five diminutive male
strippers.
</P>
<P>
   In what one newspaper has called ``Monica Week,'' Lewinsky
arrived in London Thursday for a tour to promote her book, which
will be on the shelves here Friday.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, she is scheduled to appear at Harrods, the toney
London department store, to sign copies. Her itinerary includes 19
stops across Britain before heading home March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Even though most Britons have heard her story umpteen times,
Lewinsky will nevertheless generate a buzz.
</P>
<P>
   ``People will still be interested because of the sexual nature
of it,'' said Martin O'Hara, a surveyor who lives in the Surrey
village of West Horsley. ``But I shan't be attending.''
</P>
<P>
   While ``Monica Lewinsky: The Interview'' generated some interest
in the media Thursday, it didn't seem to cause Britons to cancel
plans in order to sit riveted to the television. ``Now, when
Princess Diana gave an interview,'' O'Hara observed, ``everybody
went home to watch it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky long has been a familiar character in the British
tabloids, which have dubbed the scandal that nearly unseated the
president ``Zippergate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mirror reportedly paid Lewinsky several hundred thousand
dollars for its ``world scoop'' interview, which has appeared this
week in installments.
</P>
<P>
   While most of the Mirror's coverage has been fluff, Lewinsky
displayed a mischievous sense of humor when she joked at one point
about her infamous encounter with the ''first cigar,'' which she
described as a ``silly'' thing that happened only once.
</P>
<P>
   ``However, I don't think I'll be going to a cigar bar again,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She also will grace the cover of the U.K. edition of the women's
magazine, Marie Claire. She was photographed by Patrick
Demarchelier, who created the famous Diana front cover for Vogue in
1991.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the many odd intersections between the former
intern and late princess.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Morton, who authored ``Monica's Story,'' was Princess
Diana's unofficial biographer and lead propagandist in her war with
Prince Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Harrods, where Lewinsky will first meet the British public, is
owned by the father of Dodi al-Fayed, Diana's companion who died
with her in Paris in a 1997 car crash.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sunday Mirror interview, Lewinsky compared herself to
Diana, saying she was in the ``similar situation'' of being
``wronged'' by the man she loved.
</P>
<P>
   She claimed her affair with Clinton was similar to Diana's
marriage to Prince Charles. ``I'm not a princess in a royal sense
but I was also wronged by a man who said he loved me,'' she told
the Mirror. ``And remember, I was in love with him. I was trapped,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he saw a common theme between the two. ``They
were both very naive,'' he said. ``They never understood the effect
of power. Diana didn't recognized how much power she had, and
Monica didn't recognize the power of the president. She also didn't
recognize how shallow her relationship was with Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   In the TV interview, Snow asked if she had a love/hate
relationship with the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not love him, but sometimes I hate him,'' she responded.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a black suit with her hair discreetly coiffed away from
her face, she recounted the now familiar story of their blossoming
affair.
</P>
<P>
   She giggled girlishly and covered her face when Snow asked if
Clinton made her tingle early in their relationship, which she said
was motivated at first for her by ``lust.''
</P>
<P>
   Was it more than sex?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yes,'' she said excitedly. ``The sexual aspects of the
relationship were just one component of it, it was my love.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he love you?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think in his own way he did, I think in his own way he
thought that I was special, I don't know about now,'' she said. ``I
don't know if that's the truth but I think so.''
</P>
<P>
   What did she think of Clinton in the beginning?
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he was a brilliant man who had a very big heart who
was kind, not necessarily nice, but kind,'' she said. ``A person
who had a large appetite for love I don't mean in the crude sense
love.''
</P>
<P>
   What would she do with the dress if she could get her hands on
it?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd burn it,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
