<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8131 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-BALLONISTS-ART-NY     03-04 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-BALLONISTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRITISH BALLOONISTS PASS   HALFWAY   POINT IN AROUND - THE - WORLD
TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: U.K., Switzerland, British Columbia, Egypt)  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By MALCOLM W. BROWNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two British balloonists seeking to become the first to circle
the world nonstop have surpassed some of their biggest hazards,
greatly improving their chances of ultimate success.
</P>
<P>
   The pilots of the huge balloon, Andy Elson, a 45-year-old
aeronautical engineer, and Colin Prescot, 48, Thursday completed
difficult maneuvers to skirt Chinese air space, which was barred to
them. With that, they put their worst political problem behind them
and headed for weather that is expected to be swift and smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Their balloon, the Cable &AMP; Wireless, was reported Thursday to be
over the South China Sea, nearing Taiwan and the voyage's halfway
point.
</P>
<P>
   The team, which set off from Spain on Feb. 17, set a new
ballooning endurance record on Saturday, when they passed 9 days
and 18 hours aloft, a mark set in February 1998 by the
Swiss-registered Breitling Orbiter 2 (one of whose pilots was
Elson).
</P>
<P>
   But Cable &AMP; Wireless has not yet broken the distance record:
14,232 miles flown last August by an American commodities broker,
Steve Fossett.
</P>
<P>
   Many balloonists have attempted circumnavigation, but none has
ever come close.
</P>
<P>
   The obstacles are formidable:
</P>
<P>
   _ The balloon must remain aloft, with food and water for its
pilots and fuel for its hot-air burners, for at least two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   _ Meteorologists and the air crew must work in close
cooperation, constantly changing altitude to take advantage of
winds heading in the desired directions. _ Balloonists must avoid
countries where they lack overflight permission and could be forced
down. China, which lies athwart some of the most desirable jet
streams, has refused to allow balloons piloted by Britons or
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday the Cable &AMP; Wireless fought through violent
thunderstorms over Thailand, and after passing over Indochina, the
two pilots had to fly a restricted course to avoid Chinese air
space. They reported passing within 30 miles of Hainan island,
which is Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Elson and Prescot expect to enter a jet stream in the next day
that could drive them speedily across the Pacific Ocean to
Vancouver, British Columbia, and beyond.
</P>
<P>
   A second balloon, the Breitling Orbiter 3, took to the air from
Switzerland on Monday to race the Cable &AMP; Wireless. The Orbiter 3,
like the Cable &AMP; Wireless, was built by the British company Cameron
Balloons Ltd., and is lifted by both helium gas and hot air. The
pilots are Dr. Bertrand Piccard, a Swiss psychiatrist, and Brian
Jones, a British balloonist.
</P>
<P>
   To reach the desired jet stream, Piccard reported having to fly
southwest over the Sahara before turning eastward. His ground crew
expect the Orbiter 3 to reach Egypt Friday.
</P>
<P>
   After a half dozen failed attempts during the past year, it
became clear that balloons need greater endurance if they are to
thread their way around political and geographical barriers, which
uses up fuel and supplies. To accomplish this, balloons have to
carry more fuel for heating the air that supplies part of the lift;
but this means building larger balloons to carry more fuel
containers.
</P>
<P>
   This led to design changes. The Cable &AMP; Wireless contains more
than a million cubic feet of helium and hot air, making it the
largest balloon of this type ever built. Its hot-air burners are
fueled with kerosene rather than the more usual propane; kerosene
containers weigh less than pressurized propane cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   These changes, the Cable &AMP; Wireless team reported, have made it
possible to use a ``low and slow'' strategy that has so far evaded
the major obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Orbiter 3 began its flight nearly two weeks after
the Cable &AMP; Wireless, its crew expects to catch up. Because of its
Swiss registry, the Orbiter 3 has been granted permission by China
to fly over the south of the country to take advantage of a
high-speed jet stream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
