<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Virginia obtains AOL center Georgia failed to secure
 &HT;    By Scott Thurston
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Three weeks after dismissing Cobb County, Ga., as a
candidate for a new $550 million computer center, America Online
has chosen a site in northern Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   The decision came after the Virginia General Assembly quietly
approved tax exemptions worth $18 million or more on the new
facility, The Washington Post reported Thursday. Incentives also
would cut Dulles, Va.-based AOL's existing expenses by $4 million a
year, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   The new center will be located in Prince William County, near
Manassas. Virginia Gov. James S. Gilmore III has scheduled a news
conference Wednesday to announce the AOL deal, the Post said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's loss of the facility _ and how Virginia won it _ may
fuel the debate over sweetening Georgia's recruitment incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Roy Barnes' press secretary, Gary Horlacher, declined to
comment on AOL's decision. But he said the governor ``conceptually
agrees with those who are seeing the anecdotal evidence that
Georgia needs to do something. He's also said he's not going to do
anything that will not be fiscally prudent for the state.''
</P>
<P>
   There were indications the General Assembly would consider
boosting incentives this year, but Barnes' desire for harder study
appears to have delayed action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor's approach is to take a really comprehensive look
at all things that can be called incentives, and I think that's the
right approach,'' said Randy Cardoza, commissioner of industry,
trade and tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Site selection experts say incentives aren't usually the top
draw for relocating or expanding companies but can become a
``tiebreaker.'' Indeed, the Post reported that North Carolina
offered AOL $28 million in tax credits over seven years.
</P>
<P>
   A complete price was never placed on Georgia's bid, although
Cobb County Commission Chairman Bill Byrne said earlier the state
was willing to buy a $5 million site as part of an incentives
package. In December, Byrne said AOL had chosen a Cobb site for the
data center. But last month AOL said it had ruled out Georgia as a
site for the center.
</P>
<P>
   According to The Washington Post report, Virginia officials
pushed a bill through the just-ended legislative session to waive
the 4.5 percent sales tax on computer servers and other equipment
purchased by Internet providers that offer their own content. The
bill's sponsors sold the incentives as part of a general update of
the tax code, the Post said, and only a small group of state
officials knew the legislation was being written to benefit AOL.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
