<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENS-WEARHOUSE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    K&AMP;G Men's Center selling chain to rival
 &HT;    By Patti Bond
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Atlanta-based K&AMP;G Men's Center Inc. has agreed to sell
its chain of 33 stores to Men's Wearhouse Inc. for as much as $133
million in stock, or $13 a share, in a pooling-of-interest
transaction announced Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Fremont, Calif.-based Men's Wearhouse, the largest U.S. retailer
of men's suits, plans to combine 20 of its lowest-price stores with
K&AMP;G's operations and run it as an Atlanta-based division. Men's
Wearhouse runs K&AMP;G look-alike stores known as SuitMax in Atlanta
and six other cities. A store in Detroit operates as Suit
Warehouse.
</P>
<P>
   The company will likely close overlapping off-price stores in
markets such as Atlanta, which has four K&AMP;G stores and one SuitMax,
said John Dancu, K&AMP;G's chief operating officer. K&AMP;G will retain its
name, he said.
</P>
<P>
   K&AMP;G's successful corporate run began to unravel last summer. A
series of disappointments kept the company from regaining
investors' confidence, analysts said. Stephen Greenspan, chairman
and president of K&AMP;G, launched the no-frills company 10 years ago
in the Chattahoochee warehouse district. Then a liquidator,
Greenspan founded the company by selling a truckload of men's suits
leftover from a department store bankruptcy. He raked in $120,000
the first weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend formula remained a hit for some time. K&AMP;G built a
profitable enterprise by staying open three days a week and running
warehouse-style stores in industrial neighborhoods. The company
went public with eight stores in 1996 and charmed Wall Street with
its bare-bones style, aggressive growth plans and strong sales.
</P>
<P>
   After a secondary offering last summer, the love fest started to
cool. In July, the stock neared its all-time high at $26.62 1/2,
which analysts called a rich price for a small company. Plus, the
men's suit market began to soften in the second half of the year as
the continued growth of ``business casual'' wear counteracted the
expansion of tailored suit superstores. Investors and insiders
began selling, and the stock took a dive. Since September, the
price has stayed near $10.
</P>
<P>
   Industry observers had been expecting K&AMP;G to sell to Men's
Wearhouse, but not so soon, said Robinson-Humphrey analyst Dan
Wewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a bittersweet situation. They negotiated from a weak
position rather than a strong one,'' Wewer said. ``I thought they'd
wait and get the stock back up.'' K&AMP;G closed Thursday at $9.37 1/2,
up $1.
</P>
<P>
   Several setbacks in 1998 probably laid the groundwork for the
merger, Wewer said. Unusually warm weather during the fall and
winter hurt K&AMP;G sales, and the company made some bad real estate
decisions in Houston, Los Angeles and New York. ``They probably saw
some tough times ahead, especially with aggressive growth by Men's
Wearhouse,'' Wewer said.
</P>
<P>
   The merger keeps K&AMP;G's growth plans alive. ``We've always had a
goal of 100-plus stores, and we still want to be a national
retailer. That won't change,'' Dancu said. K&AMP;G currently is in 16
states.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan will become chief executive of the Men's Wearhouse
division and will join the company's board of directors. The rest
of K&AMP;G's management team will remain intact for the time being,
Dancu said.
</P>
<P>
   Pending approval of K&AMP;G shareholders, the companies expect the
transaction to close in the second quarter of fiscal 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition is the second in five months for Men's
Wearhouse. In November, it agreed to buy Canada's Moores Retail
Group Inc. for as much as $127 million in stock and debt. The
company operates more than 400 stores in the United States. It had
sales of $767.9 million in fiscal 1998.
</P>
<P>
   For the first nine months of fiscal 1998, K&AMP;G had sales of $91.6
million.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
