<SLUG> BC-TURNER-CABLE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ad executives love Turner tales about old times and new
 &HT;    By Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Does this city love Ted Turner or what? This town's
infamously hard-knuckled ad executives gave Turner a standing
ovation Thursday as he regaled them in funny tales of his early
years.
</P>
<P>
   What a change from 25 years ago, when Turner first came to New
York trying to sell Madison Avenue on the merits of his fledgling
cable TV channels. Back then nobody would advertise with him.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday the city was eating out of his hand as he addressed
a luncheon crowd of some 1,500 executives. Turner, now vice
chairman of Time Warner, was the luncheon speaker at the annual
conference of the Cable Advertising Bureau. CAB represents media
buyers, the people who buy ad time on television and in newspapers
and magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was going to be hard to convince the New York
advertising community, but I had no idea how hard,'' Turner
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first team of salesmen ended up like the soldiers in the
opening scene of 'Saving Private Ryan.' They were mowed down to a
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Turner, who founded the Atlanta-based television network of the
same name, didn't launch the first cable TV channel. He was,
though, the first to try to get advertising on his channels.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were what I'd called a transactional network,'' Turner
teased. Only companies that sold merchandise through direct mail
would advertise initially on TBS, Turner's first channel.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers mailed their checks to TBS, and Turner used that mail to
measure his channel's initial viewership. He divided the piles by
location. Half of it, he found, was from people outside Atlanta,
and he used that fact to argue TBS had a national viewership.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't exactly a compelling argument to Procter &AMP; Gamble,
but I thought it was pretty cool,'' said Turner.
</P>
<P>
   The insider's wisecrack left his audience in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   In separating his mail, Turner said he noticed something else.
Every 20th letter had a stamp without a postmark.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, I said, here's a chance to make some revenue,'' said
Turner. ``I took the letters to our mail room and made them cut off
and re-use the stamps. I figured I made a dime on every stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the early days were tough, Turner said he misses them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be back in sales, but they've kicked me upstairs
to a nice corner office,'' he said. ``I try and keep up with it. My
secretary gets me the sales reports, which makes me feel like Paley
in his final years at CBS.''
</P>
<P>
   Paley, of course, is William Paley, the legendary broadcaster
who founded CBS. Turner tried unsuccessfully to buy the network
early in his career.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
