<SLUG> BC-COKE-PROXY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bonuses fizzle for Coca-Cola chairman
 &HT;    By Henry Unger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Reflecting Coca-Cola Co.'s turbulent financial
performance, the total cash compensation for Chairman and Chief
Executive M. Douglas Ivester fell $470,000 last year to $3.59
million, the company's proxy statement shows.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, however, was given 250,000 shares of restricted stock
valued at $16.9 million. That's almost double the value of
restricted stock he received a year earlier, when he was president
and chief operating officer. The total value of Ivester's
restricted stock is $131 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company said the 1998 increase in restricted stock reflected
its long-term confidence in Ivester's leadership ability. He,
however, will forfeit that stock if he doesn't stay with the
company for at least another decade and retire from it. Those
conditions exist to retain ``those individuals who are key to the
creation of share-owner value,'' the proxy said.
</P>
<P>
   That value has come under immense pressure lately, with the
stock price falling 29 percent from its 52-week high last July.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester, 51, saw his base salary remain the same at $1.25
million. His last salary increase was in November 1997, after he
took over from the late Roberto C. Goizueta.
</P>
<P>
   Ivester's annual cash bonus, which is based on company
performance, fell to $1.5 million last year, down from $2 million
in 1997. The company's profits last year fell 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   And cash payments to Ivester from a long-term incentive plan,
which also is based on the company's performance, dropped to
$702,000, compared with $1.1 million in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Ivester exercised stock options that were awarded 10
years ago, giving him a paper gain of $37 million. He also has the
rights to additional stock options worth $106 million, which he has
not exercised yet.
</P>
<P>
   In an annual report, which also was released Thursday, Ivester
came out swinging against company critics in his letter to
shareholders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, as our stock slid from its July high, pundits were
quick to pronounce us and other multinational companies passe,'' he
wrote. ``Exposed to the world's economic woes, we were deemed to be
_ get this _ too global.''
</P>
<P>
   But, Ivester said, he takes the global label as a compliment.
And despite that the continued financial woes overseas will make
1999 another challenging year, Ivester said the company's long-term
strategies will successfully propel it into the future.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
