<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UKRAINE-ASYLUM-525&AMP;AD     03-04 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UKRAINE-ASYLUM-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UKRAINE'S EX-PREMIER SAYS HE'S CLOSER TO GAINING ASYLUM IN U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Pavlo Lazarenko, the former Ukrainian prime minister
who asserts that the nation's leaders are using corruption charges
to persecute him, said Thursday that he had cleared the first
procedural hurdle toward winning political asylum in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Without confirming or denying that, a federal official in the
United States remarked later that more than four in five applicants
for asylum clear the same bar. Only a fraction of those who succeed
win permanent residence in the United States, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement made public by his lawyers, Lazarenko said the
federal Immigration and Naturalization Service has concluded that
he displays a credible fear of persecution should the United States
return him to Ukraine against his will.
</P>
<P>
   ``While my supporters in Ukraine continue to advance my platform
for a vibrant economy, I will continue to seek temporary political
asylum in the United States,'` Lazarenko's statement read. ``I am
confident that officials here will understand my situation and act
accordingly.''
</P>
<P>
   In a separate statement, Ukraine's prosecutor general, Mykhaylo
Potebenko, told the Interfax-Ukraine news service that he was
confident of Lazarenko's eventual return to Ukraine for
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   He said Ukraine had given the United States evidence of
Lazarenko's crimes, and that no nation would wish to grant him safe
haven given the evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   Lazarenko, who was second-in-command to Ukraine's president,
Leonid Kuchma, in 1996 and 1997, has been in federal custody in
Queens since Feb. 19, when he arrived at Kennedy International
Airport and was judged to have an invalid visa.
</P>
<P>
   He fled Ukraine only days before prosecutors there charged him
with embezzling and misusing millions of dollars in government
funds as part of a long-running corruption scheme. In December, the
Swiss government arrested Lazarenko at the border and charged him
with laundering millions of dollars through numbered bank accounts
there.
</P>
<P>
   In Ukraine, which has been plagued by endemic official
corruption since its independence in 1991, Lazarenko is widely
reported to be one of the nation's richest men. Repeated reports
have placed him at the center of multimillion-dollar kickback and
rake-off schemes as prime minister and, before that, as governor of
an eastern Ukraine region.
</P>
<P>
   While conceding that he is ``no angel,'' Lazarenko has insisted
that he has acted legally. Then and now, he has asserted that the
corruption charges are a plot by Kuchma to destroy him politically.
</P>
<P>
   The two men have been bitter enemies since Kuchma dismissed
Lazarenko almost two years ago, and Lazarenko is now a minor-party
opponent of Kuchma's in Ukraine's presidential election in October.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Thursday, Lazarenko said the Ukrainian charges
were ``totally without substance'' and that the Swiss and Ukrainian
accusations ``are part of a systematic, politically motivated plot
to repress opposition.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not be intimidated by such tactics,'' he said, adding
that he is continuing his presidential campaign even as he seeks to
remain in the United States.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lazarenko's lawyers said Thursday that the ruling in his favor
came after a four-hour interview by immigration officials and an
eight-page, point-by-point review of his assertions of persecution
at the hands of the Kuchma administration.
</P>
<P>
   James Mayock, a partner in the San Francisco law firm that
represents Lazarenko, said his cause was not hurt by the fact that
his client was mentioned in the State Department's own global
reviews of human-rights problems.
</P>
<P>
   The department's 1997 report, which was somewhat critical of
Ukraine's human-rights record, hinted at political motives for what
it called an ``alleged assassination attempt on the then-prime
minister, Pavlo Lazarenko, whose car reportedly barely escaped a
bomb explosion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard not to find he has credible fear when you're
mentioned in that report,' Mayock said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
