A8155 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-     03-04 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-BARNHOUSE-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCHOOLS REALLY DID `PILLAGE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By WENDELL BARNHOUSE 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The Star-Telegram has uncovered indisputable
evidence of a Texas-based plot to pilfer another of this city's
prize possessions.
</P>
<P>
   Your Intrepid Reporter believes that the Big 12 Conference
basketball tournament, contractually obligated to this site through
2000, will be moved when new deals are arranged. I discovered this
breaking news story by accident.
</P>
<P>
   Here at Kemper Arena (think Reunion Arena, but uglier and
farther away from downtown) you have your basic backstage series of
rooms and hallways. Searching for a soda machine (I loathe Dr
Pepper, the Big 12's Official Drink), I noticed a room marked
``Storage'' where the door was ajar.
</P>
<P>
   Curious, I looked inside. Behind a stack of Kings and Scouts
souvenirs (NBA and NHL franchises that also left town), I saw two
men sitting at a table. Each were talking on cell phones while
typing on laptop computers.
</P>
<P>
   Hmmmmm. Fellow journalists looking for privacy? I said hello.
Both turned, their faces ashen at being discovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whar yew frum, son?'' the stocky one asked me. My answer
seemed to relax both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can't tell nobody nuthin' 'bout this,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   They introduced themselves. The stocky one said he was Robin
Pillage. ``Pillage?'' I asked. ``It's pronounced Pil-laj,'' he
hissed, emphasizing the second syllable. The taller one said he was
I.M. Swindle. When I asked if he was related to the pitcher, he
just glared.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Pillage, the talkative one, told me of their mission.
</P>
<P>
   As the locals believe, there's a conspiracy afoot. The diehard
former Big Eight Conference schools _ which are conveniently
forgetting the two Oklahoma schools _ blame the South (i.e. Texas)
for all the talk of taking the Big 12 tournament and leaving K.C.
with nothing more than blues and barbecue.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of moving the tournament away from Kansas City to
cities like St. Louis, Oklahoma City, Dallas and San Antonio has
the folks around here whining like an 18-wheeler zipping down the
interstate.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri coach Norm Stewart is saying that the Texas schools
haven't been pulling their weight. And Nebraska coach Danny Nee
says it would be a mistake to leave Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Harrumph,'' Pillage said, spitting into a Styrofoam cup.
``He's just a coach. They don't listen to coaches. Stewart, he'll
be gone in a few years, may never have to play a tournament in
Texas. And Nee? He's the basketball coach at Nebraska. That should
clue you in on his clout, hoss.''
</P>
<P>
   As everyone knows, he continued, what the Big 12 office has been
doing is getting organized. New commissioner Kevin Weiberg has
simplified and standardized the method by which cities will bid for
the tournament. If the tournament leaves Kansas City, it will be
for the best offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the guy in Watergate said, follow the money,''
Pillage said. ``You open up a big enough can of cash, you can do
about anything. Those bean counters in Ames and Manhattan and
Columbia realize that if the checks keep coming with lots of
zeroes, they'll figure out ways to be happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Pillage and Swindle said they had to get back to work. Swindle
mumbled something about needing to short-circuit the scoreboard,
embarrass the locals' production values.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we tell you any more, we'll have to kill you,'' Pillage
said.
</P>
<P>
   I'm fairly certain that would be classified as ``accidental
death'' in our company insurance coverage, but I decided not to
chance it. Now that this story is public, I'll be looking over my
shoulder. Just like the good folks of Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
