<SLUG> BC-TEST-TEX </SLUG>
 EDITORS: This is a test from the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. nn
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2010EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0348 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8160 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-VIOLENCE-ART     03-04 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-VIOLENCE-ART-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHERN IRISH CATHOLIC AND PROTESTANT SAVAGERY IS NOW DIRECTED AT
THEIR OWN
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(fe) 
 By WARREN HOGE 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ It took death and dismemberment to
bring together the families of Andrew Peden, a 35-year-old
Protestant, and Andrew Kearney, a 33-year-old Catholic, but the
awkward union is serving to expose one of Northern Ireland's most
persistent and ruthless traditions.
</P>
<P>
   Both men were victims of punishment beatings, where members of
the paramilitary armies that control working-class neighborhoods
turn their violence not on their declared enemies from the other
side of the religious divide but on their own, in a vicious effort
to avoid being swept away in the march toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   Gangs in ski masks haul their victims into darkened alleys and
back streets from homes, street corners, pubs and vehicles. They
bind them, hang them upside down from railings or pin them to the
ground in a crucifixion posture, then beat them with hammers, iron
bars and baseball bats studded with nails. Then they shoot them in
the kneecaps, the thighs or the feet.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney died from an attack by a methodical Irish Republican
Army squad of 10 people who dragged him from the bed where he was
playing with his two-week-old daughter, shot him three times and
then locked him in the elevator of his building and ripped out
telephone lines so no rescuers could reach him before he bled to
death. His crime had been punching an IRA official in a pub
argument.
</P>
<P>
   Peden barely survived shotgun wounds and 10 hours of assault by
members of the Ulster Volunteer Force. He required months of
hospital treatment and a double amputation, leaving him with two
stumps on either side of his groin and a palsied and stunted body
that needs a daily dosage of 42 pills to keep functioning. His was
a case of mistaken identity.
</P>
<P>
   In a grim paradox, beatings increase at times like the present,
when cease-fires and political negotiations drastically reduce the
killing between the two warring religious communities and bring the
exhilarating promise of peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two months of 1999, with the peace arrangements
taking hold, there were 65 such attacks, 26 more than in the
corresponding, less-settled, period last year, just before the
peace agreement. The attacks ceased last year in the weeks just
before the April 10 signing, but that same night they resumed _ and
their number has been mounting ever since, to the current rate of
one a day, the highest in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The groups weren't challenged when they had the guns behind
them, and this is the way they point out that they still have
them,'' said David Hanna, chief information officer of the Royal
Ulster Constabulary. ``They've had social control for 30 years now,
and they don't want to lose that edge in the new circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   Sam Cushnahan, director of Families Against Intimidation and
Terror, a nonsectarian organization that seeks to give voice to
victims of violence, said, ``It's all about power and control.''
</P>
<P>
   The militias took on their enforcement role, particularly in
Catholic neighborhoods, to supplant the reviled British security
forces and the largely Protestant Royal Ulster Constabulary, and to
maintain unity and discipline in their communities as the sectarian
conflict became more intense.
</P>
<P>
   They became such an accepted and feared institution of life in
Northern Ireland that in many cases young men would be delivered to
punishment squads by their relatives and then picked up and taken
home bloodied and battered afterward. The original aim was to curb
drug dealing, vandalism, car theft and other ``antisocial
behavior,'' but today the scores being settled are just as often
grudges, disputes over women and disrespect shown a militia leader.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the sectarian bombings and murders, which still occur,
the savagery is not the work of renegades at odds with the
cease-fire. It is practiced by men and women who answer to
political parties sworn to the nonviolent principles of last year's
accord.
</P>
<P>
   No one questions the fact that parties like Sinn Fein, the
political wing of the IRA, or the Progressive Unionists, the
political representatives of the Ulster Volunteer Force militia,
control the vigilantes and can halt them when it suits their
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the graphs and see a sudden falloff in
punishment beatings,'' Cushnahan said, ``look at the date, and
you'll see it's because someone like Clinton was due to come here
or there was an election scheduled. They can switch it on and
off.''
</P>
<P>
   The walls of Cushnahan's downtown office are covered with
photographs of teen-agers on crutches and artificial legs or lying
in hospital beds with blood stained bandages around their knees.
One pictures John Brown, an 80-year-old pensioner with wounds on
both his ankles and his knees inflicted by an IRA punishment squad
that attacked him in his home. They had mistaken him for another
elderly man suspected of pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   The gangs operate with impunity because no victims testify and
no witnesses come forward for fear of even more vicious
retaliation.
</P>
<P>
   Hanna remembers getting a rare tip about a teen-ager who had
just been bundled into a car by a Protestant punishment squad.
``When we got there, this kid was a quaking nervous wreck, but
after we rescued him, he said he was fine and that there had been
no problem,'' he said. ``He knew he'd be killed if it was thought
that he had talked to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Peden and Kearney would be just two more soon-forgotten grisly
statistics in Northern Ireland's three decades of bloodshed were it
not for the determination of their families to protest.
</P>
<P>
   ``These groups say they exist to protect our communities,'' said
Peden, propped between two pillows on his living room sofa. ``They
call themselves the sons of Ulster. You call this protection?'' he
asked, pointing down at his severed limbs.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He knows the identities of the men who beat him and sees them in
his neighborhood, the all-Protestant Glencairn housing project. He
wakes up each day to the hated sight of a second-story window in a
building directly across the street: It is the apartment where he
was tortured and shot after being abducted from his own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   For Andrew Kearney's mother, Maureen, 65, speaking out was a
bold departure from a lifelong commitment to the Republican cause,
which favors the end of British rule here and eventual union with
the Republic of Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criticizing the IRA is like condemning my own family,'' she
said. Her father was a member; her brother was one of the IRA men
interned by the British in 1971; a nephew served 20 years in prison
for IRA actions. Bobby Sands, who achieved martyr status with his
hunger strike death in 1981, was her cousin; a memorial to Sands
stands a block away from her house in the solidly Catholic
Twinbrook housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Kearney nor Peden had any involvement in the tribal
politics of Northern Ireland, and their experiences illustrate the
random and unforgiving nature of the vigilante justice that rules
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   Kearney was marked for punishment because he came to the rescue
of a 17-year-old boy being beaten by an IRA brigade commander in a
pub and then challenged the man to a fistfight outside.
</P>
<P>
   Peden became a target because he was thought to be an ally of a
paramilitary neighbor he had simply given a lift home. On arriving
home, the neighbor spotted the car of a leader of a rival group he
suspected was having an affair with his wife. He had the intruder
beaten. The victim ordered revenge. Someone, it turned out, had
noted the license plate of Peden's car.
</P>
<P>
   Peden was seized, blindfolded and thrown onto the floor of a
passing vehicle the next day, Saturday, May 2, as he was preparing
to take his family on a weekend trip to his mother-in-law's house.
He had no idea why he was being assaulted, and when he tried to
protest his innocence during the beating, he said, he was hit and
told to shut up.
</P>
<P>
   At one point his torturers gave him a piece of paper and told
him to write a farewell note to his children. ``Daddy loves you''
was all he remembers writing before being beaten unconscious.
</P>
<P>
   As for Kearney, he had received warnings that he was going to
``get done,'' his mother said, and for more than a year he had been
assuring her that he was ``looking over his shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   At the urging of a local priest, he offered to compose a letter
of apology and recite it in the pub, but IRA representatives told
Mrs. Kearney that it would not satisfy the offended commander's
desire for revenge. The masked men came to get him just after
midnight the morning of July 19, the date that is now on his
tombstone.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kearney has submitted the bill for his funeral to Sinn
Fein, and when she saw one of the men she believed responsible for
her son's killing in a her local supermarket, she pressed a
memorial card picture of Andrew into his hand and loudly accused
him of murder. ``He just laughed,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the Irish Republican Army, an organization she has been loyal
to her entire life, she now says: ``They're taking the violence
they used to use against the British and the security forces, and
they're turning it on their own community. They're thugs, scum.''
</P>
<P>
   She has cooperated with the police, though that has usually
brought retribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``You go to the police in these neighborhoods, and you have a
petrol bomb through your window the next day,'' Peden said.
</P>
<P>
   His greatest wish is to get the money to leave his neighborhood
and into a bungalow so he can more easily get around. One of his
stumps is infected so he cannot yet wear the artificial legs he has
been fitted for.
</P>
<P>
   His son Gary, 15, recently alarmed him by saying that he would
kill the men who had maimed him. ``I've got to get him out of
here,'' Peden said, with desperation in his voice. ``I don't want
him to become part of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the attack on her husband, Linda Peden had a tolerance
for the punishment beatings typical of working-class neighborhoods
in Belfast. ``You never approved of them, but you felt the victim
had done something wrong,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She has met with representatives of the militia that beat her
husband, and she said they now concede that the attack was a
mistake. ``But what good is that after he has been left with half a
body?'' she asked. ``We haven't got a life now. I even have to lift
him on and off the toilet.''
</P>
<P>
   Though taking ``effective steps'' to prevent punishment beatings
was one of the written principles endorsed by all the parties at
the peace talks as a condition of entry, leaders have routinely
ignored pleas to curb them.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Adams and Martin McGuinness, leaders of Sinn Fein, and
David Ervine, head of the Progressive Unionists, refused to attend
a meeting last month with Mo Mowlam, the British Secretary for
Northern Ireland, when they learned the subject was the surge in
punishment beatings.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that even a resolution of the remaining problems
confronting the peace agreement, hoped for by the end of this
month, will put an end to the vigilante acts. ``It's unfortunately
the kind of violence that this society has learned to tolerate,''
Cushnahan said. ``It only affects working class areas, and people
in what I call the leafy suburbs aren't effected by it.''
</P>
<P>
   The paramilitary groups argue that the beatings respond to
community pressure for crime control in the absence of a trusted
police force. But with the continuing perversion of the
paramilitary's enforcement and with reforms coming to the police
force, cynicism is making inroads into that longtime tolerance.
</P>
<P>
   ``They say we have peace, and the bombings may have stopped, but
the rest goes on,'' said James Peden, Andrew Peden's uncle.
``There's no peace here.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Kearney commented, ``When peace was declared, people
expected peace. Now you don't know whose house violence is going to
come to next.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely that her son's killers will ever be arrested,
because no one will produce the needed evidence. But she says she
is determined to fight for an end to the beatings, and she says she
has received lots of private support from her cowed neighbors, if
not any public show of it.
</P>
<P>
   She set her jaw, tossed her white hair and thrust her finger
toward the window looking out on the distant hillside where Andrew
is buried.
</P>
<P>
   ``The punishment gangs like to say, `It's just to let you know
that we haven't gone away,' '' Mrs. Kearney said. ``Well, I'm now
letting them know that I'm not going away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
