<HEADLINE>
TEXAS BILL WOULD BENEFIT UNINSURED CHILDREN 10 AND UNDER  

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Children aged 10 or younger who lack health care
coverage take the highest priority under a children's health
insurance plan adopted unanimously by a Senate panel Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Bill 445, which attempts to strike the middle ground in
the politically explosive issue of children's health care for the
working poor, could be taken up by the full Texas Senate next week,
its sponsor predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill, tax dollars would pay health insurance premiums
from birth to age 10 if a child lives in a family with income up to
200 percent of the federal poverty level. That's $33,600 for a
family of four.
</P>
<P>
   A band of Democrats in the House, however, insist the plan must
cover all children at that poverty level, not just the youngest
ones, since federal money is available. The Senate plan doesn't go
that far, but leaves the door open for broader coverage later.
</P>
<P>
   Passions are running high as Republicans react to a warning that
55 House Democrats have signed a petition that health care for kids
is at least as important as tax breaks for the oil industry,
declared an emergency by Gov. George W. Bush. Some have threatened
to block the oil tax cut if their goals for children's health
coverage are not met.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good in my heart that we have an excellent product, a
responsible mechanism to address the needs of the uninsured
children of the state,'' Senate sponsor Mike Moncrief, D-Fort
Worth, said after the Senate Health Committee approved his bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be a travesty to leave behind a legacy of
failure,'' he added, explaining that the state should proceed with
fiscal caution. ``I don't know of a greater opportunity Texas has
ever had or will ever have again to address the needs of so many,
not just in this generation, but in future generations.''
</P>
<P>
   Politically, stakes are high.
</P>
<P>
   Texas ranks at least second in the nation for uninsured
children, and every dollar the state puts up for the Children's
Health Insurance Program (CHIP for short) would be matched with
three more from federal taxes. Plus, the state is sitting on a $2.5
billion budget surplus and $17.3 billion tobacco settlement, of
which $500 million a year is dedicated to children's health.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a lot of Democrats believe that the problem of
uninsured children in Texas is an emergency that is equally as
important as the emergency the governor says exists in the oil
industry,'' said state Rep. Kevin Bailey, D-Houston, head of the
Legislative Study Group. ``Our goal is just to make sure children's
health is treated at least as importantly as the oil industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Officially, Bush has said he wants a clear signal from both the
House and Senate before deciding what approach to take.
</P>
<P>
   Under Moncrief's bill, children ages 11-18 would be covered only
if their families' incomes did not exceed 150 percent of poverty _
$26,300 for a family of four.
</P>
<P>
   Medicaid, the federal health insurance for the poor, would
continue to cover children in families the same size with incomes
of $16,800 or less.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly hope the health of these children isn't going to
hinge on some political wheeling and dealing,'' said Lisa
McGiffert, a Consumers Union analyst who testified in support of
funding health coverage for all children in homes up to 200 percent
of the poverty line. ``It's about helping families who are working
and can't afford health insurance for their kids. It should stand
on its own.''
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders estimate the insurance program would cost the
state $153 million for the first year, but in a worst-case scenario
could escalate up to $360 million a year as more people enrolled.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, House Republicans are willing to pay for coverage of
children who are 8 years and younger in families with incomes up to
200 percent of the poverty level, said state Rep. Kenny Marchant,
R-Coppell.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he and other Republicans want to ``safeguard
against getting into a situation ... where the federal government
pulls its funding and we end up with an entitlement program.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
