<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-GIRLTALK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL TALK ISN'T WHAT IT USED TO BE EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and l coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA MATCHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Obviously, girl talk is not what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   Or so it was reasonable to conclude on Wednesday night when
Barbara Walters plied Monica Lewinsky with questions about her
compulsive tendency to talk about what she did with Bill Clinton.
``You told 10 other people you had this relationship with the
president,'' Walters exclaimed. ``I mean, Bigmouth! Why did you
want people to know?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I trusted my girlfriends implicitly,'' cooed Monica Lewinsky.
``And that's the kind of relationship I have with my close
friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Say what? Is this kind of tell-all relationship with friends
another one of the former White House intern's infinite quirks? Or
is her intimate confessional style what young women are trading in
these days?
</P>
<P>
   The answer seems to be that girltalk these days is racier,
spares less, and spills more. Even at that, say those who study and
write about young women's relationships, the Monica Lewinsky brand
of chitchat _ in all its florid detailing, its frankness about
sexual pleasure, and its sheer repetition factor _ is gossip at its
most extreme. ``It's Monica out of control,'' says social critic
Camille Paglia, who often writes about women's sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, there are no statistics ``to see if women are
confiding more than they used to be,'' observes Florence Isaacs,
author of the new book ``Toxic Friends/True Friends: How Your
Friends Can Make or Break your Health, Happiness, Family and
Career.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone interviewed agreed that unlike men, most women have
a visceral need to share intimate and provocative details of their
lives with their closest friends. ``Girls like to bond in ways that
reveal their innermost secrets,'' says Paglia. ``It's an
addiction.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think for women it's like a tree falling in the forest. If
no one hears it, it didn't really fall,'' says Meghan Daum, 29, who
writes a monthly column on cultural issues for Self magazine. ``You
know when Monica said she had to replay the phone answering machine
message for her friends? Everyone does that. It's a huge part of
being female, it's a ritual. The relationship has to be
validated.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Lewinsky's bold sexuality doesn't seem beyond the norm to
those 30 and under. ``It's not unusual in that generation,'' says
30-year-old writer and social commentator Katie Roiphe.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think women of her age are more in control of their
sexuality. This partly has to do with growing up in the last
glimmer of the sexual revolution. And I think that women in their
20s are more comfortable with the idea of sleeping with lots of
people than our mothers were,'' says Roiphe. ``People do talk about
sexual details. I don't think of that kind of sexual confession as
particularly unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course Lewinsky wasn't sharing just any old details. She was
getting down to the level of sperm and specific accessories.
</P>
<P>
   Leslie Yazel, 28, editor of the ``Friends'' page in Glamour
magazine, says, ``I was struck by the level of detail she would
tell friends about the cigar.''
</P>
<P>
   And everyone, it seems, was struck by how wide a net of ``best
friends'' Lewinsky cast. ``It doesn't seem surprising to me that
she would have confided to one or two close friends,'' says Roiphe.
``But the fact that she has these 10 best, best, best friends seems
to me most typical of the particular theatrical and needy emotional
type that Monica Lewinsky is. That says something about her, and
not a generation.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the maturing process happens when you realize you
don't have to tell everyone,'' says Jane Larkworthy, 36, beauty
editor of Jane, a lifestyle magazine for 18- to 34-year-olds.
Because what you are really saying is, `See, I'm loved, I'm
attractive.' ''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, laughs Larkworthy, ``I know lots of
respectable women who, if they had the chance to be intimate with
the president, would do it in a heartbeat. If nothing else, they'd
do it for the bragging rights.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
