<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-STRIKE-ZONE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT LONG LAST: STRIKES WILL BE STRIKES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT CHARLOTTE, Fla. _ Much yelping and other forms of verbal
disgust are expected to be heard across Florida and Arizona
starting today.
</P>
<P>
   Normal citizens should not be concerned, although a pair of ear
plugs might be necessary. Who wants to hear rich men cry?
</P>
<P>
   But all the commotion, if it occurs, will be about the game of
baseball attempting to do something unique. Like play by its own
set of rules. How revolutionary, huh?
</P>
<P>
   Beginning with spring training contests, the strike zone is
going up. Supposedly.
</P>
<P>
   For major-league hitters, that's almost the same as telling them
salaries are going down. I said almost.
</P>
<P>
   The point of silliness was reached in the postseason last fall.
``I'd say some of us \Rumpires\S got killed on TV,'' noted American
League umpire Durwood Merrill, referring to announcers making the
constant comparison of certain strike zones to a ``postage stamp.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can put this in the mail:
</P>
<P>
   Over the past decade in baseball the strike zone for many
umpires has transformed pitchers into modern day William Tells.
They have to hit an apple to get a called strike.
</P>
<P>
   By rule, the strike zone is supposed to be letters _ or chest
high _ to knees. The book has read that way for only 100 years. But
if umpires suddenly started calling it correctly, the strike zone
for today's pitchers would look like the Grand Canyon.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball would also be a crisper, quicker and better game if the
strike zone would suddenly become the strike zone again. But such a
thing was attempted a couple of years ago in spring training and,
by the ruckus it created, you would have thought the IRS had
eliminated tax shelters for .300 hitters.
</P>
<P>
   But commissioner Bud Selig's office is better organized and
better baseball staffed than any time in the past five decades, so
...
</P>
<P>
   Sandy Alderson, who works under Selig after being the highly
respected general manager in Oakland, issued a new edict several
weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The high strike, he told managers, would be called and enforced
starting in spring training and continuing in the regular season.
Way to be brave, Sandy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to go up,'' said Merrill, a 23-year veteran who is
known for a liberal horizontal strike zone. ``But I can guarantee
you, the first week of the season, if we go up with the strike
zone, ejections are also going way up.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires know well the ``hot spots'' for creating adversity with
players and managers. At the top of that list, Merrill said, is
calling a strike if a pitch is above the belly button.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's by far the biggest gripe we get,'' he said. ``You are
going to hear everything imaginable from the dugout, then you have
to stay on the dugout, and then they yell at you to get your head
out of their dugout, and you are telling them you aren't listening
to that stuff for nine innings, and then, of course, come the
ejections.''
</P>
<P>
   Will Merrill, a Hooks resident who is based out of Tampa in
spring training, be calling a higher strike today?
</P>
<P>
   ``If that's what \RSelig's office\S wants, I'd love to go up,''
he said. ``But at the same time, is the commissioner's office going
to back us when Mo Vaughn, Juan Gonzalez, Rafael Palmeiro and
players like that are being run \Rejected\S in the first week of
the season? Because it's going to happen. The fans pay to see the
stars, not see us running them.''
</P>
<P>
   Rangers second baseman Mark McLemore said it will be interesting
today in Sarasota, where the Rangers open Grapefruit League play
against the Cincinnati Reds. And if the ``high'' strike becomes
reality, ``then I'm gonna start adjusting,'' he shrugged. ``I'm not
gonna like it, but it's all about the survival of the fittest. You
can scream all you want, and many hitters will, but if enforced,
the screaming will mean you won't be around very long. The umpires
won't take much of that.''
</P>
<P>
   As the strike zone started to shrink, beginning in the '70s,
hitters gladly accepted the favor. Pitchers, meanwhile, were forced
to concede any pitch above the belt, and a ridiculous trend took
root.
</P>
<P>
   Johnny Oates is a manager who says none of his pitchers should
be making pitches in that area anyway. They are too hittable. But
on the flip side, the more strike zone a pitcher has to work with,
the more effective he becomes, even with the ``up'' pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Since all else has failed, why not simply revisit the rule book?
Let a strike be a strike and let the game move along at a more
rapid pace. It will work if Selig and Co. make it work.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe today we start finding out if the commissioner's office is
serious. If so, bring ear plugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
