<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8172 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CA-SUN-MEDIA-LADN     03-04 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CA-SUN-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEDIANEWS GROUP TO EXPAND SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA PRESENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ MediaNews Group Inc. announced Thursday that its Garden
State Newspapers affiliate and Donrey Media Group, which is owned
by Stephens Group Inc. of Little Rock, &UR;  &LR; Ark., have agreed to expand
their previously &UR;  &LR; announced California partnership to include the
San Bernardino Sun.
</P>
<P>
   The partnership will be managed by MediaNews.
</P>
<P>
   The Sun, owned by Gannett, the nation's largest newspaper
company, will be contributed to the partnership, adding 80,040
daily and 88,589 Sunday circulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The addition of The Sun to our group will consolidate the
rapidly growing Inland Empire region of the Los Angeles newspaper
market and allow better and more efficient service to our readers
and advertisers,'' said William Dean Singleton, president and CEO
of MediaNews and Garden State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are very excited about what this will bring to our
California group.''
</P>
<P>
   Ike Massey, president and CEO of the Los Angeles Newspaper Group
and publisher of the Daily News of Los Angeles, will be in charge
of the partnership's Southern California division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bringing the San Bernardino Sun into the partnership will give
the Los Angeles Newspaper Group more than 585,000 daily circulation
and more than 623,000 Sunday circulation,'' Massey said. ``Our
newspapers will reach across Los Angeles and San Bernardino
counties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Participation in California Newspapers Partnership provides
Gannett with the opportunity to better serve readers and
advertisers all across the Inland Empire,'' said Gary Watson,
president of Gannett's newspaper division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our decision in January to enter into a strategic partnership
with MediaNews Group, on its own, was a good one. That partnership
decision just got better with the addition of Gannett,'' said
Jackson T. Stephens, chairman of Stephens Group Inc., owner of
Donrey Media.
</P>
<P>
   Garden State announced the formation of the partnership on Jan.
12 with Donrey. An agreement was reached this week to include
Gannett.
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement as previously announced, Garden
State will contribute its Alameda Newspaper Group, which comprises
six daily newspapers published in the San Francisco Bay area; its
San Gabriel Valley Newspaper Group, which includes the San Gabriel
Valley Tribune, the Pasadena Star-News and the Whittier Daily News;
and the Times-Standard, a daily in Eureka.
</P>
<P>
   Donrey will contribute 10 daily newspapers and two nondaily
newspapers in California, most located close to Garden State
newspapers, including the Inland Valley Daily Bulletin in Ontario,
The Times-Herald in Vallejo, the Enterprise-Record in Chico, the
Hemet News, the Daily Democrat in Woodland, the Lompoc Record, the
Ukiah Daily Journal, the Red Bluff Daily News, the Mercury-News in
Oroville, the Redlands Daily Facts, the Advocate-News in Fort Bragg
and the Valley Times in Moreno Valley. Gannett will contribute the
San Bernardino Sun.
</P>
<P>
   Upon closing, the partnership will publish 21 daily newspapers
with daily circulation of 611,040 and Sunday circulation of
581,589.
</P>
<P>
   Garden State also owns and publishes the Daily News and the Long
Beach Press-Telegram. Those newspapers, with a combined daily
circulation of some 308,000, will not be contributed to the
partnership, but do operate as part of the Los Angeles Newspaper
Group.
</P>
<P>
   When the partnership transaction is completed later this month,
Garden State will publish 23 dailies in California with a combined
circulation in excess of 919,040 while Denver-based MediaMews
overall will publish a total of 51 daily newspapers and 119
nondaily publications in 13 states with daily circulation of more
than 1.8 million and nondaily circulation in excess of 2 million.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
