<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8178 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRO     03-04 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT CASTS LOVE ASUNDER
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Lynn Redgrave &LR; , 56, has filed for divorce after learning that
66-year-old  &UR; John Clark &LR; , her husband of 32 years, had fathered a
child by his personal assistant, who later married his son and
became his daughter-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really were one big happy family, of sorts,'' Clark told
the New York Daily News. It was last Thanksgiving, he said, that he
told Redgrave that the 4-year-old child was his. ``She was busy
cooking the turkey. We had guests. The entire holiday was pretty
awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, he said he was glad about his actions. ``My kids
were so slow giving us grandkids. I had to make our own.'' (See Who
Said What for more marital speculation.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MONICA MOMENTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Our five favorite moments from ``Monica's Story'' by &UR; Andrew &LR; 
 &UR; Morton &LR;  (St. Martin's; $24.95):
</P>
<P>
   _ The president told Monica about scars from his unhappy
childhood, when chubbiness caused him to run so slowly that he
never got any chocolate eggs at Easter.
</P>
<P>
   _ Monica told the president about scars from her unhappy
childhood, when she wasn't invited to Tori Spelling's birthday
party and her father wanted to spend only $500 on her bat mitzvah.
</P>
<P>
   _ The president gets romantic with Monica: ``If I were 25 years
old and not married, I would have you on the floor in three
seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Monica says that when locked up with Starr's inquisitors, she
seriously considered jumping out the hotel window to commit
suicide, until she realized that FBI snipers that might be posted
on surrounding rooftops might shoot at her.
</P>
<P>
   _ In a pre-interview meeting with  &UR; Barbara Walters &LR; , Monica
talked about how she had always been a good girl, not drinking, not
doing drugs, studying hard. ``Next time, shoplift,'' said Walters.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ New mother  &UR; Scary Spice &LR;  is commemorating her pregnancy by
ordering a statue of herself pregnant for her garden, reports
MSNBC.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Ute Moeller &LR; , chief makeup artist at the Fox News Channel in
Washington, told Washingtonian magazine that the only talking head
who won't let her apply makeup to his face is  &UR; Ralph Nader &LR; . She
also said the subjects who want to look sexiest are conservative
Republican women.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Sarah Ferguson  &LR; told Ladies' Home Journal that she's happy to
love herself. She knew, she said, ``that Diana had died not really
loving the person she was. I knew that I didn't want to die like
that. I wanted to know myself and get to loving myself.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, Ferguson added, ``Historically, many of the women who
left the royal family have been beheaded. But I've still got
mine.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LAW AND ORDER &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ On a westbound BART train the other morning, an East Bay man
commuting to his San Francisco office noticed that the man in the
seat behind him was using tiny scissors to trim his bonsai pine.
``Is that allowed?'' he asked a BART cop who happened to be
standing nearby. There are signs on BART that ban eating and
drinking and the playing of loud radios, the cop noted, but no
prohibition on bonsai.
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Richard O'Lone &LR;  notes, from reports in the Carmel (Calif.)
Pine Cone, that Carmelites are trying to figure out what to do
about ``the scruffy guy who shows up every Wednesday afternoon on
the main drag and salutes passers-by with an upraised single digit
on each hand.'' He is careful not to block the sidewalk and remains
at his post for about four hours before climbing into a vehicle and
driving away.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Hillary need not be odd to stay with him. ... How much do we
know even about our good friends? And their marriages are not set
in such extreme circumstances as is the Clintons'. Among the themes
of my book are that at the deep levels people are hard to know;
that for this reason and others, useful advice is hard to craft;
that the definition of a good marriage varies greatly among
couples; and that people do well to leaven standard self-help with
a hearty dose of their own private values, which may entail staying
longer than that sort of advice has recently advocated.''
</P>
<P>
   _ &LR;   &LR; Peter Kramer, author of ``Should You Leave?'' (Penguin;
$13.95), in response to Personals' asking him whether Hillary
should leave Bill Clinton.
</P>
