<HEADER>
A8181 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-700(2T     03-04 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARINE-AVIATOR-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINE PILOT WHOSE PLANE CUT GONDOLA CABLE IN ITALY, KILLING 20, IS
ACQUITTED
</HEADLINE>
 (See also MARINE-REACT)  
(fe) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD 
 
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
 
  CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. _ A Marine Corps pilot whose plane cut a
gondola cable in Italy last year, sending 20 people to their
deaths, was acquitted of involuntary homicide and manslaughter on
Thursday by a jury that found no negligence even though the plane
was flying lower and faster than rules permitted.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby, 31, of Mission Viejo, Calif.,
stood at attention to hear the verdict. There was no change in his
bearing as the president of the jury, Col. William T. Snow, said,
``This court finds you, of all the charges and specifications, not
guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilot's sister, Cary Lee Horsager, seated along with about
30 spectators in the spare military courtroom here, let out a
whoop. A prosecutor, Maj. Vernon S. Couch, turned to relatives of
three victims seated behind him to say, ``I'm sorry.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby's reaction was somber. ``Basically all I really want to
say is it's been a tragedy for all involved, and my heart and my
thoughts and prayers go out to the families of the victims of this
tragedy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The acquittal also stunned and angered people in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby still faces charges of obstruction of justice, as does his
navigator, Capt. Joseph P. Schweitzer, 30, of Westbury, N.Y.,
because they allegedly concealed a videotape on which they had
recorded part of the flight and which investigators thought might
be useful to determine what happened. The whereabouts of that tape
is still unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But after the verdict on Thursday, it was not certain whether
the Marines would still press homicide or manslaughter charges
against Schweitzer. During the flight on Feb. 3, 1998, Ashby sat at
the jet's single set of controls and Schweitzer sat to his right
and was the mission planner.
</P>
<P>
   Had Ashby been convicted, he faced up to 10 years in prison for
each death and would have been led directly to the brig. Instead,
the judge, Col. Robert Nunley, said, ``Captain Ashby is certainly
free to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The 17-day court-martial, along with pretrial hearings and two
Marine Corps investigations, made clear that lack of communications
led to the accident on the Mount Cermis gondola.
</P>
<P>
   But the verdict, delivered after seven hours of deliberations,
raised the possibility that the most serious punishments meted out
will have been against the squadron commander, who was relieved of
command, and the squadron's director of safety standardization, who
received a letter of reprimand that effectively ends his career.
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the victims, German skiers who were on vacation,
were tearful and outraged on Thursday. Sindy Renkewitz, whose
father and sister were on the cable car, along with her sister's
fiance, said she had worried that the Marine Corps jury would not
convict one of their own. ``There's a saying in Germany; it says,
one crow doesn't pick out the eye of the other one,'' said Ms.
Renkewitz.
</P>
<P>
   Rita Wunderlich said through a translator, ``I buried my husband
a year ago. Today it was his second funeral.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wunderlich, who was not present when Ashby spoke to
reporters after the verdict, said, ``If Mr. Ashby really feels
sorry and he told you so, why didn't he tell us?
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have looked into our eyes, but I don't know if he can
do that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my daughter had 20 persons on her conscience, it doesn't
matter whether guilty or innocent, I don't know if I could have
entered the courtroom,'' Ms. Wunderlich went on. ``And then I don't
know if she were declared innocent, if I could have screamed out of
joy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every normal person would have said he's guilty; it's only the
members of the jury and his defense attorneys who think that he was
innocent, and I cannot understand that,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was supposed to stay 1,000 feet above the ground but
hit the cables at about 360 feet.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the acquittal was no surprise; a hearing officer who
conducted eight days of hearings last year in a proceeding loosely
equivalent to a civilian grand jury, warned that convicting the
crew would be difficult because many parties were at fault.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A key question before the jury was whether Ashby's conduct
matched that of a ``reasonable pilot'' in the same or similar
circumstances. Investigations after the crash showed that hardly
anybody in the squadron could describe the rules correctly and that
the American charts, used by the Marines and the Air Force, did not
show the ski lift.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the plane may have had problems with its radar
altimeter, which measures distance above the ground. The crew,
flying the plane through typically aggressive maneuvers meant to
stay below the mountaintops and thus simulate radar evasion, may
have been flying the plane in a way that rendered the radar
altimeter useless, although they were relying on it to keep them
safe.
</P>
<P>
   In that sense, the acquittal was an indictment of the Marine
Corps' training, equipment, management and procedures, as well as
certain aspects of Air Force operations. Communications between the
Air Force squadron resident at Aviano and the Prowler squadrons
that rotated through were poor.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction prosecution, if it is successful, could lead to
a sentence of up to one year. But Frank Spinner, the civilian
lawyere representing Ashby, said he would appeal to Lt. Gen. Peter
Pace, the commander of Marine Forces, Atlantic, who ordered the
court-martial in the first place, to consider a less formal
disciplinary procedure that would result in a smaller punishment.
</P>
<P>
   Hiding the tape was ``regrettable,'' he said, ``but I don't
think it rises to the level of obstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Marines, Maj. Scott B. Jack, said Thursday
afternoon that ``the trial counsel is continuously re-evaluating
the aspects of the case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashby testified during the trial that it was his camera but
Schweitzer's tape. He said that Schweitzer did not use the camera
during the low-level portion of the flight, when the accident
occurred, and that he had taken the tape from the plane and later
given it to Schweitzer.
</P>
<P>
   Spinner told reporters that the verdict showed that the crash
was a training accident, not a crime. ``I think it's time, now that
the truth has come out in the court room, for the Marine Corps to
look back, at how this trial came about,'' he said. ``And I think
it's time for Congress perhaps to look at the Marine Corps once all
these issues are resolved and perhaps look at what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How is it that the Marine Corps could claim that Captain Ashby
committed an act of involuntary manslaughter, recklessness, and how
is it that a jury could acquit him of those same charges and even
lesser charges?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   The obstruction charge was added after the original charges, and
Ashby elected to face that in a second court-martial. Schweitzer
agreed to face all the charges at once. David Beck, who is
Schweitzer's civilian lawyer, said Thursday afternoon that he would
ask that the charges be dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Ashby was acquitted on 20 counts of involuntary manslaughter,
which carries a maximum sentence of 10 years per count, and lesser
charges of destruction of government property and private property.
Under the Uniform Code of Military Justice, the crash was a crime
if the pilot was negligent and an accident if he was not.
</P>
<P>
   If the jury had voted to convict, the relatives would have been
asked to testify in a ``penalty phase'' about the impact of the
accident on their lives. Their American lawyers are seeking special
legislation in Congress to compensate them; the Pentagon has told
them to pursue their claims through the Italian courts, a process
that the lawyers say will take eight to 12 years.
</P>
<P>
   Congress has, however, appropriated $20 million to rebuild the
ski lift.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
