<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0365 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8187 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANNIE-REVIEW05-COX     03-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANNIE-REVIEW05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stars ablaze in amiable `Annie'
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' which opened on Broadway
last night, Bernadette Peters finally has the sun-splashed,
melody-rich, girl-gets-boy musical that she has always deserved. At
50-going-on-30, the pocket goddess has no trouble commanding the
boys' attention, and in the strapping baritone Tom Wopat, she
finally has one worth getting.
</P>
<P>
   And Broadway at last _ just two months before the Tony Award
cutoff _ will have its first bona-fide hit musical of the season,
if there's any justice.
</P>
<P>
   That's a big if, however, considering that some elements of this
revival don't come close to the stars' level. If Peters and Wopat
weren't onstage so much, this Graciela Daniele production might
seem plastic and pat. Aside from a few witty, athletic dance turns
(choreography by Daniele and Jeff Calhoun), the show behind the two
stars is merely OK.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Berlin was once asked if he wrote songs for posterity and
answered, ``No, for prosperity.'' He was too modest; in ``Annie''
he did both. Working from a lively but not outstanding book about
the romance of 19th-century sharpshooters Annie Oakley and Frank
Butler, Berlin capped his career with one of the great scores in
Broadway history.
</P>
<P>
   The 1946 show is best remembered for the joyously explosive
voice of Ethel Merman, who, in ``There's No Business Like Show
Business,'' famously hit the ``No'' and ``Show'' notes of the song
like Annie blasting clay pigeons out of the sky. But the show was
also tailored for another Merman quality, or lack of it: sex
appeal.
</P>
<P>
   A revised book by the perennially overrated Peter Stone
(``Titanic'') is intended to clean up now-unacceptable attitudes.
The song ``I'm an Indian, Too'' has been axed; other cartoony
depictions of Native Americans might have been corrected by cutting
a few lines. But Stone bends over backward to give Sitting Bull and
the other Indians lots of weak jokes at the expense of the
palefaces, in the same way that TV children are always more clever
than their TV dads.
</P>
<P>
   Stone handled the gender issue more gracefully. Annie still
stoops to conquer, wins Frank's heart by letting him have the
lion's share of the sharpshooting glory, but Frank is rewritten
just enough that one sees a '90s-style man behind his tough old
chauvinist hide. While Wopat sings with deliberate sappiness of an
``Old-Fashioned Wedding,'' Peters struts around singing her faster
counterpoint about big, loud nuptials, making it clear that her
submissiveness was just an act to get him down the aisle. (The
number is so funny that the preview crowd called for two encores.)
This Annie suggests that as a wife she may be closer to
Shakespeare's Kate: a shrew untamed.
</P>
<P>
   In the hands of a lesser performer, this deception would
backfire. But Peters pulls it off, keeps the character lovable,
radiating a sensuality without surrender. Wopat, in addition to his
fine voice, has a buccaneerish masculinity far beyond the Ken dolls
who pass for musical leads these days. When the hourglass-shaped
Peters huskily murmurs, ``I just want to be near you, Frank,'' it's
not the laugh line of a lovesick puppy _ it's an offer no
red-blooded male can refuse.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the sparkling innocence of Peters, even more than her
allure, that lights the stage. ``I Got the Sun in the Morning'' has
been given a slower, swing tempo that better suits her voice, but
the song's simple message _ more spiritual than it gets credit for
_ shines through. Peters can play the tomboy clown, but it's in her
transformation to a graceful, stunning Victorian belle that she
steps from Merman's shadow. Peters has a great brass instrument of
a voice, but with a sweeter, melting quality that lends new magic
to ``Moonshine Lullaby'' and ``They Say It's Wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Clasping her hands to her chest on the cresting notes of the
latter, proclaiming love to be wonderful, wonderful, you have
absolutely no doubt that she knows it, and feels it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Annie Get Your Gun''
</P>
<P>
   Open-ended run. Marquis Theatre, 1535 Broadway, New York.
212-307-4100.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: The re-coronation of Queen Bernadette.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
