<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia singers don't make finals in opera tryouts
 &HT;    EDs: Embargoed for Sunday, March 7.
 &HT;    By Judith Green
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Neither winner of the Georgia district Metropolitan
Opera auditions will be going to New York for the finals in April.
The regional auditions, bringing together the winners from Georgia,
Florida and the Carolinas, were held last weekend at the Lovett
School in Atlanta, and the Georgians were outflanked by singers
from the neighboring states.
</P>
<P>
   Kirsten Marie Chavez, 28, a mezzo from Florida, and Laura
Ingram, 29, a soprano from North Carolina, tied for top honors and
will represent the Southeast region. Judges Paul Kilmer, artistic
administrator of the Opera Theater of St. Louis, Gail Robinson of
the Metropolitan Opera and Beverly Wolff, a voice teacher at
Florida Southern College, declined to name a first- or second-place
winner.
</P>
<P>
   Adina Aaron, 26, a soprano from Florida, won third place, and
Cynthia Watters, 24, a soprano from Carrollton, won an
encouragement award.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  STRINGERS: Jeffrey Schoyen, assistant
</P>
<P>
   professor of strings at the University of Nebraska
</P>
<P>
   in Kearney, wrote to praise William Pleeth,
</P>
<P>
   Jacqueline du Pre's teacher. In the credits of the
Oscar-nominated film ``Hilary and Jackie,'' he is listed as a
nameless ``cello teacher.'' He was, in fact, the largest reason _
beyond her natural talent _ for du Pre's artistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a teacher,'' says Schoyen, who studied with him, ``Pleeth
is as inspiring as du Pre was as a player. His imagination had no
boundaries, and he would encourage me not to blindly accept a
traditional interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   That kind of open thinking is obvious in the musical showmanship
of his showiest student, and it's presented in stark contrast (in
the film) to the Royal College of Music flute teacher who kills off
the musical gifts of Hilary du Pre, Jacqueline's sister.
</P>
<P>
   Schoyen, an Atlanta native, said another fine Atlanta cellist,
Lawrence Foster, studied with Pleeth. Foster was shot and killed in
the city in 1980. Pleeth, now in his 80s, still maintains an active
teaching schedule in London.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ALMOST A NEW FACE: William L. Baites, formerly interim
director of the Rialto Center for the Performing Arts, is now the
official director. Baites previously was director of the concert
series at Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  DOVE AND CROW: The piece Marietta Simpson sang at the Atlanta
Symphony Orchestra's Jan. 29 tribute concert to Robert Shaw is
generally known as ``Sometimes I Feel Like a Motherless Child.''
The arrangement of this familiar spiritual for alto and choir, by
Shaw and Alice Parker, is titled ``Sometimes I Feel Like a Moanin'
Dove.'' Thanks to reader John B. White Jr. for his interest and
research.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  E-mail: jgreen(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Judith Green writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
