<HEADER>
A8189 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PEOPLE-BIRTHDAY05-COX     03-04 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEOPLE-BIRTHDAY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Magazine that changed the way America looks at celebrities turns
25
 &HT;    By Bo Emerson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   People, ``the mother of all human interest magazines,'' is
celebrating its 25th anniversary by taking over the world, or at
least the newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrity-studded weekly, which in 1974 invented
``personality journalism'' and changed the definition of news, is
the most lucrative weekly in the country, earning, it says, even
more than big brother Time.
</P>
<P>
   People discovered, way back in 1974, that Americans were hungry
for the dish on Burt and Dinah; Cher and Gregg; Andy and Fergie.
Unlike the Hollywood fan mags and tabloids, People covered
celebrities with Time's hard-news sensibility.
</P>
<P>
   Today, mainstream media is following People's lead. Newsweeklies
profile rock stars. Women's service magazines feature the faces of
Oprah Winfrey and Julia Roberts out front, whereas 20 years ago,
``their covers were chocolate cakes,'' says former People managing
editor Richard Stolley.
</P>
<P>
   In its wake came the entertainment media boom. Magazines (Us,
the revamped Vanity Fair, Entertainment Weekly); television shows
(``Enter-
</P>
<P>
   tainment Tonight''); and an entire cable channel _ the E!
Network _ were inspired or made possible by People's success.
</P>
<P>
   Even USA Today took a page from People's approach, with its
short stories and multiple photographs, says Samir Husni, professor
of journalism at the University of Mississippi.
</P>
<P>
   People has done its own proliferating, spinning off publications
on celebrity fashion and housing (the remarkably successful
InStyle), teen celebrities (Teen People), and Spanish-speaking
celebrities (People En Espanol.). Even People's spinoffs have
imitators, witnessed by the new InStyle wannabes, Celebrity Style
and McCall's brand new (launched Feb. 23) StarStyle.
</P>
<P>
   It's no accident that the apotheosis of modern celebrity,
Princess Diana, is the most popular People cover girl (she's
appeared 50 times), or that the magazine's best seller (at 5.2
million copies) was devoted to Diana's death.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine claims an audience of one in five American adults.
Its circulation is 3.6 million, but People says its ``pass-along''
numbers are high _ roughly 10 pairs of eyeballs on every copy sold,
or 36 million readers. (People sells 80,000 copies in metro
Atlanta.)
</P>
<P>
   The magazine's guiding logic revolves around understanding the
arc of a celebrity's ``hotness'' and by Stolley's laws, which
define a strict hierarchy of desirability. For a cover image, the
maxim goes, young is better than old, pretty is better than ugly,
rich is better than poor, and ``nothing,'' says Stolley, now a
senior editorial advisor, ``is better than the celebrity dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Celebrity grief, called OPP, or ``other people's problems'' at
story meetings, is also a mainstay. It allows readers to identify
with the personality, says managing editor Carol Wallace, and to
put their own problems in perspective. ``They think, `God, famous
people get sick, famous people have divorces, famous people get
married and have babies.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes People must profile an uncooperative subject _ called
a ``writearound'' _ as in the controversial Chelsea Clinton cover
story. But more often the star will participate. Michael J. Fox
approached the magazine when he wanted to tell the story of his
ordeal with Parkinson's disease, and People obtained exclusive
access to Barbra Streisand's 1998 wedding to James Brolin.
</P>
<P>
   The access might come with a price tag _ People had to pay
$175,000 to Elizabeth Taylor's favorite charity to shoot her
wedding to Larry Fortensky _ but the editors say they never pay for
stories or relinquish editorial control.
</P>
<P>
   Another mainstay is the ``real people'' story, such as the
account of a dad who hiked 48 miles through snow to save his
family, or the tot who survived devastating burns. People defines
its stories as ``ordinary people doing extraordinary things.''
</P>
<P>
   Occasionally all these elements come together, as when the
magazine sketched the tragedy of AIDS through the life of a little
boy named Ryan White. ``That put a human face to this story,'' says
People's president Nora McAniff.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's not the magazine's coverage of the Oklahoma bombing
or the Hitler diaries that attracts so many readers (two-thirds of
whom are women), but such perennial creampuffs as its ``Sexiest Man
Alive'' and ``The 50 Most Beautiful People in the World'' issues.
Syracuse University professor of pop culture Robert Thompson calls
these bon-bons ``reading material for people who like to watch
television.''
</P>
<P>
   An airheaded reputation has dogged the magazine from the
beginning. People was a punchline in ``The Big Chill,'' when it
served as an emblem of empty fluff (''It's just good investigative
journalism'' deadpanned Jeff Goldblum, playing a People reporter.)
</P>
<P>
   But readers don't care. ``They can take shots at us, but in the
end I know, and 36 million readers know, that we produce quality
journalism,'' says Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   McAniff demonstrates her magazine's attraction by leaving a copy
in the waiting room when she visits advertisers. She guarantees
that the magazine will be gone when the meeting adjourns. It is.
``We are,'' she says, ``the most stolen magazine in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Bo Emerson writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
