</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARIZ-GERMANY-EXECUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA EXECUTES GERMAN MAN IN GAS CHAMBER  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ A German citizen was executed in a gas chamber in
Arizona on Wednesday night, leading Germans Thursday to accuse the
United States of ``barbarism'' and of flouting international law.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate, Walter LaGrand, 37, was put to death in a cloud of
cyanide gas for his role in the 1982 murder of a bank manager.
</P>
<P>
   LaGrand's brother, Karl, 35, was executed last week in Arizona
for his role in the same crime.
</P>
<P>
   The LaGrands were convicted in 1982 of stabbing Walter Hartsock
to death in a botched bank robbery.
</P>
<P>
   Both brothers chose the gas chamber in the hope that courts
would find the method unconstitutional. But when this tactic
failed, Karl LaGrand accepted a last-minute offer of a lethal
injection on Feb. 24.
</P>
<P>
   Walter LaGrand opted for the gas, with its resonance of the
Holocaust for Germans. That potent symbolism fueled the outcry
here, with members of Parliament calling for sanctions against the
United States and radio stations flooded with indignant calls.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is barbaric and unworthy of a state based on the rule of
law,'' Justice Minister Herta Daeubler-Gmelin said.
</P>
<P>
   Walter and Karl LaGrand were born in Augsburg, Germany, but
moved to Arizona as infants after their mother married a U.S.
soldier she had met in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Germany has no death penalty. Both Ms. Daeubler-Gmelin and
Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer had appealed for clemency, saying
the LaGrands had been denied their rights as German citizens
because prosecutors did not inform the German consulate of the
brothers' arrest in 1982 until a decade later.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Dee Hull rejected the appeals, saying the LaGrands had
enjoyed the same rights any U.S. citizen would have had. Arizona
officials conceded, however, that the Vienna Convention, under
which the LaGrands should have been advised of their right to
consular assistance at their trial, had not been observed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2028EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
