<SLUG> BC-BANKBOS-FUND-UNIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKBOSON FUND UNIT TO HEIGHTEN SUPERVISION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN WILMSEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ After an inquiry by state securities regulators,
BankBoston's mutual fund unit Thursday agreed to beef up
supervision of its sales force to prevent ``switching,'' the
practice of steering customers toward new investments to generate
fees and commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Without admitting any wrongdoing, BankBoston Investor Services
agreed to monitor all mutual fund transactions and hire an outside
auditor to review the bank's mutual fund activities for the next
two years, according to a pact with the Massachusetts Securities
Division.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement requires the bank to tell customers the reasons it
recommends switching from one mutual fund to another and warns them
that such a change could result in extra fees and taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The bank must also set up an automated surveillance program that
produces daily lists of potential switch transactions and conduct
yearly seminars for members of its sales force, according to the
agreement. The bank also agreed to pay a $22,000 fine to cover the
cost of the securities division's investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is all about enhancing consumer protection,'' said
Matthew Nestor, director of the securities division. ``It will make
sure customers are informed and make sure decisions are made for
sound investment reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   BankBoston officials claimed the state's review failed to
uncover evidence of switching at the bank but it agreed to the
changes to ensure ``the protection of our customers,'' said bank
spokesman John Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were no violations or complaints, and we already had
strong proceedures in place,'' he said. ``While there was an
inquiry, what we did was voluntarily enhnace some policies.''
</P>
<P>
   The division began its inquiry last August after receiving a tip
that the bank's sales staff may have inappropriately encouraged
customers to shift from no-load, or no-fee, mutual funds into
fee-bearing load funds and annuities.
</P>
</TEXT>
