<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-PAINS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLARINET PLAYERS SOUGHT FOR RESEARCH ON PERFORMANCE PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHARLOTTE HUFF 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It all starts with the thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Years of devotion to the clarinet can weigh heavily on the
digit, sometimes triggering pain up through the wrist and hand to
the shoulder and neck.
</P>
<P>
   North Texas researchers are searching for 60 clarinetists to
help study better playing techniques for fiercely competitive
musicians who are often slow to help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years in the music business, if you showed a sign of
weakness, it meant you were on the way out,'' said John Scott, a
clarinet professor in the College of Music at the University of
North Texas in Denton.
</P>
<P>
   The study is the first by researchers at the Texas Center for
Music &AMP; Medicine to look at the mechanics of instrument playing.
The center was jointly launched last year by UNT and the University
of North Texas Health Science Center in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   In a world filled with sports medicine information, too little
is understood about how or when musicians suffer
performance-related muscle and nerve damage, said Kris Chesky,
research assistant professor in UNT's College of Music. The
clarinet, Chesky said, presented a good starting point, because
most of the instrument's weight falls in one place.
</P>
<P>
   And therein lies the problem, said Dr. Bernard Rubin, chief of
rheumatology at UNT Health Science Center, who co-directs the
center with Chesky.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get a tendinitis at the wrist or at the forearm, similar
to what you see with tennis players, with the force that they have
to grip the racket,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   The thumb, he added, is not just called upon to support the
instrument, but also to push it toward the mouth, creating a seal.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your thumb gets tired,'' Rubin said, ``you must grip the
mouth tighter to get that seal, so then people complain of jaw and
neck problems.''
</P>
<P>
   If they complain at all.
</P>
<P>
   Scott, faced with pain in his left arm five years ago, sought
help only when it became so fierce that he had difficulty gripping
a toothbrush or writing more than a few sentences. For the first
time in his 40-something years, Scott started stretching before he
lifted the instrument and wore an arm brace, both of which he
credits with providing some relief.
</P>
<P>
   Did he continue to play?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' he said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Next on the center's program: research into the drum and the
trumpet.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
