</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADMINISTRATION NAMES PROFESSOR CHIEF COUNSELOR OF PRIVACY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By   JOEL BRINKLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration has appointed an
opinionated law professor from Ohio State University as the
government's new chief counselor of privacy, just as the United
States and Europe try to resolve a serious disagreement over
privacy regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Peter P. Swire, a specialist in privacy law, will start work in
the Office of Management and Budget next week with the mission of
coordinating administration privacy initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore said Thursday that he welcomed the
appointment, adding that Swire ``will provide expertise on privacy
issues, helping to find an appropriate balance between individual
privacy rights and the legitimate use of personal information by
government and the private sector.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gore promised to appoint a privacy `czar' in response
to complaints that the administration's privacy initiatives were
uncoordinated. Now, however, a Commerce Department official, not
Swire, will mediate the dispute between Europe and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   And the Federal Trade Commission, another important source of
privacy regulation and enforcement, operates largely independent of
the administration.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute with the European Union involves Europe's law, which
took effect at the end of October, prohibiting the transfer of
personal information to countries that do not have adequate rules
to protect it. EU officials have made it clear that they do not
regard this country's privacy protections to be adequate, and the
Clinton administration is in negotiations with the EU to avert
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Swire, along with Robert Litan of the Brookings Institution,
published a book on the subject last fall entitled: ``None of Your
Business: World Data Flows, Electronic Commerce, and the European
Privacy Directive.''
</P>
<P>
   In it, he wrote: ``Unlike the nations of Western Europe, the
United States does not have a single, comprehensive privacy law.
Nor does it have an agency charged with administering privacy law.
The United States approach to date has been more selective,
regulating the private sector fairly strictly in certain areas, but
not legislating for a wide range of uses.''
</P>
<P>
   An administration official said Swire's job will be to work with
the several federal agencies that have responsibilities in this
area to make sure the government's approach is coordinated, but he
will not set policy.
</P>
<P>
   Swire said the OMB had asked him not to accept interviews. But
Litan, who wrote the book on privacy with Swire, said, ``I think
Peter will be very successful. He has a tremendous facility for
getting people from different backgrounds to work together. And
he's extremely knowledgeable about privacy and the EU directive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
