<HEADER>
A8202 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHURCHFIRES05-COX     03-04 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHFIRES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Burned churches cope with fraud surrounding aid
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel and Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOLIGEE, Ala. _ After three black baptist churches burned here
within three weeks of each other starting around Christmas 1995,
money for rebuilding poured in. Nearly $300,000 in donations flowed
into a town with less than 1,000 people, a general store and a post
office that closes for lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Like dozens of rural outposts in the South, Boligee welcomed the
bounty that came as part of a national response to the rash of
church fires that occurred during the next two years. The National
Council of Churches in New York distributed many of the private
donations, awarding $6.6 million nationwide since 1996. The NCC has
given 149 grants in 32 states _ including $220,000 in Boligee.
</P>
<P>
   Southern churches have received three-quarters of the grants.
Nationally, 78 churches rebuilt or bought new buildings, and
another 71 are building or planning.
</P>
<P>
   But the money managed by the NCC was only a fraction of the
donations and insurance settlements spent since church fires caught
the attention of President Clinton in 1996, and a smattering of
fraud has seeped through.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the president of one of the country's largest black
religious organizations was convicted in Florida for grand theft of
donations intended to rebuild churches. A jury ruled that the Rev.
Henry Lyons, head of the National Baptist Convention, took $244,500
in donations from the Anti-Defamation League and put $60,000 of it
into a personal savings account and gave $12,000 to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented evidence that Lyons wrote the ADL,
claiming he had given $70,000 to Boligee churches. Pastors,
however, testified receiving only one-third that amount.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have a lot of money flowing, particularly a lot of
money in a small community, it upsets the balance,'' said Betsey
Miller, head of the Church Rebuilding Project for the National
Council of Churches. While he was mayor of Boligee, A.L. ``Buddy''
Lavendar said personal contributions began flowing to him ranging
from $5 in cash to a $5,000 check. The 71-year-old ended up
collecting $40,000 _ nearly three times the Greene County annual
median household income of $14,300. He established a local
rebuilding fund controlled by Boligee's three burned churches and
himself. The Mount Zion, Little Zion and Mount Zora churches all
have been rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   Since accepting donations, Lavendar has been accused by the
local newspaper of spending some of the money on a personal
vacation, been the subject of an investigation urged by local
pastors, lost re-election and filed a $6 million libel suit,
claiming the published allegations are untrue. Later, a former
Mount Zion deacon was indicted on charges he stole $10,500 in
donations.
</P>
<P>
   There were other contributions solicited by local and national
organizations that never made it to Boligee, Lavendar claims.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got stopped on the way _ and that's above what I got and
what Lyons got,'' Lavendar said.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, though, donations have been a blessing.
</P>
<P>
   The Mount Olive Full Gospel Church in south Fulton County, Ga.,
burned in 1994 and relied on $100,000 in donations to rebuild _
including $34,500 from the NCC. Pastor Horace Lewis said he spent
months writing for help. Lyons' deception diverted funds he could
have used.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything that shines is not gold,'' Lewis said. ``This was
an opportunity for people to go out and do things like that, go out
and take advantage of the churches and fires.''
</P>
<P>
   During reconstruction, Lewis sent building proposals and
schedules to the NCC. Volunteers rebuilt the sanctuary on eight
consecutive Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   The fire at Lewis' church and the three in Boligee are among 427
pending investigations _ two-thirds of the 670 cases covered by the
National Church Arson Task Force from January 1995 to the present.
The task force opened 89 investigations in 1997, and 55 through
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials said the arrest last month of Scott Ballinger
in Indiana may account for up to 50 fires in the South and Midwest.
Still, that would leave hundreds of cases unsolved. The task force
has concluded there is no evidence of a national conspiracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never claimed there was a national conspiracy,'' said Ken
Jacobson, assistant director for the Anti-Defamation League. ``One
doesn't have to conclude there's a conspiracy to conclude there's a
serious problem.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Clinton pledged government-backing for up to $10
million in loans for burned churches. Of an estimated 200 churches
eligible, only 12 have applied.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Housing and Urban Development has
approved eight loan requests totaling $2 million, said deputy
director Tony Johnston. The agency is processing another two
requests, he said. It turned down two others because, in one case,
the fire was ruled accidental. In the other, the church's
documentation was insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   If a church defaults on a HUD-approved loan, the government
repays the lender. In exchange for the guarantee, banks lend money
at below-market interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the flow of loans has been slow.
</P>
<P>
   HUD is preparing to offer greater technical assistance to
churches in preparing loan applications that will satisfy banks and
the federal agency's strict requirements, Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
