<SLUG> BC-DELAY-ACCUSATIONS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELAY `CLEARS THE AIR' IN ASSERTING CHARGES, RUMORS ARE FALSE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Majority Whip Tom DeLay vigorously defended
himself Thursday against published reports that he may have lied
under oath and against rumors that he had an extramarital affair
that produced an illegitimate child.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last four months I have been accused of perjury,
accepting illegal honoraria and being the biological father of my
foster children, '' DeLay said in a statement, asserting that all
of the charges are false.
</P>
<P>
   The public defense followed a private meeting Wednesday with a
group of his deputy whips, where the Houston-area Republican said
the reports and rumors were part of a conspiracy by the White House
and Democratic lawmakers to ruin his reputation because of his
forceful advocacy of President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   A close aide to the Texan said DeLay wanted to ``clear the air''
by answering any questions his colleagues had about stories
regarding his conduct in a lawsuit five years ago. He also has been
dogged by rumors, largely unpublished but making the rounds on
Capitol Hill, that he had an affair while in the Texas Legislature
more than 15 years ago that produced a child, whom he later took
into his home under a foster care program.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement, DeLay expressed outrage at the rumors. He
called them ``the most despicable charge of all.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My response is that I am the proud foster parent of two
children and I will continue to be regardless of how my political
enemies try to exploit my foster children for political gain,''
DeLay said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a cleansing thing for Tom,'' the aide said of his
meeting with colleagues. DeLay decided to respond to the
allegations partly because ``some members were getting questioned
about them'' by reporters and constituents.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were being asked questions they couldn't answer,'' the
aide said, ``and Tom wanted to let them know that none of this is
true.''
</P>
<P>
   The charge that he may have lied under oath in a lawsuit brought
by a former business partner five years ago stemmed from published
reports a month ago. But rumors about an extramarital affair that
produced a child have not been widely reported, except in a New
York Post gossip column last month that was later picked up by a
political newsletter. A Capitol Hill newspaper printed but then
retracted a story that DeLay had accepted more honoraria than
allowed by law.
</P>
<P>
   Although DeLay and his aides have charged that the accusations
were being circulated by Democrats out to get him, elements of them
were floated as long ago as two years by Texas Republicans, some of
whom have counted themselves among his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Chronicle reported in January that DeLay, facing a
lawsuit brought by a former partner in Albo Pest Control Inc.,
denied under oath in a February 1994 deposition that he was an
officer or director of the company and then backtracked to say he
couldn't recall what position he held.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to the deposition and afterward, however, DeLay filed
financial disclosure forms with Congress listing himself as
chairman of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute with former business partner Robert Blankenship was
settled out of court in January, 1995. But Blankenship and his
Houston attorney, Gerald De Nisco, said they were unaware of the
congressional filings at the time or they would have raised them as
an issue with the court.
</P>
<P>
   De Nisco told the Chronicle that DeLay, in his view, either lied
in the deposition about being an officer or director in the company
to avoid any financial liability, or lied on his financial
disclosure reports.
</P>
<P>
   In his whip meeting Wednesday, DeLay offered what his aides
described as a ``clarifying document'' that he said was sent to the
court five months after the deposition. One of his aides said it
was designed to correct any ``misimpressions'' that may have been
left by his deposition.
</P>
<P>
   But the document filed in July 1994 was an amended pleading and
counterclaim filed in response to the Blankenship lawsuit, and it
did not specifically address the deposition DeLay gave five months
earlier. It did, however, make clear that DeLay was indeed both a
director and officer in the company.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay said in his statement Thursday that he couldn't remember
``my formal role in the company'' at the time of the deposition,
which is why he later filed ``a formal pleading to the court
clarifying any confusion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that this was never an issue in the case. It was
never an issue at the time of the deposition,'' he said, suggesting
that his political opponents raised it only after he began
demanding that Clinton be impeached for lying under oath in the
Monica Lewinsky matter. DeLay continued to insist that he did not
commit perjury ``or pull a Clinton under oath.''
</P>
<P>
   In response, De Nisco said Thursday that the amended pleading
filed by DeLay after the deposition ``still doesn't mitigate the
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of taking the deposition, the guy perjured
himself. There is no doubt in my mind that the guy looked me in the
eye and perjured himself,'' De Nisco said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
