<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TURKISH-COINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONAIRE AGREES TO RETURN ANCIENT COINS TO TURKEY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a, w and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANNE E. KORNBLUT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Capitulating to claims that he was hoarding ancient
treasure, billionaire William I. Koch says he will deliver nearly
1,700 coins to the Republic of Turkey, settling a massive lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement came a full decade after the lawsuit was filed in
Boston federal court, and was somewhat unexpected: Koch, a
businessman and America's Cup winner with a history of waging
lengthy lawsuits, had insisted that the coins rightfully belonged
to him and his two partners _ and won support for his claim from a
former curator at the Museum of Fine Arts in Boston. The Turkish
government, meanwhile, represented by New York attorney Lawrence M.
Kaye, had vowed not to relent until the entire hoard had been
returned.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's settlement was a clear indication of the strength
of the Turkish case, and signified a great victory for Turkish
officials, who have made a 10-year crusade out of retrieving lost
artifacts and works of art. Under the agreement, Turkey will get
the coins; Koch, in return, will have his name carved into a plaque
where the coins will be displayed in Turkey, with a statement that
reads: ``With special appreciation for the American businessman
William I. Koch.''
</P>
<P>
   The coins include Athenian decadrachmas some 2,000 years old,
according to the Turkish government, which are believed to be worth
several million dollars.
</P>
<P>
   The treasure _ variously described as the ``Elmali Hoard,''
after the region in southern Turkey where it was found, and the
``King Tut of numismatics discoveries'' by experts in the classics
world _ has been in dispute virtually ever since it was unearthed
in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Three peasant farmers discovered the collection with nothing
more than a handheld metal detector, then cleaned the coins and
sold them to well-known coin smugglers in the Grand Bazaar in
Istanbul, according to Turkish officials. The peasants were caught
and prosecuted; the coins, meanwhile, made their way out of Turkey
and into foreign hands, in violation of Turkish law.
</P>
<P>
   Even as the Turkish government began an international hunt in
pursuit of the collection, the coins were scattered around the
globe, with some landing as far away as Los Angeles, in the
possession of former LA Kings owner Bruce McNall. McNall later
returned his coins, when the Turkish government noisily protested.
But Koch and his partners, who had bought the vast majority of the
coins for approximately $3 million, did not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Koch and his two partners, Jeffrey Spier and Jonathan
H. Kagan, refused to publicly acknowledge the coins had even come
from southern Turkey, and at no point during the dispute publicly
admitted they were in the wrong. In a statement provided for a
Globe article about the hoard last December, Koch insisted the
coins were not the same ones claimed by Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   Supporting the defendants' claims that the coins were not the
lost Turkish hoard was Cornelius C. Vermeule III, the curator of
the classical art department at the MFA for nearly 40 years before
retiring in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   After learning from Kagan, a partner at the investment firm of
Lazard Freres, that he might be able to buy the coins, Koch turned
to the MFA to get them authenticated. Vermeule, an idiosyncratic
expert known for his sharp memory and his fluency in seven
languages, examined the hoard and encouraged Koch to buy it.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly thereafter, however, Vermeuele received a letter from a
bank manager in Switzerland, warning him that Turkish officials
were searching for the illegally-smuggled hoard. But rather than
warn Koch against the purchase, Vermeule sent the billionaire a
letter advising just the opposite. Koch apparently did not hesitate
before buying the coins.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15 years that followed, one problem arose after the next.
Several dealers became suspicious of the coins. Then two Turkish
journalists, Meylik Keylan and Ozgen Acar, wrote a story about the
hoard for Connoisseur Magazine, informing the art world that one of
the great coin discoveries of the world had been ferreted out of
its native land and hidden in an American businessman's vault.
Three years later, in 1989, Turkey filed suit.
</P>
<P>
   Koch _ who last made headlines in Boston when he sued his
mistress, Catherine de Castelbajac, in housing court, for refusing
to leave his Four Seasons penthouse _ Thursday accepted an
invitation from the Turkish Ministry of Culture to travel to Turkey
for a ceremony returning the coins. In a statement, he neither
admitted guilt nor accepted the Turkish government's claim that the
coins originated in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Koch said: ``I want the Turkish people to enjoy these
coins for years to come.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
