<HEADER>
A8208 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ALA-GAY-ATTACK-450&AMP;AD     03-04 0641
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALA-GAY-ATTACK-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECTS CONFESS TO KILLING MAN WHO THEY SAY MADE HOMOSEXUAL
ADVANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Two Alabama men told the authorities this week that
they beat a man to death with an ax handle last month and then
burned his body because the victim had previously made a homosexual
advance to them.
</P>
<P>
   Al Bradley, a sheriff's deputy in Coosa County, Ala., a rural
area between Birmingham and Montgomery, said Thursday that the two
men had confessed this week, after waiving their right to counsel,
and were then charged with the Feb. 19 murder of Billy Jack
Gaither, a 39-year-old textile worker.
</P>
<P>
   The suspects, both of whom are being held in the Coosa County
jail in lieu of $500,000 bond, are Steven Eric Mullins, 25, and
Charles Monroe Butler Jr., 21. Both are construction workers from
Sylacauga, Ala., Bradley said. Butler confessed on Monday and
Mullins on Wednesday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This Steven Mullins, the Butler boy and the Gaither man were
acquaintances,'' Bradley said in a telephone interview. ``How long
they've known each other is not determined. But we do know they had
known each other at least two weeks, because that's when Mullins
said Gaither approached them in a sexual manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing took place at the time,'' he continued, ``but Mullins
states in his confession that that made him upset, that he didn't
like it because Gaither was gay.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that Mullins called Gaither at home on the night of
the killing and that Gaither then drove to pick up Mullins and
Butler at their homes. They drove to a reservoir outside of
Sylacauga, where the two suspects beat Gaither and placed him in
the trunk of his car. They then drove the car to Mullins' house,
picked up some kerosene, matches and two old tires, and drove to an
isolated area known as Peckerwood Creek.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy said the suspects lighted the tires with the
kerosene, removed Gaither from the trunk, beat him in the head with
an ax handle and then placed his body on the burning tires.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died of severe blunt head trauma,'' Bradley said. ``Once
they saw that the body was going to burn they drove Gaither's car
to a landfill in Sylacauga and burned it up.'' Gaither's remains
were found the next day by a passerby.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said that Butler emerged as a suspect after he told a
friend about the crime and said he was having trouble sleeping. The
friend tipped off the authorities, who then arrested the two
suspects, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of gay rights groups quickly compared Gaither's killing
to that of Matthew Shepard, a 21-year-old gay college student in
Laramie, Wyo., who was kidnapped last October after leaving a bar
and was then severely beaten and tied to a fence for 18 hours. Two
men have been charged with Shepard's murder.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``What's becoming very clear is that hate in this country is
turning lethal with alarming frequency,'' said David M. Smith, a
spokesman for the Human Rights Campaign, a gay and lesbian
political group in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Gaither had worked for 19 years at a large distribution center
for Russell Corp., a manufacturer of sporting apparel, in Alexander
City, Ala. Bobbie Jo Story, a co-worker at the center, said Gaither
lived with his parents and was well-liked.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a real nice, loving boy, good hearted,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   An article Thursday in The Birmingham News quoted Gaither's
father, Marion H. Gaither, as saying that he did not believe his
son had been gay and that he suspected robbery as the motive for
the killing.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said, ``We have no reason to believe that the statements
Mullins and Butler gave us about him being gay are not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Marion Gaither, reached at his home Thursday, declined to
comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
