<HEADER>
A8212 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-TRADE-600(2TAKE     03-04 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-TRADE-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. CALLS CHINA TRADE TALKS `PRODUCTIVE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also CHINA-ZHOU) 
(js) 
 By ELISABETH ROSENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ After two days of meetings, China and the United
States have ``made important progress'' in defining terms for China
to join the World Trade Organization, said the United States'
senior trade official. But the official cautioned that there were
still significant differences between the countries and ``a number
of issues remained to be addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese government has exhibited a very serious attitude
and strength of purpose that has helped to make this week
particularly productive,'' said Charlene Barshefsky, the U.S. trade
representative, who said that she had met for over two hours with
Prime Minister Zhu Rongji.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the many caveats, Ms. Barshefsky's remarks were by far
the most optimistic assessment in many months of China's chances of
joining the WTO, the Geneva-based organization that sets the rules
for international trade. She said that her chief negotiators would
remain in the Chinese capital to work on a more detailed plan,
although she refused to elaborate on areas of concern.
</P>
<P>
   China has long sought entry into the organization, but on the
more lenient conditions offered to third-world countries. The
United States has countered that China's economy is too large to be
classed among the world's poorest nations.
</P>
<P>
   Just three months ago, Chinese and U.S. officials were saying
that membership in the organization was a dead issue this year,
convinced that China's current economic slowdown would make it
impossible for the country to open its markets to the extent
required for membership.
</P>
<P>
   But the prospect of more stringent trade organization entrance
requirements in the future, as well as the need for an image-lift
before Zhu's visit to Washington next month, have rekindled
interest in a deal. On Thursday, Chinese officials seemed
determined to make a run at membership in the organization,
whatever the short-term economic pains.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Barshefsky said that two or three months ago, Chinese
officials suddenly ``indicated that they wished to re-engage in
earnest'' _ a request that has been followed by a series of
negotiations, culminating in Ms. Barshefsky's visit to Beijing this
week, ``at the request of the Chinese government.''
</P>
<P>
   Some experts say the new enthusiasm is related to the fact that
Taiwan, which China regards as a breakaway province, is itself
concluding membership negotiations. But a stronger impetus seems to
be that the trade organization is expected to redraw the membership
requirements this fall at a meeting in Seattle, and many believe
that entrance requirements will get stiffer at that time.
</P>
<P>
   ``If China doesn't become a member before the Seattle meeting
later this year, the issue will drag on for years,'' said Ji
Chongwei, a senior researcher in the central government's
Development and Research Center. ``I personally think it is hopeful
that China can reach an agreement with the U.S. in the near
future.''
</P>
<P>
   The need to mend fences before Zhu's visit to the United States
next month has also put pressure on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   The collegial relationship that the United States and China
built up through early 1998, culminating with President Clinton's
visit last summer, has been deteriorating since late last year,
bruised by Beijing's renewed crackdown on political dissidents and
other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Although Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright took great
pains to promote cordial engagement when she visited here this
week, the two sides have exchanged harsh words over human rights,
defense policy and technology exchanges in recent months.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing and Washington, there is hope that progress toward
China joining the organization would patch up the facade if not the
substance of the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both China and the U.S. hope to make some breakthroughs on
bilateral relations during Zhu Rongji's visit,'' said Xue Ning, a
researcher at the World Trade Organization Shanghai Research
Center, a Chinese government research agency. ``There won't be
progress on issues like Taiwan, human rights, Tibet or religious
belief. So to make the visit look good, both sides have the
incentive to reach some agreement on WTO.''
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to imagine what kind of deal could emerge or what
trade barriers the Chinese would be willing to drop at a time when
many factories are idle and laying off millions of workers.
</P>
<P>
   They have until now been extremely reluctant to significantly
lower import duties, or to allow foreign companies to operate in
such potentially lucrative sectors as insurance, banking and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   A 100 percent import duty on foreign cars has insured that
middle-class Chinese generally buy tinny domestic models. Many
major Western banks and insurers have set up offices in China in
the hope that the service sector would soon open, but their
representatives now sit idle.
</P>
<P>
   If tariffs were lowered and market access improved, ``Chinese
companies will lose some share'' of the market, Xue said. But there
are potential benefits as well, like greater access to Western
markets at a time when China's exports to countries like Japan and
Thailand have dried up with the Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say they believe that any deal would have to
involve a timetable for the gradual lowering of tariffs and opening
of markets over a period of years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is done overnight, many Chinese industrial sectors
won't be able to handle it, since China's state-owned enterprises
still have a lot of problems'' said Ji. ``This can only be done
step by step.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if negotiators from the two sides can agree on terms, it
remains to be seen if the U.S. Congress will go along.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, which submits China's most-favored-nation trade status
to an annual review, would have to vote to change that practice in
order for China to be accepted into the WTO, since the
organization's 134 members are automatically granted that status.
</P>
<P>
   And at a time when the Senate is criticizing China's
human-rights record, Congress will certainly require, at the very
least, a solid deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The WTO package will be scrutinized _ it must be real, it must
be tangible,'' Ms. Barshefsky said, adding, ``Accession will only
occur on commercially viable terms.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
