<SLUG> BC-BKC-UCONN-SETON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCONN SURVIVES CHALLENGE BY SETON HALL, 57-56 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Incredibly, he wasn't even listed among the league's
top 15 players when it came to announcing the Big East's
all-conference first-, second-, and third-team selections. But, in
an irony of ironies, Kevin Freeman Thursday bolstered his chances
of landing a spot on the all-tournament team by leading the
top-seeded Connecticut Huskies to a 57-56 victory over No. 9 seed
Seton Hall in the quarterfinals of the Big East tourney at Madison
Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   Freeman, a 6-foot-7-inch, 235-pound junior forward from
Springfield, Mass., went over 1,000 points for his career by
leading the Huskies (26-2) with 22 points on 10-for-14 shooting
while grabbing 5 rebounds and scoring a huge offensive board that
gave UConn the lead for good with a minute and a half to go.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I didn't come here trying to make a point,'' Freeman said,
when asked if he looked to this game as a chance to avenge the
postseason snub by the league's coaches. ``I came here to win _ I
think winning games will make a point to the rest of the league. I
don't look at it as an individual. I think it's more important to
the team if we win these next few games. Then, I think I'll be
alright.''
</P>
<P>
   Said UConn coach Jim Calhoun, whose team advanced to the
semifinals where they will face No. 4 seed Syracuse, a 70-62 winner
over fifth-seeded Villanova, ``He is one of the best 10 or 12
players in the league and clearly he has proven that. Without
question, he is so important for us every single night, and tonight
I think he was the difference in the game, because we didn't have a
particularly good game.''
</P>
<P>
   Seton Hall coach Tommy Amaker and his Pirates (15-14) had a lot
to do with that. For the third time this season, Amaker deployed a
scheme that called for his team to execute a deliberate,
controlled-tempo game plan that, invariably, frustrated the
up-tempo Huskies and left them panting to bust loose on a big run.
</P>
<P>
   But it never happened, not even when the Pirates lapsed into a 5
minute 14 second drought between baskets. UConn went on an 8-2 run,
but Seton Hall still managed to lead, 18-17, before Richard
Hamilton, the conference Co-Player of the Year, hit for 3 of his 15
points on a trifecta with 12.9 seconds left that gave UConn a 22-21
lead at intermission.
</P>
<P>
   ``They completely dictated the pace.'' Calhoun said of Seton
Hall. ``They did a terrific job of dictating pace. . . .
Psychologically, I thought they did a good job of tantalizing us,
keeping the ball, keeping the ball, and making us frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   The Huskies were forced to play catch-up for much of the
second-half, managing to stake a pair of 1-point leads (38-37 and
49-48) only to have it immediately wrested away on the following
Seton Hall possession. Until, that is, Freeman, who now has 1,003
career points, broke the 1,000-point barrier e when he converted
Hamilton's errant 3-pointer into a towering offensive putback that
gave the Huskies the lead for good, 51-50, with 1:25 to go. He hen
extended it, 53-50, when he converted Khalid El-Amin's dish off a
dribble-drive lane penetration into an easy low-post dink with 29.2
seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought Kevin Freeman was just a warrior,'' said Amaker.
``That's the way he's played all year, and that's his style of play
and how tough he can be. He made so many big plays, so many big
plays for their team to win the game.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough, it seemed, to soften the blow of his postseason
snub.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the guys on the team were upset by it,'' Freeman
said. ``It seemed like Rip (Hamilton), with me not getting on the
team, it really hurt him. And he got Player of the Year and I'm
like, `How can you be mad when you got Player of the Year?' But
it's that sort of respect that we have for each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me out when I had to deal with it the first day or
two,'' he added. ``It was a motivational factor. But I didn't think
I had to go out and score 22 points. If we continue to win, then
they'll have to respect me and know that I might beat you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
