<HEADLINE>
FLYING HIGH, OR NOT, AFTER A PROMOTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., N.Y., N.C.)   (af)  
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   (italics)Life, like footballs, takes some funny bounces.
Sometimes the promises of promotion and big titles hide a reality
that proves disappointing. And sometimes disappointment turns out
to be the key to the door to advancement.(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1962, when Edward McManus was working in a ladies' sportswear
business in the Garment District of Manhattan, he got his first
executive promotion. His boss had bought a small regional airline
and decided to make McManus its vice president of customer
relations _ in addition to keeping him on as manager of showroom
sales for the main business.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no extra money,'' McManus recalled the boss saying,
``but the title will look good on your resume.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus, who now lives in Marlborough, Mass., said the airline
consisted of an eight-passenger twin-engine Beechcraft. It flew
twice a day between Fitchburg, Mass., home of the sportswear
factory, and the Butler Aviation terminal at La Guardia Airport.
The airline counted on Butler for fuel, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We refueled on credit and then took off before they noticed we
owed them a lot of money,'' McManus wrote.
</P>
<P>
   But one day, Butler rebelled, insisting on cash for fuel until
the corporate bill was paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had our plane on the tarmac with eight paying passengers and
no fuel,'' McManus recalled. ``I called my boss and told him what
had happened. `You're a vice president!' he shouted. `Think of
something!' He hung up.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus boarded the plane and told the passengers that as a
result of a grievous misunderstanding the airline, was unable to
get its fuel on credit. The passengers became restive. McManus
quickly assured them that if each of them gave him $20, he could
buy the necessary fuel and have them home in no time. And the
advance would be credited against future fares.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctantly, the passengers began to ante up.
</P>
<P>
   ``One older gentleman glared at me as I approached his seat,''
McManus wrote. ``He slapped a $20 in my hand, and then another
$10.''
</P>
<P>
   McManus asked, ``What's the extra $10 for?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Check the oil,'' the man said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 10 years ago, Maureen Duffin-Ward of Raleigh, N.C., was
working as an account executive at Foote, Cone &AMP; Belding, a large
advertising agency in Philadelphia. Even better, her client was the
Bell Atlantic Yellow Pages, the agency's biggest account. And even
better than that, the television commercials for the client were
filmed in New York or Los Angeles and often involved celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   She recalled that the management supervisor, then the No. 1
person on the account, said he had a great opportunity for her: She
could become an account supervisor _ but not for Bell Atlantic and
not for the agency, either. He was leaving to become president of a
smaller agency and wanted her to join him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more politics,'' she recalled him saying. ``More money, and
a bigger office than the one you have. And a southern exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duffin-Ward looked up the agency in a directory. With 65
employees, it sounded small. ``But my ficus would have a shot,''
she remembered thinking. ``And I just loved this boss. He wouldn't
steer me wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   On her first day on the new job, a colleague took her around to
meet everyone. When they were finished, she asked, ``Is there
another floor?'' The colleague seemed confused.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I read that you have 65 people, and that was more like
11,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, that must have included our Chicago and Cleveland offices,
too,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Duffin-Ward walked back to her office, disappointed. Then
she went to lunch with her boss to meet her new client, a designer
of industrial fasteners.
</P>
<P>
   On the way, the boss told her more about the agency. ``We don't
do TV or radio, even newspapers,'' she remembered him saying.
``It's all business-to-business.'' With clients who sold only to
other businesses, she wouldn't even be producing ads that the
public would see.
</P>
<P>
   There was more, in the same depressing vein, and Ms. Duffin-Ward
was convinced that she had made a terrible mistake.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of family and friends, she decided to stick it
out for a year. ``And I learned a lot about businesses I had never
heard of,'' she wrote. ``Almost a year to the day, I gave my
two-week notice, having landed a six-figure sales job at a local
television station. They were impressed by my `entrepreneurial'
position, thinking it would prepare me for new business sales.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So in retrospect,'' she said of her detour into unhappiness,
``it was the best job I ever had _ good luck in disguise, for
sure.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
