<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8227 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DISASTER-AID-HNS &LR;      03-04 0744
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISASTER-AID-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICANS STALL AID PACKAGE PRIOR TO CLINTON'S CENTRAL AMERICAN
TRIP 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congressional Republicans have stalled emergency
legislation to provide Central America with almost $1 billion in
disaster aid as President Clinton prepared for a four-day tour of
the hurricane-stricken region.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the House and Senate ordered budget-writers to not
push the relief bills until they come up with ways to pay for the
aid, a directive that some lawmakers say would mean cutting
domestic programs coveted by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to providing $956 million to help Honduras,
Nicaragua and other nations battered by hurricanes Mitch and
Georges, the emergency spending measure also would provide $152
million in relief for U.S. farmers and $100 million for Jordan to
build up its military and repay debts in the wake of King Hussein's
death.
</P>
<P>
   To finance Clinton's emergency spending proposals, the
Republican-controlled Senate Appropriations Committee on Thursday
approved a relief package that would be funded by reduced spending
_ called offsets _ in a variety of federal programs, including food
stamps for poor Americans and environmental programs pushed by Vice
President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   At the behest of GOP leaders, the House Appropriations Committee
postponed a vote, originally set for Thursday, on a similar bill.
``Finding doable and credible offsets involves a delicate balance
because there's a danger of losing votes,'' said Elizabeth Morra, a
committee spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The White House immediately accused the Republican leadership of
playing politics instead of helping deal with the crises. ``If you
look at the menu of things put down (for cuts), it has the real
scent of politics to it,'' said presidential spokesman Joe
Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Democratic Leader Tom Daschle joined in the criticism,
accusing Republicans of taking away ``assistance for the needy in
this country to pay for assistance for the needy in Honduras.''
</P>
<P>
   House Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, said, ``There is a
general feeling we ought to find offsets'' to pay for the aid
Clinton wants for Central America. ``It's not politics; it's budget
responsibility,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had proposed financing the aid by using part of the $109
billion federal surplus expected this year. House leaders, quick to
portray themselves as more fiscally responsible than the Democratic
president, decided against using the surplus, pointing out that
Clinton earlier had wanted it reserved to save Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we spend money, we won't steal it out of Social Security,
and that's the first case out of the box,'' said conservative Rep.
Tom Coburn, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   If a compromise is not found, the bill might die on the floor of
the House or the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get the bill through and didn't think it would be
difficult at all,'' said a spokeswoman for Democrats on the House
Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The delays come four days before Clinton is to tour communities
in Nicaragua, El Salvador and Honduras that were heavily damaged in
October when Hurricane Mitch swept through the region. The
president also is to meet with Central American leaders gathering
for a summit in Guatemala.
</P>
<P>
   Considered the worst natural disaster on record in the Western
Hemisphere, Hurricane Mitch killed more than 9,000 people, left
more than 3 million homeless and destroyed more than $8.5 billion
worth of property.
</P>
<P>
   Also Thursday, Clinton asked Congress to provide enhanced trade
benefits to speed economic recovery in the stricken Central
American countries and several in the Caribbean hit by Hurricane
Georges.
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Sandy Berger said the new measure
would eliminate U.S. tariffs on certain textile and apparel
products. The benefits would apply from Oct. 1, 1999 to June 30,
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The president Thursday also appointed former Florida Gov. Buddy
MacKay as special envoy to the Americas, a $125,000-a-year post
vacated months ago when Thomas F. ``Mack'' McLarty returned to
private business.
</P>
<P>
   McKay, who lost to Republican Jeb Bush in last fall's race for
governor, was Florida's lieutenant governor until December, when
Gov. Lawton Chiles died in mid-December. MacKay served three weeks
as governor before turning the office over to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
