s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-TRAINING-ART-$ADV     03-04 0715
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TRAINING-ART-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR YOUNG ENTREPRENEURS, A STEP PAST THE CLASSROOM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Colo., N.C., Wash., Mass.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7)  
 (af)  
 By PAUL WISENTHAL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Every day after school and on weekends, Federica
Bautista, 18, sells fruit, vegetables and flowers from a pushcart
stationed at the entrance to Flushing Meadows Corona Park in
Queens. When it's cold outside, she takes delivery orders by
telephone at her home, a two-bedroom apartment she shares with
seven relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Her weekly earnings of $100 to $150 on sales of $400 help
support her widowed mother and her 2-year-old son, Abraham.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bautista, a single mother who emigrated from Mexico in 1991,
used to fear for her financial future. But last year, she helped
her family to escape welfare after she completed an after-school
program offered by the National Foundation for Teaching
Entrepreneurship. The foundation provides students in poor urban
neighborhoods with training and seed capital to start their own
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The group is one of about 20 nonprofit agencies authorized by
school boards across the country to teach business literacy. The
largest of these, Junior Achievement, reaches more than 3.1 million
students, up 17 percent last year, by bringing business people into
the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``So many of our kids are disconnected from opportunities and
options available to them from our economic system,'' said James B.
Hayes, chief executive of Junior Achievement, based in Colorado
Springs. ``For many, their only example is playing for the Chicago
Bulls or selling narcotics.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the groups are going a step beyond the literacy training
by teaching students to run their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The National Foundation for Teaching Entrepreneurship had its
own origins in New York, after Steve Mariotti, a high school
teacher in the South Bronx, saw the effects of narcotics and
violence on his students. With no understanding of how the economy
worked, many still dreamed of having their own businesses.
</P>
<P>
   To teach them, Mariotti established the foundation in 1988.
Eleven years later, it has a budget of $5 million a year, with
22,000 graduate entrepreneurs and offices across the country. Major
donors are the Koch family foundations, the Heinz endowments, Fleet
Bank, the W.K. Kellogg Foundation, Microsoft and the Ronald
McDonald House Charities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Bautista turned to the foundation after seeing a poster at
school. She learned everything from how to write a business plan to
how to negotiate with wholesalers. Later, she received $50 toward
the cost of opening her flower and fruit stand.
</P>
<P>
   Among other agencies, Rural Entrepreneurship Through Action
Learning, or REAL Enterprises, based in Durham, N.C., trains
entrepreneurs in rural areas across the country. Among its
successes are Spencer Hall, 18, who started Expertise Computers in
1994 in Deer Park, Wash. Today, with $750,000 in sales and five
employees, Hall installs computer systems for small businesses,
professionals and schools.
</P>
<P>
   Every state has some form of entrepreneurship education. But
tight budgets often limit the offerings to relatively few students.
</P>
<P>
   To expand the reach, the National Foundation for Teaching
Entrepreneurship, in partnership with Microsoft, plans to start
BizTech, an on-line entrepreneurial learning system at www.nfte.com
in May.
</P>
<P>
   Some past sponsors of entrepreneurship programs have had second
thoughts. Gary Kaplan, executive director of Jobs for Youth Boston,
ran entrepreneurial programs until 1991. He now says that, with 25
percent of the population functionally illiterate, ``teaching
entrepreneurship is not a substitute for teaching reading, math and
science.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a measure that would have allocated $60 million to
states for entrepreneurship education in public schools stalled in
Congress. Its sponsors plan to try again this spring.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ms. Bautista, she now plans to go to college. ``I want to
become a teacher or perhaps study medicine,'' she said. ``But I
will still want to have my own business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
