<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-SENIORITY-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESERVING MEDICARE'S ROOTS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, MARCH 7) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Pa., Conn., Mass.)   (af)  
 By FRED BROCK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Thomas C. Matzzie graduated from the University of Notre
Dame in 1997 with a degree in economics, he decided not to follow
many of his classmates into high-paying careers on Wall Street or
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he took a lower-paying job, as a policy analyst at the
Institute for America's Future, a liberal research organization in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Matzzie, 23, who grew up near Pittsburgh, credits Medicare _ of
all things _ with giving him the chance to follow his interests
rather than chase a big salary. ``When I was a senior in high
school, my grandmother _ who has since died _ became very ill,'' he
recalled. ``Medicare was there and helped pay the expenses that
would otherwise have bankrupted our family. Because of Medicare I
was able to go on to college and then have the freedom to do
nonprofit work that pays less, because I know that the burden of
taking care of my parents will be a lot less with Medicare.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he won't use Medicare himself for another 40-plus years,
Mattzie sees how his well-being depends on it. If only the same
could be said for the broader public, whose awareness seems to have
dimmed.
</P>
<P>
   In the current debate over the program's future, many people
have forgotten and others are too young to know what it was like
before 1966, when Medicare began. Back then, young people feared
that caring for a sick parent, retired and no longer covered by
health insurance, could ruin them.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore R. Marmor, a professor of politics at the Yale School
of Management and the author of ``The Politics of Medicare,''
(Aldine, 1998) says a founding principle of Medicare was the
``importance of relieving children of the financial catastrophe
that illness could mean for their parents and then for them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That understanding has been weakened to the point of
amnesia,'' he added, partly because Medicare's benefits have come
to be taken for granted, and partly because the financial relief
they offer has been blunted by growing drug and nursing home costs,
which the program doesn't cover.
</P>
<P>
   Another founding principle of Medicare is threatened by a
proposal to split it in two, allowing a choice between the
traditional plan, with the government paying the bills, and the
chance to shop for private insurance whose premiums the government
would largely pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``This so-called premium-support proposal, which is really a
voucher plan, would undermine Medicare as a social insurance
program,'' Marmor said. ``People would face a dizzying array of
private plans and would have to pay the difference between a
federal voucher and the cost of a health plan. This would shift the
risks of inflation to the elderly and to health plans and away from
the Medicare program itself.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ideological attack and an effort to reject by
stealth the social insurance premises of the Medicare program,'' he
said. ``It rejects the original notion that Medicare should be a
common program for everybody who is over 65.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, wealthier elderly Americans could have
better coverage. That, he argues, would encourage one Medicare
program for the affluent and another for everybody else.
</P>
<P>
   This solution is hardly the only way to rescue Medicare, Marmor
said. He cites Congressional Budget Office figures showing that
raising the Medicare payroll tax to 2.02 percent, from 1.45
percent, would keep Medicare's hospital insurance trust fund in
balance through 2025. Someone making $40,000 a year would pay an
additional $228 a year, or 62 cents a day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we to believe that the public is unwilling to accept tax
increases of this magnitude to support the growing numbers of their
parents and grandparents who become eligible for Medicare?'' he
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Mayer certainly wouldn't object to such an increase,
both to insure the program's future and to pay for prescription
drugs. Ms. Mayer, 83, of New Bedford, Mass., is the oldest student
at the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth, where she will
receive a BA degree in June.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the days before Medicare, she sees the program as a
reflection of our values. ``It's important to us as a society that
we take care of people,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
