<HEADER>
A8233 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT &LR;      03-04 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLIVETTI-TELECOM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNDS VOICE OPPOSITION TO OLIVETTI'S BID FOR ITALIAN PHONE
COMPANY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Olivetti, Italy's No. 2 phone company, has yet to begin
its formal $60 billion bid for the country's largest phone company,
Telecom Italia, but large British and U.S. investment funds are
complaining that as the biggest shareholders in the target company
they may be getting a bad deal.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the grumbling is about Olivetti's price for
Telecom _ 10 euros, or $11, a share, to be paid in a mix of cash
and securities, which they say is far too low for a phone company
some believe is worth at least 30 percent more.
</P>
<P>
   Big U.S. and British funds also object to the bid's implications
for the future of shareholder rights in Europe. The bid is moving
ahead under revised Italian takeover and corporate governance
regulations aimed at making the process more open and fairer to
shareholders. But some fund managers protest that the deal looks
more like old-style European capitalism, in which corporate control
is exercised through opaque financial holding companies and
minority investors find their rights trampled.
</P>
<P>
   The takeover attempt represents the first time a purchase would
be financed through the huge new euro-denominated securities market
taking shape following the introduction of the single European
currency in January.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti's bid, announced less than two weeks ago, is led by its
chief executive, Roberto Colaninno. He is the head of an investor
group in a holding company called Fingruppo SpA. In cascading
fashion, Fingruppo owns a 39 percent share in a Luxembourg-based
holding company called Bell SA, and Bell in turn holds a
controlling 12 percent stake in Olivetti.
</P>
<P>
   But the chain does not end there. Olivetti will start the bid
through a gaming machinery subsidiary called Tecnost, and some
investors fear that Tecnost and Telecom may be merged, if the bid
succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   The fight for Telecom Italia is gaining additional attention
because it comes just as another high profile company, the Italian
fashion group Gucci, is trying to repel a hostile takeover by the
French luxury goods maker, LVMH. A Dutch court began hearings this
week to decide whether Gucci's defense is legal.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti won approval to make &UR;  &LR; a bid from the Italian stock
market regulator, Consob.
</P>
<P>
   The company is now in the phase of gathering financing and
preparing a prospectus for the formal bid which is expected in
April.
</P>
<P>
   Telecom and its chief executive, Franco Bernabe, are preparing
to defend themselves. In a board meeting called Thursday in Milan,
the Telecom board was expected to review plans by Bernabe to merge
Telecom with its profitable wireless phone unit, Telecom Italia
Mobile, a move that would not only make sense by offering customers
single number service through both fixed line and mobile
connections, but would raise the value of Telecom, possibly beyond
Olivetti's reach.
</P>
<P>
   Olivetti and its advisers have kept a low profile, in part not
to upset the Securities and Exchange Commission in the United
States. Olivetti has chosen not to raise financing for the takeover
in the United States, and its advisers say that is to avoid lengthy
U.S. procedures that would slow the timing of the bid. But here too
the big U.S. investment funds are critical. They suspect that the
intention is to skirt tougher U.S. takeover rules that might upset
Olivetti's designs.
</P>
<P>
   To foil Olivetti, Bernabe must gather the votes of shareholders
controlling 30 percent of Telecom's capital. Telecom's core
shareholders, mainly Italian banks and investment groups, represent
about 7.5 percent of that capital; more than half is controlled by
British and U.S. investment funds.
</P>
<P>
   The first of the large funds to go public with objections was
Standard Life Investments, the asset management arm of Standard
Life Assurance Co. of Britain. Leon de Jerez, director of
continental European equity investments, is blunt about his
objections to Olivetti's bid.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal itself is too cheap,'' he said in a telephone
interview. ``Ten euros is not the right price.''
</P>
<P>
   He also objected to how the deal would be financed, which would,
in his view, so increase Telecom's debt as to weaken the company
competitively.
</P>
<P>
   But his larger objections, he said, go farther. Olivetti wants
to take control of Telecom by purchasing only its common stock with
voting rights, ignoring non-voting shares. Moreover, Colaninno and
the investors backing him would acquire Telecom through a company
called Tecnost that Olivetti fully controls, but their control of
Olivetti itself is through minority stakes in two holding
companies, one of them being Bell, which is based in Luxembourg. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &UR;  &LR; Some fund managers suspect that Olivetti's ultimate
intention is to merge Tecnost with Telecom after the takeover.
``You would wind up with nonvoting shares in Tecnost,'' said Frank
Semack, a fund manager at Federated Global Research Corp. in New
York, a unit of Federated Investing.
</P>
<P>
   Other U.S. asset managers with stakes in Telecom, including
TIAA-CREF, the private pension fund for teachers in New York, USAA
Investment Management Company of San Antonio, and Janus Funds of
Denver, are said to oppose the Olivetti bid because it is too low,
includes debt and securities they do not want, and would likely
force out Bernabe, a proven manger they trust.
</P>
<P>
   Grant Gartman, legal counsel at the Investor Responsibility
Research Center in Washington, said that Europe was not alone in
experiencing the kind of deal Olivetti contemplates. In the United
States, he said, despite cries of foul from minority shareholders,
corporate predators will have a subsidiary take a stake in a target
company, then merge the subsidiary with the target.
</P>
<P>
   The Olivetti bid, said John Bennett, a fund manager in London at
Global Asset Management, which ranks Telecom among its top 10
investments in Europe, is a ``test case'' for the Italian stock
market regulator.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
