<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-COINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOCH GIVES DISPUTED ANCIENT COINS TO TURKEY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Greece)   By BARRY MEIER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Turkish government got 1,700 coins Thursday. William I. Koch
got one. So ended one of the most bitter disputes over antiquities
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a decade, Turkish officials and Koch, an investor
known for his 1992 victory in the America's Cup yacht race and
taste for litigation, have battled in court over a treasure trove
that included the rarest and most valuable Greek coins ever found.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish officials insisted the treasure had been illegally dug
up in Turkey in the early 1980s, smuggled out of the country to
Germany and eventually sold to Koch, who then was a trustee of the
Museum of Fine Arts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Koch contended the coins he and his partners bought were not the
ones sought by Turkey. However, some of the coins in dispute, which
were issued around 465 B.C. and are called decadrachms of Athens,
are so rare that it seemed impossible for there to be two separate
caches of them.
</P>
<P>
   Koch said in an interview last year that he was a coin novice
and had purchased the ancient coins in the hope of turning a quick
profit. But his troubles began soon after buying the coins for $3.2
million when Ozgen Acar, a Turkish journalist who specialized in
antiquities, began to investigate an illegal dig in Turkey. In a
1988 article in Connoisseur magazine, he and a co-author described
how the trail led to Koch.
</P>
<P>
   A legal battle ensued. Both Koch and the Turkish government
threw sizeable resources into it, hiring investigators and even
horticultural experts who battled over the timing of certain events
based on the flowers that happened to be in bloom.
</P>
<P>
   With a trial set to begin next week, Koch apparently decided to
concede, though not before extracting a measure of dignity from
Turkish officials. In a ceremony at the Turkish Embassy in
Washington Thursday, Koch gave the 1,700 coins to Turkey. A Turkish
official gave him a coin-shaped medal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
