u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-775&AMP;A     03-04 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-POLITICS-775&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZEDILLO SUGGESTS U.S.-STYLE SYSTEM TO PICK PARTY'S PRESIDENTIAL
NOMINEE
</HEADLINE>
  (fe) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ President Ernesto Zedillo of Mexico urged his
governing party on Thursday to break with 60 years of authoritarian
tradition and elect its presidential candidate this year through a
series of state primaries culminating in an American-style party
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's proposal to 1,800 government officials and party
leaders, which drew an extended standing ovation, was technically
only a recommendation. But officials of the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, known as the PRI, said there was little doubt
that the party would follow Zedillo's suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   The system he outlined would end the uniquely Mexican tradition
known as the dedazo _ literally, the ``fingering'' of candidates _
under which the 10 PRI presidents who preceded Zedillo all
hand-picked their own successors. But the president also said on
Thursday that he still intended to play a powerful role in the
party's candidate selection, leading several analysts to conclude
that the innovations he has in mind may be more of form than of
substance.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo previously pledged in interviews that he would not
choose the PRI's candidate this year and had expressed admiration
for American-style primaries. But not until Thursday had he begun
to sketch out the procedures of the candidate-selection scheme he
wants the PRI to adopt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I reiterate today with absolute clarity that I will not
designate the PRI candidate,'' Zedillo said in a speech
commemorating the 70th anniversary of the party's founding in 1929.
``Our selection process should use the popular secret vote of our
active members and of all citizens who lean toward our party.''
</P>
<P>
   A senior aide to Zedillo said after the president's speech that
many elements of the candidate selection process under
consideration have been modeled on the U.S. model.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be very much the American way,'' the aide said. But
it is too soon to see how much the two systems might resemble each
other.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's speech at party headquarters drew thunderous ovations
from the party's top leadership but also some grumbling, outside
the auditorium, from party gadflies who said his proposals were
less democratic than meets the eye.
</P>
<P>
   Under the selection process Zedillo outlined, successive local
primaries would result in the election of delegates, who would meet
later with representatives of the PRI's labor, peasant and other
wings to select the presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   More than his predecessors, Zedillo is a democrat by conviction,
but his proposals appear motivated as much by tactical necessity as
by idealistic principles. The use of the dedazo has opened deep
party fissures before every election since the 1970s, as powerful
politicians passed over for the nomination have nursed their anger
in political feuds. A man spurned for the nomination in 1987,
Cuauhtemoc Cardenas Solorzano, defected from the PRI to form an
opposition party that is today the PRI's most dangerous rival.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, several analysts said, Zedillo believes that if the
party organizes primaries in which not only PRI members, but all
Mexican voters, are encouraged to participate, his own preferred
candidates will probably prevail over hard-line party
traditionalists.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo drew sustained applause by criticizing several leaders
of the traditionalist wing, known as the dinosaurs, who have
already announced their own candidacies. He chided them for
threatening party unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Comrades, besides democracy, we need unity, a lot of unity, to
win in 2000,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's address appeared to be Zedillo's most vigorous use to
date of his own influence to mold events within his party, from
which he once pledged to maintain a ``healthy distance.''
</P>
<P>
   Paradoxically, even as Zedillo voluntarily pledged to give up
the Mexican presidency's greatest power, the unilateral choice of a
successor, he vowed to use his powers in the PRI's internal
deliberations more forcefully than at any previous time. He is in
the fifth year of his six-year term and is ineligible to seek
re-election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have every right and complete moral and political authority
to express my opinions about the process by which our party will
select its presidential candidate,'' Zedillo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who use my pledge not to designate the candidate to say
that this in a process in which I won't get involved, in which I'll
be indifferent or standoffish, are mistaken,'' Zedillo said.
Hundreds of party leaders, apparently impatient with Zedillo's
previous hesitancy about directly involving himself in party
affairs, gave that line sustained applause.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Agustin Basave, a former PRI congressman who last year helped
found a caucus that has been pressing party leaders to allow the
rank and file to organize the candidate nomination process, said
Zedillo's proposals could give him tremendous power to influence
the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the president did today was smack his hand on the
table,'' Basave said. ``He said, `I'm the boss of the PRI and I'm
going to exercise my power in the party. I'll not designate the
candidate, but I'll set the rules and serve as referee. Well, the
line separating the referee from the guy who picks the candidate is
very thin.''
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Bartlett, a former interior minister who is a leader of
the PRI's dinosaur wing and has declared himself a candidate for
the nomination, praised the president's decision to end the dedazo
tradition. But he reserved final judgment on the proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of details are still not spelled out,'' Bartlett said in
an interview. ``How and who will organize these state elections?
How will they count the votes? These are some of the things that
must still be defined, and party members should help set these
rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Alfonso Zarate, who edits a political newsletter here, said
Zedillo's speech ``makes it clear that the president intends to
keep tight control of the succession process.
</P>
<P>
   ``He laid out the party line in the orthodox way Mexican
presidents have been doing this for 60 years,'' Zarate said.
</P>
<P>
   A PRI official said party officials would circulate Zedillo's
proposals for internal debate in coming weeks before approving the
final candidate selection procedures in May. The PRI's top leader,
Mariano Palacios Alcocer, said in an interview this week that the
party will select its candidate by mid-November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
