<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWT05-COX     03-04 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soft money is building a big cushion for Gingrich plans
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his newest incarnation, former House Speaker
Newt Gingrich is returning to an old model to help him raise large
amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   His political action committee, the Friends of Newt Gingrich
PAC, is accepting so-called soft money _ large and unregulated sums
from contributors that may not have to be disclosed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   FONG PAC, as it is known among Gingrich aides and supporters, is
telling prospective contributors it ``may accept unlimited
contributions from corporations or individuals,'' according to its
latest fund-raising letter.
</P>
<P>
   The contribution form includes spaces for donors to place a
check mark next to $50,000, $25,000, $10,000 or other.
</P>
<P>
   The solicitation of soft money harkens back to Gingrich's days
as the chairman of GOPAC, the Republican political organization he
used to build his stature and help dozens of future members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   GOPAC not only accepted soft money, it for years refused to
reveal the sources of its contributions. In Georgia, the State
Ethics Commission dismissed a complaint against GOPAC in 1995 that
sought to force the organization to disclose all its fund-raising
activities.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's new PAC is based in Georgia, but he has a national
fund-raising base that is the envy of most politicians.
</P>
<P>
   While Gingrich has not revealed his future political plans _
speculation has ranged from a bid for Georgia governor in 2002 to a
presidential campaign in 2004 or 2008 _ an advocate of limiting the
role of money in politics offered a simple explanation for the
PAC's willingness to receive large contributions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to raise it because people are willing to give it
that way. The amounts are off the chart,'' said Bill Hogan of the
Center for Public Integrity.
</P>
<P>
   Several telephone calls to Gingrich's office in Georgia and to
his political adviser's office in Washington were not returned.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law places limits of $1,000 per election on
contributions to candidates for Congress and the presidency. PACs
that contribute to federal campaigns may accept $5,000 a year from
contributors and give $5,000 an election to candidates.
Corporations cannot make federal contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's PAC will have to abide by those limits for its
federal election activities. But it will maintain a separate
nonfederal account, which may be used to fund other political
activities, including travel, contributions to candidates on the
state and local levels and materials that present Gingrich's views.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution of political tapes to prospective office
holders, for example, was a key component of GOPAC's work in the
years leading up to Gingrich's rise to the speakership in January
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich announced that he was stepping down as speaker three
days after the November elections, in which Republicans
unexpectedly lost five seats in the House. He would have faced a
serious challenge to hold on to the speakership.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich is accepting speaking engagements, reportedly for up to
$50,000 each, and he will form a consulting company. His supporters
have left no doubt that the former college professor will remain
active in politics.
</P>
<P>
   His political action committee will give him the means to do so.
Through the end of the year, the PAC had $275,000 in ready cash.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich will add substantially to that amount by mid-April when
his political supporters will hold a $1,000-a-plate ``Salute to
Newt'' gala in Washington. The April 14 event also will benefit one
of his favorite charities, the Juvenile Diabetes Foundation.
Actress Mary Tyler Moore, who chairs the Juvenile Diabetes
Foundation International, is scheduled to introduce Gingrich. And
actor John Ratzenberger, who played Cliff the mailman on TV's
``Cheers,'' will serve as master ceremonies, according to a memo
promoting the event.
</P>
<P>
   Former GOP colleagues who are now prominent lobbyists in
Washington are serving as co-chairmen.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
