<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0403 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8246 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLACKMUN-ROE-WADE-HNS     03-04 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLACKMUN-ROE-WADE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKMUN'S MAJORITY OPINION PLUNGED U.S. INTO STRUGGLE THAT
CONTINUES TODAY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like the very debate over abortion, people's reactions to the
death of retired Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun bend to the
extreme.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the abortion rights movement are mourning him as an
unabashed hero _ the man who not only framed a woman's right to
abortion but also secured her right to control her destiny. Leaders
of groups opposed to abortion, however, describe Blackmun as the
man whose words became a death sentence for unborn children.
</P>
<P>
   In the narrowest light, his legacy was the landmark ruling he
authored in 1973 that legalized a woman's right to abortion in the
United States. But the court's decision, galvanized behind
Blackmun's majority opinion, also plunged the country into a
titanic political and moral struggle that continues today.
</P>
<P>
   It is a testament to the raw, emotional power of Roe vs. Wade
that Blackmun's words from the 26-year-old Supreme Court opinion
still characterize the nation's uneasiness over this most personal
of issues:
</P>
<P>
   ``We forthwith acknowledge our awareness of the sensitive and
emotional nature of the abortion controversy, of the vigorous
opposing views, even among physicians, and of the deep and
seemingly absolute convictions that the subject inspires,''
Blackmun wrote. ``One's philosophy, one's experiences, one's
exposures to the raw edges of human existence, one's religious
training, one's attitudes toward life and family and their values,
and the moral standards one establishes and seeks to observe, are
all likely to influence and to color one's thinking and conclusions
about abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our task, of course, is to resolve this issue by
constitutional measurement, free of emotion and of predilection,''
Blackmun wrote. But the subsequent change in law unleashed a
torrent of emotions and sparked the organization of groups who
opposed abortion so vehemently they were willing to take their
opposition to the sidewalks in front of abortion clinics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in many mays responsible for the pro-life movement,''
said Bill Price, president of Texans United for Life. ``In our
books he was justice gone astray, part of the cabal of justices who
believed in legislating from the bench and just wiping away state's
abortion laws passed by the elected representatives of the
people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``National Right to Life expresses our condolences to the family
of Justice Blackmun,'' said David O'Steen, executive director of
the National Right to Life Committee. However, he added, history
will remember Harry Blackmun as the architect of a tragic Supreme
Court decision, which ``has resulted in the deaths of 38 million
unborn children since 1973.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the abortion rights movement say Blackmun was a man
of courage who paid dearly for his judicial stance. Kate Michelman,
president of the National Abortion and Reproductive Rights Action
League, noted that he received massive amounts of hate mail and was
dogged by protesters at his office nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``He eventually began traveling with bodyguards and was even
shot at while in his own home,'' Michelman said, adding that the
bullet slammed into a chair his wife had just been sitting in. But
he never wavered in his belief that women should make their own
choice about abortion free from government interference, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is important to acknowledge Justice Blackmun's
importance to women's historic struggle for equality and
emancipation,'' Michelman said. ``His contributions were, I think,
singular and monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   ``His legacy is broader than just legalizing abortion,'' said
Priscilla Smith, staff attorney for the Center for Reproductive Law
and Policy. ``His legacy is also in establishing that women could
be equal participants in the economic life of the country as well
as the family life of the country.``
</P>
<P>
   ``The right to vote, which was a constitutional amendment, had I
think equal significance to women's struggle for equality,''
Michelman said. ``But in terms of women being able to really effect
control over their own destiny and how they would contribute to the
nation's life, Roe vs. Wade gave us that ultimate control.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
