r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LA     03-04 0940
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAINERS FACE TOO MUCH TRAFFIC ON WAY TO HALL OF FAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ Trainers Richard Mandella and Neil Drysdale
have big chances in Saturday's Santa Anita Handicap, Mandella with
Puerto Madero and Event of the Year, Drysdale with Dr Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, they have almost no chance in the national racing
Hall of Fame voting under way this month among 130 writers,
broadcasters and thoroughbred historians.
</P>
<P>
   The problem isn't Drysdale's and Mandella's credentials. They
deserve enshrinement and with any luck they'll get it eventually.
The problem is that the other name on the ballot this year is D.
Wayne Lukas, the holder of just about every major training record,
and under the election rules only the top vote-getter makes the
Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lukas has to be put in there,'' said none other than Drysdale.
``It would be a travesty if he's not.''
</P>
<P>
   If this were baseball _ whose Hall of Fame election format makes
sense to just about everyone but Pete Rose _ then Lukas, Mandella
and Drysdale all could be honored. Instead, it's tough luck for
those of us who would like to vote for all three.
</P>
<P>
   Just as it's tough luck for those of us who would like to vote
for !ital!none of the nominees in the jockey category _ Northern
California's Russell Baze, veteran Earlie Fires and the late Jackie
Westrope _ one of whom will be named a Hall of Famer sometime
during Kentucky Derby week.
</P>
<P>
   The way the voting goes now, your chances of making the Hall of
Fame depends on who else achieves the eligibility threshold _ 25
years as a trainer, 15 years as a jockey _ when you do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an awful big industry to only take one a year,'' Mandella
said. ``There's a lot of deserving people.''
</P>
<P>
   Mandella, 48, trained 1993 Horse of the Year Kotashaan and won
six consecutive $1 million races from 1996 to '98, including Dare
and Go's upset of Cigar in the '96 Pacific Classic and the 1-2-3
sweeps in the '97 Big 'Cap and Hollywood Gold Cup. He'll win an
unprecedented third straight Santa Anita Handicap if he can beat
Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   Mandella said the Hall of Fame ``is not something I thought
about 25 years ago. I was just hoping to have some of those `M'
webbings (on his stalls) and be able to make a living training
horses.''
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale, 51, a well-traveled native of Surrey, England, trained
1992 Horse of the Year A.P. Indy, one of his five Breeders' Cup
winners. A.P. Indy is nominated in the ``contemporary male horses''
category with Exceller and Precisionist.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read about (the nomination) in the paper and part of me
said, `It's an honor to be selected,' '' Drysdale said from his
Hollywood Park barn. ``The other part of me said, `Christ, I must
be getting old.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Either Drysdale, Mandella or Lukas will become the fifth Hall of
Fame trainer active in Southern California, joining Charlie
Whittingham, Jack Van Berg, Ron McAnally and Bobby Frankel.
</P>
<P>
   But it seems Lukas can lose only if it's a popularity contest.
He has clashed with reporters and vowed to boycott the Aug. 9 Hall
of Fame ceremonies in Saratoga Springs, N.Y., because the former
quarterhorse trainer believes he met the 25-year qualification
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Back to substance: A $1 million Big 'Cap victory would add to
the resumes of Mandella, who has won the race with Siphon and
Malek, and Drysdale, who hasn't won it.
</P>
<P>
   Malek wasn't entered Thursday. He'll go straight to the March 28
Dubai World Cup. But Chile-bred Puerto Madero, coming off a Donn
Handicap victory over Silver Charm, and 4-year-old Event of the
Year, the Strub Stakes winner, were the strength of the Mandella
team anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale's Dr Fong is fifth on the morning line at 10-1 in the
six-horse field. But the European import was underconditioned when
he ran second in his dirt-track debut in the Strub, should improve
at 1\ miles and looks like the right long shot.
</P>
<P>
   __ The undercard: Both sub-features on Big 'Cap day are
star-studded: The 7-furlong San Carlos Handicap finds Kona Gold
(120 pounds) trying to go gate to wire against Big Jag (118), Gold
Land (118), Lord Grillo and Dramatic Gold. The mile-on-turf Arcadia
Handicap pits Breeders' Cup Mile runner-up Hawksley Hill (122)
against Ladies Din (120) and five others.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Solis rides both highweights.
</P>
<P>
   The pick-six, for which Santa Anita is guaranteeing a pool of at
least $1 million, begins with the sixth of 11 races on a noon card.
</P>
<P>
   Big 'Cap coverage starts at 2 p.m. on Channel 11. The race is
the second in the ``NTRA Champions on Fox'' series.
</P>
<P>
   __ Quiet comeback: Out-of-town race of the week is Kentucky
Derby and Preakness winner Real Quiet's return to action in
Sunday's New Orleans Handicap at the Fair Grounds. He and Kent
Desormeaux will face a soft field in Real Quiet's first race since
his Belmont Stakes defeat in June.
</P>
<P>
   Real Quiet looked so sharp in a :58 1/5 workout at Santa Anita
on Tuesday, it's possible Baffert is running the wrong horse in the
Big 'Cap.
</P>
<P>
   __ The deepest field: A Blood-Horse magazine panel placed Man o'
War atop the 100 best thoroughbreds of the century. The rest of the
top 10: Secretariat, Citation, Kelso, Count Fleet, Dr. Fager,
Native Dancer, Forego, Seattle Slew and Spectacular Bid.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar (19th) is the highest-ranked horse who raced in the 1990s,
ahead of Sunday Silence (31st), Skip Away (32nd), Easy Goer (34th),
Silver Charm (63rd), Holy Bull (64th), Go for Wand (72nd), Lure
(85th) and Bayakoa (95th).
</P>
<P>
   Ruffian (35th) is the highest-ranked filly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
