<SLUG> BC-CARLOS-MUMMIES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Carlos Museum meets funding goals for mummies
 &HT;    By Catherine Fox
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Michael C. Carlos Museum of Art said Thursday it
has succeeded in raising the $2 million it needs to purchase a
cache of ancient Egyptian artifacts, including mummies and mummy
cases as much as 3,000 years old.
</P>
<P>
   The community responded so overwhelmingly since the Carlos
announced its quest last month that the Emory University museum
decided Feb. 11 to go ahead with a letter of intent, even though it
remained $275,000 short of its goal.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, additional support from the board and by an unnamed
foundation has enabled the Carlos to meet the price set by the
anonymous dealer for one of the last such collections in private
hands.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund-raising isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still seeking funds for conservation, installation and
publication,'' Carlos director Tony Hirschel said.
</P>
<P>
   The Carlos is waiting for official approval from the Canadian
government to take the collection out of the museum that houses it
in Niagara Falls, Ontario. It expects to hear something in a couple
of weeks. Hirschel said he hopes to ship the mummies to Atlanta in
May, and he promised to keep the community posted about when to
expect to see them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
