<SLUG> BC-MARINE-REACT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY OUTRAGED AT ACQUITTAL OF U.S. PILOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: See also MARINE-AVIATOR)  
(rk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Italians reacted with shock and outrage Thursday night to
the acquittal of an American pilot who, in their view, recklessly
sheared the cables of an Italian ski lift, causing the death of 20
tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema, who was giving a speech at the
John F. Kennedy Library in Boston, said he was baffled by the
acquittal of the pilot, Capt. Richard J. Ashby. D'Alema, who is in
the United States to hold his first official meeting with President
Clinton, said he would bring up the verdict on Friday when he was
at the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``It leaves us very worried because that was an incident where
we expected that justice would be done,'' D'Alema said.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, other politicians and ordinary Italians were far less
constrained.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am outraged and indignant at this verdict which takes no
account of Italy's ban on low-level flights,'' said Valdo Spini,
the chairman of the defense committee of the lower house of
Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Spini added with sarcasm, ``At this point we will end up blaming
the skiers who were on that wretched cable car.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of the victims expressed shock at the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a disgraceful verdict,'' said Klaus Stampfl, an Italian
from Bressanone, whose mother died in the accident. ``During the
hearings that took place in Trento I gave a letter to an American
prosecutor in which I asked that justice be done. I think, at this
point, that my preoccupations were founded.''
</P>
<P>
   Stampfl said he followed the case in the United States and was
horrified.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I felt that they were almost having fun during the
hearings,'' he said. ``Certainly, it was not a serious trial like
it could have been had it taken place in Italy.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``At this point the 20 victims have no value. No one
is guilty of the tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The verdict revived Italian calls for a trial in Italy. It also
revived political animosities between the United States and Italy
that have mostly been dormant over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the heated emotions spilling over at home, D'Alema
sought a rational approach, suggesting that Italy might try to find
other legal avenues, like a civil lawsuit or a prosecution of
senior officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand whether this verdict means canceling
every responsibility or whether the military judges felt that the
responsibilities lie elsewhere,'' he said Thursday night. ``This is
a problem that is difficult to judge right now because we don't
have the verdict, but certainly in these hours we are busy trying
to better understand to see which roads can be taken to obtain
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   After the accident, which occurred at the resort town of Mount
Cermis last February, Italian criminal investigators had fought to
have the plane's crew tried in Italy, and they were supported by
many ordinary Italians, who feared that the American justice system
would not deal as severely with American servicemen.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The Italian government recognized the U.S. right to prosecute
its own servicemen, part of a bilateral agreement within the NATO
charter. Some politicians said Thursday that those agreements
should be re-examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because if in cases like this, the right of each nation to try
its own military leads to results of this kind, obviously, these
rules must be re-examined,'' Spini said.
</P>
<P>
   Italian prosecutors in Trento said the acquittal vindicated
their earlier demand for an Italian trial. Thursday night, Bruno
Giardina, one of the investigators who followed the case, said that
he was not surprised by the verdict and that an earlier decision by
an American military court to exempt some higher-ranking Marine
officers made him realize that there might be no finding of
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Italians had long been lobbying for a trial in Italy,
and Thursday they expressed a sense of vindication.
</P>
<P>
   Beppe Contrelli, a lawyer with the February 3 Committee for
Justice, an organization that sought an Italian trial, said: ``It
is a disgraceful verdict. Let it be a lesson for those who expected
justice, rapidity and severity from American justice. Twenty
useless victims have been condemned to a death without justice, as
we had foreseen for months. That is why the committee had long
fought to hold the trial in Italy. In retrospect, I must say that I
was right.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Italian politicians viewed the verdict as an indictment of
the American system of justice. Mauro Piassan, head of the Greens,
a left-wing environmentalist party, called the decision ``a
scandalous verdict that offends those 20 dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Injustice has been done,'' Piassan said. ``The homicidal
behavior of the American military has been rewarded. They played
war, they killed 20 people and they were let off. Those 20 victims
were offended, and their dear ones have been deceived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
