<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-BOX-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALASKA AIRLINES AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALASKA AIRLINES AT A GLANCE:
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS: Major airline serving 41 cities in Alaska, Washington,
Oregon, California, Nevada and Arizona, as well as cities in Canada
and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Carried 13.1 million passengers in 1998, with an average
passenger trip length of 864 miles. Leading non-stop routes are
Seattle-Anchorage, Seattle-Los Angeles and Seattle-San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   LOCATION: Headquarters, training center, cargo center and
two-bay maintenance facility in Seattle; regional headquarters, air
cargo and hangars in Anchorage; reservations center in Phoenix; and
two-bay maintenance facility in Oakland, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   WORKFORCE: 9,244 full- and part-time.
</P>
<P>
   FLEET: Owns or leases 84 jetliners, split between McDonnell
Douglas MD-80s and Boeing 737s. Ordered eight new 737s at a total
cost of $256 million in 1998, has options for 26 more.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL DATA: Profitable in 24 of the past 26 years, with
record profits in recent years. 1998 consolidated net income was
$124.4 million, compared with a prior year net income of $72.4
million.
</P>
<P>
   HISTORY: Incorporated 1932 in Alaska. Became part of Alaska Air
Group, a holding company incorporated in Delaware in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Acquired Horizon Airlines, a Seattle-based regional carrier, in
1986. Both operate as integrated subsidiaries of the Alaska Air
Group. Combined, they carry 2.5 percent of all U.S. domestic
passenger traffic, and have a reputation for superior customer
service and amenities.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with major competition from low-cost rivals Southwest,
United Shuttle Express and now-defunct MarkAir, Alaska has cut
costs and expanded West Coast routes in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Has been named the nation's best airline by Travel &AMP; Leisure
magazine and by readers of Conde Naste Traveler in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Suspended service to Russia in 1998 because of economic
instability there.
</P>
<P>
   MAJOR ACCIDENTS: An Alaska Airlines 727 jetliner crashed into a
mountain northwest of Juneau on Sept. 4, 1971, killing all 111
people aboard. Another 727 slid off a runway in Ketchikan on April
5, 1976. One passenger died. Several passengers and crew members
were injured.
</P>
<P>
   KEY EXECUTIVES: John F. Kelly, chairman, president and CEO of
Alaksa Air Group; William S. Ayer, president of Alaska Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   BOARD OF DIRECTORS: Ronald F. Cosgrave, Mary Jane Fate, Bruce R.
Kennedy, R. Marc Langland, Byron I. Mallott, Robert L. Parker Jr.,
John V. Rindlaub, Patricia Q. Stonesifer, Richard A. Wien.
</P>
<P>
   SOURCE: Securities and Exchange Commission filings, corporate
reports and P.I Research.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
