<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKNOTE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORM, A SHY GUY?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ There might not be enough words in Webster's
to fully describe Dennis Rodman. Colorful. Strange. Talented.
Controversial. Genius.
</P>
<P>
   But SHY?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, yes. The same guy who's made a reputation of
outrageousness off the court is a wallflower in the locker room. In
his first week with the Lakers, Rodman has said little to teammates
once the final buzzer sounds. Lauded as a communicator and leader
on the court, he's seldom heard off it.
</P>
<P>
   On the team bus and plane, he sits with his two bodyguards.
Before and after games, he usually dresses away from the locker. He
still refers to the team as ``they,'' not ``we.'' The guy who sits
next to him in the Forum locker room hasn't had a conversation with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' said Travis Knight. ``He's there when it counts,
I guess.''
</P>
<P>
   And Knight's description of the multitattooed, multipierced,
multicolor-haired Rodman might be the most unique of all. ``He's a
regular guy,'' Knight said with a straight face. ``He may not be
like you or me, but he's still a regular guy. He's quiet. Maybe
he's got a lot on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's fine with the Lakers, so long as Rodman plays like
the seven-time rebounding champion he is.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all that matters,'' Kobe Bryant said. ``He could come
in here right now and not say a word to anybody, but on the
basketball court, you feel his impact.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for camaraderie?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's overrated,'' Bryant said. ``If you have guys that are
friends off the court and you win a championship, that's perfect,
but in the NBA you rarely see that.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Something Olden: Last time the Lakers saw Olden Polynice, the
Seattle center was neutralizing Shaquille O'Neal, dancing and
fist-pumping in celebration, then following up with observations
about how the Lakers huddle is one big, profanity-laced screaming
match.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics are in town tonight and the Lakers haven't forgotten
the loss _ or Polynice's antics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of got embarrassed,'' Eddie Jones said. ``We also got
talked about, so I think the motivation is they embarrassed us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Every individual is really feeling what their players said and
the way the guy was dancing,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the finger-pointing and dancing, that's just not the way
to play this game.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Polynice's critique, Jones said, ``Olden's gonna say
whatever; Olden wants to be in L.A. so bad. He may not say much
here, though. He may not dance on the court here in L.A.''
</P>
<P>
   Added O'Neal, who watched Polynice get 17 rebounds and 15
points, ``I'm the bridge, Olden is water, which means no matter
what he does, no matter how high his tide rises, he'll always be
under me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Parting shot: Jones, who long ago tired of trade talk
involving him and Charlotte's Glen Rice, has acquired a healthy
sense of humor about it. For the last two days, he's ended
interviews with reporters by shaking everyone's hand, smiling and
saying, ``Guys, it's been nice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
