<HEADER>
A8258 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-READING-SCORES05-C     03-04 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-READING-SCORES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Grading the reading skills of Georgia's students
 &HT;    By Doug Cumming
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The latest evidence of weak reading skills among
Georgia's children, from what is called the nation's report card,
didn't surprise elementary school teacher Rebecca Pruitt.
</P>
<P>
   When she began nine years ago out of Georgia Southern University
with a degree in elementary education, she had not been taught how
to teach reading. Now a literacy teacher at Conley Hills Elementary
in East Point, she has what few elementary teachers get in college
_ a systematic reading program to offer children. For eight years
in first- and second-grade classrooms, ``I basically followed a
textbook and what was in the curriculum, and what my county said I
should follow, but I didn't really understand how I could teach a
child to read.''
</P>
<P>
   Scores released Thursday from the National Assessment of
Educational Progress show that reading problems are not confined to
a small segment of poor or disabled students, but cut across the
mainstream of children from the cities to the suburbs, locally and
nationally.
</P>
<P>
   Observers say it is too soon to see results of a growing
emphasis that Georgia, like many other states, has been putting on
reading. ``I think it's akin to a tanker given the command to make
a right turn,'' said Jim Puckett, head of the Georgia Association
of Educational Leaders, which represents school administrators.
``It takes a while for that ship to actually make the turn.''
</P>
<P>
   But while the latest NAEP scores confirm the need for change,
the change that is coming slowly to Georgia may be just as spotty
and unfocused as the old ways.
</P>
<P>
   The official state curriculum was revised in 1997 to put more
emphasis on phonics, but objectives for what students should learn
in reading in first and second grade are a hodgepodge of old
concepts that come from various schools of thought and opinion. For
example, students are expected to figure out words from their
context, memorize increasing numbers of words, and use rhymes and
initial consonants to sound out parts of words.
</P>
<P>
   Reading experts say this is not a balanced approach, but a
chaotic one that ignores research on reading. Laura Fredrick, an
assistant professor of educational psychology at Georgia State
University who has instituted a well-researched reading program at
two Georgia schools, wondered why the state doesn't simply adopt
reading strategies that have scientific data behind them.
</P>
<P>
   She said one problem may be the tendency of her fellow education
professors to ignore research data, ``unless it's think-pieces we
happen to agree with.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she's not happy with the state curriculum having bits
and pieces of various theories, it was a result of a committee of
hundreds of people from universities, schools and the public
putting it together, said state school Superintendent Linda
Schrenko.
</P>
<P>
   Even the state Department of Education's two reading programs,
Reading First and Reading Challenge, span a wide range of programs
and methods, generally mixing phonics, or teaching letter-sound
correspondence, with lots of reading of children's literature.
Results from the first year of the program are not yet available.
</P>
<P>
   Keisha Shivers, 9, happens to be in a Reading Challenge
after-school program in Cobb County that uses a program called
Sing, Spell, Read, Write, which includes music to reinforce the
rules of sounding out words.
</P>
<P>
   Her mother, Jean Word, said she hopes phonics works for her
daughter, because her own reading instruction left her to figure
out words by memorizing them or looking for clues from the
sentence. With that method, ``you don't have a way to break them
down.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Board of Regents now requires elementary education
students to take more reading classes, it won't help to take more
of the same courses, said Peggy Torrey, head of the Professional
Standards Commission, which certifies teachers and colleges of
education.
</P>
<P>
   Pruitt, the literacy teacher, agreed. Her undergraduate courses
in reading consisted of activities and units of study, but ``no one
really sat me down and said, `This is how you teach reading.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
