<SLUG> BC-POINTCAST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CEO Pushes Out of PointCast  &HT;       
 By Jon Swartz 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
PointCast Inc., the once high-flying Internet pioneer that has
experienced turbulence for more than a year, yesterday announced
the resignation of CEO David Dorman, who disclosed that the company
is seeking a buyer.
</P>
<P>
   Dorman, 45, yesterday was appointed chief executive of a new $10
billion joint venture between AT&AMP;T Corp. and British
Telecommunications PLC's. He said he will step down as PointCast
CEO and remain chairman until a buyout or merger agreement is
completed in several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ```PointCast is near the goal line. We expect to have a deal
done,'' Dorman said.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Koen, PointCast's new president and CEO, said Dorman's
comments about a pending sale was ``news to me.'' Koen said
PointCast was in the midst of negotiations for a strategic
partnership. ``We're intent on getting a deal done soon,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PointCast was the original purveyor of ``push'' technology,
which collected news and information from the Internet and
delivered it directly to computer users for free. But the
technology quickly fell out of favor with some consumers and
businesses, who griped that their Net connections were bogged down
by the onslaught of data.
</P>
<P>
   Dorman was recruited from SBC Communications in late 1997 to
reverse PointCast's flagging fortunes and take it public within six
to 12 months. But his 16-month legacy was spotty, according to his
detractors. During his reign, the company scrapped plans for an
initial public offering and labored to find a buyer or strategic
partner. On top of that, its subscriber base declined to 1.1
million from 1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said the Sunnyvale company unsuccessfully sought a
business partner for more than six months and that recent
negotiations with several Baby Bells to provide high-speed Internet
access were beginning to unravel.
</P>
<P>
   At the AT&AMP;T-British Telecommunications subsidiary, Dorman will
oversee international operations for large, multinational
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Observers said Dorman's substantial experience in the telephone
industry and at a startup &UR;  &LR; are assets. However, his lack of an
international business background is a ``question mark,'' said
Jeffrey Kagan, an independent telecommunications analyst in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of POINTCAS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Dorman previously was a top-ranking executive at Pacific Bell and
Sprint. He was an architect of the strategy that led to the $18
billion merger between Pacific Telesis and SBC in 1997. But he
bolted SBC two months later to join PointCast in October. Dorman
also was courted by Apple Computer in 1997 to take over as its CEO,
but he declined.
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of POINTCAS () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
