<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MENS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Men's Wearhouse Buys Chain To Better Suit Its Business  &HT;       
 By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse said yesterday that it will more than double its
business in very low-end suits by acquiring K&AMP;G Men's Center Inc.
of Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   The all-stock deal, valued between $121 million and $133
million, will merge K&AMP;G's 33 superstores into the 20-unit Value
Priced Clothing division of Men's Wearhouse of Fremont. Both
operations are so-called weekend warriors _ they are open Fridays
through Sundays and sell suits for $99 to $199.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse's VPC division is separate from its 411 Men's
Wearhouse specialty stores, which sell better-quality suits for
$199 to $699 and are open all week.
</P>
<P>
   The acquisition will boost Men's Wearhouse's market share in
men's tailored apparel to between 11 and 12 percent from the
current 9 percent, said Kelly Armstrong, an analyst at First Union
Capital Markets.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong forecasts $171 million in sales for K&AMP;G in 1999,
compared with $61 million for the VPC division. The transaction is
expected to be finalized by July.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said she expects the deal to add to Men's Wearhouse's
earnings this year. With more stores, the company should be able to
strike better deals in advertising and sourcing, she added. The
company already is the largest in its category in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The deal adds 13 new states to Men's Wearhouse's VPC division.
K&AMP;G and VPC both have stores in Los Angeles, Texas and Atlanta. VPC
operates SuitMax stores in those markets and in New Orleans, as
well as Suit Warehouse stores in Detroit. K&AMP;G's other markets are
Colorado, Indiana, Kansas, Maryland, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New
Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Seattle and
Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Men's Wearhouse is giving K&AMP;G shareholders between 4.1 million
and 4.4 million shares, depending on their trading price prior to
closure of the deal. Each K&AMP;G share will be converted to between
0.4 and 0.43 of a share of Men's Wearhouse stock.
</P>
<P>
   Separately yesterday, Men's Wearhouse said February sales rose
12.5 percent to $53.4 million while sales at mature stores grew 2.7
percent. Revenues last year totaled $768 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
