<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8264 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON &LR;      03-04 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKWAYS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Column: When a New Job Is a Step Down  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; Question: &LR;  My company just eliminated my job as part of a
budget-cutting initiative and offered me a new position elsewhere
in the firm. The company claims this is a lateral move. But this
new job really carries less professional status and responsibility,
and is not something I would ever have applied for on my own. If I
decline to take this job, can I negotiate a severance package? What
kind of package should I seek?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Answer: &LR;  Frankly, you're not in a real strong negotiating
position.
</P>
<P>
   Companies typically offer severance packages when people are
being laid off. But your firm isn't laying you off: It's offering
you another position that, while not as good as your old one, is
still a job.
</P>
<P>
   You should start by taking a hard look at this new job and
whether it really is as bad as you think. There may be an upside
that you're not seeing _ a chance to learn new skills, branch out
in a new career direction or solve some intractable business
problems that will make you a star at the company.
</P>
<P>
   But let's assume the job would genuinely be a step down and you
don't want to spend one day doing it.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at what kinds of severance, if any, the company has
given to other employees in your situation. Also, do an honest
assessment of your reputation at the company: They may be more
willing to help you if you've worked there for a long time or have
been an outstanding contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Then go to your boss and explain that this new position won't
challenge you or help you meet your career goals. Ask if the
company could help you make the transition to a new job by:
</P>
<P>
   _Continuing your salary for 90 days while you job hunt. (This is
a real longshot.)
</P>
<P>
   _Continue your health benefits for 90 days or until you find a
new job.
</P>
<P>
   _Pay for five or six sessions with a career coach or counselor.
</P>
<P>
   Will the company do any of this? It's hard to say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really depends on the company,'' said Charles Prugh, a San
Francisco career counselor and outplacement expert. ``Some may help
this person out. Others won't and will say, `You're out of here on
Friday.'''
</P>
<P>
   On Overload
</P>
<P>
   Q: I have a business with one employee, an office manager who is
paid $28,000. I don't pay her overtime since I consider her an
exempt employee. But I've been told this may be open to challenge
since she cannot possibly handle the office's growing workload in
40 hours and so must work weekends, evenings, etc. Am I on shaky
ground here?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: I'd say you're on pretty shaky ground, not just legally
but &UR;  &LR; managerially.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  The legal issue is whether this employee can really be considered
exempt from overtime. She wouldn't qualify for a managerial
exemption, since she doesn't supervise any other employees. She
might qualify for an administrative exemption, but that would
depend on how much independence and authority she's allowed in her
job.
</P>
<P>
   California law says that exempt administrative employees must
work under general supervision rather than close supervision.
</P>
<P>
   They must also spend more than 50 percent of their time on tasks
involving the exercise of ``discretion and independent judgment in
the performance of intellectual work.''
</P>
<P>
   That means if this office manager spends most of her time on
routine clerical tasks like typing and answering phones, she
wouldn't qualify. But if she spends more than half her time on
things like drafting a budget or searching for new office space,
she might qualify.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's only one person in the office, I'd suspect she's
doing a lot of clerical duties,'' said Larry Shapiro, editor of the
California Employer Advisor newsletter in Tiburon. ``And if more
than 50 percent of her time is spent on clerical duties, that could
be a (legal) problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Your best bet is to talk to an employment lawyer about the
specifics of her job and whether she is correctly classified as
exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, I'd take a hard look at her workload _ even if she is
truly exempt.
</P>
<P>
   Working nights and weekends on a regular basis is a lot to ask
from someone who's paid just $28,000 a year. You run a serious risk
of burning her out and losing her. You also run a risk that work
won't get done as well as it should, and important tasks may fall
through the cracks.
</P>
<P>
   It may be time to bite the bullet and pay for a second employee
to help handle your growing workload.
</P>
<P>
   Stress in the '90s
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just moved and found a job that pays well but involves me
wearing two different hats. The stress has me questioning the job's
worth. On top of that, the company is being taken over by a very
large firm with a mixed reputation. The money is good, but I'm way
stressed out. What should I do?
</P>
<P>
   A: A new job, a heavy workload and a corporate takeover ... you
could hardly write a better recipe for 1990s stress if you tried.
</P>
<P>
   Try talking with your boss about ways to restructure your job so
it's less stressful. If that doesn't work, you need to assess how
deeply the pressure is affecting your life.
</P>
<P>
   If it's something you can tolerate, it might be worth holding on
for a while to see if things improve under the new owners.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of WORKWAYS () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  If you're finding yourself depressed, sleepless or chronically
irritable with family and friends, it may be time to move on. Good
pay isn't worth the loss of your health or your relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Don't simply up and quit, though: It will be easier to find new
work if you're currently employed. And simply knowing that you're
looking for an exit may improve your spirits.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Send your work and career questions to Ilana DeBare, Workways, San
Francisco Chronicle, 901 Mission St., San Francisco 94103. Or send
e-mail to workways(at sign)sfgate.com. &LR;   &LR; Or call (415) 764-2815. We
can't respond to each query, but we will answer as many in print as
we can. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2111EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
