<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0415 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-500&AMP;AD     03-04 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-YELTSIN-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YELTSIN CALLS FOR TYCOON'S OUSTER FROM DIPLOMATIC POST 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ President Boris Yeltsin demanded on Thursday night that
Boris Berezovsky be ousted from a prominent diplomatic post,
climaxing a power struggle that has roiled the capital.
</P>
<P>
   One of Russia's best-known and most cocksure tycoons, Berezovsky
has been serving as the chief executive of the Commonwealth of
Independent States, a largely ineffectual organization of 12 former
Soviet republics.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky, who was traveling in Azerbaijan on Commonwealth
business, said Thursday that he would not stay in his post if a
single leader turned against him.
</P>
<P>
   But few expect his near-certain dismissal to end the infighting
in Moscow. With Yeltsin ailing and presidential elections scheduled
for next year, political maneuvering has become the main
preoccupation of Russia's leaders these days, not overhauling the
nation's economy, which remains mired in depression.
</P>
<P>
   Positioning himself to succeed Yeltsin, Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov launched a broad effort to consolidate his power. He waged
a strong campaign against Berezovsky, who is unpopular with the
public because of his image as an unscrupulous wheeler-dealer who
has had a Rasputin-like influence over the Yeltsin family.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky's companies were raided by federal agents in black
ski masks. Conversations he taped between himself and Yeltsin's
daughter were seized and then leaked to the Russian press, a move
that succeeded in hurting his relations with the Yeltsin family.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov even issued a not-so-veiled threat to throw Berezovsky
in jail. Or as the prime minister put it, 94,000 prisoners would be
set free to make room in the jails for an incoming wave of corrupt
businessmen and government officials.
</P>
<P>
   But Berezovsky had refused to yield.
</P>
<P>
   The 53-year-old financier and veteran intriguer held a news
conference on Monday in which he insisted he was the victim of a
dark conspiracy. He cast the Primakov government as a throwback to
the Soviet past and demanded that the Communist Party be banned.
And Nezavisimaya Gazeta, the newspaper Berezovsky controls, has
alleged that Primakov's team is riddled with corruption, pointing
particularly to the first deputy prime minister, Yuri Maslyukov, a
Communist.
</P>
<P>
   Kremlin spokesmen said that Yeltsin was seeking Berezovsky's
dismissal because the businessman had exceeded his authority.
Technically, however, Yeltsin lacks the power to fire Berezovsky.
That authority is reserved for the commonwealth.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky has his admirers. Aides to Georgian President Eduard
A. Shevardnadze and Ukraine's president, Leonid Kuchma, criticized
Yeltsin's decision, saying he failed to consult with his fellow
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   But Yeltsin's opposition makes Berezovsky's dismissal virtually
a foregone conclusion. Berezovsky, for his part, said he would
attend a coming meeting of the Commonwealth but would not stay if
any president was against him.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Berezovsky has been hired and fired before. The businessman made
a fortune through his Logovaz car dealerships and later acquired
large stakes in oil, television, banking and airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Along with Russia's other so-called oligarchs, Berezovsky helped
finance Yeltsin's re-election in 1996. He was rewarded by being
named deputy secretary of the national security council.
</P>
<P>
   Berezovsky was later ousted from that job only to be appointed
to his current position at the commonwealth. Since then he has
backed a range of candidates including former Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin and Alexander Lebed, the former general who is now
governor of Krasnoyarsk.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's move against Berezovsky marked a dizzying comedown for
a man who helped organize the publication of Yeltsin's memoirs and
is said to have advised Yeltsin family members on their personal
finances.
</P>
<P>
   It is, however, unlikely to end the political squabbling. And
Berezovsky may not be the only victim.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow has been rife with rumors that Maslyukov and other senior
aides may be fired. A Communist who once served as head of the
central planning minister during Soviet times, Maslyukov has been a
target for critics, who say he has failed to win support from the
International Monetary Fund or hammer out an effective economic
plan,
</P>
<P>
   As rumors of a political shake-up have spread, Yeltsin's
spokesmen have even felt compelled to issue denials that Primakov
will be fired.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
