<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IBM Selling Dell $16 Billion in Computer Parts  &HT;       
 By David Einstein 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
The old guard and the young stud of the computing industry are
getting pretty chummy.
</P>
<P>
   In a blockbuster alliance announced yesterday, IBM will sell an
estimated $16 billion worth of computer parts to Dell Computer
during the next seven years. The companies also will jointly
develop new technology, which Dell could put in its products and
IBM could sell to other customers.
</P>
<P>
   The deal _ believed to be the largest such agreement _
guarantees hefty new revenues to IBM, the world's biggest
information technology company.
</P>
<P>
   And it could aid Dell in its quest to surpass Compaq as the
world's No. 1 maker of personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's stock jumped $4.25 to $171 as investors concluded that
it's a sweet deal for Big Blue. But Dell's shares rose just 94
cents to $81.88, reflecting concern that it may take more than a
high-profile alliance to reverse a recent slowdown in the company's
revenue growth.
</P>
<P>
   Dell's stock was trading as high as $108 early last month. But
it got hammered after the Round Rock, Texas, company reported a
less-than-expected 38 percent increase in sales for the fourth
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Dell, which pioneered direct sales of PCs, had been growing at a
50 percent-plus clip. It has been hurt by increasing competition
from Compaq and others. In addition, prices for corporate PCs _
Dell's main market _ are expected to slide this year, just as they
have in the consumer market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dell is striving to pass Compaq in the worldwide market, and
in order to meet that goal, they need to make some major strategy
adjustments,'' said Martin Goslar, director of PC market research
for Chaners In-Stat Group.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance with IBM _ which spends more than $5 billion a year
on research _ could lead to new products that give Dell a leg up in
the market for PCs, network servers and computer storage systems _
all areas in which it goes up against Compaq.
</P>
<P>
   For IBM of Armonk, N.Y., the alliance furthers chief executive
Louis Gerstner's goal to make sales of technology to other
companies a main engine of growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This agreement is a recognition of the value of IBM's
technology leadership in the marketplace,'' said James Vanderslice,
who runs the company's Technology Group. ``It's also further
evidence of our commitment to bring IBM-developed technology to
market quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Dell will buy high-capacity disk drives, flat-panel
displays and network cards from IBM, along with memory and custom
chips. The agreement also calls for Dell to have access to future
products such as copper-based chips that run much faster than
today's chips, which use aluminum to connect millions of
transistors.
</P>
<P>
   Dell said it might use IBM processors in some of its models _ a
move that would be a blow to Intel, which now supplies all of the
main chips for Dell computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microprocessors are among the areas where IBM has a good deal
of capability,'' said Dell spokesman T.R. Reid. ``If we can bring
that technology to bear in products for the benefit of customers,
we will do it.''
</P>
<P>
   IBM spokesman Tom Beermann said, however, that as far as he
knows, there are no plans to include processors in the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The IBM-Dell arrangement also could put pressure on Compaq,
which competes against IBM in large-scale computers and against
Dell in PCs. Compaq has been trying to emulate both companies
lately, embracing the direct-sales concept of Dell while offering
services similar to those that have helped IBM grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   Compaq's stock fell 56 cents to $33.31 yesterday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
