</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUALITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Management Fads Have Helped Improve Performance at U.S. Companies  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Sun Microsystems' microelectronics division was having problems
with its ability to handle customers' problems.
</P>
<P>
   When corporate buyers asked Sun to test a nonworking microchip
or motherboard, they'd often have to wait six months for a
diagnosis. Sometimes, Sun misplaced the product and the customer
wouldn't get an answer at all.
</P>
<P>
   So Sun set up a 15-member interdepartmental team to improve its
failure-analysis process. Now _ just more than a year later _ Sun's
customers can get a preliminary diagnosis of their problem within
six days and a final fix within 24 days.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of success story has become increasingly common in
American business during the past 20 years, according to Robert
Cole, a business professor at the University of California at
Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   And some of the credit, Cole says, should go to management
trends such as quality circles, total quality management and
re-engineering _ fads that typically evoke more ridicule or
cynicism than respect.
</P>
<P>
   `` `Dilbert' (the comic strip) has done very well by these fads,
and clearly, some were implemented quite badly by companies,'' said
Cole, author of a new book, ``Managing Quality Fads: How American
Business Learned to Play the Quality Game'' (Oxford University
Press, 1999).
</P>
<P>
   ``But across the broad range of manufacturing industries,
quality has substantially improved since the early 1980s,'' Cole
said. ``And some combination of these factors is responsible for
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole's book charts the history of quality fads in America from
the late 1970s, when companies first became alarmed by competition
from Japan.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the '60s and '70s, American cars all had clocks, but the
clocks never worked and no one ever thought twice about it,'' Cole
said. ``Then the Japanese arrived on the scene, and their clocks
worked. ... A lot of the quality movement has been about closing
the gap with Japan.''
</P>
<P>
   The earliest efforts to close the quality gap with Japan
consisted of what Cole calls ``quality by exhortation.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of QUALITY0 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Executives felt that if they could simply inspire their workers
to do a better job, they would get better products.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of our quality problems were the result of bad work
systems, but the initial reaction was to blame workers and
unions,'' Cole said. ``Then came a lot of different gurus with
conflicting advice, so there was a tremendous confusion about which
way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies jumped on a series of quality-related bandwagons that
included:
</P>
<P>
   _Quality circles, in which small teams of workers were formed to
tackle manufacturing problems.
</P>
<P>
   _Statistical process control, the use of statistical methods to
analyze and improve business processes.
</P>
<P>
   _Continuous improvement, a theory based on the Japanese concept
of kaizen, which said that companies could reap big gains in
productivity through a series of incremental process improvements
over time.
</P>
<P>
   _TQM, a catchall term referring to a variety of
quality-improvement practices.
</P>
<P>
   _Benchmarking, where companies compared their business processes
with top-performing firms in their own or other industries.
</P>
<P>
   _Re-engineering, which applied the idea of process improvement
to large corporate functions like order processing, sometimes
overhauling an entire segment of a company.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies zigged and zagged from one quality initiative to
another, leaving employees disoriented and cynical.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the quality efforts in the United States failed
because they were `programs du jour,''' said Jim Lynch, director of
corporate quality at Sun Microsystems in Palo Alto. ``Or people
confused process management with real tangible results. What's the
point of making sure that a process is `defect-free' if it's a
process that doesn't matter to your customers?''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other companies quietly took lessons from each fad
and built them into a coherent whole.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of QUALITY0 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  ``Our story is a story of continuity, not fads,'' said Richard
LeVitt, director of quality at Hewlett-Packard in Palo Alto. ``As
new things come along, we incorporate them. It's not so much
replacing one idea with another as adding that new idea.''
</P>
<P>
   How has the changing parade of quality fads affected today's
workplaces?
</P>
<P>
   Cole says that one legacy is the understanding within all kinds
of companies _ not just within manufacturing firms _ of the
importance of work processes and systems.
</P>
<P>
   Few managers today believe that they can solve problems simply
by exhorting employees to work harder. Instead, they try to look at
how to improve their business processes.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understood the concept of process in manufacturing in
the early 1980s, but applying it to administration or design would
have been a stretch,'' Cole said. ``Today, people see things like
product design as a process, not just as the result of a
collaboration of brilliant individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   Another legacy is the continued use of employee teams, either on
a regular basis or to solve specific problems, like the
failure-analysis team at Sun.
</P>
<P>
   A third legacy is the common focus today on customer service _
even in industries that traditionally didn't have a service focus.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole thrust of the quality movement was to focus
managers' attention on customers _ anticipating customers' needs
and meeting those needs,'' Cole said.
</P>
<P>
   At Sun Microsystems, executives have made a conscious effort to
stay away from quality fads and buzzwords.
</P>
<P>
   ``The debate about TQM being good or bad is a waste of time,''
Lynch said. ``We've deliberately avoided the debate around the term
TQM. There's no need to waste your management time on these
debates.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sun's homegrown solutions to quality improvement still have
roots in some of those management fads.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Sun CEO Scott McNealy invited a series of other CEOs to
brief his executive staff on their firms' quality initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 3 of QUALITY0 () &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  One guest was the CEO of Motorola, who talked about his company's
use of employee teams _ a descendant of the old ``quality circles''
fad.
</P>
<P>
   Sun set up its own ``SunTeam'' program. Now, the company has
about 300 teams _ with some 4,000 employees from both rank-and-file
jobs and management _ working on specific ways to improve
operations.
</P>
<P>
   Dean Kunesh is the quality engineer who was tapped to head a
team focused on the failure-analysis problems in Sun's
microelectronics division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were losing customers' parts _ and let me tell you, that
was really embarrassing,'' Kunesh recounted. ``Parts were coming in
at the front desk and being placed in engineers' chairs or left
with the receptionist. It wasn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   The team included customer service representatives, engineers,
even people who worked on the loading dock. They studied the
system, interviewed customers and came up with some new ways of
doing things.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Kunesh's team suggested letting customers talk
directly with an engineer when things weren't working right _
rather than going through a nontechnical intermediary. They set up
a matrix for tracking where parts were sent, who was handling them
and how long each step was taking. And they added a
customer-feedback page to every diagnostic report provided by the
division.
</P>
<P>
   The result? A dramatic decrease in diagnostic time _ down from
six months to less than one month.
</P>
<P>
   Kunesh credits his team's work with helping boost one big
client's quarterly order from $3 million to $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   And whether it's called TQM or something less trendy, he said,
the process worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be successful with the basics _ communications,
customer service, having respect for your fellow employees,''
Kunesh said. ``TQM may be a fad word. But no matter what you call
it, if you're doing those basics, you'll be successful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
