<SLUG> BC-NCR-PROXY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NCR chairman's bonus boosted to $665,704
 &HT;    By Laura A. Bischoff
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Lars Nyberg, chairman and chief executive of NCR
Corp., saw his bonus for 1998 climb 414 percent to $665,704,
boosting his total compensation for the year to $2.25 million,
according to the company's latest proxy statement.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg's compensation last year included $991,888 in salary,
$665,704 in bonus and $602,328 in other pay and stock options,
according to the proxy, filed Thursday with the Securities and
Exchange Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Nyberg's bonus in 1997 _ a difficult year for the Dayton-based
computer equipment and services company _ was $129,500. In 1996,
his bonus was $772,915. His base salary has jumped 53 percent over
the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   As previously reported, 1999 looks even better for Nyberg. He
stands to collect $5.8 million in cash bonuses on top of his usual
salary and bonus. If he is still with the company in September, he
will receive 149,533 shares of NCR stock worth about $6.3 million,
plus be eligible to purchase another 149,533 shares at $33.44 a
share. NCR stock closed Thursday at $41.37 per share.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 stock option and grant and cash bonuses are part of an
agreement Nyberg and NCR reached three years ago. The deal calls
for Nyberg to receive $3.87 million if he is still with NCR as of
June 1 and another $2 million if he signs on for another two years
at the helm. Nyberg, 47, has said he expects to continue leading
company. He has been its top executive since June 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly, executive compensation is tied to performance at
large corporations. NCR languished in 1997, but made a dramatic
turnaround last year, boosting earnings 1,642 percent to $122
million, or $1.20 per share, compared with $7 million, or 7 cents
per share, for all of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   NCR is also planning an unusual move to consolidate the number
of stockholders, according to the proxy statement. NCR will ask
shareholders at its April 15 annual meeting to approve a plan to
purchase shares from 628,000 people who own fewer than 10 NCR
shares. The move is expected to save $2.5 million a year in
administrative and mailing costs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
