<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8273 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-920(2TA     03-04 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-REPUBS-920(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPUBLICAN LEADERS IN CONGRESS AGREE ON BROAD BUDGET PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican leaders of Congress agreed Thursday
on the broad outlines of a budget plan that they said would
immediately wall off Social Security funds so they could not be
used to pay for tax cuts or new government spending.
</P>
<P>
   The budget framework for fiscal year 2,000, hammered out in days
of closed-door meetings among senior House and Senate Republicans,
would adhere to the stringent spending limits enacted in the
balanced-budget agreement reached between President Clinton and
Congress two years ago. And it would provide for a relatively small
tax cut in the fiscal year beginning Oct. 1, growing into a tax cut
of as much as $800 billion over a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we have a package that is historic,'' said Rep. John
Kasich of Ohio, the chairman of the House Budget Committee. ``For
the first time we are making the argument that government should
not take any of the money that comes in for our senior citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The outline represents the Republicans' effort to avoid the
feuding and disarray of last year and to set the stage for a battle
with Clinton over fiscal policy in an age of windfall surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is intended to protect Republicans from charges by
Clinton and Democrats that they would use Social Security money to
finance tax cuts for the wealthy. In fact Republicans hope that
their plan will prove an impediment to Democrats, leaving them open
to accusations that they are raiding Social Security if they want
to increase domestic spending.
</P>
<P>
   But the plan will force Republicans to give up hopes that they
could enact a large tax cut before the 2000 election year. While
numbers were still being assembled, Republicans said the tax cut in
the 2000 fiscal year would be about $10 billion to $15 billion. And
the outline will require the House and Senate Republicans to make
billions of dollars in spending cuts to stay within the budget
limits set in 1997. That will not be an easy task, particularly in
the House where Republicans hold a scant six-seat majority.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich and Sen. Pete Domenici of New Mexico, chairman of the
Senate Budget Committee, acknowledged that they still had to sell
the blueprint to their rank and file. Some moderates could oppose
the cuts in domestic spending the plan would necessitate. The two
men hope to report th budget plan out of their committes later this
month.
</P>
<P>
   The White House on Thursday night signaled that simply setting
aside Social Security money would not be enough to satisfy Clinton.
``Their plan is still nearly $700 billion short for Medicare,''
said Gene Sperling, the senior White House economic adviser. ``And
its not clear whether they extend the life of Social Security a
single day or how they could put together a budget that would not
lead to significant reductions in areas like education, environment
and health care.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans countered that they were actually doing more to
safeguard Social Security than Clinton. Domenici cited a study by
the Congressional BUdget Office that said the president's budget
would save only 58 percent of next year's Social Security surplus.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's running around saying he's the one saving Social
Security,'' Domenici said. ``If saving the trust fund and not
spending it is the test, we're 100 percent pure, and he's 58
percent pure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican agreement on Thursday came as the party's
congressional leaders made a determined effort to avoid the
mistakes of last year when Clinton first proposed that surpluses be
set aside to ensure the solvency of the Social Security trust fund
for the baby boom generation.
</P>
<P>
   His stand left Republicans divided over whether to save the
surplus or enact large tax cuts. The House and Senate never enacted
an agreed-upon budget plan. The result was that Clinton won
increases in education spending and other domestic spending in a
last-minute spending bill just before the election. Republicans
lost any leverage because they were afraid of being accused once
again of provoking a shut down in the government.
</P>
<P>
   For years money brought into the government through Social
Security taxes had been used to mask the true size of the federal
deficit and to pay for spending programs unrelated to retirement.
In the 2000 fiscal year, for example, the Congressional Budget
Office has projected a surplus of $133 billion. But if Social
Security funds are subtracted, the government still has a deficit
of $4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The move to wall off Social Security funds immediately was
promoted by Domenici, who wanted to blunt any charges by Democrats
that Republicans were raiding the popular federal retirement
program. Under the plan the Social Security surplus _ expected to
reach 1.8 trillion over the next decade _ can be used for debt
reduction or else for an eventual Social Security overhaul. To
spend the surpluses any other way would require 60 votes in the
Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal was initially resisted by Kasich who had wanted to
phase in such a plan over several years in order to be able to dip
into the surplus for a little bit longer. That would have made it
easier for Republicans to craft a large tax cut as the centerpiece
of an election year agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans said that Kasich was ultimately pleased with the
decision to stay within the budget limits set in the balanced
budget law, despite pressure for more spending. And he took
satisfaction in the Senate's agreement to a phased-in tax cut.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Republicans said their plan would also live within next year's
spending limit of about $550 billion for discretionary spending in
domestic and military programs. And they said they would accomplish
this while also raising military spending. Even if programs are
frozen at this year's levels, Congress will still have to make
savings of about $15 billion because of inflation. And that is
before increases in military and education spending, which are
desired by both parties, are taken into account. Such increases
would require offsetting spending cuts in other programs.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich and Domenici did not say what kind of tax cut the
Republicans will enact and the budget resolution is usually silent
on that question, leaving it up to Congress' tax writing committees
to decide that later in the year. Republicans are deeply divided
over whether to pursue an across-the board 10 percent tax cut,
whether to enact tax credits for certain social purposes, or
whether to pursue other tax reductions, such as a cut in the
so-called marriage penalty which results in married couples
sometimes paying more in taxes than if they were single.
</P>
<P>
   One option that might make it easier for Republicans to stay
within the budget caps, several Republicans said, would be for them
to enact a tax cut, such as a reduction in the capital gains tax,
which could initially bring in more government revenue by spurring
economic activity.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich, who is running for the Republican presidential
nomination, said he is still committed to the sweeping 10 percent
tax reduction. He joked he would find a way to include a subliminal
message in the budget plan in favor of that kind of tax cut.
``But,'' he admitted, ``who knows how it's going to come out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
