<SLUG> BC-LEWINSKY-REACT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEWINSKY INTERVIEW DREW INTEREST OF VIEWERS  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By LAWRIE MIFFLIN With STUART ELLIOTT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Americans were sick and tired of Monica Lewinsky,
and even Barbara Walters would not offer enough incentive to watch
more, some people said. Others said Ms. Lewinsky's face and voice
would be magnetic. The fascination theorists were right.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Walters' interview on Wednesday night attracted an average
of 48.5 million viewers, and an estimated 70 million people watched
all or part of the two-hour program, in about 33.2 million homes (a
33.4 Nielsen rating). Of the television sets in use in those two
hours, 48 percent were tuned to ABC, an exceptionally high number
for a news program, and high for any broadcast television event in
this multichannel age.
</P>
<P>
   Although far more people watched the last Super Bowl (an average
of 83.7 million) or Academy Awards show (87 million), or even last
May's final episode of the sitcom ``Seinfeld'' (76.3 million), no
single network news program has ever been watched by as many
people.
</P>
<P>
   And no such news program, it is believed, has ever pulled in as
much money for a network. Advertising industry executives estimated
that ABC made $20 million to $25 million in commercials sold for
the hours between 9 and 11 p.m. that night, at least three times
its normal revenue for those hours on a Wednesday. The precise
figure cannot be calculated because advertisers negotiated assorted
deals for this expanded edition of ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC News, which said it did not pay Ms. Lewinsky for the
interview, certainly did a comprehensive job of promoting it,
which, in turn, helped kick off sales of Ms. Lewinsky's book,
``Monica's Story,'' published Thursday by St. Martin's Press.
</P>
<P>
   A company spokesman, John Murphy, said Thursday that the
publishing house was preparing to print 400,000 more books to fill
back orders, in addition to the initial run of 400,000 copies. It
remains to be seen whether the book can maintain the momentum of
the initial rush.
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, Joe Lockhart, President Clinton's press
secretary, said the president did not watch the interview.
</P>
<P>
   ABC did all it could to generate interest in the program, which
had added importance to the network because it appeared on the
final night of a ``sweeps'' month when Nielsen ratings are used to
set advertising rates for the next quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The day of the interview, Ms. Walters talked about it on ``Good
Morning America,'' ``Live With Regis and Kathie Lee,'' ``The View''
(a late-morning talk show of which she is a co-host with three
other women) and ``World News Tonight.'' Afterward, she was a guest
on ABC News' ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a real information age media event, with pre-game and
post-game commentary, instant replay and instant polls,'' Diane
Sawyer, the co-host of ABC News' ``Good Morning America,'' said
shortly after 7 a.m. Thursday, as ABC picked up the ball again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good Morning America'' devoted most of its two hours to the
interview _ replaying highlights, showing polls and viewers'
e-mail, and interviewing experts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Two hours of Ms. Lewinsky might be too much, some television
industry experts thought. But the Nielsen ratings increased in each
of the first three half-hours, and declined only between 10:30 and
11 p.m. Sets in use declined then, too.
</P>
<P>
   For the February sweeps period, Ms. Walters' interview propelled
ABC into a tie for second place, with Fox, among 18-to-49-year-old
viewers, the group that advertisers pay the most to reach.
</P>
<P>
   Because this ``20/20'' was a ``special'' (at two hours), ABC
could ask advertisers for a higher price, and did: $800,000 per
30-second commercial. But industry sources said very few paid that
price (five times the normal rate for ``20/20''), and most will end
up paying $300,000 to $500,000 per spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
