<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8284 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN05-COX     03-04 0670
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woman who aided '94 GOP House takeover signs on to Bush's
exploratory committee
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The woman who helped mastermind the 1994
Republican takeover of the U.S. House has signed on to help direct
Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Sources close to Bush confirmed Thursday that Maria Cino, former
executive director of the National Republican Congressional
Committee, will take a top staff job in the campaign, now in the
preliminary fund-raising stage.
</P>
<P>
   Word of Cino's hiring comes as Bush prepares for a Sunday
announcement of the members of the exploratory committee that will
quickly rev up to full-speed fund-raising. Former Secretary of
State George Shultz, who has been consulting with Bush, is expected
to be a committee member.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, Bush's big weekend will begin with fund-raising efforts
for President Bill Clinton's hometown congressman. Bush is the
featured speaker at the Dallas event for U.S. Rep. Jay Dickey
(R-Arkansas).
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Bush will drop by the University Interscholastic
League girls basketball tournament and then head to Houston for a
Saturday night speech to congregants at Second Baptist Church.
</P>
<P>
   After a Sunday morning speech at the same church, Bush will
return to Austin to introduce members of his exploratory committee
at an Austin Convention Center news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members, such as Cino, will not be introduced Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Cino, now affiliated with the Washington law and lobbying firm
of Wiley, Rein &AMP; Fielding, served as executive director of the
National Republican Congressional Committee from 1993-1996.
</P>
<P>
   According to her resume, she was ``responsible for managing two
historic (U.S.) House Republican victories.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the GOP took control of the House for the first time in
40 years. In 1996, the party retained the majority for the first
time in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   Her current firm has lobbied on behalf of a long list of
clients, including Eastman Kodak, United Airlines, United Parcel
Service, Dallas-based A.H. Belo Corp. (owner of the Dallas Morning
News), Gannett Company (owner of several newspapers) and the
Newspaper Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   Cino's clients have included United Airlines and the Federal
Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Fielding, a senior partner at the firm, served as counsel
to President Ronald Reagan from 1981-1986. He served as deputy
counsel to President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   At NRCC, Cino's boss was then-U.S. Rep. Bill Paxon of New York,
was was the committee chairman. From 1989-1992, Cino was chief of
staff for Paxon.
</P>
<P>
   In a reminder that political circles are sometimes tight ones,
Paxon is married to former U.S. Rep. Susan Molinari. Former U.S.
Rep. Guy Molinari, Susan's father, is coordinator of the Draft Bush
2000 Committee that has won the support of 76 current members of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Among those is Dickey, a four-term House member whose district
includes Hope and Hot Springs, the cities in which Clinton was
raised.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, as the Senate impeachment trial churned toward
acquittal of Clinton, The New York Times reported that Dickey was
among several House members targeted for defeat by the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought his story was a compelling story,'' Bush said of
Dickey. ``He is from President Clinton's home state and had been
threatened politically for making a tough decision so I thought I'd
try to help him as much as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton aides denied there was a political hit list.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey, who had remained undecided for several weeks prior to
the House impeachment vote, wound up voting for two of the four
articles of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Dickey, noting that Bush is about the hottest political property
in the nation, said Thursday, ``The timing of this event is
certainly fortuitous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My supporters are looking forward to hearing from Governor
Bush,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
