</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) SALT LAKE CITY, Utah -- March 04, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN.
MARCH 7 -- BIZ-AMERICAN-SKI, 3-04 -- American Skiing has grown from
a single location in 1994 to nine, including the Canyons Ski
Resort, now being expanded in Utah. But warm, dry winter weather
has cut revenues in recent months. One analyst called the company
the most highly leveraged in the winter recreation industry.
(George Frey/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN. MARCH 7 --
ABOUT-CARS-WAGONS-3, 3-04 -- With a 282 horsepower V8, the BMW 540i
is the the more muscular sibling of the 528i. The V8 overpowers
everything in the class, moving from 0 to 60 miles an hour in a
slender 6.3 seconds. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN. MARCH 7 --
ABOUT-CARS-WAGONS-2, 3-04 -- The Audi A6 Avant wagon can handle up
to seven passenger in three rows of seats. In Europe, where station
wagon memories linger, Audi and BMW are the latest car makers to
believe they have an alternative for the thinking driver. (New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN. MARCH 7 --
ABOUT-CARS-WAGONS-1, 3-04 -- The Mercedes-Benz E320 is at the high
end of the resurgent wagon group. The wagon rebirth should appeal
to people who camp, ski or scuba - or look as if they do - and want
the zip of a performance sedan at the tip of their toes and the
prowess of its road-holding in their hands and don't want a sport
utility vehicle. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) BEKAA VALLEY, Lebanon -- March 04, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SAT.
MARCH 6 -- LEBANON-HASHISH-COX, 3-04 -- Lebanese farmer Ali gave up
growing Hashish when authorities cracked down on drugs in the Bekaa
Valley. ``They said they were going to pay us something for what we
lost, but they didn't,'' says Salwan, 64, who is bitter that he
hasn't received the aid he expected to help find new crops. He says
he now grows wheat at barely 15 percent the price of cannabis.
(Larry Kaplow/Cox Newspapers Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) LOS ANGELES -- March 04, 1999 -- SCI-LA-QUAKE, 3-04 -- A
view of the the Los Angeles skyline last year. Using information
once jealously guarded by oil and gas companies, scientists have
identified a major new fault under downtown Los Angeles. Called the
Puente Hills blind thrust, the fault, which is active, lies hidden
in the basement of the metropolitan area and is capable of
producing a devastating earthquake. (Monica Almeida/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- NY-MRSCLINTON, 3-04 --
Students listen to first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton during a visit
to their school in Manhattan on Thursday. Mrs. Clinton continued
her visit to the city on Thursday amid increasing speculation about
her possible run for the Senate seat of Sen. Daniel Patrick
Moynihan, a fellow Democrat who is retiring. (James Estrin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) DETROIT -- March 04, 1999 -- DETROIT-SCHOOLS, 3-04 --
Stephanie Rountree leads her second grade students in songs
celebrating African history on Thursday. Frustrated by the many
problems of Detroit's schools, Michigan's governor and
Republican-controlled legislature are moving swiftly this winter to
require Detroit's mayor to take over this city's school
system.(Peter Yates/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) TAMPA, Fla. -- March 04, 1999 -- BBA-YANKS-HUNTER, 3-04
-- Jim ``Catfish'' Hunter, right, sits with fellow pitching legend
Whitey Ford inside the Yankees dugout prior to a game against the
Toronto Blue Jays on Thursday. Hunter, in his first public
appearance since announcing he was diagnosed with Lou Gehrig's
disease four months ago, took part in pregame ceremonies at the New
York Yankees' exhibition season opener against the Toronto Blue
Jays. (Barton Silverman/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) WASHINGTON -- March 04, 1999 -- OBIT-BLACKMUN-3, 3-04 --
The flags outside the U.S. Supreme Court fly at half staff on
Thursday in honor of retired Justice Harry Blackmun who died.
Blackmun, author of the 1973 decision that legalized abortion
nationwide and set off one of the most explosive political debates
in American history, died on Thursday at age 90. (Shana Raab/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- FIDDLER-DANCE-REVIEW, 3-04
-- Takehiro Ueyama, left, and Andy LeBeau in front of other members
of the Paul Taylor Dance Company in ``Fiddlers Green.'' Taylor's
recent dance works have tended to be very funny or very nasty,
sometimes both. But this new and beautiful production reminds us
that the essential Taylor is the one who hears music and
choreographs to it. (Ruby Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- March 04, 1999 -- CONGRESS-BANKING, 3-04
-- Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, center, during a Senate Banking
Committee meeting on Thursday. A financial overhaul bill proposed
by Gramm split the committee along partisan lines on Thursday. The
bill faces a presidential veto because President Clinton believes
it would lift Depression-era barriers between banks, securities
firms and insurance companies, and would fail to protect consumers.
(Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- March 04, 1999 -- OBIT-BLACKMUN-B&AMP;W-2,
3-04 -- Retiring Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun speaks to
reporters after his final news conference in 1994. Blackmun, author
of the 1973 decision that legalized abortion nationwide and set off
one of the most explosive political debates in American history,
died on Thursday at age 90. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 --
SUB-CHENOWETH-THEATER-REVIEW, 3-04 -- Kristian Chenoweth, who plays
Sally in ``You're a Good Man Charlie Brown,'' signs autographs
outside the Ambassador Theater last Saturday. Chenoweth has been
receiving some of the season's best reviews as Charlie Brown's kid
sister. (Chang W. Lee/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BOSTON -- March 04, 1999 -- VOICE-SURGEON, 3-04 -- Dr.
Steven Zeitels examines his patient, Livingston Taylor, a singer
and songwriter, at the Massachusetts Eye and Ear Infirmary. On
almost any day, the voices of professional singers can be heard
scaling octaves in Zeitels's examining rooms. (Tom Herde/Boston
Globe Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BELFAST, Northern Ireland -- March 04, 1999 --
NIRELAND-VIOLENCE-2, 3-04 -- Andrew Peden, 33, a Protestant, at his
home in west Belfast. Peden barely survived shotgun wounds and ten
hours of assault by Unionist Volunteer Force fighters last year
that required months of hospitalization and a double amputation.
Peden was a victim of punishment beatings, a practice where members
of the paramilitary armies that control working class neighborhoods
in this conflicted British province turn their violence not on
their declared enemies from the other side of the religious divide
but on their own. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BELFAST, Northern Ireland -- March 04, 1999 --
NIRELAND-VIOLENCE-1, 3-04 -- Mrs. Maureen Kearney, a nationalist
Roman Catholic, holds a cross with a photo of her son Andrew
Kearney who was killed last year by members of the Irish Republican
Army. Kearney was a victim of punishment beatings, a practice where
members of the paramilitary armies that control working class
neighborhoods in this conflicted British province turn their
violence not on their declared enemies from the other side of the
religious divide but on their own. (Carlos Lopez-Barillas/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) UNDATED -- March 04, 1999 -- CARS-EURO-MINIVANS-3, 3-04
-- Citroen's Picasso will soon be available in Europe's hot
compact-minivan market. According to Georges Douin, vice president
for product design at Renault, traditional sedans and hatchbacks
held 85 percent of the European market in 1990 but fell to 70
percent in 1990. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) UNDATED -- March 04, 1999 -- CARS-EURO-MINIVANS-2, 3-04
-- Renault's Scenic just about created Europe's compact-minivan
market, which is on the rise. It arrived in force in 1997, and
275,000 Scenics were sold last year - more than the combined sales
of the Megane hatchback, sedan and convertible models. The Scenic
made Megane the No. 2 nameplate in Western Europe after
Volkswagen's Golf. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) UNDATED -- March 04, 1999 -- CARS-EURO-MINIVANS-1, 3-04
-- The A-Class by Mercedes-Benz. At major shows like the Geneva
Motor Show, which opens next week, it is clear that the European
market is moving from sedans and hatchbacks to a minivan-like shape
known as monospace. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) TYRE, Lebanon -- March 04, 1999 -- JOURNAL-LEBANON-COX,
3-04 -- Sheikh Nabil Kaouk, leader of Hezbollah, or Party of God,
for southern Lebanon, in his office during a recent interview. In
the background is a portrait of the overall leader of the Lebanese
Hezbollah movement, Sheik Hassan Nasrallah. ``We hope the Americans
will stop hating us,'' said Kaouk. ``We are dying from American
weapons (used by Israelis) and they don't feel guilty about that.''
(Photo by Larry Kaplow/Cox Newspapers)(Larry Kaplow/Cox News
Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- March 04, 1999 -- NY-GORE, 3-04 -- Vice
President Al Gore reacts to a student's answer during a visit with
second graders at the Helen Keller School in the Bronx on Thursday.
Gore asked a student what she wished to do when she grew up. The
student replied she wanted to be vice president. (Keith Meyers/New
York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK, N.Y. -- March 04, 1999 -- ANNIE-THEATER-REVIEW,
3-04 -- Bernadette Peters plays the sharpshooter Annie Oakley in
Irving Berlin's ``Annie Get Your Gun,'' which opened last night at
the Marquis Theater. Every so often, though not close to often
enough, something sharp and radiant pierces through the acrid smog
that makes up this misconceived revival. That something is not
surprisingly Ms. Peters. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) REDWOOD CITY, Calif. -- March 04, 1999 -- GERM-WARFARE,
3-03 -- Frank James,77, who survived the Bataan Death March as well
as atrocities as a prisoner in the Japanese Army's Camp Mukden, in
Manchuria, in his home during a recent interview. More than 50
years after the Japanese army attacked China with germ weapons and
conducted gruesome experiments on thousands of human beings, Japan
is resisting demands that it compensate the victims or make records
of the atrocities public. (Darcy Padilla/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) WASHINGTON -- March 04, 1999 -- OBIT-BLACKMUN-B&AMP;W-1, 3-04
-- Retiring Supreme Court Justice Harry Blackmun speaks to
reporters after his final news conference in 1994. Blackmun, author
of the 1973 decision that legalized abortion nationwide and set off
one of the most explosive political debates in American history,
died on Thursday at age 90. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) HOLLYWOOD -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
20-DATES-FILM, 3-04 -- Myles Berkowitz, the director and star of
``20 Dates.'' By bending the rules to send up the conventions of
romance, Berkowitz, 36, produced a movie that defies genre labels.
``It's a screwball romantic comedy, it's a document of single life
today, it's guerrilla filmmaking,'' says Berkowitz, 36, who found
love with Elisabeth Wagner in the middle of filming. (Monica
Almeida/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
CANBY-THEATER, 3-04 -- Corin Redgrave, left, and Sherri Parker Lee
in Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales,'' at Circle in the
Square on Broadway. As staged by Trevor Nunn, the artistic director
of the Royal National Theater in London, the production is so
spectacularly realized that it both serves the play and celebrates
the Williams career, for which it can be seen as a kind of gaudy
preface. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
SNAKEBIT-THEATER, 3-04 -- David Marshall Grant, the author of
``Snakebit,'' which reopens Monday at the Century Center for the
Performing Arts. Peter Marks, writing in The New York Times, calls
the play ``the intimate sort of Off Broadway theater that has you
picking apart the characters long after the curtain falls.'' (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
DANCEGALAXY, 3-04 -- Medhi Bahiri, far left, the creative director
of DanceGalaxy, with Suzanne Goldman, Allison Brown, center, and
Judith Fugate, the company's artistic director, right. Ms. Fugate
and Bahiri are part of a growing trend, in modern dance for the
most part, of providing showcases for the kind of burnished
artistry that comes only with age. The troupe makes its formal New
York debut on Tuesday at the Joyce Theater. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
BAND-IN-BERLIN-THEATER, 3-04 -- From left, Timothy Leigh Evans,
Mark Bleeke, Wilbur Pauley, Hugo Munday and Peter Becker in Susan
Feldman's ``Band in Berlin'' at the Helen Hayes Theater. Even the
production team has trouble describing the collage of film, slides,
puppets and live singers that constitutes ``Band.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
