<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8298 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-REDSOX-FISK-BOS &LR;      03-04 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-FISK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX, FISK DISCUSS A JOB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT MYERS, Fla. _ For close to five years, Dan Duquette has
courted Carlton Fisk about taking a job with the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday, the Vermont-born, New Hampshire-bred,
one-day-Hall-of-Fame-bound catcher indicated that he is close to
saying yes to the team with which he began his much-decorated
career, but left under acrimonious circumstances. Apparently he is
prepared to embrace the team as his own again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're serious,'' Fisk, 51, said as Duquette escorted him
through the Sox clubhouse Thursday morning. ``There's been some
contact over the years, and now it's coming to a head.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette said the nature of the job is still under discussion.
``Maybe he'll be on-field with players, maybe he'll do some
coaching, maybe he'll be a special assistant to the general
manager,'' said the GM, smiling broadly.
</P>
<P>
   The assistant's job would appear to be the most likely scenario
for Fisk, allowing him the flexibility to spend some time in
uniform while also keeping a hand in front-office matters,
including player evaluation and personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, who visited with Fisk while hitting
ground balls on a back field, played against Fisk when both were in
the minor leagues. That was in 1971, when Fisk was with Triple A
Louisville and Williams was with Tidewater. The following season,
Fisk was the unanimous choice as American League Rookie of the
Year, setting off a 22-year career during which he set the major
league record for games caught.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would think so,'' Williams said when asked if hiring Fisk
would be a positive for the ball club. ``Him being a Red Sock for
so many years, the things he did in Boston, you people know better
than I do. Say his name, it's synonymous with the Red Sox. Even
though he played for the White Sox, this is where it's still.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be real good for the organization to bring
back somebody who played as long as he did. They still show shots
of his (1975 World Series) home run, to say the least a dramatic
home run, and they'll be showing that for a long time from now.''
</P>
<P>
   Duquette and club CEO John Harrington first met with Fisk in
1994, Duquette's first year with the team, and a year after Fisk's
career came to a bitter end, at age 45, when the White Sox released
him.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Fisk was assisting in the coaching of his son
Casey's team at Illinois State. But otherwise Fisk stayed away from
the game. There was no going back to the White Sox, not after he'd
openly warred with club owner Jerry Reinsdorf. And there had yet to
be a healing of the rupture with the Red Sox, which dated back to
1980, when amid a bitter contract dispute, Haywood Sullivan failed
to mail Fisk's contract in time, making him a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   But there were signs of a thaw in September 1997, when Fisk was
inducted into the Red Sox Hall of Fame and honored at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you grow, you mature in life,'' Fisk said on that
occasion. ``I think every guy, kid, athlete who has grown up in New
England fantasizes about playing for the Boston Red Sox in Fenway
Park, wearing the Red Sox uniform, and I was fortunate enough to
realize that fairy tale. A lot of fairy tales have been told and in
every one of them, there's a scary part, an unpleasant part, but
they all culminate with happy endings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be a happy ending. Maybe it's a happy
beginning.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk, who has a home in Sarasota, about 90 minutes from the Sox
facility, figures to be an on-field presence in spring training if
he takes a job with the club. The Red Sox, with young catchers
Scott Hatteberg and Jason Varitek, would welcome his wisdom,
especially coming from a chiseled specimen who looks as if he could
still strap on a chest protector, if it weren't for the five knee
operations and three hand operations he endured.
</P>
<P>
   What has he been doing with himself? ``Golfing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, someone suggested, he could be Duquette's media
liaison. ``Yeah, right, you know the way I got along with you
guys,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the title, veteran Tim Wakefield said Fisk belongs
here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before he even told me (about a possible job), I said to him,
`I'd love to see you in uniform again,' '' Wakefield said. ``To
have somebody of that caliber, that stature, helping young guys,
just talking to him would be a great asset to our club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
