in Tennessee Williams' ``Not About Nightingales,'' at Circle in the
Square on Broadway. As staged by Trevor Nunn, the artistic director
of the Royal National Theater in London, the production is so
spectacularly realized that it both serves the play and celebrates
the Williams career, for which it can be seen as a kind of gaudy
preface. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
SNAKEBIT-THEATER, 3-04 -- David Marshall Grant, the author of
``Snakebit,'' which reopens Monday at the Century Center for the
Performing Arts. Peter Marks, writing in The New York Times, calls
the play ``the intimate sort of Off Broadway theater that has you
picking apart the characters long after the curtain falls.'' (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
DANCEGALAXY, 3-04 -- Medhi Bahiri, far left, the creative director
of DanceGalaxy, with Suzanne Goldman, Allison Brown, center, and
Judith Fugate, the company's artistic director, right. Ms. Fugate
and Bahiri are part of a growing trend, in modern dance for the
most part, of providing showcases for the kind of burnished
artistry that comes only with age. The troupe makes its formal New
York debut on Tuesday at the Joyce Theater. (Ruby Washington/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- March 03, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., MARCH 7 --
BAND-IN-BERLIN-THEATER, 3-04 -- From left, Timothy Leigh Evans,
Mark Bleeke, Wilbur Pauley, Hugo Munday and Peter Becker in Susan
Feldman's ``Band in Berlin'' at the Helen Hayes Theater. Even the
production team has trouble describing the collage of film, slides,
puppets and live singers that constitutes ``Band.'' (Sara
Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
