<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-CONVENTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRAT PLANS FOR CONVENTION IN LA HIT A SNAG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY RAKOWSKY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Don't print the LA 2000 T-shirts and buttons yet. Los
Angeles' bid to host the Democratic National Convention next year
has run into ``difficulty,'' according to sources close to the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The sticking point is a familiar one: Republican Mayor Richard
Riordan does not want to be liable for raising $35 million to host
the convention, sources said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan has urged the DNC to sign a contract with the
businessmen spearheading the city's bid _ billionaire Eli Broad,
entertainment industry mogul David Geffen, and Los Angeles lawyer
William Wardlaw. But the DNC has always signed its convention
contract with a government executive, not a group of private
citizens, according to several people familiar with the process.
</P>
<P>
   The snags in LA's bid persist two weeks after Boston Mayor
Thomas M. Menino unexpectedly announced that Los Angeles was
negotiating a formal contract that spelled a sure end to Boston's
first quest to land the nomination party for August 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Menino's announcement preempted a party announcement about the
LA negotiations, surprising members of the DNC.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday a DNC spokeswoman said the negotiations are continuing
with Los Angeles, but declined to discuss any details.
</P>
<P>
   Menino made his DNC remarks on the same day he learned that the
US Department of Housing and Urban Development had issued charges
against the city for failing to protect minority residents of
public housing from harassment before 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While some local observers wondered if there was any tie between
the two events, Washington sources said it did not appear that
Menino's statements raised much ire in the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   But in Denver Thursday, there was some sentiment that Boston had
dropped off the convention radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been given an indication by folks in Washington that if
LA doesn't work out, they would stay in the West,'' said Mike Dino,
who has headed Denver's bid for the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Dino said Mayor Wellington Webb has been too busy preparing for
his reelection bid in May to think about the Democratic convention
the past several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Dino said if LA or Denver had been able to muster the private-
and public-sector support that Boston had for its convention bid,
the contract would have been signed with LA or Denver months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's bid included an $8 million pledge from the city and
another $8 million from the state as well as pledges from the
business community to round out a $34 million bid.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston could never compete, insiders said, with the 54
electoral votes of California. That storehouse of electoral power
is the prize the DNC and Vice President Al Gore are not likely to
let slip, some said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
