<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: HOW BIBI GOT RE-ELECTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM, June 2, 1999 (NYT) _ Israel's Likud prime minister,
Benjamin Netanyahu, won re-election tonight in a landslide over the
Labor party leader, Ehud Barak, pulling in 64 percent of the vote
against 36 percent for Barak. Pollsters said Netanyahu's lopsided
victory was due to one factor: his decision, on the eve of the
voting, to unilaterally withdraw all Israeli troops from south
Lebanon _ a move that has set off an earthquake in Israeli politics
and throughout the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's come-from-behind victory was stunning. On May 17,
only two weeks ago, in the first round of voting for the prime
ministry, Netanyahu was trounced by Barak, who seemed to be a
shoo-in to win the second and final round.
</P>
<P>
   At that time, though, Netanyahu was sinking in the Lebanese
quagmire, which was killing Israeli boys and seemed destined to
kill his political career too. Israeli pundits were pointing out
that Bibi was handling the Lebanon issue the same way he did the
Palestinian issue _ wavering between one half-baked strategy and
another, using sound bites to defuse it as a political threat to
him, but without being ready to either pull out, use decisive
military force or open talks with Syria that might produce a
decisive diplomatic solution for both Lebanon and the Golan
Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by an Israeli radio reporter what had prompted him to go
for a unilateral withdrawal, Netanyahu said: ``I finally said to
myself: `Look, what are Israel's strengths? Our political strength
is that we don't want an inch of Lebanon, we're just there for
security. And our technological strength is that we have the most
advanced army in the Middle East, which can deter and trounce any
conventional military threat.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I looked at it that way,'' continued Netanyahu, ``I
realized that by staying in Lebanon we were actually undermining
both our strengths. Politically we could not defend ourselves,
because when people shot at our boys in Lebanon, the rest of the
world would say: `What do you expect? You're in someone else's
country.' And technologically, we were fighting the most low-tech
guerrilla war possible in a terrain we didn't really know against
an enemy we couldn't really see. The Syrians and Iranians were
getting all the advantages of pressure on us, without any of the
costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that Israeli troops are out of Lebanon, noted Netanyahu,
everything is reversed: Politically, if the Iranian-directed
Lebanese Hezbollah guerrillas try to come across the border, they
will be invading Israel, and Israel will be justified in massively
retaliating against Lebanese, Syrian and Iranian troops that abet
such an invasion. And if Israel does retaliate, it won't be with
guerrilla warfare, but with the Israeli Air Force massively
striking Lebanese, Iranian and Syrian military targets in Lebanon,
and maybe inside Syria.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli move has totally unnerved the Syrians, the Hezbollah
guerrillas and Iran. ``They are all now in a quandary,'' said the
Middle East expert Stephen P. Cohen. ``The Hezbollah guerrillas are
saying to themselves: `Now that we have liberated Lebanon, do we
want to use that as leverage to rule Lebanon? Or do we want to use
that as a springboard to move on to Jerusalem?' If they want to do
the latter, now they're really going to have to pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cohen said what had really shocked him, though, was Netanyahu's
decision to accompany his unilateral withdrawal with an offer to
resume negotiations with Syria over the Golan Heights _ on whatever
terms Syria wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now the Syrians have to choose,'' said Cohen. ``Either they
take up the Israeli offer, and go for full peace, or they are going
to have to pay retail for staying in Lebanon. From now on, the
continued Syrian presence in Lebanon will not be seen as protection
of Lebanese sovereignty but as the only real threat to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu's move was welcomed by even some of his harshest
critics. The New York Times Foreign Affairs columnist Thomas L.
Friedman wrote: ``For a long time Bibi has been running on the
slogan that he is `a strong leader for a strong country.' By
constantly avoiding big decisions on the Palestinian and Lebanese
issues, though, Netanyahu did not look like a very strong leader,
and he was making Israel look like not a very strong country. With
this unilateral withdrawal, Bibi has made himself the dynamic
player in the Middle East today, and people will have to give him a
second look.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
