A8309 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MRSDOLE-PRESIDENCY-NY     03-04 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRSDOLE-PRESIDENCY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOLE TO START EXPLORATORY PANEL IN SIGN THAT SHE PLANS '00 RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Tenn.)  (js) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a clear sign that she intends to run for
president, Elizabeth Dole, the former president of the American Red
Cross, plans to announce next week that she is starting a committee
that will allow her to explore a candidacy and raise money for a
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign watchers had been picking up uncertain signals about
Mrs. Dole's intentions, particularly as Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, another likely candidate for the Republican nomination,
began accumulating endorsements and scheduled his own announcement
for Sunday that he is starting an exploratory committee. Lamar
Alexander, the former governor of Tennessee, plans to announce that
he is running, not just exploring, on Tuesday in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole is now taking several steps to erase any doubts and
begin actively to compete for campaign dollars. She is announcing
the formation of her exploratory committee on Wednesday in Des
Moines, according to Joyce Campbell, a spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said she was building a portfolio on various issues and
has bought television time in both Iowa and New Hampshire to run
commercials next week in conjunction with her announcement.
Supporters said that in the commercials she would highlight her
experience as a cabinet member and begin to convey her views, which
are largely unknown since she has never run for office. She also
plans a four-day campaign-style swing around the country.
</P>
<P>
   She has hired a campaign manager, Tom Daffron, a former chief of
staff for Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn. And she has hired a
communications director, Ari Fleischer, who has been the spokesman
for the House Ways and Means Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole and Bush join more than a half-dozen other Republicans
who have announced similar committees or candidacies, or intend to
in the near future, because the primary schedule is so compressed
and the amount of money finite.
</P>
<P>
   They include Sen. Robert Smith of New Hampshire, the
conservative columnist Pat Buchanan, former Vice President Dan
Quayle, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Rep. John Kasich of Ohio, the
magazine publisher Steve Forbes and the conservative activist Gary
Bauer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
