<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8313 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     03-04 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' BOSS OF BOSSES FACING TOUGH DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This just in from the Boss of Bosses: There will be no
``rent-a-players,'' no Theo Fleurys, for the Dallas Stars in their
1999 Stanley Cup quest.
</P>
<P>
   Owner Tom Hicks isn't interested in parting with any of the
Stars' young, talented minor-league prospects for a player who'll
be history before the ice melts after the last game of the year at
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   But don't get a game misconduct by throwing a temper fit before
you get to Hicks' kicker:
</P>
<P>
   Anyone the Stars trade for _ like NHL stalwarts Mark Recchi of
Montreal or Adam Graves of the New York Rangers, for instance _
should plan on sticking around for a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the kinds of the players who could help you for four
or five years to come,'' Hicks said yesterday during a break from a
business meeting in Utah. ``We'd want to sign them long-term.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can get the right player, \Rgeneral manager\S Bob
\RGainey\S has my full support. If he can't, we'd just as soon keep
our assets, because we think we can win this year with what we've
got.''
</P>
<P>
   The important thing is that Hicks, Gainey and coach Ken
Hitchcock are all fully committed to a whatever-it-takes approach
to winning the Cup. The Stars are too good and too close to let
this one slip away because they weren't willing to add one more
crucial and necessary piece.
</P>
<P>
   If that means trading the next budding superstar at Kalamazoo,
so be it. We'll help him pack and pin an I-Almost-Did-Dallas bumper
sticker on his sports utility vehicle. These opportunities don't
come along often enough to let them slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to trade a player that would hurt us to do
something that would be of questionable benefit, because everything
is working real well right now,'' Hicks cautioned. ``We have some
issues with the expansion draft coming up this summer and we have
some people we know we might lose. If we could trade somebody we're
going to lose anyway and get somebody who can help us, that would
be good.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, that would be really good. Wouldn't it?
</P>
<P>
   This just in from Hitchcock: Maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think our whole view is that we don't want to
undervalue what we've accomplished in two years,'' Hitchcock said
from Long Island, N.Y., where the Stars played the Islanders last
night. ``It's like renting a player and it's a crapshoot. We've had
players come in here and it's taken 8 or 10 weeks for those players
to become acclimatized to our group, to match the energy our
players have.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've built a strong chemistry, not just with the players who
are here but the ones who are close at Kalamazoo. When you make a
trade, even for a really good player, other people on your team
have to sacrifice. Roles change. Sometimes that chemistry works and
sometimes it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with a coach who believes in his players and is
willing to go to war with them.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing wrong with adding another howitzer to the front line,
though, either.
</P>
<P>
   Did trading for Fleury hurt Colorado's chemistry? On the
contrary, word from the Rocky Mountain State is that Pikes Peak
grew another 2,000 feet. They had to peel the Avalanche players off
the ceiling, they were so electrified by the news.
</P>
<P>
   The message that Colorado management sent to the players came in
neon lights that the whole league could read: We're doing whatever
it takes to win the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   Calgary did that in 1988, if you'll recall.
</P>
<P>
   That's the year the Flames traded a young, flashy winger with
thoroughbred bloodlines to the St. Louis Blues for three players
you probably never heard of named Steve Bozek, Robb Ramage and Rick
Wamsley.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Blues got Brett Hull, who had just scored 26 goals and
had 24 assists in his first full NHL season. A year later the
Flames won the only Stanley Cup they've ever won and the three
players they acquired for Hull played key roles.
</P>
<P>
   Was it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' Stars center Joe Nieuwendyk said, ``I've never
heard anybody in Calgary complain about that trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitchcock, who admits he's so focused on dealing with the
players he already has that he'd rather not know what Gainey is
doing until he's asked for his input, remains uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just can't take away the value of what your team spends
six months trying to accomplish,'' Hitchcock said. ``You already
know what you've got now. You don't know what you've got when you
start making changes. When you make a trade, somebody's coming in,
but somebody's going, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got good players littered throughout our lineup. We have
a relentless type of game that can wear on teams and we don't want
to lose sight of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Heavens no. Fact is, the Stars are probably good enough to win
the Cup right now. But adding a Recchi or a Graves can only make
them better, especially in the pressure-cooker atmosphere of the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks until the NHL trading deadline. Two weeks to show
Colorado that nobody wants the Cup more than the Stars, not just
this year, but every year.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks to go for the jugular.
</P>
<P>
   That's why I'm glad the Boss of Bosses is in charge.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
