<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0441 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8316 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHILDRENS-INSURANCE05     03-04 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHILDRENS-INSURANCE05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas lawmakers reach compromise in children's health insurance
plan
 &HT;    By Scott S. Greenberger
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ After weeks of political wrangling, Texas
senators on Thursday crafted a health insurance plan that would
cover young children whose families make up to twice the federal
poverty level. But families making the most money would be cut off
_ at least for the first few years of the program _ as soon as
their children turn 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we'd all like to be able to cover every single child
that needs health insurance. But I think we need to be responsible
in how we reach that goal,'' said Sen. Mike Moncrief (D-Fort
Worth), author of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   In a striking example of how levers are pushed and pulled at the
Capitol, the Senate's health insurance compromise may end up
boosting the House prospects of a bill to provide tax relief to the
depressed oil and gas industry. The House Ways and Means Committee
approved that measure late Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Health Insurance Program would use federal and
state money to insure children whose families earn too much to
qualify for Medicaid, the federal-state health care program for the
poor, but can't afford private health insurance.
</P>
<P>
   About 1.4 million Texas children don't have health insurance,
and CHIP has garnered nearly unanimous support. The question has
been whether it should cover children in households making up to
twice the federal poverty level or 150 percent of it. The federal
poverty level for a family of four is $16,450.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 471,000 Texas children would be eligible for CHIP
under the 200 percent threshold. About 220,000 are in families
making between 150 percent and 200 percent of the poverty level.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents of the 150 percent threshold said it would be
fiscally irresponsible to go any higher because future federal CHIP
contributions are uncertain, and nobody knows how many people will
enroll in the program. Supporters of a 200 percent limit said
advocates of the lower level were overestimating the number of
people who would enroll in the program.
</P>
<P>
   The compromise approved by the Senate Health Services Committee
would cover children up to 10 years old whose families make up to
twice the poverty level. But children between 11 and 18 initially
would be covered only if their families make 150 percent or less of
the poverty standard.
</P>
<P>
   After CHIP begins, the Health and Human Services Commission
would take a look at the program's enrollment every six months to
determine whether the state can afford to ratchet up the income
levels for older kids.
</P>
<P>
   Leading advocates of the 200 percent level praised the Senate
action _ but they still plan to push for the higher threshold for
all children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us are not going to agree to anything less than 200
percent,'' said Rep. Kevin Bailey (D-Houston). ``If it delays it
for a short time, we may be able to live with it, but we need to
get the full coverage up to 200 percent of poverty as soon as
possible for all children,'' he said. Bailey said the key for him
will be who decides whether there is enough money to extend the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Elliott Naishtat (D-Austin) took a harder line.
</P>
<P>
   ``To start out excluding any segment of the potentially eligible
population is a step in the wrong direction,'' Naishtat said. The
Mexican-American Caucus also has issued a statement opposing a CHIP
with different income standards for children of different ages.
</P>
<P>
   Some lawmakers said Thursday's compromise may be connected, at
least indirectly, to a bill that would give a $45 million tax break
to the troubled oil and gas industry. The bill would waive
severance taxes due between Feb. 1 and Aug. 31 on crude oil
production from ``stripper'' wells that produce 15 barrels a day or
less, as long as the price of oil has been less than $15 for three
months in a row.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush gave the oil and gas legislation emergency
status, and it has already won Senate approval. But a two-thirds
vote in the House is needed to keep it on a fast-track, and many
House Democrats were troubled by the prospect of taking emergency
action to help the oil industry without providing health insurance
to as many children as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we lead the nation in uninsured children _
that is at least as important an emergency as what the oil industry
is facing,'' Bailey said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush remained noncommital Thursday night about his support for
the CHIP compromise and denied there was any deal. ``There is no
quid pro quo when it comes to CHIP or any other piece of
legislation,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, on Thursday, the Capitol was buzzing with rumors that
House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Rene Oliveira allowed the
bill, which had been bogged down, to be voted out of committee
Wednesday in response to the emerging CHIP compromise. Oliveira
denied a direct link, but he acknowledged that the CHIP agreement
might persuade some of his colleagues to support the oil and gas
bill on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to mix the apples and oranges _ but I know some
members are,'' Oliveira said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
