<HEADER>
A8317 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPO     03-04 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-LEGIS-CAPITOLREPORT05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    House, Senate honor journalist for integrity
 &HT;    By Staff reports
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The House and Senate stopped Thursday to honor
the late Carole Kneeland, a longtime Austin journalist who died
last year of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Kneeland, the wife of Austin American-Statesman columnist Dave
McNeely, was known as an advocate for aggressive reporting and
strict ethics for journalists. She help create ``truth tests'' for
political advertising and clear criteria for determining a public
interest before reporting crime. She died Jan. 26, 1998, at age 49
after fighting her cancer for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although time cannot diminish the tragedy of a rich life cut
prematurely short, neither can it dim the memory of this remarkable
individual,'' the Senate said in a resolution unanimously adopted
Thursday. ``The joy and dedication Carole Kneeland brought to her
life and work will burn on brightly forever in the hearts of all
those fortunate enough to have known her.''
</P>
<P>
   COLONIAS MAY GET OMBUDSMEN
</P>
<P>
   Residents of colonias, which are substandard developments in the
border region, would get some relief under budget recommendations
from the Special Senate Committee on Border Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to the Senate Finance Committee, the panel
recommended approval of Secretary of State Elton Bomer's proposal
to station six ombudsmen along the Texas-Mexico border. The
ombudsmen would help residents of colonias secure modern water and
wastewater services under state and federal programs. Hidalgo,
Cameron, Starr, Maverick, Webb and El Paso counties would each get
one ombudsman. The plan would cost $300,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   The border committee also recommended a $50 million boost in the
state's Housing Trust Fund, which assists low-income families in
the border region and elsewhere around the state. This could create
more than 7,000 new housing units, according to an analysis by the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   The panel stopped short of endorsing a proposal for a five-year,
$2 billion program to build 40,000 units of affordable housing in
the border region. The proposal was announced last week by Daisy
Stiner, executive director of the Texas Department of Housing and
Community Affairs. The committee recommended allocating $750,000
for a feasibility study of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   SALES-TAX HOLIDAY NOT DEAD
</P>
<P>
   Though it's no longer on his list of priorities, Gov. George W.
Bush's office continues to express interest in a so-called
sales-tax holiday.
</P>
<P>
   As he campaigned for re-election last year, Bush said he would
include among his legislative proposals a two-week ``holiday'' from
the sales tax on children's clothing. That proposal was dropped
after Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander projected
lower-than-expected revenue during the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that announcement, Bush budget chief Albert Hawkins
appeared Thursday before the Senate Finance Committee to talk about
a broader sales-tax holiday. That proposal, by Sen. Rodney Ellis,
D-Houston, would eliminate the sales tax from any clothing item
worth $200 or less for nine days in August. Ellis said he would be
open to lowering the no-tax threshold, though he doesn't want it
too low.
</P>
<P>
   Hawkins said the holiday idea still is a valid way to get
consumer sales-tax cuts this year. As written, the sales-tax
holiday would cost the state about $120 million during the next two
years.
</P>
<P>
   NEW WATER DISTRICT IN WORKS
</P>
<P>
   The use of underground water in Bastrop and Lee counties would
be regulated for the first time under legislation introduced
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The measure would create a ground-water conservation district
with powers to require permits and impose fees. Most residential,
agricultural and smaller commercial wells would be exempt.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed Bastrop-Lee County Groundwater Conservation
District could require users to obtain permits before transferring
ground water to other areas. San Antonio has proposed pumping
ground water from that area and piping it across several rivers and
creeks to ease that city's dependence on local supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Details involving permits and fees would be up to the
conservation district's nine-member board, which would be appointed
by local governments and water agencies. The district would not go
into effect unless voters in the two counties approved it.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, House Bill 2237, is sponsored by Rep. Robby Cook,
D-Eagle Lake. An identical version is expected to be filed by Sen.
Ken Armbrister (D-Victoria).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
