<SLUG> BC-UDALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON ELITE GATHER TO HONOR ARIZONA'S MO UDALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress, it seems, never needed Mo Udall more.
</P>
<P>
   About 300 members of Washington's power elite gathered Thursday
to honor the Arizona congressional legend as a man who possessed
qualities now considered more precious than ever before on Capitol
Hill:
</P>
<P>
   Grace, civility and, above all, humor.
</P>
<P>
   With the rancor of President Clinton's impeachment trial still
fresh in their minds, Udall's former House and Senate pals immersed
themselves in memories.
</P>
<P>
   Udall, who died in December, was remembered as the best, and the
funniest, of a bygone era before national politics turned _ in the
words of former Sen. Alan Simpson _ ``mean-spirited, pinched and
driven.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He would not have liked what has happened in these chambers,''
Simpson, R-Wyo., said at the service. His stories of Udall's life,
which included debilitating Parkinson's disease, provoked a blend
of laughter and tears.
</P>
<P>
   The lawmakers gathered in an ornate room in the Cannon House
Office Building, from where the Democrat Udall represented Arizona
for 30 years. His son, Mark, was elected to Congress last year from
Colorado and maintains an office in the same building. So does Mo's
nephew, Tom Udall, who was elected to the House last year from New
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Among the highlights from Thursday's speeches:
</P>
<P>
   _Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., said she marveled at how Udall
could be such a staunch environmentalist coming from a state
``where the trees have turned to rock'' and where the ground is
``covered with kitty litter.'' Udall had been fond of the ``kitty
litter'' analogy himself.
</P>
<P>
   _David Broder of ``The Washington Post'' said residents of New
Hampshire had been in ``culture shock'' when Udall began
campaigning for president in their state because he was ``a crazy,
one-eyed Mormon from St. Johns, Arizona.''
</P>
<P>
   _Brad Udall said that humorist Art Buchwald once delivered some
of Mo's best punch lines right before Mo was supposed to speak. So
Mo told the crowd that he and Buchwald had made a deal to switch
speeches in advance, and that now Mo was left with Buchwald's
inferior address.
</P>
<P>
   _Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., said of Udall, ``Mo knew there were
SOBs in politics, but he knew that you didn't have to be one to
beat one.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark and Tom Udall were joined at the ceremony by a number of
dignitaries, including Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt and his
wife, Hattie, Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, Senate Minority
Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt,
D-Mo., Sen. Edward Kennedy, D-Mass., and Sen. Ben Nighthorse
Campbell, R-Colo.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizonans attending included Republican Sen. John McCain,
former Democratic Sen. Dennis DeConcini, Democratic Rep. Ed Pastor,
Republican Rep. Jim Kolbe, White House aide Fred DuVal, and Mike
Rappoport, a top manager of the Salt River Project utility. Members
of Udall's family in attendance included his wife, Norma, sons
Mark, Brad and Vince, and daughters Anne and Kate.
</P>
<P>
   McCain introduced a Senate resolution declaring Udall ``a model
member of Congress'' and an ``example of bipartisanship.''
</P>
<P>
   A portrait of Udall with a wry smile was placed in front of the
seated lawmakers. It was flanked by an American flag and an Arizona
flag. A U.S. Army chorus sang ``The Impossible Dream.'' Mo Udall
might have joked that the song was a metaphor for his failed 1976
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The service was less somber than a memorial held in Tucson in
January, closer to his death. Mostly, the members of Congress
feasted on Udall's own stories and jokes.
</P>
<P>
   In his time, they said, Udall had what every politician wants:
the ability to engage an audience. It sprang from his wit, his
sincerity, his humor and a sparkle in his one good eye. He lost the
other in a childhood accident. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
