<HEADLINE>
N.H. HOUSE VOTES PERSONAL INCOME TAX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH JIMENEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CONCORD, N.H. _ A cherished New Hampshire symbol trembled
Thursday when the 400-member House of Representatives voted to
enact the state's first personal income tax.
</P>
<P>
   The historic measure, which passed by only four votes, is
intended to address a 1997 court order that rejected the state's
system of funding public schools almost exclusively through local
property taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That order gave the governor and Legislature until April 1 of
this year to find a solution. If they miss the deadline, the school
portion of local property taxes will become uncollectable and
teachers will begin receiving pink slips.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed by a 194-190 margin, would establish a 4
percent personal income tax combined with a $6 per $1,000 valuation
statewide property tax that would mainly hit vacation homes and
commercial property. Primary residences would be exempt from the
new tax _ a change that would drastically lower tax bills for
people now paying as much as $5,000 per year on a $100,000 home.
Existing property taxes for non-school services would remain in
place.
</P>
<P>
   Combined with an increased cigarette tax and other revenues, the
bill would raise some $960 million of the state's $1.3 billion
annual public education budget.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers say passage of the bill by New Hampshire's
new Democratically-controlled Senate is virtually assured.
</P>
<P>
   That means that unless Governor Jeanne Shaheen, a Democrat,
makes good on her standing threat to veto any income tax that is
not approved by statewide referendum, New Hampshire will lose its
status as the only state never to have enacted a broad-based sales
or income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Though some states allow for such a question to be put before
voters, New Hampshire does not, and the state Supreme Court has yet
to issue a requested advisory opinion on whether a referendum would
be constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Shaheen plans to announce a tax plan of her own next week. It
reportedly relies largely on revenues from an expansion of gambling
at the state's four race tracks and an increase in taxes on
business.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement issued shortly after the vote, the governor
reaffirmed her pledge to veto an income tax bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that an income tax is the wrong solution for New
Hampshire and that we can solve this problem without such a tax,''
Shaheen said.
</P>
<P>
   There may be enough votes to override a veto in the Senate, but
there probably are not enough to override it in the House, where
Republicans are the majority.
</P>
<P>
   Passage of the combined 4 percent income tax came despite
Shaheen's threat and a furious anti-tax advertising campaign backed
by some of the state's most influential business executives, its
Republican congressional delegation, and four past Republican
governors.
</P>
<P>
   The ads warned, ``We need not look any further than to our
neighbors in other New England states to see that the result of an
income tax will be an exploding bureaucracy and rapid expansion of
the size and scope of state government.''
</P>
<P>
   If the tax is enacted, it will alter the flow of tax dollars
between New Hampshire and neighboring states. New Hampshire will
gain about $60 million in income tax revenues now paid by residents
who cross the border to work in Massachusetts, according to state
Senator Mark Fernald, one of the bill's sponsors.
</P>
<P>
   In 1990, about 75,000 New Hampshire residents worked in
Massachusetts, and roughly 18,000 Bay Staters worked north of the
border. Judging by congestion on Interstate 93, those figure are
now much higher, according to Tom Duffy, a New Hampshire state
planner.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, Massachusetts levies a 5.95 percent income tax on New
Hampshire residents who work in Massachusetts. If the New Hampshire
tax passes, however, the bottom line for commuters will be the
same: If you live in one state and work in another you pay first to
the state where the income is earned, then pay the difference _ if
one exists _ to your home state.
</P>
<P>
   Ecstatic income tax proponents said the vote marked the death of
the vaunted anti-tax ``pledge'' that all successful gubernatorial
candidates in recent decades have taken.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are making up for 100 years of propaganda around this
place,'' said Senate President Clesson ``Junie'' Blaisdell.
``People know that the way we've done it over the years is wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates said the vote also spotlighted the waning political
power of the state's biggest newspaper, The Union Leader of
Manchester, whose conservative publisher, the late William Loeb,
crafted the pledge.
</P>
<P>
   Blaisdell was not optimistic about the governor's ability to
sell her plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is talking about business in New Hampshire picking up
another couple hundred million dollars in taxes,'' he said. ``That
is going to be a tough sell.''
</P>
<P>
   State Representative Elizabeth Hager, the prime sponsor of the
new tax bill, said its passage in the House also signaled a shift
away from strict conservative domination of the state's Republican
Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has always been a Republican state and it still is but
these people were ready for an income tax,'' Hager said. ``This is
the fairest way to do it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
