A8330 &Cx1f; tic-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMWEST-SPLIT-AZR &LR;      03-04 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMWEST-SPLIT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
3RD UNION LEADER BREAKS RANKS IN AMERICA WEST TALKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ A strike coordinator for America West Airlines' flight
attendants union who resigned this week said Thursday that the
airline made informal offers to come close to matching the union's
$74.5 million contract demands.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Baister is the third union leader to break ranks in the
past three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The union and the company are $5.8 million apart on a contract
and the relatively narrow gap is not enough to justify a strike,
said Baister, who resigned Tuesday in frustration with the
Association of Flight Attendants Council 66 leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a union supporter, but this is an insignificant amount of
money to go out on strike for,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Bunch, chairwoman of the union's negotiating team, and
Taina McDowell were removed Feb. 10 because they supported an offer
the union rejected three times in December, according to union
President Bill McGlashen.
</P>
<P>
   McDowell said Thursday that company negotiators made informal
offers in January that exceeded their official offer of $68.7
million.
</P>
<P>
   She questioned whether a strike, which could begin after March
19, is justified if the two sides are so close.
</P>
<P>
   But confusion remains about the offers and how far apart the two
sides really are, according to Baister, who says she and other
flight attendants are frustrated that they can't get straight
answers from union leaders.
</P>
<P>
   When the union pegged its contract demand at $74.5 million in a
Feb. 24 letter to members, it appeared that there was only $5.8
million separating the two sides, not the $16.5 million figure
McGlashen had been talking about since an impasse was declared in
early February.
</P>
<P>
   America West was encouraged that both sides were within reach of
a settlement, and in a Feb. 27 letter urged the union to work
toward ironing out a deal.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, McGlashen said the union valued the company's offer
at $58 million and the gap remains at $16.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   But Baister and McDowell say the union has said at its meetings
that the company's offer is $68.7 million in new costs over the
five years of the contract. That is in addition to the current
labor costs for flight attendants of $67.6 million annually.
</P>
<P>
   If the gap is $5.8 million, that amounts to just $1.16 million
per year separating the two sides, or an average of about $483 for
each flight attendant. The difference for individual flight
attendants is just $40 per month.
</P>
<P>
   McGlashen said Thursday that regardless of what values the
company and the union place on their offers, the fact remains that
the two sides are $16.5 million apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company never made an offer that got close to ours,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding Baister's resignation, McGlashen said there has been
no ``slippage in solidarity'' among the 2,400 union members as the
strike deadline approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is typical when you're in this countdown,'' he said of
Baister's decision to leave. ``It's stressful and it's tough.
Everyone is wondering if we are going to have a strike.''
</P>
<P>
   America West obviously is hoping it can avoid a walkout, but
would not comment on the resignation of the strike coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to make an agreement that is affordable, fair to
the flight attendants and consistent with and fair with regard to
the arrangements we have with our other employees,'' said Stephen
Johnson, senior vice president of corporate affairs.
</P>
<P>
   No negotiations have been set, but are expected to begin next
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, America West is continuing to try to clarify
the union's offer and reach a settlement. Greg Garger, vice
president for labor relations, sent a letter to McGlashen on
Tuesday seeking clarification of the union's offer. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
