<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8334 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-ANALYZETHIS05-     03-04 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-ANALYZETHIS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Crystal, De Niro held hostage by contrived plot
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ ``Garbo laughs!'' screamed the tagline for
``Ninotchka,'' the 1939 Ernst Lubitsch gem, in which a famously
stiff Greta Garbo tossed back her head and let fly a liberating
guffaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``De Niro cries!'' could sell the diverting but uneven mob
comedy ``Analyze This,'' where Robert De Niro spoofs his indelible
persona by, among other things, bawling.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro plays formidable New York wiseguy Paul Vitti, an
aspiring don with shiny suits and shiny hair. (Right now you're
thinking: De Niro can do this role in his sleep. He can, and he
does.)
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, Paul is seized by panic attacks: can't sleep, can't
perform in bed, can't inspire terror in his rivals. He's short of
breath. He weeps.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro's whimpers are, of course, as unlikely as Garbo's laugh.
It's a sight. His tears are blubbery and overwrought, wrung right
out of vaudeville. They are comic cloudbursts no less hammy than
the Cowardly Lion's in ``The Wizard of Oz.'' Shudder to think.
</P>
<P>
   A contrived happenstance lands De Niro mug-to-mug with uptown
therapist Ben Sobol, played by Billy Crystal, who muffles his usual
impish cutes. If the setup sounds familiar, you might have seen
``The Sopranos,'' the new HBO series that has the head of a mob
family in therapy for anxiety attacks. (Both parties have claimed
ignorance.)
</P>
<P>
   So here's your high concept: What if a guy who's used to getting
his way by physical force finds himself in the painstakingly
cerebral process of psychotherapy, where the shrink gets to ask the
questions? The equation _ polar opposites clash for laughs _ is a
time-honored device that works OK for a stretch, but gasps as
``Analyze This'' reaches an ironic epiphany we saw coming miles
ago.
</P>
<P>
   De Niro soon warms up to this therapy thing and forces the
reluctant Crystal to remain his shrink. Some mild but obvious
laughs spring from their sessions. When Crystal brings up the
Oedipal complex, De Niro impatiently insists, ``English, English.''
There's also plenty to make you squirm. (``If you turn me into a
gay, you're dead!'' Say what?)
</P>
<P>
   De Niro proves a needy client as he struggles to keep a stoic
front for the increasingly suspicious mob. His unorthodox demands
make a shambles of Crystal's middle-class placidity, mangling the
shrink's efforts to marry his fiancee (the exquisitely bubbly Lisa
Kudrow) and eventually landing him in the mafia's cross hairs.
</P>
<P>
   Director Harold Ramis (``Caddyshack'') sustains a snappy pace
and never overplays his parody of the genre. But the script, by
Ramis and two other writers, lacks tang and the crunch of
freshness. The movie ingratiates with slapstick, poop and crotch
jokes _ weak emergency measures when intelligence fails.
</P>
<P>
   And you'd expect more pyrotechnics between De Niro and Crystal.
The dearth of chemistry is a problem of the actors' generosity:
Neither seems willing to abandon his popular repertoire, and the
results bump rather than click.
</P>
<P>
   Save for his acerbic turn in ``Midnight Run,'' De Niro hasn't
had great luck with comedy. He mugs relentlessly and simply
transposes his volatile thug persona into a clownish parody. The
always likable Crystal is held hostage by a passive role that asks
him to react for most of the movie.
</P>
<P>
   As with too much Hollywood product these days, mechanical
writing is the culprit for what could have been an edgy, incisive
comedy. The big machine seems terrified of startling the megaplex
masses with anything brash and fresh. Its idea of audacity is to
toss around the F-word like handfuls of confetti. (Only Samuel L.
Jackson gives the word more poetic punch than De Niro.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This'' amounts to a collection of modest comic bits in
a homogenized whole. Thinking about what it could have been is
enough to make a grown man cry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Analyze This''
</P>
<P>
   2 stars
</P>
<P>
   Starring: Robert De Niro, Billy Crystal, Lisa Kudrow
</P>
<P>
   Director: Harold Ramis
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriters: Peter Tolan, Harold Ramis, Kenneth Lonergan
</P>
<P>
   MPAA rating: R for language, mild violence, sexuality
</P>
<P>
   Running time: 103 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
