<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8335 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-TREASURY-SCANDAL-B     03-04 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-TREASURY-SCANDAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MALONE SAID TO HAVE BLOCKED FIRING OF TREASURY AIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TINA CASSIDY AND FRANK PHILLIPS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Robert E. Foley, a high-ranking treasury official
charged with stealing $2.4 million from a fund under his control,
was slated to be fired last summer for abusive behavior but
then-Treasurer Joseph D. Malone blocked the move, people familiar
with the situation said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Malone told his staff members to work out their
differences with Foley, who had landed his job with the help of
Richard C. Arrighi, a major contributor to the former treasurer's
campaign as well as a Boston attorney who represented Foley in real
estate deals.
</P>
<P>
   Malone denied Thursday that Foley, a former deputy treasurer,
was close to being fired, but confirmed he asked his underlings to
resolve their dispute. He said Arrighi, a fund-raiser he had known
since 1990, never asked him to save Foley's job.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, prosecutors for the first time linked Foley's alleged
scam to John Trischitta, who worked for Foley and was arrested two
weeks ago on charges he helped Martin Robbins, an ``heir finder,''
pilfer $6.5 million from the same account, the Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Attorney General Carol Starkey argued at Foley's
arraignment that he and Trischitta worked together to raid the
fund, where unclaimed state payments are held, over the last five
years. She provided no further details.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, 39, was arrested Wednesday on charges of larceny and
bribery for allegedly siphoning $2.4 million from the account.
Sources said Foley had Trischitta sign large unpaid checks over to
him, funneling the cash through outside companies, including the
Reinke Group Inc., owned by Thomas Ciliberto of Woonsocket, R.I.
</P>
<P>
   Ciliberto, also arrested Wednesday, pleaded not guilty in Boston
Municipal Court and was expected to be released on $10,000 cash
bail or $100,000 surety. Foley was also released on $25,000 cash
bail after pleading not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   The arrests, combined with the disclosure of Arrighi's
relationship with Foley, raises new questions about Malone's
eight-year tenure at the treasury. When the scandal first broke
last month, Malone defended his management and blamed an errant
employee for the problems. But with the involvement of Foley, one
of Malone's five top deputies, he now must face the fact that one
of the worst cases of public corruption in recent state history
took place on his watch.
</P>
<P>
   Foley, who left his job last Friday, had clashed repeatedly with
employees and managers.
</P>
<P>
   Tonia Duchano took over management of the treasury's Abandoned
Property Division, where the unclaimed funds were transferred after
13 months, when treasury officials were unsatisfied with Foley's
controls over the account. She said she continually asked for him
to be fired, and after several meetings with Malone, the treasurer
agreed Foley should be dismissed or transferred to the state
Lottery. But nothing happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right before the primary, I went in to have a meeting with
Joe,'' said Duchano, now in a private sector job. ``I had a blunt
talk with Joe and I said, `I don't understand why Foley's still
here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Malone apolgized, she recalls, and said he thought Duchano and
Foley were getting along.
</P>
<P>
   Malone confirmed her account but denied an unconfirmed report
that Arrighi had spoken with him about keeping Foley.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the best of my knowledge that did not occur,'' Malone said.
``It's an interesting thing. There was clearly a conflict between
Bob (Foley) and Tonia (Duchano) but the people in Bob's department
were very complimentary of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Arrighi, 40, has personally contributed to Malone, giving the
legal maxium of $500 in 1995, 1997, and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A native Rhode Islander, Arrighi was hired as a partner at Burns
&AMP; Levinson last year when the Boston law firm expanded its
commercial and real estate finance practices. He also worked for
Warner &AMP; Stackpole, a firm that handled one-third of the bond deals
under Malone. Foley used Arrighi to set up two real estate trusts
to buy commercial and residential parcels in 1990 and 1991, when he
joined the treasurer's office.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are trying to determine if any of the nearly $9
million stolen from the Unpaid Check Fund since the early 1990s
wound up in those trusts.
</P>
<P>
   Arrighi did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in Malone's office said the issue with Foley was that he
rubbed colleagues the wrong way and refused to take direction from
his superiors. At the time, there was no evidence of his alleged
scheme to steal millions from the state's Unpaid Check Fund.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury officials were also angry that Foley had begun a
relationship with his assistant in the cash management division,
Amelia Tamburrini. Both were recently divorced and plan to marry.
</P>
<P>
   Foley was deputy treasurer in charge of cash management until
new Treasurer Shannon O'Brien replaced him last Friday with her own
appointee.
</P>
<P>
   Foley had been put in charge of making changes in the cash
management division, but refused to carry out any of the plans
Thomas Trimarco, Malone's top aide, and others wanted implemented.
</P>
<P>
   Other Malone staff members confirmed Foley was constantly at
odds with other treasury officials, often acting rudely and failing
to cooperate or take orders from Trimarco. The issue boiled over
last summer while Malone was deeply involved in his bid to win the
Republican gubernatorial nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Sources said Trimarco repeatedly complained to Malone about
Foley and agitated for resolution. Trimarco was not available for
comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Malone, sounding subdued, said he felt as if he had been
``punched in the stomach'' by the emerging scandal.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Stephen Kurkjian and David Armstrong contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
