</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;      
</HEADLINE>
  
 Column: Why HP's Decision to Spin Off Its Measurement Unit
Makes  Sense  By Mark Veverka  
 c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Perhaps Hewlett-Packard should call its proposed offspring ``HP
Classic.''
</P>
<P>
   After all, the test and measurement operation that will be at
the heart of the new independent company is the very business upon
which Mssrs. Hewlett and Packard founded their world-famous
granddaddy of garage startups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they started the company, HP was the leader in the test
and measurement industry,'' says Shekar Gopalan, an industry
analyst for Mountain View consultancy Frost and Sullivan.
</P>
<P>
   And HP Classic _ or whatever _ should still be the lead dog when
it comes to market share. The unit currently controls about 41
percent of the $10 billion (sales) test and measurement market.
Plus, judging by previous performance, it should rake in another
$3.4 billion or so in sales from three other solid business
segments: medical instruments, electronic components and chemical
analysis.
</P>
<P>
   HP Classic ``has everything to gain from the spin-off,'' says
Gopalan, an unabashed fan of HP's decision to split the T&AMP;M
business from the company's more dominant computer and printer
segment. While sputtering, HP's sexier information technology
operations account for about $40 billion in annual sales.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, by getting out from under the formidable shadow of the
colossal computer biz, ``the new measurement company is likely to
be more focused and will thrive like an entrepreneurial startup,''
Gopalan predicts.
</P>
<P>
   And that is exactly what corporate divestitures are supposed to
do. The breakup of Sears, Roebuck is a prime example.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, after nearly a decade of lackluster stock
performance, Sears abandoned its ``socks to stocks'' strategy by
spinning off Dean Witter, Discover, Allstate, Coldwell Banker and
its commercial development company.
</P>
<P>
   The old Sears was so unwieldy that few investors were aware that
the merchant owned half of Prodigy, the online service, in a joint
venture with IBM.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of STREET05 (91318 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  For years, the mismanagement of Sears' underperforming core
retail business was camouflaged by the success of the other
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Once it was stripped to the bare retailer, investors could more
clearly monitor how it was performing _ for better or worse. And
the other companies, in turn, fetched higher values after being cut
loose.
</P>
<P>
   The same should hold true for HP. Earlier this week, the company
announced its plan to split itself into two parts. The announcement
thus far has drawn a lukewarm response from investors. HP stock
closed on Tuesday, the day of the announcement, at $68.63, up
$2.75. But yesterday, while the Dow soared 191.52, HP stock fell
$1.38 to $67.44.
</P>
<P>
   In Wall Street parlance, the corporate restructuring is actually
more of ``carve out'' than a ``spin-off.'' A spin-off is when a
company decides to sell a division or a business unit by offering a
majority stake to the public in an initial offering.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, HP plans to offer a minority stake of HP Classic
to the public in September or October at a still undetermined
price. In other words, HP is carving out 15 percent of its $7.4
billion noncomputer business.
</P>
<P>
   After those shares begin to trade, the stock market will
determine HP Classic's value. For example, if the IPO price is $15
a share and the shares fetch, say, $30 on the open market, bankers
will multiply $30 times the total number of HP Classic shares to
calculate the market value of HP Classic. (The new company's IPO
will offer only 15 percent of its total shares because the federal
government requires that these types of transactions keep initial
stakes below 20 percent in order to get tax-free status.)
</P>
<P>
   After HP Classic's value is established, investment bankers can
then determine how many HP Classic shares should be given to
Hewlett-Packard stockholders, who still own the remaining 85
percent of the newly created company.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 2 of STREET05 (91318 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR;  Once that step is taken, Hewlett-Packard will distribute the HP
Classic shares, and the test and measurement business finally
becomes an independent company.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, and usually in practice, the stock market should
value HP Classic and Hewlett-Packard shares at a combined price
that is greater than what HP fetched before the split.
</P>
<P>
   Why?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, shareholders usually expect the separated
companies to perform better. For another, investors can focus on
the parts of the business that they really want to own, explains
Dresdner RCM Managing Director Walter Price Jr., a portfolio
manager of the firm's global technology mutual fund.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, as Hewlett-Packard became a global computing giant,
investors wanted to see consistent growth comparable to Dell or
IBM, when those stocks were humming. So, when the test business
reported (like it had from time to time) that the Asian flu was
going to cause a shortfall in earnings for the sector, shareholders
betting on computer growth weren't willing to ride out the T&AMP;M
storm, Price explains.
</P>
<P>
   Once the company completes its divestiture a year or so from
now, Hewlett-Packard should be a purer play on personal computers
and printers. Likewise, HP Classic should act more like its test
and measurement brethren.
</P>
<P>
   ``It attracts a different kind of investor,'' Price says.
</P>
<P>
   And it might even attract a decent return.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Street Smarts runs every Tuesday, Wednesday and Friday. Mark
Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San Francisco,
Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(AT SIGN)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2150EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
