<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0454 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8337 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTEL-SFCHRON &LR;      03-04 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Intel Plans To Acquire Level One  &HT;       
 By Dan Fost 
 &HT;     c. 1999 San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
Intel Corp. said yesterday it will buy Sacramento-based Level One
Communications for $2.2 billion in the biggest acquisition in its
31-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Level One makes chips for computer-networking equipment and will
give the Santa Clara chip giant another foothold in this
fast-growing market.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our strategy is to be a major building-block supplier in all
aspects of this networking business,'' Intel chief executive Craig
Barrett said during a conference call. Right now, sluggish
computer-networking components are creating bottlenecks that
prevent computer chips from working as fast as they can. Intel
believes this is slowing sales of its core microprocessors.
</P>
<P>
   Intel hopes that if it becomes a major player in the
networking-chip business, it can help solve the bottleneck and also
prod others to work on it.
</P>
<P>
   Intel ``needs to invest in anything that might drive greater
microprocessor sales,'' said Drew Peck, an analyst with S.G. Cowen
and Co. in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Intel recorded sales of $26 billion last year, but its earnings
actually fell 13 percent to $6.1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Intel chips run 80 percent of the personal computers sold in the
United States today. With signs that PC sales might be slowing, and
with Advanced Micro Devices giving Intel vigorous competition in PC
chips, Intel is looking beyond the computer, into chips for
telephones and corporate networks.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, growth was driven by the PC industry, but it's
clear that the telecommunications industry is going to drive the
semiconductor industry for the next decade,'' said Arun Veerappan,
an analyst with BancBoston Robertson Stephens.
</P>
<P>
   Level One, founded in 1985, employs 800 people and had 1998
revenues of $263 million. No layoffs are planned, and Level One
chief executive Robert Pepper will become an Intel vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Level One has been ``the Rodney Dangerfield of chip companies,''
said Kenneth Pearlman, an analyst with CIBC Oppenheimer. ``They've
been blowing the doors off their business,'' growing 68 percent
last year and 40 percent in 1997, but the company's stock price has
not reflected that success, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the stock swap, Intel will exchange 0.43 share of its stock
for every one of Level One's shares, essentially valuing Level One
at $48.75 per share.
</P>
<P>
   That's an 80 percent premium over Level One's closing price
yesterday of $27.13.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was announced after the market closed. Intel stock
closed at $113.38, down $1.31.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Intel closed a $185 million deal, announced in
October, to buy a Massachusetts networking company, Shiva Corp.
Earlier this year, Intel announced a joint venture with Analog
Devices Inc. to make chips for handheld computers.
</P>
<P>
   Peck, the S.G. Cowen analyst, said Intel has made hundreds of
investments in small companies to try to spur innovation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
