<HEADLINE>
MERRILL LYNCH GOES INTERNET, ALLOWS SOME CUSTOMERS TO BYPASS
BROKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Please note that the word STAR in parentheses has been used
in the 12th graf instead of the symbol, which is non-transmittable
to some newspaper systems.) 
(rk) 
 By JOSEPH KAHN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., the country's largest brokerage
house, dipped its toes into Internet stock trading Thursday night.
Now, it has to show it can swim.
</P>
<P>
   In the evening hours, Merrill's technicians switched on the
firm's long-awaited Internet trading option for a select group of
customers, allowing them for the first time to buy and sell listed
stocks without calling one of the firm's 15,000 brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill will soon give those clients the ability to invest in
mutual funds and to buy certificates of deposit as well as stocks.
And if the early foray goes well, Merrill plans to soon extend
online stock trading to more clients, including those who pay full
commissions to trade with Merrill, senior executives there said.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's Internet offering is too limited _ and the fees
Merrill charges for its services too high _ to offer immediate
competition to the Internet stock brokerages that have begun luring
clients away from the established Wall Street firms. But Merrill's
main task is not to lure low-end customers away from online
brokerage firms, but to keep its own eight million clients, and
their $1.4 trillion in assets, on board.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to combine the advice from its full-service broker
with all-hours stock trading for clients who want to do it
themselves. Analysts are skeptical that the offering will quash the
anti-Internet image that has dogged Merrill recently, but Merrill
argues that it is changing perceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to be the premier destination portal for financial
information and services,'' said John ``Launny'' Steffens, the vice
chairman in charge of the firm's brokerage force. ``But we also
offer the wisdom of a human being, and that's a winning strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Some investors seem to agree. Word of the foray into online
trading combined with two recent upgrades on Merrill stock by Wall
Street analysts to give the firm's stock a big lift Thursday.
Merrill rose $6.6875 a share, or 8.6 percent, to $84.375, and
volume was double the daily average.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill's stock had been under a dark cloud for months, in part
because it has been seen as doing less than other firms, including
leading competitors like Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, to come to
grips with how the Internet is changing financial services.
Steffens, himself a former retail broker, contributed to that
impression when he frowned on Internet stock trading in a speech
last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The do-it-yourself model of investing, centered on Internet
trading, should be regarded as a serious threat to American
financial lives,'' he said then.
</P>
<P>
   Steffens says now that he intended to warn people against
hyperactive day trading, a caution that he says proved prescient
given the recent rise in concern from government regulators and
evidence that rapid turnover in stock portfolios can lead some
investors to financial ruin. What he did not mean, he said, was to
disparage the use of the Internet to trade stocks per se.
</P>
<P>
   But the original comments, and the subsequent clarification,
show the problem Merrill faces.
</P>
<P>
   It risks undermining its own network of brokers, who still make
most of their money from commissions linked to stock trading, by
rushing to offer services that compete with online rivals Charles
Schwab, E(STAR)Trade and others.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill also faces the reality that the Internet caters not
only to trigger-happy day traders, but also to wealthy clients who
want to do at least some of their own stock trading for a fraction
of what Merrill charges for the same service.
</P>
<P>
   The market isn't waiting for Merrill to resolve the issue, says
Bill Doyle, director of online financial services for Forrester
Research. His company just surveyed nearly 100,000 people in North
America to learn more about their investing habits.
</P>
<P>
   Of the wealthiest segment of that group _ people with $750,000
or more in assets _ one in 10 already had begun trading stocks
through online brokerage houses, and a quarter of that number keep
most of their assets in online brokerage accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is serious money that's moving online,'' Doyle said.
``That's a big part of Merrill's decision. They can't stand back
any longer while assets are moving over.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   The question confronting Merrill and every other Wall Street
brokerage firm is to what extent they are willing to sacrifice
retail stock trading commissions to make a bigger splash online.
Merrill's early online trading move does not address that issue.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill has so far limited online trading to customers who have
at least $100,000 in assets with the firm and who choose to pay an
annual fee for managing their money, a fee that includes the cost
of trading stock for their accounts. Only 55,000 customer accounts
are in that category.
</P>
<P>
   But Steffens said that if early tests went well, Merrill would
extend the online service to more of its customers. He said a
decision on how much to expand the service would come soon,
possibly in a few months.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this goes well, we will be inclined to expand,'' he said.
``We could extend the offering across our customer accounts, and
quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Merrill brokers _ the firm calls them financial consultants _
are wary of the Internet because it could threaten their
livelihoods, Merrill executives acknowledge. But Steffens said
Merrill had long since grown past the point where commissions make
up a large percentage of its revenues _ they represented about 11
percent of its $17.5 billion in revenue last year _ and he said the
firm was prepared to compete on prices if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there going to be more pressure on prices? Yes,'' Steffens
said. ``Is there going to be more pressure on our sales force to
add more value? Double yes. But we are as convinced as ever that we
can help people and add significant value.''
</P>
<P>
   Cushioning the transition are signs that Merrill's retail
brokerage operation, while almost certainly facing some defections
to online rivals, is hardly bleeding. Quite the contrary, its
commission revenue is still growing. So is the number of accounts,
which rose by 40 percent last year and at a 30 percent annual rate
in the first two months of this year, during a boom in online
trading, Steffens said.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, Merrill's ability to compete with cut-rate, online
brokers will depend on how much investors are willing to pay for
investing services other than trading. That includes the advice
brokers give their clients and the stock research Merrill
investment bankers produce.
</P>
<P>
   Merrill recently extended, until the end of this month, a trial
in which it provides its stock research free online. The program
has been a success, people at the firm said, because it generated
130,000 new leads for Merrill brokers _ customers seen as
candidates to invest their money with Merrill. But the free
research also reiterates a persistent Internet theme: customers
often expect something for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   But free research and the introduction of online trading at
least put Merrill firmly in the camp of full-service firms ready to
do battle on the Internet, says Steve Franco, an analyst with Piper
Jaffray Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have legitimized the channel after being very vocal
against it,'' Franco said. ``Longer term, they have to demonstrate
they can do as well there as they did in the old world.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
