<HEADER>
A8340 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCI-IMMORTAL-CELLS-2T     03-04 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-IMMORTAL-CELLS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENE STUDY BOLSTERS HOPE FOR TREATING DISEASES OF AGING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By NICHOLAS WADE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A gene that confers fountain-of-youth properties on human cells
grown in laboratory glassware has been tested in mice to see if its
absence will cause the opposite effect, that of premature aging.
The answer _ which is partly yes _ sustains but does not yet
fulfill the hope that manipulations of the gene will provide
treatments for cancer, heart disease and other maladies of aging
human tissues.
</P>
<P>
   Geron, the company that owns patents on the gene, said the new
result, reported in Friday's issue of Cell, bolstered its hopes for
deriving treatments from the gene. Other experts said the
experiment, although a well executed and necessary step toward
unraveling the mysteries of aging, was hard to interpret because of
the complexity of the subject and the early stage of research on
the gene.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to create a great stir,'' Dr. Leonard Guarente, an
expert on aging at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, said
of the experiment, noting that the altered mice grew gray hair but
did not show many other symptoms of human aging. ``It mirrors aging
in part, but not in whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The gene is one that makes the critical component of an enzyme
called telomerase.
</P>
<P>
   Research into the cellular basis of aging, long an intractable
field, was rejuvenated in January of last year when biologists
reported that human cells whose telomerase had been activated by
inserting extra copies of the gene kept dividing well beyond the
usual point _ some 50 divisions or so _ at which cells normally
stop dividing and die.
</P>
<P>
   Biologists refer to the cells as ``immortalized,'' because they
seem capable of dividing indefinitely while maintaining their
youthful appearance. In a progress report in December, the altered
cells were said to be still flourishing, with no sign of cancerous
growth.
</P>
<P>
   The reason telomerase has this effect in human cells is clear
enough. The chromosomes _ the units in which the cell's genetic
material is packaged _ are protected at either end with long
stretches of repetitive DNA called telomeres. Each time a normal
cell divides, the telomeres get shorter, as if marking off the
permissible number of divisions; when the telomeres reach a
critical minimum length, the cell starts to die.
</P>
<P>
   Though all cells possess the genes to make telomerase, the
enzyme that rebuilds shortened telomeres, in most cells the
critical telomerase gene is permanently switched off. This gene is
one that makes the template for the repeated DNA units of which
telomeres are composed.
</P>
<P>
   Only in egg and sperm cells, in special regenerative cells
called stem cells, and in cancer cells is the telomerase template
gene active.
</P>
<P>
   Immortalizing human cells is certainly an interesting feat, but
what does that mean for people? Does the shortening of the
telomeres with age, in fact, have anything to do with the aging of
the body as a whole?
</P>
<P>
   The experiment being reported Friday is the first effort to
answer the question as it applies to a whole organism, in this
case, mice. Dr. Ronald A. DePinho of the Dana-Farber Cancer
Institute in Boston, along with colleagues there and at other
institutions, has worked with mice in which the critical telomerase
gene has been deleted from the genome.
</P>
<P>
   Mice, as it happens, have very long telomeres, and the first two
generations of mice that lacked the telomerase template gene were
unaffected by its lack.
</P>
<P>
   DePinho and his colleagues have now bred third- to
sixth-generation mice, with progressively shorter telomeres, and in
these mice, especially as they age, short telomeres are a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The third-generation mice developed gray hair, male pattern
baldness and erosive skin lesions considerably more often than
normal mice of the same age. The sixth generation mice that lacked
telomerase displayed these symptoms at an earlier age, going gray
at the age of 3 months.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the hearts, livers and kidneys of the mice
were normal, and they did not develop thinning of the bones or
cataracts.
</P>
<P>
   As to life span, the first to fifth generation mice that lacked
telomerase lived as long as normal mice, 50 percent of them living
for 24 months. Only in the sixth generation mice, with critically
short telomeres, was life span affected; half of these mice were
dead at 18 months.
</P>
<P>
   An obvious pattern in these results is that the tissues that
demand a steady proliferation of cells _ like skin and hair _ or
that need to regenerate under stresses _ like a wound healing _ are
the ones that are jeopardized by short telomeres.
</P>
<P>
   A second important finding is that the mice with short telomeres
have a higher incidence of cancer, suggesting that short telomeres
can destabilize the cell and initiate tumors.
</P>
<P>
   The question now is what relevance do these findings have to
aging and cancer in humans. On this point there is a wide range of
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Calvin B. Harley, Geron's chief scientific officer, said the
DePinho article was ``very exciting from our perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It provides strong support,'' Harley continued, ``for what
we've been saying all along for the promise of telomerase in
treating aging and cancer.''
</P>
<P>
   Geron, which has financed several advances in the telomere
field, but not DePinho's present work, hopes to add the telomerase
gene to the cells of human tissues that have lost the capacity to
proliferate.
</P>
<P>
   Harley said the finding that short telomeres increase the risk
of cancer was ``a major new piece of data that may explain why the
frequency of cancer goes up in old age.''
</P>
<P>
   Other experts are not ready to concede that the relevance of the
mouse results to human aging or cancer had been proved.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Robert Weinberg, a cancer expert at the Whitehead Institute
in Boston, said the new report was ``very interesting'' and
``validated the notion that telomere integrity is essential for
cellular proliferation.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of proliferative capacity in telomere-deficient mice
could be the same process that occurs when human T-cells are
depleted in AIDS, but that and any other relation to human aging
remains to be proved, in Weinberg's view.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth,'' Weinberg said, ``is, I don't know how many other
aspects of human aging are or are not connected the telomere
shortening.''
</P>
<P>
   Guarente also said it was too early to say whether the
telomere-deficient mice are an accurate model for some or any of
the aging processes seen in humans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an extremely interesting study with possible relevance
to human aging,'' Guarente said, ``but we'll need a lot more
information before we can be certain of that relevance.''
</P>
<P>
   DePinho is also cautious about interpreting his findings, saying
telomere attrition is one component of aging, which, along with
other factors, affects the ability of an organism to withstand
acute stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``From these studies,'' he said, ``we've learned that if you can
maintain telomere function you are better able to maintain overall
fitness, so I think that is very good news. But we aren't going to
be erecting any Ponce de Leon fountains around Geron. It won't
reverse organismal aging as we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   A difficulty in extending the findings from mice to people is
that mice evidently use the telomere system in a somewhat different
way. Mice have very long telomeres and presumably the mice that die
a natural death die from causes other than telomere shortening _
like oxidative damage, accumulating genetic errors and the other
kinds of wear and tear that probably play a role in human aging
too.
</P>
<P>
   With humans, telomeres are set much shorter, perhaps because
cancer is a far more serious danger for a long lived species. Human
telomeres are short enough that a proliferating tumor cell will run
out of telomeres before it gets to any significant size. Advanced
tumors must subvert this last ditch defense by activating
telomerase.
</P>
<P>
   But has evolution, in selecting the ideal limit for human
telomeres, had to make a trade-off between cancer prevention and
life span? In other words, do short telomeres ever limit human life
span by causing failure in aging tissues?
</P>
<P>
   Geron scientists and other experts believe human cells in the
aged do get critically short of telomeres, particularly when high
demands are put on the proliferative capacity of skin or
blood-forming cells.
</P>
<P>
   But biologists like Weinberg argue that no one has yet been
shown to have died of short telomeres, and that Geron's proposal to
activate telomerase in aging tissues could remove an important
defense against cancer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
