u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-RELIEF-NYT &LR;      03-04 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-RELIEF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET POLITICS IS DELAYING RELIEF FOR CENTRAL AMERICA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Alaska, Texas, S.D., N.D., Ill., Iowa)  (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Nearly $1 billion in emergency aid to
storm-stricken Central Americans ran afoul of partisan budget
politics in the House and Senate Thursday, dooming any chance that
President Clinton could deliver the relief package when he visits
the region next week.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans in both houses were willing to approve the aid, but
only on conditions the president would find unacceptable _ cutting
an equal amount from programs like food stamps and welfare
assistance. The House Republicans disregarded pleas from their new
speaker that they go along with Clinton's plans without causing
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems that the Republican majority is looking more to play
politics with some of the issues than in providing the very needed
aid,'' said the White House spokesman, Joe Lockhart, who denounced
the proposed cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Appropriations Committee unanimously approved $1.9
billion in new spending, which included $956 million to help
countries like Honduras and Nicaragua rebuild after they were
devastated by storms last fall. It also contained $100 million in
aid to Jordan and $285 million in assistance for U.S. farmers and
ranchers hurt by the economic turmoil in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Ted Stevens, R-Alaska, who heads the Appropriations
Committee, said the offsetting cuts came from programs that
received extra money last fall, which would not all be spent this
year. But he acknowledged that the cuts were politically sensitive
and might not survive a White House veto or negotiations with the
House.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens and the Republican leadership are under strong pressure
from fiscal conservatives to stay under the self-imposed spending
caps, and not skirt the restrictions by giving the spending
emergency status as Congress often does in providing aid for
natural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   In another jab at the administration, the committee approved by
voice vote an amendment from Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, that
would bar the federal government from recouping any settlement
proceeds the states have negotiated with the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The White House's five-year budget projections assume that the
federal government would receive $18.9 billion from the tobacco
settlements. Despite Thursday's vote, the committee was sharply
divided, foreshadowing a fierce floor battle.
</P>
<P>
   Across the Capitol, a meeting of the House Appropriations
Committee was canceled Thursday after Speaker Dennis Hastert of
Illinois, also under pressure from budget hawks as well as top
lieutenants like Tom DeLay and Dick Armey, both of Texas, ordered
the panel to find offsetting cuts in its budget to pay for the
Central American aid.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay and Armey, taken aback by the Senate seizing the
traditional House role of demanding fiscal responsibility, also
expressed anger that the government was willing to send millions to
storm victims in Latin America and the Caribbean, but shortchange
U.S. farmers.
</P>
<P>
   The House action dealt a setback to Hastert, who expected to
benefit along with Clinton from quick action on the emergency
foreign assistance. Hastert had not originally sought offsetting
cuts for that aid, although lawmakers had done so for the
assistance to Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The simple fact is, a lot of our members want to be fiscally
responsible,'' said John Feehery, Hastert's spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The about-face illustrates the problems Republicans face as they
run into self-imposed budget restraints despite large projected
surpluses. It also shows the challenges Hastert confronts in
dealing with a six-vote House majority and rumblings that DeLay,
the minority whip, is calling the shots.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats seized on the Republicans' decisions to portray a
Republican Party insensitive to the needs of the poor in this
country and abroad.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find it puzzling that the offsets suggested by some of our
Republican colleagues would cut food stamps and welfare assistance
for the needy in this country to pay for assistance for the needy
in Honduras,'' said Sen. Tom Daschle of South Dakota, the
Democratic leader.
</P>
<P>
   But all of the committee Democrats voted for the bill, accepting
Stevens' explanation, as did Tom Harkin of Iowa, or vowing to fight
the cuts on the Senate floor or in House-Senate conference
committee, as did Byron Dorgan of North Dakota. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The proposed cuts from the current budget include $262 million
in food stamps, and $70 million in climate change and international
environmental programs. The bill also included $80 million to
provide new detention centers for Central American immigrants
fleeing their storm-ravaged countries. To pay for most of this, the
committee cut $65 million from border enforcement naturalization
programs.
</P>
<P>
   To win Democratic support, Stevens added $130 million in
agricultural aid to the original bill, and created a new program
for the steel industry that would guarantee up to $1 billion in
emergency loans.
</P>
</TEXT>
