<HEADER>
A8344 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-ANSWERS05-     03-04 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-ANSWERS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves face question marks
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lake Buena Vista, Fla. _ Underneath the usual laid-back,
games-don't-count exterior, there are several forces driving the
Atlanta Braves during this exhibition season.
</P>
<P>
   While spring training is mostly about getting in shape and ready
for the season, there are some important questions facing the
Braves as they move closer to Opening Day on April 5.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves open their Grapefruit League season today in
Kissimmee, Fla., where they'll play the Houston Astros at 1 p.m.
It's fitting that Atlanta will open with rookie Bruce Chen on the
mound, who is one of the three big question marks of this camp.
</P>
<P>
   Will Chen have a good camp, giving the Braves confidence that he
can be the No. 5 guy in the rotation? How will Ryan Klesko fare at
first base? And thirdly, how will the new hitters like Bret Boone,
Brian Jordan and Otis Nixon blend into this lineup?
</P>
<P>
   For this 31-game mini-season, starting with the Astros and
ending with the Indians at Turner Field on April 3, the answers
will come into focus, as will others like Mark Wohlers' comeback
bid, and which minor league players will eventually help this team.
</P>
<P>
   First and foremost is seeing how Ryan Klesko does at first base.
He's been taking ground balls there for two weeks, getting in extra
defensive work with bench coach Bobby Dews, and reports success.
The Braves will gauge his progress before deciding their next, if
any, move.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting coach Don Baylor's emphasis with Klesko so far has been
on hitting left-handed pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to get used to seeing lefties again,'' said
Klesko, who only occasionally faced left-handers in the past
several years. ``Knowing what to look for.''
</P>
<P>
   Chen, meanwhile, has been ready for today's start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just like the fact that I'm going to be pitching and it's
going to be soon,'' Chen said. ``It should be fun. You've been
working out the whole offseason, you want to see how you've
progressed.''
</P>
<P>
   This time last year Chen was in the habit of leaving pitches up
in the strike zone, something he could get away with in the minor
leagues. As a result, he surrendered four home runs in 10 2/3
innings last spring.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered he still had the same tendencies when he returned
to Atlanta last September, but he's spent the offseason working on
getting the ball down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched Greg Maddux, Tom Glavine and Denny Neagle throw down
to the knees every pitch,'' Chen said. ``If you're going to miss,
you have to miss low. My average pitch was four or five inches
higher than their average pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the number of eyes on him this spring, Chen said he won't
mind it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always going to be people watching,'' he said. ``That
doesn't bother me. I'm not playing for them. I'm playing for myself
and for the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bobby Cox plans to experiment with his lineup, given the
new additions to the team and the loss of Andres Galarraga.
Newcomer Otis Nixon is a primarily a leadoff man and Brian Jordan
is the logical choice to hit clean up, which leaves Boone as the
only wild card.
</P>
<P>
   Boone hit second on Thursday against Georgia Tech but could end
up hitting sixth, seventh or eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this lineup everybody's so good,'' Boone said. ``Coming off
a year when I drove in almost 100 runs, I can't hit third or
fourth, which is good. If I hit seventh, whatever ... Where you hit
in the lineup whether it's second, third, fourth, fifth or sixth,
in certain situations you've got a job to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Boone, who's been traded twice in his career _ from Seattle to
Cincinnati and from the Reds to Atlanta _ said he's had no trouble
getting used to his new team.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always an adjustment period you go through getting
used to the guys, but it's been easy,'' Boone said. ``There are so
many great players on this team. They all seem to be nice guys.
They go about their business.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting used to each other on the field will come naturally,
Boone figures. Boone figures preseason numbers are not important,
but he'd like to have a good spring anyway.
</P>
<P>
   ``You always want to do well, it doesn't matter whether it's
whiffle ball or a practice game,'' Boone said. ``You want to get
your swing ready, get your legs ready defensively and hit the ball
hard. If you do that, you can have a good feeling going into the
season.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside of these questions, it's business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to get everybody in shape, pick the best 25 and
get out of here healthy,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
