<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two Bautista HRs in 15-5 opening win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. _ The Braves started their spring
training season with an offensive exhibition, putting up 15 runs on
Georgia Tech. That's the most the Braves have ever scored in
winning all nine spring games with the Yellow Jackets.
</P>
<P>
   The main attraction was Danny Bautista, who hit a pair of home
runs, one to straight-away center field and another that bounced
off the scoreboard in left center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you guys he's been swinging the bat better than anybody
against our live pitching,'' manager Bobby Cox said after the
Braves' 15-5 win. ``He's been the hitting star of the early camp.
He's been popping the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not Bautista's hottest start, though. He said he also
hit two runs to open spring training when he was playing for the
Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's all you can have when you really work,'' said Bautista,
who is aiming for a roster spot as a bench player. ``I saw the ball
good today. What I was doing in the batting cages I tried to bring
to the game.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves combined for 14 hits, three home runs, and two
doubles. Twenty different Braves got at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally we don't score much (this early),'' Cox said. ``Just
one of those days, you know. Glad to see it.''
</P>
<P>
   HUNTER ADAPTING
</P>
<P>
   Brian Hunter, who celebrated his 31st birthday on Thursday, got
his first action as a Brave since 1993 after signing two weeks ago
to back up Ryan Klesko at first base. Hunter went 0-for-2, scored a
run and showed the versatility that could help him make the team,
substituting in left field.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter, who was 7-for-29 (.241) as a pinch hitter last year for
St. Louis, knows that will be his role as a Brave.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something I like to do, but I can do it,'' said
Hunter, who got some tips last year from Willie McGee, who's been
primarily a pinch hitter for the last three seasons. ``Willie
taught me how to get prepared. The worst thing you can do is be
surprised (when you're called upon).''
</P>
<P>
   WEISS BACK
</P>
<P>
   After being in bed for two days with strep throat, shortstop
Walt Weiss was back in the clubhouse reporting much better health
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``My throat has never felt like that before,'' Weiss said. ``I
still feel a little bit light-headed but I'm fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Weiss apparently caught it from his 4-year-old son Brody, who
had a serious bout with E. coli last summer that has left his
immune system weakened.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss did not play in the game against Tech but did participate
in the morning's cutoff drills.
</P>
<P>
   GOOD NEWS FOR HELMS
</P>
<P>
   An MRI revealed minor league third baseman Wes Helms did not
have any tears in the rotator cuff of his throwing shoulder, which
has been giving him problems lately. ``It showed no tear, and
that's the important thing,'' trainer Dave Pursley said. Helms will
take at least three or four days off, and treat the shoulder with
anti-inflammatory medicine.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
