<SLUG> BC-BKW-BSKYPAD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE TOURNEY FITS CSUN'S BUDGET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ While Cal State Northridge would have been
financially unable to host the Big Sky Conference men's basketball
tournament, there was no problem in hosting the women's tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our responsibility to host the tournament and do it
right,'' interim athletic director Sam Jankovich said. ``We're
hoping the community gets behind it and we break even. This
community has the responsibility to come out and support that.''
</P>
<P>
   The reason Northridge can host the women's tourney, which began
Thursday night, is it costs less money to run it. Whereas the men's
contest costs the host institution $160,000, Northridge needs only
to spend about $12,000 for the women.
</P>
<P>
   The men's tournament host has to pay for the airfare, hotel
accommodations and per diem money of all six participants, plus the
officials. Northridge only has to take care of the officials, plus
any promotions it cares to arrange.
</P>
<P>
   The department is dipping into its $90,000 postseason budget to
pay for the tournament, said Grace Collins, the school's associate
athletic director/business.
</P>
<P>
   CSUN can make money on the tournament through ticket sales,
concession sales and corporate sponsors, but no one in the athletic
department expects a profit. Northridge finished last in the
conference in attendance, plus it's a long way for most of the
schools to come. Each participating school received 200 tickets;
only Portland State didn't return all 200. PSU returned 100,
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason for the returns, she said, was the schools were
confident tickets would be available for anyone making the trip.
Montana and Northern Arizona expected about 50 supporters each,
Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Logistics: With a capacity of 1,600, Northridge plays in the
smallest building in the conference. The next smallest is Portland
State, at 1,775, but if PSU were to host the tournament, it could
move into the 12,884-seat Memorial Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   A small building means difficulty in televising Saturday's
tournament final, which Fox Sports will do. Sports information
director Ryan Finney said Fox will bring five cameras, one of which
gives a diagonal view of the basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have room for it,'' Finney said. ``We'll probably
move it to a hand-held camera at center court.''
</P>
<P>
   The other four cameras will be in place: one above center court,
one above the baseline and one each behind the baskets.
</P>
<P>
   __ TV or not TV: What if they gave a final and no one saw it? If
Northridge reaches Saturday's final, it will be televised live on
Fox Sports Northwest at 5:05 p.m. Matador fans will have to wait
until 10 p.m. Saturday to see Fox Sports West 2's tape-delay
airing.
</P>
<P>
   __ Did you know?: The women's tournament has been held in the
state of Montana all but twice since its inception 11 seasons ago _
this year and 1992 in Boise, Idaho. . . . The conference champion
earns an automatic berth in the NCAA Tournament _ and likely a
14th, 15th or 16th seed. The conference is ranked 21st out of 26
conferences in winning percentage against the other conferences and
in strength of schedule. The team with the strongest schedule is
Weber State, at 179. Northridge is ranked 254.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
