<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOW UP 191.52 AS IBM LEADS THE CHARGE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After weeks of sour news on technology stocks, the
sector received a boost Thursday when IBM announced that it had won
a $16 billion order from Dell Computer for parts like disk drives
and displays.
</P>
<P>
   That news gave the broader market a lift after more than a week
of a general slide. But despite the 2 percent jump in the Dow Jones
industrial average and the 1.5 percent surge in the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, the market is still locked in the trading
range it has been in since January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are stuck in a trading range because we had prices get well
ahead of earnings,'' said Douglas R. Cliggott, U.S. equity
strategist at J.P. Morgan Securities. ``Values are stretched so far
it will be difficult for the market to make any headway unless
interest rates go down.''
</P>
<P>
   So far this year, long-term interest rates have jumped more than
half a percentage point despite the lowest inflation, according to
some measures, in more than 40 years. The reason for the rise has
been the refusal of the economy to slow down and the growing
concern among investors that the Federal Reserve will have to raise
rates to rein in growth.
</P>
<P>
   With Friday's jobs report for February, investors will get a new
indication of how strong the economy still is and, in turn, a
signal on whether interest rates will keep rising. The consensus
estimate for nonfarm payroll job growth is 245,000.
</P>
<P>
   If the jobs report is stronger than expected, that will probably
send interest rates higher. That should put more pressure on stocks
because higher rates make their valuations more expensive. But
investors, at least for a day, may decide that stronger economic
growth will produce enough of a pop in earnings to overcome this
drag.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow rose 191.52 points, to 9,467.40. It is 176 points below
the record it hit in January and is up only 1.4 percent since last
July, when last year's sell-off began. The S&AMP;P 500 climbed 18.94
points, to 1,246.64, while the Nasdaq composite index rose 27.69
points, or 1.22 percent, to 2,292.89. The Russell index of
smaller-company stocks finished up 2.07 points at 394.02. While the
three other major indexes are up slightly for the year, the Russell
is off 6.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   While the IBM announcement helped lift the broad market, its
effect on technology shares was less than might have been expected.
And that is because investors continue to have doubts about the
outlook after a series of announcements of earnings and sales
shortfalls from the likes of Dell, Micron Technology, Compaq
Computer and 3Com.
</P>
<P>
   Cliggott said that a report released Thursday showing that
factory orders increased 1.7 percent in January, to a seasonally
adjusted $349.6 billion, indicated that the growth trend for
semiconductors was still healthy. But the data also showed that the
growth rate for the personal computer and telecommunications
sectors was slowing, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of IBM finished the day up 4\, to 171. But it was well
off its high of 177. Intel rose as high as 117~ in early trading
but fell in the afternoon, finishing down 1 5/16, to 113].
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2205EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
