<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8354 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IBM-DELL-ART-NYT &LR;      03-04 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IBM-DELL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELL DEAL POINTS TO IBM'S GROWTH IN COMPONENTS BUSINESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By SAUL HANSELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Signaling that its future may depend as much on computer parts
as on entire machines, International Business Machines Corp. said
Thursday that it expected to sell $16 billion worth of disk drives
and other components to a rival, the Dell Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   IBM claims to spend more on research and development than any
other technology company, and it is awarded the most patents of any
company in the world. But until recently, it hoarded its
discoveries for use in its own machines.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, however, it has been successful in selling
small, high-capacity disk drives for use in laptop computers. Its
PowerPC chip has been used extensively by Apple Computer for its
Macintosh family of computers.
</P>
<P>
   Although components represent only 8 percent of IBM's $81.6
billion in annual sales, the business is growing at 40 percent a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``This deal helps legitimize IBM's claim they are a real
technology company,'' said Kevin McCarthy, an analyst with
Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette. ``Their R&AMP;D spending is starting to
pay off.''
</P>
<P>
   For Dell, the deal promises discounts associated with a large
contract. Moreover, it gains an earlier window into IBM's research
efforts. Dell conducts little research of its own. It has grown by
efficiently assembling and distributing technology developed by the
Intel and Microsoft corporations and others. Dell will gain access
to IBM's vast portfolio of patents as part of the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   The companies said that Dell would purchase $16 billion worth of
parts over seven years, but that is based on a number of optimistic
assumptions. Dell's entire spending on components and other cost of
goods sold was $14 billion in 1998. Of that, only a few hundred
million was spent on disk drives from IBM. IBM told analysts that
the deal would not increase significantly its sales in the early
years of the contract.
</P>
<P>
   But executives of both companies said that toward the end of the
deal, Dell's purchases from IBM would grow rapidly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may end up being IBM's biggest customer, which is kind of
eye opening,'' said Michael D. Lambert, a Dell senior vice
president. Still, he said that Dell was not bound to the $16
billion figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not locked in,'' he said. ``It's a best-efforts
arrangement. We said that if things go where we expect them, the
business ought to add up to $16 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors nonetheless took the deal as a positive sign. IBM's
shares rose by $4.25, to $171. Dell's shares increased by 93.75
cents, to $81.875.
</P>
<P>
   Publicly announcing such a long-term deal is unusual in the
fast-moving computer business, where manufacturers select
components for each new model based on what is available in the
marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   IBM executives say they are trying to escape such cyclical
beauty contests and forge the sort of long-term, high-level
relationships with manufacturers that it has long sought with
corporate computer users. Moreover, such a big announcement
represents an effort by IBM to attract attention to its components
business.
</P>
<P>
   For Dell, Lambert said that committing to such a big contract
was necessary because IBM and Dell were such long-term adversaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sends a strong signal internally that we can talk about the
future in collaborative terms,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts wondered if IBM hoped to forge deeper ties with Dell.
IBM's rapidly growing Global Services unit would love to offer
installation and maintenance services for Dell's customers.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts wonder whether IBM might outsource some or all of
its computer manufacturing business to Dell as part of a broader
arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   ``IBM still insists they are committed to the PC business,''
McCarthy said. ``But longer term, they may want out, and Dell could
be a bigger partner.''
</P>
<P>
   The growth in IBM's components business came as its personal
computer business foundered. It lost ground to low-cost machines
from Compaq that won the consumer market, and Dell's lean
direct-sales approach won huge gains among IBM's traditional
corporate customers.
</P>
<P>
   IBM found it had less competition and higher margins selling
components. It says it earns more profit from an Apple Powerbook _
equipped with a disk, display screen and PowerPC chip from IBM _
than Apple earns.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, executives of the company's computer system units
initially objected to selling the most advanced technology to
rivals. But ultimately, Louis V. Gerstner Jr., IBM's chairman, made
it clear that each division would have to compete on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, IBM consolidated its component businesses,
including disks, chips, printers and networking equipment, in one
division run by James T. Vanderslice, who had run the successful
disk business. One of his first sales calls was on Dell.
</P>
<P>
   IBM's competitors in the disk drive market played down the
effect of the deal on their sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing for us should change,'' said Phil Montero, a spokesman
for Seagate Technology. ``Dell has always had more than one
supplier.'' He said that just under 5 percent of Seagate's sales,
or $340 million, were to Dell.
</P>
<P>
   Seagate's stock fell by $1.625 Thursday to $28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2208EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0466 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8355 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROSOFT-NYT &LR;      03-04 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT TO SELL BUSINESS INTERNET SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also MICROSOFT-REORG)  (DW) 
 By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Projecting a vision of a world in which most buying and selling
takes place between machines, Microsoft Corp. Thursday announced
its electronic commerce strategy, a range of software products and
services designed to automate business.
</P>
<P>
   Although Microsoft generally has been perceived to be trailing
in Internet commerce systems, the company Thursday offered Biztalk,
a new language, or a set of conventions, that it said would help
draw together disparate business practices and electronic commerce
technologies via the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet is the ultimate market,'' said Bill Gates,
Microsoft's chairman and chief executive. ``It's great news for
businesses because they can reach out to more customers than ever
before.''
</P>
<P>
   The new approach will offer businesses the ability to configure
electronic systems for retail or business-to-business commerce in a
``Lego block'' approach, Microsoft executives said.
</P>
<P>
   But they did not announce specific product availability dates or
prices, saying only that they would be available shortly after the
company's much-delayed Windows 2000 operating system, the successor
to Windows NT, which is scheduled to be released before the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft also announced Commerce Server version 3.0, a software
program designed for Windows 2000.
</P>
<P>
   As part of its new initiative, Microsoft also announced a
variety of new business partnerships and the acquisition of
Comparenet, a comparison-shopping Web site that it intends to
integrate into its MSN Web portal.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft is trying to turn MSN into a marketplace by offering
services that will make it easier for small businesses to build an
online store.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts said that although Microsoft was late and
trailed competitors like IBM in the electronic commerce space, the
software company's new strategy appeared to be a systematic
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely late; it's a me-too strategy compared to
companies like Yahoo and America Online,'' said Michael Putnam, a
business and technology analyst at Forrester Research Inc., a
market research firm in Cambridge, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   He added that the strategy was a good one but suggested that
Microsoft might run into resistance from competitors and from its
own customers and business partners in its attempt to evangelize a
broad standard with the Biztalk language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Biztalk is a good thing,'' he said. ``Standards
are critical for the growth of Internet commerce, but this is like
General Motors making the traffic rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft executives predicted Thursday that the accelerating
pace of electronic commerce shortly would begin to transform some
products that have been sold as physical objects into digital
information.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of products that today are in physical form will become
digital,'' Gates said.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts were skeptical that Microsoft would be able to
achieve meaningful dominance in electronic commerce markets,
because it will have difficulty harnessing broadly used Internet
standards to its proprietary software.
</P>
<P>
   The company has chosen to build its Biztalk ``framework'' around
an industry Web standard known as XML, which is being used to
connect data bases to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they're not using industry-standard XML, they're out of
luck,'' said Kimball Brown, a computer industry analyst at
Dataquest, a San Jose, Calif., market research firm. ``Microsoft is
going to have to play by industry rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
