<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-420&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONITOR CHIEF CALLS KOSOVO CLOSE TO FLARE-UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also KOSOVO-U.S.) 
(js) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The senior general in charge of
international monitors in Kosovo warned Thursday that the troubled
province was perilously close to a major conflagration, as two
separate incidents in the province nearly flared into violence.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 Serbian policemen lined up their armored vehicles
threatening to storm a village after two Serbian brothers were
killed in northern Kosovo. In another area, the Serbian police said
they would run an armed patrol deep into territory controlled by
Kosovo Liberation Army guerrillas, who in turn threatened to fire
on them.
</P>
<P>
   Unarmed international monitors tried to get the two sides to
step back from confrontation in each area, but by evening the
standoffs continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has got pretty serious,'' said Maj. Gen. John
Drewienkiewicz, the British chief of operations of the Kosovo
Verification Mission, run by the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe to insure compliance with a cease-fire here.
The monitors could not carry on forever, he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think we can stagger on with this mission
indefinitely because we had difficulties in December, and it has
been getting steadily worse,'' he said in an interview. ``The place
is hugely volatile.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army now has 15 companies out of their barracks,
conducting operations around Kosovo, setting up scattered camps in
villages and fields, in broad violation of the cease-fire accord
signed in October.
</P>
<P>
   That agreement, brokered by a U.S. envoy, Richard Holbrooke,
with the Yugoslav president, Slobodan Milosevic, allows for only
three companies, or about 400 troops, to be out at any one time.
There are nearly 2,000 Serbian troops on the move in Kosovo now.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you keep pouring people out of their barracks, something is
going to happen,'' Drewienkiewicz said. ``If you slop petrol all
over the floor, eventually someone comes in and stubs a cigarette
out in it.''
</P>
<P>
   He said scattered camps of Serbian forces and the ethnic
Albanian guerrillas were ``all on alert, all ready to move and not
ready to be the first to step back.''
</P>
<P>
   Drewienkiewicz, who introduces himself as ``General DZ,'' said
the situation was not so bad that he feared for the safety of the
1,300 monitors in Kosovo, but he said only an international
military force could do the job now.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not verifying a cease-fire,'' he said. ``We are hanging
on to a cease-fire and negotiating its reconstitution by the
minute.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Every day the monitors have to wade through rumor and
counterrumor to establish who started a clash and why.
</P>
<P>
   The Yugoslav army and the Serbian police often use their heavy
firepower to respond to a killing or ambush, resulting in hundreds
of villagers' fleeing their homes.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas are reacting to the large concentrations of
Serbian forces by reinforcing positions and performing hit-and-run
ambushes and shootings. Several policemen have been killed in the
last week.
</P>
<P>
   Drewienkiewicz said that the Kosovo Liberation Army issued
instructions to its men this week to refrain from such attacks and
that the warning seemed to be having some effect. But Serbian
forces appear to be ignoring the remonstrations of the Organization
for Security and Cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   The primary aim of the Serbian military activity is not clear,
but observers are concerned the Yugoslav army may be preparing a
major offensive.
</P>
<P>
   The operations around the border are evidently to guard the
country against the supposed NATO threat, Drewienkiewicz said.
</P>
<P>
   More than 2,000 troops of a NATO extraction force are based over
Kosovo's southern border, in Macedonia. They are on hand to rescue
the monitors if needed but may form the vanguard of the
international military peacekeeping force that will enforce any
peace deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are there, with a lot of heavy metal, and the Serbs must
be aware of it,'' the general said. Serbian forces have wired with
explosives several bridges and tunnels on the Kosovo border,
apparently in preparation for a NATO attack.
</P>
<P>
   They have also massed large numbers of tanks and armor mounted
with anti-aircraft guns in the border region, clearing many
villages of their inhabitants in the process.
</P>
</TEXT>
