<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANGBURN'S-SALE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSELL STOVER BUYS PANGBURN'S NAME, TRADEMARKS, INVENTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM FUQUAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ Pangburn Candy Co., which traces its roots back 85
years in Fort Worth, was unceremoniously put to rest Thursday in a
bankruptcy court auction that attracted winning bids of $4.5
million.
</P>
<P>
   The brand name and its flagship pecan patties will survive as
part of the Russell Stover Candies empire. But the company's Fort
Worth factory will close, throwing several dozen employees out of
work.
</P>
<P>
   The company, founded in 1914 at H.T. Pangburn's downtown Fort
Worth drugstore, filed for bankruptcy Feb. 1 after two consecutive
years of losses.
</P>
<P>
   Its fate was sealed Thursday morning in a dingy basement room at
the federal courthouse. Fifteen registered bidders took less than
90 minutes to conclude the auction.
</P>
<P>
   Pangburn employees are expected to be told Friday that they will
lose their jobs, workers said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The company has laid off many of its 100 full-time workers in
the past two weeks, operating its plant at 2000 White Settlement
Road with a skeleton crew, employees said.
</P>
<P>
   Pangburn officials did not return requests for comment Thursday.
The company has been owned by an investment group headed by Jim
Phillips, a Fort Worth lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover, which is based in Kansas City, Mo., made the
only winning bids at the auction through its Whitman's Candies
affiliate.
</P>
<P>
   The first bid, for $4 million, won the rights to the Pangburn
name and trademarks, including the popular Millionaire$. A second
bid, for $500,000, won the company's inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Both were swiftly approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Massie
Tillman, and Russell Stover said it plans to complete the deal
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan on manufacturing the Pangburn products out of our new
plant in Corsicana,'' said Scott Ward, co-president of Russell
Stover. He said it should take four to five months to transfer
production to the Corsicana factory, a $35 million,
450,000-square-foot facility that started making candy just last
week.
</P>
<P>
   Ward invited idled Pangburn factory workers to interview for
positions at the plant, which is expected to employ 600 within a
year. About 120 people work now in Corsicana, Russell Stover's
eighth U.S. production site.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Stover is the nation's third-largest chocolate maker,
behind industry giants Hershey's and M&AMP;M Mars. It is the No. 1
seller of boxed chocolates, with sales of more than $500 million,
Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   Only one bidder, Maxfield Candy Co. of Salt Lake City, offered
to buy all of Pangburn's assets, including the equipment and
accounts receivable. President Taz Murray bid $4.5 million but
would go no higher, citing Pangburn's unprofitability.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to offer what we felt it was worth,'' Murray said. He
acknowledged that his price was far less than the company's
valuation of about $17 million as of Dec. 31. But ``an asset is
only worth what it produces in income,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Philip Gay, president of DFG Confectionery of Fort Worth, also
wanted to bid for the entire company. DFG acquired the Sweet Shop
last year and wanted to consolidate Pangburn with its operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, by the time you added up the sum of the parts,
it was $6 million-plus, and that was too much,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he said Russell Stover made a good deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They paid a good price for what they got,'' he said. ``They're
growing, and Pangburn fits in nicely with what they're doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Bidders offered about $500,000 for the equipment and accounts
receivable. But when Pangburn's lawyer, Mark Petrocchi, said the
company wants at least $1.5 million for those assets, his remark
drew only silence. The company will continue efforts to sell those
assets.
</P>
<P>
   NationsBank Dallas, Pangburn's only secured creditor, has first
call on proceeds from the asset sales.
</P>
<P>
   Between Russell Stover's $4.5 million, cash in the company's
bank accounts and other sale proceeds, the bank should reclaim its
nearly $7 million in outstanding loans, said John Penn, a lawyer in
the Fort Worth office of Haynes &AMP; Boone.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's lackluster bidding bodes ill for Pangburn's
unsecured creditors, who lack collateral for their more than $3
million in claims.
</P>
<P>
   The largest unsecured creditor, Gonzales Labor Systems of
Arlington, is owed about $250,000 for providing temporary workers.
Owner Cruz Gonzales said Thursday that Pangburn was not his largest
customer but represented about 8 percent of his billings.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Prostok, a Fort Worth lawyer with Cantey &AMP; Hanger and
representative for the unsecured creditors, said he hopes to
recover 50 cents on the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Absent from Thursday's bidding was Peggie Muir, former chief
financial officer of Pangburn. She left the company about two years
ago and founded Mrs. Burden's Gourmet Candy Co. in Fort Worth. Muir
had said she wanted to combine the two operations, keeping Pangburn
in town.
</P>
<P>
   She rounded up financial backers that would have supported a bid
of at least $5 million but said she couldn't negotiate a break on
the $516,000 annual rent on Pangburn's production plant. The
facility is owned by an investment group that, until July, owned
part of Pangburn.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I could have made it work, except we couldn't get
comfortable with the lease,'' Muir said. ``That's when my money
went away. Nobody wants to throw $5 million or $6 million into a
bucket with a hole in the bottom.''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
