<HEADLINE>
AFTER LULL TO GAUGE DAMAGE, BRITISH JETS HIT IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a lull in fighting following the disruption
of oil exports from Iraq to Turkey, air strikes against Iraq
resumed Thursday when British jets attacked a surface-to-air
missile site in southern Iraq, U.S. and British officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The disruption of the oil flow, which occurred on Sunday and
Monday after U.S. jets struck radio towers that control the
pipeline, prompted criticism from some allies that the repeated air
strikes in the no-flight zones had gone too far.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and British jets suspended their patrols long enough to
allow U.N. inspectors to investigate the damage, an administration
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite initial Iraqi claims that the damage was extensive, oil
began flowing early Thursday and quickly returned to earlier
levels, according to the United Nations, which oversees the program
that allows Iraq to sell up to $5.2 billion of oil every six months
to buy food and medicine.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline, which runs from Kirkuk to Ceyhan, Turkey, carries
1 million barrels of oil a day, roughly half of what Iraq has been
pumping under the program.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. strikes on Sunday and Monday knocked out two of eight
communication towers linked to it. U.N. inspectors reported
significant damage from explosions and heat, providing far more
detailed assessment of the attacks than the Pentagon has been
giving.
</P>
<P>
   At the first tower, 40 miles from Zakho, a generator room was
completely destroyed, according to the inspectors' report. At the
second tower, at Ain Zalah, two missiles ``completely destroyed'' a
control room.
</P>
<P>
   After the strikes, the Pentagon reviewed the decision to select
the towers as targets and concluded that they were being used by
the Iraqi military to communicate and thus were legitimate targets,
an administration official said.
</P>
<P>
   A military official said the Pentagon had not ruled out
attacking other communications posts but would consider their
``dual use'' in planning future strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we fully understood enough about what that radio
relay did in terms of monitoring pipeline flow,'' the official
said.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's strikes, British Tornado jets attacked a missile
site about 15 miles south of Basra. No U.S. aircraft were involved.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
