<SLUG> BC-READING-SCORES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORES ON READING HOLD STEADY AS CONNECTICUT LEADS GAINERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., N.Y.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By RANDAL C. ARCHIBOLD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a nationwide test that measures the reading ability of public
school students, no state lost ground last year, and a handful _
led by Connecticut _ made significant gains, according to
state-by-state results released Thursday by the Department of
Education.
</P>
<P>
   The results, for fourth- and eighth-graders in the National
Assessment of Educational Progress, inspired policy-makers and
politicians _ including Vice President Al Gore as he visited the
Bronx _ to urge a redoubling of efforts to improve reading and
writing skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are two challenges that I think are particularly
important in improving education,'' Gore said after reading to
second-graders at Public School 153 in Co-op City in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first is reducing class size and the second is making sure
all children, by the time they are 8 years old, can pick up a book
and say, `I can read that all by myself.'''
</P>
<P>
   The test, one hour long and a combination of multiple-choice and
written responses, was given in February 1998 to 18,680 fourth- and
eighth-graders whose states and territories volunteered to take
part.
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth grade, 39 states and four territories took part,
and for the eighth grade, 36 states and four territories.
</P>
<P>
   The tests are graded on a scale of 1 to 500, with the national
average for fourth-grade public school students at 215, a
three-point gain from 1994 but the same as 1992.
</P>
<P>
   For eighth-graders, the average was 261, but no comparison for
previous years is available because this was the first year those
results were computed state by state. The overall results, without
the state-by-state breakdown, were reported last month.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Education also breaks down the results by four
achievement levels _ below basic, basic, proficient and advanced _
and uses ``at or above proficient'' as the benchmark for the
strongest reading skills.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, 29 percent of the fourth-graders were at or above
proficiency _ a slight rise from the 28 percent in 1994 and 27
percent in 1992 _ and 31 percent of eighth-graders rated proficient
or better.
</P>
<P>
   Affluent states outperformed less-prosperous ones and
traditionally strong regions like the Northeast had higher scores
than traditionally weaker ones, like the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Connecticut were jubilant about the results, which
showed improvement among all races in both scores and the
percentage of students judged proficient.
</P>
<P>
   Theodore Sergi, the state's education commissioner, said
affluence was a factor in the overall score, but he noted poorer
students showed gains as well. Sergi attributed the success in part
to a statewide push to demand proficient reading at the earliest
grade levels.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth-graders in Connecticut scored 10 points higher on the
fourth-grade test, rising to 232 from 222 in 1994 (the score in
1992 was also 222). Eighth-graders scored 272, 11 points higher
than the national average.
</P>
<P>
   In proficiency, Connecticut students also outranked their peers
in other states, with 46 percent of fourth-graders rating at or
above proficiency compared with 29 percent nationally. Forty-two
percent of eighth-graders were at or above proficiency compared
with 31 percent nationally.
</P>
<P>
   New York performed about average in 1998 and showed no gain from
1992 on the fourth-grade test. Eighth-graders performed slightly
better than the national average. Black and Hispanic students, who
tend to be poorer and in schools lacking the resources of their
suburban counterparts, did more poorly on the test.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey chose not to participate in the test.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
