<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO LONG, DODGERS; HELLO, AGUASCALIENTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. _ The Dodgers pulled a fast one on the Angels, who
aren't too happy about it.
</P>
<P>
   The annual Freeway Series has been reduced from three games to
one this spring because the Dodgers jumped at the opportunity to
play host to the defending World Series champion New York Yankees
on April 3 and 4.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are upset for two reasons:
</P>
<P>
   __ It was their turn to play host to two of the three games.
They will play the Dodgers April 2 at Edison Field but lose the
gate for a second game.
</P>
<P>
   __ The Freeway Series games have been the final games before the
start of the regular season, so facing major-league level
competition is important. With most major-league teams already
having their schedules set, the Angels could not find another
major-league team to play. Instead, the Angels will play the
Aguascalientes Railroadmen of the Mexican League _ equivalent to
Triple-A _ April 3, then play Cal State Fullerton April 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one thing that irritates me is we're a good team with good
players and we can't get a game (against another major-league
team),'' said Angels manager Terry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Collins added that he was appreciative to Aguascalientes and
CSUF for the games because otherwise the Angels would have had no
one to play.
</P>
<P>
   Angels closer Troy Percival has another perception.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they (Dodgers) realize we might be stealing their
thunder,'' said the Southern California native. ``I think they know
there's another good team in town. They have the tradition and
they've earned it, but we're starting to step on their toes a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels are fighting for respect across the country, not just
in Southern California, Percival said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all the media and the fans,'' Percival said. ``We're
respected by other teams. We can't control what anyone else thinks.
We play hard and we play the right way. We've won some people over.
</P>
<P>
   ``You listen to the Yankees last year. They were saying they
were glad they weren't playing the Angels (in the playoffs).''
</P>
<P>
   Last season the Angels were the only team to take the season
series from the Yankees, winning six of 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   __ Bumps and bruises: Pitcher Chuck Finley, bothered by a
strained muscle in his upper back the past few days, threw off the
mound Thursday. He is expected to start Saturday's Cactus League
game against the Oakland A's in Phoenix if there are no setbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman Randy Velarde was hit on the left forearm by a
pitch thrown by nonroster pitcher Reid Cornelius in an intrasquad
game Thursday afternoon. Velarde had the forearm wrapped in ice,
but no X-rays were planned. ``The perfect spot for him is on the
forearm,'' Collins said, noting Velarde's well-developed physique.
</P>
<P>
   The intrasquad game was called after six innings _ one pitch
after Velarde was hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got these young pitchers who want to impress you and
sometimes they overthrow,'' Collins said. ``Up steps Mo Vaughn and
they try to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Reggie Williams (food poisoning) and catcher Phil
Nevin (sore hamstring) had the day off.
</P>
<P>
   __ Today's play: The Angels begin Cactus League play today at
12:05 p.m. at Tempe Diablo Stadium. Steve Sparks (9-4, 4.34 ERA in
'98) will start for the Angels against the A's. The game will be
broadcast on KLAC-570.
</P>
<P>
   Finley is tentatively slated to start Saturday's game and Tim
Belcher will start Sunday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2222EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
