A8373 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PORN-NYTSF &LR;      03-04 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PORN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S HANDS-OFF POLICY TOWARD PORN 
</HEADLINE>
   (Commentary)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Mike McManus is a syndicated columnist whose ``Ethics &AMP;
Religion'' appears in almost 100 newspapers)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480)  
 &HT;    
 By MIKE McMANUS  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    During his original race for the presidency, Bill Clinton was
asked by Morality in Media, the oldest anti-porn group, whether he
would enforce federal obscenity laws that had begun to be enforced
in the Reagan and Bush administrations.
 &HT;    Clinton wrote back: ''Be assured that aggressive enforcement of
the federal obscenity laws, particularly by the Child Exploitation
and Obscenity section, will be a priority in a Clinton-Gore
Administration.''
 &HT;    That's one promise he has not kept. Morality in Media (MIM)
President Robert Peters reported recently that U.S. attorneys in
fiscal 1997 began only six prosecutions of obscenity, down from 42
initiated in 1992. That's a drop of 86 percent!
 &HT;    ''Adult Video News,'' the video porn trade publication, endorsed
Clinton for re-election in 1996 due to his ''hands-nearly-off porn
policy.'' Not surprisingly, Larry Flynt, publisher of ''Hustler''
magazine, was the president's most ardent defender during the
impeachment proceedings. He offered $1 million to anyone who could
document having had extramarital sex with prominent Republicans,
and brought down Rep. Robert Livingston, who acknowledged having
adulterous affairs, declined to run as speaker of the House, and
has now resigned.
 &HT;    A U.S. News &AMP; World Report cover story reports that in 1996,
''Americans spent more than $8 billion on hardcore videos, peep
shows, live sex acts, adult cable programming, sexual devices,
computer porn and sex magazines an amount much larger than
Hollywood's domestic box office receipts and larger than all the
revenues generated by rock and country music recordings. Americans
now spend more money in strip clubs than at Broadway, off-Broadway,
regional and nonprofit theaters, at the opera, the ballet and jazz
and classical music performances combined.''
 &HT;    So? What is the problem with sex between consenting adults?
 &HT;    In 1986 the Meese Commission on Pornography concluded that
''clinical and experimental research'' is ''virtually unanimous''
that ''exposure to sexually violent materials'' sparks ''an
increase in the likelihood of aggression.'' In an Introduction I
wrote to the report, I cited evidence. First, a study that rapists
are 15 times as likely as non-offenders to have had exposure to
hard-core pornography ''during childhood or between six to ten
years old.''
 &HT;    Second, ''cross-national data from areas as disparate as
England, Australia, Singapore and South Africa'' found that ''rape
reports have increased where porn laws have been liberalized while
the same steep rise is not in evidence where restrictions exist.''
 &HT;    Third, even nonviolent, soft-core pornography may ''legitimate
rape.'' The eight major men's magazines such as Playboy, Hustler
and Penthouse, had sales that were five times higher per capita in
such states as Alaska and Nevada than in other states. And rape
rates were six times higher per capita in Alaska and Nevada than
North Dakota.
 &HT;    Those findings are 13 years old, and have been disputed by some
researchers. But a report for the National Coalition for the
Protection of Children and Families by Dr. Stan Weed cited a 1994
review by Lyons, Anderson and Larsen of 152 studies which concluded
that by witnessing rape pornography scenes, 88 percent of men felt
rape victims were ''less injured, resisting less, and experiencing
less trauma. Further, when assured of anonymity, about half of the
men surveyed expressed some likelihood of raping.''
 &HT;    What about nonviolent porn? Prolonged exposure to it ''promotes
acceptance of pre- and extramarital sexuality ... decreases trust
among sexual intimates ... spawns doubts about the value of
marriage as an essential societal institution ... breeds discontent
with the physical appearance and the sexual performance of intimate
partners.''
 &HT;    Pornography is thus a major destroyer of marriages.
 &HT;    Further, hard-core pornography is far more available now than
when the Meese Commission filed its report. A huge new source is
the Internet, where there are 70,000 publicly viewable Web sites.
Teenage girls can be seen having sex with animals, for example. A
single site had 407,000 visitors on Dec. 4, according to the
National Journal.
 &HT;    Yet there has never been any federal prosecution of Internet
purveyors of porn or any of Cable TV. A MIM-sponsored poll reveals
that 87 percent of women and 72 percent of men believe ''federal
obscenity laws against hard-core pornography should be vigorously
enforced.''
 &HT;    But we have a president against whom credible charges of rape
were filed by Juanita Brodderick last week.
 &HT;    ''Clinton has not denied them as any decent man would,' says Pat
Trueman, who directed Bush Administration obscenity prosecution. He
sees no hope of change: ``There are few rapists concerned with the
problem of pornography in America. We have not had obscenity
prosecution and we should not expect them from a morally bankrupt
president.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----
 &HT;    c.1999 Mike McManus
