</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY SPEAKS ON WOMEN'S ISSUES AT U.N. 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the second day of her visit as a potential
candidate for a New York Senate seat, Hillary Rodham Clinton spoke
out Thursday at the United Nations against ``the egregious and
systematic trampling'' of women's rights under the Taliban in
Afghanistan, and called the trafficking in women and children in
Asia an international human rights violation.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton, who has made women's human rights a focus of her
work as first lady, has spoken out repeatedly on both issues, and
her remarks were consistent with Clinton administration policy. But
they come at a time when she is under increased scrutiny as a
potential Senate candidate, and underscore her strong stand on
women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-minute speech to 1,000 U.N. staff and delegates in the
U.N. Trusteeship Council, Mrs. Clinton said that she had spoken
with young girls in Thailand whose parents had sold them as
prostitutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could often tell the home of where girls had been sold
because they might even have a satellite dish, or an addition built
onto the house,'' Mrs. Clinton said. ``But I met the girls who had
come home after they had been used up, after they had contracted
HIV and AIDS. If you've ever held the hand of a 13-year-old girl
dying of AIDS, you can understand how critical it is that we take
every step possible to prevent this happening to any other girl,
anywhere, in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Echoing remarks often made by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, Mrs. Clinton said: ``It is no longer acceptable to say
that the abuse and mistreatment of women is cultural. It should be
called what it is _ criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   In the afternoon, Mrs. Clinton spoke about women's sports at the
Lab School at the O. Henry Learning Center in Chelsea, where a
student basketball player, Sofia Totti, introduced Mrs. Clinton as
``hopefully, a runner.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton grinned _ the only sign she gave Thursday to New
York Democrats who are in a frenzy hoping that she will run next
year for the seat being vacated by Daniel Patrick Moynihan.
</P>
<P>
   All day, Mrs. Clinton avoided the crowd of reporters trailing
her. Three times at the United Nations, Mrs. Clinton walked by
penned-in reporters shouting questions about the Senate race
without saying a word.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berry said that Mrs. Clinton ``doesn't have anything to add
right now'' to her earlier comments about the race.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Mrs. Clinton said she was giving ``careful thought''
to a Senate run and that she would make a decision ``later this
year.'' Her advisers have not given a more specific timetable,
although the view of New York Democrats is that the longer Mrs.
Clinton waits to announce a decision _ perhaps as late as the fall
_ the more likely she is to run. Many Democrats want her to make up
her mind more quickly so that she doesn't hamper other candidates
from raising money.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton appeared at the Lab School to promote an HBO film
on women's sports with Bille Jean King, the former tennis champion;
Nikki McCray, the women's basketball star; and Dominique Dawes, the
gymnast and Olympic gold medalist. Afterward students sent written
questions to the panel, but none were for Mrs. Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In her remarks to teachers and junior high school students, Mrs.
Clinton said she wanted Congress in a bipartisan way to make
teachers and lowering classroom size ``their very top priority.''
She also recalled playing ``half-court'' basketball in high school,
when girls had to stay on one side of the court.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton said the girls asked why they could not play like
the boys and were told, ``We're sorry, but we just don't think
girls' hearts can take that much exertion.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton seemed to have a lot of support among the students,
a number of whom volunteered to reporters that they had seen the
``20-20'' interview with Monica Lewinsky the night before.
``Hillary is very strong,'' said Christopher Williams, 13, an
eighth grader. ``If she can live through that and get along, she's
like superwoman. That's a lot of stress.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
