<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GERMAN OFFICIAL SUGGESTS ALLIANCE WITH EX-COMMUNISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ROGER COHEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Already under fire from business, Germany's finance
minister, Oskar Lafontaine, has divided his own governing Social
Democratic Party and irked Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder with a
suggestion that a political alliance with former East German
communists would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Lafontaine, the chairman of the Social Democrats, said on Monday
that a 1994 statement by the party ruling out political cooperation
with the Party of Democratic Socialism, the former communists, was
``superfluous,'' ``old hat'' and ``overtaken by reality.''
</P>
<P>
   His policy switch reflected the fact that the Party of
Democratic Socialism is now an important political force _ it won
5.7 percent of the national vote in federal elections last year and
21 percent of the vote in the former East Germany _ and already
cooperates with the Social Democrats in the government of two
eastern states.
</P>
<P>
   But in Germany's charged political and economic environment,
where business confidence has been eroded by Lafontaine's new tax
proposals and by his constant skirmishing with central bankers over
interest rates, an opening to the former communists amounted to a
high-risk political gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who is in the uncomfortable position of being
beholden to Lafontaine for party support at the same time that he
is uneasy about his finance minister's more left-leaning
inclinations, shot back on Tuesday, saying he had ``made it clear
that there will be no cooperation with the PDS in the German
Bundestag.''
</P>
<P>
   Any cooperation at the local or state level would ``not be
transferred to the federal level,'' the chancellor added.
</P>
<P>
   The exchange between the two men amounted to one of the more
evident expressions of a simmering tension whose roots seem to lie
in the fact that Lafontaine was the architect of Schroeder's
electoral victory last year and seems disinclined to bow entirely
to the chancellor's authority.
</P>
<P>
   Since the government took office four months ago, the
differences between the two men have tended to paralyze economic
decision-making, leaving the direction of policy unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But Lafontaine appeared more concerned with political than
economic considerations. The government of Social Democrats and
environmentalist Greens lost its majority in the upper house of
Parliament when it was defeated last month in state elections in
Hesse.
</P>
<P>
   To regain that majority, the government needs to win other
regional elections this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
