researchers. But a report for the National Coalition for the
Protection of Children and Families by Dr. Stan Weed cited a 1994
review by Lyons, Anderson and Larsen of 152 studies which concluded
that by witnessing rape pornography scenes, 88 percent of men felt
rape victims were ''less injured, resisting less, and experiencing
less trauma. Further, when assured of anonymity, about half of the
men surveyed expressed some likelihood of raping.''
 &HT;    What about nonviolent porn? Prolonged exposure to it ''promotes
acceptance of pre- and extramarital sexuality ... decreases trust
among sexual intimates ... spawns doubts about the value of
marriage as an essential societal institution ... breeds discontent
with the physical appearance and the sexual performance of intimate
partners.''
 &HT;    Pornography is thus a major destroyer of marriages.
 &HT;    Further, hard-core pornography is far more available now than
when the Meese Commission filed its report. A huge new source is
the Internet, where there are 70,000 publicly viewable Web sites.
Teenage girls can be seen having sex with animals, for example. A
single site had 407,000 visitors on Dec. 4, according to the
National Journal.
