<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ALYDAR-BRIBE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY HORSE FARM OFFICIALS INDICTED IN ALLEGED BRIBERY SCHEME 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ky.) 
 
By ED ASHER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Two executives of a famed Kentucky thoroughbred farm
have been indicted on charges of offering a $1.1 million bribe to a
director of a now-defunct Houston bank to obtain $50 million in
loans.
</P>
<P>
   A federal indictment unsealed Wednesday provides new details of
possible links between Calumet Farm Inc. of Lexington, Ky., and the
failure of First City Bancorporation of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors allege that beginning in February 1988, Calumet
President John T. Lundy and chief financial officer Gary Matthews
conspired to pay a $1.1 million bribe to a First City director to
obtain the loans, presumably to prop up the financially ailing
farm.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Julia Hyman declined to say whether the
money was actually paid to the director, who was not named in the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   ``That will come out at trial,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says the director had a ``valuable lifetime
breeding right'' in Alydar, a famed race horse owned by Calumet,
and had ``other business with Calumet.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lundy, Matthews and the director intentionally failed to
disclose the latter's financial interest in Calumet to First City
officers, the indictment alleges.
</P>
<P>
   It says the director used his bank position not only to
facilitate approval of the loans to Calumet but also to ``frustrate
and impede First City officers' attempts to collect from Calumet.''
</P>
<P>
   The indictment, returned Dec. 11, charges Lundy and Matthews
with one count each of conspiracy to defraud a financial
institution, scheme to defraud and bank bribery and three counts of
false statements to bank officials.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stem from an ongoing investigation into loan
activities involving First City, which failed in 1992. First City
was later reorganized into First City Financial Corp., a Waco-based
firm that handles mortgages for borrowers with credit problems.
</P>
<P>
   Also on-going is an investigation into Alydar's mysterious 1990
death, which Hyman said involves ``possible insurance fraud.'' The
horse's death from a leg broken in his stall was ruled accidental.
</P>
<P>
   Alydar, history's most heavily insured thoroughbred, was put up
by Calumet as collateral on its loans from First City, Calumet's
biggest creditor.
</P>
<P>
   First City had warned the farm that a $15 million loan payment
was due by February 1991 or foreclosure could begin. After Alydar
died suddenly on Nov. 13, 1990, Calumet collected $36.5 million in
insurance claims, with $20.5 million of that going to First City.
</P>
<P>
   Lundy was arrested by U.S. Customs Service officials Tuesday
night in Miami on his arrival from Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   His bond hearing is scheduled Thursday in Miami, and Hyman said
prosecutors will ask that he be held without bond. ``Based on
flight risk,'' she said, declining to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews, arrested Wednesday in Lexington, was released on a
$10,000 personal recognizance bond and directed to report to court
in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Calumet _ which produced Whirlaway, Citation and six other
Kentucky Derby winners _ collapsed soon after Alydar's death.
</P>
<P>
   Its 1991 bankruptcy was the largest farm collapse in
thoroughbred history, listing debts of more than $120 million. It
was sold the next year at auction for $17 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $36.5 million Alydar insurance claim was the largest of its
kind.
</P>
<P>
   At least five people, including former First City vice chairman
Frank Cihak, have been convicted of fraud in connection with other
loans by the bank.
</P>
<P>
   Cihak was sentenced in 1996 to nearly 22 years in prison for his
part in what prosecutors called a multimillion-dollar kickback
scheme. At the time, Cihak was already serving a sentence of more
than 12 years in a federal prison in Michigan for another First
City-related conviction.
</P>
<P>
   In November, Alton Stone, a former Calumet groom, was sentenced
to five months in prison and five months' home confinement for
lying to a grand jury investigating Alydar's death.
</P>
<P>
   Hyman said at the time that Stone lied to cover up a plot to
defraud the bank and the insurance companies in connection with
Alydar's death.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
