<HEADLINE>
BRAZIL INCREASES A KEY INTEREST RATE TO 45 PERCENT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass.)   (af)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil _ The Brazilian central bank raised its
benchmark interest rate Thursday to 45 percent and granted its new
president expanded powers to adjust rates in an effort to head off
a surge of inflation and to stabilize the country's battered
currency.
</P>
<P>
   The monetary authority's actions were the first to be taken
under Arminio Fraga, a former aide to the financier George Soros.
Fraga was confirmed on Wednesday as central bank president by the
Brazilian Senate after an acrimonious debate.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference in Brasilia Thursday afternoon, Fraga
promised a vigorous response to the country's financial crisis,
saying his administration would be ``pro-active, not reactive.''
</P>
<P>
   The interest rate increase, from 39 percent, helped steady the
Brazilian currency, the real, in trading Thursday. The real has
declined in value against the dollar by more than 40 percent since
mid-January.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting an all-time low of 2.22 to the dollar on Tuesday,
the real recovered strongly, closing at 2.07 to the dollar, up 3.9
percent from Wednesday. The stock market also reacted favorably,
grateful for any indication that the government was taking the
offensive. Sao Paulo's Bovespa exchange rose 3.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In remarks to reporters after announcing the interest rate
increase, Fraga made it clear that his primary goal was to stem the
sharp rise in consumer prices brought on by the devaluation of the
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``The exchange rate is important, but what will determine our
success or not is the rate of inflation,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   With the real under siege, the central bank earlier this week
announced, apparently at Fraga's behest, that banks' compulsory
deposit requirements would be raised to 26.5 percent as of Friday
and 30 percent later this month. The monetary authority said it was
taking that step ``to dry up liquidity'' and ``relieve pressure on
the real.''
</P>
<P>
   In raising interest rates, Fraga was adhering to advice
profferred by the International Monetary Fund. At a news conference
in Washington on Wednesday, the fund's chief economist, Michael
Mussa, said that while he hoped Brazilian ``interest rates will end
up this year substantially lower'' than they did in 1998, ``if the
real continues to depreciate, they will probably need to push up
interest rates further.''
</P>
<P>
   But not all analysts agree with that approach. In an interview
with the Globo News cable channel on Wednesday, Jeffrey Sachs, a
Harvard University professor who has served as an adviser to
several emerging countries, argued that Brazil should immediately
cut the interest rate to 20 percent in an effort to create jobs and
slow the increase of its mounting internal deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
