<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STOCKS GET LIFT FROM IBM BUT STAY IN TRADING RANGE
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of sour news on technology stocks, the sector
received a boost when IBM announced that it had won a $16 billion
order from Dell Computer for parts like disk drives and displays.
Despite the increase, the market is still locked in the trading
range it has been in since January.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average rose 191.52 points, or 2
percent, to 9,467.40. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed
18.94 points, or 1.5 percent, to 1,246.64, while the Nasdaq
composite index rose 27.69 points, or 1.22 percent, to 2,292.89. In
the bond market, Treasury securities were little changed.
</P>
<P>
   NONCOMBATANTS STUCK IN TRADE WAR
</P>
<P>
   After months of bitter feuding between the United States and
Europe over bananas, scores of companies are now caught in a bitter
trade battle in which they have no stake and over which they have
no control.
</P>
<P>
   RETAIL SALES CLIMB 7.6 PERCENT
</P>
<P>
   Retailers' sales at stores open at least a year rose 7.6 percent
in February, more than expected, as shoppers snapped up basic
household goods at discounters like Wal-Mart Stores and new spring
fashions at clothing chains like Gap. Among the apparel chains, Ann
Taylor Stores posted a sales increase of 21.4 percent, lifting its
shares $2.75, to $41.75.
</P>
<P>
   BANK LEGISLATION SEEMS IN TROUBLE
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate committees took action on sharply conflicting
bills to eliminate Depression-era barriers between banks,
securities firms and insurance companies, reducing the chances that
Congress will pass major banking legislation this year.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT BREAKUP PROPOSED
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest software-industry trade group has warned
the government not to impose sanctions on Microsoft that could
``fracture'' Windows' role as an industry standard if the company
loses its antitrust suit. But a report by the group recommends that
the government consider breaking up Microsoft as a cure for what
the report regards as the lack of competition in the software
industry.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft announced its electronic commerce strategy, which
includes software and services designed to automate business.
</P>
<P>
   INTEL TO BUY CHIP MAKER LEVEL ONE
</P>
<P>
   Intel agreed to buy Level One Communications for $2.2 billion in
stock as it pushes into the fast-growing market for chips used in
networking equipment.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL RAISES INTEREST RATE
</P>
<P>
   The Brazilian central bank raised its benchmark interest rate to
45 percent and granted its new president expanded powers to adjust
rates in the future to head off inflation and stabilize the
country's battered currency.
</P>
<P>
   RARE COINS GO TO TURKEY
</P>
<P>
   The investor William I. Koch handed a trove of ancient Greek
coins to the Turkish government. Officials said the coins, which
were issued around 465 B.C. and which Koch bought more than a
decade ago, had been illegally removed from their country.
</P>
<P>
   MILLER LITE CAMPAIGN HALTED
</P>
<P>
   Miller Brewing is making an abrupt about-face by ending a
campaign for the flagging Miller Lite beer brand that attempted to
appeal to younger consumers with offbeat entertainment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
