<SLUG> BC-LA-INTERACTIVE-MEDIA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAY LURE GAME MAKER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ One of the biggest names in videogame production
will move from New York City to Los Angeles to be closer to
competitors such as THQ Inc., an industry journal reported this
week.
</P>
<P>
   MCV, a business weekly that tracks the $6 billion-per-year
videogame market, said the new chief executive at Manhattan-based
GT Interactive Software Corp. told his staff that he plans to move
much of the firm's headquarters from the Big Apple to Southern
California in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   The executive, Thomas Heymann, headed the The Disney Store chain
before he left the Walt Disney Co. Heymann took over as chief
executive and chairman of the New York software firm Feb. 9.
</P>
<P>
   GT Interactive is one of the nation's top game makers for the
PC, Macintosh, Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64 platforms. For the
nine months that ended Dec. 31, the company generated sales of
$479.3 million on games such as the ``Doom'' series, ``Duke Nukem:
Time to Kill,'' ``Deer Hunter'' and ``Deer Hunter II.'' Less
homicidal titles include ``Blue's Birthday Party.''
</P>
<P>
   By moving the company to Southern California, Heymann would put
it closer to THQ, Interplay and Activision, as well as the gaming
wings of movie studios Sony, Universal Studios, Warner Bros. and
DreamWorks SKG. But precisely where the Manhattan firm might set up
shop is open to debate.
</P>
<P>
   Rohit Shukla, executive director of the Los Angeles Regional
Technology Alliance, said the most likely move would be to the West
Los Angeles area or Burbank because of the large number of
game-making firms already located there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a company is just getting started in town, they need to be
around other people, breathe the dust, that sort of thing,'' Shukla
said.
</P>
<P>
   A third option would be Culver City, he said, largely because of
the presence of Sony.
</P>
<P>
   GT Interactive releases software under a number of labels,
including Humongous Entertainment, Cavedog Entertainment and
Oddworld Inhabitants.
</P>
<P>
   Heymann was unavailable for comment Thursday on the possible
move, and a company spokesman would not comment on the MCV story.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short of it is, this isn't the time for us to discuss
plans being considered,'' said spokesman John Uppendahl.
</P>
<P>
   If the company moves, Heymann will almost certainly lose some
staff members reluctant to make the switch. And that may be part of
his plan, since the Los Angeles area probably has more videogame
programmers than any other part of the country.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, local players say they haven't had any
employees give notice to join GT in new Los Angeles offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a small industry that it's pretty common'' to see
employees poached from one firm to another, said Amy Greenholtz, a
spokeswoman for THQ. ``But I haven't heard anything.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
