<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: AVOIDING DUKE AND WATCHING THE WIZARDS OF RANKING  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here is something I learned from reading the wires between games
of the Big East basketball tournament: All Division I teams are
rated by the Collegiate Basketball News, all the way from No. 1
down to No. 310.
</P>
<P>
   The lowest team on this unofficial rating percentage index is
Jerry Falwell's school, Liberty University of Virginia, which has
lost all 20 of its games.
</P>
<P>
   The way I hear it, Liberty could have scheduled an easy victory
against the Teletubbies, who, after all, suit up only four weird
little runts, but Liberty refused to play the Teletubbies in that
spooky dome of theirs, where guys might whack you with their
pocketbooks.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of this gigantic spectrum are the Duke Blue
Devils, who inexplicably lost a game this season and are
everybody's worst-case scenario in the national tournament.
</P>
<P>
   The College of Charleston (No. 37) doesn't want Duke, Samford
(No. 74) doesn't want Duke, Winthrop (No. 150) doesn't want Duke.
Nobody wants Duke, not early, not midway through, not until the
night of March 29 in St. Petersburg, Fla., at the very earliest.
</P>
<P>
   The trick is to avoid the best team in the country as long as
possible. This takes on special meaning for a school like
Connecticut, which would like to get to a Final Four before this
millenium runs out.
</P>
<P>
   Imagine Connecticut's potential chagrin Thursday when it was
slogging along behind Seton Hall midway through the second half. A
loss to those people could have jeopardized an entire season of
work up in the outback of Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   There was an operative theory that a loss to Seton Hall could
have dropped Connecticut into the same East Regional with none
other than the Duke Blue Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just what I was thinking about at the 10-minute mark,''
said Jim Calhoun, the coach of Connecticut, who has a pretty decent
sense of irony for a man in his gloomy profession. `` `Seattle or
Lexington? Did you book rooms at the Omni or the Marriott?' That's
exactly what I was thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut survived the ordeal, 57-56, and lived to play
against Syracuse in Friday night's Big East semifinal. Calhoun then
gave his own personal spin on why Connecticut should be seeded
first in some regional, any regional.
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun said that this Big East tournament is important, but
that it really should have no bearing in where his team will be
seeded by a hidden committee in Kansas City on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   These Wizards of Odds employ their own official rating
percentage index that they decline to make public, which is why the
Collegiate Basketball News performs the vital public service of
using the same criteria for its own ratings. It currently projects
Duke to the East, Michigan State to the Midwest, Connecticut to the
West and Auburn to the South.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's done,'' Calhoun said, noting that Connecticut has
won 26 of 28, and has played two top teams, Stanford and Michigan
State _ ``plus winning the Big East against St. John's and Miami,
who could be Final Four teams, certainly.''
</P>
<P>
   Calhoun suggested that the wizards' minds already are made up,
and there is no point in confusing them with trivia like a
potential upset in the Big East tournament, which essentially
serves no purpose other than keeping people out of snow flurries in
early March.
</P>
<P>
   But while Connecticut was losing to Seton Hall, had Calhoun seen
his life _ at least his No. 1 seeding _ flashing before his eyes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think a 25-3 record, as lousy as it may be, would probably
qualify,'' Calhoun said, graciously noting that this was merely his
opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Then he speculated what could happen if Maryland ran the
Atlantic Coast Conference, forcing the wizards to reconsider Duke's
body of work for the entire season. Calhoun wanted logic to work
both ways, but as a man who has built a neat little dynasty in the
Big East, he's entitled.
</P>
<P>
   His players said they wanted a No. 1 seeding in a regional
``because that makes the whole field easier, you get to play a lot
of so-called weaker teams,'' as Khalid El-Amin said.
</P>
<P>
   What about avoiding Duke? ``Whatever the selection committee
does, we have to deal with it,'' said Ricky Moore.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with Duke in the Final Four would be fine with
Connecticut. The Teletubbies didn't make it to the tournament, once
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
