<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8388 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IOWA-POLITICS-2TAKES-     03-04 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IOWA-POLITICS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IOWA STILL THE PLACE TO GO FOR PRESIDENTIAL POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ Every four years, it seems, there is more
talk about Iowa's first-in-the-nation caucuses being a political
anachronism and a distortion of the presidential nominating
process.
</P>
<P>
   In today's America, the argument goes, the state is too bucolic
and too homogeneously white to be considered ``typical,'' and
therefore no longer qualifies as an ideal testing ground for
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   There is talk like that again now, 11 months from the 2000
caucuses scheduled for Feb. 7. But at the present rate that
declared and undeclared candidates are visiting Iowa, it appears
this year's complaints, like those of earlier years, are nothing
more than talk.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the recent headlong rush of many states to hold early
caucuses and primaries, to a man _ and woman _ the current White
House seekers are serving notice that as far as they are concerned,
Iowa's caucuses still stand, as they have for the past three
decades, as the first serious nominating hurdle to be cleared.
</P>
<P>
   A week later comes the equally traditional, equally challenging
and equally derided first-in-the-nation primary in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the current field of aspirants, including Vice President
Al Gore and the two leading Republicans, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas and Elizabeth Dole, the former head of the American Red
Cross, now have volunteers working Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   A few, like former Vice President Dan Quayle, have even advanced
to having paid staffs in place.
</P>
<P>
   But several, most notably Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., seem to be
slow off the mark in getting organized in the state, a shortcoming
that could be politically fatal if no action is taken by late
spring. Still, McCain himself drops in periodically.
</P>
<P>
   For that matter, every announced and potential candidate, except
Bush, has now showed up in the state at least once, and most many
times over.
</P>
<P>
   Former Sen. Bill Bradley of New Jersey, Gore's only challenger
thus far, flew in Monday for his fourth visit in five weeks,
working the streets and shops of Marshalltown, just northeast of
here, with folksy charm.
</P>
<P>
   He turns out to be a campaigner who, like Gore, is neither
telegenic nor able to pump up large crowds _ except, of course, in
the basketball arena _ but who nevertheless is a master of the
one-on-one ``retail'' politicking that counts most in down-home
states like Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, former Gov. Lamar Alexander of Tennessee
showed up in Des Moines for a banquet on Tuesday. It was more than
his 60th visit since his solid third-place finish in 1996, and the
talk is that he probably has the best campaign organization here at
this point.
</P>
<P>
   But, Republican leaders wonder if is it an organization that can
make him competitive with Bush and Mrs. Dole, given the large leads
they now have in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday another Republican, Pat Buchanan, the author and
pundit, came in for a news conference. It was Buchanan's very first
stop after announcing his third presidential candidacy the day
before in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   The message he carried was somewhat different from his pitch in
the 1996 Iowa caucuses, when he successfully captured enough of the
state's large Christian conservative vote to finish a surprisingly
strong second. This time around he is talking mainly about
agricultural policy, not abortion and moral decline.
</P>
<P>
   Come Friday, still another Republican, Rep. John R. Kasich of
Ohio, returns, ready to offer up his latest thoughts on taxes and
budgets during a four-day ``Rolling Through Iowa'' tour. Every stop
will be at a bowling alley, which is about as retail as it gets.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the other candidates who are in or still thinking
about getting in?
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Dole has made only one visit. But when she did, she packed
a 2,500-seat hall in Ames, a university town.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen a `potential' candidate draw like that,'' said
David Yepsen, the dean of Iowa political analysts, who has been
covering presidential caucuses for the Des Moines Register for more
than 25 years. ``The place was humming with enthusiasm for a new
face, not for Bob Dole's wife. A lot of it came from new people,
especially young people and women.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This merits close watching,'' Mr. Yepsen said, noting that a
candidate in a crowded field in Iowa can win a plurality with about
25,000.
</P>
<P>
   As for Bush, it now seems to be only a matter of time before he
shows up, though for a while there was considerable talk that he
never would, because he figured he could afford to skip Iowa. But
after Mrs. Dole entered the picture and a delegation of Iowans flew
to Austin, Tex., to speak with the governor, that talk died.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes, the publishing magnate who first sought the
Republican nomination four years ago, has been spending almost as
much time in Iowa as Alexander. In 1996 he made no real effort to
build a campaign organization here and relied mainly on a
television blitz that promoted his call for a flat tax and ripped
at other candidates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But this time around, he is building a campaign organization and
concentrating heavily on the Christian conservative vote, which is
at least a third of the Republican vote.
</P>
<P>
   Many Christian conservatives worry, however, about just how
strongly Forbes opposes abortion, their most heartfelt cause.
Equally troublesome for him is that every other Republican aspirant
is likely to pick up some of the Christian conservative vote, with
several candidates chasing as hard after it as Forbes is,
especially Gary Baue, former head of the Family Research Council;
Alan Keyes, the talk show host, and Sen. Bob Smith of New
Hampshire. Smith, with little fanfare, has spent the better part of
60 days over the past several years quietly working the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big as the Christian conservative vote is in Iowa, it's hard
to know what to expect from it in the caucuses if it gets shattered
into half a dozen or more small pieces,'' said Dee Stewart, the
executive director of the state's Republican Party. ``That might
leave room for some other candidate who is buried in the pack and
not dependent on that particular vote to suddenly do better than
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly what the Iowa caucuses are all about:
expectations met, expectations not met and expectations exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's what we do here in Iowa, our political assignment,'' said
Gov. Tom Vilsack, a Democrat who has vowed to defend Iowa's
first-caucus status against all challengers. ``We take the first
shot at winnowing the field. We build them up and tear them down.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0491 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-ART-     03-04 0792
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS ACTS TO ALTER RULES ON BANKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Mass.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Diminishing the chances that Congress will pass
major banking legislation this year, House and Senate committees
took action Thursday on sharply conflicting bills to eliminate
Depression-era barriers between banks, securities firms and
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers in the House completed most of the drafting of a bill
that has broad Democratic and Republican support and suggested that
the House of Representatives might be able to muster enough votes
from both parties to roll back the restrictions of the
Glass-Steagall and Bank Holding Company Acts. Those laws were
products of the nation's experiences of the 1930s, when many large
and small banks and securities firms collapsed.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate banking committee tempered expectations that the
106th Congress will be any different than other legislative bodies
in the last 20 years that were unable to repeal the legislation
because of rivalries among regulators and heavy lobbying by
competing industries. In an unusual twist for banking legislation,
it appeared this time around to be falling victim in the Senate to
bare-knuckled partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   More ideologically divided than at any time in recent history on
banking issues, the Senate banking committee passed a measure on an
11-9 party line vote.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton said on Wednesday that he would veto the
measure, and unless major compromises are reached _ a dim prospect
judging by Thursday's action _ there will be no new banking
legislation approved by Congress this year.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the effort against the administration is Sen. Phil
Gramm, the Texas Republican who heads the banking committee and
last year single-handedly derailed a hard-earned compromise bill
forged by Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., who was then heading the
banking committee.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, whose administration had expressed support for many of
the provisions in the House bill, earlier this week told Gramm that
he would veto the Senate measure because it would not do enough to
encourage lending to poor neighborhoods, protect bank customers who
also use those institutions to buy stocks and provide enough of a
role for the administration to regulate banks through the Treasury
Department.
</P>
<P>
   By structuring new super-banks that offer insurance and
securities underwriting under a holding company, the Senate
legislation also tilts toward giving more regulatory authority to
the Federal Reserve, as Alan Greenspan, its chairman, has sought.
The House measure, by contrast, puts merchant banking and
securities underwriting in operating subsidiaries, and as such,
would continue to provide a major regulatory role for the Treasury.
</P>
<P>
   The administration appears to be embarking on a strategy of
focusing on moving a bill through the House to try to build
pressure on Gramm to make compromises. In so doing, administration
officials still face a number of obstacles. Even if the legislation
is completed next week by the House banking committee, as expected,
it could be significantly rewritten in the House commerce
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Gramm on Thursday showed no sign that he was
interested in negotiating with the Democrats. Instead, he made his
legislation even less palatable to Democrats and the White House
when he got the committee on a largely partisan vote to amend it to
exempt small banks from the community lending laws. Those laws
require banks and savings associations to lend to the poor and
minorities in their neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of prayerful work has gone into this bill but not all
our prayers have been answered,'' Gramm said. ``One of those
prayers that has not been answered is a bipartisan effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats bristled at the confrontational approach Gramm
has undertaken as he begins his tenure as chairman of the banking
committee, a position that D'Amato was forced to relinquish by his
defeat last year by Charles Schumer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president has made it very clear he will veto this bill,''
said Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass. ``I'm not into Pyrrhic exercises. I'm
failing to understand why it is that we're here with a bill as
critical as this and yet we're at an impasse before we start.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm responded that he was more than willing to listen to any
ideas proposed by the members.
</P>
<P>
   ``But are you willing to change your bill?'' asked Kerry. The
question, which remains central to the issue of whether there will
be banking legislation, went unanswered Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
