<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PENTAGON-HACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENTAGON FOILS COMPUTER HACKERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Military security analysts uncovered and stopped
computer hackers who had discovered a new way to attack open
Pentagon networks on the Internet, Pentagon officials said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony before Congress last week, John Hamre, the deputy
secretary of defense, said in a closed-door hearing that this new
method had been uncovered by analysts at the Naval Surface Warfare
Center in Dahlgren, Va., Defense Department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The specialists at Dahlgren found a method to thwart those
low-level probes, which differ from the more frequent brutal
assaults on security systems, and alerted all the military services
to the new problem and a remedy for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are literally hundreds of attempts weekly to break into
the computers,'' a Pentagon spokesman said. ``It's constant because
there's a certain cachet to getting into the Pentagon system.''
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has estimated that 99.95 percent of computer
hackers fail to penetrate beyond the open networks, which contain
unclassified material, and so pose no national security concern.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable example of hackers using this new method
occurred in January when a military computer server near San
Antonio was probed for two days from foreign Web sites. These
probes reached only the open military networks connected to the
Internet and it was unclear whether the probes originated overseas
or were merely routed through those sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``These hackers try to cover their tracks by initiating the
intrusions through an overseas site that has nothing to do with
where the hackers actually are,'' the Pentagon spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, each armed service has installed new programs
to detect hackers and to protect sensitive material. As the number
of surveillance programs have increased, so has the number of
detections.
</P>
<P>
   These new military computer security officials have said they
are fighting a ``cyberwar.''
</P>
<P>
   ``To them it's a war, but it's like the war on crime or the war
on drugs _ it's the information security guys' war,'' said William
Arkin, author of ``The U.S. Military On Line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2242EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0496 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8400 &Cx1f; tab-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEMPLETON-SELF-CONTRO     03-04 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEMPLETON-SELF-CONTROL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLDWIDE LAWS OF LIFE:
 THE LAW OF RESPONSIBILITY SAYS `THE BUCK STOPS HERE' 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Sir John Templeton, the Tennessee-born billionaire and founder
of the Templeton funds, built his fortune on his legendary ability
to perceive value that others overlooked. In his column, he urges
us to recognize the value of spirituality in life.)
</P>
<P>
   (``Self-control leads to success.'' -- John M. Templeton)
</P>
<P>
   (To purchase this ``separate buy'' article from the New York
Times Syndicate please contact syndicate sales representative DEBRA
WEYDERT at 732-390-4480) &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; By JOHN M. TEMPLETON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. Templeton Foundation Press &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; Distributed by N.Y. Times Special Features &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes you may be tempted to think that life seems to be one
big muddle and doesn't make any sense at all. Well, there may be a
good reason for thinking that way.
</P>
<P>
   Let's look at an analogy. We could be very much like one who
goes to the theater after the curtain has gone up and the play has
been in progress for some time. The latecomer has no knowledge of
the beginning of the story, nor any idea of what the ending may be.
The script may not make sense, and the person may feel confused
regarding the plot of the story.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, in the drama of life, we may not always know or
understand the plot. Sometimes the script seems pointless. We may
fail to grasp the grand scope of the universal dramas in which we
may be participating.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, there could be an attempt to blame the
``director,'' the ``producer,'' perhaps even the playwright, for
the situation. However, in the universal drama of life, there are
no ``bit players.'' And there is no one to blame! Life can seem
less of a muddle if we read the script correctly and become aware
that we have unique qualities and can bring gifts to the ``show''
that no one else can give.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps you've heard the expression, ``the buck stops here.''
This saying is cousin to another one that is quite commonly used in
the United States, ``passing the buck.'' When a person is accused
of passing the buck, he may be said to be avoiding responsibility
and passing it on to someone else. When someone says, ``The buck
stops here,'' he infers that he will handle the matter himself and
take full responsibility for the outcome. Which one of these
expressions do you find yourself in the habit of using?
</P>
<P>
   You may know of someone at this moment in your life who may be
rebelling against unfairness of one sort or another. Perhaps you,
yourself, may be choosing to be antagonistic? Many people
throughout history have chosen to rebel against their government or
their society in order to bring about a higher purpose. Some may
have understood that the cost of their rebellion could be their
very lives; yet, they consented to pay that price. These people
have often assisted in making great changes for the benefit of the
people.
</P>
<P>
   If a student chooses to rebel against his parents, for example,
and as a result finds himself without a place to live or without
any money for college, he must be willing to accept this as the
cost of his rebellion. Likewise, it makes no sense to complain if
our employer cuts our pay when we have failed to do the work we
agreed to do. In that situation, we have received what we have
deserved, and we should learn to accept it without protest.
</P>
<P>
   One time at a county fair, a farmer exhibited a pumpkin grown in
the exact shape of a two-gallon jug. ``When it was no bigger than
my thumb,'' he said, ``I stuck it in the jug and just let it grow.
When it filled the jog, it quit growing.''
</P>
<P>
   What the glass jug did for the pumpkin, our thoughts do for our
life. We may grow as big, as mature, and become as creative as the
things we think about and believe in. But we stop growing at the
limit of our thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things we need to do is to banish the thoughts
that say the control of our life is held by another. We have a
built-in control tower called the faculty of free will, and nothing
can move into our mind unless we are willing to place the ``stamp
of approval'' on the delivery.
</P>
<P>
   The law of responsibility applies in every area of our lives.
For example, if we choose to abuse our bodies with drugs or
alcohol, it becomes imperative that we know the cost of this
decision. We must ask ourselves if the drugs and alcohol are worth
the cost in sickness and wasted time.
</P>
<P>
   One may ask the question, ``How can I take control over my life
when I am faced with such inner turmoil and confusion and my
problems are so large?'' One thing we can do at once is take the
same thought energy we have expressed in ``how can I take
control?'' and turn it around into the thought, ``I am one with the
wisdom of God; I know what to do, and I do it!''
</P>
<P>
   One of the best ways to exhibit the self-control that leads to
success is to know that faith, not fear; love, not hate; joy, not
sorrow; peace, not tension; freedom, not bondage is the role we
choose to play.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever we choose in terms of our behavior in this life, we
will be much better off if we can truly say, ``The buck stops here.
I am willing to pay the price for my decision. I am willing to
accept the consequences of my actions.''
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Excerpted from ``Worldwide Laws of Life'' by John Marks
Templeton. Published by Templeton Foundation Press)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2243EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0497 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8402 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-2TA     03-04 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ITALY, ALLURING IDEAS ARE BLOSSOMING 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By ANNE-MARIE SCHIRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ Designers, like many other people, often do their
best work under stress. When the fashion world turned away from the
precise tailoring Italy was known for, the country's designers
floundered for a moment, toying with American-style sportswear and
utility gear.
</P>
<P>
   But they now seem to be blossoming with ideas for more feminine,
more alluring ways of dressing. When you compete in a global
marketplace, you can't afford to stand still.
</P>
<P>
   Look at two of Italy's top stars _ Tom Ford of Gucci and Giorgio
Armani. They're both already on fashion's Mount Olympus, but you
won't catch them napping. They both forged ahead this week with
inspiring fall collections.
</P>
<P>
   If anyone should be under stress these days, it's Ford, whose
company is battling Bernard Arnault's powerful LVMH Moet Hennessy
Louis Vuitton, which is trying to take control of the Italian
house. The outcome may affect Ford's future at Gucci, but he didn't
let that cramp his design style.
</P>
<P>
   The collection he showed Tuesday night _ with his friends
Donatella and Santo Versace offering emotional support from the
front row _ was his most wide ranging to date. In the past, he's
settled on a theme, like the 1970s or glam rock, but this time he
let loose a cornucopia of ideas. Ford promised before the show that
it would go over the top, and it sometimes did.
</P>
<P>
   There were fabulous glossy leathers in flesh-toned beige, black
and bottle green, sometimes with vertical seams suggesting a stripe
and sometimes draped like fabric and adorned with a leather rose.
He updated the peasant blouse in black leather and softened the
sleeves on other pieces by adding fullness below the elbows.
</P>
<P>
   Some of his sexy bell-bottom pants, with their tight fit through
the thighs, were made even clingier with ruching borrowed from
Austrian window curtains. There were also ruched velvet tops and
knee-length skirts, club-ready beaded lace pants with thin ties
around the knees, and sheer wool tops gathered in front to
accentuate the breasts.
</P>
<P>
   The collection was varied enough to appeal both to women who
want to look sleek and to those who want to ooze sensuality, and
yet it was always unmistakably Gucci as reinvented by Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Armani's take on fashion is more sedate, but equally
imaginative. His front row on Wednesday evening included young
celebrities like Ashley Judd and Joaquin Phoenix as well as the
ageless Sophia Loren (whose entrance into the trendy Bice
restaurant the night before was greeted with applause).
</P>
<P>
   The man who defined an era with his universally imitated
broad-shouldered pants suits has moved with the times into soft,
hip-riding pants with elastic waists and languorous long skirts in
materials that float. These are topped with thin sweaters or clingy
T-shirts, or jackets stripped of lapels, padding and often buttons.
</P>
<P>
   In a collection that extends the meaning of the color gray even
for the gray-obsessed Armani, there are touches of cerulean blue
and apple green. Some jackets have diagonal slits that bare a
sliver of skin, and others have necklines or hemlines turned back
to reveal the colored lining.
</P>
<P>
   Armani's newest pants have a suggestion of draping around the
knees achieved by a few judicious stitches. Others have a row of
loose elastic around the hem that blouses them slightly. Although
this is a winter collection that includes speckled shearlings and
crocodile-patterned suedes, many fabrics are gossamer.
</P>
<P>
   Evening clothes in particular would be totally sheer if they
weren't covered with intricate beadwork patterns. And nothing
demonstrates better how Armani has dealt with the challenge of
changing tastes than those glorious evening dresses, which have
upped the glamour quotient at many an awards show.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty, rather than glamorous, is the word for Alberta
Ferretti's evening dresses, in colors like rose, wine, yellow,
cream or brown velvet forming geometric or mazelike patterns on
tulle. With high waistlines and uneven hems, the clothes have a
youthful femininity that was more ingenue than movie star.
</P>
<P>
   For daytime, Ms. Ferretti showed dresses and coats with high
waists tied with rickrack, and shearlings trimmed with multicolored
embroidery. She is one of the Italian designers who snuggle
comfortably and tastefully into fashion's current decorative mood.
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Berardi, a London-based designer who showed in Milan for
the first time this week, is on the opposite end of the sensibility
spectrum. He titled his collection ``Never Mind the Borgias,'' a
tipoff of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   In a churchlike space divided by heavy pillars, he set up a
cruciform runway covered with melted candle wax and centered by a
gigantic censer on a rope swung by an alb-clad ``acolyte.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Models, in elaborate wigs that burlesqued the coils and braids
of Renaissance hairdos, wore punk styles with multiple zippers or
silver studs, kilts with layers of pleats that dipped down to an
uneven hem, a long red turtleneck dress slit up to Naomi Campbell's
waist on one side, and skirts of delicate bobbin lace, as well as a
spectacular hand-painted white shearling coat over a dress in a
matching floral pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Berardi dared to offend by showing exaggerated versions of nuns'
head coverings and a priest's cassock outlined with flashing lights
in the shape of a cross. It was the kind of show that would look
more at home on a London catwalk than in Milan, but it added a jolt
of electricity _ and eccentricity _ to the week.
</P>
<P>
   Veronique Branquinho, who shows her signature collection in
Paris, designed the Ruffo Research line of leathers and shearlings
shown here Monday night in an old tram station. Raf Simons designed
the men's portion of the show. His contributions, except for the
tight pants and down-filled leather jackets, tended to be rather
classic, while hers were more imaginative.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Branquinho showed skirts made of alternating strips of shiny
leather and suede, pullovers and skirts of ultra-thin shearling
striped with bits of the fur side, her favorite Victorian-style
shirt interpreted in black leather, and a floor-length shearling
coat as narrow as a rail.
</P>
<P>
   John Bartlett's collection for Byblos was aimed at a racy young
woman who would wear a cropped leather jacket with jeans,
high-heeled sandals and a biker's shiny silver key chain draped
over her hip.
</P>
<P>
   There were also leather jackets with knitted sections, two-toned
T-shirts with curved shirttail hems, a charcoal cardigan with a
giant pink argyle on one side (to go with the argyle knee socks
teamed with high heels), and black dresses and skirts with a
sparkling band here or there.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were perfectly fine though lacking in the strong
signature of Bartlett's designs under his own label. But they were
certainly better than what Josephus Thimister served up in his
first collection for Genny (which, like Byblos, is owned by the
Girombelli group).
</P>
<P>
   The Genny styles were simply rehashes of clothes seen on other
runways in other years, and a great disappointment to those who
have admired Thimister's couture collections in Paris and expected
him to reinvigorate Genny. Maybe next time he'll get up his courage
and let loose.
</P>
<P>
   There's nothing uptight about Alessandro Dell'Acqua's collection
except the fit of some of the clothes, like the skinny leather
pants or the leather bustier worn with a ruffled chiffon bib and a
cream-colored chiffon skirt. He designs for a hip young woman with
an adventurous fashion streak, quite the opposite of Ferragamo's
customer, who finds contentment in luxury fabrics and beautiful
workmanship.
</P>
<P>
   Ferragamo's cashmeres, alpacas, satins and velvets are certainly
luxurious, and no one could fault the make of the double-faced
wools and reversible leathers. But umpteen versions of the kimono
jacket do not a collection make.
</P>
<P>
   It's tempting to say, ``Shoemaker, stick to your last'' to
Ferragamo, as well as to Bottega Veneta. The clothing of both
houses needs more pizazz, though Bottega Veneta did have one
inspired notion: double sweaters that reverse from featherweight
cashmere to airy mohair.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Max Mara and Sportmax lines cater to a customer who
wants fashion that is current but not too advanced, things that
this season mean tasteful embroidery and beadwork on casual styles
like sweaters and suede jackets, and knitted coats layered over
furs. The Max Mara company is one that has successfully weathered
the change from strict tailoring to feminine styles with a hint of
romance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
