<SLUG> BC-MONICA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INITIAL LEWINSKY BOOK SALES SLOW IN ARIZONA 
</HEADLINE>
 BOOK-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JULIE AMPARANO  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Throngs may have tuned in to watch Monica Lewinsky discuss her
affair with President Clinton on Wednesday, but the show wasn't
enough to send Valley viewers rushing to local bookstores to pick
up her memoir.
</P>
<P>
   Titled ``Monica's Story,'' the book mostly sat on the shelves of
Valley bookstores after being released Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw everything I needed to know last night on 20/20,'' said
Marina Martin, who was cruising the aisles at Barnes &AMP; Noble
Booksellers in southeast Phoenix. ``She didn't say anything that
made me want to buy her book.''
</P>
<P>
   ABC estimated that 74 million people watched the 20/20 segment
with Barbara Walters. The show was second only to the number of
people who watched the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research gave ABC's Wednesday night interview a
33.4 rating and 48 share, which means that just under half of the
nation's working television sets were tuned in.
</P>
<P>
   Lewinsky provided the most-watched interview since Oprah
Winfrey's prime-time questioning of Michael Jackson in 1993, which
had a 39.3 rating and 56 share.
</P>
<P>
   But Monica's performance at Valley bookstores was lackluster.
</P>
<P>
   By mid afternoon, B. Dalton in Westridge had only sold about
four, Bookstar in Central Phoenix touted seven and Barnes &AMP; Noble
in Ahwatukee had only one.
</P>
<P>
   Other stores, such as Waldenbooks, Borders and Brentano's
Bookstore, wouldn't release actual booksales, citing company policy
against revealing such information. But employees reported they
hadn't seen many people purchasing the book.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet and in Washington, D.C., however, Lewinsky's
book was being snapped up. The confessional was No. 1 on the
bookseller lists of Amazon.com and barnesandnoble.com., although
neither would say what that status meant in terms of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of those pop culture phenomenons,'' said Ben Boyd,
a spokesman for barnesandnoble.com. He said the book was selling
2.8 copies per minute for a few hours late Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, booksellers copiously took names and phone of
eager book buyers, promising to call as soon as a truck delivered
the books on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   In Arizona, many booksellers weren't deterred by the low demand
for Monica's book, which was a collaboration with Princess Diana
biographer Andrew Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Moreno, a supervisor at B. Dalton booksellers in the West
Valley hopes sales will pick up over the weekend. His store is
offering the $24.94 book at a 30 percent discount this week, a
routine discount for new books.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's early and people are working. But maybe after work today,
we'll get more sales,'' said Moreno, adding that they hold sold
about four copies of the biography.
</P>
<P>
   Added Mark Sutz, of Changing Hands bookstore in Tempe: ``We
think people are interested in reading about what she has to say.
That's why they watched her on T.V. You know she can say more in
the book than she could on T.V. There are unique legal barriers
that don't allow her to say certain things on television. But she
can talk about it in print.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(The Associated Press contributed to this article.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
