</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER SCOREBOARD OPERATOR LANGHAM SHARES LEAD AT DORAL
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Franklin Langham used to work at the Masters when he was
a teen-ager living in Thompson, Ga., 30 miles from Augusta. As a
scoreboard operator at the 16th green, Langham watched Seve
Ballesteros, Jack Nicklaus and other great players, while dreaming
of one day becoming a professional golfer.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it was Langham's turn to put his name on the leader
board. Shooting a five-under-par 67, including birdies on his final
two holes, Langham was in a four-way tie for first place after the
opening round of the Doral-Ryder Open. Langham shared the lead with
Tommy Armour 3rd, Bob Burns and Scott Dunlap. Of those four
players, only Armour has won a PGA Tour event, and his lone victory
came in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   While some of the field's more prominent names struggled at
Doral Golf Resort and Spa, Langham enjoyed his best round of the
year, taking advantage of calm afternoon conditions, after the
morning winds died down. Langham's best career finish on tour was a
tie for second place at last year's Deposit Guarantee Golf Classic.
But Langham tied for seventh last week in Tucson, and he carried
confidence and momentum into Thursday's round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have been hitting the ball well for a while,'' said Langham,
30, a University of Georgia graduate who finished 117th on last
year's money list. ``I just started making the putts you need to
play well, the 12- and 15-footers for birdies. I feel my game
starting to come around.''
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that marquee names were missing among the
leaders, because some of them were also missing from the
tournament. Tiger Woods and David Duval, both of whom played Doral
last year, decided to skip this week's tournament, fatigued from
playing a heavy West Coast schedule. Last week's Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship added a big money event to the
schedule, and many players who were in California last week decided
to pass on Doral.
</P>
<P>
   However, Langham is more worried about the strength of his game
than the strength of the field. And he realized he would still have
to play the best tournament of his career to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a player's standpoint, there are a lot of guys that can
play out here,'' Langham said. ``I guarantee if you look at the
winning score, it is going to be a good score. Maybe the depth of
field you might argue is not as deep. But golf is a funny sport.
You have 144 guys that are capable of playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Starting on the 10th tee Thursday, Langham birdied his first
hole with a 5-foot putt, then made a 30-footer for birdie at No.
12. After missing a 6-foot putt for bogey at No. 13, he rebounded
with a birdie at the par-3 No. 15, hitting a 7-iron tee shot to
within 4 feet of the cup, then making the putt. Langham followed
with a 15-foot putt for birdie at No. 16, and a 4-foot putt for
birdie at No. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Then after a bogey at No. 2, when he failed to get up and down
from a greenside bunker, Langham birdied No. 8 with a 6-foot putt,
and No. 9 with a 12-foot putt. If Langham wins at Doral, he will
qualify for the Masters. ``It would be a thrill to play there,''
Langham said. ``Hopefully one day I will. I am planning on it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
