<HEADER>
A8579 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLORIDA-DUKE-ENERGY05     03-04 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLORIDA-DUKE-ENERGY05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida OKs wholesale power unit
 &HT;    By Susan Spencer-Wendel
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ State officials cracked open the door to
Florida's strictly regulated electricity market Thursday, deciding
to allow Duke Energy of North Carolina to build the state's first
wholesale power plant.
</P>
<P>
   The five members of the Public Service Commission in Tallahassee
had split votes on many of the 33 issues they considered in their
decision, but in the end they supported Duke's plan to build a
natural gas-fed, 500-megawatt plant outside New Smyrna Beach. The
plant would sell power to other utilities, including those out of
state, on an as-needed basis.
</P>
<P>
   The plant is subject to the approval of the Florida Cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   With the decision, though, other utilities are expected to
pursue power plant projects of their own in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the start of new things to come. It's the first phase of
true competition,'' said Mike Bedley, president of APEX Power
Service, an energy consulting firm based in Fort Lauderdale.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Duke will foot the bill for the $160 million plant
_ unlike established Florida utilities that charge ratepayers for
the plant's cost _ was one of the project's selling points for PSC
Chairman Joe Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a vote to be competitive,'' Garcia said. ``There will be
cheaper power to draw from . . . and that's good for Florida.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's big investor-owned utilities, Juno Beach-based
Florida Power &AMP; Light and St. Petersburg-based Florida Progress,
vigorously opposed the idea. FPL argued that the region already has
some of the lowest electric rates in the country and that it
planned to spend $2 billion during the next decade to build plants
to meet the state's power needs.
</P>
<P>
   And while it argued against a wholesale power plant in Florida,
another FPL Group subsidiary, FPL Energy, has moved in on
deregulated markets in other states and is building wholesale
plants of its own in Texas and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   FPL spokesman Bill Swank said the company will appeal the PSC
decision.
</P>
<P>
   If approved, Duke's plant would sell about 30 percent of its
capacity to New Smyrna Beach. The rest would be sold into the
wholesale market. The company hopes to have the plant completed by
the summer of 2001, said Mike Greene, Duke's vice president for
Florida operations.
</P>
<P>
   While the PSC approved the project, commissioners expressed
concern about not letting just anyone who feels like building a
power plant into the state. Commissioners talked about working out
guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to develop policy so we don't allow plants to build
willy-nilly,'' said Commissioner Susan Clark.
</P>
<P>
   But to some observers, that process seems backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``They opened the floodgates. It's too late,'' said utilities
attorney Phillip Gildan of Greenberg Traurig in West Palm Beach.
``They're going to have a tough time saying no to the next
applicant.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-03-04-99 2320EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
