<SLUG> BC-CHARGE-DROPPED05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fla. state attorney drops retarded teen's $2 theft charge
 &HT;    By John Holland
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Facing a wealth of bad publicity over a
$2 theft, State Attorney Barry Krischer dropped all charges against
a 15-year-old mentally retarded boy Thursday as local and national
scrutiny intensified.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Laster, who has an IQ of 58 and no criminal history, was
arrested Dec. 1 and charged with strong-armed robbery for snatching
$2 out of a classmate's pocket. He spent the next seven weeks,
including Christmas, behind bars after Krischer decided to charge
the Boynton Beach boy as an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer has staunchly defended his position, even as criticism
mounted from local lawyers, child advocates, voters and the media.
But Thursday, with a camera crew from 60 Minutes and local
reporters jammed into court, the state attorney reversed course.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Krischer drop the adult robbery and battery
charges, he decided not to recharge Laster as a juvenile. In a
formal court filing notable for both its length and defensive tone,
a prosecutor said the victim's testimony changed during a
deposition on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although there was probable cause for the arrest and direct
filing of this case,'' prosecutor Angela Miller wrote, it was
dropped because ``the deposition of the child victim (makes) the
further prosecution of the robbery charge no longer viable.''
</P>
<P>
   The filing also said Laster's arrest and jail time may actually
help him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This direct filing has brought about community interest in
providing services to this defendant, including but not limited to
the Association for Retarded Citizens and the Urban League . . .
.''
</P>
<P>
   Laster's mother died less than a month before the arrest. He
never knew his father, and his grandfather, who helped raise him,
died in May. His sister, Carolyn, is now caring for him.
</P>
<P>
   She spent Laster's entire $500 inheritance on a $5,000 bond to
free him, said attorney John Walsh of the Palm Beach County Legal
Aid Society, which filed motions to move the case to juvenile
court. The $500 will not be returned. Carolyn Laster did not return
phone calls Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think this case shows (prosecutors) were wrong,'' Walsh
said. ``Looking back, it should have been handled by the principal
and the school. The family and Anthony went through a lot during
those seven weeks, and we're happy it's finally over.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress Middle School Principal Steve Sills referred questions
to Krischer.
</P>
<P>
   Krischer has maintained a strict policy that all juveniles 14 or
older accused of violent crimes would be charged as adults and said
he sees no reason to deviate. It's up to the judges whether to
punish the defendants as juveniles or adults, he said, adding only
those in the most extreme cases face convictions as adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a set-in-stone policy, and it would be ethically and
legally wrong to change on a case-by-case basis,'' said Mike
Edmondson, Krischer's spokesman. ``The intent of filing juvenile
cases in adult courts is to give them a wake-up call before they go
down the road and eventually wind up in prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an attack at school, and we are not going to tolerate
that,'' Edmondson said. ``Children have the right to be safe. Our
policy is the right one, and it has worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The victim's father, whose son attends special education classes
with Laster, supported Krischer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not upset with Anthony _ he's a bully, but there are a lot
of bullies,'' the father said. ``What's really bad is there are
kids doing a lot worse at this middle school, and that has to stop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry Krischer is just sending a message, a warning, to the
other kids that they're going to jail if they start beating up and
abusing kids.''
</P>
<P>
   the father said. ``This may not be the strongest case, but it's
the right message.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
