<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ISLES-STARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLES LET STARS SLIP AWAY FROM THEM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNIONDALE, N.Y._ There has been a recurring theme on Long Island
recently. The New York Islanders play solidly against a good team,
Thursday night the Dallas Stars, and they either don't know how to
finish them off or simply can't. Bill Stewart, the Islanders'
coach, says his team lacks ``killer instinct.''
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders had the NHL's top team staggering Thursday night,
outshooting the Stars by 10-5 in the third period. But the
Islanders repeatedly failed to net those scoring chances and wound
up losing 3-2 in overtime on Joe Nieuwendyk's goal with 48 seconds
left before 9,566 fans at Nassau Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk deflected Derian Hatcher's shot from the point over
Tommy Salo, the Islanders' goaltender, who was screened. The
Islanders were outshot, 6-1, in the extra session.
</P>
<P>
   Zigmund Palffy scored both goals for the Islanders. David Reid,
Mike Modano and Nieuwendyk scored for Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders had their chances late in regulation. Early in the
third period, they got their first opportunity to steal a victory,
in the form of a 2-on-1 rush. Claude Lapointe, flanked by Sergei
Nemchinov, carried the puck into Dallas' zone.. But Nemchinov
couldn't handle Lapointe's cross-ice pass, although Roman Turek,
the Stars' goalie, would have been beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the third period, Lapointe had a breakaway but was poke
checked by Turek before getting a chance to shoot.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders were up against the NHL's best Thursday night. The
Stars, who were coming off of Tuesday's 2-2 tie against the Rangers
at Madison Square Garden, entered the game with the most victories
(38) and fewest losses (11). Dallas had twice as many victories as
the Islanders before Thursday night's face off.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders outworked the Stars early in the game and managed
to escape the first period with the score tied at 1-1. New York
outshot Dallas 11-7 during the opening 20 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas got the game's first goal from Reid at 3:27 on a
redirection of a shot by Mike Keane. Skating through the middle as
Keane fired a sharp angle shot from the corner, Reid jabbed his
stick at the puck, tipping it over Salo's glove.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders came back on a power-play goal, scored by Palffy
at 18:29. After two unsuccessful swipes at the puck by Trevor
Linden and three more by Robert Reichel, Palffy finally buried it.
</P>
<P>
   In the second period, the Islanders took an early 2-1 lead, but
the Stars evened matters.
</P>
<P>
   Palffy's second goal of the game put the Islanders ahead at
6:46. He was in the right place at the right time, coming out of
the penalty box when the puck hopped over the stick of Stars
defenseman Richard Matvichuk and through center ice. Palffy picked
up the errant pass and skated in on Turek. Palffy went forehand,
backhand and forehand again before shooting the puck over Turek.
</P>
<P>
   Modano's goal at 17:05 tied the game at 2-2. Modano redirected a
shot by Hatcher from the point past Salo.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
