A8591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRFORCE-LABCUTS05-CO     03-04 1113
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-LABCUTS05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air Force cuts loom large in research division
 &HT;    By Scott Montgomery
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Wright-Patterson Air Force Base will lose 474
civilian jobs beginning in October from a combination of previously
announced management changes and the Air Force's recent decision to
heavily emphasize space programs over other types of research,
officials announced late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A broad array of positions will be eliminated, but the largest
chunk _ 163 _ will come out of the Air Force Research Laboratory
headquartered at the base, even though the lab cuts are the result
of an Air Force budget that's still being hotly contested on
Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   In the spending plan the Air Force submitted to Congress in
February, two enormous space-based programs, a laser and a radar,
were moved into the service's Science and Technology budget. But no
extra money was added to pay for them, so other projects were
slashed to make room.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress is only in the early stages of its budget hearing
process, and has the authority to rewrite the Air Force priority
list. As late as Wednesday, some on Capitol Hill were hoping the
Air Force would postpone an announcement on laboratory job cuts,
since the budget that dictates them is months from being finalized.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Miami Valley congressional delegation, joined by
congressmen from other states with military research facilities,
have furiously exchanged letters of warning with the Pentagon about
the strategic danger of draining scientific research accounts in
the 2000 budget.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters on Thursday
acknowledged the pressure Congress has exerted in recent weeks, but
suggested that doesn't change the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody's actually shown me where the extra money would come
from,'' Peters said. ``There are some pieces of this we wouldn't
mind buying back.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Tony Hall, D-Dayton, sees it a little differently.
With so much unified opposition to the assault on Science and
Research accounts, he said he thinks Congress will find a way to
save some lost research programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year the Ohio delegation was successful in restoring cuts
in materials research,,'' Hall said. ``Working together I believe
we can add back money for some of the highest priority science
programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Dan Curtis, who is vice president of the Miami Valley Economic
Development Coalition, hopes Hall is right. The high-tech, high
education jobs at the research lab are precisely the kinds of jobs
that make bolster the Miami Valley's claim to having a kind of
military brain trust around which to build commercial high-tech
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Air Force appears to be suggesting cuts prior to
congressional consideration of the president's budget,'' Curtis
said. ``That seems a bit premature.''
</P>
<P>
   The cuts were announced in conjunction with the unveiling of a
vast redrawing of the Air Force combat structure. Last August, the
Air Force announced plans to create 10 Air Expeditionary Forces
that will be comprised of units on different bases across the
globe, with each AEF taking its turn on 15-month deployment duty.
Thursday, the Air Force revealed the details of the new structure,
which is designed to give more military units longer rest periods
and more predictable deployment schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Officials couldn't say Thursday evening how many of the 474 job
losses at Wright-Pat were for positions that are currently
unfilled, and in the process of restructuring its combat forces the
Air Force will boost its military personnel at Wright-Pat by 33
under the program just announced.
</P>
<P>
   The additions come in the 88th Communications Squadron, which
will pick up 14 military spots, and the National Air Intelligence
Center and 694th Intelligence Group, which adds 45 military
positions to its payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The other job losses come from across the base spectrum. The Air
Force Institute of Technology, which just last year seemed headed
for complete destruction, will lose 15 military and seven civilian
positions as part of the compromise brokered last spring to keep it
alive.
</P>
<P>
   Air Force Materiel Command, headquartered at Wright-Pat, will
lose 41 military and 74 civilian positions as part of the
Pentagon's continuing effort to wither administrative command posts
in favor of beefing up field operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Aeronautical Systems Center will lose 7 military and 93
civilian jobs as a result of decreased workloads in the Foreign
Military Sales Program. The acquisition work force, which has been
another favorite target of Pentagon budget snippers and is a
mainstay of Wright-Pat's payroll, is scheduled to lose 13 military
and 114 civilian positions.
</P>
<P>
   But even Air Force leaders have admitted they use a broad
definition of ``acquisition'' workers that includes research
laboratory personnel and others not directly involved in Air Force
procurement programs. It was not clear Thursday night how many of
those being cut from as part of the Pentagon squeeze on acquisition
payrolls are truly acquistion-specific workers at Wright-Pat.
</P>
<P>
   For Curtis, that almost doesn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first concern,'' Curtis said, ``is that Wright-Pat seems
to be the bank for personnel cuts, taking more than its fair
share.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, hundreds of jobs of been siphoned away during
the military's extensive draw down, which has put a premium on
combat-immediate positions and let the support work of places such
as Wright-Pat take the brunt of overall reductions.
</P>
<P>
   But it's Wright-Pat's bread-and-butter science jobs that will be
the most painful to lose.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's the immediate economic impact,'' Curtis said, ``then
there's the loss of intellectual capital, which is a little hard to
measure. But then, if you begin to lose critical mass in certain
that's an economic concern for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's precisely the argument Hall and others on Capitol
Hill want to wage with the Air Force: that by abandoning basic
research programs now, the Air Force will cut its way out of the
innovation business and lose the technological superiority it has
enjoyed for decades.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Sen. Mike DeWine, R-Ohio, who has been a chief
correspondent in recent letters to the Pentagon complaining about
the loss of science money, said he fears the Air Force isn't
considering the long term effect of its budget cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would lose not just good people, but unequaled expertise,''
he said. ``You cannot restore lost expertise overnight. ``It takes
time to build and develop this military brainpower.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
