<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-HORNETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW UGLY CAN IT GET? DON'T ASK THE NETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ It is official. The players, the fans,
the analysts and whoever else predicted success for this season's
Nets were deluded.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets are simply a weak basketball team. What else do you
call a collection of players that lets one of the lowliest teams in
the National Basketball Association strut into its house and whip
it?
</P>
<P>
   The Charlotte Hornets _ who entered with a 3-10 record, with its
stars Glen Rice and Anthony Mason on the injured list, with
haggardly, Chuck Person, 34, starting at small forward _ beat the
Nets, 96-82. Do not be fooled by the score. This game was never
that close.
</P>
<P>
   But the loss might not be the worst news for the Nets, who sank
to 3-12. Jayson Williams, who had played all season with ligament
damage in his left thumb, injured the thumb badly in the second
quarter. He was taken to a hospital at halftime and did not play in
the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The injury probably occurred when the former Net Derrick Coleman
dunked ferociously on Williams 3 minutes 27 seconds before
intermission to put Charlotte ahead by 50-39.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets, who were crushed last week by the lifeless Chicago
Bulls, put the Nets in a 17-point hole after just 6:58 of the
opening quarter. They increased that to 25 in the third quarter
before the Nets tried to charge in the end.
</P>
<P>
   Person was Charlotte's unlikely leader, scoring 21 points while
hitting five of seven 3-pointers. Bobby Phills followed with 20
points. The Hornets made 10 of 22 3-pointers. The Nets, looking
pitiful despite playing in their new and fashionable gray
sleeveless uniforms, were led by Keith Van Horn's 28 points. Kerry
Kittles added 17.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets started by taking a 7-5 lead on a 3-pointer by Kittles,
then collapsed like a house of cards. Making Person and Phills look
like two of the NBA's finest, the Nets were outscored by 22-3 over
the next five minutes as the Hornets took a 27-10 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the run took place against Coach John Calipari's
much-anticipated big lineup, which he had talked about after
Tuesday's loss to Milwaukee. With his club trailing by 10-7,
Calipari inserted forward Chris Gatling for point guard Eric
Murdock, giving him Kittles, Kendall Gill, Van Horn, Gatling and
Williams on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly Charlotte, a small, but not necessarily fast, team,
turned into the sprinting Minnesota Timberwolves. Hitting layups
and dunks while running and 3-pointers while setting up, they
outscored the Nets by 17-3 before Calipari went back to a smaller
lineup less than four minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Phills, who scored Charlotte's first 8 points, started the spurt
with a 3-pointer before Person began asserting himself. Making the
Nets pay dearly for their molasses-slow rotations, Person nailed
four 3-pointers during the opening period, including three during
the overwhelming run, to finish with 14 first-quarter points.
</P>
<P>
   Person's shooting was no surprise; the 12-year veteran has
always been able to stroke it. But the first 12 minutes were so
lopsided that the notoriously one-dimensional player dazzled in
other areas. Moments after sinking his first 3-pointer, he tossed a
nice alley-oop pass to a rising Coleman, who dunked it with
authority.
</P>
<P>
   The carefree play was a sign of things to come, as David Wesley
felt comfortable enough to give an underhand pass to Phills for a
fastbreak dunk less than two minutes later.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, after falling behind by 27-10, the Nets showed some
pride and ended the quarter with a 12-6 run to pull to within
33-22. The Hornets, making six of seven 3-pointers, shot 68 percent
in the first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   An angry Van Horn scored 10 second-quarter points to spark a
Nets rally that pulled them to within 50-45 just 1:47 before the
half, but Charlotte scored 8 of the next 10 points to lead by 58-45
at the break. The Hornets were so charmed that Brad Miller, a
6-foot-11-inch rookie from Purdue, nailed a 27-footer at the
halftime buzzer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
