<HEADER>
A8596 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DAKOTA-LAND:GIAGO-NEW     03-04 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAKOTA-LAND:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL ABOUT THE DAKOTA, THE LAKOTA AND THE SIOUX
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By TIM GIAGO 
 &HT;    (Tim Giago, Lakota Indian, is the publisher of Lakota Times
Publishing, Inc., a book publishing company located in Sioux Falls,
S.D. His Indian name is Nanwica Kciji.) 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    SIOUX FALLS, S. D. _ The state of South Dakota is divided by the
Missouri River. We have a North and South Dakota. But there are
those who believe we should have an East and West Dakota. The
people living on opposite sides of the river are oftentimes quite
different.
 &HT;    Dakota Territory was named after the Indian people first
encountered by the early explorers. The people they met called
themselves Dakota. If the settlers had come from the west instead
of the east, the first people they met would have Lakota. We would
then have had Lakota Territory which would have become North and
South Lakota.
 &HT;    It's a matter of dialect. The people (Oyate) living in the
western part of the territory spoke Lakota. The people in the east
spoke Dakota. The Lakota, or Titonwan (``People of the Prairie'')
called Teton by early Canadians and Americans, consisted of the
Oglala (Crazy Horse and Red Cloud were Oglala), Brule or Rosebud
(Spotted Tail), Hunkpapa (Sitting Bull), Miniconju, Sans Arc and
Two Kettle (Cheyenne River). All spoke Lakota.
 &HT;    A Lakota said ``Hau kola,'' or ``Hello friend.'' A Dakota said
``Hau koda.'' Where a Lakota used an ``L'' a Dakota used a ``D.''
We (Lakota) joke amongst ourselves saying, ``When a Lakota man is
enamored of a maiden he says `I love you.''' A Dakota man says `I
dove you.'''
 &HT;    So, even thousands of years ago the river that split the state
also divided a people. East of the river were the Mdewakanton
(``People of Spirit Lake''), Wahpekute (``The Leaf Shooters''),
Wahpeton (``The People on Lake Traversie''), and the Sisitonwanna,
or Sisseton (``People of the Marsh''). Combined, all of these
tribes were called the Santee just as the tribes of the west were
called the Teton.
 &HT;    In the east were also the Ihanktonwan, or Yankton (``People of
the End''), and the Ihanktonwanna, or Yanktonai (``The Little
Yankton''). The people of these tribes, though still a part of what
later became the Great Sioux Nation, spoke with an ``N'' dialect.
For ``friend'' they would say ``kona.'' All of the tribes mentioned
were later called ``Sioux'' by the white settlers.
 &HT;    Sioux was a word first used by the French fur trappers. They
took two words from the Algonquin language, nadowe (snake) and
sioux (little) and used this name which was popular among the
Ojibwa (Chippewa), enemies of the Sioux. The name means ``Little
Snake.''
 &HT;    As the late Enos Poor Bear, former president of the Oglala Sioux
Tribe, (a Lakota man who always referred to himself as ``Sioux'')
said, ``Maybe the name given us _ Sioux _ was meant to be
derogatory, but we became such fierce warriors that our enemies
trembled in their shoes or moccasins when they heard the ``Sioux''
were coming. Pretty soon the word Sioux was spoken with pride by
our people and with fear by our enemies.''
 &HT;    The Big Sioux River flows through the heart of Sioux Falls. The
majestic falls at its center gives the city its name, ``Sioux
Falls.'' If the name ``Sioux'' is a misnomer then it stands to
reason that the river would have been called the Big Dakota River
and the city would have been Dakota Falls if the early settlers
were linguistically and historically correct.
 &HT;    When the national elections roll around the people of East River
(as opposed to West River) control the votes because of their much
larger population base. Politically, the folks of East River are
just a little more liberal than those of the West River. To the
Indian people this translates into a lot less prejudiced.
 &HT;    On weekends, particularly long ones, the city of Sioux Falls has
a dramatic increase in its Indian population because many Indians
travel from the larger reservations west of the river to shop and
seek entertainment in this larger, erroneously named city.
 &HT;    I have been on sabbatical since the beginning of the year. After
selling the newspaper I began 18 years ago, Indian County Today,
and moving from Rapid City to Sioux Falls _ it's great to be back.
 &HT;    East of the river is good.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 Tim Giago 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
