<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990304.0516 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-03-04 23:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8601 &Cx1f; tab-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARRANGED-MARRIAGES-NE     03-04 1402
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARRANGED-MARRIAGES-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``THE LOVE WILL GROW''
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' is from this week's New America News
Service.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into ``k''
commentary, ``l'' lifestyle and ``a'' general news files.) 
 By PRADNYA JOSHI 
 c. 1999 A. Magazine 
 New America News Service 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Marriage. Just the sound of the word used to make me shudder.
The very thought of changing the life I've been struggling to build
for myself, the thought of doing it again with somebody else. It's
yet another huge endeavor.
 &HT;    And I'm sure that I will never be able to recognize THE time
when I'm actually ready. But after the last two years of living
alone in a large metropolis, I'm beginning to feel pangs of
loneliness that the company of my friends can't quite alleviate.
 &HT;    Despite this realization, I still continue to duck the ``big
talk'' with my parents. But on the day of my 27th birthday, my
mother put her heel (if not her entire foot) down on the matter.
There was no easy way out, and we were going to have a serious
heart-to-heart about the big ``A-word.''
 &HT;    ``So what is so wrong with an arranged marriage?'' my mother
wants to know.
 &HT;    I know I'm not alone in this. There are many second-generation
Indian Americans who find that the question travels across the seas
to perch persistently on their doorsteps _ so long as the parents
``believe.'' I'm not here to demonize the practice. I'm just saying
that it isn't for me.
 &HT;    ``It's just like interviewing someone for a job,'' pleads my
mother incessantly. ``You receive the resumes, you interview the
candidates, and then you pick one. Your company does that all the
time!''
 &HT;    And, she adds as she cites the latest figures on American
divorce rates, there is no guarantee that a marriage founded on
love is forever anyway.
 &HT;    My mother, a highly educated and competent woman, is also a
woman caught up in some old-world paranoia. She's not alone in
believing that here in the United States, there is usually
dishonesty lurking behind every bush and that risking her daughters
to the promiscuous ways of American society is beyond justifiable.
 &HT;    On that particular subject though, I like to think I know a
little better. I've always felt secure in my judgment of people's
characters and kept alive the hope that the
friendship-to-dates-to-love-to-marriage method will ensure a secure
``forever'' union.
 &HT;    But to be fair, I do find some intrigue in the centuries-old
tradition. I can fashion myself as a female Pygmalion carving out a
partner with qualities that are comparable with mine, while my
parents emulate Aphrodite by bringing such a person to life. And,
honestly, there are also times when I fancy that such a path would
also be much less painful than the Western way to which I so
stubbornly cling.
 &HT;    So I've been flirting with a combination of the here and there
by dating Indian-American-style. This incorporates a method whereby
Indian parents place a guantity of taboos on their children's
lifestyles, thus offering an entirely unique dimension to an
already angst-filled process.
 &HT;    The typical Indian American ``date,'' you see, usually doesn't
involve the romantically wined and dined evenings. Rather, we tend
to play a game of 20 Questions while out as `friends.' Within a few
short hours, we drill out everything from favorite colors to
summaries of where each wants to be in the next two decades and the
game plan for getting there _ this and more while both parties are
clearly sizing one another up without ever admitting it. Painful.
 &HT;    So, what about hitting the singles bars? I'd have to say that
I'm already weary of the scene. And unlike some of my ``magnetic''
girlfriends, strange men seldom approach me with one-liners that
compare my eyes to ocean waves as they hand me their phone numbers.
 &HT;    But that's just the initial meeting. The actual date,
American-style, is a dance of its own without manual or manuscript.
Sure, some of my friends have referred to the dating bible so
coolly titled ``The Rules,'' but the tome is hardly an accurate
guide for a generation of women who've been raised on the spunk of
Princess Leia rather than the purr of Donna Reed. I've also heard
of more contemporary versions like ``What Men Want,'' which also
purports to assist one's trek through the dating jungle.
 &HT;    But the only real truths I've discovered so far come from the
humor of Dave Barry's ``Complete Guide to Guys,'' where Dave so
cleverly compares the male mind with that of some four-legged
friends. So with Dave's insight at hand, I continue venturing out
into the world of girl-meets-boy.
 &HT;    But for me, dating a man with Western mores brings its own woes.
Case in point: Once, over dinner, I told a dashing young man that I
volunteer at an organization that assists women from violent homes.
In response he asked me whether I considered myself a
``man-hater.'' Now, would a nice Indian boy have been so insolent?
 &HT;    Questions like that actually lead me to reconsider arranged
marriages. What my parents have in mind, after all, is for the good
of everybody in the family. In their eyes, the suitable mate would
be an upstanding young man with a solid education, coming from a
good family. He would also have the same ethnic, linguistic and, of
course, religious background as mine.
 &HT;    To find a suitable match old-world-style entails a complicated
system of collecting curriculum vitaes and resumes, which list
attributes such as occupation, education, build, parents'
backgrounds and _ for some _ caste and sub-caste. And this list is
by no means exhaustive. On the home front, the collected bio-data
on important traits are carefully weighed out while the parents
chat with other Indian parents for the ``real scoop'' beyond what
is in writing. I guess you can say that this is less superficial
than sizing someone up at a party. At least it is straightforward.
No confusion about motives here. And ultimately, this route just
might be a much easier one to navigate than the conventional
Western ways of pairing up.
 &HT;    I may also be too much of a pragmatic to ever fully believe that
a good marriage is based purely on passion and allure. A foundation
for a lasting relationship must include an understanding of one's
roots.
 &HT;    In my case, it is important to me that I marry a
second-generation Indian American. So far that has been the easy
part. But I have less than a stellar track record in finding
someone who is otherwise ``my type.'' I've always believed in
certain Indian traditions (like karma, for example), so it surely
wouldn't be such a leap to believe that it is my parents who will
ultimately tie my destiny in marriage.
 &HT;    Perhaps the men in the game have the right idea. Some Indian
American men I know see arranged marriage as a convenient fall-back
option; if they don't find someone they love, at least they can ask
for someone they can tolerate. For women though, the entire affair
still carries the stigma of resignation to a life of subservience
and can serve as a painful reminder of women's roles in a
patriarchal world.
 &HT;    No one ever promised me the glass-slipper version of life. But
in the end, I'm still hoping that maybe, just maybe, I'll find
Prince Charming, fall in love and live happily ever after _ without
first asking for his picture and resume.
 &HT;    
 c. 1999 A. Magazine 
<TEXT>
 &UR; NEW AMERICA NEWS SERVICE &QC; 
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &QC;
<P>
   &QL; 
 &UR; -0- &QL; 
 &UR; (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448; fax:
816-822-1444.) &QL; 
 &UR; (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) &QL;
</P>
