<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 (These ``separate buy'' articles from this week's New America News
Service moved today.) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish a NEWAM article, it must be purchased _
the rate is not prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales
representative CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448; fax: 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to the New America
News Service, a weekly diversity package of stories by and about
ethnic minorities, gays, women and disabled Americans.) 
 New America News Service 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FINDING THE COURAGE TO CONFRONT BLACKNESS. What is the essence
of being a black male in America, in a nation that has criminalized
black male masculinity, that perceives them as exotic outsiders?
ponders columnist Bill Maxwell. ``Perhaps I have been too afraid to
confront blackness _ my own in particular _ in all of its contours
and nuances, too afraid to look inside the recesses where simple
truths are more frightening than the vast unknown,'' he writes.
``But, to understand U.S. culture at all, we need to understand
blackness.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-FACING-BLACKNESS:MAXWELL-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   ALL ABOUT THE DAKOTA, THE LAKOTA AND THE SIOUX. The state of
South Dakota is divided by the Missouri River. There is a North and
South Dakota. But there are those who believe we should have an
East and West Dakota, suggests columnist Tim giago. The people
living on opposite sides of the river, he says, are oftentimes
quite different. Dakota Territory was named after the Indian people
first encountered by the early explorers. The people they met
called themselves Dakota. ``If the settlers had come from the west
instead of the east, the first people they met would have been
Lakota,'' Giago writes. ``Then we would have had a North and South
Lakota.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-DAKOTA-LAND:GIAGO-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary and ``a'' general news files.
</P>
<P>
   GRIEF MAY FADE, BUT IT NEVER GOES AWAY. From the moment her
father's call came, forever dividing time in two _ `before' and
`after' her sister Sonja died _ columnist Kirsten Chapman fell into
a barren land. Plucked from her life, she plummeted downward, like
Alice, into another, she recalls. ``With Sonja, we hadn't had time
for a farewell, hadn't talked of her being ill _ much less close to
death. So I set about giving a long goodbye, not just to her but to
the part of me that died with her,'' she writes. ``I cannot say
when I took the first step back, nor how long the trip lasted. I
know only that I had to pass through grief's wintry door.''
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-GRIEVING-LOST-SISTER:CHAPMAN-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in
``k'' commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
<P>
   ``THE LOVE WILL GROW.'' When it comes time to marry, should one
speed up on the dating track, or would an arranged marriage be the
best route? This is the question that Indian American women have to
decide when contemplating wedded union. Pradna Joshi in A. Magazine
gives her spin on the process. ``There are many second-generation
Indian Americans who find that the arranged marriage question
travels across the seas to perch persistently on their doorsteps,''
she writes. She however, is not entirely convinced by either course
of action. But secretly, she hopes love will win the debate in her
own case.
</P>
<P>
   Moved as BC-ARRANGED-MARRIAGES-NEWAMERICA-NYTSF in ``k''
commentary, ``a'' general news and ``l'' lifestyle files.
</P>
