<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS CONTINUE THEIR PLAYOFF PUSH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Teams like the New York Rangers and the Washington
Capitals, which might not make the Stanley Cup playoffs but still
have a chance to qualify, tend to play in postseason mode during
the last quarter of the regular schedule. That is the way they
competed Thursday night at the MCI Center, and the Rangers came
from behind late to emerge with a dramatic 4-2 victory over
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict moved the Rangers into a tie with Florida for ninth
place in the Eastern Conference, only two points behind the Boston
Bruins, who hold the eighth and final playoff berth in the Eastern
Conference, with 20 games to go. The Rangers have a four-game
undefeated streak and are 6-2-1 in their last nine. They are two
games below .500 and seem to be gaining momentum even with four key
players out with injuries: Wayne Gretzky, Todd Harvey, Petr Popovic
and Jeff Beukeboom.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Knuble scored two goals for the Rangers, who tallied three
goals in the final five minutes after they were behind by 2-1. Adam
Graves and Niklas Sundstrom got the others, with Graves getting
what amounted to the game-winner on a rebound 3 minutes 32 seconds
from the end of the third period. Graves pounced upon a loose puck
after Peter Nedved's shot was knocked down by the hand of
Washington defenseman Ken Klee. It was Graves' 31st goal of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Checking was tight and effort evident throughout. Petr Bondra
gave Washington a 2-1 lead at 9:03 of the third period on a
power-play goal with nine seconds remaining in a penalty to Ulf
Samuelsson. Mike Richter, the Ranger goalie, stopped the original
shot by Sergei Gonchar. But neither Richter nor his defense was
able to control the rebound, which Bondra knocked in from short
range for his 30th goal of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But Knuble tied it at 15:31 with a slap shot from the right-wing
circle after Brian Leetch created the chance with skating and
passing from the neutral zone. Graves then untied it for good.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers went into the game with the third-best penalty
killing record in the National Hockey League. They played well
while short handed for most of the first two periods Thursday
night, killing off six minutes of disadvantage. But their efforts
broke down shortly before the second intermission and the Capitals
took a 1-0 lead on a power-play goal.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers got one back at even strength early in the third
period to tie the score and set up a tense finish.
</P>
<P>
   Scoring for the Capitals at 15:39 of the second period was
defenseman Sergei Gonchar, who drifted down the right side and beat
Richter with a shot from the circle after a pass across the zone
from Jaroslav Svejkovsky. The Capitals had the extra man because
Mathieu Schneider of the Rangers was in the penalty box for
boarding Kelly Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the period, the Rangers killed off a four-minute
power play after defenseman Chris Tamer got a double minor for
high-sticking Svejkovsky and cutting his face.
</P>
<P>
   Richter was sharp on many Capitals scoring chances. One of the
most dangerous came on hard shot by Bondra after Samuelsson turned
over the puck in the second minute of the second period. At the
other end, Olaf Kolzig of Washington stopped John MacLean's
power-play blast on the fly from the right-wing circle.
</P>
<P>
   Richter was sharp again early in the third period when Andrei
Nikolishin wheeled around Tamer and fired from close range. As
often happens, the other team went down to the other end and
scored.
</P>
<P>
   Getting the goal for the Rangers _ and delighting the many New
York fans in the audience _ was Knuble, who got open in the high
slot and one-timed a slap shot between the legs of Kolzig at the
two-minute mark.
</P>
<P>
   Assisting on the goal were Sundstrom and Manny Malhotra, who
created the chance with a cycling shift that has become
characteristic of their style. Also helping was Samuelsson, who cut
across Kolzig's field of vision.
</P>
<P>
   For the Rangers, this was the second game of a 12-game stretch
in 23 days. They next play the Bruins in Boston on Sunday. Although
both New York and Washington are competing for a playoff berth,
there were vast stretches of empty seats in the building, which
opened last season. In their previous three meetings this season,
the Capitals won twice and the Rangers won once.
</P>
</TEXT>
