<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CENTRAL-ASIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: UNSTABLE AUTOCRACIES IN CENTRAL ASIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Friday, March 5:
</P>
<P>
   A series of car bombs recently exploded at the government's
headquarters in Uzbekistan's capital, Tashkent, killing 16 people.
They narrowly missed the country's leader, Islam Karimov _ a sign
that the stability provided by the dictators of Central Asia and
the Caucasus can be quickly upended.
</P>
<P>
   Since the breakup of the Soviet Union, stability has been the
West's primary goal for these countries. The region borders such
trouble spots as Afghanistan and Iran. It is also sitting on
bountiful oil and gas reserves. While the United States has
criticized the local leaders for their autocratic ways, it has
treated them as partners, on the theory that their rule provides a
stable climate for oil and gas investment. But the attempt on
Karimov, and the failing health of President Heydar Aliyev of
Azerbaijan, are reminders that autocratic rule could give way to
instability when the dictators die.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the leaders in the region have focused all politics
around loyalty to themselves and blocked the development of
political institutions. There are few serious political parties,
parliaments or courts and no mechanisms for a peaceful transition
of power. The most democracy is found in Georgia and Kyrgyzstan,
and the least in Turkmenistan and Uzbekistan, the most populous
nation.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the leaders encourage potentially volatile clan
politics. Under Soviet rule, Central Asia republics were tightly
controlled by Communist leaders appointed by Moscow _ many of whom
are now their nations' presidents. They once relied on a network of
local state farm and provincial bosses. Today these same men head
territorial mafias that control jobs and government benefits.
Virtually all Central Asia's strongmen favor a particular mafia or
clan _ crucial in countries where such ties determine who gets
rich.
</P>
<P>
   Repression of religion is another practice that could cause
future unrest. In Uzbekistan, the independent practice of Islam is
banned, and President Karimov has closed hundreds of mosques in the
last year. The crackdown on Islam has politicized the expression of
religion and turned it into an outlet for protest against poverty
and corruption.
</P>
<P>
   While all the dictators claim to welcome foreign investment,
most will not institute market reforms or anti-corruption measures
that might stimulate economic growth. Karimov, for example, has
lost foreign investment and International Monetary Fund loans
because he continues to control access to hard currency. He does so
to reward friends by allowing them to buy foreign currency cheaply,
which they can then resell for huge profits. Instead of building
stability through economic growth and the construction of political
institutions, Central Asia's dictators count on smothering dissent.
That kind of artificial, temporary stability often ends in
explosive unrest. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
