<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: JITTERY VAN GUNDY SHOULD DROP THE BOOTCAMP BABBLE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By   HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When the coach of an 8-5 basketball team ominously
declares that ``the season is slipping away,'' he needs to take
another look at the standings, or put in a reality-check call to
John Calipari.
</P>
<P>
   That is exactly what Jeff Van Gundy said after the Knicks'
lopsided loss last weekend in Detroit. Obviously, the coach was
responding to his team's lifeless road effort, not its overall
record, but he nonetheless managed to lay the trap he often
complains the critics too often fall into in their all-or-nothing
evaluations of the Knicks. He sounded suspiciously like a fan, or,
worse, a coach who is beginning to fear for his job.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy's job could very well be on the line, given the
Yankee-sized payroll underwritten by the cable behemoth that owns
the team. Fair or not _ and I think not, based, in part, on the
excellent work Van Gundy did last season _ the Knicks haven't
advanced beyond the second round for four straight years. In this
truncated, Jordan-less season, it will be harder to explain away
another failed run to the conference final, or beyond. It will be
much easier for the Knicks to make a scapegoat of their coach.
</P>
<P>
   One who works with such expectations looks at the standings, and
can't help but notice the Nascar-like draft of contending playoff
teams. Forget, for the moment, Indiana, Miami and Orlando. Almost a
third of the way through the 50-game schedule, Van Gundy opened the
newspaper Thursday to find his Knicks a half-game behind Allen
Iverson, the one-man offense formerly known as the Philadelphia
76ers.
</P>
<P>
   This regular-season sprint is scary stuff, uncharted territory.
All the more important why Van Gundy _ whose quintessential player,
after all that has been said and spent, is a 36-year-old center
with brittle knees _ must look beyond the standard race for the
highest playoff seeding. His job is to get to the playoffs with the
best playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Let Pat Riley relentlessly drive his players, risk wearing them
out, for an extra home game that will make no difference when
Alonzo Mourning fouls out, or punches his way out, of the Heat's
next must-win playoff test. Van Gundy beat Riley in the first round
last season without home-court advantage, without even Ewing, yet
he continues to embrace the Riley way as if his former mentor
carried the coaching commandments from the mountain to Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Riley always brags that the bigger the game, the shorter his
rotation. It's a matter of trust, he claims. In Miami, Van Gundy
benched Marcus Camby and gave Chris Dudley, the backup center who
makes roughly $7 million a year, 7 minutes of his time. Van Gundy
says he does not believe that 8 or 10 minutes of rest every game
makes a difference for Ewing. This is pure Rileyspeak, boot camp
babble that defies fundamental reason. Ewing was a chronological
revelation in Miami, a statistical marvel.
</P>
<P>
   He was also, after 43 minutes of brutal combat with Mourning and
P.J. Brown, exhausted. No legs, no lift, no energy to drive the
ball to the basket on the last possession of a 1-point game.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, never strong on shot selection, always made enough bad
ones in his peak years to keep his shooting percentage around 50.
He is down around 40 this season, an alarming if understandable
decline. Ewing is formidable under good scoring conditions, but he
is not the athlete he once was. He needs his legs to create the
best opportunity, especially in the mayhem at the end of a game.
The coach's job is to make sure he has them.
</P>
<P>
   Latrell Sprewell's return in Milwaukee Friday night gives Van
Gundy a chance to restart the season with a broader sense of
purpose. A second unit of Sprewell, Camby, Dudley with Chris Childs
and Charlie Ward would give the Knicks their most athletic,
up-tempo look in years. This cannot be hit or miss, though, a
once-a-week option. Van Gundy must make a commitment to his bench,
the way Larry Bird has with the Indiana Pacers, the conference's
team to beat.
</P>
<P>
   There are more than enough bad or battered teams stumbling
about, playing too many games in too many nights. The Knicks will
get a decent playoff seeding no matter how Van Gundy plays it. He
can afford to tinker, to invest, to give Ewing and Larry Johnson
their rest.
</P>
<P>
   There are no must games until May. Only the foolish and the
desperate would push a player beyond his physical capability in
February or March. Calipari, for one, inexplicably stretched a
hamstrung Sam Cassell in the Nets' first game, and is paying a
punishing price. His season, unlike Van Gundy's, is going, going
gone. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
