u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.N.-DEADBEATS-NYT &LR;      03-04 0709
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-DEADBEATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED NATIONS TO COLLECT SUPPORT FOR WORKERS' EX-SPOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Speaking on women's issues to an audience that included Hillary
Rodham Clinton, the secretary general of the United Nations, Kofi
Annan, announced a policy change Thursday that is intended to bring
relief to a long-suffering group of women, the ex-wives of United
Nations employees.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, a growing group of former United Nations spouses,
including many in metropolitan New York, have accused the
organization of hypocrisy and callousness because it allowed
employees to avoid paying court-ordered spousal and child support.
</P>
<P>
   Worldwide, critics estimated that hundreds of women, perhaps
more, have not collected support because the United Nations and its
affiliated organizations have refused for decades to waive their
international immunity from legal process and garnishee the wages
of employees who did not pay.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday, Annan spoke of the rising worldwide poverty among
women as he announced that the United Nations would begin
garnisheeing wages of recalcitrant employees case by case. He
called the problem of unpaid support ``an issue of moral concern to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It presents us with a duty to set an example,'' he said,
according to a transcript of his speech. The details of the policy
have not been drafted, but United Nations officials said work on
the new rules was to begin Friday.
</P>
<P>
   For years, employers in the United States have had to
immediately comply with garnishment orders or risk being cited for
contempt.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Colt, the deputy chief of the Family Court Division of
the city's Law Department, represents more than a dozen United
Nations ex-spouses and greeted the announcement with skepticism.
She said the case-by-case review could mean long delays in which
the United Nations essentially acted as a court of appeals,
deciding whether to approve support payments. She said the
yet-to-be determined policy must allow for swift action.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Colt, a fierce critic of the United Nations whose
clients have largely been ignored by the organization for decades,
added: ``At least it's public acknowledgment on the part of the
secretary general that there is a problem. I guess that's pretty
major. That's an important admission on the part of the U.N., but I
don't think it's going to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Boernstein, a former United Nations lawyer who has worked
with ex-spouses, said the policy change must be made in ``good
faith,'' but added that she was ``thrilled at any progress.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the pressure must continue,'' Ms.
Boernstein said. ``I'm very excited that a small, determined group
of people can make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   International immunity exempts the United Nations and other
international organizations rom legal process in any country. The
immunity was created so that the organization could remain
autonomous from the actions of hostile governments, but the United
Nations has interpreted the immunity broadly and has refused to
recognize any court orders against its employees, including those
for support. This has provided a loophole for employees, most of
them men, to avoid payment.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 100 such ex-spouses are estimated to live in the New
York area, and the number is much larger internationally. One woman
in New York lives in a Salvation Army boarding house because her
ex-husband has refused to pay her. A Westchester County woman has
tried to collect court-ordered support for more than 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Louise Frechette, the deputy secretary general and the United
Nations' highest ranking woman, began pushing for change last
November after an article about the former spouses appeared in The
New York Times. A top aide to Ms. Frechette, Marta Mauras, said the
United Nations will not relinquish its autonomy and stressed that
most employees do comply with support orders. But she said the new
policy is very much needed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The U.N. needs to become much more sensitive and family
friendly,'' Ms. Mauras said. ``This is an issue that affects staff
members and their families as rates of divorce and separation
increase; this is one way to respond to the needs of families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
