<SLUG> BC-GOP-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP APPROVES 2000 BUDGET PLAN 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republican leaders agreed Thursday on a blueprint
for a 2000 budget plan that would prohibit Social Security funds
from being raided to pay for tax cuts and keep spending increases
on defense, education and other programs within the limits set two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   House Budget Committee Chairman John Kasich, R-Ohio, hailed the
agreement with his Senate GOP colleagues as a ``historic'' event
that lays out how the government will handle the estimated billions
in budget surpluses that are expected over the next 10 to 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The surpluses are largely made up of money from the Social
Security trust fund, which the government has for years tapped for
other purposes.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP plan, which only has the broad parameters of a 2000
spending proposal, must be approved by Republican members of
Congress before they can negotiate with the administration on a
final budget.
</P>
<P>
   But it marks the first time since Clinton outlined his own
budget proposal in January that Republicans have responded with
definitive proposals of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the plan were still sketchy Thursday evening. But the
agreement reached between Kasich and Senate Budget Committee
Chairman Pete Domenici, R-N.M., calls for a small tax cut beginning
next year, a military pay increase and increased spending in a
number of education programs.
</P>
<P>
   Its central provision, however, calls for using annual Social
Security surpluses to help pay down the national debt, instead of
being diverted to offset tax cuts and pay for other programs.
</P>
<P>
   The decision to use most of the surpluses to pay down the
national debt was designed to rob Democrats of their complaint that
Republicans want to use Social Security money to pay for tax cuts
to the rich.
</P>
<P>
   While the Republican proposal mirrors Clinton's plan to use most
of the budget surpluses to shore up Social Security by paying down
the debt, it does not include setting aside surpluses for Medicare
and other programs, which Clinton and the Democrats would like to
do.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., said the Republican
proposal was ``two thirds of the way there,'' but was not likely to
pass Congress unless it helps to keep the Medicare program solvent
beyond 2010, when it is expected to run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici insisted, however, that he wants to protect most of the
projected surpluses for the Social Security program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to lock up every penny of the Social Security
trust fund system for our nation's elderly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he told reporters that he would consider setting aside money
for Medicare if it can be reformed to prevent fraud and waste.
</P>
<P>
   Domenici and Kasich said the Republican plan calls for phased-in
tax cuts beginning next year and continuing through 2009, but it is
unclear whether they will take the form of across-the-board cuts or
targeted relief as Clinton and some Republicans have sought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans are sending too much money to this town, and we want
to send it back,'' said Kasich, who plans to seek the Republican
presidential nomination in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
