A8626 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONICA-BOOKSTORES05-C     03-04 0502
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONICA-BOOKSTORES05-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bookstores sell out of `Monica's Story,' but many customers
ready to turn page on saga
 &HT;    By Marcus Franklin
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Even before Books &AMP; Co. opened at 9 a.m.
Thursday, about a dozen people anxiously waited outside the store
to grab a copy of ``Monica's Story,'' the latest book about the
President Clinton-Monica Lewinsky affair to hit shelves.
</P>
<P>
   By 12:30 p.m., the store had sold all of its 50 copies,
according to Sharon Kelly Roth, director of public relations at
Books &AMP; Co. One customer even purchased four for friends and
relatives, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``A number of people commented that (the book) was part of
history and they wanted to have it in their collection,'' Roth
explained. ``Some were impressed with (Lewinksy's ABC-TV) interview
with Barbara Walters (on Wednesday night) and just wanted more
details. And some wanted to read the book because it had
information in it (Lewinsky) wasn't allowed to discuss on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   As part of the former White House intern's immunity agreement,
Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr first had to approve the
questions and answers given in the Wednesday special.
</P>
<P>
   Other customers, Roth said, lamented ``that they had had
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Angie Behnfeldt, 40, is tired of the topic. She, like nearly all
of the customers interviewed at Books &AMP; Co. on Thursday evening,
said she didn't watch the TV interview nor does she plan to buy the
book.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all of this is making light of the situation,''
Behnfeldt said. ``It's made her into a star and what she did was
immoral. I just don't have any interest in helping her make money
off of the book. I'm embarrassed for her.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Lill, 31, said while she doesn't plan to buy the book,
she would ``flip through it'' if she comes across a copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had about enough of it,'' Lill said.
</P>
<P>
   Even with brisk sales of ``Monica's Story,'' first-day receipts
still didn't compare to the sales of other recent hot sellers such
as ``The Starr Report'' or Princess Diana memorabilia at Books &AMP;
Co., Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Starr Report' had larger sales the first day because we
had more copies in stock and because it was all new information,''
Roth said.
</P>
<P>
   The store expects another shipment of 150 copies of ``Monica's
Story'' today, she said.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday afternoon and into the evening, Books &AMP; Co. and
other book stores around the Miami Valley, were inundated with
calls from customers to place yet-to-arrive copies on hold.
</P>
<P>
   The independent Bookfriends sold its three copies on Thursday
but expects another small shipment on Monday, according to co-owner
Jim Latham.
</P>
<P>
   Latham, who said he sold very few of ``The Starr Report,'' said
because very few of his customers inquired about Lewinsky's book,
he didn't bother to order many.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the feeling that most of (my customers) are just tired
of the whole thing,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
