<HEADER>
A8630 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLER-LITE-AD-COLUMN     03-04 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLER-LITE-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD COLUMN: A CAMPAIGN FOR MILLER LITE GOES BACK TO BASICS  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis., Minn., Texas, N.Y.)  (js) 
 BY STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miller Brewing Co. is making an abrupt about-face by
unceremoniously ending a campaign for the flagging Miller Lite beer
brand. The campaign generated contentious debate over its
unconventional content, which attempted to appeal to younger
consumers with offbeat entertainment rather than product pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beer did not play a role in the advertising,'' Jack
Rooney, vice president for marketing at Miller in Milwaukee, said
Thursday, ``and that was its fundamental weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   The replacement campaign for Miller Lite _ still Miller's
largest brand despite sales softness _ begins Friday with
commercials taking a more traditional, broadly directed and
product-oriented approach.
</P>
<P>
   In the booming light beer market, where Miller Lite now trails
the Bud Light brew sold by Anheuser-Busch, ``we can make Miller
Lite No. 1 again,'' Rooney declared, ``one day at a time, one step
at a time, based on a product proposition.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the new spots evoke the brand's popular, product-fixated
``debate'' campaign of the 1970s and 1980s, when celebrities
pretended to argue over whether they liked Miller Lite because it
``tastes great'' or because it was ``less filling.'' The overhauled
campaign, centered on contemporary celebrities good-naturedly
debating the ingredients and drinkability of Miller Lite, carries
the theme ``The great taste of a true Pilsner beer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can capture that again,'' Rooney said, referring to the
spirit and success of the original campaign, ``then the brand will
grow again.'' Sales last year fell about 2 percent from 1997, when
they rose modestly; by comparison, Bud Light has racked up
double-digit percentage sales gains.
</P>
<P>
   The new Miller Lite TV and radio commercials, print and Internet
ads and posters are being produced by Fallon McElligott in
Minneapolis, the same shop that created the quirky ``Miller time''
campaign introduced in 1997 by a fictitious adman named Dick. But
the new ads bear no resemblance to the old, which were castigated
for straying from marketing fundamentals in trying to woo ad-weary
members of Generation X with wacky animals, odd characters and
bathroom humor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it did very much to sell beer,'' said Bob Keane,
editorial director at Adams Media Beverage Group in New York, part
of Adams Business Media Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking the humor tack they did has not brought back the
younger consumer,'' he added. ``Talking about the brewing process
and the quality of the product seems like a good idea because
that's been missing from the light beer category.''
</P>
<P>
   The sudden shift in campaigns is indicative of the midcourse
corrections that have grown increasingly common as advertisers try
to respond more quickly to faster-changing consumer behavior.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the Pepsi-Cola Co. unit of Pepsico Inc. stopped
using the theme ``Generation next'' to promote the Pepsi-Cola brand
after complaints that it was too diffused and youth-oriented. A
replacement, ``The joy of cola,'' was introduced to bottlers
Thursday night and will start nationally on March 21.
</P>
<P>
   ``We learned one big lesson'' from the bizarre ``Miller time''
campaign, Rooney said, speaking in a telephone interview from
Nashville, where Miller, a unit of Philip Morris Cos., was meeting
with its wholesalers and sales force.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're advertising a product, you ought to give the
consumer a reason to choose that product,'' Rooney said. ``If you
can entertain at the same time, that's great.
</P>
<P>
   ``This campaign probably could be characterized as a bit more
old school,'' he added. ``And that's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Miller time'' campaign was the first produced for Miller
Lite by Fallon McElligott, which has handled the creative portion
of the brand's account, with billings estimated at $150 million,
since December 1996. The agency presented its replacement to Miller
executives as part of a review that ended in January with Fallon
McElligott fighting off three other finalists to retain the
high-profile assignment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the brand now has a really solid proposition,'' Rooney
said.
</P>
<P>
   The new spots depict pairs of 1990s celebrities in bars, engaged
in light-hearted banter over why Miller Lite ``tastes great'': Is
it ``the choice hops'' or because ``it's so smooth''?
</P>
<P>
   (``Less filling'' is missing, Rooney said, because it has become
``a generic attribute.'')
</P>
<P>
   The pairs include the model Rebecca Romijn-Stamos and the
sportswriter Rick Reilly; the former baseball players Robin Yount
and George Brett; the former relief pitchers Lee Smith and Mitch
Williams, and the auto racers Bobby Rahal and Don Prudhomme.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very much a current rendition of those wonderful
commercials of the '70s and '80s,'' said Michael Bellas, chairman
of Beverage Marketing Corp. in New York, which Miller ``has never
been able to really follow up.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Miller has to stabilize Lite,'' he added, ``and this is
another attempt to do that. Talking about quality and product
attributes may be what's needed at this time because that's become
far more important to beer drinkers since the '80s.''
</P>
<P>
   Rooney agreed, saying: ``Beers with what I would call more
obvious product differences have made the average drinker a little
more beer literate. We used to say Miller Lite was `a fine Pilsner
beer'; you build on what you have.'' That is underscored in four
15-second commercials that will complement the celebrity spots;
focused solely on attributes like flavor, smoothness and
ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   There are also Spanish-language versions of the celebrity spots,
created by Square One in Dallas and its Hispanic unit, Uno
Communicaciones. They feature pairs of actors (Erik Estrada and
Kate del Castillo), wrestlers (Hiji del Sol and Atlantis) and
former athletes (Tony Perez and Edward Figueroa).
</P>
<P>
   Don Coleman Advertising in Detroit, recently named to handle ads
aimed at black consumers, will also create spots for the campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Turning to Pepsi-Cola, its revamped campaign will introduce the
``Joy of cola'' theme by playing up such characteristic brand
elements as celebrities, music and humor. Like Miller Lite,
Pepsi-Cola is seeking to appeal to a broader audience than the
Generation X target of ``Generation next.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The campaign promises to offer something for everyone,'' said
Ted Sann, co-chief executive and chief creative officer at the
Pepsi-Cola agency, BBDO New York, part of the BBDO Worldwide unit
of Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   The first three spots in ``The joy of cola'' campaign will
feature the voices of Marlon Brando, Aretha Franklin and Isaac
Hayes. The voices will emanate from Hallie Eisenberg, a girl
featured in a recent commercial in which she ``spoke'' in the voice
of the actor Joe Pesci, warning a counterman at a diner not to
serve her a Coca-Cola.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
